<HEADLINE>
TOLEDO: THE PRESSURE IS ON THEM, NOT US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Perhaps it was a calculated move to calm his young
team. More likely, he was speaking with typical bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, UCLA coach Bob Toledo fired the first salvo of
rivalry week when asked about the impact of the Bruins' eight-game
winning streak over USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot more pressure on them than us,'' Toledo
said Monday afternoon. ``They've got to stop the streak. We've got
the streak. There's so much pressure on, `Stop the streak,' `Stop
the streak.' ''
</P>
<P>
   However, given several chances to extol the streak or denigrate
USC, the Bruins declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like talking about the streak, because I don't want it
to change when I'm around,'' cornerback Ryan Roques said. ``I just
leave it be and try to add one more year by year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's motivation for both teams.''
</P>
<P>
   While there's pressure on USC to end the streak, there's
considerable pressure on UCLA to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The pressure) has been there since the streak hit three or
four,'' defensive captain Pete Holland said. ``No one wants to be
the class that loses to USC.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Show of support: Toledo defended his counterpart, USC coach
Paul Hackett, who has been criticized for the Trojans' subpar
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very unfair,'' Toledo said. ``He's only been
there two years and he's trying to get the program going. I don't
know all his problems, but being a coach, you sympathize with those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad reaction: The Pac-10 was not happy with ABC's decision to
show the UCLA-USC game Saturday instead of Cal-Stanford,
Oregon-Oregon State or Washington-Washington State _ games that
involve Rose Bowl contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassment,'' Cal athletic director John Kasser
told the Oakland Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   ABC told the Pac-10 office that it was strictly a business
decision: Its important Los Angeles affiliate, KABC, needed the
Bruins and Trojans to boost ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of promoting the Rose Bowl, obviously, we
disagree with the decision,'' Pac-10 assistant commissioner Duane
Lindberg said. ``They told us it was absolutely a business
decision. This year, because USC and UCLA have been down, (KABC)
hasn't had as many exposures with those teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unanimous across the board that the conference wasn't
happy and the members weren't happy, and we all voiced that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Development of the week: The broken collarbones that claimed
UCLA's Cory Paus and USC's Carson Palmer have created an intriguing
quarterback matchup: USC's John Fox was a linebacker when the
season started, and UCLA's Ryan McCann was fourth string.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: Sacramento tailback Albert Hollis visited
campus last weekend and attended the Washington game. One of the
nation's most-coveted players, Hollis is wavering on his summer
commitment to UCLA. He has visited Georgia and plans to see Notre
Dame, Nebraska and Texas next month.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if UCLA remained the leader, Hollis paused, then shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
