<SLUG> BC-VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN-OPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNESMANN STEADFAST IN FIGHT AGAINST VODAFONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With VODAFONE-MANNESMANN) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ As chairman of Mannesmann AG, Klaus Esser
is hardly a stranger to take-no-prisoners pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find new things, accentuate our strengths and pull
ourselves out of weak areas,'' he remarked in a recent interview
with the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung.
</P>
<P>
   Few executives have applied that bromide with more gusto than
Esser. As chief financial officer and more recently as chairman,
Esser sold scores of Mannesmann's old industrial businesses while
investing tens of billions of marks in the telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, Mannesmann has been transformed from a
producer of industrial pipes into the closest thing yet to a
pan-European telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann's D2 mobile telephone network is the biggest in
Germany, with slightly more customers than Deutsche Telekom AG. It
also controls the second-biggest cellular network in Italy and is
in the process of swallowing Orange PLC of Britain for $33 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On top of all that, Mannesmann is investing billions in
hard-wired networks in Germany and across Europe. The goal: to be a
full-service provider across Europe, from mobile telephone service
to Internet and high-speed data over fiber optic networks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has been a big success. Mannesmann's stock price has
quadrupled in the last three years, and analysts estimate that 90
percent of that value reflects its telecommunications businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Esser faces his biggest challenge yet: the possibility of a
hostile takeover of historic scale and audacity by Vodafone PLC of
Britain. The deal could be worth as much as $130.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Esser is determined to fight a Vodafone takeover, arguing that
the British company would bring nothing to Mannesmann shareholders
and that the two companies' strategies are fundamentally
incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   The hostile bid has also shocked at least some German industrial
leaders. Hans-Peter Stihl, president of the German Association of
Chambers of Industry and Commerce, said Monday that the government
ought to prohibit takeovers aimed at breaking up successful
companies against their will.
</P>
<P>
   But industry analysts say Vodafone has a chance of emerging
victorious, especially if it substantially improves its offer. And
even if it does not win, they say, Mannesmann could nevertheless
fall to other suitors like British Telecommunications or even an
American company like Bell Atlantic Corp. or SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle is that any takeover needs to win 75
percent of shareholders' votes, which means that a group with more
than 25 percent of the votes has a veto.
</P>
<P>
   One of Vodafone's big problems is that its offer is entirely in
stock, and the value of any potential offer declines if its share
price weakens.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann has some defense options. On Monday it sought to at
least disrupt any takeover by suing to disqualify the Goldman Sachs
Group, Vodafone's corporate adviser, on grounds that Goldman had a
conflict of interest. Mannesmann will also seek to persuade
investors that Vodafone's all-stock offer is inherently dubious and
that taking over Mannesmann would merely dilute Vodafone's stock.
</P>
<P>
   It can try to find a ``white knight,'' a company that would
acquire enough shares to block an unfriendly takeover. Esser has
thus far held talks with several companies, including BT and Bell
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   A more likely defense, according to some analysts, would be to
line up a core group of friendly investors. Mannesmann could agree
to sell some of its industrial units to companies that in turn
increase their stakes in Mannesmann and vote against Vodafone's
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann can also try to invoke rules that prohibit any
shareholder from voting more than 5 percent of the stock. But those
rules are scheduled to expire next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann executives have repeatedly insisted that they are not
interested in white knights and that their top priority is
preserving the company's independence.
</P>
<P>
   The company's executives argue that Vodafone would add nothing
to their competitive position. Vodafone acquired AirTouch
Communications of San Francisco earlier this year, but it owns only
a minority stake in AirTouch's American properties as a result of a
deal it reached with Bell Atlantic Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann executives said they had little interest in the
American market and even less in minority stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Mannesmann executives argue that Vodafone would
disrupt their strategy of providing a full range of wireless,
conventional voice and Internet services. Vodafone has thus far
focused entirely on mobile phones, while the Mannesmann Arcor unit
is Germany's second-largest provider of fixed-line services.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Mannesmann has already adopted a variant of the
``poison pill'' defense by purchasing Orange PLC for about $33
billion. Analysts say Mannesmann paid a huge premium for Orange,
and unhappy investors pushed down Mannesmann shares after Esser
announced the deal last month.
</P>
<P>
   Because Vodafone controls Britain's second-largest cellular
network, it would be required to sell Orange if it took over
Mannesmann. Given the high price Mannesmann paid and that Vodafone
would be a forced seller, analysts estimate that it might well have
to sell Orange for 10 or 15 percent less than Mannesmann paid.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is expected to offer more than 200 euros a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
