<SLUG> BC-NY-ATM-FEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL PROPOSES BAN ON ATM FEES FOR NONCUSTOMERS
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Conn., Iowa)  (See also ATM-FEES) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Council is planning legislation to
prohibit banks from charging fees to noncustomers who use their
automated teller machines. The bill, like measures passed in San
Francisco and Santa Monica, Calif., would affect consumers who are
now often charged two fees for doing business at banks where they
do not maintain accounts, council officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Such customers are often charged $1 to $2.50 in addition to
whatever their own bank may charge for processing a transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Council Speaker Peter Vallone said the bill would be drafted
within a month and could be passed before the end of the year.
``Somebody who needs a $20 bill for something might have to wind up
paying $2 or $3 for the privilege of withdrawing his or her own
money,'' he said. ``That's absolutely wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York bill, like the laws in San Francisco and Santa
Monica and like state laws in Connecticut and Iowa, would ban the
surcharges that customers pay to the bank that owns the money
machine. Each bank now decides what, if any, fees to charge its own
customers for ATM transactions at other banks. Such charges, known
as foreign transaction fees, would still be allowed under the
proposed law.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry has opposed all of these measures; a
federal judge issued a preliminary injunction Monday barring San
Francisco and Santa Monica from enforcing their bans. Two major
banks in California have responded to the new laws by allowing only
their own depositors to use their ATM's.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is expected to mount particularly strenuous
opposition in New York, the center of the financial services
industry. ``This whole debate is based much more on emotion than it
is on logic,'' said John Hall, a spokesman for the American Bankers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Banks say that the fees are necessary to pay for computer
software, equipment, networking services and other expenses and
that a bank does not benefit in any way by making its money
machines accessible to customers of competing banks. Customers can
always use their own bank's machines without charge, they say, and
customers who want the convenience of using another bank's machines
should pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Smith, the president of the New York Bankers
Association, said his organization had requested a meeting with
Vallone to discuss the proposed legislation and hoped to dissuade
him from introducing it. ``We believe the proposal would be
injurious to the city of New York and to the consumers of bank
services and to the providers of those services,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that disclosure laws require machines to notify
customers of a charge and to offer the option of canceling the
transaction. ``You have the choice to use your own bank's
machine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   John Tamberlane, president for consumer financial services of
Republic National Bank, which aggressively promotes the fact that
it does not charge ATM fees, said individual institutions should be
allowed to set their own prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we suggesting that the clients of one bank can go into
another bank's tellers and use them?'' He added, ``It's a crazy
thing to be legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that the surcharges penalize depositors who are
simply trying to retrieve their own money and that they belie the
notion that teller machines are supposed to make banking cheaper
and more convenient. Critics say the result is often a double
charge because the banks that own the money machines may also
receive a portion of the foreign transaction fees that many
customers pay to their own banks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, then the chairman of the
Banking Committee, proposed eliminating the surcharges. The bill
was opposed by the banking industry and was not passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
