<SLUG> BC-COKE-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA BOTTLER DISCUSSES PRICE INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Insisting that there had been no fundamental shift in strategy,
Coca-Cola Co.'s largest bottler told investors and money managers
in a rare conference call Monday that its decision to raise retail
prices earlier this year should improve the company's cash flow and
profitability despite a drop in volume.
</P>
<P>
   The increases in the United States and Canada by the bottler,
Coca-Cola Enterprises, were followed in recent weeks by an increase
in concentrate prices by Coca-Cola. Both companies have said that a
marketing campaign by Coca-Cola is supposed to persuade consumers
to pay more for Coke products after years of low prices brought on
by a price war with its rival, PepsiCo, and the emergence of
private-label soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   The changes confused many on Wall Street, who had been
accustomed to using volume as the chief measure of success at both
companies. Share prices for Coke and its bottlers, and at other
soft-drink makers, have fallen sharply this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interdependence between the Coca-Cola Co. and Coca-Cola
Enterprises is firmly established,'' said Henry Schimberg, the
bottler's chief executive, who is set to retire at the end of next
month. ``CCE can't be successful at the expense of Coca-Cola, and
conversely, Coca-Cola can't be successful at the expense of CCE.''
</P>
<P>
   Schimberg added that although volume was flat for the year,
decreases in capital spending have helped create an additional $200
million in cash flow, which will be used to buy back stock. The
company is reducing its investment in cars, trucks and fillers,
said the bottler's chief operating officer, John Alm.
</P>
<P>
   Schimberg also indicated that prices would rise at the same rate
as inflation over the next several years. ``We'll continue to move
pricing forward in a rational manner,'' he said. Earnings
improvement is expected to come from more purchases made in the
highly profitable ``cold-drink'' segment of the soft-drink market,
which includes vending machines. For the year, sales in
supermarkets have fallen 6 percent, Alm said, while cold-drink
sales have risen at a double-digit rate.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts seemed mostly reassured after the conference call,
although several said only time would tell whether the Coca-Cola
strategy was effective. ``It's still going to be, show us the
volume,'' said Caroline Levy, a beverage analyst for Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
