<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-O'CONNOR-BISHOPS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'CONNOR-BISHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'CONNOR SENDS BISHOPS AN IMPLIED FAREWELL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his health uncertain and his 80th birthday
approaching, Cardinal John O'Connor, the archbishop of New York,
sat out an annual gathering of American bishops this week. Instead,
he sent a letter of gratitude that seemed a moving farewell to his
spiritual brethren.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, which was read aloud Monday morning at the annual
conference of American bishops in Washington, O'Connor alluded to
his impending retirement. Under church law, cardinals lose the
right to vote in papal conclaves at age 80, but can continue to
vote in the bishops' conference until a successor is chosen. Pope
John Paul II has yet to name a replacement for O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I have no word whatsoever from our Holy Father who,
as we know, alone makes such decisions,'' the cardinal wrote to the
bishops, ``it would seem to me to be the height of
presumptuousness, in view of my becoming an octogenarian on the
forthcoming 15th of January, to anticipate continuing in office
much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal devoted most of the letter to thanking the bishops
for the ``wonderful associations'' he had had during more than 20
years in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot recall a single difference or conflict that we have
not worked our way through in the best interest of the church
universal and of the church in the United States,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be in my daily Masses and prayers, and I humbly ask a
little remembrance in yours,'' the note to the bishops said. ``It's
been a great ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The message comes as O'Connor struggles with ill health, fueling
intense, if whispered, speculation about his possible replacement.
</P>
<P>
   As intriguing as what the cardinal's missive said was what it
did not say. It made no mention at all of his illness. In late
August, a tumor was removed from the surface of his brain, and he
underwent radiation treatments into October. Last month, he was
hospitalized for a blood clot in his left leg and for dehydration
caused by the radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal wrote that he had asked Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza,
president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, to read
the letter aloud on his behalf, adding, ``I must confess that I
fear that I would become emotional were I to try to express it
orally.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Zwilling, a spokesman for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese
of New York, said that O'Connor had expected to attend the
conference when he sent the letter on Saturday, but that an
``urgent matter'' arose Sunday evening that kept him from
traveling. Zwilling declined to elaborate, but said the conflict
was not related to the cardinal's health. Although the cardinal
stumbled as Mass ended on Sunday, he was not injured and the fall
had nothing to do with his decision not to attend the conference,
Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal did not mention his illness in the letter, Zwilling
said, because it was unrelated to his reasons for writing. More
relevant, Zwilling said, was his age. At 75, all bishops are
required to submit their resignations to the Holy See, but so far,
Pope John Paul II has not accepted O'Connor's. ``He doesn't know
when Pope John Paul II will accept his retirement and appoint his
successor,'' Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorenza said that after he read O'Connor's message to the
bishops Monday, it received sustained applause. But he said he did
not consider the letter a sign that the cardinal's retirement was
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just signifies that the cardinal is nearing 80 years old,''
Fiorenza said. ``He doesn't really know what the future holds, but
it did signify that whatever the future holds, he has enjoyed
immensely his association with the American bishops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
