<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT &LR;      11-16 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MAYOR AND THE FIRST AMENDMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 16:
</P>
<P>
   On matters large and small, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani seems deaf to
free-speech concerns. For more than a year, the mayor has imposed
tight restrictions on the use of New York's City Hall steps for
public demonstrations, ostensibly for security reasons. On Sunday,
Councilwoman Christine Quinn was told by police guards that she
could not hold a press conference on the steps, even though she was
there with fewer than a dozen community members to draw attention
to the killing of a young gay man in his apartment in Harlem. Only
after she called Council Speaker Peter Vallone to intervene was she
allowed to hold the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Under current rules, no more than 50 people are allowed in
rallies on the steps. All groups are supposed to obtain permits
from the police. But surely there is something wrong with rules
that require elected council members to get permission to hold a
news conference at their place of work. The rules raise
constitutional questions because they exempt some events sponsored
by the city, thus giving the administration the ability to
discriminate in favor of certain kinds of speech.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's record on First Amendment rights looks worse with
every new court ruling against him. Last week, federal District
Judge Allen Schwartz ruled that his administration had improperly
retaliated against Housing Works, an AIDS service organization, by
making it ineligible to receive federal grants controlled by the
city. The judge found that the actions violated the First Amendment
rights of Housing Works, which has been a vocal critic of the
mayor's AIDS policies.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, federal District Judge Robert Sweet ruled that
the manner in which the city decides on requests for temporary
commemorative street signs was arbitrary and violated free-speech
rights. Two days before that, another federal judge, Nina Gershon,
ruled that the mayor's efforts to withhold funds from the Brooklyn
Museum and to evict it from its building were unconstitutional
censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is still fighting a lawsuit, also brought by Housing
Works, to end the restrictions on rallies at the City Hall steps.
The case is in court before federal District Judge Harold Baer, who
has already rejected an earlier rule that limited demonstrations to
25 people. If Giuliani loses again on this case, it will add
another judicial rebuke to his First Amendment record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
