<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-CY-YOUNG-HNS &LR;      11-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CY-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
It took Randy Johnson, arguably the most dominant lefthander of the
decade, to outweigh 22 wins.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lacking only a flashy won-lost record, Johnson called the past
baseball season ``the best year of his career,'' and voters agreed
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson captured the National League Cy Young Award, edging the
Astros' Mike Hampton and becoming only the second pitcher to win
the award in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think this award isn't solely based on wins and
losses,'' said Johnson, who was 17-9 with a 2.48 ERA for the
Arizona Diamondbacks. ``There was a lot more to the season I had
than wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was well short of Hampton's league-leading 22
victories, received 20 first-place votes, 11 second-place votes and
one third for 134 points in balloting by the Baseball Writers'
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who went 22-4 to lead the Astros to a third straight NL
Central title, was second with 11 first-place votes, 17 seconds and
four thirds for 110 points.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Kevin Millwood was third with 36 points. The Astros'
Jose Lima and Billy Wagner tied for fourth with three points each,
marking just the third time an NL team has placed three pitchers in
the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Hampton were the only pitchers named on all 32
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed. That's the nature of the game; you
want to win everything you do,'' said Hampton, who broke the
franchise record of 21 victories set by Joe Niekro in 1979. ``It
gives me a little something to work harder for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hampton's second-place finish, Mike Scott (1986) remains
the only Cy Young winner in Astros history.
</P>
<P>
   While his record was less impressive than Hampton's, Johnson
overwhelmed the opposition in nearly every other category in his
first full season in the NL. The Big Unit, a 6-10 lefthander who
spent the final two months of 1998 with the Astros, led the league
in ERA and the majors in strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   In 272 innings, Johnson had 364 strikeouts, the fourth-highest
total ever. He finished 19 strikeouts short of the record 383 set
by Nolan Ryan in 1973. He struck out 10 or more batters 23 times,
matching the record Ryan set with the California Angels in '73, and
had a league-high 12 complete games.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest argument against Johnson was what he didn't have _
more wins. It wasn't entirely his fault _ in seven of his losses,
Arizona scored two runs or fewer, including a stretch in which the
Diamondbacks were shut out in four straight starts by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He finished strong, winning seven of his last eight decisions to
help the Diamondbacks to the NL West title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I've pitched extremely well and the opposing pitcher
has pitched that much better,'' said Johnson, who had a 1.41 ERA in
the stretch in which his team was blanked four straight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respectable numbers outside the won-lost record.
Unfortunately, people look at the won-lost record and evaluate the
year or your career on that, and it's not really fair sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who won the American League Cy Young with Seattle in
1995, joins Gaylord Perry as the only pitchers to win the honor in
each league. Perry won with Cleveland in 1972 and San Diego in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Pedro Martinez, the Cy Young winner with Montreal in
1997, is expected to join the exclusive club when the AL award is
announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Johnson, Hampton did not have an overpowering fastball to
pile up gaudy strikeout totals, relying instead on his defense.
Hampton, 27, posted career highs in wins, ERA (2.90), strikeouts
(177) and innings pitched (239).
</P>
<P>
   From June 24 to Sept. 18, Hampton did not lose a decision,
reeling off a major-league-best 11 consecutive victories. He picked
up two of his biggest wins late in the season against Cincinnati
and Los Angeles, the latter on the final day to clinch the division
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws 100 mph and strikes out a lot of batters,'' Hampton
said of Johnson. ``I'm not that type of pitcher. I have to work
hard for everything I get. I can't come out and not have good stuff
and rare back and have a 100-mph fastball to rely on. It was a
close vote, and he's definitely deserving.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson watched Hampton break into the majors at age 19 in 1993
with the Mariners and has been impressed with his progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was the real deal when we were in Seattle,'' Johnson
said. ``He went on to Houston (in a December 1993 trade) and
flourished. He was just as deserving for the award. Unfortunately,
there has to be a loser. I wouldn't have minded co-winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three times since baseball began awarding Cy Youngs in both
leagues in 1967 has an NL pitcher with as many as 22 victories not
won the award.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Juan Marichal won 26 games in 1968 but trailed
Bob Gibson, who was 22-9 with a 1.12 ERA and 28 complete games to
win both Cy Young and Most Valuable Player honors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Ron Bryant went 24-12 for the Giants but was beaten by
New York's Tom Seaver, who won 19 with a 2.08 ERA and 251
strikeouts. Atlanta's Tom Glavine and San Francisco's John Burkett
each won 22 in 1993 and finished behind Greg Maddux, who was 20-10
and led the league with a 2.36 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody deserved it, Mike Hampton did,'' Astros owner
Drayton McLane Jr. said. ``His 22 wins were so important to the
Houston Astros. We didn't have any wins to spare in order to win
our division. If he won any less, we would have been in trouble. It
would have been great for him to top off his season with the Cy
Young.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were 29-5 in Hampton's starts. The Diamondbacks went
23-12 in Johnson's starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton credited his teammates for giving him the confidence to
be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty comfortable on the mound, something I've wanted
to get. It took six, seven years to get that point,'' Hampton said.
``It's been a gradual progression. You just can't jump in and say
`I'm a superstar.' I'm happy the way everything went this season.
I'm young; I'm still learning a lot about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   With Lima (21-10) and Wagner (39 saves), the Astros joined the
1974 Los Angeles Dodgers and 1998 Atlanta Braves as teams placing
three pitchers in the top five in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson earned a $250,000 bonus for winning the award. Hampton
receives a $50,000 bonus for finishing second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 0026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
