u s BC-BKN-NETS-SONICS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SONICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERSONICS DEFEAT NETS, 100-92 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Nets inspired yet more
dreams of a miraculous comeback on Monday night at the Continental
Arena, rallying from a 22-point third-quarter deficit to get the
crowd of 12,474 excited and their victimizers, the Seattle
SuperSonics, anxious.
</P>
<P>
   But the fervent charge that saw the Nets pull within 4 points
early in the fourth quarter turned out to be fruitless, only one
more tease in this two-week-old season that is growing worse with
every game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, playing for the fourth time in six days and closing
out a five-game Eastern Conference road trip, defeated the Nets,
100-92, dashing whatever optimism their hosts felt after playing
well in Friday's loss to Charlotte and lessening the belief and
that New Jersey will eventually turn its season around.
</P>
<P>
   After following the pattern they set in losses to Indiana,
Cleveland and, to a lesser degree, Phoenix, the Nets (1-6) rightly
drew no encouragement from their late-game rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to play when you're down 15, 20 points going into
the third or fourth quarter,'' said Stephon Marbury, who scored 11
of his game-high 24 points in the final period to spark the Nets'
rally. ``There's no pressure any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there is pressure mounting around this increasingly
hapless team that for the second straight season is collapsing
under the weight of playoff expectations. The frustration and
tension that is beginning to circle the Nets manifested itself in a
pregame controversy that was sparked by the return of Kerry
Kittles.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles, who drew criticism for missing the season's first six
games while recovering from surgery on his right knee, decided to
play on Monday night after an afternoon conversation with General
Manager John Nash. Keith Van Horn, who on Friday vehemently
defended Kittles's decision not to come off the injured list, was
shocked and mystified by the change that three days had made.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that some Nets officials and players had grumbled about
Kittles' inordinately long rehabilitation, Van Horn said he
believed that his teammate and good friend had been pressured into
returning prematurely. Instead of being excited about Kittles's
return, he was stone faced and disgruntled.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, after speaking with Kittles and Nash, Van
Horn retracted his statements, albeit in a sullen mode that implied
insincerity. The dispirited look never left Van Horn's face, not
during the announcement of the starting five and not during the
game. Playing a seemingly passionless game, Van Horn floundered
after scoring 6 of his 15 points to lead the Nets to a 14-6 lead in
the opening minutes.
</P>
<P>
   From there, he missed 12 of his next 15 shots, including seven
straight in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Van Horn and Kittles, who made 1 of 7 shots in scoring 3
points in 7 minutes, admitted that the situation had affected Van
Horn's play, and afterward Van Horn apologized in a much more
genuine manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt somewhat out of place,'' said Van Horn, who shot 6 for
21. ``I shouldn't have made those comments. It's none of my
business actually. It's between Kerry and the organization and I
apologize for making them. It was stupid. It did bother me, but I
still have to go out and play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn was not alone in his futility. Ending the first quarter
down, 28-27, the Nets missed their first 14 shots of the second as
Seattle turned it into a laugher by taking a 57-43 halftime lead.
Most of the misses were long jump shots, which allowed the Sonics
to run considerably and notch 21 of their 31 fast-break points in
the first half. The Nets shot 35.6 percent from the field for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Van Horn alone in his frustration. Marbury, who more
often than not has been all the Nets have going offensively, spoke
with Nash before the game about his disappointment with the team.
He is not hiding his disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated,'' said Marbury, who had five assists and shot
8 of 22 from the floor. ``I think I'm at my peak as far as
frustration. I'm working on new things to get mad at. I don't know
how to explain it. I've never been in a situation like this before.
Every day is hard. I've never lost this many games before _ in a
row. Not my whole life of playing basketball. It's something that's
totally different. It's brand new and it's not something I'm going
to adjust to. It's a battle for me.''
</P>
<P>
   On the floor with Marbury and Jamie Feick during the Nets' late
surge were the reserves Elliot Perry, Jim McIlvaine and Johnny
Newman, sparking Coach Don Casey to toss out the idea of a lineup
change. ``It's disconcerting because maybe we don't have the right
people out on the floor to start the game,'' Casey said. ``That's a
thought that has to be explored when you're 1-6.''
</P>
<P>
   After three baskets by Marbury and one each by Feick, McIlvaine
and Newman, the Nets found themselves within 83-79 with more than
eight minutes left to play. But Vin Baker reopened the deficit by
sinking three consecutive jumpers in scoring 8 of his 21 points in
the fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
