<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-MEDICARE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS SUFFERING FROM HMO STICKER SHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Johanna Roth's jaw
dropped when she got the news from HealthNet, her Medicare health
maintenance organization.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning next year, she'll have to pay full price for her
brand-name cholesterol drug instead of the $20 co-pay she's used
to. She'll pay $5 more for each visit to her primary care doctor
and $10 more to see a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   And hospital stays, which now are free, will cost her $200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so shocked,'' the 72-year-old Kansas City woman
said. ``It's a big jump. It's a really big jump. We have savings
you hope will last, but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the nation, seniors in Medicare HMOs are being hit
with the same kind of sticker shock: Benefits are being trimmed;
premiums and co-pays are being raised. Nearly 100 HMOs are pulling
out of areas they once served, leaving several hundred thousand
seniors looking for new plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest (benefits) decline in a decade,'' said
Robert Berenson, an official of the Health Care Financing
Administration, the federal agency based in Baltimore that manages
Medicare. ``It may be a premonition of what's to come in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment in Medicare HMOs has burgeoned in recent years. HMOs
typically offer benefits that aren't covered by fee-for-service
Medicare or else require steep co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more popular HMO benefits are low-cost prescription
drugs and doctor visits, free hospital stays and extras such as
eyeglasses and hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off is that HMOs restrict choices of doctors and
hospitals, something seniors appear ready to accept. The number of
people in Medicare HMOs has increased every year since 1985. There
are now 6.3 million enrolled, including about 57,000 in the Kansas
City area.
</P>
<P>
   But Medicare HMOs are in financial trouble: Fierce competition
has forced HMOs to maintain benefits even as costs have increased.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding these problems is the Balanced Budget Act of 1997,
which ordered the Health Care Financing Administration to scale
back its annual payment increases to Medicare HMOs. When the law
was passed, these HMOs were considered overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry estimates, these new rules will cost HMOs
about $33 billion through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Payments to Medicare HMOs will rise next year, on average, about
5 percent. In many urban areas, like Kansas City, the increases
will be as small as 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Jackson County, for example, the federal government will pay
HMOs an average of $535.72 a month next year for each member.
That's just $10.50 more than this year.
</P>
<P>
   With health-care inflation running about 8 percent, it's not
just Medicare HMOs that are having a hard time, Berenson said. HMOs
in the commercial market also are raising premiums and pulling out
of unprofitable areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real thing happening is the plans are now experiencing
inflation, and they can't generate additional cost savings,''
Berenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson disagreed, though, with industry contentions that the
Balanced Budget Act was the main cause of its Medicare problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Medicare HMOs may not be paid enough, ``HCFA
doesn't believe plans in aggregate are underpaid,'' he said. ``We
simply can't pay as much as the plans say they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is working on a bill that may increase Medicare
payments to HMOs and offer financial incentives for them to serve
more areas. A vote is likely this week.
</P>
<P>
   The measures won't significantly affect HMO benefits next year,
experts say. But the HMO industry is heartened by any efforts to
address what it considers to be a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important first step,'' said Karen Ignagni,
president of the American Association of Health Plans, the trade
organization representing HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Health Care Financing Administration study found that
reductions in benefits and the withdrawal of plans from some
regions will affect millions of people in 2000:
</P>
<P>
   - For the first time, all Medicare HMOs in the nation will
charge co-payments for prescription drugs. This year, more than 1
million Medicare beneficiaries had access to plans that offered
free drugs. HMO members, on average, will pay 21 percent higher
co-payments for brand-name drugs and 8 percent higher co-pays for
generics next year.
</P>
<P>
   - About 3 million beneficiaries will no longer have access to
plans that do not charge a monthly premium. Enrollees will pay on
average $15.84 in premiums each month, almost triple what they paid
this year.
</P>
<P>
   - Ninety-nine HMOs will reduce or drop their participation in
Medicare, affecting 327,000 enrollees. Of those, 79,000 will have
to return to traditional Medicare because there will be no other
HMOs available where they live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
