<SLUG> BC-HMO-MEDICARE-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIORS SUFFERING FROM HMO STICKER SHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kansas City Star
analysis of what local Medicare HMOs will offer next year turned up
many of the same trends:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two HMOs, Cigna HealthCare and United HealthCare of the Midwest,
are pulling out of the Kansas City Medicare market in 2000; and a
third plan, Humana, will no longer serve Leavenworth and Miami
counties in Kansas. Altogether, that will leave about 3,500 Kansas
City area HMO members looking for new plans next year.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Medicare HMOs of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas
City will remain unchanged in 2000. However, the plans are closed
to new members while Blue Cross remedies administrative problems
found by a Health Care Financing Administration audit.
</P>
<P>
   Other plans, such as those offered by Humana and HealthNet, will
raise their premiums. Members of some plans, such as Principal
Health Care and Kaiser Permanente, will pay more for prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of the mainstays of HMO plans, free inpatient hospital
care, has been hit.
</P>
<P>
   HealthNet will charge a $200 co-payment per visit for inpatient
stays at a general or psychiatric hospital. Principal will charge
$25 a day for inpatient psychiatric treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the erosion of benefits, Roth expects to stay with
HealthNet. It's the only plan in town that includes her doctor of
12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where else I'd go,'' Roth said. ``But it just
gets my goat.''
</P>
<P>
   HealthNet had no choice but to cut benefits because health
expenses have risen faster than Medicare reimbursements, said
company spokeswoman Cheryl Dillard.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the cost of providing medical care to seniors is
expected to jump by 10 percent; prescription drug costs will
increase by 30 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three years of holding off the tide, we needed to make
some changes,'' Dillard said. ``We hated to do it. It was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   To offer a zero-premium plan and maintain the prescription drug
benefit that enrollees considered important, HealthNet ``took some
hits in other areas,'' such as coverage of hospital stays, Dillard
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even with the 2000 increases, we are still a really good
deal compared to Medicare alone or Medicare with supplemental
insurance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's also how Shirley Harrison, 73, of Kansas City, views her
Humana HMO. Even though she'll have to pay a $10 monthly premium
for the first time, and the cost of an ambulance ride will double
to $50, the plan is still worthwhile, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say, knowing how prices have been going up in
medicine that this isn't too bad,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   But for low-income seniors, who have enrolled in Medicare HMOs
to defray their costs, the benefit cuts could become a hardship,
said Patricia Smith, senior coordinator for health issues of the
American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Many seniors, however, may not realize the extent of the changes
until next year when they're hit by higher out-of-pocket expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't look closely (at the list of benefits), you might
not get the full sense of what the changes are,'' Smith said. ``I
think we probably will see more concern through the year as more
people recognize the changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
