<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOL-DEATH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY TRUMAN'S TAILOR DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sol Stolowy was Harry
Truman's tailor for more than 20 years but was not known to boast
about it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Status did not mean much to Stolowy, a Leawood, Kan., man who
died early Monday morning at age 91.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very humble man. He never looked for honor,'' said
Stolowy's daughter, Laurel Rogovein of Overland Park, Kan. ``It was
the friendship of Truman that he loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Stolowy, a Polish immigrant, arrived in Kansas City in the 1920s
and went to work at the Kansas City Custom Garment Co. In the early
1950s he bought the company.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak in the late '50s and early '60s, the company on 10th
Street employed more than 100 and turned out 600 suits a week.
</P>
<P>
   Truman was not Stolowy's only prominent customer. He also made
suits for Clarence Kelley, a Kansas City police chief and later FBI
director; Hank Stram, a Chiefs coach; and H. Roe Bartle, a Kansas
City mayor.
</P>
<P>
   One of Stolowy's memories of Truman was a conversation that he
recounted for a reporter more than 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I said to him, `You know, Mr. President, I come from
Poland, and never could this happen for a Jewish boy to be making
clothes for a president. Only in America.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he says: `In the U.S., anything can happen. I was a farm
boy, and I became president.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Rogovein said a raincoat that still hangs in the foyer of the
Truman home in Independence was made by her father.
</P>
<P>
   Truman was still president when Stolowy first made a suit for
him. Two of Truman's local friends referred him to Stolowy. In
1972, Truman died and was buried in a suit Stolowy made for him
earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Stolowy worked long hours in his business, habitually rising at
5 a.m. and arriving before 7. He worked late into the evenings, and
sometimes half-days on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   He closed his company in the early 1980s but opened a small
tailor shop across the street a week later. He retired in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stolowy remained active in retirement, making vests for friends
and family members, both male and female. He also donated vests for
sale at the Truman Library.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a glow, a twinkle, a love of life and a love of
people that came forth in him,'' said Rabbi Alan Cohen, a family
friend for 10 years. ``He had a wonderful way of making people feel
comfortable and important around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Services will be at 1:30 p.m. today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
