<SLUG> BC-SNELL-FINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS SEEKS $1.5 MILLION FINE FROM ONLINE UNIVERSITY PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The president of the
online Monticello University should be fined $1.5 million for
deceiving students, Kansas authorities say.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leslie Edwin Snell, a former Olathe resident, also should be
forced to pay damages to students, the state attorney general's
office states in a motion filed last week in Johnson County
District Court.
</P>
<P>
   The state filed a civil lawsuit in August against Snell and
about a dozen entities with which Snell is associated, including
Monticello, formerly was known as Thomas Jefferson University.
</P>
<P>
   The suit accuses Snell of violating the state's Consumer
Protection Act, its Charitable Organizations and Solicitations Act,
its General Corporation Code and its common law prohibiting the
unauthorized practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   Monticello misled students by promising ``real'' college degrees
when the degrees were not recognized by any accrediting agency
acknowledged by the U.S. Department of Education, the state said.
In addition, the state said, the university's advertisements and
brochures led students to think that the university had trained
faculty and staff when it had not.
</P>
<P>
   Snell, who put his Cedar Creek home up for sale and is thought
to have moved to Dallas, has failed to respond to the charges in
the time period allowed by law, according to the motion filed Nov.
9. Snell should be found guilty by default, the state says.
</P>
<P>
   The state's request is to go before District Judge Larry McClain
on Nov. 30. The judge could find Snell guilty and assess penalties
at that time, state Assistant Attorney General Derek Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   Snell could not be reached Monday. But he has denied wrongdoing
in previous communications with The Kansas City Star and in papers
filed with the district court.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 3 fax to McClain, which has been made part of the
court file, Snell wrote that he could not afford an attorney to
defend him because the state had frozen his assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about my right to due process, my right to hire counsel,
my right to privacy, my right not to have my name defamed without
benefit of a fair judicial hearing?'' Snell wrote. All the
information in Monticello's brochures is true, Snell wrote, so
``how can this material be construed to be deceptive? How can truth
be untruth at the same time?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this can happen in America in our day and time
has Thomas Jefferson rolling in his grave. The American Revolution
is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Snell says Kansas has no authority over Monticello because
Monticello did not do business in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Snell worked out of an Overland Park office building owned by
one of his entities. The building was home to Education Management
Associates, a Snell entity that provided educational services.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have not been able to find any home office for
Monticello other than the Overland Park office, which is off
College Boulevard. The Web site, www.monticelloui.org, has listed
several mailing addresses. One was in the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   As of July, Monticello had done business with about 250
students, the state's motion says. Monticello has been incorporated
in Hawaii since February 1998. Thomas Jefferson University was
incorporated in Hawaii in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas officials, with the court's permission, have frozen
accounts related to Snell in three area banks. The accounts total
less than $40,000, court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   The court, at the state's request, has agreed that proceeds from
the sale of the Overland Park office building should be sent to the
court. The building is worth roughly $860,000, court documents say.
</P>
<P>
   Snell's Cedar Creek home, which had a for-sale sign in front of
it Monday, is listed at $549,950, according to a real-estate
agent's flier. Schmidt declined to say whether the state would try
to recover any proceeds from that sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
