A1076 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-COST-INSURANCE-KAN &LR;      11-16 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COST-INSURANCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES AND EMPLOYERS FEEL THE PAIN OF RISING HEALTH-CARE
PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANAS CITY, Mo. _ Week after week,
negotiations dragged on in September and October at Mallin Bros.
Co. Inc., a 71-year-old Kansas City scrap metal company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subject of the negotiations was health insurance for
Mallin's 20 or so employees, who chop up discarded copper wire and
recycle it into copper pellets.
</P>
<P>
   Mallin Bros. President Jeffrey Mallin finally signed a new
policy and swallowed a premium increase of 19 percent. The company
shouldered the entire premium cost but is feeling the strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting out of hand,'' Mallin said. ``It's a balancing
act between being financially responsible for your company and
trying to give your employees the same benefit package they've been
receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Kansas City area and across the country,
thousands of other businesses are wrestling with the same dilemma.
Industry experts say corporate health-care costs will rise by 7
percent to 25 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers vary widely, with the highest rate increases hitting
small businesses and consumers who have individual policies.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners may feel compelled to offer health insurance to
attract and keep qualified workers, but crunching the numbers can
give them nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't keep up with 15- to 20-percent rate increases,''
said Mark Whiting, a principal with the Kansas City office of the
William M. Mercer Inc. benefits consulting firm. ``It's not
tolerable. It eats into their bottom lines too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Many business owners face these rising costs with resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like electricity bills,'' said Jan Fichman, owner of
the 7th Heaven music and accessories stores in the Kansas City
area, Lawrence and Sedalia.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some things businesses can do to lighten their
health cost burden a bit. Some shift more costs to employees, while
others seek out special programs.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Wilcoxson, a St. Louis-based benefits consultant with
Hewitt Associates, said employers typically pay about 80 percent of
premium costs, with employees paying the rest, though the range may
vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the split, Wilcoxson said many of his clients are
making their workers pay a bigger share of the premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients want to continue covering the benefit, but as the
costs are dramatically increasing, they also have to consider their
bottom line,'' Wilcoxson said.
</P>
<P>
   However, many employers hesitate to make their workers pay more
for fear of losing those workers in a competitive labor market,
Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Nov. 9, Hewitt Associates said companies are
seeing rate increases of 8 percent to 10 percent for next year.
That represents a significant boost over this year's average rate
increase of 7.8 percent, which was the highest rise since the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, an Illinois-based management consulting firm, said that
next year, most major companies will pay an average of $4,853 in
health-care costs for each employee, up from $4,412 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts give several reasons for the revved-up rates,
including expensive medical technology, legislative mandates on
HMOs and the rising cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Bowser, executive vice president and chief operating officer
of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City, said drug costs for
the area's largest insurer are going up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that new drugs, even expensive ones, save on health
care in the long run. But that argument provides little or no
comfort to those caught in the vise of rising costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's undeniable that these drugs keep people out of the
hospital and reduce the need for surgery, but those benefits are
not measurable,'' Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   And ``lifestyle'' drugs, such as Celebrex for arthritis, may do
little to keep people out of the hospital, Whiting said.
</P>
<P>
   Also driving costs up are managed-care companies looking for
higher premiums to boost their/ bottom lines. On the provider side,
doctors and hospitals say they've been cut to the bone by reduced
fees and are demanding more compensation.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, consumers demand that health plans not limit
their choices of doctors, hospitals and treatments. More choice may
contribute to higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   There also has been some speculation that premiums will be
pushed up by a move to give doctors more control over patient-care
decisions, such as the policy announced last week by
UnitedHealthcare.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealthcare, a subsidiary of UnitedHealth Group, said it no
longer would require doctors to seek approval before recommending
medical treatment or hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another year of turmoil in the health-care industry,''
Jack Bruner of Hewitt said in a statement. ``With no clear answer
to any of these issues, health-care costs will continue to rise,
leaving companies to wonder how much longer they can afford to
offer health care to their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, some companies feel that they can't afford to
offer as much as they used to. Pete Spalitto, owner of Spalitto's
Prescription Pharmacy on Independence Avenue, said many of his
customers have been hit with higher prescription costs because
their employers have cut back on drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Spalitto said two of his customers were unable to pick up their
prescriptions recently because they had exceeded the annual limit
of what their health plans would pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pretty upset,'' Spalitto said. ``There's a lot of
anxiety when you can't afford to get your prescription filled.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are seeing their patients fight similar battles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year, we have had many patients whose care was
interrupted or threatened to be interrupted because they couldn't
afford to get the insurance policy they wanted,'' said Richard
Hellman, an endocrinologist and president-elect of the Metropolitan
Medical Society of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Holland Jr., assistant vice president for corporate
benefits at Sprint Corp., said Sprint expects its health-care costs
to go up between 9 percent and 15 percent in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Holland said Sprint, the area's largest private employer, is
searching for better ways to buy high-quality health care.
</P>
<P>
   That search can be more difficult for small businesses, which
have less negotiating power and fewer employees to share insurance
risk.
</P>
<P>
   About half of businesses with 25 or fewer employees can't afford
to provide their workers with health insurance, said Shawne
McGibbon, assistant chief counsel for food, drug and health policy
at the U.S. Small Business Administration's Office of Advocacy in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injustice is rather obvious,'' McGibbon said. ``Until some
sort of mechanism can be developed to control rising
health-insurance costs, it's unlikely that the rising number of
uninsured will be able to obtain health insurance in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest for health insurance presents many tough choices.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Slosburg, president of the Daniel Slosburg Co. insurance
agency in Prairie Village, said he encourages his customers to
examine all the alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a business owner may have to choose between dental
coverage or disability coverage. Slosburg said he'd recommend a
disability plan, but many workers would prefer a dental plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you have to weigh what's best for the employees vs. what
the employees' perception is, and where the company is going to
spend its dollars,'' Slosburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Some turn to group plans designed for small businesses, such as
ChamberCHOICE, a program endorsed by the Greater Kansas City
Chamber of Commerce and operated by Blue Cross and Blue Shield of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Ross, vice president of MHM Business Services in Kansas
City, said one of the best ways to save money on health insurance
is to use an Internal Revenue Code Section 125 tax savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   In what is known as a premium-only Section 125 plan, employees
pay their portion of insurance premiums on a pre-tax basis. The
arrangement saves money for both employees and employers, Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sprint's Holland said rising premiums will
ultimately affect everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, employees pay for all of these services,'' Holland
said. ``People think this hurts companies. It doesn't hurt
companies, it hurts consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 0045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
