<HEADLINE>
FARMLAND PLANS JOINT VENTURE WITH OTHER CO-OPS TO RUN FEED
OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANAS CITY, Mo. _ Farmland Industries
Inc. and merger partner Cenex Harvest States Cooperatives plan to
form a joint venture company with Land O'Lakes to own and run the
three co-ops' feed operations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Land O'Lakes in Arden Hills, Minn., would run the feed company,
which has not taken a name, under a management contract. All three
co-ops would own the company, based on the economic interests each
brought to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The venture would include research and development, production,
distribution and marketing of formula feed and feed ingredients.
Other segments would involve animal health products and pet and
specialty products. The co-ops' feed manufacturing facilities and
other related assets would be included in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Its sales would equal about $1.5 billion, based on the three
co-ops' 1998 operations.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary agreement on the feed venture is similar to one
the co-ops signed earlier to create a joint venture for their
agronomy operations. These include crop seed, plant food and crop
protection products. The agronomy venture, however, would be run by
co-presidents from Farmland and from Cenex/Land O'Lakes Agronomy
Co., which already combines their agronomy operations.
</P>
<P>
   Both ventures would take effect March 1. That is the same date
that Farmland and Cenex plan to merge into United Country Brands.
Their member owners will vote on the merger later this month.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger isn't approved, the joint venture agreements
``might have to be reconsidered,'' Farmland spokeswoman Sherlyn
Manson said.
</P>
<P>
   Manson said the effect on jobs was unknown at this point.
Farmland's feed division has about 150 employees at the co-op's
Kansas City headquarters. She said the feed venture's headquarters
probably would be in Arden Hills, Minn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
