<HEADER>
A1082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NEWTON-FASHION-ART-NY     11-16 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWTON-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMUT NEWTON'S NEW BOOK, WITH COFFEE TABLE ATTACHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He calls her Junie and she calls him Helmie, and they
think nothing of photographing each other in the nude. But after 50
years of marriage and countless examples of their uniquely homey
intimacy _ he soaking in the family tub, she opening her blouse for
a postprandial peek _ June Newton says there's really no secret to
her union with her photographer husband, Helmut.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one, we've never found it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Newton, a trim-looking woman in her early 70s, who
photographs under the name Alice Springs, was at Christie's on
Sunday night for a cocktail party given for her husband's latest
endeavor, a 480-page booked aptly titled ``Sumo.''
</P>
<P>
   To give an idea of just how big ``Sumo'' is, it weighs 66.1
pounds and comes with its own portable coffee table (a folding
metal stand designed by Philippe Starck), and if you had looked
down from the second-floor balcony at Christie's to the copy opened
in the lobby below, you could have, for example, clearly made out
Charlotte Rampling's right nipple.
</P>
<P>
   It also costs a whopping $1,500 (table included).
</P>
<P>
   Not that this is a deterrent. Its publisher, Benedikt Taschen,
said 7,000 of its 10,000 numbered and signed copies had already
been ordered by booksellers and individual buyers. Taschen, who
described the technical problems of producing such a mammoth volume
as a three-year headache, nonetheless gave an uncomplicated reason
for doing it in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to build a monument to the most important
photographer of the 20th century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, 79, is certainly one of the most controversial
photographers ever to apply the notion of sin to fashion and
celebrity. Born in Berlin in 1920 to prosperous Jewish parents (his
father, a dead ringer for the actor Erich von Stroheim, was a
button manufacturer), Newton didn't achieve real fame until the
1970s, when he was already middle-aged and had suffered a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1987 profile in Vanity Fair, June Newton said that the
heart attack somehow gave him the freedom to evoke the hedonistic
days of his youth.
</P>
<P>
   As Newton said in 1987, when his images of leather-bound
Valkyries could still rile feminists and magazine readers _
especially of American Vogue, which had more than 1,000
subscriptions canceled after a Newton shoot depicting two women, a
man and a couple of dogs in a sexual pose _ ``My generation had all
the fun in the world, because Berlin was as wild as it could be.
There was a surfeit of nice girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, of course, nobody gets terribly worked up by images of
naked women smiling cryptically through a haze of cigarette smoke
and couture veiling, largely because Newton, in his grandfatherly
status as ``the king of kink'' (to borrow a phrase that causes him
delinquent giggles), has inspired so many contemporary
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that Newton has always been something of an
enigma: an outsider who spent most of his early adult years in
Australia, his wife's native country; a self-described ``square''
who said he has never gotten excited by his erotic photo sessions;
a provocateur who can evoke the hidden, the unspeakable, yet who
seems to hate to be touched. When a hustling member of the
paparazzi corps working the cocktail party attempted to push him
into a cozy portrait with a young woman in a daring top, Newton
abruptly broke away, leaving the woman smiling awkwardly.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Capitan, a former Newton model who later became his
stylist, was standing near the railing, looking down at the big
book as guests slowly turned the heavy pages. ``There is always
some kind of story behind his work,'' she said. ``It's always more
than a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 0047EST &QL; 
