<HEADER>
A1083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-NEWTON-FASHION-ART-2N     11-16 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWTON-FASHION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: a picture.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As she spoke, the page turners stopped at an image of a nude
woman whose body was resting halfway inside the mouth of a stuffed
crocodile. Ms. Capitan smiled. She had been the stylist on that
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl's legs were so hairy,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Did they have to be shaved?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Capitan laughed. ``No, no,'' she said. ``He's into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, at the Mercer Hotel where he and his wife were staying,
Newton spoke about his big book, his marriage and his thoughts
about current fashion photography. He is a bit frail, though no
more so than one might expect for a person of his years, and he has
an unhurried, almost mischievous manner. When a visitor stopped at
a picture of a model in lingerie and remarked that she had a
similar rig, Newton smiled and said in his Good Doctor tone, ``Tell
me more.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his initial response to Taschen's monumental proposal, Newton
said: ``He was very smart. He brought a cardboard dummy of the book
to show me with several of my pictures in it. The first one was of
my wife sitting half naked in our kitchen.'' Newton laughed
hoarsely. ``Anyway,'' he went on, ``I said yes, like a fool. It
meant a year of sleepless nights worrying about the quality of the
reproduction.'' He said he was happy with the book, which his wife
largely edited from his archives, including pictures that had never
before been published.
</P>
<P>
   As the visitor stopped at another page, this one with a model in
a bra and a saddle, Newton mused, ``I've always been accused of _
what's the word?''
</P>
<P>
   Decadence?
</P>
<P>
   ``Decadence!'' he roared ``And I was very pleased about that.''
He looked at the picture. ``It's not very daring,'' he said.
``There's no nudity. Of course, the saddle was probably the most
expensive saddle there is. Hermes.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't very impressed by current photography. ``There's a lot
of pornographic pictures taken by the young today,'' he said.
``There's a magazine, Purple.'' He frowned. ``A lot of the nudity
is just gratuitous. But someone who makes me laugh is David
LaChapelle. I think he's very bright, very funny, and good.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton has managed to be so daring within the context of a
decades-long contract with Conde Nast. He has not needed so-called
avant-garde forums like Visionaire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone from Visionaire called me up and said they couldn't
give me a lot of money but that I could do any kind of picture I
want.'' He snorted. ``I said, `Listen, I get a lot of money and I
still do what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Newton and his wife have divided their time
between an apartment in Monte Carlo and a suite at the Chateau
Marmont in Los Angeles. He danced around the subject of his
marriage, then said: ``I'm very lucky. I mean, June's a pretty rare
woman. Intelligent. Supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I never believe what young people say, that you
become a unit, that if you love each other, you become like one
person.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled. ``It's rather horrifying to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He paused over an image of a woman walking through a darkened
Paris street in nothing but an open fur coat. Published in the
1970s in French Vogue, it was one of the images that made Newton's
reputation. Now, he said it was inspired by an old German story.
</P>
<P>
   Newton clucked his tongue. ``Every European boy,'' he said,
``lives with the notion _ maybe not anymore, but certainly in my
generation _ that he will meet that girl in the coat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
