<HEADLINE>
CASINO OFFICIALS AND CUSTOMERS APPLAUD OPEN BOARDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Bonnie and Ken
Waterman did something unusual Monday morning.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mother and son from Wyandotte County in Kansas passed
through Argosy Riverside Casino's turnstiles at 8:46 a.m., becoming
that gambling boat's first open-boarding guests and among the first
in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Bonnie Waterman. ``I don't like to wait to
lose my money.''
</P>
<P>
   The open-door policy, now authorized statewide by the Missouri
Gaming Commission, allows customers to enter a casino at any time.
Gamblers still are limited to buying no more than $500 in chips or
gambling tokens every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Under open boarding, players must have a club card that is
swiped electronically. It monitors their compliance with the $500
rule and tracks them as they gamble, exit and re-enter the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Most riverboats have added extra sign-up stations for club
cards. The process takes a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the new club card system eliminates the need
to stand in line for a paper boarding ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a nuisance,'' Kansas City retiree John Riley said
Monday of Missouri's complex boarding rules. ``People from out of
town just didn't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the old rule, patrons could enter a casino only during the
first 45 minutes of each two-hour ``cruise'' session. If they left,
they could not reboard until the next cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Gaming Commission adopted the rule in 1994 to
equalize competition in St. Louis among Missouri-based boats that
cruised and others that were permanently docked.
</P>
<P>
   When casino boats on the Illinois side of the Mississippi River
abandoned similar boarding rules this summer, Missouri boats
lobbied the commission for a level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Open boarding in St. Louis started in August. Admissions and
revenue are up dramatically since.
</P>
<P>
   Local gamblers will notice a few other changes.
</P>
<P>
   Station Casino's River Queen will be closed Monday through
Friday until 5 p.m. The mirror-image River King has been
reconfigured and restocked with a wider variety of games and has
more entrances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll learn as we go,'' said John Finamore, Station's Midwest
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no layoffs. We were able to shift the work force
from one boat to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's smaller North Star vessel will open at 11 a.m. instead
of 9 a.m. Monday through Friday, said Harrah's marketing director,
Pucka Tomasic. That boat's last weekday cruise in the early morning
hours also will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In coming weeks, guests at Harrah's can also expect to be met by
an usher to answer questions about open boarding and help smooth
the club card sign-up process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate guests whose patterns of behavior will still
mimic the top-of-the-hour rush,'' Tomasic said. ``It's going to
take a few months for the market to flatten out.''
</P>
<P>
   Open boarding is a welcome change at the single-boat Argosy and
Flamingo Hilton casinos, where the wait between sessions was 75
minutes and drove business away.
</P>
<P>
   The twin boat operations staggered their cruise schedules and
cut the wait to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pain,'' said Erma Madck of Kansas City, North,
shortly before 8 a.m. Monday while waiting for the Flamingo Hilton
Casino to open for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's times I want to eat and then go back down (on the
casino floor). You can do that anywhere but in Missouri,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' said Frank Payne of Basehor, who
also was in line at the Flamingo first thing Monday morning. ``I
don't like waiting in lines. I had enough of that in the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Lopez of Kansas City, North, said open boarding wouldn't
have much effect on the morning gambling expeditions he and his
wife regularly take to the Flamingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come early to be the first ones on board and get the (slot)
machines we want,'' he said. ``We'll have to wait (for the casino
to open) tomorrow morning too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
