<SLUG> BC-STATION-CASINOS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT AUTHORITY APPROVES FLAMINGO HILTON SALE TO STATION CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hilton Hotels Corp.
tried to make a clean break with Kansas City, but legally it must
keep one foot in town even after Station Casinos Inc. buys its
Flamingo Hilton Casino.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Port Authority on Monday gave its approval for
the $22.5 million sale. The deal still needs the Missouri Gaming
Commission's endorsement. A meeting tentatively set for Wednesday
has been pushed back to Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's unanimous vote permits Hilton essentially to sublease
its right to operate a riverboat casino on public land and allows
Station to fulfill all of Hilton's other obligations under a
development agreement with the city.
</P>
<P>
   However, because Hilton's $3 million in annual rent payments to
the city is the financial underpinning for more than $21 million in
Port Authority public improvement bonds sold years ago, Hilton
cannot just disappear unless those agreements are rewritten to
include Station and the bonds are resold. That's not likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hilton is going to remain liable to the Port Authority,'' Port
Authority Chairman Bill Johnson said Monday. ``In essence, we have
strengthened our hand'' by adding Station as a lessee.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the bond proceeds helped pay for the
construction of Richard L. Brkley Riverfront Park on land west of
the casino site.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of both gambling companies were on hand Monday.
Hilton attorney Jerry Riffel said that because of the bond
agreements, it was difficult legally for Hilton to just walk away,
which it wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the Port Authority's requirements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Station now will press the Gaming Commission for a quick
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``This needs to get done by the end of the year,'' said Troy
Stremming, Station's Midwest counsel. Station had hoped to close
the Hilton deal by Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   An Illinois-based group that issued a late bid to buy the
Flamingo has appealed to the Gaming Commission to reject the sale
to Station on grounds that the company would control about half of
the Kansas City gambling market.
</P>
<P>
   The group made no public appeals to the Port Authority for its
support.
</P>
<P>
   Documents made public Monday disclosed that Station's Missouri
subsidiary that would operate the Flamingo would be a limited
liability corporation called Front Street Station.
</P>
<P>
   However, John V. Finamore, Station's Midwest president, said the
casino itself would operate under a different name. Finamore said
he would disclose Station's redevelopment plans and the new name in
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Other documents disclosed that Hilton's gravel valet parking lot
was in violation of city codes. It wasn't clear who will have to
pave the lot and bring it into compliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority on Monday also approved new terms for a 1996
agreement that spells out how Station is to involve minorities and
women in purchasing and ownership matters.
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened in January 1997, Station has met authority
quotas for hiring women and minorities. But both Station and the
Flamingo have fallen short of similar goals for buying goods and
services from minority- and women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement, pushed hard by the Black Chamber of Commerce
of Greater Kansas City, applies to both casinos. It calls for about
35 percent of the casinos' purchases to be from disadvantaged
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mabin, Black Chamber president, was cautiously optimistic
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better off than we were two months ago,'' he said. ``If
we can continue to build relationships with Station and get some
better monitoring and enforcement from the Port Authority, it could
work. ... We want to see greater opportunities for minority-owned
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for 10 percent minority participation
in the ownership of the Front Street Station corporation and a
Missouri subsidiary that owns Station Casino Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
