<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-SPI &LR;      11-16 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
  
 Huskies QB Tuiasosopo takes blame better praise  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the land of faltering Northwest stock prices, do
not include Marques Tuiasosopo with the Microsofts, the Boeings or
the Amazon.coms. His stock remains solid, if only because
Tuiasosopo is such a solid citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, when Washington's junior quarterback set an
NCAA record by passing for 302 yards and rushing for 207 in leading
the Huskies to a made-for-TV, Pac-10 victory over league-leading
Stanford, Tuiasosopo refused to accept praise for founding the
``300/200'' club.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for any of us who have watched even a bit of big-time
sports in the last few years, when stars just can't lay off the
urge to self-aggrandize, it really merits repeating what ``Tui''
did:
</P>
<P>
   He refused to take credit.
</P>
<P>
   He denied himself even a whiff of pleasure in acknowledging that
maybe, just maybe, his amazing performance was due to his personal
brand of warrior-like competitiveness _ especially since that
particular Saturday Tui was working with sore hindquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to the Tuiasosopo found Monday on the UW campus _
the dark-haired, wonderfully mannered, look-you-in-the-eye kind of
college player eating a monstrous helping of lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hungry,'' Tuiasosopo said, head bent over his plate while
admitting he had slept through breakfast and needed to make up lost
calories.
</P>
<P>
   And that wasn't the only thing he wants to make up for.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, after a string of victories over California,
Stanford and Arizona that gave the Huskies a 5-1 conference record,
Tuiasosopo made a fifth appearance on regional TV _ in the Rose
Bowl of all places _ and came up looking much more human than he
had in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, as he mastered the option and earned calls from ABC
football announcers as the early favorite for the 2000 Heisman
Trophy, Tuiasosopo was gaining stature of almost mythic proportions
_ and it seemed perfectly appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The TV camera would show Tui walking calmly to the line, calling
for the snap just as the play clock ticked down to zero, faking a
handoff and then breaking off a 17-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, the camera would then find Tui's father, Manu
Tuiasosopo, the former Seahawk who lives and dies with every play _
especially since it became excitingly clear that as Tuiasosopo
goes, so go the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   To say that the Huskies lost to the UCLA Bruins because
Tuiasosopo could not raise his level of play and take along his
entire Husky team _ as he seems to have done most all season _
would seem unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you asked Tui about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take full responsibility for the offensive part of it,''
Tuiasosopo said Monday, still trying to digest the loss and the
Rose Bowl implications and, most important, his team's psyche
heading into the regular-season finale against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``As quarterback, you've got to make decisions and get the ball
into people's hands,'' Tuiasosopo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't on the field much in the second half, and as
quarterback, I take responsibility for that. A lot of what goes on
in the offense is directed by the quarterback. That's why it kills
me so much. We weren't able to stay on the ball. We weren't able to
keep the defense rested and put points on the board and let the
defense come out and fly around and hit people and have fun,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In overtime, we had a couple of chances to score, and that
didn't happen. Then I wound up ending it with an interception. I
just didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 48 hours, Tuiasosopo said he has spent a ton of
time going over what happened against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, man. This was worse than any other weekend. There
were so many plays I'd like to have back,'' he said, reeling
through them.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there isn't anyone in the state of Washington, except for
Cougar fans, who doesn't empathize with Tuiasosopo for his
anguished mental playback over missed opportunities last Saturday
in a game the Huskies wanted, needed, could have had.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there isn't anyone who has not watched the Huskies
this supposed-to-be-low-expectation season and not born witness to
the surprisingly wondrous emergence of Washington's option offense,
led by Tui.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl dream was a heck of a lot of fun this past week.
But Tuiasosopo vows he is not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been raised to be competitive. I always want to be the
best. I want a team I play with to be the best. I want the guys to
be the best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Way back when I started playing sports, my dad asked me if I
wanted to play sports for fun or if I wanted to play to play. I
said I want to play to play. I want to do it. Ever since then,
winning is the best feeling the world, especially in a team game,
and that's what's important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bowl or no Rose Bowl, Tuiasosopo has done his job this
season. And Rose Bowl or no Rose Bowl, there is still a reason to
anticipate what he does this Apple Cup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
