<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ZEILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TALKING TO ZEILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers could be getting close to
re-signing third baseman Todd Zeile. The process with pitcher Aaron
Sele could take longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have exchanged proposals with Zeile's agent, Seth
Levinson, and Zeile said they should know soon if a deal can be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic we're going to try and do everything we can get
to get it done,'' Zeile said. ``As I said before, I enjoyed my stay
in Texas, it was the best baseball experience I've ever had, and my
first priority is to try and get something done with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said he spoke Monday with
Levinson and ``we'll continue to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal could be complicated by the Los Angeles Dodgers'
situation with third baseman Adrian Beltre. His agent, Scott Boras,
has filed a grievance asking Beltre be declared a free agent,
claiming the Dodgers signed him at age 15. Earlier this year, the
Dodgers lost two Cuban players because they signed before they were
16.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile could be interested in returning to the Dodgers because he
and his family make their permanent home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something came up with the Dodgers, I'd certainly have to
give it consideration,'' Zeile said. ``But at this time I'm a
realist, and, looking at it more from the skeptic side of things,
it's hard to consider an opportunity lcc &QR; uhat until it comes to
fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin also met with Sele's agent, Adam Katz, Monday and made a
formal offer. Melvin declined to reveal the offer but admitted the
process is only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked, and we're going to continue to talk,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Katz was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he would like to get something done quickly but
added: ``Among free agents, I see a reluctance for people to sign.
I think they want to wait until somebody makes a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Two possible benchmarks for Sele's contract are the four-year,
$32 million contract that Todd Stottlemyre signed with Arizona last
year and the three-year, $24 million contract Darryl Kile signed
with Colorado two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But much depends on the demand. Several clubs have reportedly
expressed interest in Sele, most notably Seattle and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be competition,'' Melvin said. ``There are
enough teams looking for pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Much also depends on other free-agent starting pitchers,
including David Cone, Kenny Rogers, Chuck Finley and Darren Oliver.
The Rangers are interested in all four, and Melvin is not waiting
on Sele.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've touched base with some of the other free-agent
pitchers,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin hasn't ruled out trading for more starting pitching.
Several starters are available, including Kile, Los Angeles' Ismael
Valdes and Darren Dreifort, Tampa Bay's Wilson Alvarez and Rolando
Arrojo, and Toronto's David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the possibility of a trade, but the problem is
giving up players we want to put on our team,'' Melvin said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
