<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-POWER </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SEARCHING FOR SOME POWERFUL MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
 PLAY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Doctor, the Stars have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   What's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Well, they don't exactly know.
</P>
<P>
   What are the symptoms?
</P>
<P>
   They're coughing up power-play opportunities, 3-for-24 with a
man advantage in their past seven games despite plenty of good
chances. Think about what a power-play goal here or there could
have done; four of their past seven losses have come by two goals
or less.
</P>
<P>
   Can you prescribe anything, doc?
</P>
<P>
   Well, nine out of 10 doctors agree, score one or two goals, and
they'll feel better in the morning. The Stars have scored a
power-play goal in each of their past two victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all it's going to take,'' Stars winger Brett Hull
agreed, ``a fluky goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting that power-play-stoking goal has proven to be harder
than skipping through flu season unaffected, and has left Stars
players and coaches in search of alternate remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Wear teams down, Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Become multidimensional, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Be patient, Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said, because sooner
or later a unit featuring Hull, Mike Modano and Joe Nieuwendyk at
forward is bound to score. That's why Hitchcock has decided to play
them together as an even-strength line against Washington on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always find when you put good players together success
happens because they work at it and stay with it,'' Hitchcock said.
``I find it doesn't work when they expect it to happen easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like he's talking about the Stars' power-play problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock isn't a doctor, but he has spent a good portion of
this season trying to heal what ails their aching power play.
</P>
<P>
   His studies have, at least, pinpointed one problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one-dimensional,'' Hitchcock said. ``You have to be
multidimensional on the power play. I really think that the power
play has to start relying on five guys individually rather than
Hull to shoot the puck and Zubie to pass it. I think you have to
have more than one threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Zubov needs to pepper the goalie with shots when left alone
at the point. Hull needs to find open teammates when defenders
crash in to try to prevent his less-than-secret slap shot from the
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, Nieuwendyk and Sydor need to get jump-started because
the Stars know what those power plays can do for them. Last season,
the Stars converted 18.8 percent of their regular-season power
plays; the same numbers would rank them ninth in the NHL this
season instead of 21st, where they currently are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something last year that put us over the edge a lot in
games,'' Modano said. ``The first four months, it was clicking at a
good rate, and it won a lot of games for us. It gave a lot of guys
confidence and the team confidence that when we were on it there
was a good chance we'd score on the majority of our opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's been struggling, and our team has been
struggling scoring (even-strength) goals. It kind of goes hand in
hand, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Modano-Nieuwendyk-Hull line provides a remedy to that
problem as well as a few others.
</P>
<P>
   Modano and Hull have been looking for a linemate while Jere
Lehtinen recovers from a fractured ankle. Nieuwendyk has been
looking for a line since rookie Roman Lyashenko took his spot
centering the Stars' second line.
</P>
<P>
   So necessity and curiosity prompted Hitchcock to create his
paycheck line, bringing together players that have combined for 15
goals and 20 assists this season. They certainly have the tools to
generate more scoring for a team that has averaged slightly more
than two goals a game this season. They can handle the puck, shoot
and skate, all at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of good lines in the league can do those
things,'' Modano said. ``You get other teams thinking about who
they are going to check, chances are good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's only concern is that the Stars' struggle to turn
skill into points on the power play might be contagious, and he
can't afford to have his top line ailing just as his power play
looks to be close to finding a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel it getting better and better,'' Zubov said. ``We're
getting chances. Now, we have to get a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what the doctor ordered. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
