<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING GALLOWAY SPARKS SEAHAWKS' GREAT ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ His stat line in the newspaper Monday made it
look like just another game for Joey Galloway: 4 catches, 88 yards,
0 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four seasons with the Seahawks, the mercurial
Galloway had 26 games where he caught more passes, 19 games where
he had more receiving yards and 27 games with at least one scoring
catch.
</P>
<P>
   But what Galloway did at the Kingdome Sunday was closer to the
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   One week removed from playing flag football in Ohio, six days
after ending his 101-day holdout and with only three practices
under his belt, Galloway made plays that helped his team escape
with a 20-17 victory over the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' he said Monday. ``But I think
it worked out pretty well for me from the standpoint of getting in
there and getting my feet wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wet feet? Galloway's up-to-his-armpits effort was a life
preserver in a game where it appeared the Seahawks had gone into
the tank in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Or as running back Ricky Watters said after the victory that
pushed the team's division-leading record to 7-2, ``We couldn't
have won it without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of Galloway's catches was better than the last. Each helped
turn jeers from the sold-out Kingdome crowd into cheers. Each meant
more to the team, as it struggled to overcome the Broncos' 17-10
lead.
</P>
<P>
   He opened with a modest 6-yarder on the Seahawks' opening drive
that ended with a field goal. Nothing special, except that it was
his first reception in a game since the season finale at Denver
last Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   He added a 15-yarder for a first down later in the quarter on
the drive to the Seahawks' first touchdown. A nice catch after
running a crisp route, but just a prelude.
</P>
<P>
   With the Seahawks facing a second-and-20 at the end of the third
quarter, and trailing by a touchdown, Jon Kitna lofted a pass along
the sideline. Broncos cornerback Dale Carter figured Galloway would
have to catch it out of bounds, if at all. But Galloway controlled
the ball and got both feet down for a 39-yard completion. Broncos
coach Mike Shanahan challenged the official's call, but it was
upheld after being reviewed. Four plays later, Todd Peterson kicked
a field goal to trim the Broncos' lead to 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a first-down play from the Denver 48, Kitna went to
Galloway with a pass that was slightly behind him as he crossed the
middle of the field. Galloway leaped, reached back and made the
grab for a 28-yard gain. Two plays later, Kitna passed 20 yards to
Sean Dawkins for what would be the game-winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy not having training camp and catching a lot of
passes, those were tough catches,'' coach Mike Holmgren said of
Galloway's final two receptions. ``I think if he had not caught
either ball, people would say, `Well, that was a tough catch.
That's understandable under the best of circumstances.' So that was
pretty impressive, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Big plays made even bigger because of when Galloway made them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big, big, big,'' offered cornerback Shawn Springs, who also
was a teammate of Galloway at Ohio State. ``You just expect that
stuff from Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Holmgren feared was Galloway getting injured if he was
rushed into the lineup too early. Galloway did take some hits
Sunday night, but wasn't showing any ill effects Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot better than I thought I would,'' he said. ``I did
take a couple (of hits), but I've been stretching every day with
Kent (Johnston, the strength and conditioning coach). As long as I
keep that up, then I think my body will hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Galloway is to become more immersed in the
offense. He played 22 snaps against the Broncos and Holmgren
estimated that number could increase by 10 this week when the
Seahawks play the Chiefs in Kansas City. Galloway also needs to
expand his grasp of the playbook. Sunday night, Holmgren had a
ready-list of 110 plays, but Galloway was involved in only 20.
</P>
<P>
   But Holmgren will not force Galloway on the offense at the
exclusion of Dawson, Derrick Mayes and Mike Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the tough part really is balancing that,'' Holmgren said,
``so they all get a chance to contribute and feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
