<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ALLEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' ALLEN OUT AT LEAST TWO WEEKS WITH KNEE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys won a football game but lost
perhaps their ``best player by position in the NFL'' for a minimum
of two weeks, after magnetic resonance imaging results Monday
showed a sprain of All-Pro guard Larry Allen's right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sprain,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. ``We
were really pleased. He'll be out two to four weeks, hopefully
closer to two.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who had been playing at a ``Hall of Fame level,'' as
offensive line coach Hudson Houck said, sprained the medial
collateral ligament in his right knee in Sunday's 27-13 defeat of
Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. Larry is the guy who makes it happen for us,''
Houck said. ``We'd really been coming around the last three
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, the Cowboys have rushed for an average
of 4.0 (103 on 26 carries against Indianapolis), 8.5 (205 on 24
carries against Minnesota) and 4.4 (149 on 34 carries against Green
Bay) after averaging 3.5 yards in 200 rushes through the first six
games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our offensive line intact for a few weeks in a
row,'' explained coach Chan Gailey, who was reminded by a reporter,
``Don't get used to that,'' referring to Allen's knee sprain in the
third quarter of Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get used to anything in this game,'' Gailey added
whimsically.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Cowboys is that in spite of their 5-4
record, they're in a three-way tie for first place in the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that injuries to key players continue to mount.
Aside from Allen, the injuries include:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman (concussion) was in Los Angeles on
Monday for further neurological testing. Gailey described the
chances of Aikman sitting out his second consecutive game as ``very
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith (broken right hand) will experiment
this week with a protective glove, similar to what was developed
for Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp, who had a similar
injury. Gailey noted that Smith's chances are improved by the fact
that he carries the ball in his left hand and the fracture is to
the fourth metacarpal of his right hand. But the ``extra padding''
that could speed up his ability to play is strictly experimental at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Michael Irvin (cervical contusion/genetic
condition) continues to face a decision whether to retire, though
according to sources no decision has been reached yet. Jones said
he met with Irvin on Friday to talk about the Packers game. But
Jones said, ``we didn't talk about his future. I'm not aware of
anything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback/punt returner Deion Sanders (strained right
hamstring/left groin) was on-again/off-again Sunday, playing when
perhaps he shouldn't, as the Packers failed to score on three plays
in which Sanders was rendered defenseless. But Gailey considered it
a ``positive'' sign that Sanders finished the game.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Mathis (hamstring) will not practice or play
again this week. This will be the third game in the last four weeks
that he misses.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' ongoing battle of attrition due to injuries has
produced a bunker-like mindset, Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a bunch of fighters now ... and that can carry you a
long way,'' said Gailey. ``This game was a starting point for us.
We just need to build on this, and go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Arizona, Allen will be replaced by either rookie Solomon
Page, an offensive tackle who was converted to guard briefly in
training camp because of injuries, or veteran backup Tom Myslinski,
who played most of the second half Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The long-term possibility of losing Allen would favor Page, a
second-round pick in the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best we got (to replace Allen),'' said Houck, adding
that Page's athletic ability allows him to bounce between his
natural position _ offensive tackle _ and guard, although this
isn't the same right guard position that Page played in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   If Aikman is out, Jason Garrett will continue to be the Cowboys
quarterback. Garrett, 6-2 as an NFL starter, has shown that the
Cowboys can win when he is called upon to replace Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quarterback is more about making good decisions than it is
about how strong your arm is or how far you can throw it or how
tight a spiral you have or how fast you can run,'' Gailey said.
``And Jason makes good decisions ... he doesn't hold the football
(too long). He anticipates what is given to him. He sees the
coverages and makes the right play. And he understands exactly what
his role (as a backup) is, so he is prepared for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Warren, who was benched after he fumbled twice Sunday and
was replaced by free agent Robert Chancey, will start Sunday at
Arizona if Smith is unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris didn't like it but he understood it,'' Gailey said of
the third-quarter benching. ``I talked to him after the game ...
(and) if we play this week without Emmitt again, Chris is our
starter.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said that Warren has no history of fumbling. But after
two fumbles in 19 carries, Gailey decided that Warren was out of
chances until next week. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
