<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     11-16 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FOR whatever small consolation it may be for Mike Hampton, I can
think of three fairly decent pitchers who made it to the Hall of
Fame without winning the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   The three who come easily to mind are Don Sutton, Phil Niekro
and Nolan Ryan. Idly, you wonder how Ryan missed out in 1973, when
he rang up 21 wins for the Angels, completed 26 of his starts,
pitched two no-hitters and broke the record of Sandy Koufax with
383 strikeouts in a season.
</P>
<P>
   But the award went to Jim Palmer, who had one of his typically
brilliant years for the Orioles, going 22-9 with an earned run
average of 2.40, a league best. The choice was close, and it
bothered Nolan when he read what Palmer told the press: ``Ryan goes
for strikeouts, and I go for outs.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, Nolan realized it was simply a matter of style.
</P>
<P>
   Tricky business, this Cy Young competition. Until Randy Johnson
joined him Monday, Gaylord Perry was the only pitcher to win the
award in each league. He did it with Cleveland in 1972, then
repeated himself in 1978 when he won 21 games for a weak San Diego
team. He was 40 years old at season's end.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Valenzuela was the original Teletubby at age 20 during
a 1981 season that saw him earn his trophy. The Dodgers sent a
scout to his village in Mexico to bring back his birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   It hardly seems fair, when so many pitchers would settle so
gladly for one, that Roger Clemens has collected five Cy Youngs
with Boston and Toronto and now he has a World Series ring with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But the award for the most single-minded pitcher in memory still
goes to Steve ``Lefty'' Carlton, who earned four trophies in 11
seasons and did it without talking to the press. He didn't have
much to say to the hitters, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlton did not pitch to the hitter; he pitched through him,''
his catcher, Tim McCarver, once explained. ``The batter hardly
existed for Steve. He was playing an elevated game of catch.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after he topped Robin Roberts' record for career
strikeouts by a Philadelphia pitcher, Carlton had to call the
club's publicity office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was that record I broke?'' he asked. ``Some lady wants me
to write it on a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In intensity, if not in physical appearance, Hampton inspires a
comparison to Carlton. No pitcher brings to the park a more
complete package than the combative Houston lefthander. He helps
himself at bat, with the glove and with his demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers sparkle: 22 wins, four losses, an 11-game winning
streak, an ERA under 3.00. And yet the numbers don't do him
justice. He started 34 times, and the Astros won all but five of
those games.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the club has kept a candle burning in the window for
a classic southpaw starter who can stay healthy and pile up
innings, who keeps his temper and his aim under control. Now, they
have one. This was Hampton's breakout season.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame, of course, in finishing second to Randy
Johnson, the Big Unit, the 6-10 intimidator whose tousled,
shoulder-length hair has the capacity to put hitters in a slump.
Johnson's 17-9 record failed to reflect the games when Arizona
didn't score for him or when the bullpen blew leads. But he had the
lowest ERA and the most strikeouts in the league, and he has what
Hampton has just begun to acquire: Name Brand Recognition.
</P>
<P>
   You doubt any loud protests would have been lodged if the voters
had blessed Michael, but we sense a certain irony when his Houston
teammates argue that wins should be the major criterion. When Mike
Scott captured the only Cy Young Award in franchise history in
1986, he did it with 18 wins _ but a strikeout title and a
no-hitter dripping with drama. It clinched the division title
against the Giants. Still, Valenzuela (21) and San Francisco's Mike
Krukow (20) had more victories.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching is not a stable occupation, and you never know what the
next spin of the wheel will bring. But considering Hampton is 27,
time is in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of baseball ahead of me,'' he said. ``My
confidence is at an all-time high. I'm at a point where I feel
comfortable in everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   With only the slightest nudge, Houston fans can recall the pain
of losing the National League championship to the Mets in 1986,
with Scott ready to start a seventh game that went unplayed.
</P>
<P>
   So more than their Cy Young finish, this is what bonds Randy
Johnson and Mike Hampton today. You suspect either pitcher would
forgo being considered for any trophy, any jewelry, for a chance to
pitch in the World Series. Of course, there is no rule that says
you can't do both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
