<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     11-16 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YOU ponder the fact that somehow the Rockets have become the
mystery meat of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, with the addition of Scottie Pippen, they were at
least able to sit under the shrink wrap in the butcher's case and
try to pass themselves off as top sirloin.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, they are Spam, hardly tasty and barely digestible.
</P>
<P>
   We have been told so often that the chemistry of a basketball
team is as fragile as crystal, we are almost convinced. Did the
Rockets take a hammer to theirs?
</P>
<P>
   So which is it? Are they at least taking lumps now with a hazy
purpose for the future? Or is what we are seeing the stunted growth
of a stubborn three-packs-a-day smoker who will never stand tall
enough to see the top of the kitchen table?
</P>
<P>
   This 96-87 loss to the Indiana Pacers on Monday night would not
be so painful to bear if it did not look like so many of the others
in a 2-6 start. It is still just November in the television season,
and the Rockets are already showing reruns again and again that
have less character development than an episode of Baywatch.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this one:
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets couldn't complete the job, couldn't close the door,
couldn't find the finish line if it had been painted on the ocean
and they were falling off the deck of a cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   They had the Pacers down but couldn't take them out. They had
plenty of hustle and enthusiasm but, like a class of
kindergartners, no idea what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets took a 63-53 lead and spit it back up with
turnovers, bad shots and a general lack of understanding of what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind it if a team was just better than us and came
in here with a lot more talent and beat us,'' said Hakeem Olajuwon.
``That's easy to take. But that's not the case with us. I guess we
have to learn how to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that lesson would be easier to comprehend if the Rockets
took the floor every night knowing what they were really trying to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Is this truly the dawning of a new era with a commitment to the
running game and athleticism? Or barely two weeks on one arena
referendum turndown is this already a club retreating too quickly
into the shell of its familiar former self?
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that has the rookie Steve Francis capable of
doing wonderful things, as evidenced again by his 18 points, 12
assists and six rebounds. This is a team that has Charles Barkley
working with all the pride and determination of a 16-year veteran
making his last pass through the league to grab a whopping 24
rebounds to go with his 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this remains a team that doesn't appear to have a clue as to
how to get its premier free-agent acquisition Shandon Anderson
involved in the proceeding, as indicated by another four-point game
that saw him play just 17 minutes and watch all of the fourth
quarter from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that the Rockets are not adept at handling the
ball on the run, they are surely not going to get better at it if
they don't keep the pedal to the metal and work out the kinks. This
is a club that said it was turning over a new leaf by getting rid
of the spot-up-shooting likes of Matt Maloney, Brent Price and Sam
Mack but finds itself standing under the shade of that old tree too
many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play that way, it's just too predictable,'' said
Anderson. ``Teams work the whole day on how to defend the post,
defending 3-point shooting. So when you get down to the fourth
quarter, they really have the game plan down. If we had different
options, it's really hard to defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the coaches) make the decisions. You have to run the
plays that are called. You can't go on your own and go one-on-one
and try to beat them one-on-five. It has to be a team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get better at the fast break,'' said Barkley, ``and
I don't know why we don't do it more.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, they are not doing it because they have already
talked themselves into being desperate for wins. It is so early,
and all that counts in the NBA is how you're doing late. But we are
already hearing too much about statistics and percentages and what
works.
</P>
<P>
   But let's ask this: What really is working when you're 2-6?
</P>
<P>
   When you cut off most of the running opportunities at midcourt
and settle into a half-court game, you are putting a premium on
every possession. That actually works against a bad ball-handling
team, because each turnover is more critical and there are fewer
chances to get back.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in today's plodding, conservative NBA, it is impossible to
run every time. But you can and should look to run every time. Bill
Fitch was in the house Monday night. Maybe somebody could have
asked him how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   Before we all nod off from boredom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
