<HEADLINE>
... COWBOYS GET TASTE OF REAL TRIPLETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A season can turn on this kind of team performance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's how colleague Randy Galloway ended Monday's column on the
Dallas Cowboys' 27-13 victory over the Green Bay Packers at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   All he needed for the perfect segue to Tuesday's modest essay by
yours truly was a ...
</P>
<P>
   You know: dot, dot, dot.
</P>
<P>
   To be continued, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   He is absolutely right, but don't tell him I said so. I'll even
take it a step further. I will humbly submit that Sunday's
triplet-less triumph over the staggeringly inept Packers was the
Cowboys' biggest victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That statement is made not necessarily because of how much the
victory meant, though it did shove the Cowboys back into a tie for
the NFC East lead with the Washington Redskins and New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   More critical was how devastating a loss would have been.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a team needed some good news, something positive to
build upon, it was the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   A victory over the suddenly pitiful Packers is certainly not a
panacea for everything that ails the Cowboys. They're still your
