<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL TAKES OUT FRUSTRATIONS ON PHOENIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ From multiple ejections to multiple rejections, the
pendulum that is Shaquille O'Neal's season stopped momentarily
Monday, then swung mightily in the opposite direction. The poor
Phoenix Suns were stuck in its path and got clobbered.
</P>
<P>
   As if to announce an end to the tumultuous week that was, O'Neal
put all the free-throw embarrassments, technical fouls,
disqualifications, fines and suspensions behind him and channeled
all that anger into one truly inspired performance.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four points. Eight blocked shots. Eighteen rebounds. And
a 91-82 Los Angeles Lakers victory over the explosive Suns on their
home court.
</P>
<P>
   This all came with fair warning. O'Neal himself repeated several
times that he plays better when he's teed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just an awesome game,'' coach Phil Jackson said of his
center's performance.
</P>
<P>
   And an angry game? O'Neal wouldn't say so, but his friend and
teammate Glen Rice said it was clear the big man had some tension
to unleash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, you can see it,'' Rice said. ``One of the things he's
definitely going to do is give it his all. He realizes teams are
going to take their shots at him, but he's going to stay under
control and let his game speak for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Message received.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to hear it coming either. O'Neal opened with
a 12-point first quarter and by halftime had 18 points, five
rebounds and five blocks _ two against Luc Longley, one each
against Clifford Robinson, Rodney Rogers and former teammate Penny
Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Despite logging 43 minutes and playing on a twisted left ankle,
with a sore right shoulder, O'Neal also finished strong _ 10
points, seven rebounds and two blocked shots in the fourth quarter.
He even improved his foul shooting when it counted most _ 6 of 10
in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think I dominated,'' O'Neal said. ``I still
missed too many (free) throws, but I hit one 1 of 2 when I was at
the line. I'm just going to keep practicing. It can't get no worse.
It can only get better. . . . I'm the type of player, I like to be
as close to perfect as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, who trailed by as much as 10 points in the first half,
pulled within two points at the 2:16 mark. But the Lakers were able
to pull away on a Derek Fisher 17-footer, a Glen Rice free throw,
and an O'Neal block of Hardaway. Then O'Neal hit 2 of 4 foul shots
to make it 87-80 with 1:02 to go, and the Lakers had sealed a
significant win over one of the most highly touted teams in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   And concluded for now O'Neal's strange early season odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't really been a roller-coaster ride,'' he said. ``We
lost two games, it was 100 percent my fault (for getting ejected).
I think we could have got one of those games if I was there, but
we're all still learning each other, we're all still having a good
time, I'm pleased with our record. We've played nine games _ 7-2,
that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns laid off O'Neal early, and he didn't shoot a single
free throw in the first half as he made 9 of 16 shots. That
strategy changed in the second half, and O'Neal went to the line
seven times, but made 5 of 11 field goals anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't really know what they wanted to do with him,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had plenty of support _ 23 points from Rice and 18 from
Fisher, who was 5 for 11 to post his second straight big-scoring
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher struggled, however, to contain multitalented Jason Kidd
in the second half. Jackson replaced him with the taller Brian Shaw
for a long spell but returned Fisher to the floor for the final
five minutes. He responded with five points down the stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
