<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS RECEIVERS RESORT TO PLAYING BLAME GAME AFTER LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even when things have been at their worst _ amid the
season-ending losing streaks in 1997 and 1998, and amid the
two-game losing streak they just snapped _ the Cowboys rarely were
a team that pointed fingers at one another.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith didn't single out some poor guy for
not blocking. Darren Woodson didn't single out the defensive line
for not getting any pressure on the quarterback. Michael Irvin
didn't blame the coaching staff. Team owner Jerry Jones didn't
threaten to fire the whole team if they didn't make him a bigger
return on his buck.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, it's the blame game. And the culprits, after
a 35-28 loss to the lowly Philadelphia Eagles on Sunday, were
big-mouth wide receivers Albert Connell and Michael Westbrook.
(Yes, the same Connell-Westbrook duo that said last month that
Deion Sanders couldn't cover them.)
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles began their winning drive against the Redskins late
in the fourth quarter after linebacker Al Harris ripped the ball
out of Connell's hands. Connell blamed his quarterback, Brad
Johnson, instead of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to stop an interception,'' Connell said. ``It was
a bad pass. Bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Connell also blamed the offensive line, which allowed four sacks
of Johnson. Connell said the sacks hindered the quarterback's
ability to find open receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Mike (Westbrook) were killing their corners,'' Connell
said. ``We've got to give our quarterback time.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook blamed the coaching staff for allowing certain players
to make mistakes in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain guys, it's like they can't do anything wrong,''
Westbrook said. ``No one's pointing fingers, but we need to be held
accountable for our mistakes in practice. If you're going to make
mistakes, someone needs to tell someone something. I'm told when I
make mistakes. It should be fair, is all I'm saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Westbrook's and Connell's comments all make good copy for the
media. But locker rooms are often divided when players come out in
public to point the finger of blame at someone else. The Cowboys'
locker room usually doesn't yield such spicy sound bites for the
evening news. But at least you get the feeling that people are
pulling for one another at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   You can't say the same for the folks in the nation's capital.
STUPID COACH TRICK
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ross. Detroit Lions. With 5:26 remaining in the Lions'
loss at Arizona, Ross ordered his club to go for a 2-point
conversion after Terry Fair scored on a 35-yard fumble return. The
conversion attempt failed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this strategy is that the Lions, at the time,
trailed 23-19. Had Ross called on the kicking unit, then the Lions
most likely would have trailed only 23-20 when they got the ball on
their final possession of the game.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Lions reached the Arizona 11-yard line with 1:09
to play. Down four instead of three however, the Lions had to try
to score a touchdown instead of a chip-shot Jason Hanson field
goal. The game-winning drive stalled at the 11, and the Lions'
four-game winning streak ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a card that lists all the situations, and in that
one, it says to go for one, or go for two if you want to win the
game,'' said Ross, whose club actually failed to convert ``two''
2-point conversions on Sunday. ``We didn't want to go into overtime
_ not with three games in 11 days and as banged-up on special teams
as we were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hindsight's always 20-20. I thought we were going to play to
win it. I had thought it through. It was not a snap decision.''
</P>
<P>
   And it didn't turn out to be a smart one, either. OBSERVATIONS
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it in San Francisco? The 49ers have lost back-to-back
games against the only teams who have ``lost'' to the expansion
Cleveland Browns: Pittsburgh and New Orleans. ... Depending on what
the 49ers and Carolina Panthers do in the next two weeks, the St.
Louis Rams could conceivably win the NFC West with victories in
their next two games at San Francisco and vs. the Saints. ... Seven
AFC teams have at least six victories. One of those clubs won't
make the playoffs, but that team would have a good chance of
reaching the Super Bowl if it played in the NFC.
LYONS' TOP 5 1. Indianapolis 7-2 2. Jacksonville 8-1 3. Buffalo 7-3
4. Miami 7-2 5. St. Louis 7-2
GRADING THE NFL Lawrence Phillips: F The troubled running back has
apparently flunked with his third team. Upset because of his
limited role in San Francisco's offense, he refused to practice
last week and mocked coach Steve Mariucci. The team suspended him
indefinitely then said Monday he would never play for them again.
What a waste. Robert Smith: A The Minnesota Vikings-Chicago Bears
game wasn't the only thing ``in a tight.'' Smith, the Vikings
running back, drank a lot of water to fight off dehydration in his
first game back after a hernia injury. ``I was drinking (water)
like crazy,'' he said. ``Then, starting in the middle of the third
quarter I had to use the bathroom. When we went into overtime, I
just had to hang on.'' He did, and so did the Vikings. Jim Miller:
A The Bears thought they had a quarterback controversy with Shane
Matthews and rookie Cade McNown. Turns out, their best quarterback
might be journeyman Jim Miller, who passed for 422 yards in the
club's overtime loss to Minnesota. That was the most yards passing
in a game by a Bears quarterback since Bill Wade passed for 466
against the Cowboys in 1962.
nn
</P>
