<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-ROCKETS-HN     11-16 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Larry Bird walked into Compaq Center on Monday morning, and his
eyes instinctively were drawn to the 3-point line he had claimed
almost two decades earlier.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From that spot, he recalled happily, he clinched his first
championship, beating the Rockets with a 3-pointer for the 1981 NBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, he still owns every bit of Compaq Center hardwood
that is 23 feet, 9 inches from the rim.
</P>
<P>
   A few good things have happened to the Rockets, in general and
from the 3-point line, since Bird first came to town. But with the
Pacers' coach back for one last visit, the Rockets shot themselves
out of contention Monday, losing to Indiana 96-87, their fifth
consecutive home defeat to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chance,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``We
had wide-open looks. You make them, you win. You miss them, you
sing the blues.''
</P>
<P>
   B.B. King's favorite team had led by 10 in the third quarter and
seven in the fourth. But they basically took the final quarter off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's all about,'' Tomjanovich said of the fourth
quarter. ``Playing during the course of the game is good. When it
really counts, you have to make the plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well for a lot of stretches. But when it went bad,
it went really bad. We needed someone to make a play. We made five
turnovers in a row at a crucial point. But we came back and had
another shot. We had as good or better shots. We didn't knock them
down. They did.''
</P>
<P>
   Until a pair of meaningless late bombs fell with the Pacers well
ahead, the Rockets had made just one of 15 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   After recovering from a stunning five-minute collapse, the
Rockets made the decision to live or die with their post-up game.
And for a few minutes, it worked. Hakeem Olajuwon hit a pair of
six-footers. Charles Barkley, who finished with a season-high 24
rebounds, twice followed Olajuwon misses to score inside, pulling
the Rockets within 81-79 with 2{ minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pacers double-teamed hard inside. And the Rockets went
back to bombing away from outside. Walt Williams and Cuttino Mobley
each missed 3-pointers. Olajuwon missed a jumper. Steve Francis
missed a 3, then another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got good shots down the stretch,'' Barkley said. ``They
just didn't go in. When you get good shots that don't go in,
there's nothing you can do about that. You get a wide-open shot,
and you take it. If it goes in, everybody tells you you're great.
If you miss, everybody is (complaining).''
</P>
<P>
   While the Rockets tried to gun their way back into the game, the
Pacers made six of eight free throws and added one final turn of
the knife Bird could appreciate _ a 30-footer from Mark Jackson
that swished.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Rockets had accurately shot themselves in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Before their downfall, the Rockets had led since midway through
the second quarter. They held the Pacers, one of the league's best
offensive teams, to 39.8 percent shooting, the fifth consecutive
game a Rockets opponent has shot 40 percent or worse. Besides
Barkley's rebounding dominance, he, Olajuwon and Francis had 18
points apiece. Francis had a season-best 12 assists and added six
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   With just less than 10 minutes remaining, the Rockets led 71-64.
But they came up with a collapse to rival anything in their 0-5
start.
</P>
<P>
   In a 3{-minute stretch, the Pacers reeled off 15 unanswered
points, with the Rockets' offense hitting a sudden and complete
meltdown. In that stretch, the Rockets missed four shots from the
field and two from the line and committed four turnovers. It added
up to nine possessions without scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley drove the lane but had his shot blocked. Olajuwon tried
a fadeaway from the corner but left it short. Barkley posted up,
drew a double team and found Williams open at the 3-point arc.
Williams missed. Francis tried a drive but turned the ball over.
Olajuwon posted up but threw the ball away. The Rockets set up a
play for Mobley, who missed a 3.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to their fourth-quarter fades in the season's first
week, the Rockets recovered to pull back within two.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, put the game back in the hands of their outside
touch, which failed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like in the first half we were attacking the basket
more,'' Mobley said. ``I shot 2-for-10. I feel real bad about that
one. In the second half, we were real tentative. They got us in a
half-court set, and we didn't knock down our shots. I personally
take a lot of blame. It's just shots I know I should have made.
When we run plays for our big men, we have to stay out there to get
spacing. But we should have attacked the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams argued that he should get at least as much blame. He
made half of his eight shots but missed all four of his 3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't miss outside shots. I did,'' Williams said. ``Just
let me hit a shot. I missed wide-open shots. I also made a crucial
foul trying to get a steal. That's a mental mistake. But man, we
missed wide-open shots, me and Cuttino. Those are good looks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockets found out again that it's not the shots you take
that count. It's the ones you make.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it really counts,'' Tomjanovich said, ``we have to make
the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' tormentor on the other bench understood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
