<HEADLINE>
METEOR SHOWER WEDNESDAY MIGHT BE GREAT SHOW _ OR A DUD
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A once-in-a-lifetime sky show could be on display this week if
the annual Leonid meteor shower blossoms into the full-blown storm
some experts predict.
<P>
   Then again, it could be a cosmic flop _ especially for the West
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   As happens every November, our planet is about to brush into the
dusty trail of Comet Tempel-Tuttle. The encounter creates the
appearance of ``shooting stars'' on Earth when meteors _ minute
particles of comet debris _ burn up in the outer atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   It usually takes a trained eye to notice anything unusual is
going on _ maybe 10 or 20 shooting stars per hour, all appearing to
emanate from the direction of the constellation Leo. That's barely
an increase from the usual number of meteors visible almost any
clear night.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, following a 33-year cycle traced by the comet's
path through the inner solar system, Earth will encounter a much
thicker dust cloud than usual. The peak is expected late Wednesday
night into early Thursday morning. Comet watchers will want to look
above the eastern-southeastern horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The climax of the last 33-year cycle came in November 1966.
Stunned scientists, who hadn't seen it coming, counted as many as
50 meteors a second arcing across the night sky _ roughly 144,000
shooting stars per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all felt like we needed to put on hard hats,'' recalled one
observer at the NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory's Table Mountain
Observatory in Southern California. ``The sky was absolutely full
of meteors.''
</P>
<P>
   Earth's atmosphere creates an all-but impenetrable shield that
prevents any of the tiny particles from reaching the ground, so
hard hats are actually not necessary. But there's no such shield in
space.
</P>
<P>
   That's why military authorities, NASA and commercial satellite
operators all have taken steps to protect orbiting spacecraft that
could be hit by particles traveling at the speed of 156,000 miles
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the storm is intense, there's a potential for damage,''
said Capt. Nicole Greenwood, a spokeswoman at the U.S. Air Force
Space Command in Colorado. Still, she added, ``we don't expect any
critical damage. We've done a lot of preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Protecting spacecraft may turn out to be unnecessary. There
isn't a full-fledged storm every 33 years because of the peculiar
and unpredictable paths taken by cometary debris under the
influence of gravitational forces in the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   Some comet-watchers are predicting about 1,000 to 1,500 meteors
per hour this year at the peak, enough to create a nice show for
those with a good view. Unfortunately, the West Coast ``is not the
best place to be for this storm,'' said Bill Ailor, director of
orbital and re-entry debris studies at Aerospace Corp., a Southern
California think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Earth passes through the comet's orbital plane just before 2
a.m. London time Thursday. Based on the latest best guesses, that
would give Europe and North Africa the best vantage point, while
Californians will miss most of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Although the peak is expected Wednesday night or Thursday,
experts said it might be a good idea to take a look starting
tonight, after about 11 p.m., when Leo is high enough over the
horizon to be visible in the east-southeast region of the sky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
