<SLUG> BC-KRON-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BROADCASTING INC.'S SURPRISE BID WINS KRON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  In a surprising move, little-known Young Broadcasting Inc. has
bought San Francisco's NBC television station KRON (Channel 4) for
$823 million.
<P>
   In buying the station from San Francisco's Chronicle Publishing
Young, a New York firm, outbid such media heavyweights as NBC's
parent, General Electric; Gannett Co.; and News Corp., the owner of
the Fox television network.
</P>
<P>
   The price is a record for a television station. Calling KRON a
``jewel,'' Young Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Vincent J.
Young said in an interview last night, ``I can't remember the last
time a No. 1 station was for sale in a top five market. It was an
incredible opportunity to build our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's bid consists of $650 million in cash and $173 million in
Young Broadcasting stock. The deal also includes a 51 percent stake
in the local cable station BayTV; the other 49 percent remains
owned by AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission must approve the deal
before it can be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Young's 11 other stations are in midsize markets
throughout the Midwest and South, although the company also owns
KCAL in Los Angeles, the largest station in the country that is not
affiliated with a network.
</P>
<P>
   Media analyst Robin Flynn with Paul Kagan Associates in Carmel
said that with KCAL and KRON, ``Young is now a major force in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Young said he does not plan any major changes at KRON.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we think is most important in television stations is
the localism,'' he said. ``That's why KRON is the No. 1 station and
a news leader, because of its stress on the local community. That's
what our stations do. If we change anything, we'll just do more of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The station was put up for sale in June along with the rest of
Chronicle Publishing. KRON is the most valuable piece and one of
the last to be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Chronicle Publishing also sold San Francisco's Chronicle
Books to its current editor-in-chief, Nion McEvoy.
</P>
<P>
   In August, The Chronicle was sold to Hearst Corp. for a reported
$660 million in a deal awaiting federal antitrust approval.
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining properties, television stations KAKE in
Wichita, Kan., and WOWT in Omaha, Neb., may be sold by next week.
</P>
<P>
   KRON is also the second-oldest holding in the family portfolio,
having begun broadcasting in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, the media analyst, said she was surprised that Young
ended up winning KRON. The New York chain, the smallest of the
reported bidders, had actually put itself up for sale last June,
only to take itself off the market in September after it did not
get a satisfactory offer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, NBC conducted a hard-charging campaign for
KRON. In a letter that leaked out last month, NBC President Robert
Wright warned Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette _ the investment bank
handling the sale of Chronicle Publishing's assets _ that any buyer
other than NBC would have to deal with a less favorable affiliation
agreement with the network.
</P>
<P>
   KRON's affiliation agreement with NBC runs until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   NBC then offered $700 million and a demand for exclusive
negotiating rights. The bid was rejected immediately, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Young has outbid NBC, it still needs the network's
programming. ``We intend to be a fabulous affiliate with NBC if the
relationship is two years or 200 years,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Young has one other NBC-affiliated station, in Davenport, Iowa.
The firm also owns four ABC and six CBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Flynn said Young, although small compared with other
chains, is large enough to stand up to NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Young and his father, Adam Young, founded the company in
1986. According to the Web site for the Horatio Alger Association
of Distinguished Americans, Adam Young was the oldest of eight
children, and he dropped out of school at age 14 after his father
lost his job.
</P>
<P>
   He became an NBC page and was the network's first tour guide
when it moved to Rockefeller Center.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR; He became involved in advertising and founded Adam Young
Inc., whose clients were radio stations, and then he brought his
son into the business. In 1986, they bought stations in Lansing,
Mich., and LaCrosse, Wis., and formed Young Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Young, now 85, still serves on Young Broadcasting's
board of directors. The Young family owns nearly 60 percent of the
company. The rest is publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said Young demonstrated strong management abilities with
its ownership of KCAL in Los Angeles, acquiring the struggling
station in 1996 for $387 million and turning it around with a heavy
mix of sports programming, including broadcast rights to the
Anaheim Angels baseball team and the Los Angeles Lakers basketball
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the third quarter just ended, they grew revenues (at KCAL)
11 percent, which is phenomenal,'' Flynn said. ``That station has
been a real success story for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reported net income of $4 million (27 cents per
share) last year on revenues of $277 million.
</P>
<P>
   Young plans to announce the acquisition this morning before
trading opens on Wall Street. In Monday's trading, Young stock
closed up $1.09 at $51.78, off its 52-week high of $65.25 reached
in September.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Tom Abate and Peter Sinton contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
