<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REASON THE 49ERS CAN'T WIN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ If you're cursing the 49ers these days, you're
too late.
<P>
   Eddie's been there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's what I'm told by a guy named Bill Slayter. He
says he visited his psychic, who told Slayter that Eddie DeBartolo,
former (and still sort-of) owner of the 49ers, placed a curse on
the team as a lovely parting gift when he left town.
</P>
<P>
   (If this column had background music, right now you'd be hearing
Screamin' Jay Hawkins singing, ``I put a spell on you, because
you're mine.'')
</P>
<P>
   And there is solid proof of the existence of a curse. There's no
other way to explain the fact that the 49ers are giving serious
consideration to luring quarterback Jeff Hostetler out of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what about that Montana fella?
</P>
<P>
   Eddie D was knocked out as 49ers owner when he was convicted of
a felony involving shady doings associated with the Louisiana
riverboat gambling industry. The formal turnover of Eddie's team
ownership to his sister isn't complete, but he has left town,
seemingly in an ``after-all-I've-done-for-you'' frame of mind
toward the team and the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the unlikely event that Eddie D somehow manages to regain
full-powers ownership of the 49ers, I hope he can have the curse
removed. Let's hope he saved the receipt.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIE BROWN AND/OR TOM AMMIANO might want to help bury Harvey
Milk. Because it would be a nice thing for the mayor or the Board
of Supes president to do. And it might be worth some mayoral votes
in the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   The story is complicated, but here's the Reader's Digest
condensed version:
</P>
<P>
   Milk, the gay S.F. supervisor assassinated 21 years ago, has
never been fully interred. His ashes were scattered at sea, but an
urn with his ponytail, and some bits of memorabilia, was shipped to
the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be confused with Arlington National, Congressional is a
famed but cash-strapped cemetery. Among the celebs buried there are
John Philip Sousa, Mathew Brady and J. Edgar Hoover. Congressional
also has many cenotaphs (monuments to people buried elsewhere) of
great Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was a cenotaph for Milk, whose election to the Board of
Supes was a breakthrough for gays and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Not enough money was ever raised for the monument and
interment of the remains. My source says that Milk's future burial
site has a Styrofoam marker.
</P>
<P>
   Can Tom or Willie help give Harvey a proper burial? Does anyone
still care? As grass grows, the plot thickens.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST CHRISTMAS CARD, sort of, came via e-mail ad: ``It's here,
just in time for Xmas, Guaranteed Credit Cards!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Be up to your eyeballs in debt by Thanksgiving!
</P>
<P>
   Says the ad, ``You and your family will have the best Christmas
ever with Credit Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the road to financial hell now has an express lane!
</P>
<P>
   CURSE UPDATE: When fans turn on the 49ers, they really turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of criticism of the NFL for blacking out
home TV of Raider games,'' says Warren Sugarman. ``Maybe they could
do the same for the 49ers as a humanitarian gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotta Dotz says if the 49ers are going to be a doormat, they
should sell souvenir doormats, with a 49-month guarantee and a
likeness of Bill Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, 49ers jokes. Why do we call 'em the 'Niners?
Because their offense is usually good for three field goals.
</P>
<P>
   SETTING STRAIGHT the record: Last week, KPIX showed a
documentary, ``Ed Sullivan's Greatest Hits: Two Decades of Rock &AMP;
Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The program featured, as you may have guessed, musical
highlights from the old Ed Sullivan variety show. Flashed on the
screen at one point was a photo of Country Joe and the Fish, the
famed Berkeley protest band.
</P>
<P>
   The photo may have created the impression that Country Joe and
the Fish played Sullivan. Not quite. They were the only band ever
paid  &UR; not  &LR; to appear on the Sullivan show.
</P>
<P>
   They were booked in '68, but the night before they were to be on
Ed's show, they played at a beer festival in Central Park, where
they debuted their soon-to-be-famous ``Fish Cheer,'' where Country
Joe McDonald leads the audience, ``Gimme a big F! Gimme a big U!''
And so on, then, ``What's that spell?''
</P>
<P>
   Ed himself was in the audience that night. Joe and his Fish were
not only banned from the beer festival in perpetuity, but Ed
himself personally approached the lads backstage and told them they
could keep their $2,500 appearance fee, but they would never, ever
appear on his television show.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, last week there was a TV show about the Ed Sullivan
Show, and there was Country Joe and the Fish, crashing the party 31
years after the fact. The boys still haven't lost their touch.
</P>
<P>
   HOTTEST MAGAZINE anywhere has to be Bark, a quarterly published
in Berkeley and now on sale at newsstands in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cultural arts magazine for dog lovers,'' says
editor/publisher Claudia Kawczynska.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine features original writing from top authors,
excerpts from hot books and cutting-edge design.
</P>
<P>
   The genre, I would say, is high-brow bow-wow.
</P>
<P>
   IN THIS CITY, no political angle is overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Anonymous female caller says, ``I just want to let you know that
I'm sick of Bill Bradley's armpits. Papers and magazines keep
running pictures of him playing basketball, and you always see his
armpits. Is this his campaign logo?''
</P>
<P>
   Could be worse. Bradley could have made his athletic fame as a
nude skydiver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
