<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CZECH-WALL-1117-COX     11-16 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-WALL-1117-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN COX EDs: The anniversary of the Czech 'Velvet Revolution'
is Wed., Nov. 17. Re-sending this story for those papers who
haven't used it previously.
 &HT;    TV DETECTIVE UNCOVERS RAW WOUNDS FROM CZECH REPUBLIC'S COMMUNIST
PAST
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ With a badge and a gun and a loyal
following, Major Jan Zeman is back on duty 10 years after the end
of communist rule, in pursuit of lawbreakers and subversives who
threaten the social order.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Major Zeman was the former Czechoslovakia's
favorite television police detective during communist times. But a
decision by Czech Television to re-broadcast the 1970s serial has
raised a fierce debate in the Czech Republic over whether the show
is propaganda or entertainment or history.
</P>
<P>
   Every Thursday night at 8 since its debut in mid-September,
Czechs in vast numbers have been tuning in for the next installment
of ``The 30 Cases of Major Zeman.'' The heroic, hard-nosed cop
always gets his man and every episode sends a subtle if
unmistakable message: the Communist regime, as embodied by Zeman,
is the common comrade's only friend.
</P>
<P>
   And that has former political prisoners, human rights advocates
and reform politicians upset. They're demanding that the show be
taken off the air, and accusing Czech TV of offering up
brainwashing propaganda in the guise of a historical TV
retrospective. It comes at a sensitive time when the present-day
Communist Party is enjoying a surge in support amid the country's
economic malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes those who worked for freedom look like criminals,
which of course was its original intent,'' complains Frantisek
Sedivy, 72, who served 12 years in prison in the 1950s and '60s for
spreading democratic ideology among fellow university students.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over whether there is a place for Major Zeman in
the post-communist era goes to the very heart of how this Central
European country, now a member of the NATO alliance, is struggling
to define its fledgling democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The television producers who decided to rebroadcast the serial _
with accompanying documentaries exploring how the show was a tool
of the regime _ say that their intent was to force this nation of
10 million to begin to come to terms with its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has stirred up the very questions we've been trying to
avoid,'' agrees Jiri Pehe, a Czech scholar who runs New York
University's campus in Prague.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 17 marks the 10th anniversary of the ``Velvet Revolution,''
which overthrew communism in what was then Czechoslovakia. (In
1993, the Czech Republic and Slovakia mutually agreed to become
separate nations).
</P>
<P>
   However, the transition to a free-market economy has clearly
stalled in the Czech Republic, until a few years ago among the most
prosperous and fast-changing of the former Communist states.
Economic reforms were postponed in the mid-1990s, and the weak
Social Democratic government installed in 1997 elections has been
hamstrung by its lack of a majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in the past decade, few officials of the former era
have faced trial for crimes and murders committed during the harsh,
41-year communist reign. Only five officials from the period have
been convicted in the past 10 years in the Czech Republic, while as
many as 300,000 people were jailed as political prisoners or
committed to mental institutions during communist times.
</P>
<P>
   And unrepentant Czech torturers and secret police officials have
gone so far as to form an Association for the Protection of those
Prosecuted by the Capitalistic Regime within the last few years. It
has even filed discrimination complaints with international human
rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   The public dialogue about the past has been clouded because of a
collective guilt over the crimes committed and what, if anything,
should have been done to change things sooner, according to Pehe.
``People will always tell you how the others were involved, but not
what they themselves were doing back then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Czech TV officials regard the controversy over the show as
healthy, if not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear to us that we have poked a wasp's nest. And we've
asked ourselves why people are so emotional about this,'' said Iva
Prochakova, a Czech TV producer who oversees the Zeman series.
``But the process of democracy-building requires us to look back at
our own past.''
</P>
<P>
   However, critics regard the airing of the series as highly
insensitive to the still-raw wounds of the hundreds of thousands
who suffered under communist rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Confederation of Political Prisoners has filed a
criminal complaint in court charging that the series promotes
hatred and the ``repression of citizens' rights and freedoms.'' The
country's broadcast regulators have warned of possible fines for
spreading ``totalitarian ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bret, a deputy director of the Czech police's Bureau for
the Documentation and Investigation of Communist Crimes, compares
the Zeman series to the powerful and artful propaganda of Nazi
Germany. It glorifies an agent of the Communist regime which
systematically persecuted innocent people, he contends, and it
should not be on TV because the country's young democracy cannot
handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 10 years we're assuming that society is more critical
and more sensitive to the objective truth about their history and
about their past. This is not the case,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The scripts, based on real-life events, were artful distortions
that portrayed the communist regime as generally benevolent and
just. The villains jousting with Zeman were often priests,
intellectuals, artists, students and Western spies. During
production, government handlers from the interior ministry oversaw
the scripts and shooting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one episode deals with the murder of several
Communist Party officials in a conspiracy said to involve Western
spies and priests. Evidence uncovered since the fall of communism,
and included in an accompanying Zeman documentary, reveals that the
assassinations were an inside job carried out as part of a power
struggle within the communist ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with the country's economy faltering and the reform
government tainted by allegations of corruption, the opposition
Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia enjoys the support of 20
percent of the population, according to recent polls. It marks a
high point in public support for the communists since the regime
fell in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials vow that if they came to power they would shift
the Czech Republic from its current capitalist course back to
socialism and seek to annul the country's membership in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, granted earlier this year along
Hungary and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The airing of Zeman could hasten their return, by making
communism seem cool, say critics of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The population today could be influenced by this series. Those
who see the problems of today's society may think it was a better
time when they view this propaganda,'' said Jaroslav Runt, 77, a
deputy chairman of the former political prisoners confederation.
</P>
<P>
   The country's best-known former political prisoner, President
Vaclav Havel, who spent almost five years in communist jails,
dismissed the series as ``not the first nor the last idiocy aired
by Czech Television.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is as melodramatic and dated as an episode of Mannix.
Many viewers, it seems, are drawn to the show out of nostalgia for
their youth, not the politics of the time. Tuning in each week to
see Zeman's latest exploits is merely a walk down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching Zeman is kind of like putting on an old pair of boots
you've dug out of the closet,'' said Vera Kamenicka, 58, of Prague.
``They are kind of comfortable, but out of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0071 </DOCNO>
