</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1118-     11-16 1782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-IN-AMERICA-1118-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE IN AMERICA: Sleeping in the arms of nature
 &HT;    (Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTO, Ga. _ I never knew a giant tree could rock a baby to
sleep, much less me. But it did.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. I slept in a tree. A 125-foot-tall tulip poplar. Her name
is Rachel. Sleeping in a tree isn't something to do when you need
your rest, but it's something unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't alone. We were a tree ``village'' of five, each with
different reasons for being there, just as each would have
different responses to the night in Rachel's arms.
</P>
<P>
   My tree camping experience all started when
</P>
<P>
   I decided to follow Henry David Thoreau's 19th-century advice to
learn the value of a tree. Thoreau said you can't know a tree until
you have stopped to listen to it.
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard about tree climbers who spent the nights in trees, but
it wasn't until I ran into Genevieve Summers that I knew I wanted
to try it. Summers runs a North Georgia recreational and
educational tree-climbing outfit called Dancing with Trees. She
recently sold her chimney sweep business, Moonlight Sweeps, to
devote full time to her climbing program.
</P>
<P>
   On eight wooded acres in Banks County, a half-hour northeast of
Gainesville, the 48-year-old mother of two ties knots in thick
ropes with the dexterity of a seasoned sailor and swirls through
branches with the grace of a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   My first tree-climbing experience was in Tonya, a 60-year-old
white oak, who, Summers says, just named herself one evening when
Summers was sitting silently at her trunk. Whispered her name in
Summers' ear.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the heat that caused the beads of sweat to pop out on
my forehead the first time I wriggled into a harness attached to
Tonya and stepped into the foot loop secured to my ``hot rope.''
Hiking on firm ground is more my milieu.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers, who's spent as much time in trees and on rooftops
as on the ground, assured me that she had made tree climbers from
ages 4 to 76 love swinging in the trees. The only requirements are
good health and no fear of heights. I could meet those. But what I
loved was her promise that I'd never look at a tree, pick up a leaf
or listen to the wind the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   Summers can keep up with the best of male climbers, but for her,
tree climbing is more spiritual experience than sport. ``Trees,
like women, are nurturers, life givers,'' she says. She has
fashioned the country's only climbing merit badge for the northeast
Georgia Girl Scouts.
</P>
<P>
   After my initial lesson, she declared that I was ready for a
night in the trees. We agreed to put together a ``tree village,''
inviting Tom Watson, an experienced climber and arborist, and
photographer W.A. Bridges Jr., a novice climber like me.
</P>
<P>
   The date was set for the end of September, a Sunday night when
the harvest moon would be glowing.
</P>
<P>
   But when we arrived, clouds loomed in the sky. We tried not to
notice. Before the climb, Summers insisted that we share our
expectations for the night _ with one another and with the tree.
Watson talked about being a carefree boy again. Bridges said he
already felt that Tonya was his soul mate. I recalled a professor
who said that we give trees attributes that are too large for our
minds to grasp. I wanted to try to understand that.
</P>
<P>
   Then, up we went, each at our own speed with our own thoughts. I
was wet with sweat when I finally sank into my tree boat. It's an
insecure feeling at first. We'd all seen a few flashes of lightning
on our way up and told one another that the storm was far away. I
settled in, feeling snug and cozy as a soft wind made the leaves
swish against one another with rippling sounds you can't hear from
below.
</P>
<P>
   I adjusted my headlight and pulled out a book of poems I'd
stashed in my stuff-sack, ``A Timbered Choir'' by Wendell Berry.
There was a low roll of thunder in the distance. A light rain began
to fall. Summers said we should put our air mattresses on top of us
to keep from getting wet _ warning that we'd have to bail out if
the thunder got any louder.
</P>
<P>
   For a while I felt like a snail, listening to the raindrops fall
on my shell. Then, a loud thunderclap and a driving rain, and
Summers gave the call to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   I was grateful for two things _ that I hadn't taken off my shoes
and that I knew where my gloves were. Without rubber-ribbed gloves,
rope burn is inevitable. I already had a blister from not wearing
them when I started up. In minutes, my tree boat felt like a
leaking boat.
</P>
<P>
   I was sitting in a puddle, feet dangling over the side, tossing
my air mattress, sleeping bag and pillow to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave everything else,'' Summers yelled. ``Get down fast and
get away from the tree.'' Lightning flashed. Rain pounded. We
obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   I made the inevitable beginner's mistake, clutching the moving
knot as I descended, whizzing past Summers like George of the
Jungle. Fortunately, her safety loop stopped me, so that I had only
a bruised arm to show for my mistake.
</P>
<P>
   It was midnight when we gathered for hot tea in Summers'
kitchen, vowing to try it again. Watson said it was the first time
he'd ever had to bail out in a rainstorm in his 12 years of
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' Summers said, looking at Bridges and me, ``I
think you're ready for Rachel.'' Rachel, Summers' 150-year-old
friend, was named for environmentalist Rachel Carson, author of
``Silent Spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes, I thought. Rachel's lowest branch is higher than we'd
just climbed.
</P>
<P>
   We gathered again on a clear October night more than a week
later. We were joined by Summers' neighbor, 24-year-old Melissa
Parham, an experienced climber eager to spend her first night in a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Summers offered me ``the penthouse,'' but I deferred to Bridges,
knowing that photos from Rachel's crown would be important. I knew
it was the right decision for other reasons when I tackled the
single-rope technique, necessary because Rachel is too tall for
Summers' double ropes to reach the ground. Shinning up and moving
plastic ascenders seemed to require more upper-body strength. As I
struggled upward, wondering why my aerobics and weightlifting
rituals weren't paying off, I thought about my South Georgia
grandmother who decreed that girls weren't supposed to perspire.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped to rest along the way and to admire the ``resurrection
fern'' growing in Rachel's tree ``forks.'' This delicate plant can
look totally brown and dead, then spring to life in vibrant green
with the least bit of moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Once we settled in, the evening light accentuated Rachel's
angular black limbs, forming dark borders around the leaf patterns
that seemed pasted onto the sky.
</P>
<P>
   We all stopped talking, awed by the night's wonders. Summers
heard a pileated woodpecker. Her scarf, hung to one side of her
tree boat, reminded me of the prayer cloths I'd once seen tied to
trees in Soviet Georgia. An old Soviet woman told me in broken
English that the wind sent their messages to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   I read the Wendell Berry poem I'd started when the storm hit us
in Tonya:
</P>
<P>
   What do the tall trees say
</P>
<P>
   to the late havocs in the sky? They sigh.
</P>
<P>
   The air moves and they sway.
</P>
<P>
   When the breeze on the hill
</P>
<P>
   Is still, then they stand still.
</P>
<P>
   They wait.
</P>
<P>
   They have no fear.
</P>
<P>
   Their fate
</P>
<P>
   is faith. Birdsong
</P>
<P>
   Is all they've wanted all along.
</P>
<P>
   I dozed off for a while and awoke chilled. There's no way to zip
a sleeping bag in the tree, because of the rope attached to the
harness belt. I pulled the corners of the sleeping bag around me
until I was cozy again and gazed up at the autumn sky, hiding all
but a sliver of the moon. I decided to write my granddaughters a
letter about sleeping in a tree boat. Adults might think I was
crazy. But little children wouldn't. The girls, ages 5 and 6, would
squeal appropriately about my new friend, Rachel, and my adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Then I wrote a poem of my own.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot know the sky until you have seen it from a leafy
branch.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot know the night until you have listened to the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot know acorns until they have rained softly around you.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot be free until you have slept where birds take flight.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot know a tree until you have trusted your life to her
arms.
</P>
<P>
   When morning came, Summers' friend Parham was up first. She said
she'd never slept better, descended 80 feet in record time and
headed through the woods for her red pickup truck and a regular
workday at the Clarkesville Florist.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us laid back for a leisurely breakfast: snack boxes
with cloth napkins, a bottle of orange juice made with spring
water, a fresh croissant with slices of cheese and, naturally, a
banana.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges swung around with his camera, taking pictures of all of
us stretching and eating in the morning sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   Then Summers put one last challenge to me. ``Wanna climb up to
that black cord?'' she asked, pointing to a marker about 35 feet
above. ``That's the 100-foot mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not, I thought, forgetting for a moment that my thighs and
arms were already sore.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a great climb and a spectacular view of the horizon.
The tree understory below, splotched with early fall reds and
yellows, was accented by the tip of an old persimmon tree laden
with orange fruit.
</P>
<P>
   When we finally descended, Summers had us share our thoughts as
we stood around Rachel's 13-foot trunk. Our comments reflected the
diverse life experiences we brought to the tree climb. Summers
talked about trees as equal partners in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we climb a tree, we climb into ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges said Rachel connected him with African spiritual symbols
of peace. In the branches of the tree, he said, we were all
balanced and equal, and when we descended, we could do it only by
way of a single trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the unity of the human race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I said the night was being a child again_a magical, unspoiled
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Watson talked about the scientific miracle of fall, the way the
trees are silent on the outside but operating like giant fountains
on the inside, taking nutrients and water from root to branches. He
talked about how Rachel is shutting down the food supply to each
leaf now and storing it for spring.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Watson made a simple, eloquent observation: ``The strength
of Rachel just reminds me of faith. Faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
