</P>
<P>
   Why not, I thought, forgetting for a moment that my thighs and
arms were already sore.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a great climb and a spectacular view of the horizon.
The tree understory below, splotched with early fall reds and
yellows, was accented by the tip of an old persimmon tree laden
with orange fruit.
</P>
<P>
   When we finally descended, Summers had us share our thoughts as
we stood around Rachel's 13-foot trunk. Our comments reflected the
diverse life experiences we brought to the tree climb. Summers
talked about trees as equal partners in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we climb a tree, we climb into ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges said Rachel connected him with African spiritual symbols
of peace. In the branches of the tree, he said, we were all
balanced and equal, and when we descended, we could do it only by
way of a single trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the unity of the human race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I said the night was being a child again_a magical, unspoiled
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Watson talked about the scientific miracle of fall, the way the
trees are silent on the outside but operating like giant fountains
on the inside, taking nutrients and water from root to branches. He
talked about how Rachel is shutting down the food supply to each
leaf now and storing it for spring.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Watson made a simple, eloquent observation: ``The strength
of Rachel just reminds me of faith. Faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
