<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When all goes wrong, blame Martha Stewart
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Something ``medical'' happened to me
recently, and I'm pretty sure I'm going to have to pay for it
myself. I don't think the insurance folks have a code for what I
just lived through. It had to do with Pokemon, Y2K and Christmas
hype _ all of which I blame on Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because she's Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   What happened was this: I started to snatch things up like there
was, quite literally, no tomorrow. I began losing sleep about
whether the $89 Star Wars Legos set would be available in a month.
I started to hoard things like some of those grandmas you read
about who saved itsy-bitsy slivers of soap during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when I was a dyed-in-the-wool lollygagger. If I
had to be at work by 10, I'd get up at 9:45. Birthday cards? I'd
stroll right to the ``Sorry I missed your . . . '' section. Library
books? Why do you think they print some notices on orange paper?
For me, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Then I started to pack lunches the night before. I cannot deny
that on many occasions I set the alarm for 5:45 so I could get up,
read the paper and iron a blouse. In retrospect, these were my
early-warning signs. Like thirst and diabetes. Then last weekend, I
found myself holding a toy-store flier advertising Furbies for
$27.99. ``LIMIT TWO,'' it said. And while I'd never given Furbies a
second thought, the mere chance of them not being available in case
I wanted one. . . Well. As I recall things now, that was the day I
was too confused to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am apparently kneeling in the confessional this morning,
here's something else. During this sick, sick period in my life, I
also went around town sighing, complaining to anyone who would
listen about ``my son'' and his ``addiction to this stupid Pokemon
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, alone one day on Palm Beach _ Alone? On Palm Beach? Did
that really happen, or was I sick with Pokemon fever? _ I saw a
Pikachu alarm clock. I bought it right then and there, and if
you're not horrified yet, try this:
</P>
<P>
   I put my name on the waiting list for the Pikachu backpack.
</P>
<P>
   The adorable woman who runs the adorably expensive kids' store
assured me I was not alone in my suffering. She said crazed
grown-ups cruise through her store every weekend buying up all the
Evees and Squirtles and Charmanders. Every Monday, she is forced to
call her ``Pokemon dealer.'' When she told me that, I actually had
a whole complicated thought process about how this Pokemon thing is
such a miracle from Above because it just might wipe out all drug
sales on America's street corners. I know now that was the delirium
phase of my illness.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I am telling you this is I have to assume there are
others out there like me. After all, we all take our money out of
our wallets the same way: one fist at a time. So, if you're out
there and you're suffering, I've got the antidote.
</P>
<P>
   Go see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's painful. During my exorcism, I was lightheaded and
nauseous, and for a few confused moments, I felt as though I'd
broken into my plentiful stock of Y2K champagne. But I'm happy to
report that I am making good progress. I hate that little Pikachu.
I'm returning the Furbies. Recovery, however, has not been full. I
just called the adorable woman about the backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
