<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unstuffing Ma's shelves
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``You've got too much STUFF, Ma.'' That's me
explaining
</P>
<P>
   to my ex-husband's mother what's gone wrong in her living room.
She thinks maybe it's the blue lamp. The lamp is fine, I tell her,
but the rest of the place looks like a churchyard jumble sale on
Saturday morning. She's not listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simple, Ma, you can't jam 20 pounds of STUFF into a
10-pound room.''
</P>
<P>
   Ma doesn't pay a whole lot of attention to my wisecracks,
probably because she's been listening to me for 40 years. Right now
she's looking for solutions. I suggest Good Will. ``I'm an old
lady,'' she pretends to whine but I know her better than that _
she's joking, ``and old ladies collect STUFF. It'll happen to you
too.''
</P>
<P>
   I tell her no way, but just in case, I ask her please not to
will me that doll sitting atop the bookcase _ the one made of a
floor mop, a paper lace doily, and half a coat hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to save all of this STUFF,'' she says in an effort
to justify her junk. ``What if folks come to visit and the STUFF
they gave me is gone?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple,'' I explain. ``Tell 'em you're getting forgetful and
you put it away so the great-grandchildren wouldn't break it, and
now you've forgotten where it is.'' Ma grabs a red-enameled wooden
horse she bought in Sweden and takes a playful swing at me with it.
But that reminds her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got this camel in Egypt,'' she says picking up a carved
figure from a cluttered shelf. I ask where the half-nekkid guy, the
one behind the crystal beer stein full of matchbooks came from. She
says Maui. And the elephant with a missing leg? Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you fix the bookcase?'' she wants to know. I tell her I
can but the surgery is going to be merciless. She looks away,
thinks for a moment, and gives me the green light. She even hauls
in a couple of empty packing boxes from the back porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll empty the shelves and stack stuff on the floor,'' I tell
her, ``and then you can go through and determine which STUFF to
keep and what to pitch.'' She nods but I can tell her heart isn't
in it. I dig in and she starts to sort. The floor is filling up
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta' save this,'' I hear her mutter. It's a do-it-yourself
electrical wiring book.
</P>
<P>
   ``You planning on rewiring the house, Ma?'' I ask. She says that
was a couple of years ago when she was younger (81). ``And what
about this thing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What thing?'' she asks without looking up from her sorting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing that looks like half-a-lava lamp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's half-a-lava lamp,'' she affirms, and as soon as I find
the other half, I'll have a whole one. I hear they're back in
style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about these boxes of jigsaw puzzles marked: Pieces
missing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep those. Can't tell when the missing pieces might turn
up.'' I ask how long they've been like this and she says since her
boys were little. I calculate that to be about 50 years and start
unloading the next shelf.
</P>
<P>
   There's an 1868 hymnal from the old German Lutheran church,
school books
</P>
<P>
   from the mid-1800s, in German, and Grandma Baker's collection of
leather postcards. In another stack is a daguerreotype of my late
father-in-law's father in his Prussian army uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Folded in four and stuck in an 1887 geography book is the Dec.
8, 1941
</P>
<P>
   front page of the Toledo Blade announcing we were at war with
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A baby picture of Ma's firstborn, my ex-husband, wearing a
scalloped bonnet and screaming his lungs out, rests under the rock
our son Kristofor mailed to his grandmother from camp when he was
10.
</P>
<P>
   On the shelf above is a November 1911 Redbook Magazine. American
Radiator Company in Chicago is advertising that for $125 it can fit
a cottage with an IDEAL boiler and 175 feet of 38-inch American
radiators. American Telephone and Telegraph boasts 12 million miles
of wire and 20 million calls daily. A Hamilton railroad watch costs
$38.50, and a can of Campbell's soup (21 kinds), a dime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some neat STUFF here,'' I confess. Ma says she already
knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right, but the featherless badminton bird goes, OK?'' She
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're getting somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
