r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN17-COX     11-16 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toast stew, taco glue: Top that, readers
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My First Annual Food Invention and Weird
Snacks Contest starts NOW! with a wink and a nod of gratitude to
the Spencer family of Wellington, Fla., for their inspiring letter:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Ron,
</P>
<P>
   My family and I love to sit around the dinner table thinking of
great food inventions. Our all-time favorite is taco glue.
</P>
<P>
   Taco glue would also be great for burritos. You know how
frustrating it is when your soft taco or burrito starts unwinding
and losing its stuffing. My husband, Marc, also thought that hard
tacos would be great if they had spring-loaded hinges on them. That
way, no matter how much you stuffed in it, it would not crack.
</P>
<P>
   The Spencers (Jody, Marc, Alex, Paige and Austin)
</P>
<P>
   I salute the Spencers for addressing the structurally unsound
burrito problem.
</P>
<P>
   Not only should burrito glue be developed at once, Taco Bell
should throw in a soft tortilla patch kit with a packet of glue for
those inevitable burrito grande ruptures and the tragic loss of
sour cream and guacamole. I also commend Taco Bell for pioneering
the hard taco inside a soft taco for that unique crunch-with-squish
mouth feel.
</P>
<P>
   But back to my food invention and weird snack contest. It has
long been my contention that every kitchen is a food laboratory at
some time or another and that many a delectable food concoction
could be found between the sofa cushions of America if only folks
would own up to their offbeat food inventions. It is time to
celebrate twisted kitchen creations.
</P>
<P>
   Send me snack recipes you have invented or know about, or tell
me a food that should be invented. An example of the latter would
be a leakproof, enveloping hot dog bun that you could fill with
mustard, catsup and pureed jalapenos. Jot down those unlikely food
combinations, mail or e-mail them to me and you could win an invite
to the taste-off party.
</P>
<P>
   First, second and third places will win something really neat.
Don't press me, I haven't decided.
</P>
<P>
   To get your creative and digestive juices flowing, I will offer
some food creations I've come across over the years:
</P>
<P>
   Vernor's Ginger Ale and Bosco: A Detroit inner-city favorite.
Spoon Bosco chocolate syrup into Vernor's and for reasons unknown
to chemistry, it tastes like chocolate-covered cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Mock Angel Cake: I'm sorry to have lost the name of the
contributor, but I remember the recipe well. Take stale bread and
sop both sides in sweetened condensed milk. Flop bread in copious
amounts of shredded coconut and grill both sides in butter until
coconut is golden brown. Your fillings will sing you to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Toast Stew: Heat a can of condensed vegetable beef soup. Add
chunks of cheddar and Worcestershire to taste. As cheese melts,
drop torn pieces of toast in bowl and devour.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning Fast Popcorn Balls Without Bothering to Form Them Into
Balls: Before my metabolism took out a contract on my life, I
invented this snack and consumed with impunity. Put butter and
brown sugar in a bowl that you wouldn't mind seeing turned into a
carbonized black lump. Add a teaspoon of vanilla. Put in microwave
and heat for 30 seconds. The contents will boil up into a
caramelized froth and subside into a thin golden liquid. Drizzle
liquid over a bowl of popcorn and eat until nauseous. Warning: If
you microwave too long, don't even bother with the oven EZ-Off.
Throw away the microwave and buy another.
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn Cheese-drizzle: When I told my good friend and fellow
motorcycle enthusiast C.R. of Lantana about the caramel popcorn
trick, she said you can do the same thing with grated cheddar and
butter. Heat until soupy, drizzle on popcorn and park in front of
the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Gorilla Bob's Cheapskate Souffle, courtesy of Bob Weintraub,
West Palm Beach motorcycle shop owner: Stir a couple of eggs into a
cup of cooked rice. Toss in garlic, onion, maybe a little oregano,
cook omelette style, and you're in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Andre's Dessert Omelette: I can't remember the local chef's last
name, but his confection passed on to me 20 years ago was pure
genius. Make an unflavored omelette, folding in Smucker's blueberry
jam. Top with powdered sugar and place under broiler just long
enough to melt sugar. In separate pan, heat a few ounces of
100-proof rum, light and let flame die down somewhat before pouring
remaining flaming liquid over omelette. Serve while on fire. You
know what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Ruined Strawberries and Cream: I gave it that name as a warning.
A colleague assures me that the truly tasty way to serve sliced
strawberries mounded with slightly sweetened whipped cream is to
grind fresh pepper over the cream.
</P>
<P>
   Don't send me your S'mores recipe. I know about S'mores. Been
there, eaten that.
</P>
<P>
   Send your Weird Snacks (or fun food innovations) to Ron Wiggins,
Box 24700 West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416-4700. Or email me at
ronwiggins(at)pbpost.com Contest deadline is Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
