<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed university 'riot fee' gives new meaning to
'extracurricular'
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Either a University of Colorado regent is taking
group punishment to the extreme, or he's hit on a new dimension in
campus life.
</P>
<P>
   We make rioting a club sport.
</P>
<P>
   Someday a varsity sport?
</P>
<P>
   A pro brawler's tour, maybe?
</P>
<P>
   Champion crowned at the Super Brawl?
</P>
<P>
   We can't be sure what regent Jim Martin was thinking. Maybe he
will give it some more thought. Maybe he ought to.
</P>
<P>
   In light of what has become a too-regular occurrence in the
college town of Boulder _ a Halloween-weekend riot _ Martin
proposed a mandatory student fee to raise $100,000 to pay for
annual damages.
</P>
<P>
   With 25,000 students, that would be $4 apiece. Students
naturally have assailed the proposal. I have to agree. Group
punishment is for cretins.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no way to know, short of chromosomal testing, how
many CU students are trash-can lighting, vehicle-overturning
out-of-control cretins and how many are there just to find meaning
in life.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the thoughtful CU junior quoted in a Boulder
publication lamenting how tough it is in '90s to find incitement:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '50s we had racism, in the '60s we had Vietnam. In the
'90s we don't have anything to get angry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, if I were a student and the college attached a $4
riot fee to my tuition, the first thing I'd do is riot.
</P>
<P>
   I'd want something for my money.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe there are wiley designs behind an idea that sounds so
dumb. The students obviously don't see the benefits inherent. Maybe
what the regent has in mind is making rioting an entitlement and a
campus-sponsored activity.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Rather than prohibit rioting, charge a student fee
and institutionalize it. List it in the student catalog. And watch
participation sag.
</P>
<P>
   That is, except for those who are truly devoted and skilled at
rioting. They would continue to pursue their passion. With a
$100,000 annual fund bolstering their activities, riots could be
held in venues _ intramural fields first, stadiums next. Call in
corporate sponsors. Miller beer. Zima. Clearasil.
</P>
<P>
   It would be no time before ESPN2 or MTV decided to televise. Put
an ``X'' before the event and you've got something with staying
power. The X-pletive Games. The X-crement Games.
</P>
<P>
   Young people could go to college and pursue rioting specialties
to take on the pro tour. Mini-van overturning. Recreational arson.
Low-impact looting.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado U. should consider these opportunities to bolster its
more traditional sports. For a few years its football team had a
reputation for law-breaking, despite the Bible-thumping of its
former coach. If the university can institutionalize rioting, it
can recruit multi-sport talents, like Florida State speed demon
Peter Warrick, who recently pleaded guilty to a theft charge and
was sped back onto the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Under traditional standards Warrick would be considered an
embarrassment and disgrace. But if college campuses can
institutionalize rioting, looting and theft, someone like Warrick
can simply come to school as a two-sport star.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of criticizing the CU regent, students should be
taking him up on his suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Fight Club'' _ about an underground organization of
disillusioned young men who get together and beat each other into
flank steaks _ is good enough for Brad Pitt, then a Riot Club is
good enough to have its own cubicle at the Student Center.
</P>
<P>
   The university quickly would realize that a $4 riot fee is a
bargain when a first-run movie costs $7. So instead of complaining,
students should enjoy themselves at this low, low rate. They should
know that the cost of higher education will go up.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
