<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN17-CO     11-16 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financial books abound
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The supply of new financial advice books is a gusher and
apparently a never-ending one.
</P>
<P>
   They are the fad books of the decade, much as do-it-yourself
books once were and feel-good, self-help books always are.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planning books are on the rise for several reasons.
One is that more and more Americans have investments. One recent
study showed that 52 percent of American households own stocks or
stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that we feel more responsible for building our
own financial future and less confident we can do it. In another
study, 45 percent of men and 53 percent of women said they worry
about having enough money for the future.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Americans are hungry for advice about their money,
and it explains why publishers keep on pumping out the books.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the books are silly or self-seeking. They might tell
you how your wealth depends on your feelings, for example, or why
you should invest in one particular kind of investment.
</P>
<P>
   But most of them are sound, and some of them are very good.
Among recent offerings, I like these three:
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing for Dummies''
</P>
<P>
   by Eric Tyson. $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   With the second edition of this yellow-covered guide for
beginners, Tyson continues his amiable nurturing of the intelligent
but untutored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that all of us start with the same level of financial
knowledge,'' Tyson writes. ``No one is born knowing this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He provides essays on types of investments, thinking about risk,
goal-setting and other aspects of investing.
</P>
<P>
   There are long chapters on real estate and small-business
ownership as ways of building wealth, which won't be of interest to
many readers. But the basic investing explanations are admirable.
</P>
<P>
   Strong point: Many will turn to Tyson's picks of the best in
various fields, including investment books, software, online
stockbrokers and Internet resources. His favorites among discount
brokers: T. Rowe Price (1-800-225-5132), Vanguard (1-800-992-8327)
and T.D. Waterhouse (1-800-233-3411).''Financial Fitness for Life''
</P>
<P>
   by Jerry Mason. $17.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author may not be as widely known by the public, but
financial planning professionals know him as a valuable teacher to
pros as well as beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, a teacher at Texas Tech University, organized his book
around a series of classroom-style worksheets. That makes the
learning process an orderly, step-by-step process.
</P>
<P>
   That should be rewarding to people who yearn for coherence and
are willing to work for it.
</P>
<P>
   He covers the full spectrum of financial planning issues,
including basic but often overlooked issues like organizing your
files and getting the most from your employee benefits programs.
</P>
<P>
   Strong point: I admire Mason's belief in providing more
resources for the most diligent students.
</P>
<P>
   His book names more than 800 useful organizations and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Savage Truth on Money''
</P>
<P>
   by Terry Savage. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Savage is a Chicago-based writer and pundit, the author of two
previous advice books and an online and television commentator
who's well-known to many people.
</P>
<P>
   Her approach emphasizes self-discipline and a commitment to
learning, and she takes the trouble to explain each point
carefully. The combination makes it easy to understand what you
need to do and why you must assume the responsibility to get it
done.
</P>
<P>
   She also provides many useful Web sites for serious students. My
favorite is her own, www.terrysavage.com, because she provides a
section in which she answers readers' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Strong point: Check out the many and often amusing variants of
just what the ``Savage truth'' is. Here's one of my favorites:
``There are two simple rules for amassing investment wealth: Spend
less than you make. Invest the difference _ both time and money _
to maximum advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-cost learning: tips for buying personal finance books
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for books at your local library. Personal finance books
are numbered 332 and are often in the subgroup 332.6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy your books at discount stores, such as Chapter 11, or on
the Internet. You could start at www.amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shop carefully. Don't fall for books that promise quick riches
or never-fail investment strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
