<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ART-HIBEL17-COX     11-16 2048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HIBEL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artist Hibel moved by 'purest love'
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The wall is pink, but a patch of
sky-blue paint peeks out. Just a tiny bit, around the light switch
in one of Edna Hibel's bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Hibel. One of America's most prolific and commercially
successful artists. A celebrated woman whose work can command as
much as 100 grand a canvas. A tireless taskmaster who rises at 5
a.m., eager for her easel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she can't slap a solid coat of latex on a bedroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it's funny. Ironic even. But once you get to
know her, you'll understand.
</P>
<P>
   A wall has no soul. People do.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what Edna Hibel lives for _ to capture the human
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   A Portuguese mother and child. A Russian woman in a kerchief. A
bearded Japanese farmer. Ballerinas and beggars, peasants and
kings, families and loners, and then some. All painted or sketched
with soft edges, never hard lines.
</P>
<P>
   They are, Hibel says, her ``children.''
</P>
<P>
   And she tends to them while perched beside a plate-glass window
overlooking her back yard so that she can make the most of natural
light. But because the artist, 82, dampens her first brush before
dawn, fluorescent tubes in the ceiling have to suffice until
sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   The Singer Island home she shares with her husband of 58 years,
Theodore ``Tod'' Plotkin, also 82, is a modest retreat with
pea-soup green carpet, pecky cypress paneling, bright yellow
kitchen cabinets and no house number.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone needs to know what it is,'' Hibel says, laughing,
``I'll run out and stick a sign in the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Think grandma's with lots of neat stuff to look at: china- and
wax-faced dolls in frilly floral frocks, three plaster Greek
sculpture replicas that Hibel's mom nabbed for a dollar each when
an art school went under, an old-timey heavy-as-lead metal cash
register with $1.80 popped up in the window.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not even counting Hibel's studio _ built on to the
back of the house _ which bulges with art books and supplies;
filing cabinets; paintbrushes in tarnished trophy cups (including
one she won in a 1937 tennis tournament); and unfinished creations.
</P>
<P>
   Miles of unfinished creations.
</P>
<P>
   That's because she'll dabble on one painting, put it down and
dabble on another. And another. Amazingly, she keeps track, never
fretting about what needs to be done when.
</P>
<P>
   Taking it one day at a time until she quits around 5 p.m.
Working on the same easel she's had for 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feel free to poke around,'' she says, not the least bit
overprotective of her lair, packed with propped-up canvases worth
thousands of dollars. ``I'd apologize for the clutter, but it never
looks any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Hibel's artistic prowess first became apparent to her mom, Lena,
who indulged her only daughter at an art store in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would say, `I have a talented kid, what shall I get her?'
and they'd sell her everything. That store must've thought I was
the most spoiled kid they ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't appear to be a spoiled adult. Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   She carries a cloth purse with a zebra on it, not a designer
label. She drives a burgundy Buick, not a Benz. And she doesn't
sport a chunky diamond _ or any wedding ring at all, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shake hands so much that the ring started to hurt,'' she
says, explaining why her band is tucked away. ``I switched it to
the right hand, but that didn't work either.''
</P>
<P>
   Hibel, although unassuming, is occasionally recognized by Singer
Island townsfolk, who'll sheepishly ask for her autograph. Just the
other day at a beachside restaurant, in fact, a fawning real estate
agent came over and announced that she owned ``several Hibels.''
</P>
<P>
   The artist shook her hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hibel's only sibling _ a younger brother, William, who retired
10 years ago after working for his sister's company _ also lives on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy and I were both brought up to think we were wonderful.
Anything we wanted to do, our parents loved and encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Edna loved painting, and her mother certainly encouraged
it, but she didn't want to do it for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to grow up and run an orphanage because I'd read
Little Women,'' she recalls with a smile. ``I remember playing with
other children _ we lived in an apartment building _ and I'd make
all those kids lie on the stairs and be my orphans.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she started making 15-minute ``sitting''
appointments with those kids so she could paint them. She was 13,
the same age as her father, Abraham, when he immigrated to the
States in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father got married as teenagers and had nothing.
My father told me that when he was 5 or 6 in Poland, he'd think
about America and how it was filled with flowers and butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never lost that feeling of wonderment and optimism, and I
got that from him. He felt like that till he died.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, who became a successful furrier, died in 1960. His
wife, Lena, died 28 years later, one week before her 90th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The artist credits Lena for her relentless attention to detail
(''if your hem was this much off, Mother would notice''), a quality
that contributed to Hibel's acceptance at the Boston Museum of Fine
Arts School in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that she made her first sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another student, an older woman, stopped me in the corridor
and said, 'Are you Edna Hibel? I'd like to buy that painting in the
design room.' I said, 'Oh, no. You can have it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She insisted on paying, so I said, `Would $5 be too much?' and
she said, `Don't be silly. It should be at least twice that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 17, and she wrote me a check for $10. I could've
fainted. Imagine getting paid for something you were born to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting paid would eventually come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   In a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Tod Plotkin, a Harvard grad, helped run an upscale women's
department store in Boston founded by his father. But, due to
soaring downtown rent and sprawling chains, Plotkin Brothers closed
in the late '50s.
</P>
<P>
   Hibel, meanwhile, had been a full-time mom who painted in the
attic and taught art lessons before the couple's three boys _ Jon,
Richard and Andy _ got home from school.
</P>
<P>
   Her work was often featured in exhibitions around the country,
but now it was time for Hibel to put the money where her palette
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never thought of myself as an `artist,' and next thing I
know, my work had to pay the bills. That's when I became an
`artist.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Tod had such faith. He said, `Well, we have this great talent
between us: YOU. Let's do the best we can and see what happens.'
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment he started working with me _ and by that I
mean driving the kids and doing the shopping and making the frames
so I could paint all day _ that was when everything took off.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the first Hibel gallery opened in Rockport, Mass., with
Lena Hibel at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paintings ran from $50 to $150, and Mother said, `I'm
never going to have the nerve to ask that much.' Tod said, `Fine.
You can give a painting away, but you can't sell it for less than
the price.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day she calls Tod and says, `Please. There's a
couple in here that wants a $50 painting for $25. They're so nice.'
He said, `Looks like you're going to have to give it away then.'
Well, he knew she wasn't about to do that. So she demanded $50 and
got it. After that, she was hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Rockport gallery that Hibel's most devoted patrons
_ Ethelbelle and Clayton Craig, then head of the Christian Science
Church _ bought their first paintings. They would eventually own
more than 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an indefinable something in Edna's paintings and
drawings that attracted us to her work,'' Clayton Craig once said.
``We couldn't put our fingers on this quality until we met her.
It's her character. Her great love of people _ all people _ which
she expresses in every painting, drawing or lithograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Hibel's ``something'' lured other collectors, too, and more
galleries followed: Boston, Naples, Miami and, in 1968, Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather up North just didn't agree with my mother,'' Hibel
says, explaining why the family moved to Florida in the '70s.
``Plus, we had trouble shipping out of Boston in the winter because
of the snow. I used to say I'd only paint on sunny days because of
the light, but I couldn't very well do that in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach gallery moved from Worth Avenue to Royal
Poinciana Plaza, and a museum was added in 1977. In January, the
Hibel Museum of Art announced it will move to a $1.8 million
building on the Florida Atlantic University campus in Abacoa, a
Jupiter development.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, scheduled to open in 2001, will sell Hibel's artwork
_ paintings, dolls, lithographs, plates and prints _ as well as
showcase the Craigs' extensive collection. Meanwhile, starting next
month, the nonprofit Edna Hibel Art Foundation will display her
work in the former Roberts Auction House in Lake Worth. (All other
galleries have closed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so worried at first when Tod lost the business, but it
turned out to be the best thing,'' says Hibel, referring to her
husband, who _ to this day _ drives to work each morning to oversee
Hibel's wholesale distribution warehouse in Mangonia Park, along
with the couple's son, Andy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for that, I'd probably still be painting in an
attic,'' she jokes. ``Of course, I later graduated to downstairs
when my oldest son got married. I took over his bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Edna Hibel isn't about the money. And she can't explain how a
painting is priced.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, she'd still rather give her stuff away. Just like
when she was in art school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't my department,'' she explains. ``But if you charge
one price and people pay it, and you go up a little and people
still pay, well, I guess you just keep going up a little. I know my
things go for a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed they do, at least for paintings, which run from $5,000 to
20 times that.
</P>
<P>
   There are affordable items, too. Like lithographs, $150 and up.
Prints, from $50 to $1,000. Plates, between $30 and $300. Dolls,
$150 (assembled overseas) to $2,500 (handmade by local
seamstresses).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful feeling that people want to pay their good
money for something I believe in,'' she says. ``For the way that I
express what I see in humanity: integrity, beauty and love.''
</P>
<P>
   She jokes that, yes, she makes a lot of money, but doesn't have
a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give it away,'' she says, referring to numerous charities,
scholarship funds and family.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Andy, 52, is executive trustee of the Hibel Museum and
lives in Palm Beach Gardens. Meanwhile, Jon, 58, owns a home around
the corner from his parents on Singer Island. (He and his wife
produce mystery theater shows.) And Richard, 49, runs an art
gallery in Hyannisport, Mass. There are five grandchildren, and
Hibel hopes for a great-grandchild soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to be pushy about it,'' she says with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   Hibel doesn't seem to be pushy about anything. Perhaps that's
why she's so soothing to be around. She listens intently when you
speak, never losing eye contact. And you can tell _ even if she's
just met you _ that she cares about what you're saying.
</P>
<P>
   You know she's itching to get back to her easel, but for her,
people come first.
</P>
<P>
   The real ones, not the ones on canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me that when they look at one of my paintings,
they feel like they know me. That they're a better person for
having seen it. But I tell them the truth is, they were a fine
person to begin with. What my paintings bring out is what's already
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Each and every day, Hibel yearns to bring out more _ in herself
and those around her.
</P>
<P>
   She admits, at 82, that time is precious. But she doesn't rush.
</P>
<P>
   One stroke at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I open my eyes, the first thing I want to do is get to
work,'' she says. ``I'm not nervous about it. I just love doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting is like breathing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Grantham writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: lorettagrantham(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
