<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS17-COX     11-16 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NUTS &AMP; BOLTS: Now's time to increase attic's R-value
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was in my attic the other day, checking out the energy
efficiency, and I figure I have about half as much insulation as I
need.
</P>
<P>
   I live in a two-story house built more than 60 years ago, and
the attic has a little more than five inches of blown cellulose
insulation over the floor. That gives me an insulation R-value of
about 19, while the U.S. Department of Energy's recommended attic
insulation for our climate is R-38.
</P>
<P>
   R-value is a measure of an insulating material's resistance to
heat transmission: the higher the value, the more effective the
insulation. An R-38 rating requires about 13 inches of fiberglass
insulation or 11 inches of loose cellulose.
</P>
<P>
   If, like me, you need to upgrade your attic insulation, now's a
good time to get the job done. It typically won't take more than an
afternoon, and, at this time of year, it's neither too hot nor too
cold to work in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Adding attic insulation is one of the easiest and most effective
ways to lower your home heating and cooling bills and to increase
the comfort level of your house.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTS TO USE FOR ATTIC INSULATION
</P>
<P>
   If your attic floor has no insulation, start by installing a
vapor barrier. A vapor barrier can be a paper or foil facing on a
roll of insulation material or a sheet of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   The vapor barrier is placed against the ceiling of the room
below the attic and prevents moisture from the heated areas of the
house from migrating into the insulation, where it can damage the
insulation or boards in the attic structure.
</P>
<P>
   Some insulation products come in rolls with a vapor barrier,
typically craft paper, on one side. If you're using such a roll,
remember that the paper barrier goes right against the warm room
being insulated. In an attic, that means the barrier is face-down
between the floor joists and directly against the plaster or
wallboard of the ceiling underneath.
</P>
<P>
   If a vapor barrier and insulation already are in place, you can
add insulation over the existing layers to increase the R-value.
</P>
<P>
   The two types of insulation you'll see most of in hardware and
home improvement stores is fiberglass fiber and loose cellulose.
Each product has advantages and disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   People I've talked to who have worked with both say cellulose is
usually faster and easier than fiberglass rolls. Cellulose, though,
has to be blown into place with special equipment, and it creates a
lot of dust.
</P>
<P>
   Cellulose is made of shredded recycled paper that has been
treated with chemicals to help it resist fire, insects and mildew.
It's fairly cheap, and you can buy enough loose cellulose
insulating material to add about R-19 of insulation on 1,000 square
feet for about $125. Most home-improvement stores will loan a
blower for a few hours for free if you buy cellulose from them.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy says homeowners using blown cellulose
should keep in mind that the product settles after it is applied.
To get a 10-in layer of cellulose, you might have to blow in about
12 inches. The package the cellulose comes in should tell you how
much the brand you are using compacts.
</P>
<P>
   Loose cellulose insulation can also be used to add insulation to
a house's outside walls if their insulation is currently less than
R-11. The job involves drilling through outside walls and plugging
the holes later. Research thoroughly before attempting such a
project. You might want to consider hiring a professional.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular form of fiberglass insulation comes in rolls
wrapped in thin plastic that reduces some of the skin irritation
associated with working with fiberglass.
</P>
<P>
   When building new houses, fiberglass insulation is usually the
top choice. It's easy to tack or staple rolls of fiberglass
insulation between wall studs and floor joists before the walls and
floors are installed.
</P>
<P>
   But fiberglass rolls also can be rolled between or across joists
in an existing attic. The rolls stay where you put them better than
blown cellulose, but using the rolls requires some measuring and
cutting.
</P>
<P>
   If you comparison shop, you probably can buy enough rolled
fiberglass insulation to add about R-25 in insulating value in a
1,000-square-foot attic for $300 to $350.
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLATION TIPS FOR DO-IT-YOURSELFERS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  No matter what kind of insulation you're working with, it's a
good idea to wear gloves, goggles, a loose-fitting, long-sleeved
shirt and a breathing mask.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't insulate over ventilation airways.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep the insulation materials away from electric fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't step between attic floor joists.
</P>
<P>
   In a well-ventilated attic, air flows in naturally from the area
under the eaves and exits near the apex of the roof. If you
insulate over air inlets at the eaves, you can create serious
overheating in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly if you're using blown cellulose insulation, make
sure you protect ventilation air paths before adding insulation.
The stores that sell insulation also should sell plastic baffles
that provide an air path around insulation materials.
</P>
<P>
   Recessed light fixtures in the ceilings of rooms produce enough
heat to be dangerous if insulating materials get too close.
Maintain the clearance recommended by the manufacturers of the
light fixtures and insulation you are using.
</P>
<P>
   The ceilings in your living areas were not designed to hold much
weight. If you accidently step between the joists _ those boards
set on edge across your attic floor _ you could break through the
ceiling below, resulting in a costly repair.
</P>
<P>
   A sheet of plywood laid across the joists makes a good platform
for working in the attic.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have an idea, question or concern? Contact James Cummings at
225-2395, or by e-mail at jamescummings(at)xcoxohio.com, or write
to the Features Department, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St.,
Dayton, Ohio 45402.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
