<HEADER>
A1270 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN17-COX     11-16 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Math teachers: You pushed Practical Man's buttons
 &HT;    By The Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Longing to win a fight with the spouse? Need
reassurance that your boss/condo president/irritating neighbor is _
how to put this delicately _ a knucklehead? Send your dilemmas to
Practical Man, Accent's appointed hero for a new millennium.
(Motto? He's so right you just want to smack him!)
</P>
<P>
   The practical man has a bone to pick with teachers.
</P>
<P>
   His sixth-grade son came home with a very special surprise last
week.
</P>
<P>
   An F.
</P>
<P>
   On a math test.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the love of God, boy!'' bellowed the practical man. ``What
do you mean by this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get math.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical man reeled, wobbled, then sat down. He'd heard
about people who ``aren't any good at math,'' but his son could not
possibly be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He huddled with his child. He went over the test line by line.
His heart sank. It looked like 10 minutes' work for anyone over age
9. His 11-year-old boy had spent an hour on it and scored 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number 7,'' the practical man said. ``What's 10 percent of 65?
How'd you come up with 23?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me get my calculator.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical man chuckled in disbelief. ``You don't need a
calculator for that, son. Do it in your head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to have my calculator.''
</P>
<P>
   And here, teachers, is where you come in. Because in the eyes of
Practical Man Jr., the test wasn't about math at all. It was about
calculators, which are required for all kids in his class. He had
no idea what percent means, didn't have an inkling that there was
an idea behind the % sign on his junky little gizmo. To him, math
was memorizing a correct sequence of keystrokes.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man straightened him out in short order.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got angry. What was a sixth-grader doing with a
calculator in math class? Shortcuts are not for kids. For anyone
who hasn't traveled the hard road, they inevitably lead to helpless
stupidity. You become the computer dolt who twiddles his thumbs and
calls tech support when his icons disappear. Or the dorm doofus who
lives on potato chips when the microwave dies. Or the boy who
wrings his hands and whimpers over an F because he's been taught
only how to push buttons, not how to think.
</P>
<P>
   The practical man never thought he'd have to say this to math
teachers, but come on. Get practical!
</P>
<P>
   Now, on to the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: You're absolutely correct in writing that a
practical man would not keep fish or birds. And practical man
especially abhors cats! But cut dogs some slack. They are man's _
yes, even practical man's _ best friend.
</P>
<P>
   _Randall
</P>
<P>
   Pet dogs have little appeal for the practical man. They cost
money, soil the home, foul the air and produce nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the practical man arrived at this truth not by
reason, but by bitter experience. To keep his pet-loving family
happy, he owns not only two slothful canines, but three cats, four
caged birds, two ducks, six rabbits, a turtle, a tank of fish and
lord only knows how many stealth pets such as hamsters, salamanders
and gerbils that live in children's rooms without his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   That's why he instituted the Adopt-A-Pet Program, wherein every
child is required to sponsor the pets she cares about. Sponsors are
charged with paying all pet expenses, doing all dirty work and,
most important, keeping the filthy beasts away from the practical
man.
</P>
<P>
   An age-old dilemma: My wife rails at me for scanning the TV
channels rapid-fire with the remote control. She prefers the
Stone-Age method of looking at the TV listings and choosing first.
Please tell me that my method is superior, and please, no lectures
on how I'm wasting my life watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   _Roy
</P>
<P>
   The practical man surfs. In fact, he is surfing right now,
flipping rapid-fire through his mail, searching for an intelligent
question worth more than two seconds of his . . . Click.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding, Roy. Think of TV as a restaurant. She likes to
order from the menu, but you want the all-you-can-eat buffet. The
practical man likes the freedom and the bounty of a buffet, but he
always scans the menu first. Otherwise, he might stuff himself with
chicken tenders and Tater Tots when he could have had a steak and
baked potato for a mere buck more.
</P>
<P>
   Practical Man writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
