<P>
   NEW-COMMENTARY _ Kids look at the world fresh, taking it apart
and putting it back together in new combinations. It's always been
a joy to see the world through the eyes of a child. But now that
joy is bought and sold. Corporations hire scouts to prowl the
nightclubs, the streets, the schools, the Internet sites, trying to
pick up the barest scent of something new and track it to its
source. Because these days, if you can deliver new, or even the
illusion of new, they'll make you a director, a producer, an
Internet billionaire. (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SLAVERY-COMMENTARY _ A significant number of Southerners deny
that slavery had much to do with Southern secession. They point to
states' rights, self-determination, liberty, protection of hearth
and home, everything but slavery. No historical event as vast as
the creation of a Southern nation can be explained in monocausal
terms. But there can be no doubt about the centrality of racial
slavery to the creation of the Confederacy. In fact, no slavery, no
Confederacy. (Roark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ It is pretty much a settled matter for most
Americans that execution for juvenile murder is, like a Martha
Stewart centerpiece, A Good Thing. Indeed, if there's anything
Americans like better than executing juveniles, it is executing
just about anyone else. We're a world leader. (Teepen, Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ (Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) Now that China
and the Clinton administration have signed an agreement that clears
the way for the Communist state to join the World Trade
Organization, Clinton is pledging an ``all-out effort'' with the
Congress for approval of the agreement. Likely he will run into
rough water, in part because of the Monica scandal. Thus has
Clinton's clout gone. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Hillary Clinton stepped into the Middle
East the other day with little more in mind than making politically
nice. That's impossible in the Middle East. Hillary stepped on a
large, squishy cow chip placed beneath her unwary foot by Soha
Arafat, wife of Palestinian honcho Yasser. (Rosenfeld, Cox News
Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ It was a chore getting the
stuff off my Ma's shelves. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Either a University of Colorado
regent is taking group punishment to the extreme, or he's hit on a
new dimension in campus life. We make rioting a club sport. (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Something ``medical''
happened to me recently, and I'm pretty sure I'm going to have to
pay for it myself. I don't think the insurance folks have a code
for what I just lived through. It had to do with Pokemon, Y2K and
Christmas hype _ all of which I blame on Martha Stewart. (Minor,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-CHINA _ U.S.-China relations have been so poor it is
tempting to view any change as a a boon _ the bigger the change,
the better. This week's trade deal has the potential to civilize
and enrich the world's most populous nation, to the benefit of the
rest of the world, but the deal's details and China's adherence to
them will bear watching. (Atlanta Constitution)
</P>
