<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A gardening column by Lee May. Ellen Frances
Rosser, like so many food gardeners, never stops growing for the
table. Assorted victuals thrive even as food crops for us
hot-weather growers fade into faraway memory. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's influx of new people from all
parts of the world is bringing some big changes in the way
Atlantans furnish their homes. In a market once dominated by
traditional tastes _ contemporary furnishing is making noteworthy
inroads. Driving it, designers said, are a number of factors _
fashion trends, mass media design exposure, a nostalgic recall of
classic lines as a new century looms, a strong economy ripe for
risk taking, the home invasion of technology. So what is
contemporary? Think clean lines, light woods, satin metals, natural
fabric and earth colors. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   NUTS-AND-BOLTS _ If, like me, you need to upgrade your attic
insulation, now's a good time to get the job done. It typically
won't take more than an afternoon, and at this time of year it's
neither too hot nor too cold to work in the attic. Adding attic
insulation is one of the easiest and most effective ways to lower
your home heating and cooling bills and to increase the comfort
level of your house. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 26. MOVED.
</P>
