r e BC-MUSIC-CHARLIE-ROBISON     11-16 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHARLIE-ROBISON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLIE ROBISON BREAKS THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEY GUERRA  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Robison has never played by the often-constricting rules
of mainstream country music _ even when he's had the chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin, Texas-based singer-songwriter, who plays with his
brother, Bruce Robison, and Jack Ingram, first made waves with his
independent debut album, ``Bandera'' _ named for the small Texas
town where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Excited by Robison's songwriting skills and eclectic country
flavor, major labels came calling. Warner Bros. offered Robison a
contract, and he signed on the dotted line. Disappointments soon
followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just took forever,'' said Robison, 33, of making that
album, which was shelved by the label, never to be released. ``It
was kind of an unlimited-budget deal. I didn't really like that.
You had enough time to second-guess yourself and really take a lot
of the soul out of the recording.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time for Robison to record 1998's ``Life of the
Party,'' the bigwigs came sniffing around again. Robison was
naturally wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was real tough for me to go back (to a major label), and
when Sony offered me a deal, I was like, `OK, is this what I wanna
do?''' Robison said. ``The first time around, it wasn't a great
experience at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Sony subsidiary label Lucky Dog offered Robison
what his former label wouldn't: complete artistic freedom and no
push for promotion or radio singles.
</P>
<P>
   Working with co-producer Lloyd Maines, Robison made ``Life of
the Party'' in just 10 days. The result? A solid blend of
rockabilly, Tex-Mex and honky tonk, anchored by Robison's
thought-provoking songwriting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'm a good study of the human condition,'' Robison
said. ``The best things to write about aren't famous people or
anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   It's the small towns, the scrungiest bars, just the regular
folk.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, Robison was heavily influenced by a number of
been-there, done-that songwriters, including Jackson Browne, Willie
Nelson and Guy Clark. It was only natural that his words would come
straight from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   He also admires the music of Bruce Springsteen and Tom Waits,
saying, ``They talked about how human beings weren't perfect. It
made you feel like you weren't the only one out there who had kinda
screwed up in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Robison showcases his brand of being human in a number of songs.
``Sunset Boulevard'' finds a man yearning for fame so he can deal
with a failed relationship (``I'd spend all my money/On caviar and
Rogaine/And I would not remember/How you broke my heart today'').
``You're Not the Best'' is an oddly affecting ode to a
less-than-perfect love (``We're gonna twist them lids and hope/Our
kids look more like me than you.'') Humor, it seems, is another
vital element in Robison's alternative to country-music radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys I listen to, they'd always be talking about
something real serious, and then I'd start cracking up at the same
time,'' Robison said. ``John Prine, especially, always had a way of
sneaking humor into the most serious of situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Robison is planning to head back into the studio in late
December or early January to record a new album, one he hopes will
``be along the lines of what I've always done, but I hope it still
continues to change a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Current commitments include the Lucky Dog tour, which finds the
Texas-based performers and label mates consolidating their bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great. We've all been really good friends, of
course, and Bruce has been my brother for a long time,'' Robison
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of us had kind of the eclectic country crowd
together. It was easier for the label, too. With tour support and
publicity and things like that, they were able to kinda kill three
birds with one stone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Robison brothers have shared many stages, and Bruce, along
with wife Kelly Willis, even pops up singing background vocals on
Charlie's ``Life of the Party.'' Robison admits the two brothers
have their share of disagreements, but he chalks it up to regular
family routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been real close throughout the whole journey. Musically,
there's just such a real close kinship there,'' Robison said.
``Plus, everybody's gotten so busy that this is like almost the
only time we get to hang out with each other. That's kind of a cool
aspect to it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the hectic schedule is due to Robison's marriage to
Dixie Chick Emily Erwin in May. The two made a few side trips as a
honeymoon during the Dixie Chicks' European tour.
</P>
<P>
   As for a possible lovey-dovey musical collaboration, Robison
said he and his wife plan to take their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it. That will probably happen down the line,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so important for us to completely hammer out careers
where you're looked at separately before you do anything like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Robison's penchant for remaining an individual, that
shouldn't be too much of a problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
