<SLUG> BC-BLACK-BLUE-TV-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK AND BLUE' A SURPRISING AND STRONG DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  3 stars  
(Eds: Fact box at bottom.) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Far smarter than the average woman-in-peril telefilm, no doubt
because it's based on an Anna Quindlen novel, ``Black and Blue''
offers a solemn yet surprisingly redemptive take on the issue of
battered wives. As awful as one's choices in life may be,
Quindlen's book and the film ultimately decide, one's resolute
instinct for motherhood smooths the bumps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your children make it impossible to regret your past,''
Quindlen writes at the end of her book. ``They're its finest
fruits.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Stuart Masterson stars as Fran, married to Bobby (Anthony
LaPaglia), whose job as a Brooklyn police detective, everyone
apparently agrees, protects him from censure when he beats his
wife. One day, Fran tires of the routine bruisings and approaches a
woman at a rescue shelter, who immediately decides that counseling
or divorce are not options _ Fran must change her identity and move
away. That decision is arrived at far too quickly, but after all,
this is just a two-hour film.
</P>
<P>
   Fran, pausing idiotically to cut her own hair at home before
going on the lam _ what's the point of changing your looks if you
telegraph to the guy you're hiding from that your looks have been
changed? _ takes her fifth-grade son, Robert (Will Rothaar), with
her. Though he fears the beatings his mother takes almost as much
as she does, he's terribly conflicted about skipping out on his dad
_ the film drops disquieting hints that Robert has perhaps already
assimilated some of his father's moody traits.
</P>
<P>
   They land in a rathole in Florida and struggle to remake their
lives (the rescue center provided them with new identities). Of
course, back home, Bobby isn't reacting well to his beloved
punching bag's disloyalty, and a fairly convenient plot contrivance
assists him in his search for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson _ an actress who has always been a little too
interesting and internal in her work for Hollywood to transform her
into a star _ does reliably sensitive work here. LaPaglia, in what
could easily be a thankless role, gives a finely calibrated
performance _ at times, one can almost see why Fran stays with this
lout.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this film with ``Sleeping With the Enemy,'' the fairly
ridiculous 1991 Julia Roberts vehicle that serves up essentially
the same plot, and you'll appreciate just how much this film gets
right. ``Black and Blue'' never lapses into the overheated hokum of
its predecessor, and where the couple's final confrontation was
pure lunacy in the big-screen movie, here it's chillingly
effective, disquietingly realistic and artfully discrete. A film
like this could almost give the women-in-peril telegenre a good
name.
</P>
<P>
   _ Th &UR; e  &LR; show &UR; : &LR;  ``Black and Blue.''  &QL; 
_ What &UR; : &LR;  Adaptation of Anna Quindlen's novel about a wife escaping
from her abusive husband, who happens to be a policeman. &QL; 
_ The stars &UR; : &LR;  Mary Stuart Masterson, Anthony LaPaglia, Will
Rothaar, Sam Robards. &QL; 
_ Channel &UR; : &LR;  CBS (KCBS, Channel 2). &QL; 
_ When &UR; : &LR;  9 tonight. &QL; 
_ Our rating &UR; : &LR;  3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
