<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-FRANKLIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN OF SOUL PENS IMPERFECT AUTOBIOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRENDA GUNTER  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (``Aretha: From These Roots''; by Aretha Franklin and David
Ritz; Villard, $25)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's zooming who?'' Raising more questions than it answers,
Aretha Franklin's autobiography, written with David Ritz, evokes
her 1986 hit about being played for a fool.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Franklin rose from her humble beginnings in
Memphis, Tenn., in 1942 to become the Queen of Soul is fascinating.
She warmly recalls the people and places of Detroit, where her
family moved soon after her birth. Her father, the Rev. C.L.
Franklin, a legend in his own right, set a high standard for his
three daughters and two sons to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin's mother, nurse's aide Barbara Siggers, moved to
Buffalo, N.Y., when Franklin was 6 years old. Here, in the first
chapter, the book begins an irksome pattern. Franklin explains that
her mother, contrary to what a Time magazine profile suggested, did
not abandon her family.
</P>
<P>
   Then she sets the record straight by explaining how her parents
had agreed that the children would remain in Detroit. The children
and their mother visited often for the next four years, until her
mother's death when Franklin was 10.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing an erroneous story more than 20 years old gives it
more validity than it deserves. It also adds an awkward sense of
hostility to what otherwise serves as an engaging narrative.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rev. Franklin's church grew, numerous performers began to
call the Franklin household their second home. Gospel singers James
Cleveland and Clara Ward, not to mention a young pop sensation
named Sam Cooke, stopped by often, providing musical inspiration.
Smokey Robinson was a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   When Franklin was 13, she became pregnant with the first of her
four children. She bore a second child at 16. Here again, she
offers little insight. How did a minister's daughter become an
unmarried teen mother not once but twice? She explains it away by
saying her father considered all children blessings from God. And
she coyly refers to the children's fathers in pseudonyms such as
``Romeo.'' Although there has been speculation that one or both of
the children were Cooke's, the context of her narrative doesn't
support it.
</P>
<P>
   Groomed by her father as a singer, Franklin got a record
contract with Columbia in 1960. Legendary producer John Hammond
marketed her as a jazz singer, and she gained experience on the
nightclub circuit, supported by a four-piece band. Then, in 1966,
she moved to Atlantic, where producer Jerry Wexler turned her into
the Queen of Soul. Songs such as ``Respect,'' ``Think'' and ``Chain
of Fools'' ensured her success. She currently records with Arista.
</P>
<P>
   While telling of her journey to stardom, Franklin drops names
right and left. She engages in catty commentary, criticizing Gladys
Knight and gospel singer Cissy Houston, whose daughter Whitney
calls her Auntie Ree and credits her as her inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   She describes Barbra Streisand in all but name, telling of an
incident in which the nameless diva gestured obscenely to her in
the White House during Bill Clinton's first term. She even disses
some of the family members to whom she dedicated the book.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Aretha: From These Roots'' provides no index
for the dirt-diggers among us. A more extensive discography would
have been nice, too, given her musical stature.
</P>
<P>
   Ritz, who has written biographies of Ray Charles, Marvin Gaye
and B.B.
</P>
<P>
   King, knows his subject but sometimes allows factual errors to
slip by, such as one that placed Franklin at a different stage in
her career than history indicates. As a professional writer, he
should have taken a more active role in playing down Franklin's
petty grievances and playing up the specifics of her musical
career.
</P>
<P>
   Although Franklin will always be the Queen of Soul, we may never
know quite why. ``Aretha'' does a decent job covering the basics,
but it lacks the insight that must be present to make an
autobiography a worthwhile account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
