<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVVY AGENTS GOING ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Amid the competition between traditional travel agents
and upstart online services to plan and book our vacations, a new
strategy is emerging: Travel agencies in Houston and nationwide are
beginning to establish an Internet presence of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some reports indicate that almost 50 percent of all
agencies now sponsor a Web site, although these fledgling ventures
vary dramatically in quality and depth.
</P>
<P>
   This development isn't surprising given these factors: _
Research shows that travel-related Internet sites continue to grow
in terms of access and interest, a reality standard agencies can't
afford to ignore. The variety and ingenuity of online offerings _
from last-minute air-fare specials to bid sites and auctions _ also
is expanding.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the same time, Web browsing isn't necessarily translating
into Web bookings: Online reservations also are increasing but at a
slower pace, with studies showing that most travelers _ even the
majority of ``wired'' travelers _ still favor travel agents when
purchasing trip elements.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons cited most are the importance of human contact and
concern about online security.
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST OF BOTH WORLDS
</P>
<P>
   Savvy travel agents hope to offer consumers the best of both
worlds: the opportunity to research and shop online, with follow-up
counseling readily available.
</P>
<P>
   While family-owned agencies don't possess the resources to rival
the scope of online giants such as Travelocity, Expedia and
Priceline or a projected new site involving several major airlines,
they can ``localize'' information, stress the variety of available
services _ and remind that visiting their office requires only a
short drive. In many instances, bookings would be available online
or at the agency office.
</P>
<P>
   So how is this online experiment faring in its infancy? A
surfing expedition last week proved enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   And frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ACCESSING GOOD INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   At several sites recently initiated by local agencies, I
uncovered useful information about discounted tour packages,
half-price cruises, honeymoon packages and other up-to-date
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   One site sponsored by West University Travel
(www.westutravel.com), an American Express affiliate, covers topics
as diverse as hot millennium deals, Houston-area passport
acceptance offices, descriptions of shore excursions aboard the
Houston-based Norwegian Sea cruise ship and a calendar of upcoming
area travel shows.
</P>
<P>
   Another operated by Woodlake Travel Services
(www.woodlaketravel.com), which has two offices in west Houston,
describes a wide range of trips but also provides links to currency
exchange rates, State Department Consular Information Sheets,
reports from the Centers for Disease Control, student travel
bargains _ and lodging in Scottish castles.
</P>
<P>
   Savings Travel, an agency in southwest Houston whose specialties
include consolidator air fares, offers ``Today's Specials From
Houston'' on its site at www.savingstravel.com. At
www.vacationstogo.com, operated by Houston-based Vacations to Go, a
``90-day ticker'' lists almost 200 sharply discounted cruises
available from that company for departures over the next three
months.
</P>
<P>
   Most local agencies, however, don't possess the staff or
resources of Vacations to Go, which markets nationally. And it's
evident that agencies affiliated with a national chain or
consortium hold a distinct advantage in being able to pool
resources in creating Web sites and in attracting potential
customers through a common link.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: I accessed www.carlsontravel.com, and that site
guided me to information about the 14 Houston-area Carlson Wagonlit
agencies. I learned that 12 operate Web sites, 11 are set up to
receive e-mail inquiries and two are equipped to handle
reservations online.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when I sneaked a peek at these individual sites, I found
quite a contrast. Future Travel in nearby Clear Lake City listed
about 25 discounted air-hotel special packages from Houston to
Jamaica, Cancun, Las Vegas and other destinations. Utopia Travel in
the Galleria area offered a complimentary e-mail listing of several
cruises currently available at half-price. But some Carlson
agencies merely reproduced the standard ``home page'' offered by
the parent company, providing no practical information. One
rerouted me to an agency in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   My biggest challenge was in discovering the mere existence of
other Houston agency sites. And while I'm no expert at this
search-from-scratch process, neither are many of the potential
customers agencies hope to attract.
</P>
<P>
   I was especially disappointed when I accessed www.astanet.com,
the Internet operation of the 28,000-member American Society of
Travel Agents. A consumer-friendly site in many ways, this online
service allows browsers to type the first three numbers of a ZIP
code (or a city name) and, in response, lists all member agencies
(or, if preferred, those with a special focus) within that region.
</P>
<P>
   When I typed the numbers 770 for Houston, www.astanet.com
quickly identified 180 member agencies by name, address and
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail addresses also were provided for about half the agencies.
But only one direct Internet link _ to TransAmerica Travel (at
www.traveltata.com) in southwest Houston _ was included.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, at www.supertravel.com and www.allseasons.com, I found
a wealth of general information but no Houston affiliates' Web
addresses or direct links.
</P>
<P>
   I predict that this will soon change _ that ASTA and leading
multiagent organizations will be at the forefront of identifying
and promoting individual agency Internet projects.
</P>
<P>
   And consumers can only benefit from new options for discovering
vacation bargains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
