<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1337 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-16 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG DROPPINGS NOT OFTEN FATAL TO LAWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHY HUBER  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: I have heard that dog urine and droppings can
damage a lawn. Can you tell me what effect these have on a
well-maintained, healthy lawn? A: We live in a neighborhood with
lots of dogs and dog walkers, but no sidewalks. Our lawns run right
to the narrow street, and dog excreta is a daily deal. I'm not
complaining; we have dogs, too.
</P>
<P>
   But I've noted that a small amount of urine either has no effect
or results in a small brown or yellow circle ringed in dark green.
Dog urine contains nitrogen and works like fertilizer. The grass
seems to handle urine just fine in relatively small doses. The
brown/yellow spots eventually green up again.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the dog can be a factor. And because they squat,
female dogs can leave greater concentrations, which you can dilute
by watering.
</P>
<P>
   According to research I've read, it's possible that dog excreta
does greater damage to lawns already maxed out on fertilizer. It
all amounts to nitrogen overload.
</P>
<P>
   If a dog frequently visits the same spot, the grass in that area
likely will die. In this case, I would redirect the dog. But
because our growing season is so long, the spot should eventually
fill back in.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is tolerant. And I'm not happy when our male
dog lifts its leg and marks a prized perennial. While one visit may
not do much damage, continued visits will, so I grab the water hose
in an attempt to wash away the odor that triggers return visits.
</P>
<P>
   While dog urine is liquid and the nitrogen is more quickly
absorbed, dog feces break down more slowly and are less likely to
burn the lawn. Of course, if a dog messes regularly where there's
traffic, you'll likely want to remove the feces.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Since I'm not a scientist, I did a little Internet research of
my own and found quite a bit has been said on this subject. One
article listed on the Aggie Horticulture Plant Answers Web site is
a detailed report from a Purdue University veterinarian. His paper
puts a lot of lawn myths to rest. For details, see
aggie-horticulture.tamu.edu/plantanswers/turf/doglawnproblems.html.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do I care for a potted thornless lime? How do I get a
potted bird of paradise to bloom again? A: The thornless lime is
pretty easy. Give it plenty of sun to maximize blooms. Provide a
good, well-draining potting soil. You can work a little sand,
perlite or large-size composted bark into the potting soil to
prevent future compaction.
</P>
<P>
   Your small tree likes moderate water but not soggy conditions.
Keep the soil evenly moist, especially for summer production. The
best results come with a biweekly or monthly application of a
balanced liquid fertilizer such as a 10-10-10 during the growing
season. Slow-release fertilizers are suitable, too. Flush the
container every six weeks or so to discourage a buildup of salts.
</P>
<P>
   Should chlorosis develop _ yellowing between veins in the leaves
_ you may be overwatering. A second possibility is low soil
fertility. The third cause is improper soil pH. Citrus fruits do
not like a too-alkaline soil, indicated by a high pH, preferring
one that is neutral to slightly acidic.
</P>
<P>
   This citrus requires minimum pruning. Remove suckers and damaged
or dead wood, and occasionally shape the tree, if needed. Avoid
fall pruning, as this will promote new growth more vulnerable to
frost.
</P>
<P>
   Repot next spring if necessary. Fifteen-gallon containers are
recommended for mature trees so the plant can become large enough
to bear good quantities of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   You're likely to find that spring brings the heaviest blooms and
fruit, but the thornless lime will continue to bloom anytime it is
warm. Fruit drop is common among citrus, and there's nothing a
gardener can do but be patient. Fruit drop should decrease with
age.
</P>
<P>
   The plant should be OK to 32 degrees, but below that pull it out
of the cold. If the plant should burn back, it likely will regrow,
unless a severe freeze kills the roots.
</P>
<P>
   Bird of paradise (``Strelitzia reginae''), native to South
Africa, grows to about 4 feet in height and prefers a
well-draining, fertile soil, moisture during the growing season but
drier conditions while dormant. Give it sun to light shade.
</P>
<P>
   Bird of paradise will not bloom until it's mature and has formed
a large clump, which may take several years. To encourage flowering
then, apply a fertilizer low in nitrogen and high in phosphorus and
potassium. Cool winter temperatures are said to help flowering once
a plant is mature, and container plants flower best if somewhat
root-bound.
</P>
<P>
   While bird of paradise may survive a dip to the mid-20s, it's
best to protect it during freezing weather.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
