<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MADE-FOR-TV START BY THE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Jets holding an 18-point lead over the Patriots at the
end of the first half, ABC's Al Michaels quipped, ``Isn't this a
fine kettle of Tuna?''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the funniest thing ever said on Monday Night Football,
but it was apt.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells appeared every bit the curse radio talk-show
callers have made him out to be. But a curse had nothing to do with
Curtis Martin's 36-yard draw play in which he ran into the end zone
untouched. It was a perfect call that caught Chris Slade
overrunning the play. In the second half, the Jets orchestrated an
11-minute drive that resulted in a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't have scripted a better game for the Jets, so
far,'' said Boomer Esiason at the start of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Everything went the Jets' way early. ``The 2-6 Jets came here to
the home of the 6-2 Patriots and have completely dominated the
game,'' Michaels said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Michaels and Boomer Esiason disagreed with Patriots coach
Pete Carroll's decision to go for a touchdown instead of kicking a
field goal from the Jets' 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer was particularly baffled by Drew Bledsoe's first
interception when he threw a bomb into the wind. ``Drew has a
strong arm but the ball just hung up there,'' Esiason said.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer praised Jets quarterback Ray Lucas for his poise and
enthusiasm. Lucas scrambled out of the pocket for a nice
first-quarter gain. ``That's what football players do,'' Esiason
said. ``They make things happen. Lucas is a football player first
and a quarterback second.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels got off a good line about the Jets' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of single coverage on Ben Coates near the goal line,
Parcells had two men on the tight end, prompting Michaels to
describe the defense as ``coverage by mugging.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels, the only one left from MNF's glory days, showed again
that he is the consummate professional. His voice is timeless,
equally at home with old-school announcers like Curt Gowdy and new
kids like Joe Buck. He has called Super Bowls, Olympics, World
Series, and the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels is probably best known for his call of the US Olympic
hockey team's upset victory at Lake Placid in 1980: ``Do you
believe in miracles?''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Michaels has been unafraid to criticize NFL team
owners or even television networks. During a broadcast of the
Oakland Raiders' 13-3 loss to the Denver Broncos two years ago on a
Monday night, Michaels called the Raiders ``the most underachieving
team in the league'' and derided the team's slogan, ``Commitment to
Excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders criticized Michaels, but he responded by saying he
was simply being true to his fans.
</P>
<P>
   Using a two-man booth has allowed the game to breathe a little
more, said Michaels, and that fits perfectly with the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers are inundated with special effects,'' he said. ``Why
do I have to listen to a sound effect every time there is a
different camera shot? If producers don't use special effects
judiciously, it could turn viewers away from their television sets.
We don't want to be stodgy or anything, but viewers have become so
accustomed to so much noise and clutter that silence is almost
welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football'' is still a fixture in the American
sports landscape, still important after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hope that people are not footballed out by Monday,''
Michaels said.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a sign of surrender. Michaels said that ``Monday
Night Football'' has maintained ``its sense of uniqueness,''
despite a slew of competition from various cable stations and prime
time network shows such as ``Ally McBeal'' and professional
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've evolved over the years,'' Michaels said. ``We try to
entertain with more information. The viewers expect more these days
and we are, essentially, in the copycat business. Fox comes out
with a scorebox and now everyone has one. Our philosophy is to not
ask ourselves what we can do differently but what can we do to
enhance the show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly writes about the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
