u s BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     11-16 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER MASTERFUL GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He thought it was stacked against him from
the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   A Monday night game on the road against a team that considers
his team its most bitter rival.
</P>
<P>
   And waiting for him was an officiating crew he would have
preferred not to see because of past experiences.
</P>
<P>
   But when it was all over, and he had another improbable victory
to add to his brilliant coaching dossier, the Jets' Bill Parcells
was more tired than jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   His team had overcome tremendous odds to gain its most
satisfying win of the season, but he wasn't about to gloat. He
likes too many Patriots players to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was tilted the Patriots' way. At home. Two weeks off.
Friendly officiating crew. Sellout crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells had given his team a pregame message, something he
has said for weeks: ``It's too soon to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   They might be in the midst of a tremendously disappointing
season, but Monday night they fought to save some face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play a complementary game to win,'' said Parcells
Saturday. ``We have to run the ball on offense; take time off the
clock; keep Drew (Bledsoe) from completing any 30-yard passes. If
we do that, we have a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets did, and they won. The game wasn't as close as the
final score. They used the wind to breeze to a 24-3 lead entering
the fourth quarter, and then watched as the defense came apart
before regrouping to stop the Patriots twice in the final five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' game plan was simple: Do everything possible to knock
down Bledsoe. They were not going to let him get comfortable in the
pocket, and they would try to have someone in his face all night.
</P>
<P>
   The first three quarters were a nightmare for the Patriots'
quarterback. He had just 73 yards passing and had thrown three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets pressed him, knocked him down, chased him out of the
pocket, completely throwing the Patriots' passing game out of
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets weren't even concerned with the Patriots' running game.
They never considered it a threat. Bledsoe was the target and they
zeroed in on him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the lone mistake the Jets' defense made came in the
fourth quarter when they seemed to play soft with a 21-point lead.
When they did, Bledsoe took advantage and ignited the Patriots to
two quick touchdowns. After that, the Jets blitzed relentlessly and
Bledsoe didn't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin was a one-man gang for the Jets, who lined up and
ran power football at the Patriots' line. Most of the time they ran
Martin to the perimeter behind a cortege of pulling linemen,
letting him pick his spot to make a slashing run across the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The wind was strong the entire evening and the Jets made better
use of it than the Patriots. New York held the ball for 37 minutes
38 seconds, more than 15 minutes longer than the Patriots (22:22),
meaning they had the ball for a full quarter more than the
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets scored all of their touchdowns with the wind in the
second period; the Patriots didn't score a point with the wind all
night.
</P>
<P>
   The critical sequence in the game came in the third period, and
trickled into the fourth, when the Jets held the ball for for 19
plays and 11 minutes before kicking a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   That forced the Patriots to try to make up a 21-point deficit
going into the wind in the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   With a little more than 2 minutes left, Parcells had to make a
key decison. The Jets led, 24-17, but the Patriots had a fourth and
1 at the New England 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about going for it right there,'' said Parcells.
``If we made it, we won the game. But I thought we would be better
off punting the ball, and having our defense stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   They did and he had another victory over the Patriots in
Foxborough, that was good, but in his words, ``nothing special.
People keep trying to say this is special. It's not. It's just
another win. I'm happy for my players. They played hard and did
what they had to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
