<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BARROS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARROS, OTHER CELTICS SUBS, TRY TO GET STRAIGHTENED OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ _ He is a writer, known for his accurate phrasing.
There have been times when he has sat on the team bus and penned a
few verses. He shares his work, too. Last season, he thought about
the role of the Celtics' second unit and gave the group a perfect
nickname: The Bomb Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven games into the season, the writer _ Dana Barros _ has
a significant task. Some of the Bomb Squad members have changed,
and the man who named them now sees some strange numbers next to
his name.
</P>
<P>
   Barros is averaging 4.6 points and shooting 42 percent in 15
minutes per game. Some of his most unpleasant days as a pro came
when he played in Seattle, but Barros still didn't have numbers
like that in any season with the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Is it time to panic? He might do that if he didn't have
archives. All he has to do is go through his files and stop at the
folder marked ``1999 Season, Beginning Of'' to put this in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was terrible at the beginning of the season,'' he
said. ``I shot something like 20 percent from 3-point range at the
beginning of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   His 3-point shooting is not a problem now. He has taken seven
shots from Faraway Land and made four of them. Being the economical
writer that he is, Barros summed up his early weaknesses in one
sentence: ``I just have to be more aggressive.'' Later, he
explained, ``Right now, I'm just a spot-up shooter and I'm a better
player than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, several members of this season's Bomb Squad are better
than they have shown. Tony Battie can be very effective when he
spots up 10 feet from the hoop and releases a high-arcing jumper.
But that hasn't happened enough and Battie is shooting 39 percent
from the floor. Walter McCarty began the season with a stunning
performance against the Raptors, including 6 for 6 from 3-point
range. Since then, he has gone 2 for 10 on his threes and is
shooting 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Williams? He has played 100 fewer minutes than Vitaly
Potapenko but has attempted five more free throws than the
6-foot-10-inch center. The problem with Williams is simply time. As
in, where does he find it playing behind Adrian Griffin and Paul
Pierce, No. 1 and No. 2 on the team in minutes played?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rick Pitino said he was pleased with the bench play, with
the exception of Saturday night's loss at Chicago. The bench was 3
for 20 from the field at the United Center. Barros was 1 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   As the literary leader-unofficial spokesman for the Bomb Squad,
Barros said he knows what the group must do. It is nothing
complicated. Simply, the players have to depend on each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play that way,'' Barros said. ``We don't have a
go-to guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The second unit will get some reinforcements in the next several
weeks. Calbert Cheaney will return when he recovers from an ankle
sprain. Pitino said Monday that if the team followed the examples
set by Cheaney and Griffin, the Celtics would have an outstanding
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a big if,'' Pitino said.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Doug Overton also might help Barros. Overton is
a veteran point guard, so he and Barros could play together for
stretches in which Barros would be the shooting guard. That would
allow the 5-foot-11-inch Barros to concentrate more on scoring,
something the second-team Bombers seem to need desperately right
now. A long-term solution will be the return of Danny Fortson. The
power forward should be back in a month. That means either Fortson
or Griffin will become a second-teamer.
</P>
<P>
   If that role goes to Fortson, the Squad will not have to worry
about second and third chances because Fortson is a rebounder. If
Griffin goes to the bench, he has shown that he can score and
rebound _ especially rebound _ when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   While scrimmaging with the Celtics' Green Team in Monday's
practice in Waltham, Antoine Walker led a fast break. He looked to
his left and passed to his right, where Barros caught the ball and
put in a nice layup. As the players walked to the sideline, Walker
said, ``Nice finish, Dana.'' He paused and added, ``Finally.'' They
both laughed. Now Barros will try to finish like that in a real
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
