<HEADLINE>
MLS CUP BECOMING A HOT TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The weather is cooling but ticket sales are heating up for
Sunday's MLS Cup final at Foxboro Stadium, thanks to D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold 2,500 tickets this morning and I would be surprised if
the crowd isn't more than 40,000,'' Revolution CEO Brian O'Donovan
said. ``This is a dream match, what everyone was hoping to see _ a
rematch of the 1996 final.''
</P>
<P>
   D.C. United qualified for the final for the fourth successive
year, taking a 4-0 victory over Columbus in the Eastern Conference
playoff Saturday. The Los Angeles Galaxy won the Western Conference
title with a 3-1 victory over Dallas Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both United and the Galaxy have reputations for presenting an
aesthetically pleasing brand of soccer, and both teams have dynamic
attacks, though the Galaxy has changed its emphasis to defense.
</P>
<P>
   This game also will mark the potential of club soccer in the
Boston area. Though the Revolution have attracted crowds of about
17,000 per game, the largest Foxboro Stadium soccer attendances
have been for international matches. The largest crowd for a
stand-alone club match was 38,633 for Columbus's 1-0 victory over
the Revolution on Sept. 21, 1996, the final regular-season game of
the first MLS season
</P>
<P>
   ``The attendance should exceed expectations,'' O'Donovan said.
``If we had been in the playoffs and were competing to be in this
game, it would have made a huge difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are pleased, since this is a game being played in late
November, in which the local team wasn't near this thing in terms
of generating local excitement. What other sport, other than the
Super Bowl, could have drawn this well under these conditions, with
two teams which aren't from the area? It shows how much people want
soccer here and are willing to go after it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No stopping him
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was apparently little the MLS or the Revolution could have
done to prevent Joe-Max Moore's move to Everton FC last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I've dreamed about my whole life,'' Moore said
after stopping in Boston on the way to Marrakech to play for the US
national team in an exhibition Wednesday. ``People talk about Serie
A in Italy and the Spanish League, but for me it doesn't get any
better than the Premier League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of good memories of playing for the Revolution.
Everyone treated me fairly. But this move wasn't about money. I
didn't want to pass up on a chance to play in the Premier League.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is awaiting a work permit before the transfer is approved.
Moore said he fulfills the requirement of playing at least 75
percent of the US's international matches _ in fact, he has been
called up for 82 percent of the team's games, but was prevented
from playing in some games by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the English mentality is to work hard, and I've never
seen anyone work harder than me,'' Moore said. ``So I should fit
in. Everton's players are all at a very high level and the guys
work hard every day. The fans expect that from the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their best striker is Kevin Campbell, and I spent some time
with him and he's a great guy. I think I would fit in there right
now. They also have Francis Jeffers, who is injured but is expected
to be the next big player in England. They have quite a few players
at that position, but that's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore did not have a rewarding experience with the Revolution.
He arrived with the team in a midseason crisis in 1996 and
converted 11 goals in 14 games in nearly leading it to the
playoffs. The Revolution continued to exist on the edge of playoff
elimination the next three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everthing is in place for this to become a championship
franchise,'' Moore said of the Revolution. ``The owners are great,
so is management, and the fans are what I stayed for. But a lot of
things need to happen. Sunil (Gulati, managing director of Kraft
Soccer) knows how to work within the MLS to get players, and then
it will be up to the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to keep saying it, but we were always close to turning
the corner. It's hard to put a finger on what went wrong. I'm not
sure it was the style of play because we played a fairly good
style; we tried to play good soccer. It just didn't come together
at the right times.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too much fun
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Scholes will miss the England-Scotland match Wednesday at
Wembley after having been cautioned for excessive celebration after
his second goal in England's 2-0 win over the Scots Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Scholes, a Manchester United midfielder, certainly was justified
in commemorating the success. England is virtually assured of
qualifying for the European Championships next summer in Belgium
and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, more than 100 fans were arrested for what amounted to
excessive celebration before and after the match at Hampden Park in
Glasgow. No major injuries were reported, and only 10 supporters
were detained overnight, indicating that law enforcement confronted
the situation reasonably well.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland, though, must ignite its offense when it visits Turkey.
The Turks scored a late penalty kick to tie, 1-1, in Dublin. The
Irish strike force will be Tony Cascarino and David Connolly, since
Robbie Kane is suspended and Niall Quinn injured his neck in
pregame warmups.
</P>
<P>
   Ukraine also surrendered a late goal and had two players ejected
in a 2-1 loss to Slovenia. But with Milan's Andrei Shevchenko
leading the attack, Ukraine has a good chance to advance Wednesday
in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   In the final qualifier, Denmark must protect a five-goal
advantage at home against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Confusion reigns
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Brazil-Nike-Ronaldo connection continues to confound. Brazil
had a game scheduled against Spain in Vigo last weekend and planned
to send the Olympic team to Australia for a game Saturday and one
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To further confuse matters, coach Wanderley Luxemburgo decided
to join the Olympic team and sent Olympic assistant Candinho to
Vigo with the senior team. Ronaldo wanted to go to Australia, where
local promoters and Nike needed him for promotional purposes, and
where, at age 23, he seemed to fit in well with younger teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Inter protested that Ronaldo was being overworked,
and FIFA upheld the appeal by decreeing that Ronaldo was eligible
for only one game in Australia. Luxemburgo refused to compromise,
saying he wanted Ronaldo for either both games or none.
</P>
<P>
   Then, local hero Harry Kewell of Leeds United failed to appear,
and Manchester United goalkeeper Mark Bosnich was injured.
Promoters ended up giving away tickets to the match. Brazil won,
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No killjoy
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Romario, the best Brazilian goal-scorer of the decade, could be
available. Flamengo president Edmundo Santos Silva said Romario
would be dropped from the team for _ once again _ excessive
celebration. Romario and four teammates apparently went to a disco
in Caxias do Sul after a 3-1 loss to Juventude eliminated Flamengo
from playoff contention on the final day of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to go out at night,'' Romario said. ``I think
it is very normal that people go out to have fun. I like to go out
and I will always do so, wherever I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
