<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTER FINALLY CHECKS IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ After a slow start, things appear to be falling into
place for Anson Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Centering a checking line with Rob DiMaio and P.J. Axelsson, the
6-foot-1-inch, 185-pound Carter has regained a scoring touch that
abandoned him during an anemic eight-game stretch in which he
notched just one assist.
</P>
<P>
   He ended that drought with a goal in last Thursday's overtime
victory over the Maple Leafs and followed up with two goals and two
assists in Saturday's 5-2 win over the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Carter feels the turnaround is just a matter of playing smarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the key,'' he said, ``I was working hard. But now
I'm playing smarter and the bounces are going my way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't jumping on the loose pucks. I was working hard,
trying to get the puck back, but I was standing around, waiting to
see what Allie (Jason Allison) or Andy (Dave Andreychuk) were going
to do, so I was standing around, not playing the way I'm capable of
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting, hoping things would happen. When I'm playing
smart, I'm not waiting, I'm attacking the puck in all three zones
and reading the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting used to a new linemate (Andreychuk) also may have had an
effect on his performance early. ``I was trying to figure out what
Andy can do and can't do on the ice, and I'm sure he was doing the
same thing with myself and Allie,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has had no problem assimilating with DiMaio and Axelsson.
The trio has accounted for five goals and 14 points in the last 10
games, despite shadowing the opponent's best scoring line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense will come, but that's not our focus right now,''
he said. ``Now it's the day-in and day-out challenge to be prepared
and don't get embarrassed. You're playing against a team's top
players so the chance of getting embarrassed is there every single
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after his outing against the Rangers, Carter downplayed his
scoring. ``I was still trying to keep team goals in focus,'' he
said. ``My main job is to control the tempo and take away the
offense. After the game, you think about it, but during the game,
there's too much going on.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Carter has played center. He played
that position at Michigan State and for a while with the Capitals
before suffering a thumb injury that forced a move to right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns switched Carter to center at the suggestion of
assistant general manager Mike O'Connell. ``It's worked out fine,''
Burns said. ``He's got the speed, he's got the size, he's got some
determination in him to play against those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I disagree when anybody tells me anybody can check. It's a
tough role to play, you just don't put someone out there, you have
to work at checking, you have to know your game. You can be a fast
skater and it doesn't mean nothing. You have to know the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was surprised by his move to the checking and had a rude
awakening in the Bruins' 6-2 setback at Buffalo last Wednesday. ``I
definitely wanted to redeem myself,'' Carter said. ``Coach showed a
lot of faith in me, putting me out there against (Mats) Sundin. But
not one guy makes up that line, all three guys do, that's
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to step up and accept the challenge. When the coach
challenges you like that, you want to be able to raise your game to
another level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
