<HEADER>
A1357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS-ART     11-16 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS COOK UP A STUNNER, LEAVE PATRIOTS WITH UPSET TO STOMACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In a span of three hours, the Patriots went
from being potentially the first-place team in the AFC East to the
fourth-place team. Their fourth-quarter comeback fell one score
short in a 24-17 ``Monday Night Football'' loss to the rival New
York Jets as the Patriots once again failed to impress the nation's
football audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best team won tonight,'' said a dejected Drew Bledsoe
after Monday's game. ``There are reasons for it. We definitely had
opportunities. We were inside the 5-yard line twice and we came out
of it with 3 points. Can't do that. Can't turn the ball over three
times and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't run the ball effectively, didn't convert third downs
and they did. They had an excellent game plan. Al Groh and Bill
Belichick are the two best (defensive coaches) we face every year.
I've said it before: They're the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets forced Bledsoe into three interceptions and rode the
play of Ray Lucas, the former Patriot practice-squad receiver
making his second start at quarterback, to a 24-3 fourth-quarter
lead. Another former Patriot, Curtis Martin, ran for 149 yards on
31 carries in a splendid performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great to come in here and beat the coach that cut
me,'' said Lucas, who passed for 153 yards, completing 18 of 31
attempts, with two touchdowns and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots looked like a team that had had 15 days off and
couldn't quite recapture its passion _ until the fourth quarter,
when they put two scores on the board. But they were unable to
score on their final three possessions, with Bledsoe going 1 for 9
and their night ending when Tony Simmons dropped a pass on fourth
and 18 with a minute left when he would have had a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it too far behind him and he couldn't turn around and
make the play,'' said Bledsoe. ``There was never a time when I
thought we were going to lose the game. I had confidence all the
way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we leave here and have to go to Miami and Buffalo and the
Colts. We have a tough road ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are now 2-4 in Tuna Bowls. They fell into a 21-3
hole at halftime, and things didn't start much better in the third
quarter, as Bledsoe was intercepted twice in the first 6:08.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Marcus Coleman's second interception of the game, at
the Jet 12, was followed on the very next series by linebacker
Marvin Jones's first career pick, at the 15, just as Bledsoe was
driving the Patriots into the red zone.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who was given the nod as the fourth Jet signal caller of
the season after a miserable run by Rick Mirer, looked like a
seasoned quarterback. He put together a dream drive of 11:22 across
the third and fourth quarters, moving the Jets 62 yards on 19
plays, to set up John Hall's 26-yard field goal that gave New York
the three-touchdown advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots began closing the gap. Bledsoe's 13-yard screen
pass to Kevin Faulk with 10:07 remaining capped a 10-play, 58-yard
drive and made it 24-10. By now, the stadium was half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots pulled within a touchdown when Bledsoe connected on
a 31-yard pass play with Troy Brown, who faked Ray Mickens at the
15 and pranced into the end zone with 6:58 left. The drive lasted
1:12 and was aided by a fourth-down interference call on Aaron
Glenn against Shawn Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll.
``It took us a while to get adjusted to their defenses. I feared
what would happen after the bye is we wouldn't stay on the even
track we've been on. We're very disappointed we weren't able to do
that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited game with emotions running high, the Jets blitzed
Bledsoe incessantly, taking away his deep receivers and forcing the
Patriots to run, which they couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots caught a break late in the first quarter when a
Lucas third-and-8 pass intended for Wayne Chrebet tipped off his
fingers into the hands of Chris Carter, his third interception of
the season, at the New England 36.
</P>
<P>
   But after three plays netted minus-6 yards, Lee Johnson had to
punt into a swirling 30-mile-per-hour wind. His 28-yard kick left
the Jets at their 42.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who had been running the majority of the time, went to
the air with the wind at their backs. Lucas led an eight-play,
58-yard drive, connecting with Chrebet for 8 and 26 yards and
capping it with a 1-yard pass to an uncovered Keyshawn Johnson in
the corner of the end zone. Johnson's TD made up for a questionable
interference call on him two plays earlier for pushing off on Law
in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Faulk made his best play as a Patriot to
date, taking Hall's kickoff 3 yards deep in the end zone, breaking
a tackle at the 30, and rambling 95 yards to the Jets' 8, where he
was caught by Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he could have scored,'' said Carroll. ``We couldn't get
it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Allen (14 carries, 36 yards) ran the ball to the 5 on
first down, then lost a yard on second down. A completion to Allen
got the ball to the 1, but on fourth down, the Patriots tried to
make a statement instead of taking the sure 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   Allen was stuffed by Roman Phifer and Anthony Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   It was a momentum-turner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge disappointment,'' said Carroll. ``We decided
to go for the touchdown rather than settle for the 3, and it didn't
work there.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Jets' subsequent possession, a 29-yard pass to Chrebet
was overturned on replay. Brown, returning to his punt-return role,
took Tom Tupa's kick back to the Jets' 49. From there, Bledsoe
found Terry Glenn at the 40, and Glenn made a move to the outside
and ran all the way to the 23. Bledsoe then hit Ben Coates for 7
yards, Allen ran for 2, and Jason Ferguson leaped offside on a
third and 1, giving New England first and goal at the 9.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots were unable to get it any closer than the 4.
Bledsoe's third-down attempt hit Phifer's backside as he had Coates
covered like a blanket. The Patriots settled for a 22-yard Adam
Vinatieri field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets made it an extra-embarrassing first half for the
Patriots after taking over at their 42. Lucas hit Johnson on a
pretty 19-yard sideline play, and after a 6-yard loss on a pass to
Martin, Lucas hit Chrebet for 11 yards to the 36. Martin took a
handoff, started up the middle, then cut to the right and was gone,
36 yards for the score with 6:09 remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 14-3, the Patriots were backed up to their 15 after a
holding call on Chris Floyd on the kickoff. Bledsoe tried to get it
back in one throw, had Jefferson deep down the field, but he was
throwing against the wind and the ball was knocked down enough for
Coleman to intercept it and run it back to the Patriots' 36.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, showing great poise, engineered a quick scoring drive,
finishing it by throwing 11 yards to tight end Fred Baxter in front
of Lawyer Milloy, making it 21-3 20 seconds before halftime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
