u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-     11-16 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ESPECIALLY HUMBLING PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Maybe that 2-point win in September wasn't
quite the exorcism Patriots fans thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night Bill Parcells waddled into Foxboro Stadium with a
team whose hopes long ago had been crushed and which was playing
football without a real quarterback. Waiting for them was a team
that believed it was the best in football. Waiting for them were
Pete Carroll and his New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Result? Jets 24, Patriots mystified.
</P>
<P>
   How could the 2-6 Jets come into Carroll's house and steal his
furniture from right in front of his nose with 53 of his best
employees surrounding him? How could those 53 men come off a bye
week and say goodbye to the top of the AFC East by losing to a team
that was life and death with the Arizona Cardinals?
</P>
<P>
   How do they get beat by a quarterback they didn't want, making
only the second start of his career?
</P>
<P>
   How? Because there's nothing special about them.
</P>
<P>
   How do they get run over by a running back they didn't want, a
running back they'd whispered was damaged goods three years (and
approaching three straight 1,000-yard seasons) ago?
</P>
<P>
   How? Because there's nothing special about them.
</P>
<P>
   How do they allow an offense averaging barely 14 points a game
not only to smoke them but to cap the barbecue with a 19-play,
62-yard drive in the second half that lasts 11 minutes 23 seconds?
</P>
<P>
   How? Because there's nothing special about them.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Patriots get back on the field Sunday in Miami,
Carroll and his boss, owner Bob Kraft, will have become tired of
hearing the word ``how.''
</P>
<P>
   That there is nothing special about Carroll and his Patriots is
a fact but not a condemnation. It is simply something they must
recognize and understand, because in this era of NFL mediocrity,
they still can reach the playoffs if they can just bring themselves
to see what they are and come out and play with a feverish fear of
defeat every time.
</P>
<P>
   They did not do that Monday night, and so they got their heads
handed to them by an inferior team that came in with a superior
game plan and the will to execute it. They were beaten as much by
their glowing self-image as they were by the Jets . . . although
the Jets did a pretty good job of it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We show the mark of a good team when we're down,'' said
cornerback Ty Law. ``We show the energy to come back. But we need
to do that from the first whistle. We know we can play at crunch
time but when there's no pressure we don't play well. That's been
consistent here for several years. I'm awed by it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Awed and mystified.
</P>
<P>
   The loss technically dropped the Patriots into fourth place in
the AFC East, but so competitive is the division that they are only
a game behind Miami and Indianapolis and a half-game behind the
Bills. Their position in the standings is of little import at the
moment, because they play all three teams in the next four weeks
and thus could right their ship well before Christmas if they can
just make themselves understand one thing.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing special about them.
</P>
<P>
   To do that they cannot go into those games the way they went
into this one. They cannot go in sure of their dominance, because
as Law pointed out and this team has proven time and time again
that the instant it starts thinking it's better than it really is,
it plays worse than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   These Patriots are a team that not only cannot stand success, it
cannot stand even the thought of success. For whatever reason,
Pete's Patriots remain unable to handle prosperity and need to
remind themselves daily of one thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing special about us, there's nothing special
about us.'' They need to keep saying it the way Dorothy kept saying
``There's no place like home'' in ``The Wizard of Oz'' until she
finally got home.
</P>
<P>
   If that becomes their mantra for the next month, they might well
end it atop the AFC East despite such a dismal performance because
there's nothing special about anybody else, either.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame in this. The NFL has become a league of teams
about whom there is nothing special, and ultimately two of them
have to reach the Super Bowl. One of them still could be the
Patriots if they simply look at this defeat for what it is.
</P>
<P>
   It was a reminder of what a few people have been trying to tell
them for a couple of years now: They're just another team, except
on the days when they decide to fight for their lives. Then they
are more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of slogans like ``We're No. 1'' posted on the locker
room walls, this team needs to put up one that says ``We'd like to
be No. 1 but there's nothing special about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing a song such as ``We Are the Champions'' on
the PA system, they need to play to ``I'm a Loser and I'm not what
I appear to be.''
</P>
<P>
   If they can do that often enough, the Patriots can survive this
unseemly defeat to Parcells's Jets.
</P>
<P>
   But if they think they got hit by a lucky punch, they're wrong.
Dead wrong, and their playoff hopes will be just as dead if they
don't realize that they got hit by a team not that different from
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A team that had nothing special about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
