<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLICATED DIVISION PROBLEM GETS NO EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ As the eternally hapless Chester A. Riley
used to say, ``What a revoltin' development this is!''
</P>
<P>
   Bad? No, this wasn't bad. This was execrable. And why? Bye
Week-itis? Brain lock? The fix perhaps being in? (Just kidding.)
Inexplicable cosmic forces? Or was it that the 2-6 Jets were never
really all that bad and the 6-2 Patriots were never really all that
good?
</P>
<P>
   There is no definitive answer. None. In the weeks to come, we
will all know whether or not this embarrassing 24-17 loss to the
Jets was a bizarre aberration or the beginning of the end. What we
do know is that this turn of events (a) brought a smile to the
faces of Messrs. Jimmy Johnson, Wade Phillips, and Jim Mora and (b)
enabled the hard-luck Jets to salvage a little self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   The only consolation for the Patriots is this: If the Jets
really are as good as they looked in Periods 2 and 3 of this game,
they might be able to do unto others on the schedule as they did to
the stunned Patriots at Foxboro Stadium. Based on what they did
Monday night, the Jets have the capability of being a major problem
for the Dolphins, Bills, and Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the whole thing could have been another kind of
aberration. Is Ray Lucas really a capable NFL quarterback? Maybe,
maybe not. But he was good enough to win a big game. The unarguable
reality is that he outplayed Drew Bledsoe in his own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers weren't dazzling. He's not going to be AFC Offensive
Player of the Week after completing 18 of 31 passes for 153 yards.
He had two touchdown passes and he had two interceptions. There was
good and there was bad. But under the circumstances it was a
reasonably heroic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Come on, consider the circumstances. Who is Drew Bledsoe? A Pro
Bowl quarterback enjoying his finest pro season, that's who. And
who is Ray Lucas? A utilityman getting his first NFL win against a
team, and coach, that had deemed him superfluous two years ago. In
the '30s and '40s, they used to make a lot of movies on far
flimsier premises than this.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a nice job,'' said Tom Tupa, the ex-Patriot who punted
seven times for a 45.6-yard average, and who still may be the best
healthy quarterback on the Jets. ``He went out and made plays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence in the huddle was what you'd expect,'' saluted
wide receiver Wayne Chrebet, who caught seven of Lucas's passes,
good for 70 yards. ``He did a tremendous job for us. I know that he
doesn't want to be a backup quarterback. He wants to lead a team.
Tonight he put that pressure on himself, and he came through. It
was a huge win for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The game got away from the Patriots in the second quarter, when
the Jets scored three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, it seemed like we had the ball the whole
time,'' observed Tupa.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried the same approach that worked many long weeks
ago against the Colts. That is to say, they fell way behind (28-7
on that particular occasion) before compressing all their goodness
into what was an extended two-minute drill. It looked as if the
madcap offensive strategy might work again when they scored twice
in the fourth quarter after falling behind by a 24-3 score. And
when Lawyer Milloy came up with a tipped interception with 5:58
remaining, they were in excellent shape with a first down at the
Jets 27.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where it ended. Bledsoe, in the midst of a Mike
Taliaferro game (15 for 36, 170 yards), threw incompletions to
Shawn Jefferson, Vincent Brisby, Kevin Faulk, and Jefferson again.
They would never again be in a position to accomplish anything on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Shed not a tear for the home team. How can you excuse a supposed
contender that comes out so pathetically flat in the first game
following a bye? How can you excuse a team that has two separate
first-and-goals from the 5 and comes away with 3 points? You can't.
From a Patriots standpoint, this game was a thorough abomination
that raises serious questions about their overall status. Once
again, those early-season squeakers, including the gift against the
Jets in the Meadowlands, look like nothing less than early
Christmas presents from the Grid God.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets paid proper lip service to the Patriots. After all,
they've got to talk up a win like this. It's only human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they took us for granted or not,'' mused
Chrebet. ``They're a good team, but maybe we were a little more
prepared to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets leave here aroused. This is a team that had specialized
in fourth-quarter giveaways. Now it is a team that thinks it has
found a cure. They are looking at this game as proof that it surely
ain't over until it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all believe,'' declared Curtis Martin, whose 149 yards on
31 carries included a 36-yard cutback touchdown run in the second
quarter. ``We know this has happened before. Bill (Parcells) has
coached a team that was 2-6 or 3-6 and that wound up making the
playoffs. What this does for us is give us momentum, momentum to
turn the season around.''
</P>
<P>
   Great. Let a new, aggressive fox loose in the AFC East henhouse,
as if things weren't crazy enough in football's toughest division.
</P>
<P>
   Having the Jets back in the mix is bad for everyone else, and
losing this particular game is truly bad, bad, bad for the Patriots
and Pete Carroll. He is now 2-4 in Tuna Bowls. Those inclined to
question him will question him. With two weeks to get ready, his
team looked very unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it was a revoltin' development, all right. Now the Patriots
head to Miami, where Jimmy Johnson has already declared war on
mankind. And Chester A. Riley was just a TV character. The Dolphins
are very real.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
