<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF SHORT MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; You know all is right with the world when you see that Nick
Leeson has hit the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that fine young chap Nick? He is the fella who worked
in the Singapore office of the distinguished British bank Barings.
He was the futures trader who in 1995 bet wrong on the direction of
Japanese stocks and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Few people have bet as wrong as Nick did. Young Nick, just 26
years old at the time, ran up a debt of $1.4 billion, which in the
parlance of the casino is a bit more than betting one's shirt, or
the farm, or the ranch, or one's whiskers _ it's even a bit more
than betting one's sweet behind.
</P>
<P>
   In his roll of the dice, Nick went as far as one could go: he
bet the bank and when the numbers went against him, this fine young
chap put an end to Barings, which had been in business for 233
years.
</P>
<P>
   Nick, the working-class boy with the high school education,
wasn't just a bad arbitrageur. He also was clumsy at covering his
tracks. Though he had the doughy white face of an innocent, he
pulled a few fast ones and then, like a boy, he ran when the
authorities found out.
</P>
<P>
   He was captured in Frankfurt and imprisoned for 4 1/2 years in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was released and returned to London in July of
this year, he'd already sold his story to book publishers and the
newspapers. He'd nearly exhausted his options for rebuilding his
life. After all, he isn't expected to jump back into the financial
casino. Due to his notorious skills, he won't likely be permitted a
license to trade on the London International Financial Futures
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   So what in the world could the fine young chap do?
</P>
<P>
   Why, hit the lecture circuit, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At first I couldn't imagine why 100 Dutch businessmen, brokers
and bankers would pay $300 each to hear young Nick speak in
Amsterdam. More astonishing was why the conference organizers would
pay the bloke $100,000 to stand up and perform.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit me. This was no run-of-the-mill conference. This was
the Barnum and Bailey of the business big top. And Nick, sweet
Nick, was the circus freak. Step right up, folks, and see the
astounding, the marvelous, the scary, the terrible Boy Scoundrel!
</P>
<P>
   But alas, I was wrong. It was a genuine business conference. I
should never have been surprised that Nick was the honored guest.
Today, sins are committed and soon forgotten. A major life
insurance company agrees to pay a billion dollars to settle claims
it tricked policy holders. Seven of the world's largest drug
companies promise to hand over a billion dollars to resolve charges
they fixed vitamin prices for years. We quickly forget, and
business goes on.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not surprising that Nick has a series of speaking
engagements booked in coming months. Sweet-faced Nick also will be
appearing in ads to offer his stamp of approval on selected
products.
</P>
<P>
   He even has a media adviser who boasts of his client to the Wall
Street Journal: This man is inundated with offers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it seems pretty clear that all is right with the world now
that Nick Leeson has hit the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   He committed his sin, and we've quickly forgotten. The time has
come for him to rebuild his shattered life.
</P>
<P>
   But how? He has no more books to peddle and no job. All that
this fine young chap has left is his good name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
