<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDER THAN IT LOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; First Jaguar. Now Cambridge University?
</P>
<P>
   When the University of Cambridge and the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology last week announced plans to form a joint institute,
it sounded for all the world like one of those ``dynamic and
challenging partnerships'' that begin with a little shared research
and development and ends in the acquisition of one famous brand by
another.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible, of course, in the case of the two great
universities.
</P>
<P>
   But the close proximity to the deal of Alex Trotman, former
chief executive of Ford Motor Co., was an indication of just how
unusual was the agreement to exchange students and faculty (fifty
juniors a year, for example), perform integrated research, and
otherwise seek to build competitiveness in Britain on the American
model.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman, a Scot and Cambridge grad, worked half his life in the
United Kingdom and the other half in the United States. He was one
of the facilitators of the deal by which Detroit's automotive giant
in 1989 bought Jaguar, England's best car maker, for $2.5 billion.
He was one of the powers behind the MIT-Cambridge deal, and he
hailed its potential ``social and economic benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   When the government of Tony Blair swept into office in 1997, it
was armed with a slogan _ Cool Britannia _ that signaled its
determination to shake up traditional ways. As the first Labor
government in a generation, it had an unusual mandate to foster a
new entrepreneurial culture among the British.
</P>
<P>
   It has proved harder than it looks. Certain British industries
continue to dominate world markets easily enough: news, finance,
fashion, and design. But though UK companiies have promising
positions in high-tech industries from pharmaceuticals to the
Internet, new business formation and productivity gains haven't
been sufficiently forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the Blair government's determination to do something to
shake British attitudes to their roots. After Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown visited MIT in early 1998, he set out to
promote a significant intervention in British higher education by
MIT's senior staff.
</P>
<P>
   Brown first proposed hooking up MIT with a consortium of
schools, including Bristol University and the London Business
School. MIT held out for an affiliation with Cambridge University
alone _ or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge authorities with backgrounds in the sciences were
happy to explore a joint venture, vice chancellor Sir Alec Broers
in particular. Broers, a computer scientist who for a time was an
IBM senior fellow, has had a string of notable successes in
creating university partnerships at Cambridge _ a Microsoft
software think tank chief among them.
</P>
<P>
   But the 800-year-old university, nestled in the countryside an
hour northeast of London by train, has yet to perfect a reputation
as the central place for European research and development.
Although it was the first university in Europe to establish a
``science park'' to encourage business formation, nothing like the
profusion of new businesses characteristic of Massachusetts has
followed, much less the explosion that is Silicon Valley, and talk
of ``the Cambridge Phenomenon'' is often overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of ``missing links'' in British business culture is not
difficult to find. Indeed, that its engineers are treated as
second- and third-class citizens behind its scientists has been
noted regularly by writers on development for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   Biology professor Ricard Hynes, who has studied at both
Cambridge and MIT, described the difference this way in an MIT news
release: ``MIT is go-go-go, run-run-run. MIT students like constant
testing. In Cambridge they tend to think around and find the one
way . . . In Cambridge, there is basically one exam every three
years _ you could explore a subject. Also, you had a choice on your
exams.''
</P>
<P>
   When the pact was announced last week in London, you could all
but hear the English molars grinding. The Blair government agreed
to put up 80 percent of the $135 million that would be required for
the first five years; British industry agreed to raise the rest.
The money for the most part would flow to Cambridge, Mass., in
order that the Yanks would serve as ``torchbearers to UK's
enterprise future.'' A few Cambridge dons were furious at the
government, and one promised a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work? Of course it will. Fifty undergraduates at a time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
