<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POKEMON' SHOVES ASIDE LEADING MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How is it that Bruce, Brad, Nicolas, and Harrison have gotten
their $20 million butts so thoroughly kicked by Pikachu, Charizard,
Psyduck, and Togepy?
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is supposed to be the serious season, the
season of Streep and Scorsese when so-called ``adult films''
replace the plot-deprived, big-bang movies of summer. This is
supposed be that heady time when moviegoers turn their fickle heads
toward the kinds of ambitious, thought-provoking films whose names
are expected to be called and called again come Oscar nomination
time.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the biggest film thus far this fall a silly imported
Japanese cartoon aimed at kids?
</P>
<P>
   In less than a week, ``Pokemon: The First Movie,'' has earned
more than $52 million, $32 million this past weekend. It's a
wonderful, though not entirely unexpected, box-office boost, but
make no mistake this has been the autumn of Hollywood's discontent.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than halfway through the fall movie season, and
you can practically see the sweat stains on those well-cut
Hollywood suits. At least a half-dozen heavily hyped releases have
stiffed at the box office in recent weeks. And these are films
starring such box office golden boys as Harrison Ford (``Random
Hearts''), Nicolas Cage (``Bringing Out the Dead,'' directed by
Martin Scorsese), Bruce Willis (``The Story of Us,'' also with
Michelle Pfeiffer), Brad Pitt (``Fight Club,'' costarring Edward
Norton), and Robin Williams (``Jakob the Liar''). Guess all those
positive blurbs from Ron Brewington of American Urban Radio
Networks, and WBAI's Paul Wunder _ those ubiquitous quote machines
who talk in exclamation points and who never saw a big studio
release they didn't like _ have been for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Also disappearing fast is ``Music of the Heart,'' starring Meryl
Streep. So what's the deal? Well, except for ``Fight Club,'' which
was just too gleefully nihilistic for many tastes, none of these
films were very good. (``Music of the Heart'' is OK, but it's also
relentlessly sappy.) Perhaps audiences are finally making it clear
that they need compelling stories, not just lots of star-wattage on
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are still lots of buzzy big releases with big
stars on the horizon, including Jim Carrey as the late, great
comedian Andy Kaufman in ``Man on the Moon,'' Denzel Washington as
wrongly imprisoned boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter in ``The
Hurricane,'' and Tom Hanks in an adaptation of Stephen King's ``The
Green Mile.'' But, if the first half of the season is any
indication, Hollywood may be in for a long, cold winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has it that Aussie actor Russell Crowe, so good as Big
Tobacco whistleblower Jeffrey Wigand in ``The Insider'' (and even
better in ``L.A. Confidential'') is being positioned as the next
Mel Gibson. Geez, let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe Fiona Apple can sometimes be a bit of a ninny. Her
minidiatribe at the MTV Video Music Awards a few years back is
near-legendary, and the 90-word title of her new CD, is earning
more than a few exasperated rolls of the eyes. But let no one deny
what a stunning talent she is _ and she's only 22. Her CD, ``When
the Pawn. . .'' is one of the best releases of the year. I, for
one, don't care if she lapses into occasional petulant bratspeak,
so long as she keeps making music this challenging and stirring.
</P>
<P>
   So do you think network execs have tried contacting Charles Van
Doren _ the 1950s quiz show scandal poster boy _ to host one of
these new primetime game shows?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as part of VH1's ``Divas Week,'' the cable network
aired episodes of Cher's 1970s solo variety show. To wit, there was
Cher performing a medley of Stevie Wonder songs with the Osmonds.
And just when it seemed things couldn't get any weirder, there was
Cher singing a Beatles medley with Tina Turner and Kate Smith _
yes, that's ``God Bless America'' Kate Smith. Man, they just don't
make TV like that anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
