<HEADLINE>
QUIET KOPIN'S TECHNOLOGY SET TO MAKE NOISE AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kopin Corp. is a small technology company with no profits and a
stock that has tripled in price since June.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet company, right? Wrong. Internet companies are born
hot. Kopin, of Taunton, Mass., has been plugging away for 15 years,
mostly in obscurity. It has taken that long for the company's
scientists to find real world applications for their Buck Rogers
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our technology was ahead of the market,'' says John
Fan, Kopin's patient founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Fan and a handful of others left MIT's Lincoln Laboratories in
1984 to start Kopin. Their goal was to make semiconductors using a
technique with parallels to genetic engineering. Like their
counterparts in biotechnology, they found the task more difficult
than they imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The company went public in 1992 and didn't come out with its
first product until 1995; its second product debuted in 1997. Kopin
has never had a profitable year. But that may be about to change.
The small group of analysts who follow Kopin's fortunes predict the
company will mark the new millennium with its first-ever profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is real demand for what they make now,'' says Joel Pitt,
an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``We are not talking
about something that is still around the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Kopin's main product is _ take a deep breath _ a heterojunction
bipolar transistor wafer. It is called HBT for short. Kopin's
customers use the wafers in the production of semiconductors that,
in turn, are used in cellular telephones. The net result, says Fan,
are phones that have clearer signals.
</P>
<P>
   The cellular business is hotter than hot. Qualcomm, a California
wireless company and a leader in the field, has seen its stock
appreciate 1,400 percent this year. Other companies in the same
business, including some of Kopin's customers, are also basking in
the market's warm glow.
</P>
<P>
   Kopin's HBT business is heating up too. SunTrust Equitable
Securities estimates that wafer sales will reach $28 million this
year and $50 million next. The business is already profitable, say
analysts, and Kopin is in the process of quadrupling its capacity
to make wafers.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the real Buck Rogers business: cyber displays,
miniature high-resolution displays for consumer electronics. Kopin
makes a display with a 1/4-inch diagonal screen. We're talking
about a display smaller than the fingernail on your pinkie.
</P>
<P>
   Kopin has been teasing and disappointing investors for years
with prospects for this business. The goal, or what analyst J. D.
Abouchar of Preferred Capital Markets calls the ``holy grail,'' has
always been a cellular phone with a tiny display that will let the
user see all sorts of information.
</P>
<P>
   The grail is still out of reach, says Abouchar, but in the
meantime Kopin has found other markets for its products. Kopin
displays are currently being used as viewfinders on camcorders and
viewfinders on brand new digital cameras. Down the road, the
cellular phone market may yet develop. Even without it, analysts
expect good growth for Kopin's displays and possibly even profits
by later next year.
</P>
<P>
   If we were really smart market columnists, we would have told
you about Kopin in the spring. The stock has gone from 13 1/16 in
late March to 60 3/4 Monday. But hey, what do you expect for your
50 cents?
</P>
<P>
   The question to be asked now is: Can Kopin actually deliver the
results to justify its market value of close to $900 million? It is
one thing to have potential. It is quite another to win contracts,
build products, and make the trains run on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is ever certain,'' says William Becklean of SunTrust,
who nonetheless recommended Kopin in a recent report that put a
target price on the stock of 69.
</P>
<P>
   John Fan concedes the company is facing new challenges, but he
says Kopin is ready. Fan certainly must be. At 55 he has had a
chance to watch entrepreneurs half his age make overnight fortunes.
After 15 years, Fan's stake in Kopin is worth only $15 million,
pocket change by today's high-tech standards.
</P>
<P>
   Fan laughs when asked how he feels about the Internet
multimillionaires. ``I have an Asian background,'' he says. ``We
never compare people. I am happy for those companies that are very
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for Kopin, ``In general, we are happy where we are now,''
says Fan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
