<HEADLINE>
IN N.E., YOU DON'T LET THE WEATHER FOOL YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 15 years, New England ski areas make the point in winters
like the last one: Guaranteed skiing is real.
</P>
<P>
   On those slushy, foggy Fridays that seemed to doom so many
weekends last season, most fair-minded skiers who did make the trek
were forced to admit that almost every weekend the skiing was
pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   A vague term, to be sure. To some, the first scrape of steel
edge on hardpack constitutes terrible conditions. Or, regardless of
the surface, if it rains, snows, or even in flat light, some skiers
will complain that the skiing was not worth the ticket price.
</P>
<P>
   But again, those who make the extra push to get out onto the
snow throughout a New England winter will recognize that the skiing
is almost always better than bad weather leads them to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Our smattering review of New England resorts this year starts in
Vermont with the biggie in the east, Killington. To understand the
scale of this American Ski Company holding in Sherburn
(800-245-7669), imagine 300 snowmaking guns. That's how many
Killington bought this year just to beef up the system.
</P>
<P>
   If you hate crowds, the big K is not for you on weekends, though
weekdays, especially in January, skiers and boarders have the run
of the entire multi-peak, 200-trail area. Killington has by far the
most complete mix of offerings _ from cruisy, white-paved
boulevards, to VW-size moguls, steep and deep, off-piste glade
skiing without equal _ and does each extreme well.
</P>
<P>
   The apres-ski life is the biggest and most raucous it gets this
side of Aspen, as the access road fairly vibrates with rhythm into
the long winter nights. New this year is a much-needed enlarged
base lodge at the original base area. An easy drive from Boston _
Interstate 93 to Interstate 89 at Bow; at White River Junction take
Route 4 west to Shelburn.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Stratton Mountain (802-297-2200) in southern Vermont
will be pleased to find a new lift access to the summit, one of the
major drawbacks to skier flow at this area. Both of the old slow
lifts _ Grizzly and North American _ are gone, replaced by a
high-speed six-pack that rounds out duty with the gondola.
</P>
<P>
   Also new for this year at Stratton is a beefed-up snowmaking
system, also needed, and part of the area's long-range plan to
bring total coverage to the entire mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by ASC rival, Intrawest, Stratton's niche is high-comfort
resort living with groomed, cruisy skiing, spiced up by forays into
the off-piste terrain. In the main, Stratton is for skiers who like
their runs smooth, fast, and without surprises. It's fast
ego-building skiing, just the kind you want someone to catch on a
videocam. In very cold weather, one of Stratton's best features is
the Sunbowl which, like its name, is a warm pocket out of the
prevailing winter wind. One hint: Skiers wishing to avoid crowds,
drive through town and pick up the road to Sunbowl on the right.
This is a good bypass. Dining is a good range, soup'n'pizza to
gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between the two giants is Okemo in Ludlow. Well noted
for its grooming and buffed surfaces, Okemo is a true intermediate
mountain with endless cruising runs, some of them steep enough to
get up to gliding speeds and long enough to give skiers a feeling
of having skied a downhill race. While some attempts have been made
to spice up the terrain offerings with relative steeps like Double
Diamond and Outrage, these are tough in name only; at bottom, Okemo
is comfortable for what it does and does better than most. This is
low-stress skiing, with a way down from every lift for every skier.
</P>
<P>
   As an accent to this skiing and boarding comfort zone one feels
at Okemo is the fact that the area has enough slopeside condo
housing to make ski-in ski-out possible for almost every visitor.
Downtown Ludlow is still a piece of lovely, authentic Vermont. The
restaurants and apres-ski establishments _ many appropriate for
underage kids _ give the village an upscale feel of Woodstock and
Stowe. Scenery around the Black River is wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying on the theme of easy, low-stress skiing in a very
comfortable environment, Bretton Woods still captures the niche as
well as any area in New Hampshire. Located just above Franconia
Notch in the White Mountains, this area is making some big-time
moves.
</P>
<P>
   First, the completion of renovations to the famed Mount
Washington Hotel _ across the road from the ski area _ adds a
sudden infusion of big-market possibilities to what was always a
genial skiing backwater.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the hotel winterization comes the first expansion to
the alpine ski area with the addition of West Mountain, which
brings the area to more than 330 skiable acres. The new terrain is
gladed and designed to give skiers somewhat steeper terrain than
one is used to at the area. This is just the beginning of an
expansion aimed at transforming Bretton Woods into the major
leagues of New Hampshire resorts. More is coming on the alpine
side, and the nordic mix _ Bretton Woods being a premier area in
New England _ makes this a future destination.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bretton Woods' proximity to Cannon and even Loon
offer alternatives to people skiing the region for several days.
Transferable and packaged ticketing is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Though years of buffing out the trail system may have taken much
of the snarl out of Wildcat in Gorham _ Pinkham Notch _ this
4,000-foot peak that looks across to Tuckerman Ravine on Mount
Washington, gives advanced skiers everything they want in a full
day of skiing.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-foot vertical is easily accessible by intermediate
skiers. Many of the trails have an old New England feel of narrow
switchbackers down a steep mountain side. Others take the fall line
more directly and swiftly. And Lift Lion has moguls that will take
the tuck out of the best bumpster on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcat has improved its lift capacity with a detachable quad,
has beefed up snowmaking some, and still maintains one of the more
competitive pricing structures in the region (800-255-6439).
</P>
<P>
   A short drive outside hopping North Conway lies Attitash/Bear
Peak. In a more quiet way than most of ASC holdings, this area has
also transformed itself over the years, like so many Les Otten
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wildcat, the area still has plenty of terrain steeped in
the Olde New England feel _ narrow twisters through the woods, fun
to make turns on. But with the addition several years ago of Bear
Peak, the area added a whole new feel. Like flagship Sunday River
with its ever-horizontal expansion, Bear Peak did not add vertical,
but gives Attitash a wide-open cruisy feel of a more modern area.
Though 300 feet less vertical than Attitash, Bear Peak is less
chopped up, with much longer, undulating runs.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity to North Conway says it all about the dining and
apres-ski possibilities, but they can start closer to where you
kick off your boots _ at Margueritaville just down the road.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, the two great rivals, now corporate bedfellows _
Sugarloaf and Sunday River _ (though well off the beaten path of
the New York skiers who give Vermont areas their reputations in
skier feedback magazine columns) constitute the best skiing in the
East. Sunday River consistently makes and grooms snow well enough
for early season openings, and has never forgotten its mission of
getting the product down on the hill.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular ski areas in New England, with a decided
Boston base, what Sunday River lacks in big boney vertical terrain,
it makes up for in horizontal expansion and tremendous terrain
variety. The eight peaks contain 126 trails and 654 acres, and it
can take half a day to ski (and ride lifts) getting from Jordan
Bowl at one end to Barker at the other.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday River has excellent slopeside housing options, improving
dining and apres-ski amenities, but not on a scale with some of the
well-established destination resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Further northwest is just such a resort in Sugarloaf. With a
2,800-foot vertical with more than 1,400 skiable acres and the only
above-treeline skiing in the East, Sugarloaf wins a prize in the
largest/highest/longest competition.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sugarloaf, now with much improved snowmaking and its
high-speed quad, new trail additions, and this year a 1,000-foot
lift-served tubing park _ has answered many of its old critics.
Thanks to an infusion of ASC development money, the Loaf simply
improves yearly as a destination resort _ as it had to do since
it's so far from anything else.
</P>
<P>
   The expert terrain is nonpareil in New England, the cruising is
wondrous, leaving skiers to choose either skiing the upper half or
top-to-bottom runs like Tote Road than push three miles of rolling,
undulating terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Night life is spread around a number of good bars and
restaurants, ranging from spaghetti-benders like Hugs to true
four-star gourmet in One Stanley Avenue. For more info call
800-843-5623.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
