u t BC-TRAVEL-SKI-FASHION-BO     11-16 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-FASHION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIWEAR: HIGH-TECH YET NOSTALGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE HATFIELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While ski clothes continue to move toward the millennium by
growing ever more technical, warmer, dryer, and cozier, they're
beginning to look back toward the good old things of the past as
well, embracing touches that were part of skiwear years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Parkas and pants, for example, this ski season will employ all
the bells and whistles of high-tech fabrics, becoming stronger and
tougher and withstanding more snow and sleet and wind than ever.
Obermeyer, out of Aspen, is making pants and shells and jackets in
a 3,000-miller laminate fabric that breathes so well that its
manufacturers discovered that to do it in a parka weight, which has
more insulation than a jacket, would be useless. A parka was too
warm, and too insulated, they found. Employees from the company who
tried such parkas out last January came back in, saying they were
too warm to ski.
</P>
<P>
   The best-selling men's ski parka this season at St. Moritz
Sports in Wellesley is the ``Alaska,'' made by Killy. It is a
high-end technical line with numerous panels, and the more panels a
jacket has, the better it fits. The parka, in a micro fabric in
black, silver, and white, fits like a glove and it is, of course,
waterproof and windproof and costs $598 as the top of the Killy
line. A similar Killy jacket for men sold out by the beginning of
December last year at St. Moritz. The store had ordered 30 of them.
The Alaska is the jacket that Paul Turner, clothing manager of the
store, has chosen as his ski parka for the season, which speaks
well for its success. Even the Gore-Tex in the Alaska is softer and
more supple than untreated Gore-Tex in its native state, which is
thin and crispy.
</P>
<P>
   A word to the wise concerning Gore-Tex, by the way. Now that
skiers know enough to ask for it by name, they don't need to,
because the material is now being made by any number of
manufacturers under different names. The problem is, if you ask for
it by name, you might pay as much as $100 more because of that
name, while most skiwear now has identical fabric inside. But
because other manufacturers are not allowed to use the name, they
don't charge as much. Parkas by Marmot, for example, have a
material with Gore-Tex-like qualities, but at $289 and $399, the
jackets are much less expensive than the Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska is a three-quarter-length jacket that cinches at the
waist and fits taller, thinner men better than the ``Eisenhower
cut'' Killy jacket, which is cut wider in the shoulders, is
slightly shorter, and is a better choice for the shorter, stockier
man.
</P>
<P>
   The B-line of Killy jackets is as good technologically, but at
$528 they do not have quite as much detailing. The collar that is
leather in the Alaska, for example, is made of fabric in the B-line
jackets. All of these jackets, however, have a back pleat that
makes it more comfortable for the active man who moves his
shoulders as he skis.
</P>
<P>
   Single-color parkas in navy or red are more suitable for the
35-year-old-plus conservative man who doesn't want his jacket to
scream ``skier.'' These come in the $450 and $448 range. Newer
colors from Obermeyer include bright pistachio green, mango yellow,
Dijon mustard, and columbine blue.
</P>
<P>
   Spyder, the company sponsoring the US Ski Team this year, is
known for its distinctive spider web logo on its ski clothing. The
men's Spyder jacket, with a two-tone spider web pattern on one
corner, is known as a very rugged jacket, and at $320 is selling
very well this year. Spyder also makes ``windstopper'' fleece
sweaters with snowflake patterns, consisting of an acrylic and wool
body lined with windproof material, and at $249 can be used in lieu
of a ski shell, weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Spyder has had great success with its spider-logo ski clothing
in women's and children's versions as well. You can find hats in
both baseball and wool skullcap style, and many parkas feature a
tiny spider encased in a hologram running across the back of the
jacket. A children's unisex item that is flying out of the stores
already is the white cotton turtleneck shirt with zip front and a
huge red and black spider web across the front. At $35, 30 of these
were sold in four days at St. Moritz Sports. Another popular
children's line is the Back Hill line of Burton Snowboards, with a
stinging hornet logo. Popular colors are lime and navy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular women's Killy items is the black short
jacket with zip-off sleeves that can turn it into a vest. At $438,
Turner notes that ``I never hear a bad thing about it once it has
been sold.'' There's also a new four-way stretch pant for women
with Gore-Tex that is windproof and waterproof and, at $245, ``a
very warm pant,'' according to the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Helly Hansen's skiwear comes from a heritage of sailing, so that
it is not only windproof and waterproof but practically
indestructible. Designed in Europe, the women's jackets are ahead
of the fashion trends and are tending more to soft pastels this
year, including a beautiful baby aqua color. There's a white ski
pant, which is, as is everything else in the store, machine
washable, and there are more and more fleece items, including a
black fleece turtleneck by Marmot.
</P>
<P>
   But fleece can't be made into interesting patterns, and that's
partly why good old tight-weave sweaters are coming back into the
ski picture. Nils Skiwear makes a beautiful women's sweater in soft
blue with a border of black and white snowflakes down the zip
front. The sweater also has a black-lined wool hood, and costs
$150.
</P>
<P>
   The newest look in Obermeyer's women's skiwear is the ``Ladies
Sporto'' suit called The Enforcer, which is a flax- white suit with
a vest worn over it in different colors. The suit is in a European
cut with wide shoulders and a close fit through the body and legs.
It has a lot of features for a suit under $300, including plenty of
Thermolite, a DuPont fabric that keeps you warm.
</P>
<P>
   Another fashion forward look from Obermeyer for women is a down
parka of Luminex rubber. It comes in pistachio, columbine blue,
black, and white.
</P>
<P>
   The tried and true Norwegian sweater has returned in a big way.
Dale of Norway, which is making sweaters for both the US and the
Norwegian ski teams this year, makes wonderful ones of 100 percent
wool, with hangtags that tell stories of Norwegian explorers and
make you feel good about buying them, at $199. The Fridtjof Nansen
model, for example, is named after a polar hero and explorer who
won a Nobel Peace Prize in 1922 for his humanitarian achievement
with the Norwegian Refugee Council. Part of what you pay for the
sweater goes toward the council to support refugees and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Every Norwegian sweater pattern, as every Scotch plaid, tells a
story of a certain clan, and these are all in traditional Norwegian
family patterns, recognizable to those in the know, simply works of
art to those who aren't. These may look like the same ski sweaters
that your parents wore, but even Norwegian sweaters must move
forward, and you can get a windstopper version in the same
traditional patterns but with a lining for that purpose, for $280.
</P>
<P>
   The two newest items in skiwear are for the head and the feet.
Bandit Headwear makes a clever headband that keeps your head warm
and also has a slot sewn into the sides for your sun- or
eyeglasses, so that they don't slip.
</P>
<P>
   The newest things for apres-ski cold feet are the Merrell Snow
Clogs, made of Polartek, a structural fleece, with soft cushy
insides and tough rubber bumpy soles. They come in ``jungle slide''
or clog style, or ``winter moc'' style, in brown, black, or dark
green, are for men and women, and cost $55 and $65. Women who first
see the clunky shoes in the store, Turner says, remark, ``These are
the ugliest things I've ever seen.'' When they try them on, they
say, ``These are the most comfortable things I've ever worn.'' He
sold three pairs as he was putting them out on the selling floor
this fall and calls them ``a wonderful alternative to boots.''
</P>
<P>
   Obermeyer skiwear can be found at Bob Smith Wilderness House and
The Ski Market, or by calling 800-525-4203, or at
www.obermeyer.com. To find retail shops for the Bandit headband,
look on line at www.banditheadwear.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
