<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKI-UTAH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTAH AND THE OLYMPICS: A GOOD FIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years from now the Winter Olympics return to the United
States for the first time since 1980 when Lake Placid was host. As
magical a place as that Adirondack hideaway may be, with that
steeped-in-history feel, Placid even 20 years ago seemed strained
to the breaking point as host for such a worldwide event. Memories,
however, remain warm _ Eric Heiden's five gold medals, and the US
hockey team's upset win over Russia's Red Army.
</P>
<P>
   But in 2002 when Salt Lake City hosts the Winter Games, the look
is very different, and Utah could not be a more fitting region.
Already a World Cup Skiing city, Park City has real mountains,
demanding courses, and something no other part of the world has yet
been able to guarantee _ from the Eastern United States to western
Canada to Europe to Japan: consistent snow. All the rest of the
skiing venues in the state can make the same claim.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as many Utah ski fans have pointed out the worst thing
that can happen in this part of the central Rockies is too much
snow. But compared to too much rain in Nagano and too much warm
chinook wind in Calgary, and snow droughts in Europe, we'll take
our chances with Utah's embarrassment of riches _ that is, heavy on
the champagne powder.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Utah one of the greatest prospective Olympic venues
perhaps in the whole 78-year history of the Winter Games that began
in Chamonix, France, also makes the state one of the best
destinations for winter vacationers. To be sure, much of the nearly
$800 million invested in the games will show up on the slopes.
Following are some thumbnails of Utah skiing.
</P>
<P>
   We start with The Canyons (435-649-5400) because most people
have never heard of the area _ yet. That's because in its modern
incarnation as the newest American Skiing Company resort, The
Canyons is just entering its third season. In that time, The
Canyons _ once known as Park West _ has undergone one of the most
amazing transformations ever wrought on ski country.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the numbers, The Canyons has added 1,200 skiable
acres to a total of 3,300 acres _ one of the largest ski areas in
North America. Last season was the coup de grace for the area,
which opened 800 new acres of expert terrain served by the Ninety
Nine 90 express quad chair that will keep the terrain set aside
fairly exclusively for skiers who belong there _ truly advanced.
</P>
<P>
   So large and varied is The Canyons that every level of skier
will find, not just some terrain, but a bewildering amount of it.
Skiing spread throughout the peaks, ridges, bowls, and chutes of
The Canyons offers every exposure, terrain, and surface. There are
groomed smoothies for those intermediates still working on those
turns before kicking it up to the open bowls and glades where
skiers find the famous Utah ``cold smoke'' powder and wear bandanas
over their mouths to keep from breathing it in.
</P>
<P>
   If it's size and variety any ski group is looking for, The
Canyons, simply put, covers every possible offering with so much
terrain that no one will ever feel the repetitiveness that marks
lesser mountains and ski areas.
</P>
<P>
   Off slope, the infrastructure is coming. This year ASC will open
a new 360-unit hotel in the center of a slopeside village, with
three new restaurants ready for the pre-Olympic explorers checking
out this newest jewel in the Rocky Mountain firmament.
</P>
<P>
   Another relatively new area in the state is Snowbasin
(801-399-1135), generally known to locals in the Ogden region. But
four new high-speed lifts put in for the Olympics to access the
upper reaches of this steep area have put Snowbasin on a much
different competitive footing.
</P>
<P>
   The new lifts access enough new terrain to give this now-large
area 3,200 skiable acres, many of them in the steep and deep
country that Utah powder hounds crave. Allen's Peak, a 1,000-acre
highland once unaccessible, is now easy to reach. Same with
Strawberry Bowl with its new 1,000-plus acres.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago there was a serious lack of FIS downhill courses in
the United States, leading to an embarrassingly feeble downhill
course at Vail's 1989 World Alpine Championships. Last year, a
decade later, Vail had built the awesome Birds of Prey course, as
tough as any in the world. But not to be outdone, Snowbasin, site
of the 2002 Olympic men's downhill, has also built a croaker of a
course, one that gets the attention _ and praises _ of the toughest
Austrian flyboy. The top of the course is so steep that Hermann
Maier and the boys will accelerate to 85 miles per hour six seconds
out of the starting shed.
</P>
<P>
   But Snowbasin has more to offer recreational skiers than most
have ever discovered. When the new Olympic road is completed to the
Ogden area, it will be even easier to reach. But for a trek to new
territory, Snowbasin is a find.
</P>
<P>
   Better known _ in fact the standbys of Utah skiing _ Snowbird
(800-385-2002) and Alta (801-359-1078) are the two areas that first
brought in the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Just half an hour from Salt Lake City lies Snowbird, an area
that averages a whopping 500 inches of snow yearly. That means on
any given day, skiers headed up to Snowbird will probably have some
fresh powder to ski in. For Easterners, this is the place to rent a
pair of fatties, and get a lesson in the champagne powder. Skiing
with no bottom under foot is a whole new feel, an exhilarating one
at that.
</P>
<P>
   Located in Little Cottonwood Canyon, Snowbird also has a
world-class spa and the famous Cliff Lodge at its base. Putting on
boots here, looking out at Mount Baldy is only the first moment at
Snowbird where you suck in your breath. Your first ride up the
100-passenger tram is the second. And it only gets better from
there.
</P>
<P>
   Alta was one of the earliest Utah areas. Built in the '30s, and
loved by ages of powder hounds, Alta has the reputation for steep
cornices and bowls, hidden veins of powder always to be mined over
some newly discovered ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Alta does have some really fine novice terrain. What it has
less of are those groomed intermediate runs that many Easterners
seem to like. So, come to Alta to change your approach. Go for some
untracked powder and open bowl sking. Many worldwide skiers still
count Alta, with its 2,200 acres, its moderately-priced lift
tickets, and its no-snowboard policy, as their number one place to
ski.
</P>
<P>
   Park City (800-453-1360) is the heart of the US Alpine ski
world, home and headquarters of our national ski team, and site of
the kickoff of the World Cup season each Thanksgiving time. Little
wonder that this 3,300-acre area has really kicked it up a notch in
preparation for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   What other mountain anywhere has four high-speed six packs
running up its steeps all day? And a 750-acre high adventure area
for skiers and boarders seeking some difference in the pace of
their sport. Park City offers as thorough a mix of skiing tastes as
you can find at one area, and is the most accommodating site in
Utah. But this is hardly the area to come for skiers in a
getting-away-from-it-all mood. This is the buzzing hub of the ski
world.
</P>
<P>
   Its first innovation many years ago was to greet skiers with ski
valets, and pamper them from arrival to departure. Now, a decade
old, Deer Valley Resort (800-424-3337) is still known as one of the
plushest, service-oriented resorts in ski country. This works for
some, not for others.
</P>
<P>
   Deer Valley works best for skiers who like predictability,
beauty, groomed snow, and some of the best cruising runs in the
Rockies. Apres ski life is both an epicurean and bacchanalian
delight.
</P>
<P>
   But Deer Valley is trying hard not to stagnate as the resort for
old softies, and has started coming with some tough, off-trail
skiing, as well as some hard rock down in the village at night. In
2002, Deer Valley will be home to the very youth-oriented Freestyle
events, and it's working on the transition already. A welcome one
at that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
