<HEADLINE>
BE A SMART PARKGOER: KEEP TO YOUR LEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much is happening so quickly in the Land of Theme Parks _ the
Orlando, Fla., area _ that Fodor's Travel Publications now updates
its ``Walt Disney World, Universal Studios, and Orlando'' guide
twice a year. Here are tips from Fodor's on easing the theme park
hassle:
</P>
<P>
   --When entering the parks, walk to the left. Everyone naturally
goes to the right, so you'll move much faster on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   --Measure your children's heights before leaving home. You don't
want them getting too excited over a ride that they're not tall
enough to be allowed on.
</P>
<P>
   --Bring your own drinks if the parks allow it. If possible,
freeze them the night before so they'll stay cold all day.
</P>
<P>
   --Consider leaving the parks in the afternoon and going to a
water park or your hotel pool, thus keeping cool while escaping the
afternoon crush.
</P>
<P>
   --Bring a change of socks daily. They'll make your youngsters'
feet (and yours, too) feel rested and put a little more oomph in
everyone's step.
</P>
<P>
   --If you're traveling with small children, add an extra day or
two _ and go on the tamest rides first. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What is the official mammal of Florida? &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: The Bird Emergency Aid and Kare Sanctuary on Big Talbot
Island, near Jacksonville, Fla., is also known by its acronym:
BEAKS. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``We have a new tourism slogan: `Come Back to Miami _ We
Weren't Shooting at You' '' _ Dave Barry (who, for once, was making
that up). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bus driver joke (on the drive from sunny Orlando to the Disney
Cruise Line Terminal in sunny Port Canaveral, Fla.): ``The ride
should take about an hour. If we encounter snow and ice, it'll take
a little longer.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Florida forbids singing in a public place while
attired in a swimsuit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Event to remember: Next Saturday, St. Augustine, Fla., turns on the
lights _ more than a million tiny ones that outline the houses and
buildings of the historic downtown area. The ``Night of Lights''
inaugurates a holiday celebration that will run through Jan. 30. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of the times: A sign in the Outback Steak House in Orlando
(and presumably other Outback locations), points toward the ``Used
Beer Dept.'' Writes Mary Powers of Gloucester: ``I laughed when I
realized it was pointing to the restrooms!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum of the month: Everybody say, ``Vroom!'' The Don Garlits
Museum of Drag Racing, near Ocala, Fla., is hot-rod heaven, with
dragsters from over the years, including the record-breaking
``swamp rats'' that were driven by Big Daddy Garlits himself. There
is a variety of other vehicles, including ``muscle cars,'' and
Garlits's fellow racers are saluted. For more information, call
352-245-8661. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alaskan pelican sighted: Outdoor sculptures for two state office
buildings in Florida and Alaska were done by the same sculptor _
eagles for Alaska and pelicans for Florida. But they were delivered
to the wrong places. Deciding this was a wonderful mistake, the
buildings kept the misdirected sculptures, leaving the pelicans on
display in Alaska and the eagles in Florida. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: You've heard of ``carpe diem'' (``seize the day'').
Well, the Downtown Disney entertainment complex in Lake Buena
Vista, Fla., advises ``carpe p.m.'' (``seize the night''). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The panther, one of the world's most endangered
animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
