<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING, WHERE IT ALL BEGAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you haven't made plans for Thanksgiving, why not celebrate it
where it all began?
</P>
<P>
   In Plymouth, ``America's Hometown,'' visitors can not only walk
where the Pilgrims did, but feast on a traditional Thanksgiving
meal at Plimoth Plantation, a re-creation of the Pilgrims' village,
or in area restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   While Plymouth is just an hour from Boston, and can easily be
seen in a day trip, it's also well worth staying overnight to fully
appreciate all that can be seen. A visit to Plimoth Plantation can
easily take most of the day, particularly if you take time to chat
with the Pilgrims, costumed reenactors who will gladly talk about
anything as long as it is not later than the village's time of
162730.
</P>
<P>
   There's also Plymouth Rock; the Mayflower II, a replica of the
Pilgrim's original vessel; open houses at the Jabez Howland House,
the only home in Plymouth where Pilgrims actually lived; the
Richard Sparrow House, the oldest in Plymouth; Harlow Old Fort
House, built out of timbers from the Pilgrims' original fort; the
Pilgrim Hall Museum, with 17th-century artifacts of the original
colonists, and on Nov. 20 the Majestic Thanksgiving Parade.
</P>
<P>
   Along the waterfront, visit also the Ocean Spray Cranberry
Museum, where you can learn everything you ever wanted to know
about this traditional part of the Thanksgiving meal. Nearby in
South Carver is Edaville Railroad, a narrow gauge train that
travels on five miles of tracks alongside cranberry bogs.
</P>
<P>
   If you stay over, take in a Colonial Lantern Tour (508-747-4161)
where you can walk through history.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving day, Plimoth Plantation offers two meal choices:
a Victorian Dinner (three seatings), which celebrates 1863, when
Abraham Lincoln declared Thanksgiving an official holiday; and a
Thanksgiving Day Buffet. For information on these meals, call (508)
746-1622 or log on to www.plimoth.org.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of lodging, including the John Carver Inn, which
has a wonderful indoor Pilgrim-themed swimming pool that the kids
will love (508-746-7100 or 800-274-1620). The inn has a two-night
package at $299 for two that includes breakfasts, a dinner
allowance, and admission to Plimoth Plantation. Other choices
include the Sheraton Inn (508-747-4900), which has a $94 a night
double occupancy rate through Nov. 22; and the Governor Bradford on
the Harbour (800-332-1620), which offers an ocean view room at $80
a person.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Thanksgiving in Plymouth, call
508-746-2334 or, on the Web, visit www.thanksgivingusa.com. For a
free guide to Plymouth, call 800-231-1620 or visit
www.plymouth-1620.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
New in Florida &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A dazzling new 36-minute ice-skating tour of seven countries has
opened at Busch Gardens Tampa Bay. World Rhythms on Ice celebrates
Africa, England, Brazil, China, Antarctica, Germany, and America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben Hur _ The Musical,'' a $9 million production based on the
classic story of Ben-Hur, has opened in Orlando at the convention
center. The show will continue through 2003 and has ticket prices
ranging from $20 for children 3-17 to $36 for adults in orchestra
seating.
</P>
<P>
   VISIT FLORIDA is offering six self-directed driving tour
itineraries to visitors looking for specialized Florida
experiences. Each tour takes four or five days to complete,
although visitors can opt to do just a portion of the tour. The
tour themes are: African-American Heritage Trail, Cuban Heritage
Trail, Native American Heritage Tour, Florida's East Coast
Lighthouse Tour, Birding in Northeast Florida, and North Florida
Outdoor Adventure Trail. Copies of the tours are free and can be
obtained at the five Official Florida Welcome Centers or at
www.flausa.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida International Museum in St. Petersburg has opened
its first permanent exhibition, which features the world's largest
private collection of John F. Kennedy mementos. The items were
gathered by Evelyn Lincoln, the late president's personal
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   An entire gallery is devoted to first lady Jacqueline Kennedy,
including a letter she wrote to Lincoln after her husband's
assassination: ``Dearest Evelyn, there will never be Camelot
again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``John F. Kennedy: The Exhibition'' runs daily through May 29,
2000. Tickets are $13.95 for adults, $5.95 for children 6 to 18,
free under 6. For information, call 877-535-7469 or visit
www.floridamuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona USA is expanding the experience of the Richard Petty
Ride-Along program. Previously fans had only been able to ride
shotgun in a Winston Cup stock car at Daytona International
Speedway. Now, motorsports enthusiast will be able to climb into
the driver's seat and tackle the 31-degree high banks at the
world-famous speedway for the thrill of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Adventure Museum in Punta Gorda offers ``Up in
Smoke: The Cigar Industry in Florida.'' The focus is on the
historical, economic, and cultural importance of cigar
manufacturing in Florida as well as the people who made the cigars.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Museum of Science &AMP; Space Transit Planetarium is
marking its 50th anniversary with the opening of ``Smithsonian
Expeditions: Exploring Latin America and the Caribbean.'' The
exhibit showcases the Smithsonian's contributions to the study and
preservation of the natural history and culture of the Americas for
more than 150 years. Also opened is BusyTown, a bilingual
interactive science exhibit bsed on the stories of
author/illustrator Richard Scarry.
</P>
<P>
   After a nine-year restoration effort, Key West's historic Custom
House has reopened as the Key West Museum of Art &AMP; History.
</P>
<P>
   Lignumvitae Key State Botanical Site, an island located one mile
north on mile marker 78 in Islamorada, has been added to the
National Register of Historic Places. Lignumvitae has one of the
largest stands of tropical hardwoods in the Florida Keys, and is
also recognized for its Native American burial grounds, and
circa-1919 coral rock house. Excursions to the island are offered
by Robbie's Boat Rentals at mile marker 77.5
</P>
<P>
   The site of the $400 million shipwrecked Spanish treasure
galleon Nuestra Senora de Atocha is now accessible to divers. Sunk
in 1622, and discovered in 1985, the Atocha has been called the
richest shipwreck find this century. Atocha Dive Expeditions offers
divers a chance to view the site located in about 55 feet of water
35 miles southwest of Key West. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deal &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you were born in 1959, China Air has a deal for you. To
celebrate its 40th year, China Air is offering a $198 round-trip
coach fare to China, along with similar savings on first and
business class. Travel must begin on Nov. 30. Arnold Greenblat of
Atlas Travel in Brockton (508-583-773) found this deal. His agency
does not charge service fees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Just for women &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica Journeys, a program begun 10 years ago by Mary Ann Jones
as an outgrowth of her experience and appreciation of Jamaica and
its people, will offer a new series of travel, workshops, and
retreats beginning at Thanskgiving and continuing through March.
The programs are for women ``either side of 50.'' Among upcoming
programs are one on the art and craft of writing and another on
yoga. For information, call 508-432-3114 or 617-254-1729.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Getaways &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica Naturally offers trips to that Central American land
for those who enjoy nature. A number of trips are planned for
January to discover the flora and fauna. For information, call
Margaret Connors in Duxbury at 800-230-5200.
</P>
</TEXT>
