<HEADLINE>
NOW IT'S GRAND IN WINTER, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To gaze at the Mount Washington Hotel in Bretton Woods, N.H., is
to understand the term ``grand hotel.'' The massive red-and-white
Spanish Renaissance building, with its 900-foot veranda and the
Presidential Range as a backdrop, has been nicknamed the Queen of
Mountain Resorts. And now it's a snow queen, too.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Nov. 24, the hotel, a stately summer destination since
1902, will be open four seasons. The conversion of this National
Historic Landmark to a winter-ready establishment took some doing .
. . and $2 million. More than 800 windows were replaced with
double-pane insulated glass. Thermostats were installed in the 200
guest rooms and suites, a backup boiler system was built, a backup
generator was added, and the hotel's water treatment systems were
winterized. As part of the preparation, thermometers were hung from
corridor ceilings to make sure the passageways were warm. And to
test the accommodations, general manager Anthony Ferrelli and his
wife lived in the hotel all last winter, and department heads were
invited to spend a night.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Bretton Woods Ski Area was purchased by the hotel,
so there are a variety of ski-and-stay hotel packages. This winter
West Mountain opens adjacent to the Bretton Woods Ski Area, with
snowmaking, new trails, and lifts. Bretton Woods says this gives
the area the most ski terrain in New Hampshire. And the Bretton
Woods Cross Country Ski Resort is right on the hotel grounds.
</P>
<P>
   So there should be plenty to do, both on the slopes and in the
hotel, with its restaurants, banquet rooms, and Cave Lounge, which
features live evening entertainment. Actually, just walking around
this famous hotel is entertainment of a sort. One thing, though:
Looking down the long, long corridors, you may be reminded of the
hotel in that spooky movie ``The Shining'' and assume, as many do,
that it was filmed at the Mount Washington. You're not even close _
the Stephen King book was inspired by the Stanley Hotel in Estes
Park, Colo., but for technical reasons exterior shots were filmed
at at the Timberline Lodge on Mount Hood, Ore., and interior sets
were built in England.
</P>
<P>
   (The Mount Washington Hotel will be open late November to early
April, then mid-May to mid-October. Several special events are
planned this winter, including an opening gala Nov. 24-28 and a
winter carnival Jan. 7-20. For more information, call 800-258-0330
or visit www.mtwashington.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ski Trivia: How many mountains does Vermont have: (a) 2, (b) 22,
(c) 220, or (d) 2,200? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A consistent grouping of elongated bumps from which
snowboarders jump is known as a whale, whale tail, or whoop de
doo. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Sure, we're dreaming of a white Christmas. . . . We're
dreaming of a white Halloween, a white Father's Day, and a white
Cinco de Mayo.'' _ from an ad for K2 skis. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sky-high dining: Leysin, in Switzerland's Lake Geneva area, has
quite a place to eat: the Kuklos revolving restaurant complex,
6,000 feet high, which offers a panorama of the mountains and, on a
clear day, all of Lake Geneva. Leysin is also home to a challenging
new half-pipe and the World Masters Snowboard series. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? 220.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
