<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MCFEELY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH-PENALTY FIGHT PULLS HISTORIAN INTO THE PRESENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ William S. McFeely's ``Proximity to Death''
begins with a journey from Athens to Sparta. Though it's modern-day
Georgia the Pulitzer Prize-winning biographer of Ulysses S. Grant
and Frederick Douglass is traveling in, the echo of ancient Greece
is intentional. For the subject of McFeely's book is an issue as
old as Socrates or Antigone: the morality of the state taking a
life in the pursuit of justice.
</P>
<P>
   McFeely is one of America's most distinguished historians of the
Reconstruction era. Four years ago, he found himself transported
from past to present when a lawyer representing an inmate on death
row called to see if he would be willing to testify as an expert at
a hearing. McFeely said yes, and ``Proximity to Death'' _ a book
about the death penalty and a band of Atlanta lawyers opposed to it
_ is the result.
</P>
<P>
   It makes considerable sense that McFeely, 69, should turn to
capital punishment as a subject. ``One way or another,'' he says,
``I've been teaching about race all along,'' and the US justice
system is at its most black and white _ in both senses of the term
_ where the death penalty is concerned. As of April 1, 43 percent
of death row inmates were black (a number more than three times the
percentage of blacks in the overall population), and 84 percent of
the victims in death row cases were white _ though only 50 percent
of murder victims were.
</P>
<P>
   McFeely's involvement with race extends all the way to his
kindergarten days in suburban New Jersey. He recalls how the site
of a class picnic had to be changed because one of his classmates
was black. It ended up at McFeely's house.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter century later, when McFeely was at graduate school at
Yale, the civil rights movement was cresting. That, combined with
the presence of C. Vann Woodward, the dean of Southern historians,
helped determine McFeely's destiny. He signed up for Woodward's
seminar on Reconstruction and, he says, ``I was hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   McFeely's raspy voice is well suited to his bulldog face and
energetic manner _ neither of which seems especially professorial,
though. This is as it should be, perhaps, since he took a somewhat
roundabout path to scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Amherst College, he took a job with
National City Bank (now Citigroup) in New York. ``I wasn't all that
much of a banker,'' McFeely says, ``but when I used to travel for
the bank _ my district was West Virginia, Pennsylvania, New Jersey
_ my job was really to call on the little country banks and small
companies. I'd be in a little town like Pottsville or something,
and what do you do in the evening? I'd find myself walking the
streets of the town and getting a sense of it. I have got, I think,
the kind of curiosity that makes me able to connect the formal
historical past with how people relate to it in the present.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years as a banker made McFeely realize high finance wasn't
for him. He had vague thoughts of becoming a secondary school
teacher when an Amherst faculty member told him to call on the
chairman of the American Studies program at Yale. This was in
August, and classes were about to begin, so the chairman fobbed off
McFeely on the dean _ who let him in on probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too naive to know it was impossible to do what I wanted
to do,'' McFeely says. ``It was incredibly scary, looking back. I
had a wife, no money, kids, and no assurance I'd make it.''
</P>
<P>
   McFeely and his wife have been married 47 years. Herself a
historian, Mary Drake McFeely is finishing a book for the
University of Massachusetts Press called ``Can She Bake a Cherry
Pie?,'' a study of women and cooking in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The McFeelys, who divide their time between Wellfleet and
Cambridge, have a son and daughter. The son, Drake, is president of
W. W. Norton, which makes him his father's publisher. ``Drake and I
work very hard to stay out of each other's way there,'' McFeely
laughs. ``I was there first,'' he's quick to add.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a PhD with a dissertation on O. O. Howard, the
Union general who headed the Freedmen's Bureau after the Civil War,
McFeely taught at Yale before moving on to Mount Holyoke College to
become dean of faculty and professor of history. He stayed there 16
years, until wooed away by the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Culturally, the Pioneer Valley is about as far as you can get
from the Deep South and still hear American English being spoken.
Of course, there are those who would argue that Athens, the site of
the university, while it may be in the South, is barely of it. It's
home not just to the Georgia Bulldogs, pride of the Southeastern
Conference, but also the rock groups REM and the B-52s. It says
something about both McFeely and the homeyness of Athens that
during his 11 years in Georgia he became both an REM fan (``The
band is really something'') and friendly with its members.
</P>
<P>
   McFeely retired two years ago. ``I do miss teaching,'' he says,
``but I'm also enjoying the luxury of just concentrating on
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   In both the new book and its immediate predecessor, ``Sapelo's
People'' (1994), a quite amiable examination of the past and
present inhabitants of one of the Sea Islands off Georgia, one can
see a writer enjoying the opportunity to take chances and use
different literary muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did switch gears,'' McFeely says. ``I do think people can
hear my voice in my biographies of Grant and Douglass, but they're
both 19th-century figures, long dead, and I took a standard,
scholarly, third-person approach. But, somehow, writing in the
first person feels comfortable to me . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun writing about the present. I don't think of myself
as a journalist, but I can understand the fascination of talking to
people who are different from you and getting to know them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of those people McFeely came to know are convicted
murderers sitting on death row. He remains in correspondence with
them and clearly takes their plight to heart. What had been a vague
and somewhat abstract opposition to capital punishment has become,
in the four years since his appearance before that sentencing
hearing, distressingly specific and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a violent culture,'' McFeely says, ``and I have a theory
that the death penalty is the capstone of this whole sense of
violence . . . its ultimate expression.'' The passion of his
opposition has not blinded McFeely to how widespread the support
for capital punishment is in this country, but he draws on his
scholarly background for an encouraging analogy. ``The
Abolitionists must have thought theirs was a hopeless cause, but
eventually they prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (with this book) I've opened up the discourse a little
bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
