<HEADLINE>
BECK STILL MINING JUNK CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's how it starts: ``Sexx Laws'' shimmies from the speakers
like some sort of ``Hullabaloo''-style go-go revue _ all funked-up
horns, reverberating synths, boogaloo bass, jittery tambourine.
``Can't you hear those cavalry drums/Hijacking your
equilibrium/Midnight hags in the mausoleum/Where the pixilated
doctors moan,'' Beck drawls, moving on in short order to the
cokeheads, concubines, coquettes, handcuffs, and brief encounters
in expensive cars. An unnerving old-time banjo break momentarily
derails the dank pageantry. You can practically see the singer
shuck 'n' jive. On ``Midnight Vultures'' (DGC), out Nov. 16,
29-year-old Beck continues to fulfill his destiny as post-modern
geek-pimp for the surreal, curator of the slash-and-burn art of
ironic overkill, and purveyor of a brilliant, musical merging of
satire and critique.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually gone is the freaky folk-hop of 1996's ground-breaking
``Odelay''; so are the warped psychedelic noodlings that fueled
last year's ``Mutations.'' But junk culture is still his landscape,
and fractured dance music his main architectural statement. This
time around Beck finds his muse in the tacky glamour of late-'90s
Los Angeles. His musical persona is a twisted tormentor of a soul
man, brought into vivid relief by a core band of keyboards and
bass, plus a pair of computer programmers and guests who include
ex-Smiths guitarist Johnny Marr, techno-folkie Beth Orton, and
``Odelay'' producers the Dust Brothers. ``I'll feed you fruit that
don't exist/I'll leave grafitti where you've never been kissed,''
Beck sings on ``Nicotine and Gravy,'' lounging in a sonic waterbed
of sighs and cackles, percolating bass lines, and a spry, sing-song
loop imploring ``I don't want to die tonight.'' The sun seems to be
setting _ fast _ behind Beck's famously mixed metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   Song titles say a lot about the album's general state of mind.
``Hlwd. Freaks.'' ``Mixed Bizness.'' ``Peaches and Cream.'' ``Get
Real Paid.'' The latter is a space-age club tome to contemporary
society where the robotic voices drone ``we like the guys with the
bulletproof vests/we like the girls with the cellophane chests.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Debra'' is a longtime concert staple that sounds for all the
world like a laid-back R&AMP;B love ballad, replete with dazzling
falsetto vocals, but the sweet tune quickly reveals itself as a
tale of seductive lechery: ``I want to get with you/Only you/And
your sister/I think her name's Debra.''
</P>
<P>
   Twisted collage is the thing, and while the album's emphasis is
on R&AMP;B, Beck manages to channel arena rock (power chords the
consistency of shredded plutonium) and the Beatles (ooh-la-la-la
harmony vocals from ``Nowhere Man'') in one fell swoop on
``Pressure Zone.'' Unfortunately, ``Milk and Honey'' is just bad
arena rock, albeit made slightly more palatable with sampled
sounds, taped voices, and implicit irony. He introduces electronica
to the bossa nova via shades of aural paisley on ``Broken Train,''
to better, and ultra-groovy, effect.
</P>
<P>
   Beck has called ``Midnight Vultures'' his ``dumb party record.''
Which shows just how intact his sense of irony is. In the land of
cell phones and laser surgery, at a time when teen bands and
boneheads vie for pop music's crown, Beck's music is a breath of
modern-rock air: smart, risky, witty, and relevant. You can also
spaz out to it on the dance floor. Who could ask for anything more?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
