<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ART-DECO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI BEACH ART DECO DISTRICT NOW STYLISH INTERNATIONAL GETAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ There is nowhere else in America quite like the
South Beach section here. Never has been, really.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us can recall the time when what is now trendily known
as SoBe, which for a period between the world wars was a
fashionable winter haven for celebrities and the well-to-do, had
fallen on hard times. A neighborhood of deteriorating old hotels
occupied largely by elderly retired garment workers from New York,
it was derisively known as ``God's Waiting Room.'' Wholesale
demolition seemed an eventual certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few visionary and determined preservationists,
recognizing that South Beach contained the country's largest
concentration of buildings in the Art Deco style _ an international
design style that peaked in popularity in America in the 1930s and
1940s _ came to the rescue. Organized as the Miami Design
Preservation League, they restored many buildings and saved others
from the wrecker's ball. They also gave the neighborhood its own
distinctive color scheme, replacing the original shades of white on
most buildings with a rainbow of pastel colors inspired by Necco
candy wafers.
</P>
<P>
   By 1979 some 900 buildings in the area were placed on the
National Register of Historic Places, and the federal government
created an Art Deco Historic District, the first for the purpose of
preserving 20th-century architecture. The league has an office at
1001 Washington Ave. and distributes maps pinpointing the Art Deco
landmarks. It also conducts walking tours of the district during
which affable and enthusiastic guides point out both the league's
triumphs (beautifully restored buildings) and its failures (parking
lots where Art Deco gems once stood).
</P>
<P>
   Historic it may be, but the Art Deco District also makes almost
any list of hippest places in America. Most of the action is in the
10 blocks along Ocean Avenue from Fifth to 14th streets: an almost
unbroken lineup of Art Deco buildings (the majority small
bed-and-breakfast hotels) facing the ocean and Miami Beach's best
beach.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first part of the district to be restored and
gentrified and remains the most atmospheric. Also, definitely the
most photographed.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion photographers were quick to appreciate the district's
visual charms, using its sun-drenched streets, palm-tree-lined
beachfront, and colorful buildings as backgrounds for fashion
layouts in the world's top magazines. Many episodes of ``Miami
Vice,'' a popular TV show in the mid-1980s, were also filmed in
SoBe, spotlighting its charms (while exaggerating its dangers) for
viewers in some 135 countries. This exposure on TV and in glossy
high-fashion magazines, probably more than anything else, made the
Art Deco District the trendy international destination it has
become.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago the lobby area of many classic Ocean Avenue Art
Deco hotels such as the Avalon, Cardozo, Clevelander, Waldorf
Towers, and Edison housed the offices of modeling agencies or were
assembly points for fashion shoots. These days, most businesses
related to the booming fashion industry are found several blocks
inland on Lincoln Road, the upscale eight- block-long pedestrian
shopping and dining mall that claims to be ``The Fifth Avenue of
the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the lobbies and adjacent verandas where impossibly
good-looking male and female models used to congregate at first
light (the fashion photographer's favorite time of day) are likely
to be occupied by restaurants or cafes, and the avenue is more or
less one sidewalk eatery and drinkery after another. The lobby and
patio of the Avalon Hotel, for instance, are taken up by one of
SoBe's best seafood restaurants, A Fish Called Avalon. (To heighten
the Art Deco atmosphere, Avalon's owner usually parks his vintage
1950s' canary yellow Oldsmobile convertible right in front of the
restaurant.)
</P>
<P>
   At the epicenter of this lively strip _ and arguably its best
people-watching perch _ is the News Cafe. Although it has an indoor
area and a shop that sells sundries, books, and newspapers and
magazines from around the world, the News is essentially an outdoor
cafe and conversation pit. It's open 24 hours a day, and the buzz
of talk in most of the world's major languages rises and falls
around the clock but never stops.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many of its customers are Europeans accustomed to
having a service charge automatically included in their bar and
restaurant tabs, the cafe _ like many other SoBe establishments _
calculates a 15 percent ``suggested tip'' and puts it on the check.
</P>
<P>
   Every few years or so the Art Deco District seems to shed a skin
and become something a bit different. It also changes, sometimes
quite dramatically, throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   In early morning, crews from fashion magazines and advertising
agencies are nearly as much in evidence as joggers and dog walkers.
The sight of beautiful female models wrapped provocatively around
palm trees or tossing beach balls at each other with
near-hysterical glee is commonplace along Ocean Avenue, at least
around 6 a.m. or so.
</P>
<P>
   During the day the wide beach, which periodically has to be
shored up and resanded by the Army Corps of Engineers, fills up
with people. By midafternoon it's usually a colorful human mosaic
of swimmers, tanners, exercisers, and gawking tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening the oceanfront cafe and restaurants get busy,
their kitchens scenting the humid air with delicious aromas while
competing sound systems fill it with pounding, nonstop salsa
rhythms. After midnight, the crowd gets younger and the scene tends
to shift to inland discos and clubs. However, during SoBe's
equivalent of Mardi Gras, the mid-January ``Art Deco Weekend''
organized by the Design Preservation League, the mid-section of
Ocean Avenue is closed to traffic and given over to street dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Avenue is the Art Deco District's undisputed showcase.
However, there's also a lot to see and do nearby. Parallel Collins
Avenue, for instance, is dotted with upscale shops and boutique
hotels like the Marlin, Raleigh, and Delano, which have been
tastefully (and expensively) restored and attract celebrity guests.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Collins is a beloved SoBe institution, Puerto Sagua, a
pleasant but unpretentious restaurant at 700 Collins renowned for
massive portions of flavorful Cuban food. A typical luncheon
special _ such as fricasseed chicken served with plantains, yams,
and a small mountain of rice _ if completely consumed (not easy)
provides enough calories to keep an average person going until
lunch the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Avenue, a block in from Collins, has retained a funky
old-time South Beach feeling. There are a few upmarket shops but
many more family-run markets and fruit stands. The avenue also
boasts one of the district's few non-Art Deco architectural
landmarks: the impressively domed Miami Beach Post Office.
Acoustics beneath the great dome are so good concerts are sometimes
held there.
</P>
<P>
   Another Washington Avenue landmark is the Wolfsonian Foundation
building, an imposing Spanish baroque structure that looks as if it
was teleported from Seville. Actually, it was a storage warehouse
built in 1927 in the then fashionable Mediterranean Revival style
and converted into a design museum in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   A fascinating place, the Wolfsonian displays carefully selected
items from local multimillionaire Mickey Wolfson's collection of
more than 70,000 varied objects, including books and paper,
furniture, bric-a-brac, sculpture, paintings, and architectural
models. All represent some aspect of the cultural, political, and
technological changes that swept the globe in the century before
World War II. It's a wildly eclectic collection that incudes items
as disparate as a bentwood rocker manufactured in Gardner, Mass.,
at the turn of the century and a beautifully bound Braille edition
of ``Mein Kampf!''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to polyglot Ocean Avenue, American English and
Cuban-accented Spanish are the languages most frequently heard
along Washington Avenue. An exception is the corner of Washington
and Espanola Way, where you're likely to hear anything from Arabic
to Zulu.
</P>
<P>
   That's because this is the site of the Clay Hotel and
International Hostel, which draws its mostly youthful and
backpack-carrying guests from around the world. Built in the '20s,
The Clay was once one of Miami Beach's most fashionable hotels. It
was in its ballroom that legendary Cuban bandleader Desi Arnaz
introduced the rhumba to America. (He later became even more famous
as the husband of Lucille Ball of ``I Love Lucy'' fame.)
</P>
<P>
   Not your usual hostel, the Clay has private rooms with baths as
well as bunk-filled dormitories. An unusual amenity for an American
hostel is the Clay's sidewalk cafe on Espanola Way, which is itself
rather unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Only a block long, Espanola Way was designed as an artists'
quarter and is intentionally picturesque, paved with cobblestones
and its Mediterranean-style buildings ornamented with tiles,
brightly colored awnings, and elaborate wrought-iron balconies.
Most of the buildings have art galleries, boutiques, and craft
shops at street level with artists' studios in the upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   Many ``Miami Vice'' episodes were filmed on Espanola, which on
the television screen often echoed to the sounds of gunshots. In
real life, however, the loudest sound you're apt to hear is a
cheerful German or Aussie backpacker calling for another beer or
cafe cubano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
