A1397 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-16 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ARE NOT BEMUSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words we argue most about, at any given moment in history,
are what Bryan Garner calls ``skunked terms'' _ they're so tainted
by the debate between the traditionalists and the innovators that
it's hard to use them unself-consciously, whichever side you're on.
Hopefully is the prime example, and Garner's Dictionary of Modern
American Usage (1998) also has entries on data, decimate, enormity,
and other such troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   While we're rooting for our favorites in these long-running
fights, though, other words are quietly slipping out of their old
meanings and putting on new ones, as secretly as caterpillars
growing into butterflies. One of these is bemused, which seems to
have taken flight almost unnoticed by the traditionalists who would
have tried to pin it down.
</P>
<P>
   Bemused is supposed to mean ``utterly muddled, stupefied,
confused, bewildered'' or, more benignly, ``preoccupied,
distracted.'' But that doesn't seem to be the intent of most
writers using it in recent decades, even the usage writers: ``When
these items are couched in truly criminal syntax, some bemused
reader is sure to send the clippings my way,'' wrote columnist
James J. Kilpatrick in 1998. And William Safire, in 1993, advised
Clinton to ``take control of the East Room. (Presidential press
conferences) are not occasions to look bemused at confusion and to
marvel at `self-selection' by shouting reporters.''
</P>
<P>
   And here are a few from the Globe:
</P>
<P>
   --``After a half-hour that focused almost exclusively on Silber,
it was left to a bemused John Moffitt, campaign manager for William
Weld, to remind the panel that Weld won the election.''
</P>
<P>
   --``It was the music that astonished audiences and critics more
than the choreography, though they were more bemused than
outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   --``As she read the story, (Virginia Buckingham, now Massport
head) was alternately `stunned and bemused.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The usage advisers who've noticed the new bemused on the wing
tend to caution against using it as a synonym for amused, but that
doesn't seem to be what's happening: Sometimes the two words are
even paired, as in the Globe story reporting that ``Dylan seemed
alternately bemused and amused by his brief foray into prime
time.'' We seem to want bemused to blend ``faintly amused'' and
``faintly surprised,'' often with a dash of irony. It's still a
work in progress, though, so opinions and usage samples that will
help refine the definition are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But hold the objections, please. It's too late for that: Bemused
is simply doing what all our words do through the centuries,
finding the niche where it's most likely to survive. We don't need
the older bemused anymore: We have more colorful words for drunks
and daydreamers. Nor are Muse-based puns _ bemused to mean
enraptured by one's muse _ much in demand these days.
</P>
<P>
   What we do need is an agreement on the meaning of bemused, now
that we like it so much. As one usage guide noted a decade ago, the
word is ``slippery to handle''; it's time to get a grip, or some
readers will be bothered, bewildered, and not at all bewitched.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
