<HEADLINE>
&HT;        FOOD PRODUCERS FORESEE BATTLE OVER BIOTECHNOLOGY IN TRADE
TALKS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Nov. 15 - For the U.S. food industry, lowering trade
barriers on biologically altered food products will prove to be a
bone of contention between the U.S. and European countries at
upcoming trade talks, a food lobby coalition said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Round Agricultural Committee, a coalition of 90 farm
industry associations that supports elimination of barriers to food
trade, represents several industries that biologically engineer
their products to modify their shape or size. The coalition seeks a
World Trade Organization ruling that would ensure that these
products get unrestricted access to foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel of industry officials at the press conference said
they don't expect the Europeans to change their position without a
struggle in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they [the European Union] are going to be pursuing
this very hard,'' said Dean Kleckner, president of the American
Farm Bureau Federation. ``This is the toughest issue that's facing
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current WTO rules, member countries have the right to
block food imports they deem as risks to people's health or the
environment. While American farmers lead other nations in the
commercial application of agricultural biotechnology, some of the
15 European Union countries believe altered food is unsafe, and
uphold barriers on their importation.
</P>
<P>
   Corn, cotton, and soybean industries, which use biotechnology
for 35 to 50 percent of their total output, argue it makes for a
superior product. Representing these industries, the coalition
claims the trade barriers are politically motivated and not
scientifically sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not allow non-science-based safety standards, which do
nothing to protect consumers, to erect artificial barriers to
international trade,'' said John Cady, president and CEO of the
National Food Processors Association.
</P>
<P>
   On the biotechnology dispute, Kleckner said he favored forming a
separate negotiating group within the talks to focus solely on t
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
