<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1401 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-ATLANTIC-BOS &LR;      11-16 1808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-ATLANTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE ATLANTIC'S HELM, TWO CONTRASTING SKIPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The two men who recently took over the helm of The
Atlantic Monthly, Boston's 142-year-old literary landmark that was
once home to Emerson and Thoreau, could not seem more different.
</P>
<P>
   David Bradley, 46, is a disarmingly soft-spoken and idealistic
entrepreneur. Michael Kelly, 42, is a high-profile Beltway
columnist best known for his searing criticism of the Clinton White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Odds were that the first meeting between Kelly and Bradley would
be the last. It was 1997, and Bradley had abandoned his thoughts of
public office and was turning his attention to publishing. Having
just purchased the National Journal, he was looking for a name
journalist to bring some buzz to the little-known Washington
insider magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly had just been fired as editor of The New Republic after
clashing with its owner, Martin Peretz. But he was a hot commodity
who was talking to The New York Times, The Washington Post, and The
New Yorker about his next job. He agreed to meet Bradley largely as
a courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   Something clicked. The two men talked for almost 12 hours over
two days, and Kelly signed on to become David Bradley's new star
columnist. It is an unlikely team, the modest multimillionaire with
the Swarthmore and Harvard pedigree, and the combative career
journalist with a degree from the University of New Hampshire. And
now it is entrusted with the future of Boston's venerable and
vulnerable Atlantic Monthly, which Bradley bought from Mort
Zuckerman in September for about $17 million. The test is whether
they can transform the much-respected but oft-ignored Atlantic into
the highbrow magazine of the moment, perhaps filling the void
created when Tina Brown tarted up The New Yorker with S &AMP; M and
O.J.
</P>
<P>
   They face formidable obstacles. Both men are native
Washingtonians who are strangers to Boston's literary and social
culture. Bradley is but a novice when it comes to general-interest
magazine publishing, and Kelly's role as a noisy Beltway pundit
raises questions about how well he can adapt to a publication that
takes a broader view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But they also bring assets to the table. Bradley is considered a
benevolent, generous owner who may be willing to lavish the kind of
tender loving care and resources on a magazine that clearly was not
Zuckerman's priority in recent years. And Kelly, by all accounts
the possessor of a keen mind, brings a resume that includes major
magazine duty, and that responds to the kind of varied interests
that make him, in his own words, ``a generalist . . . not a
political junkie.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they have one huge advantage: a chemistry rarely seen
between owner and editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have found each other and are completely sympatico,''
said Atlantic senior editor Jack Beatty, who met them after the
sale. ``They have a real singular relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   News accounts of Bradley buying The Atlantic were filled with
unlikely descriptions. The Washington Post called him ``unusually
self-effacing,'' and The New York Times went with ``sweet natured
Mr. Rogers.'' The Web site for Bradley's Advisory Board Co.
strategic research firm _ half of which was spun off in a $142
million public offering this year _ lists not only its strengths,
but, remarkably, its ``weaknesses.'' Bradley is not your typical
ego- and bottom line-driven media mogul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking there's a catch here,'' said Craig Crawford,
editor of the Hotline newsletter that is part of Bradley's National
Journal Group. ``I keep thinking he's going to turn into Howard
Hughes or Rupert Murdoch. . . . He has this very compelling,
intense, yet quiet manner that just draws you in. At first, I
thought I'd become part of a cult.''
</P>
<P>
   The product of what he calls ``a lovely, nice start in life,''
Bradley attended Sidwell Friends School in Washington, went to
Swarthmore, and then to Harvard, where he got an MBA. He served as
a White House intern during the year Richard M. Nixon resigned and
then taught economics in the Philippines on a Fulbright
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, he started the Advisory Board Co. as part of a
master plan to strike it rich young and pursue his goal of becoming
a Maryland senator. Then, on a long plane flight to Vietnam in
1994, Bradley had an epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this terrible moment of complete solitude'' and realized
that ``I don't have the gift,'' he said. ``There is no leadership
gift within me. There has never been an occasion where I could walk
into a room and light it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Deciding that he would have to ``audit politics without taking
the course,'' Bradley, in 1997, bought the National Journal Group
of publications and began his second career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before he hooked up with Bradley, Kelly had a long, strange
trip. Also raised in Washington, he is the son of liberal community
activists who worked in the newspaper business. (His mother,
Marguerite Kelly, still writes a syndicated parenting column.)
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from UNH in 1979, Kelly got a job scheduling
guests for ``Good Morning America.'' In the early '80s he moved to
The Cincinnati Post and then to The Sun in Baltimore, where he
covered Michael S. Dukakis's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly met his wife, Madelyn, then a CNN producer, on that
campaign, and followed her to Chicago, where he struggled as a
freelancer until the Gulf War came along. He covered that conflict
for The Boston Globe and The New Republic, which won him a National
Magazine Award for reporting. ``It was the first time I had ever
written anything that I thought was good,'' he said. (He later
wrote a book on the war called ``Martyrs' Day.'')
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was then hired to cover the 1992 presidential campaign by
The New York Times. Two years later, he moved to The New Yorker to
write its ``Letter from Washington,'' a stint marred by fractious
relations between Kelly and a Clinton-adoring staff member, Sidney
Blumenthal, who went to work at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Peretz offered Kelly the job of editing The New
Republic, his respected journal of opinion. By that time, Kelly was
becoming known as a fierce Clinton critic, a view enunciated in a
1994 piece on the president's flawed character for The New York
Times Sunday magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly says his upbringing was ``moralistic, but moralistic in
the political sense, not the religious sense. . . . What I objected
to'' with Clinton, he said, ``was really one thing, honesty. It was
always the lying that mattered to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers wondered whether Kelly, who continued to pound the
White House in his New Republic column, could mesh with Peretz, who
had a well-known fondness for Vice President Al Gore. In nine
months, the answer was clear. Kelly was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly says he was dismissed three days after he vetoed Peretz's
effort to insert an unsigned ``Notebook'' item into the magazine
defending Gore against allegations of campaign finance violations.
Peretz says Kelly was a very good ``line editor,'' but ``not a big
ideas person'' and ``obsessive'' in his criticism of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that I loved to edit, loved to play with ideas and
writers,'' Kelly said of his tenure there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he sought out the former New Republic editor, Bradley knew
of Kelly's sharp-edged commentary. ``You'd assume he was sort of
nasty,'' Bradley said. Kelly ``has a gift that I could not
understand from the political writing I had seen.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, after the National Journal editor Steve Smith left for
US News &AMP; World Report and Kelly replaced him on an interim basis,
Bradley presented him with a crucial decision. Bradley had dreams
of a ``Henry Luce moment'' and of starting his own high-end
general-interest magazine. He asked for Kelly's long-term
commitment to follow him on that journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never plotted out my life in anything remotely like those
lengths of time,'' said Kelly, who waited several months before
agreeing to Bradley's request. But ``I knew he was good for his
word, I knew he was serious about building and creating magazines
and editorial businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a month and a half ago, after lengthy negotiations
interrupted by an illness that robbed him of his voice, the largely
unknown Bradley became the surprise owner of The Atlantic Monthly.
(He now jokes how ``it's the saddest thing'' that his mother has
been able to fill only four pages of her new scrapbook with
clippings about Bradley.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very elegant moment,'' he said, ``to figure out if we
can understand this business.''
</P>
<P>
   The best reason for optimism at The Atlantic may be the National
Journal. Under Bradley, the editorial budget nearly doubled, said
the president and publisher, John Fox Sullivan. And Kelly hired 25
new editorial people in two years. Sullivan said that at the first
major strategy meeting he convened after buying the journal,
Bradley told his executives: ``Let's not worry about the money.
Let's figure out how to make it the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also seems to be talking about pouring resources into
his new acquisition _ at least for the near future. ``I think I
should be prepared, if need be, to lose a couple million a year
with The Atlantic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his new North End office, Kelly is surrounded by
manuscripts and a flow chart of The Atlantic's operations. While
trying to get up to speed, he suggests that some changes _ from
expanding the number of pages to new graphics to more emphasis on
books _ are in the offing. He walks a fine line, suggesting changes
to the magazine but promising not to alter its mission and
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reader's magazine,'' he said. ``It needs to be a
magazine for people who are passionate about reading and passionate
about writing. It has made a home for pieces that are allowed to
stand on their own for great writing. They're not buzz driven or
celebrity driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some observers wonder whether Kelly, with his Beltway
background, is a good fit for a big-ideas magazine. Peretz has
asked whether a Washington journalist with a newspaper background
understands The Atlantic ``sensibility.'' But the outgoing Atlantic
editor, William Whitworth, seems reassured. One night over dinner,
he and Kelly talked about ``the kind of journalism we admire, the
kind of writers we admire. . . . In that sense, we were in the same
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   From when they first met, Bradley said, he sensed that what
Kelly ``really wanted was to be editor of The New Yorker.'' The
Atlantic's new owner has not quite handed his editor that
opportunity. But only a few years after engaging him in a unique
journalistic partnership, he has come remarkably close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
