<P>
   DRUCKER-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ Corporate America and Peter
Ferdinand Drucker have fallen out of favor with each other.
Drucker, who turns 90 on Friday, still has his disciples, but at
the bleeding edge of business the old master's lifework is commonly
seen as simplistic, portentous, off the mark, idealistic, out of
date. Not for 20 years have the corporate world's heavy hitters
hung on his every word. For his part, The Man Who Invented
Management (a biographer's apt label) disdains a corporate order
that is in thrall to stock prices and that rewards its chief
executives as though they were power forwards. By Fred Andrews.
</P>
