<HEADLINE>
BRECKENRIDGE PICTURES ITSELF AS PLACE WHERE OIL GUSHED AND FOOTBALL
THRIVED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRECKENRIDGE, Texas _ Driving through this West Texas town, it
is apparent that there was once a bigger community here.
</P>
<P>
   Breckenridge is a respectable town, big enough for a couple of
banks, several feed stores and a line of merchants along the main
drag. It calls itself ``The Dynamo of West Texas'' and it is
scrubbed and cleaned, well-marked and colorful.
</P>
<P>
   But the muscular-looking Stephens County Courthouse appears
bigger than it should for a town this size. The bank with the big
``B'' on top is taller than you would expect.
</P>
<P>
   Breckenridge was once a boomtown well beyond its current size.
</P>
<P>
   Oil was discovered in the nearby Ranger field in 1916 and in the
next four years, exploration spread north. In 1920, Breckenridge
exploded from 1,500 residents to more than 10,000, and an estimated
200 wells were drilled within the city limits. The boom lasted only
a few years, and now the town has a more stable population of about
5,500. But signs of the boom are still there. You can see them
painted on the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The largest mural is on the side of a vacant building at Court
Street and Walker, which is U.S. 180 running through the heart of
town. The painting is huge _ a half-block long and 2 stories high _
done in black and white and various shades of gray. The scene is a
football field, surrounded by townsfolk hanging on every free inch
of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   The band and student body take up the grandstands; the teams are
on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Hovering above the playing field, in a nearly transparent white,
are ghostly figures of players from the past. The mural is titled
The Spirit of the Buckaroos, in honor of the local high school
team.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, minus the ghost players, is taken from a 1924 photo.
There is a panel on the side that chronicles the Buckaroos'
successes. It says the team was state co-champion in 1929 and 1959,
and state champ in 1951, '52, '54, and '58.
</P>
<P>
   There are six murals in all. The most popular is a 1923 street
scene painted behind the drive-through of First American Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our first black and white and it's lighted at
night,'' said Shelly Hargrove, manager of Main Street Breckenridge.
``People love that one. It is the closest to the original
photograph of any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Older residents especially enjoy the murals, she said. ``Some of
them actually remember what Breckenridge was like back then. It
really stirs up the history of this town.''
</P>
<P>
   Breckenridge's murals were recognized Friday as the state's best
public improvement project by the Texas Downtown Association at its
conference in Houston. Artist Billy Ines painted all six murals and
although Hargrove said Breckenridge has three more planned for him,
he might be hard to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were in Houston for the award, there was a line of
people waiting to talk to him,'' she said. ``Nacogdoches,
Gatesville, Brenham, Quanah ... and I get calls almost weekly from
places around here, Throckmorton, Graham and Eastland. They all
want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remind him he still has work to do right here. We
have a lot more history.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
