<HEADLINE>
SOME LESSONS ARE COSTLIER THAN OTHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Since student loans have been introduced, what percentage
have been paid off and what percentage of students have defaulted
altogether?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.M., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: As of November 1997, 35.4 percent of the borrowed money has
been paid off and 8.8 percent was given to recipients who
defaulted, according to congressional testimony by David A.
Longanecker of the Office of Postsecondary Education.
</P>
<P>
   Longanecker testified that the federal government had made $285
billion in higher education loans to students and parents since
1959.
</P>
<P>
   Of these loans, $101 billion has been repaid and $68 billion was
loaned to students who are still in school. In the remaining $116
billion due to be repaid, $25 billion was loaned to students who
have defaulted on their obligation.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Department of Education began removing schools from
loan eligibility if too many students defaulted, the yearly default
rate has dropped from 22 percent in 1990 to 8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I send Payne Stewart's wife a card of condolence
and a personal note?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.B., Hurst, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Stewart's family in care of the First Orlando
Foundation, First Baptist Church of Orlando, 3000 S. John Young
Pkwy., Orlando, FL 32805-6691.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions in Stewart's honor can be made to the Payne
Stewart Memorial Fund at the same address.
</P>
<P>
   The First Orlando Foundation is a nonprofit group organized by
the church in 1988 to support its ministries. Stewart, who attended
services there, donated $500,000 a few weeks before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Rupert Everett is scheduled to do a film opposite Madonna.
When is it expected to be released?
</P>
<P>
   _ Y.N., Dallas
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The Next Best Thing,'' a comedy/drama that also stars
Benjamin Bratt and Illeana Douglas, has finished filming and is
scheduled for March 2000 release.
</P>
<P>
   It's the 24th film directed by John Schlesinger, who won an
Academy Award in 1970 for ``Midnight Cowboy'' and was nominated for
``Darling'' and ``Sunday Bloody Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
