<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      11-16 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE, WATER SHIELD SHOULD GO OVER BARE SHEATHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for Ocala, Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am having my house reroofed, using 22 squares (2,200 square
feet) of shingles to go over one layer of old shingles. Bids ranged
from $3,200 to $4,000 and included new ridge vents. Continuous
soffit vents would be $400 more. Stripping added $1,800 to $2,000.
I am not objecting to the price, but one roofer recommended putting
Ice &AMP; Water Shield over the old shingles. Is that a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   PAT DELEO, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. In a word, no. The Ice &AMP; Water Shield is a rubberized
membrane set along the edge of the roof 3 to 6 feet up from the
roof edge, and is intended to prevent leaking from water backed up
by ice dams. The Ice &AMP; Water Shield should go over bare wood
sheathing to make it stick to the sheathing and lie flat, so enough
shingles should be removed to allow this. Even the manufacturer,
W.R. Grace, suggests that its shield go over bare sheathing.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, you certainly have no complaint about the bids;
they are all bargains. The low bid is less than $1.50 per square
foot, and the high is less than $2. If the work is of good quality,
you can't get any better. Those soffit vents for $400 are also a
good buy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I relocated several windows and doors and, as a result, had
to reshingle around those moved windows and doors; the shingles are
white cedar Extras, and, needless to say, they differ from the
weathered shingles that remained on the house. How can I make the
new shingles look like the old?
</P>
<P>
   JACK ALDRICH, Shrewsbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You have three choices. No, four. The first and easiest is to
sit back and wait for the new shingles to weather. You are a little
inland for rapid weathering, which occurs fastest in a marine
environment, but in two years no one will see the difference. The
other choices require coating the entire house, or at least the
wall where the changes were made, with:
</P>
<P>
   1. Bleaching oil, which will hasten weathering and make the
color more even.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bleaching stain, which produces a rather distinct gray color,
not much like weathering.
</P>
<P>
   3. Semitransparent stain, which provides a color other than the
weathered look.
</P>
<P>
   Short of leaving everything alone and tolerating the different
colors, I suggest using the bleaching oil. Only one coat is needed
forever. The others also need only one coat, but require recoating
every five years or so.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Hi, handyman, remember me? I'm the one who was looking for
five-eighths-inch ball bearings for my glider. You found the
bearings in the McMaster-Carr catalog, and I appreciate that, but I
also found the catalog on the Net at www.mcmaster.com, and received
the needed bearings in a short time.
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS EVANS, Franklin, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since there was no question, there is no answer, except the
handyman's appreciation of the information, which he immediately
put in his file. Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am putting in 6 inches of fiberglass insulation in my
cellar ceiling, with the vapor barrier paper up, touching the
ceiling above. What about all those wires and pipes in the ceiling;
should they be covered?
</P>
<P>
   ANTHONY COSTELLO, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If they are near the ceiling or between the joists, cover
them; if they are at the bottom of the joists, don't; it is simply
not practical to do so. Covering the pipes will provide insulation
so they will not freeze in the cold cellar, made colder by
insulating the ceiling. If you are concerned about no access to the
pipes and wires if they need repair, don't be. It is unlikely that
they will fail; after all, the wires and pipes in other walls and
ceilings of the house are inaccessible, and how many times have you
had to fix them? It would not hurt to insulate any exposed pipes
with foam tube insulation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My metal bulkhead doors have 7 1/2-inch-wide exterior plywood
on each side so the doors can cover the oversized opening. The
plywood does not hold paint. Can I cover it with aluminum?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK SHEA, Marblehead, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I told you on the phone that the aluminum will not hold
paint, but on second thought, you can cover the plywood with
aluminum and paint it, and keep painting it whenever it needs it.
Or, let the aluminum weather; it will turn a dull gray, which may
nor may not be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The plywood should hold paint, but it may not be doing so
because it is punky or because there are too many coats of paint
already on it. The second reason it is not holding paint is the
slope, which allows rain water to wear off the paint.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you can try is to replace the plywood with a 1 x 8
pressure-treated board on each side. Let the boards weather. Or,
stain them with one coat of a semitransparent stain. It will erode,
but you'll need only one coat every three to five years, and it
will not peel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know that driveway sealer is mostly cosmetic, but I plan to
seal my driveway to fill the cracks. Will sealer fill cracks?
</P>
<P>
   AXEL WIRTH, Amherst, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sealer will fill cracks an eighth-inch and smaller; it will
not do very well on cracks a quarter-inch or wider. Fill the wider
cracks with driveway crack filler, sold in caulking cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   Filling the cracks either way helps keep water from getting into
the cracks and then freezing in winter, making them wider. But it
is not critical to the life of the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
