<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      11-16 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A KNICK REBORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Public Interests)  
 (af)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let's hear it for the athlete as president!'' said John
McEnroe to the Bill Bradley rally at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   We had to get there eventually. Every American who lived through
high school has been programmed to regard the star player as a
superior species. What's amazing is that it's taken the athletes so
long to decide that, as natural winners, they ought to be running
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill Bradley, hopefully, has been pretty selective in
terms of the celebrities that he has asked to jump on board,'' said
Bob Cousy, the former Celtic, in an interesting example of
celebrity snobbism. ``So the point is: If we're all pretty good
guys and we've lived our lives properly, then, hey, why don't you
listen to us in this case and vote for Bill Bradley?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it might work for motor oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's early presidential campaign was a long lope away from
his years with the New York Knicks. I once asked him whether he
thought the NBA players' strike would be over in time to save the
season, and he said he didn't much care. Campaigning, he gave the
impression he'd gone directly from a small town on the Mississippi
River to the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But now he's getting back in touch with his inner jock. In the
process he's putting his long arm around thousands of male fans,
some of whom began to look like teenagers gawking at Ricky Martin.
A team of all-star Bradley supporters, led by the likes of Bill
Russell, blitzed the Sunday morning talk shows to extol his honesty
and team spirit, and left Tim Russert grinning like a pom-pom guy.
Who cares who has the best health care plan? The idea of being pals
with Walt Frazier and Julius Erving is beyond ultra-cool, far
better than eight years as anybody's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he secretly likes it or not, being a basketball player
is Bradley's unique selling point, the thing that separates him
from the other serious, intelligent Democratic senators of the
world who got their letters in high school track. Kids today have
no idea who he was, but a whole lot of middle-aged white men grew
up watching him play, identifying with the way he compensated for a
lousy jump and lack of speed. Happily for Bradley, these are now
the exact same people who run Wall Street and make campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   So there he was last weekend, helping his former teammates
re-create a moment from the last game of the 1970 NBA playoffs,
passing the ball to Willis Reed for the basket. (It was not exactly
a you-are-there experience. The candidate did his dribbling in a
blue suit.) Sitting on the sidelines, he listened to testimonials
from superstars of the past _ (italics)select(end italics)
superstars, of course, like Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and John Havlicek.
(Al Gore, who should really stop competing in this game, announced
Monday that he had snagged the endorsement of Michael Jordan's
mother.)
</P>
<P>
   But the pro-Bradley testimonials were not particularly
convincing, unless you're one of those people who believe
professional athletics builds character. Lots of players said they
remembered Bradley, who was not the Knicks' leader, for his
leadership. Jerry Lucas talked about how he and the candidate used
to have ``audio codes that nobody understood but us,'' in a tone
that suggested they were in communication with alien messengers.
Bill Walton delivered his own personal brand of political analysis.
(``Freedom is so much more than telling kids it's all about smoking
and carrying AK-47s.'')
</P>
<P>
   Success in sports has actually been a shortcut into politics for
some time now _ it sometimes appeared that the entire House
Republican caucus consisted of former college quarterbacks. But a
basketball player-politician is pretty unusual, and perhaps
Bradley's experience playing in what was already becoming a black
sport has made him sensitive to racial issues. The fact that his
black fellow players feel that's true may be the only important
thing that we can learn from his sports career.
</P>
<P>
   My own favorite story was Frazier's description of how, when
they shared a room in the days before TV remote control, Bradley
would sit at the end of the bed hunched over the set, obsessively
changing channels. (``He never said, `Hey, Clyde, are you looking
at that?''') If being good at basketball signifies presidential
character, what does hogging the TV set mean?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1537EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
