A1518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SCHOOLS-POLL17-COX     11-16 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-POLL17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MANY PARENTS WON'T SEND KIDS TO A BETTER SCHOOL
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Would you rather send your child to a good school
near your home, or a better school that is pretty difficult to get
to?
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-four percent of parents chose the better school and 40
percent chose the closest school in a national survey released
Tuesday by Public Agenda.
</P>
<P>
   That surprised the pollsters, who thought that even more parents
would choose the better school, said Steve Farkas, chief researcher
at the nonprofit polling organization in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   To find out why 40 percent of the 394 parents favored
convenience, they interviewed another 208 parents this summer in
areas where many parents already have a choice of schools. The
places were Cleveland and Milwaukee, which give some parents
vouchers for tuition in private schools, and Arizona and Michigan,
where many public charter schools compete with the regular public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that academic excellence is not the only thing
that parents take into account when deciding where their children
should go to school,'' Farkas said.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents gave three main reasons for settling for second
best: the child's safety, the child's feelings, and the family's
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of parents wanted a school to be close enough to let them
``show up right away'' in an emergency, Farkas said.
</P>
<P>
   Black parents in Milwaukee were wary of suggestions that they
send their children to better schools outside the city. Some
worried that suburbanites might not make their children feel
``welcome and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The third factor was simply a matter of convenience,'' Farkas
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If both parents commute, many are already stretched getting
everything together and everybody off to the right school and
job,'' he said. ``They hesitate to take the extra hour to get up
earlier so a student can go to another school that's far away.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
