<HEADER>
A1521 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DARK-THANKSGIVING-NYT     11-16 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARK-THANKSGIVING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN'S PARADOXICAL THANKSGIVING VISION ECHOES THE PSALMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``In everything give thanks,'' St. Paul advised in his letter to
the Thessalonians in the Christian New Testament.
 &HT;    With a booming stock market, high employment, the frontier-like
energy of cyberspace and millennial optimism, it is easy to follow
Paul's dictum as we pause for our yearly Thanksgiving celebration.
 &HT;    There's that nagging Y2K computer glitch problem, but otherwise?
This Thanksgiving seems the harbinger of a prosperous new century.
 &HT;    Americans tend to equate Thanksgiving with material prosperity.
``Dear God,'' runs our national prayer, ``Thank you for everything
we have. And bless all those poor people who don't have as much as
we do. Amen.''
 &HT;    Paul's words, ``in everything give thanks,'' serve as a
discomforting reminder for our national celebration. ``Everything''
means giving thanks in all circumstances: good and bad, rich or
poor, health or illness, peace or war. In all things, give thanks
to God.
 &HT;    Although New Englanders have celebrated it since 1630,
Thanksgiving Day only became a national holiday in 1863 when, in
the midst of the Civil War, Abraham Lincoln instituted it as a
yearly celebration.
 &HT;    In 1863 the war was a stalemate. Generals won battles and lost
them. The Union gained ground in the West; the Confederacy held
firm in the East. On both sides, troops deserted the army.
 &HT;    Civilians tired of the whole thing. In the summer of 1863,
antiwar riots broke out in Boston and Richmond. Even that year's
Emancipation Proclamation failed to rally expected popular and
political support. General Sherman urged Lincoln to turn the
conflict into total war: ``If need be, take every life, every acre
of land.''
 &HT;    In his annual message to Congress that year, Lincoln himself
showed the war's strain. Ill, lacking his usual insight, and
suffering from recurring nightmares, the president stated that
``Under the sharp discipline of civil war, the nation is beginning
a new life.'' But what new life? Lincoln did not say. It was too
dark for even the usually visionary president to see.
 &HT;    Although hope was obscured, Lincoln still issued his
Thanksgiving Day Proclamation echoing St. Paul's command: ``in
everything give thanks.'' Until World War II, there was no worse
season in American history than the fall of 1863. Give thanks? For
what? Political crises, death, uncertainty, war?
 &HT;    And to whom? Certainly God could not be thanked for such
suffering. America's traditional Protestant God seemed far away.
Countless citizens turned to alternative beliefs -- such as atheism
and spiritualism -- to try to answer the difficult questions raised
by the war.
 &HT;    Lincoln, mired in his own internal religious struggles,
nevertheless believed that human affairs unfolded under the rule of
God. God's will, however imperfectly understood or recognized, was
working itself out through the conflict.
 &HT;    Lincoln did not identify God's cause with that of the Union
Army. Instead, he understood himself as a sinful servant upon whom
God's judgment rested. The only ``side'' is God's. Human beings can
only approximate it.
 &HT;    Therefore, the North should not only give thanks for great
military victories. Rather, the nation should give thanks because,
however mysteriously, God's will was being accomplished through the
suffering. From evil, good. From death, life. Give thanks because
God is found in and through all things.
 &HT;    Lincoln's paradoxical Thanksgiving vision echoes that of the
Psalms in the Hebrew Bible. ``Give thanks to the Lord, for he is
good; for his steadfast love endures forever.'' The Psalms portray
the full range of human experience. Joy, anger, love, hatred, fear,
prosperity, suffering, victory, rage. But they consistently give
thanks to God for everything from God's gracious provision to God's
presence in the midst of evil. In everything, give thanks.
 &HT;    Thankfulness places us rightly before God. By thanking God in
all circumstances, we are reminded we are not ultimately in
control. When we have much, prosperity is a gift. When we have
little, we rest in God's comfort.
 &HT;    Thankfulness is an attitude of mind that keeps us from thinking
too highly of our achievements or thinking too little of our worth
as God's children. Thankfulness breeds the contentment that,
whatever the circumstance, God is with and for us.
 &HT;    This Thanksgiving, give thanks. Not because we invested in the
right stock. But because God is with us, even in the midst of our
prosperity. God has not abandoned America to material success but
is, mercifully and persistently, calling us to remember who we
really are.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
