<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-FILM-SKIN-630-SFCHRON     11-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SKIN-630-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FACE TO FACE WITH THE STARS: A dermatologist sizes up  celebrities,
warts and all, on his Web site  
 By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dermatologist Vail Reese has two passions _ skin
and the movies. The result: A Web site devoted to both.
</P>
<P>
   Skinema (www.skinema.com) is a 3-year-old site on which Reese
analyzes movies and movie stars in terms of skin, hair and nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved film,'' says Reese, 35, who as a youngster
studied at American Conservatory Theater's Young Conservatory and
considered becoming an actor.
</P>
<P>
   But his Web site, he says, is more than entertainment. It serves
a medical purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in residency,'' says Reese, ``doctors always used W.C.
Fields as an example of a condition called acne rosacea _ it's an
adult form of acne which is not caused by alcohol, though it can be
made worse by alcohol. Dermatologists would say, `If we're not
aggressive about treating this, you could end up looking like W.C.
Fields.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Naming an actor gives the patient an immediate visual memory _
you know, `A picture's worth a thousand words.' So I thought, why
not use actors to illustrate other skin conditions, which I see
routinely?''
</P>
<P>
   Reese, who has been in practice for five years, goes to the
movies regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a cliche in movies that skin conditions are used
to show evil characters,'' he says. ``Most of the time it's
scarring, sometimes albinism. When a movie has an evil character
suffering from albinism, my patients deal with the aftermath for
weeks _ they get extra stares. Part of the point of the Web site is
to educate people.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinema has no advertising and is done as a ``nonprofit hobby,''
says Reese. ``I'd rather keep it pure.''
</P>
<P>
   What follows is the skinny on Hollywood skin, according to
Reese:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Madonna: &LR;  ``She has adult acne. So does Cameron Diaz and
Vanessa Williams. Patients who have adult acne feel better when I
let them know that stars like Madonna and Cameron Diaz have the
same condition.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Robert Redford: &LR;  ``Here is a classic example of the effect of
the sun _ furrows, wrinkles, discoloration. The bumps on Redford's
chin are protuberant flesh-colored nodules, moles that have grown
inward.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Matt Damon: &LR;  ``He has a lot of moles _ all over his neck and
back. You can see them in `Good Will Hunting' when he takes off his
shirt. They are not skin cancer, but having so many does increase
the risk of melanoma. He needs to have them checked regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Minnie Driver and Julianne Moore: &LR;  ``Both are fair-skinned
actresses who have sun spots that are indications of sun damage.
Moore says she is wearing sunblock these days, which is a good
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Winona Ryder: &LR;  ``Winona Ryder, Christina Ricci and Kate
Winslet are part of a new generation going for a fair look. There
is no question these women are considered attractive. Hopefully,
they signal a new generation's attitude toward sun exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in contrast to people like George Hamilton and Warren
Beatty, who influenced a generation to have `a healthy tan,' which
is anything but healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; James Woods: &LR;  ``He has acne scarring, which you see in a lot
of male actors who are rugged types _ Tommy Lee Jones, Dennis
Farina, Ray Liotta. It is rarely seen in actresses, though
Elizabeth Hurley has some mild acne scarring that's mostly hidden
by makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Jean-Claude Van Damme: &LR;  ``He has a bump on his right
forehead. It's most likely a lipoma _ a benign growth of fat cells.
One wonders why he hasn't had it removed. A little scar on his
forehead might fit more with his rugged image.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Catherine Zeta-Jones: &LR;  ``She has a vertical line-like scar on
her neck from a tracheotomy. As a child, she had severe pneumonia
and a tube was inserted into her windpipe to help her breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michael Jackson: &LR;  ``Vitiligo is a condition in which the
immune system attacks the skin and removes color in patches. Skin
slowly fades over the years. What Jackson has does not appear to be
vitiligo, though it could be that he does have it and uses makeup
to even out the skin tone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
