<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-2TAKES     11-16 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE APPETITE WAITS FOR NO BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the most challenging part of cooking Thanksgiving
dinner is deciding what to serve until the turkey is carved. You
need some kind of diversionary starter for everyone to nibble at
while the lumps are being mashed out of the potatoes and whisked
out of the gravy, but it can't be anything really rich or heavy or
filling, or no one will ever make it to the pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   And it certainly can't be anything that takes more than a few
ingredients and a couple of steps to assemble on a day when even
the best cook feels overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   You could just go out and buy a few sneaky convenience foods,
but the flavors would seem off before a meal that celebrates real
home cooking. A better way to give the appearance of being a
generous and caring cook without becoming a galley slave is to
choose from some quick, simple and surprisingly different starters
based on ideas borrowed from classic hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of these takes more than 15 minutes of work, most of
them far less. They are all familiar enough to serve to
unadventurous relatives on this all-American holiday, but each one
has a little twist.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps my favorite is real onion dip, ideally served with
potato chips but almost as good with calorie-deficient raw
vegetables. Ever since Lipton took over the supermarket aisle,
onion dip has been routinely made with powdered onion soup mix.
Even in cookbooks you find recipes like, ``Stir 3 tablespoons onion
soup mix into 1 cup sour cream.'' There had to be a way to make it
simple without opening up a packet full of mystery ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to me that the original idea was to imitate the
dominant flavor of onion soup _ caramelized onions _ so I tried
doing exactly that. I minced some onions, cooked them in oil until
they were well browned and then stirred them into sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fresh, three-ingredient dip (if you count the oil,
which you drain), with clarity, intensity and complexity of flavor.
(You can make and serve this right away, but the onion taste
intensifies if you allow it to sit, refrigerated, for about a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, I decided I could improve on the standard recipe for
shrimp cocktail sauce, which I always found thin and uninspired.
Without departing too far from the original, made with Heinz chili
sauce, I came up with a richer, tastier cocktail sauce by borrowing
an idea from the famed French chef Joel Robuchon, who adds a little
butter.
</P>
<P>
   That not only makes the sauce cling to the shrimp better, but
makes it taste equally good warm or cold. (I like it warm, just as
a contrast to the cold shrimp.)
</P>
<P>
   Three other Thanksgiving tidbits I developed are even easier,
starting with marinated olives. All you have to do is toss a
variety of olives in olive oil, garlic and herbs; let them stand an
hour; then stand back while guests ask incredulously, ``What did
you do with these?''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of a fragrant, tangy lemon cut into segments makes
them even more special. But the real key is to use an assortment of
good olives, preferably the kind produced in France, Italy, Greece
or Spain and sold in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, include some oil-cured olives, which really come to
life when marinated. You can marinate the olives up to a week in
advance if you like.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually warm fall this year inspired another super-simple
appetizer. Fresh figs are still in produce markets _ and still
ripening in California _ and they can be halved and stuffed with
any creamy, flavorful cheese. Usually I rely on a good blue, but
creamy goat cheese, drizzled with balsamic vinegar, is more
crowd-pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I wanted a simple, light dipping sauce for raw
vegetables, so I warmed olive oil with garlic, freshened the mix
with uncooked olive oil, seasoned it with lots of salt and pepper
and spiked it with lemon rind. The flavors go great with fennel,
one of the easiest of vegetables to convert into crudites.
</P>
<P>
   Just trim the bulb by cutting off the bottom half-inch or so,
then stand it up on its flat end and slice downward to make thin
strips. Stack the slices and cut into dipping sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could just open up a bag of baby carrots and serve them
with that homemade aromatic oil. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FIGS STUFFED WITH GOAT CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces, approximately, of soft, fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon good balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   12 fresh figs, washed and drained. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Use fingers to roll the goat cheese into 24 small balls, each
{ inch or less in diameter. Place them on a plate, and drizzle with
vinegar. Shake gently to coat evenly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut figs in half. Press a cheese ball into the center of each
fig; as they are stuffed, return them, stuffed side up, to the
plate where the cheese was coated in vinegar. Serve within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REAL SOUR CREAM ONION DIP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup neutral oil, like canola or grape seed
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, minced, about { cup
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place oil in an 8-inch skillet, and turn heat to medium-high.
When it's hot, a minute or two later, add onion, salt and sugar.
Cook, shaking pan occasionally, until onion browns, about 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour onion and oil into a fine strainer; reserve oil in
refrigerator for another use. Stir onion into sour cream. If time
allows, cover and refrigerate for 24 hours. Serve with potato chips
or raw vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MARINATED OLIVES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, largely unattended &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6 cups assorted olives
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, peeled and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh thyme or rosemary leaves (or 1 teaspoon
crumbled dried leaves)
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, cut in half and pulp removed as you would from a
grapefruit. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toss together all ingredients in a bowl. Marinate at room
temperature for at least an hour, or as long as 12 hours. Before
serving, marinated olives may be refrigerated, but they should be
removed from refrigerator an hour or two before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FENNEL WITH OLIVE OIL DIPPING SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Minced zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. For the dipping sauce, combine half the olive oil and garlic
in a small saucepan and turn heat to medium-low. Cook, shaking pan
occasionally, until garlic begins to sizzle. Remove garlic from oil
and pan from heat. Add cold oil to pan along with salt, pepper and
lemon zest to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Trim fennel and cut into thin strips. Serve with dipping
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: At least 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLD SHRIMP WITH WARM COCKTAIL SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds large shrimp, peeled and deveined if desired
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons horseradish, or to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place the shrimp in a saucepan large enough to hold them
comfortably. Add enough cold water to cover them. Turn the heat to
high and bring the water to a boil. Cover the saucepan, remove it
from the heat and let the shrimp sit 10 minutes. Drain the shrimp
in a colander or through a sieve. Place in a large shallow bowl and
chill completely. (Or, if you're in a hurry, you can just run the
shrimp under cold running water to cool them off.)
</P>
<P>
   2. To make the sauce, combine the ketchup, the vinegar and the
butter in a small saucepan. Mix them well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook the sauce over medium-low heat, stirring occasionally,
until the butter is completely melted. (At this point, you can keep
the sauce warm for more than an hour, but keep the heat under it as
low as possible.) Add horseradish to taste.
</P>
<P>
   4. Serve the cold shrimp with the sauce, warm or cold.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: At least 10 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
