<HEADLINE>
CONCERNED ABOUT INFLATION, FED RAISES INTEREST RATES BY 0.25
PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Reserve raised interest rates by a
quarter of a percentage point Tuesday, saying that the combination
of strong growth and low unemployment had left the economy
vulnerable to an outbreak of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time this year that the central bank has raised
rates to check the economy's momentum, and signaled that the Fed's
growing faith in technology to improve business efficiency and
temper inflationary pressures has its limits.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining its action, the Fed emphasized a concern that Alan
Greenspan, its chairman, has raised in recent months: that the
economy is literally running out of workers, and that pressure to
raise wages and then prices will inevitably mount.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said it was raising its benchmark federal funds target
rate on overnight loans between banks to 5.5 percent from 5.25
percent. The move completed a process of reversing the three
quarter-point reductions in the Fed funds rate last year in
response to the financial crisis that spread from Asia to Russia
and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank also said it would increase its largely
symbolic discount rates on loans to financial institutions from the
Federal Reserve system to 5 percent from 4.75 percent. It was the
second quarter-point increase in the rate this year after two
quarter-point reductions last year.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the Fed's official short-term rates quickly
began to ripple out into the longer-term rates paid by businesses
and consumers. Banks quickly began raising their prime lending rate
by a quarter of a point, to 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed said the cumulative effect of this year's rate increases
should ``markedly diminish the risk of inflation going forward,''
and that it had removed its formal policy of leaning toward further
rate increases in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took the statement to mean that the Fed was likely to
hold rates steady at its next meeting, on Dec. 21, and probably for
at least a month or two into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been sharply divided over whether the Fed would
tighten policy at its meeting Tuesday. And they said beforehand
that the outcome would go a long way toward defining the degree to
which the central bank believes huge business investments in
efficiency-enhancing computers and other technology can keep costs
under control and avert an inflationary buildup of wage and price
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed did not provide any details of its internal debate. But
its statement, issued shortly after 2:15 p.m., suggested that it is
by no means ready to abandon its traditional fear of inflation,
even though by most measures inflation remains hard to find even in
the face of persistently strong growth and historically low levels
of joblessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although cost pressures appear generally contained, risks to
sustainable growth persist,'' the Fed's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite tentative evidence of slowing in certain
interest-sensitive sectors of the economy and of accelerating
productivity, the expansion of activity continues in excess of the
economy's growth potential,'' the statement said. ``As a
consequence, the pool of available workers willing to take jobs has
been drawn down further in recent months, a trend that must
eventually be contained if inflationary imbalances are to remain in
check and economic expansion continue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
