<HEADLINE>
CHICKEN WITH ALL DARK MEAT  
 SAVING LIMA BEAN SKINS  
 SERVING YOGURT LIQUID 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I spotted a ``black chicken'' for sale in Chinatown that
looked dark purple. What is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Black chicken (zook see gai), also known as silky chicken or
black-meat chicken, is a game bird weighing 1{ to 2 pounds that
originally comes from China. The skin of the bird ranges in color
from deep gray to inky purple to black, and the flesh beneath is
dark and flavorful. In the United States, black chickens are bred
in South Carolina and Pennsylvania and can be found for sale in
Chinese meat markets.
</P>
<P>
   Black chicken is believed by the Chinese to be extremely
healthful and is often made into soup. A recipe can be found in
``The Wisdom of the Chinese Kitchen'' by Grace Young (Simon and
Schuster, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you cook dried lima beans so that they stay whole
without shedding their skins?
</P>
<P>
   A: Beans that lose their skins usually do so when they are
overcooked. A simple remedy might be to pull the beans from the
heat a few minutes earlier than you usually do. Beans should be
cooked until they are just tender all the way through, but not at
all mushy. A trick to see if your beans are done is to remove a few
with a slotted spoon and blow on them. The skins should easily
break open.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is to skip the presoaking step, and simply cook the
dried lima beans at a slow simmer until they are just tender. It
also helps to cook beans in plenty of water so that they have room
to float around without colliding, which can loosen the skins and
cause the beans to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the liquid that separates out at the top of a
refrigerated container of yogurt contain any nutrients? Should I
drain it off or stir it back in?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The liquid does contain traces of the same proteins, live
bacterial cultures and nutrients found in the solid part of yogurt.
If you want to get the most from your yogurt nutritionally, stir it
back in. This will also give the yogurt a little bit of a looser,
runnier consistency. Conversely, pouring off the liquid leaves a
slightly creamier yogurt. Taken several steps further, many recipes
call for purposely draining away much of the liquid, which gives
yogurt a thick, spreadable consistency. Since the amount of
nutrients in question is small, it's really a matter of taste
whether to stir or drain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
