<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-PECAN-TART-ART-NYT &LR;      11-16 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PECAN-TART-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOO-FREE PECAN PIE, STRIPPED DOWN TO ITS CRISP ESSENTIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minimalism is sometimes a very good thing, especially when it
comes to the pecan pie. Anne Rosenzweig's version, which she serves
at the Lobster Club in Manhattan, is the perfect example: just a
crisp square of puff pastry topped with a thin layer of molten
caramel and toasted pecans. It's served hot, right out of the oven,
with a jaunty finish _ a little cube of vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Rosenzweig has done, of course, is reinvent the heavy
Southern classic as a golden, fragile tart. This fall, she took a
look at the traditional pie and decided that needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things that are wrong with it,'' she said.
Namely, the crust and the filling. The pecans were faultless, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   So she eliminated the crust and the filling and came up with a
version so thin and light that it shatters in the mouth and proves
once again that less can be more.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant the tart is $7, but it can easily be made at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The components can even be put together a day in advance: put
the baked puff pastry in plastic wrap, and leave it overnight at
room temperature. Store the caramel sauce in a plastic squeeze
bottle in the refrigerator. The next day, put the bottle into a pot
of boiling water and heat it for 5 to 10 minutes _ just until the
syrup softens. Assemble the tart, and bake.
</P>
<P>
   To get cubes of ice cream, Ms. Rosenzweig recommends using a hot
knife to cut them from a block. Lay the little cubes on a cookie
sheet, and keep them frozen until you're ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   CRACKLING THIN TART WITH PECANS AND STICKY CARAMEL
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Lobster Club
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the caramel sauce:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   { cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   For the pastry and assembly:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 5-by-5-inch puff pastry squares
</P>
<P>
   3 cups pecan pieces.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare the caramel sauce: In a medium heavy saucepan,
combine light brown sugar, granulated sugar, corn syrup, heavy
cream and salt. Place over high heat, and bring to a boil. Boil for
10 minutes, then remove from heat and add butter. Stir well to mix,
and keep warm. (The sauce may be prepared a day ahead of time and
stored, refrigerated, in a squeeze bottle. Reheat by placing the
bottle in a pot of boiling water until softened and warm.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare puff pastry: Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Place puff
pastry squares evenly spaced on parchment paper laid on a baking
sheet. Chill for 15 minutes. Cover with another sheet of parchment
paper, and weight with another baking sheet on top. Bake for 8
minutes, remove top baking sheet and top parchment paper, and
continue to bake until golden brown, 2 to 3 minutes. Remove from
oven. (The puff pastry may be baked a day in advance and stored,
sealed in plastic wrap, at room temperature.)
</P>
<P>
   3. To assemble: If necessary, reheat oven to 450 degrees. Pour
warm caramel sauce over pastry squares, and sprinkle an equal
number of pecans on each square. Bake tarts until caramel is bubbly
and pecans are toasted, about 4 minutes. Serve hot, unadorned or
with a square of ice cream on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
