<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR CHARDONNAY AND CHAUVINISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the earliest accounts of the first Thanksgiving,
the meal included birds, corn, peas, roast venison and beer. Beer?
Apparently there was not yet a decent wine shop in all of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably quite a few people who still drink beer with
their Thanksgiving dinner and, given some of the delicious beers on
the market now, it could make for a delightful partnership. But
beer is filling, and with the amount of food most of us are
expected to ingest on Thanksgiving, wine is a wiser and more
festive choice.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Thanksgiving repast is neither a delicate meal
nor a sophisticated one; it does not blend subtle, fleeting tastes
and aromas. So it is not a time to bring out great white
Burgundies, for instance. A big Champagne, like Krug or Bollinger,
will hold its own quite well with turkey. But most people are
saving their Champagne for the New Year's Eve of all New Year's
Eves.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Thanksgiving is an American event whose centerpiece,
the turkey, goes back, oh, 40 million years or so. I guess that
makes it as indigenous as an American creature can be. In my
chauvinistic view, the bird _ and the rest of us _ deserve American
wines.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing domestic wines offers an unexpected bonus. White
Burgundy may be out, but California chardonnay, which for my money
is too overwhelming for most fowl, is the perfect match for turkey.
There are some restrained, elegant chardonnays around, though for
the most part California chardonnay is a big-bodied, robust white
wine full of up-front flavor and aroma. In other words, just right
for the less than subtle taste of a roast turkey filled with a
pungent dressing.
</P>
<P>
   For a rich, powerful chardonnay, I'd suggest Chalone Vineyards
1997, a big, buttery, complex wine from the Gavilan Mountains south
of San Francisco. It will hold its own in any company, including
game. Or if you are planning a venison dinner and you prefer a
white wine, this could be the one for you. (About $30.)
</P>
<P>
   A bit less strident, perhaps, but still assertive is Fess
Parker's American Tradition Reserve Chardonnay 1997, from the Santa
Ynez Valley north of Santa Barbara. The wine has plenty of extract,
a nice touch of oak, and a remarkably long finish. (About $20).
</P>
<P>
   For something completely different, there's Tablas Creek Blanc
1997, a muscular blend of three Rhone Valley grapes: marsanne,
viognier and roussanne. Tablas Creek is a relatively new winery
near Paso Robles, in San Luis Obispo County, started in 1990 by the
Perrin family of Chateau de Beaucastel in Chateauneuf-du-Pape.
While not a replica of a blockbuster Hermitage white, this white is
both elegant and intense. (About $27.)
</P>
<P>
   Most traditionalists will want a red wine with their
Thanksgiving dinner and, if they are also patriots, they will
probably call for zinfandel, the grape America has adopted as its
own. Ridge Vineyards in Santa Clara makes a variety of zinfandels
from grapes purchased all over California, the unifying factor
being what one wine guide calls the ``classic restraint'' of the
winemaker, Paul Draper. I take that to mean the wines are rich and
intense but less rough and rustic than so many other zinfandels.
Ridge's 1996 Sonoma Station Zinfandel has zinfandel fruitiness and
classic Ridge structure. (About $20.)
</P>
<P>
   Amador County, far to the east of the Napa Valley, produces some
of the best zinfandel grapes. Ravenswood, in Sonoma County, another
winery that made its name with zinfandel, uses Amador grapes for
one of its most enticing bottlings, Ravenswood Amador County. The
scent of blackberries fills the room once the bottle is opened; on
the palette, the flavors linger on and on. (About $15.)
</P>
<P>
   For most families, the best choice is a wine priced low enough
so that opening another bottle or three or four is not going to
precipitate a post-dinner economic crisis. (``That uncle of yours
can sure put it away!''). For many savvy wine drinkers, the choice
is Marietta Cellars Old Vine Red, a blend that lets the winemaker,
Chris Bilbro in Sonoma County, use whatever he thinks will produce
the kind of wine he wants to make. Zinfandel, carignane, syrah and
cabernet may find their way into this delicious, full-bodied wine.
Different vintages may be used, which is why the wine is identified
only by lot number. Currently for sale, if you can find this very
popular wine, is Lot No. 23. (About $12.)
</P>
<P>
   By this point, there are probably quite a few people muttering,
``Where's the merlot?'' For me, most merlot is too soft and
unstructured, without enough tannin, for a main course like turkey
_ unless it is bolstered with 30 percent cabernet sauvignon. Here
is one that sort of breaks the rules. Canoe Ridge from Washington
State has merlot's softer taste, but it has good body. (About $19.)
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, it would have been difficult to create a
completely American wine selection for an important meal. No
longer. A Schramsberg Blanc de Blancs as an aperitif will match any
French Champagne in its price range. (About $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Then end the day not with Cognac or grappa but with a great
American drink, Laird's 12-year-old apple brandy. (About $50).
Thanksgiving became an official holiday in 1863; the Lairds began
making apple brandy in 1780. Did somebody say something about
tradition?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1650EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
