<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUCH OF THE LIPS AND VOILA, A PRINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note this is a new column)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If an award were given to the most underappreciated wines,
chenin blancs would be wearing gold. Those same bartenders who pour
chardonnay in their sleep might choke at a request for chenin
blanc, even if you used one of the grape's proper French names:
Vouvray, Savennieres or Montlouis. But chenin blanc just needs half
a chance to prove its charm.
</P>
<P>
   It is an amazingly versatile grape. It can be dry enough to
pucker your mouth, or voluptuously fruity or sweet enough to drink
for dessert. Because the grape is both high in acid and rich in
flavor, well-made wines go beautifully with all sorts of foods and
have the potential to age.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that so many chenin blancs are not well made,
resulting in cheap wines that are too sharp or sweet. This has
given a bad reputation to Vouvrays in particular. But if you can
find good examples you will be richly rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Few white wines can match the power and subtlety in a great
Savennieres, and even fewer are better values. And chenin blancs
from Coteaux du Layon make sweet, luscious dessert wines when
infected with botrytis cinerea, the noble rot mold.
</P>
<P>
   The best chenin blancs come from the Loire, where the grape,
sometimes called pineau de la Loire, may have been cultivated as
far back as the ninth century. The Loire may have history on its
side, but when it comes to quantity, France is outdone as a chenin
blanc grower by both California and South Africa, where the grape
is often called steen. Chenin is also grown throughout Latin
America, where it's called pinot blanco.
</P>
<P>
   Because the grape is sturdy and relatively easy to grow, chenin
blanc is most often used in both South Africa and the United States
for blending to produce inexpensive mass-market white wines. When
chenin blanc wines are produced in California and South Africa,
though, they are generally pleasant, and often good values.
</P>
<P>
   These six wines give a hint of the grape's range.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Poniatowski, Vouvray Aigle Blanc, 1996: $17
</P>
<P>
   Dry and refreshing with a hint of sweetness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Domaine Deletang Montlouis, Les Batisses, Demi-Sec, 1997: $17.
</P>
<P>
   Semisweet, with a wonderful range of fruit flavors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Domaine des Baumard, Savennieres, Clos du Papillon, 1996: $20
</P>
<P>
   A luscious dry wine with a touch of citrus.
</P>
<P>
   Yves Soulez, Chateau de la Genaiserie, Coteaux du Layon
St.-Aubin, 1995: $40 (500 ml.)
</P>
<P>
   An ultrasweet dessert wine with a honeyed texture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pine Ridge, California, 1998: $11
</P>
<P>
   Tart, dry and and pleasant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KWV, Steen, Western Cape, South Africa, 1997: $7
</P>
<P>
   A simple, appley wine. Very good value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Prices are those paid in various Manhattan shops.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1651EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
