<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BRUSSELS-SPROUTS-ART-     11-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUSSELS-SPROUTS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING ON THE SWEET SIDE OF SPROUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: recipe in 2ndtake)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brussels sprouts have an image problem, but it's perplexing
considering their assets. They are not difficult to cook. They have
a long season, stretching through winter. And they are not
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   For any cook with an offbeat aesthetic, brussels sprouts are a
wonderful weird little vegetable. The round, bulbous heads grow
like buds on the neck of a thick hard trunk about two feet high.
They are like cabbages in miniature, with tightly wound ruffled
leaves, and they have a pleasantly assertive, sweet and cabbagey
flavor. They are lovely when blanched and rolled in browned butter,
tossed with chestnuts or scented with bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees, of course. Few people have mixed feelings
about brussels sprouts. They either love them or hate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only place on the planet I eat brussels sprouts,''
said Raliegh Neal, a manager at the Grange Hall in New York's
Greenwich Village, when I ordered them. It is not that Kevin
Johnson, the chef, performs miracles on them. He just cooks them
properly.
</P>
<P>
   And that is often the problem with brussels sprouts. These are
not forgiving vegetables, and in the hands of an inexperienced
cook, they can turn to mush.
</P>
<P>
   There are two simple rules for success with brussels sprouts.
First, never buy any that are larger than a small plum. (It is best
to buy them at a farmers' market, where they are freshest, because
they are often sold on the trunk. But bring a shopping cart; they
are not easy to transport.)
</P>
<P>
   Second, don't overcook them. It may sound obvious, but the
perpetrators are many. Brussels sprouts are not like red cabbage.
They don't improve with long, slow cooking. They just get smellier.
</P>
<P>
   Most brussels sprouts recipes involve two techniques: blanching
and sauteing. Blanching removes the raw, green flavor, sets the
color and cooks, but not all the way through. Sauteing brings on a
richer, deeper flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking the sprouts whole is challenging. Cookbooks will tell
you that you need to cut a small ``X'' in each base. It's a fine
task if you're a surgeon, but it's about as much fun as pushing
fish mousse for quenelles through a sieve. If you must cook them
whole, press the point of a knife into the base; an entire ``X'' is
not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It's simpler to cut them in half or quarters so they can be
braised,  &UR; quickly &LR; , without blanching first. Or you can always just
slice them, as Bill Schutz, the chef at Waterloo Brasserie in
Greenwich Village, does. In a dish with chanterelles, the sliced
sprouts are a bright accent. They are full-flavored and alive, and
they crunch in your mouth. The chanterelles melt. What makes these
seemingly disparate ingredients fuse is a creamy, smoky sauce
scented with maple syrup and bacon.
</P>
<P>
   When brussels sprouts are left almost whole, they are delicious,
too. At Babbo, chef Mario Batali serves them like jewels, on a
plate set on a starched napkin. They are browned on the edges, with
every layer of their cut halves caramelized. Crisp pancetta adds
crunch and salt; thyme and parsley, sprinkled in as the sprouts are
finished, are the first things you smell.
</P>
<P>
   The brussels sprouts and carrots with almonds served at the
Grange Hall are as unpretentious as home cooking. In fact, Johnson
doesn't even bother to peel the carrots. The dish is an ecstatic
jumble of colors and shapes _ green bulbs, angular sticks of carrot
and toasted almond slices. Each bite is sweet and nutty and
wonderful. But then brussels sprouts are lovely with nut flavors.
An easy way to get that taste is to saute blanched and quartered
brussels sprouts in butter and add a little walnut or hazelnut oil
at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking brussels sprouts shouldn't be a project. They have very
direct flavor and texture. All they need is a little coaxing, light
cooking and the absence of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS SPROUTS WITH PANCETTA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Mario Batali of Babbo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds brussels sprouts, blanched and cut in half
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces pancetta, cut into {-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch chopped thyme, more if needed
</P>
<P>
   Large pinch chopped parsley, more if needed
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring a large pot of generously salted water to a boil. Add
the halved brussels sprouts, and cook until they are tender but
still slightly crisp, about 5 minutes. Using a slotted spoon,
transfer them to a bowl of salted ice water to cool; then, drain.
Cut the sprouts in half lengthwise and dry thoroughly on a tea
towel.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large saute pan over medium-low heat, cook the cubed
pancetta until most of the fat has been rendered and the cubes are
crispy, about 12 to 15 minutes. Remove pancetta with a slotted
spoon, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   3. Increase heat to medium-high, add the brussels sprouts and
cook until they are browned on the edges and tender, turning often,
about 5 to 7 minutes. Add reserved pancetta, thyme and parsley, and
stir to mix well. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS SPROUTS AND CHANTERELLES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bill Schutz of Waterloo Brasserie
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   \ pound bacon, cut crosswise into \-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   1 small sprig rosemary
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon crushed black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   { pound chanterelle mushrooms, chopped
</P>
<P>
   20 brussels sprouts, trimmed and thinly sliced crosswise.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saucepan, bring the maple syrup to a boil. Add
half the bacon, rosemary and black pepper; cook for 1 minute. Add
cream, and reduce by half. Remove from the heat, and strain through
a fine sieve into a bowl. Taste and adjust seasoning. Reserve until
needed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a large saute pan over medium-high heat. Add olive oil,
then shallots. Cook for 1 minute. Add chanterelles and remaining
bacon, and saute until chanterelles are soft, about 3 to 5 minutes.
Add sliced brussels sprouts, and cook until slightly soft but still
crunchy, about 3 minutes. Add reserved sauce, and stir to combine.
Spoon into a serving dish, and drizzle with pan sauce. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS SPROUTS AND CARROTS WITH ALMONDS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Kevin Johnson of Grange Hall
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   3 cups trimmed brussels sprouts (about } pound)
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups julienned carrots (unpeeled)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Spread almonds evenly on a
baking sheet, and toast until lightly golden, about 3 to 5 minutes.
Remove from oven, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring a large pot of generously salted water to a boil. Add
brussels sprouts, and cook until slightly tender but still crisp,
about 5 minutes. Drain, and when cool enough to touch, cut them
into quarters and dry well on a tea towel. Set aside. Meanwhile,
bring a medium pot of generously salted water to a boil. Add
carrots, and cook until slightly tender, about 1 minute. Drain. 3.
In a large saute pan over medium-high heat melt butter. Add
almonds, and saute until just slightly darker, about 1 minute.
Increase heat to high, add brussels sprouts and carrots, and cook,
stirring constantly, until vegetables are warmed through and
browned on the edges, about 5 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
