<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MADRID-MUSEUM-NYT &LR;      11-16 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADRID-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOME FOR THE BARONESS' ART? YES, NEXT TO THE BARON'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Some people become art collectors by birth,
which was certainly the case with Baron Hans Heinrich von
Thyssen-Bornemisza, whose grandfather collected Rodin sculptures
and whose father built up an impressive collection of Italian
primitives and Renaissance oils. The Baron then added richly to
what he inherited, so that the 800 paintings on permanent display
at the Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum here since 1992 cover the 13th to
20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Others become collectors by marriage, which is what happened to
Carmen ``Tita'' Cervera, the former Spanish beauty queen who in
1985 became the baron's fifth wife. Thanks to gifts from her
multimillionaire husband and purchases of her own, her collection
has grown to some 600 works. And now it too is to have its own home
in two large buildings adjacent to the existing Thyssen-Bornemisza
Museum, itself just a stone's throw from the Prado Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The new deal is not unlike that made by the baron in 1988 when
the Spanish government agreed to spend $45 million on preparing the
late 18th-century Villahermosa Palace to display paintings he was
lending for 10 years. Spain then bought the collection for $350
million in 1993. Now the government is to spend $40 million
renovating space for the baroness' collection, which will initially
be on loan for 11 years, although an eventual sale or donation is
also in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Baroness Thyssen-Bornemisza (pronounced TEESS-ahn
boar-nuh-MEES-uh) has well and truly made her mark here. She was
instrumental in bringing her husband's collection to Spain from
Switzerland when several other countries were eager to receive it.
And now, she says with only a touch of irony, it is ``patriotism''
that has prompted her to settle her collection here. No wonder that
King Juan Carlos awarded her Spain's Gold Medal of the Arts in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Her collection includes works by Corot, Monet, Gauguin, Pissarro
and Sisley, although it cannot be compared in quality to that of
the baron, who filled important holes in Spain's own museum
collections with his Impressionist, Post-Impressionist, American
and modern paintings. Nonetheless, the baroness has built up a fine
collection of European landscape paintings and has gone out of her
way to buy Spanish _ and Catalan _ art of the 19th and early 20th
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save my husband's collection, I too became a collector,''
she explained recently. ``And luckily I understand art. I would
have done it anyway for my husband, but I love collecting. I
believe that museums of private collections are often more
beautiful than official museums because you choose your paintings
more carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all her passion for her husband and their collections,
the baroness, now 56, has also learned it is not easy to be the
fifth wife of an extremely wealthy man 22 years her senior who has
four children from earlier marriages. Notably, complications have
arisen since the baron decided to include her and Borja, her son
from a previous relationship, among his heirs. So, in the way
things often happen when money is up for grabs, she is involved in
a messy family battle.
</P>
<P>
   A court case in Bermuda is pitting the baron against his oldest
son, Georg Heinrich, 49, for control of the Thyssen-Bornemisza
Group, an industrial giant worth around $2 billion. The baron ceded
control of the group to Georg in 1983 in exchange for an annual
payment, but he now claims to have been hoodwinked and wants to
annul the 1983 agreement. Unsurprisingly, Georg is resisting, and
the court battle in Bermuda, which is the group's legal residence,
could go on for years.
</P>
<P>
   Since the baron suffered a stroke two years ago, the baroness
has emerged as his spokeswoman and chief strategist. In a recent
conversation in the boardroom at the Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum, she
seemed as keen to defend her husband's position in the dispute as
she was to talk about art. ``I told my husband that everyone sees a
dollar sign on his face and they all end up with dollar signs on
their own faces,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her critics, of course, see just such a sign on her face. And
they blame her for the rift between the baron and Georg, who have
not spoken to each other for three years. Certainly, if the baron
resumes control over the Thyssen-Bornemisza Group, he will be free
to bequeath a share in the group to the baroness and Borja, his
adopted son, as well as to his four other children, Francesca,
Lorne, Alexander and Georg. For the baroness, though, the dispute
stems from Georg's refusal to pay his father his due. ``These have
been terrible years for my husband,'' she said. ``They have
destroyed his health.''
</P>
<P>
   Family tensions had already surfaced when the baron decided to
transfer much of his art collection from his Villa Favorita in
Lugano, Switzerland, to the new museum in Madrid. ``His idea was
always to keep the collection together,'' the baroness said.
Eventually, the baron's four children and his wife each created
trusts with his or her one-fifth share of the $350 million paid by
Spain for the collection, with the balance of his enormous
collection again distributed among the five. And it was at this
point, with some 200 paintings to her name, that the baroness
decided to become a collector in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   She said that it was during her earlier marriage to actor Lex
Barker that she became interested in art, thanks to his collection
of turn-of-the-century American painting. But when she first
visited the Villa Favorita, she recalled, ``I couldn't believe what
I saw.'' Subsequently she joined the baron when he went shopping
for art. ``He said he always bought through intuition,'' she said.
``He said I had the same intuition.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, under the guidance of Tomas Lorens,
the chief curator of the Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum, parts of the
baroness' collection have traveled widely, from the new Shanghai
Museum to the Frick Collection in New York. In the basement of the
museum here, through Jan. 16, she has placed 65 of her paintings in
a show called ``Painting Nature: Genre and Landscape Paintings from
Bruegel to van Gogh.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum extension, which will house most of the Carmen
Thyssen-Bornemisza Collection beginning in October 2002, will be
linked to the Villahermosa Palace at three levels and will include
temporary exhibition galleries more spacious than the present
basement. There is evidently no need to change the museum's name
since the baroness is already present: in the museum's large
atrium, she and her husband preside in life-size paintings. The
only other portraits in the space are of King Juan Carlos and Queen
Sofia of Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
