<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CHOPS-ART-NYT &LR;      11-16 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE PIGS DO FLY: THIS CHOP ISN'T PORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the flickering candlelight at Coup in New York City, the slab
of grilled meat could have easily been a pork chop or a veal chop.
It was on the bone, after all, about an inch thick, a great
15-ounce portion.
</P>
<P>
   But I hadn't ordered veal, or pork, or even steak. This was
something else entirely, something altogether improbable and a
little bit bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   They call it a turkey chop.
</P>
<P>
   I dug in, more convinced than ever that I was about to eat
anything but turkey. The meat was firm but moist, seared with a
perfect pattern of grill marks. Another bite. Mild flavor, in the
manner of veal. And another. The turkey chop may be the most novel
thing on the menu, but in the end, there was no mistaking: it was
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this was not just another pallid little cutlet. Somehow,
the tasteless, dry bird had been transformed into a meaty, tender
cut that you would eat happily rather than because it was
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to put on my investigative reporter's apron and
speak to the chef, Kevin Roth. He agreed to share his secret with
me, even though he had asked his butcher not to cut anyone else's
turkey the way he was cutting it for Coup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will help me to become famous,'' Roth said. ``I
sure hope so. You want to be different from other chefs, and
hopefully it will set me apart.''
</P>
<P>
   When I found out soon after that a chef in Boston, Todd English
of Olives, was also serving turkey chops (a trend in the making!),
Roth was a bit chagrined.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, English said he had created his version in the
1980s, long before Roth. English was also happy to share his chop
information and, in fact, had already put his recipe and butchering
directions on the Web site of the National Turkey Federation
(www.turkeyfed.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was butchering veal, and there was a turkey next to it.''
English said. ``If you split a turkey breast down the breast plate,
it looks similar to a veal loin.''
</P>
<P>
   English confessed that he had created his version as a joke. ``I
tell people it's from a new bird they've invented with four legs,''
he said. He often takes the chops home and cooks them on his grill.
</P>
<P>
   English's turkey chop is different: it resembles a pork loin
chop with the bone in the middle. Roth's chop has bones down the
side, and looks like a veal chop.
</P>
<P>
   But how do they carve these things? I dug deeper. I clicked on
the turkey Web site and found English talking and cutting away. I
downloaded the instructions and called Lobel's, the butcher shop on
Madison Avenue. Evan Lobel, one of the partners, had never heard of
such a thing, and was mystified by my description. Still, he agreed
to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning I joined him for a butchering session. Even for
an experienced butcher, it was not so easy. Lobel was dissatisfied
with the chops from the first half of the breast. So, he made some
adjustments, like trimming off the ends first, leaving on more
skin, removing less bone. Eureka! Perfect turkey chops.
</P>
<P>
   First, Lobel cut the turkey breast down the middle and removed
the keel bone for the rib cage and breast. (Do not attempt this at
home unless you have a band saw.) Then the chops were cut about two
inches thick against the grain of the meat. (Band saw again.)
</P>
<P>
   Cutting across the grain is one of the two key differences
between a roasted turkey breast and turkey chops. It changes the
texture completely. But English's chops are not like Roth's,
because after English cuts the chops, he then joins the ends
together and ties them with butcher's twine.
</P>
<P>
   My investigation was almost complete. I tried the chops at
Olives, which were even more tender and juicier than the ones at
Coup.
</P>
<P>
   And I made them for myself _ and that is when I learned the
final secret to a flavorful, juicy piece of turkey: brining the
meat for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   I believe English when he says, ``We actually have turkey chop
junkies who come just for them.''
</P>
<P>
   You, too, can make turkey chops at home and flabbergast your
guests, but first you've got some obstacles to overcome. You have
to be willing to spend more for turkey chops than you would for
veal, because there is a lot of waste. (Turkey enchiladas, anyone?)
You may have to buy the whole turkey, and if you are feeding more
than two people, you will certainly have to buy the whole turkey
breast.
</P>
<P>
   If you live in New York City, you can place an order with
Lobel's (by phone at 212-737-1373, or through its Web site,
www.lobels.com), for $16.98 a pound. Saturday is the deadline for
Thanksgiving orders.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can take the directions and pictures from the turkey
federation's Web site to you butcher, and throw yourself on his
mercy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLAZED TURKEY CHOPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Todd English of Olives &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1} hours, plus 48 hours' brining &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the chop: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 cup maple syrup or honey
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   20 whole peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 bulb garlic, cloves separated but unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   { cup grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   6 turkey chops, cut 1 inch or more thick
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the glaze: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   { cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   \ cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken or veal stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. For the chops, in deep glass dish large enough to hold all
the chops, combine all ingredients but the chops and oil. Add 6
cups boiling water, mix well, and cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add chops to cooled brine, cover, and refrigerate for 48
hours.
</P>
<P>
   3. For the glaze, combine all ingredients but butter in
saucepan, and bring to boil over medium-high heat. Cook until
mixture reduces to almost a syrupy consistency, for 20 to 25
minutes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare grill, indoors or out. Remove chops from brine; dry
with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   5. Bring brine to boil in saucepan; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   6. Brush chops generously with oil. Sear on both sides on grill,
and then cook away from hottest part of grill, turning to cook both
sides. Brush chops often with brine to keep moist. Cook for 15 to
20 minutes, or until all the pink is gone.
</P>
<P>
   7. Just before chops are cooked, warm glaze slightly; whisk in
butter. Brush over chops; serve with cranberry relish or compote.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Chops will become very dark, like grilled steak. If you
want them less dark, reduce maple syrup to { cup. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
