<HEADER>
A1569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN17-CO     11-16 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: It's all about Monet
 &HT;    (Eds: Third in a series from Paris.)
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIVERNY, France _ I came to see Claude Monet's home and gardens.
Claude wasn't home. He hasn't been for quite a while.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fathers of Impressionism, he died in 1926, well into
his 80s. Just as well. His eyes were gone by then and he could no
longer paint.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he cared so much about painting. The world, which cares
very much about his painting, may be surprised to hear such.
</P>
<P>
   But I have it on good authority _ in Claude's own words. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``Nous causerons jardinage, comme vous le dites, car pour l'art
et lat litterature, ciest la blague. Il n'y a que la terre.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to argue with that.
</P>
<P>
   For the half-dozen or so readers who don't read French, it is to
say ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll talk about gardening ... because art and literature,
they're a joke. The only thing that matters is the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to dirt, dirt in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Monet painted to make a living, as much as $2,000 a canvas
toward the end of his career. These days, of course, his paintings
are worth all the money there is, and then some. Too bad for poor
old Monet. He could have had one heck of a garden, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, he didn't do so badly with Giverny. That's pronounced
``gee-ver-nee'' and loosely translated as, ``Gee, Vern. Neat.''
Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Monet came to this village in Normandy, northwest of Paris, in
1893, the same year he married his mistress, Alice Hoschede.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Hoschede was his second wife, the ugly one. The pretty
wife was Camille, who had died in 1879. She was the one you see in
his paintings. But you won't see her in any family photos. Alice
Hoschede tore them all up after she had the run of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Be it noted that Monet never painted any pictures of Alice
Hoschede. Probably he was doing her a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Giverny, Monet concentrated on the flowers, especially
water lilies, the subject of his most famous paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Monet accumulated some 2 1/2 acres for house and garden,
orchards and lawns. A second parcel, acquired later, was where he
dug the ponds and established his water garden.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he dug the ponds himself. Not that he maintained the
gardens himself.
</P>
<P>
   Monet had a staff of seven gardeners, which is probably why he
preferred gardening to painting. The painting he had to do himself.
</P>
<P>
   Today a highway cuts through the property. Visitors _ 400,000
annually from April to October _ have to walk through a tunnel to
tour the water garden. The Japanese bridge is there, just as it is
in his paintings, though it's been reconstructed.
</P>
<P>
   Most everything about Monet's home and gardens were restored
after World War II, thanks mainly to some $14 million donated by
Americans, especially the Reader's Digest-Lila Wallace Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Each year Reader's Digest sends three American artists here to
paint. That's in keeping with a longtime tradition. There had been
an American colony of painters here since the turn of the century,
sometimes, it is said, driving Monet to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Monet enjoyed his solitude. He liked to eat and drink, sit and
smoke. I don't think he liked to paint. Many of his paintings he
destroyed, more so toward the end of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Don't go looking for any that survived here at Giverny. His
heirs sold them all years ago. Better to visit the Museum d'Orsay
in Paris, which boasts the world's best collection of Monet's work.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs art? Give me good ol' dirt any ol' day.
</P>
<P>
   I like this place. I like what I know about Monet, that he was
stout and wore a long gray beard, handsome qualities in any man.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think I could have been Monet _ except for the
painting, of course, not to mention Alice Hoschede.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1715EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
