<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VOYAGE-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     11-16 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOYAGE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VOYAGE TO THE NORTH STAR': A BOAT THAT'S `ALL WRONG' 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: pubication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Schenck is the sort of very rich guy who expects to get his
way, and we know from the very first line of Peter Nichols'
fogbound and tempest-tossed novel of maritime adventure what will
happen if he doesn't: ``On his first and only Kenya safari in 1932,
Carl Schenck was attacked by his white hunter after he
machine-gunned the heads off three loping giraffes from the open
cab of the safari truck.'' There is more than a little
foreshadowing here of the lethal sort of heedlessness that we will
see later as Nichols' first novel, ``Voyage to the North Star,''
unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   And a fiercely eventful novel it is too, an old-fashioned
adventure yarn given an impetuous, accident-prone propulsion by
Schenck, who does stupid and reckless things and assumes,
correctly, that his money will save him. The novel does not take
place on an African safari, Nichols' opening lines being all we
hear of that continent. Instead, Nichols takes us on a journey by
luxury yacht from a Gatsbyesque compound off New York's Long Island
to the barren coastline of Baffin Island, north of Labrador, where
his protagonist goes to hunt seals and polar bears.
</P>
<P>
   It is in moving from one terrain to the other, from
Depression-era New York to the coast of Arctic Canada, that
Nichols' story takes on its major themes, consciously derived from
those of Conrad and Melville. He depicts a theatrical cast of
characters morally adrift on a barren shore where some of them are
tempted to escape the normal constraints on human behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols does not write with the grandeur or the intellectual
originality of either of these great forerunners in the genre of
seaborne adventure. Nonetheless, his story pulses with action that
is given an extra measure of verisimilitude by his deep knowledge
of boats and the sea and the watery landscapes of the Far North.
</P>
<P>
   The story's main figure in many ways is not Schenck, but another
character, Will Boden, whom we first meet as a day laborer chipping
the paint off rusting hulls in New York Harbor. It is the
Depression, when jobs are hard to get and the rich are being
ruined, but we soon learn that Boden has been ruined in a different
way. He is a child of privilege who decided to go to sea, but a
seizure of mistaken judgment lost him his boat, and when that
happened, he lost his livelihood and a good deal of self-respect as
well. He has lost so much, in fact, that he doesn't have much else
to lose, and that gives him a kind of manly independence.
</P>
<P>
   Boden goes to work for Schenck, who seems to be getting richer
all the time even as other tycoons are falling into suicidal
bankruptcy. His first job is to drive an experimental speedboat
from New York to Florida for Schenck, who has teamed up with the
flier Eddie Rickenbacker in a scheme to manufacture passenger boats
that can beat the train from Pennsylvania Station to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But Schenck, whose hero is Theodore Roosevelt, is soon
distracted by a yearning to gain fame as a hunter and explorer of
the north. He buys a 225-foot luxury yacht and hires a crew to take
him, his comfort-addicted wife and his moody daughter to the
Arctic. The boat, unsuitable for far northern conditions, already
has a captain, a former British naval officer named Percival, who
is very conscious of his rank. Schenck asks Boden to go as
navigator, but Boden refuses, showing his good sense:
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat's all wrong,'' he tells one of his friends, providing
a bit more foreshadowing. ``The skipper doesn't know where he's
going. Schenck's a madman. It's going to be a holy disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boden goes anyway, as a coal stoker. Nichols tries to make
sense of this decision. He brushes in the death of Boden's mother
and his estranged wife's announcement that she has found somebody
else, an aging writer who dyes his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about killing myself,'' Boden tells his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then this is for you,'' the friend replies of Schenck's
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Nichols introduces others into this journey. One
is a handsome Ivy League youth, Gar Chamberlain, a former lover of
Schenck's daughter, Harriet. His father has just lost all his money
in the crash, prompting Gar to want to learn practical seafaring
skills. Harriet herself is sweet and spoiled in what would normally
be a harmless way _ but not in the territory where Nichols has
taken her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a young physical culture addict named Joey,
silent, sinister and slavishly devoted to Schenck. The story has
encounters with icebergs, polar bears and snowstorms. But it is a
small band of Eskimos, depicted by Nichols with marvelously earthy
exactitude, who emerge at the center of what is finally a tale of
moral transgression.
</P>
<P>
   Any sea venture, whether ``Moby-Dick'' or ``Voyage to the North
Star,'' depends on technical authenticity, and Nichols does not
fail in this regard. This is a writer who knows the difference
between a lead line and an air baffle, civil twilight and nautical
twilight, and he writes about boats and icy seascapes with poetic
pleasure. He has taken the trouble to learn about the Eskimo
language and the multiculture of Northern trading posts. Not the
least of the enjoyment of this novel of faraway regions comes from
the sense that the author has been there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voyage to the North Star'' does threaten in places to
overheat, and some of its characters straddle the vague border
between the tragic and the merely ludicrous. But at the center of
the story is a believable greed for power, which becomes
indistinguishable from evil, and when the reckoning for that evil
takes place, Nichols' novel provides a chilling Conradian dose of
ironic justice.
</P>
<P>
   In all, ``Voyage to the North Star'' is a tough-minded, exciting
debut for a writer who combines a powerful sense of elemental place
with a keen awareness of the elemental human flaws.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VOYAGE TO THE NORTH STAR'
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Nichols
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 342 pages. Carroll &AMP; Graf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
