<HEADER>
A1573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT     11-16 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND EVERY SUCCESSFUL PIE STANDS THE RIGHT PAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like casserole dishes, pie pans are equipment that few cooks put
much thought into choosing. Many use what was handed down to them,
or they buy something pretty, or they cheap out and go for an
aluminum pan from the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not prudent decisions, for the pie pan is as
crucial to the finished pie as the dough. Different materials hold
heat differently, and different designs affect the way the pie
cooks. If the fit is wrong, the pie will suffer for it.
</P>
<P>
   Because a pie is served in its pan, it ought to be one that you
want to look at. And considering the effort it takes to make a pie,
you should get it right.
</P>
<P>
   A great variety of materials are available: glass, aluminum,
stoneware, nonstick and ceramic. And even more designs. Some are
deep, some are shallow. Some have wide rims, some have none. To
determine the best, I tested eight kinds, using the pumpkin pie
recipe from ``The Pie and Pastry Bible'' by Rose Levy Beranbaum
(Scribner, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO METALLIC makes a shallow aluminum pan, perforated on the
bottom. I thought the holes would help the crust bake dry on the
bottom. But that proved to be misguided optimism. The pumpkin
filling cooked through before the dough did, producing a gummy,
white, half-cooked dough and a filling on the verge of cracking.
Two 9-inch pans are $5.49 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway (80th Street),
New York City, (212) 787-2000.
</P>
<P>
   A PYREX pie pan, similar in form to the Chicago Metallic, was
also disappointing. Again, the pan did not get hot enough to cook
the pastry before the filling. And with a wet filling like pumpkin,
which tends to weep liquid after baking, the pastry should be
completely cooked through. The 9-inch Pyrex is $3.95 at A Cook's
Companion, 152 Atlantic Avenue (near Clinton Street), Brooklyn,
N.Y., (718) 852-6901.
</P>
<P>
   A great bargain, by contrast, is the 8}-inch PROGRESSIVE
INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION nonstick pie pan, which is $2.98 at
Zabar's. It held heat well and baked evenly, producing a pumpkin
pie with a browned crust, still tender from the butter. But the
nonstick coating displayed other problems, not to mention having no
esthetic appeal. While slices were easy to remove from the pan, the
surface was so slippery that part of the crust's border simply slid
off the pie while it was baking. Next time, I would form the border
closer to the inside of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was ROSE'S PERFECT PIE PAN. Rose is Ms. Beranbaum,
the cookbook author. Her 8-inch, shallow, wide-lip ceramic pan is
made by Mudworks Pottery. It's a beautiful dish and has a recipe
printed on the bottom for her delicious cream cheese pastry. The
pan also works well. The pastry was as brown as almond skin and not
at all doughy, and the wide rim made the pan easy to transport to
and from the oven. It was not, however, perfect for pumpkin pie. A
dish this shallow seems better suited for double-crusted pies with
fruits, like apples, mounded high in the center. Ms. Beranbaum's
kind of perfection does not come cheap: the pan is $38.95 at A
Cook's Companion.
</P>
<P>
   EMILE HENRY produces classic-looking Burgundy-clay pie pans.
They come in bright, happy colors, and some have fluted rims, so
even if your pie doesn't look great, what's cradling it does. The
one I tried, a 9-inch pan, had just a single flaw: the sides of the
crust cooked quicker than the bottom. It's a problem easily solved
by baking the pie closer to the bottom of the oven or on top of a
baking stone. It's $24.95 at Broadway Panhandler, 477 Broome Street
(Wooster Street), (212) 966-3434.
</P>
<P>
   Another attractive pie pan with the same problem is the heavy
CLAY CITY POTTERY pan. An 8-inch pan is $17.50 at Broadway
Panhandler. Like Rose's pan, it has a good wide rim for lifting,
and the rim is unglazed, which prevented the pastry from weeping
into the pan. But the pan left the center less cooked than the
sides.
</P>
<P>
   The best pan was the 9{-inch CHANTAL deep-dish stoneware pan. It
has an odd design, with ridged sides that have a softer slope than
the Emile Henry and no real lip. Though it is made for thicker
pies, like double-crusted peach pies, it worked well with pumpkin
pie. I made a border for the crust on the ridge below the rim,
which provided a perfect shield from the oven heat (crusts often
brown too much before the interior of the pie finishes baking) and
allowed the pumpkin filling to puff up and bake to a soft
puddinglike texture without cracking. The gentle slope of the sides
also made it easy to lift out slices. More important, though, the
pie baked evenly. The entire crust was a deep golden brown like
bread crust and crisp but tender. This pan is $12.98 at Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   I could not leave out grocery store aluminum foil pans.
Typically, they come three to a pack for about $2. They are so
cheap for a reason: they are incredibly flimsy. Getting the pie
with its loose filling into the oven was a near disaster: the pan
almost folded in half. The very bottom layer of the pastry cooked,
but not the rest, giving it a cardboard texture. Pie pans, even Ms.
Beranbaum's luxury version, just aren't that expensive. You might
as well splurge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
