<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LIBERTY-FILM-REVIEW-N     11-16 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIBERTY HEIGHTS': ROCK 'N' ROLL AND PREJUDICE IN EVER MISTY
BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baltimore has been awfully good to Barry Levinson. Whenever this
gifted filmmaker seems in danger of succumbing to Hollywood's
schlockiest temptations, he dips back into the personal memory bank
of his Baltimore boyhood and comes up with something sweet and
heartfelt. In ``Liberty Heights,'' his fourth Baltimore-based film,
Levinson pores over the social traumas and cultural trivia of 1950s
America as reflected in his native city with the concentration of a
diehard nostalgist minutely inspecting the still-visible scars of
his own hypersensitive adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   In remembering the virulent anti-Semitism and racism of
Baltimore in the mid-1950s, this warmly sentimental, sometimes very
funny film subscribes to the notion propagated by countless other
movies, television shows and rock 'n' roll histories that America
was more or less born in the mid-1950s; before that were the dark
ages. And in a way it's true. With the rise of television, rock 'n'
roll and the teenage car culture, the shell of America's devouring
pop fun house was already in place by 1954, the year ``Liberty
Heights'' begins.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious problems facing any movie revisiting such familiar
territory are finding a fresh point of view and coming up with
characters who transcend the pre-``Happy Days'' teenage stereotypes
we know too well. The strategy of ``Liberty Heights'' is to build
an atmosphere that is so intensely true to the period that you
can't help but dream its dreams and be caught up in its tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty Heights'' remembers this era through the eyes of two
brothers, teenage Ben (Ben Foster) and the slightly older Van
(Adrien Brody), growing up in a middle-class Jewish family in the
mostly Jewish northwest section of Baltimore. The most irritating
symbol of their uncertain status in a gentile-dominated world is a
country club with a posted sign at the entrance reading ``No Jews,
dogs or coloreds allowed.'' The boys' father, Nate (Joe Mantegna),
runs a discreet numbers racket and operates a burlesque house with
two partners. And some of the movie's wittiest moments recreate
pieces of vintage burlesque skits. Their mother, Ada (Bebe
Neuwirth), is tight-lipped, puritanical and devoted to her husband.
A meddlesome but good-hearted grandmother is also on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Much as Levinson's 1982 film ``Diner'' did, ``Liberty Heights''
focuses on the boys' fumbling rites of passage, but here the time
is two or three years earlier. Again, Levinson shows a special
knack for capturing the boastful, clinging camaraderie and cultural
fetishes of innocents trying to invent themselves in a more
restrictive era. Masking their anxiety in foolish braggadocio and
speculation, they swap apocryphal sexual lore while pining after
forbiddingly unattainable goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ben develops a crush on Sylvia (Rebekah Johnson), a sensible,
well-mannered middle-class black girl in his high school, and the
pair sneak out on a chaste date in which she instructs him to
huddle below the front seat of the car so they won't be seen
together. Van pines for Dubbie (Carolyn Murphy), a haughty
horseback-riding debutante he meets at a Halloween party where she
is dressed as a fairy princess waving a wand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty Heights'' is a leisurely paced series of anecdotes
that jump from character to character to create the sense of a
society in accelerating flux. The most dramatic sequence crosscuts
from a James Brown concert at which Ben discovers the thrill of
soul music to a high-toned teenage society bash attended by an
anxious Van searching for his dream girl.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has some lovely comic touches. Ben, whose voice-over
narration frames the story, is astounded to discover the existence
of a gentile world where people consume bread that isn't toasted.
In another scene, a friend of Van's, visiting an elegant WASP manor
with lavishly furnished antiques and expensive rugs, naively
assumes that a family that can't afford wall-to-wall carpeting and
Formica tables must be poor or very stingy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberty Heights'' pointedly compares anti-Semitism with the
far more severe prejudice against blacks, who are shunned by WASPS
and Jews alike in mid-1950s Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious plot turn, Nate and his partners come up
with a promising new twist on their numbers racket, which backfires
when Little Melvin (Orlando Jones), a black drug dealer who has
placed 50-to-1 odds on a number that carries a bonus, unexpectedly
wins $100,000. Lacking the money to pay the prize, Nate is forced
to bargain with Little Melvin, with disastrous consequences for
Nate and his family.
</P>
<P>
   But because ``Liberty Heights'' looks back through Ben's and
Van's youthful eyes, even the harshest turn of events wears a misty
nostalgic glow. The family dynamics remain unexplored, as do the
darker aspects of Nate's profession. Mantegna's Nate is a model
father, husband and breadwinner who just happens to be operating
outside the law. His sons are just as lovingly drawn. Foster's Ben
is a likable all-American boy who even when rebelling (one
Halloween he dresses up like Hitler) is essentially sweet-natured
and pliable. Brody's Van is surprisingly soft-edged, given the
hopped-up energy that the actor effuses almost like perspiration.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Liberty Heights'' is much too soft at its center, it
still offers a deeper immersion in that old '50s feeling than any
other Hollywood film in recent memory. As its inviting period
soundtrack fills in the background and its youthful characters
lurch through their pseudo-sophisticated rituals of rebellion and
desire, the gawky sincerity of an earlier era comes stumbling back,
a little tipsy and poignantly alive.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTY HEIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `Liberty Heights'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations, a
glimpse of nudity and some strong language.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Barry Levinson; director of photography,
Chris Doyle; edited by Stu Linder; music by Andrea Morricone;
production designer, Vincent Peranio; produced by Levinson and
Paula Weinstein; released by Warner Brothers. Running time: 134
minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Adrien Brody (Van), Bebe Neuwirth (Ada), Joe Mantegna
(Nate), Ben Foster (Ben), Orlando Jones (Little Melvin), Rebekah
Johnson (Sylvia), David Krumholtz (Yussel), Richard Kline
(Charlie), Vincent Guastaferro (Pete), Justin Chambers (Trey) and
Carolyn Murphy (Dubbie).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
