<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Nov. 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The unusually dry weather pattern of recent weeks will persist
over a large area from the Rockies to the East Coast Wednesday, but
a frontal system moving into the interior West will signal the
beginning of a gradual shift to moister conditions in much of the
nation over the next several days. Despite the shifting pattern, no
major storms or Arctic chill will invade the nation through the end
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds and showers will move east with a cold front
through Nevada and Idaho toward the west slopes of the Rockies. In
the wake of the front, snow levels will gradually sink below 6,000
feet late in the day and at night. Farther west, drier air will
cause clouds to break near the Pacific Northwest coast.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably mild conditions and plentiful sunshine will prevail
from the Rockies to the Plains states. Breezes from the southwest
will increase during the afternoon as low pressure begins to
strengthen over the interior West. Showery rain will develop
Wednesday night near the west slopes of the Rockies. By early
Thursday, the showers will change to snow over the higher
elevations of the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure will keep the East dry with ample
sunshine. The chill will begin to moderate over the Northeastern
states as northwesterly winds diminish, but afternoon temperatures
will stay several degrees below the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Lenny, with its highest winds near 110 mph, will
produce torrential rain as its center moves about 100 miles south
of Puerto Rico toward the northern Leeward Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Backward Hurricane
</P>
<P>
   Compared to a typical tropical cyclone in the Caribbean, the
eastbound Hurricane Lenny has been moving backward. Normally,
systems in the Tropics are embedded in a current of easterly winds
that carry them toward the west. The tropical easterlies result
from the circulation that forms between a broad belt of low
pressure near the equator and a high pressure zone that girdles the
globe around 30 degrees north latitude. Occasionally, especially
late in the season, the prevailing westerly winds of the middle
latitudes can penetrate south, shifting the tropical windflow into
reverse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1730EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
