<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-BATTERED-REVIEW-NY     11-16 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BATTERED-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK AND BLUE': A BATTERED WIFE RUNS AWAY, AND THE DETECTIVE
FOLLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: producton notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Black and Blue,'' as blunt as its title, feels as immediate as
a jab in the gut. Like the bully it portrays, it knocks you to the
floor and leaves you there, stunned. You're in pain, all right, but
you haven't gone very far.
</P>
<P>
   The film, on CBS on Wednesday night, is the grim story of a
battered wife who flees Long Island with her 10-year-old son. She
covers a lot of miles, but she hasn't really gone very far either.
</P>
<P>
   You never doubt that her husband, a New York City police
detective, will track her down, even though her escape has been
choreographed by a shadowy organization that helps such victims
disappear into new identities. While you wait nervously for the
ill-tempered cop to turn up, you wonder about him and his wife,
bound so tightly by pain and regret. But they never progress from
symbols into three-dimensional people. You want to care, at least
about her, but you can only watch as the melodrama stalls this side
of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the more fully realized novel by Anna Quindlen, ``Black
and Blue'' revolves around Fran Benedetto: nurse, loving mother to
10-year-old Robert and punching bag to her husband, Bobby. As
played by Mary Stuart Masterson, Fran is a suffering Madonna, more
icon than person. She is goodness incarnate, just as Bobby (Anthony
LaPaglia) is evil on the hoof. After he beats his wife savagely,
and she demands that he look at her bruises, Bobby sneers, ``What
are you gonna do, Frannie, call the cops?''
</P>
<P>
   These familiar actors have explored these poles before; you can
make out echoes of other performances here. But this film, written
by April Smith and directed by Paul Shapiro, strains the dedication
of both the actors and the viewer. It tells you that Fran and Bobby
were once bound by a love that has fermented into a volatile, toxic
brew. Everything she does, everything she is, just enrages him.
You're left to wonder how they could ever have stood each other.
</P>
<P>
   The other cast members must cope with one-note roles as well.
Sam Robards is all caring sunshine as the schoolteacher who finds a
place in his heart for both Robert and Fran. Joanne Merlin is all
malevolent darkness as Bobby's mother who eggs him on to vengeance
with lines like ``You gonna let a snotty little Irish girl get
you?''
</P>
<P>
   The one performance with any depth comes from Will Rothhaar, the
boy who plays Robert. He locates the stifling ambivalence that
makes him hate his mother's humiliation and still love his father.
This is no lovable tyke. His character's sarcasm, which seems to
come as naturally as breathing, is a constant reminder that as long
as Fran keeps the boy with her, she is never really rid of Bobby.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's cleverest moment, Robert refuses to hide his
disgust for the dumpy apartment to which his mother has taken him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it?'' he demands. ``This is Florida?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is  &UR; part &LR;  of Florida,'' Fran says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the pool?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other part.''
</P>
<P>
   But this lightness quickly evaporates, and the film is left to
sink.
</P>
<P>
   All concerned are to be commended for confronting a serious
subject without a hint of sugar coating. But this drama could have
had the resonance of a contemporary tragedy. Instead, it's more
like a bellyache.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   BLACK AND BLUE
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Wednesday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Gerald W. Abrams and Jennifer Alward, executive producers; Anna
Quindlen, co-executive producer; Terry Gould, producer; Michael R.
Goldstein, co-producer; Paul Shapiro, director; written by April
Smith based on the novel by Anna Quindlen; music by Jonathan
Goldsmith. Produced by Evolve Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Mary Stuart Masterson (Fran Benedetto), Anthony LaPaglia
(Bobby Benedetto), Will Rothhaar (Robert Benedetto), Sam Robards
(Mike Riordan) and Joanne Merlin (Ann Benedetto). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
