<HEADER>
A1590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      11-16 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH URGES TEXAS OFFICIALS TO FOCUS ON STATE BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PEGGY FIKAC  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush took a break from his
pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination on Tuesday to
encourage appointed representatives of Texas agencies to focus on
their state duties despite other demands on their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I'm spending a fair amount of time out of the
state these days,'' Bush told about 200 people he has named to
various commissions and boards, the second such seminar he has
addressed this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm focused on Texas, though. I mean, I'm still the
governor,'' he said. ``And I've got a lot of work to do as the
governor, which I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush likened his balancing act between his job as governor and
courting voters to the demands of daily life experienced by those
on state panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your families, you live in communities, you've got
your own businesses to run or your jobs to do, but you need to be
focused on this job, too,'' he said. ``So my first admonition is:
take your responsibility as seriously as I take mine. It's a big
deal to serve Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor encouraged the appointees to focus on a small
number of goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt government ought to do a few things and do
them well,'' he said. ``I know that if there are so many goals,
there end up being no goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said politics did not come into play in choosing the
appointed board members that oversee state agencies. ``We didn't
ask the question how capable are these people from a political
perspective. We asked the question how capable are these folks for
serving the state of Texas,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
