<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      11-16 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: ABC'S `MILLIONAIRE'; NBC SCHEDULE CHANGES; COMEDY
CENTRAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to Milk A Money Cow  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining questions about the runaway ratings train
called ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' are: How big can it get?
and What does ABC do with it next?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first question seems to be: As big as anything
on television in decades. As for the second question, ABC is doing
what any producer does with a hit: extending its run. The network
announced Tuesday that it would add three editions of
``Millionaire'' this month.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of ``Millionaire'' on the November sweep ratings has
been nothing short of tidal. The show has laid waste to just about
everything in its path, plowing through nights like Sherman going
through Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Only two shows have been able even to hold their own against
``Millionaire'' this month, NBC's ``Friends'' on Thursday night and
Fox's ``X-Files'' on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is all but certain to win the ratings race on the strength
of the night-after-night winning numbers put up by ``Millionaire,''
and the decision to add more nights is an effort to insure that
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The latest run of ``Millionaire'' was scheduled to end Sunday
night, giving ABC 15 nights of a sweep rating stunt. Now ABC is
moving programming around to accommodate editions of
``Millionaire'' next Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday nights. Each of
those shows will be on at 8 and be an hour long.
</P>
<P>
   With ABC already comfortably ahead of NBC and CBS in terms of
total viewers and NBC in terms of the young adult viewers that
those networks use as their main measuring stick, that should
easily be enough to guarantee ABC's first sweep ratings victory
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, ABC still faces the difficult decision of how to
maximize the advantage it now has with the ``Millionaire''
phenomenon. That may mean adding the show to its weekly schedule
once or twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry executives suggest that ABC may be compelled,
even if it goes to a regular prime-time edition, to add an edition
of the show as a syndicated entry. The show could then replace
``Jeopardy'' if that syndicated game show ever moves away from its
home on the local stations owned by ABC. ``Millionaire'' also would
probably become a billionaire in terms of the profits it could make
for ABC in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives do not expect to address the ultimate plan for
``Millionaire'' until the latest run of shows is over.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Rolls the Marbles
</P>
<P>
   NBC has announced broad changes in its prime-time schedule for
every night except Wednesday and Thursday, all to take place in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Most significant are the moves of several dramas. The promising
new ``Law and Order'' spinoff, ``Special Victims Unit,'' will move
from Monday at 9 to Friday at 10, giving its creator, Dick Wolf,
the 10 p.m. time period he coveted for that decidedly adult show.
</P>
<P>
   Another new drama that NBC is very high on, ``Third Watch,''
moves to Monday at 10, the spot that Wolf most coveted but was told
he could not have last spring.
</P>
<P>
   That was because it belonged to the NBC news magazine
``Dateline.'' But NBC has been persuaded to move ``Dateline'' after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline NBC,'' said
Tuesday that he was comfortable with the Monday move now because in
January ``Dateline'' would not have to face ``Monday Night
Football'' at 9 and mainly because in all the changes NBC left all
five weekly editions of ``Dateline'' on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best news for us,'' Shapiro said, ``is that we move our
Sunday show from 7 to 8 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays many NBA basketball games on NBC last until 8 p.m.,
which is the rest of the reason.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will also try to find more viewers for its best-reviewed new
show this season, ``Freaks and Geeks,'' by moving it from the
obscurity of Saturday at 8 p.m. to a more accessible time, Monday
at 8 p.m. That displaces two comedies that viewers seem to be
aggressively avoiding, ``Suddenly Susan,'' which is being shelved
for now, and ``Veronica's Closet,'' which is, to the surprise of
many, once again being handed one of NBC's best comedy spots,
Tuesday at 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   The one new show being added by NBC is ``The Others,'' a
supernatural thriller, which is getting the Saturday at 10 slot. To
make room, ``The Pretender'' moves to 8 and ``Profiler'' to 9.
</P>
<P>
   New Cable Executive
</P>
<P>
   The Comedy Central cable channel reached a long way to find a
new creative executive for the network _ all the way to England.
</P>
<P>
   The channel yesterday named Bill Hilary, a program executive
with the BBC in London, to the new job of general manager. He will
be responsible for all programming, marketing, advertising and
promotion for the channel.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment was made by Comedy Central president Larry
Divney, , who will shift his own duties to building a business
strategy for expanding the channel.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary has had a long career in British television, most
recently as the head of the BBC's Independent Commissioning Group,
which was responsible for developing programming for that network.
Previously he worked for Channel 4 and Granada Television, mainly
developing programs for young audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the appointment of Hilary, Comedy Central announced
the departure of Eileen Katz, the channel's executive vice
president for programming, saying she had decided to leave the
company. Hilary will be assuming the programming duties previously
held by Ms. Katz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
