<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSIDER THE SCRAMBLED POSSIBILITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Nov. 23.)  
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to grow up and have your parents never stop
reminding you how they sacrificed so you could have straight teeth,
a university education and an elaborate wedding. But what if they'd
spent $150,000 on a beautiful egg from a fashion model donor just
so you would be physically gorgeous?
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine the stress on a child who was created only for
his ideal looks? What happens the first time he falls down and goes
boom on that perfectly sculpted nose?
</P>
<P>
   If you were the result of a genetic mating based on physical
perfection, would you also get to be just a scruffy little kid?
Would you be permitted to bruise, get a pimple, freckle from the
sun? Would your parents ever stop staring at you?
</P>
<P>
   You wonder about these wannabe parents who would buy the eggs of
a fashion model off the Web from a photographer and horse breeder
just so they can get the prettiest baby. Maybe they'd do better to
save their money and buy a Lexus. Then if they didn't like its
looks after all, they could trade it in on an Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Who would consider doing baby business, anyhow, with an egg
broker who says things like, ``It's the butterfly that's the
prettiest that gets the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   A baby bred just for looks will not get to be cute just because
he's a baby. That kid better come out smiling and ready for video,
with a dimple in his chin and eyelashes to die for. He better have
them fainting in the delivery room and running into the sides of
buildings when he goes by in his stroller.
</P>
<P>
   The designer child made from a fashion model egg or fashion
model sperm (the same egg man promises soon to have handsome sperm
for sale) will not get to have baby fat. Or appear in public with
mashed bananas on his expensive face. He will have to have
Hollywood hair, not little baby tufts, and that skin better be free
of diaper rash.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the poor designer kid when she goes to preschool, forbidden
to mess up her looks with fingerpaint and mud. Who will play with
her if she can't get dirty?
</P>
<P>
   What happens to the kid if she grows a weak chin or her teeth
come in crooked? You have to watch it with these models, you know.
They are not always what they seem. Their cheeks can be filled out
with collagen, their stomachs smoothed by liposuction. Maybe
they've had the bottom they were born with hoisted and that amazing
little waist came from having a couple ribs removed.
</P>
<P>
   Eggs don't lie and some may come with the ``before'' flaws. What
if beautiful baby has allergies that make her eyes run and her nose
get all red during pollen season? Most parents learn to cope with
what they get, but how will those who paid big money for physical
perfection adjust to not getting the look they ordered? Will they
sue?
</P>
<P>
   And what will happen when perfect child becomes perfect
teen-ager and wails that his pecs are too small and her hair not
curly enough and it's all the parents' faults for not placing an
exact order. It would seem unfair for designer parents to tell
their children, ``Nobody's perfect,'' or ``Beauty is only skin
deep.''
</P>
<P>
   This whole idea of going for the perfect 10 child is scary,
silly and easy to mock, but let us trust that Mother Nature, with
her wonderful sense of mix and match, will show who's boss in the
gene dabbling business and implant a mind of her own even in this
thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the first tongue stud on that designer child. Oh, don't
you wish for a tattoo that says ``Cherry Poppin' Daddies'' etched
across one perfect flank. And won't it be deliciously just when a
child of the golden egg goes in for a little cosmetic realignment
and comes out looking real, like the rest of the family. Kind of
like Aunt Bertha.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
