<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`42 UP': AT 42, A POINT OF RECKONING FOR CHILDREN OF 1964
</HEADLINE>
 (Production notes at end)  
(nk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Tony was 7, he was a grinning Cockney optimist from the
East End of London, spouting plans to become a jockey and cavorting
exuberantly at the playground. Now he can be seen as a 42-year-old
who dodges sour glances from his glum-looking wife, a woman who was
once filmed by Michael Apted as Tony's beaming young sweetheart.
``I must say, it's not easy being married,'' says Tony, with the
boyish scrappiness and joy long gone from his face. About his life
as a cabby with a fenced-in suburban back yard, he acknowledges:
``I think this must be the limitations for me now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to watch Michael Apted's ``42 Up,'' the latest
in the series of milestone documentaries that began with ``7 Up,''
without more complex and piercing emotions than those prompted by
previous installments. When this hugely ambitious project began, it
was a longitudinal study of class divisions among English
schoolchildren. But time and persistence have turned it into much
more.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious labor of love for Apted, the series (which revisits
its original interview subjects every seven years) has moved beyond
the time-lapse sociology that gave it such fascination. With its
participants in middle age, the project has reached the point of
reckoning associated with an American 25th high school reunion,
with all the stark honesty that that implies.
</P>
<P>
   This haunting group portrait could once be watched for a sense
of how its participants were evolving, but by now there is a sense
of destiny fulfilled. Ambitions have been realized or thwarted.
Young romantics have become beleaguered single parents. Some
participants look eager and vital, while others still pay the price
for choices long since made. These 42-year-olds seem long past the
stage of letting chips fall where they may.
</P>
<P>
   A word about the courage of those seen in ``42 Up'': Imagine
subjecting yourself to this kind of unflinching scrutiny. The
series has been so widely seen that it is now part of the
42-year-olds and their evolution. So when Tony drives his cab, he
feels at least as famous as any of his passengers. And when Nick,
the farm boy who moved to the United States to teach at a
university, is asked by Apted about future plans, he says: ``My
ambition as a scientist is to be more famous for doing science than
for being in this film. But unfortunately, Michael, that's not
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``42 Up,'' which opens Wednesday at the Film Forum and must be
seen by anyone following the series, has no need for new tricks. It
simply divides its time evenly among revealing portraits of those
still willing to talk to the camera. Two of the three most
privileged boys from ``7 Up'' have dropped out by now, even the one
who is himself a documentary filmmaker, but the others remain game
even when their circumstances are less than blissful. Jackie, who
has rheumatoid arthritis and is on her own with three young sons in
a bleak spot near Glasgow, says: ``I'm lucky. There are people who
are a damn sight worse off than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the developments seen here are touchingly positive. The
boy who wanted to be a missionary, Bruce, is now teaching at a
girls' school in the East End and has unexpectedly found himself a
wife. (Like most of the participants who mention marriage, he uses
the practical word ``partnership'' to describe it.) And Susie, who
at 14 was a rebellious aristocrat and later settled down with a
family and a tennis court, is now providing bereavement counseling.
Most poignant, once again, the plight of Neil, who was once a
bright, handsome child, then became a troubled derelict who spoke
with unflinching candor. Now Neil has gotten himself elected twice
as a councilman and is obviously doing better. Who knows how much
Neil's role as the handsome, fragile Kurt Cobain of this series
helped him with voters?
</P>
<P>
   About class distinctions, its original concern, ``42 Up'' now
finds the expected: Prosperous 42-year-olds find the world a fair
place, while some of their childhood schoolmates struggle with debt
and find life much harder. Though that point has been proven, the
project and its goals live on.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `2 UP'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by Michael Apted; director of photography,
George Jesse Turner; edited by Kim Horton; released by First Run
Features. At the Film Forum, 209 West Houston St., South Village.
Running time: 130 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Nick, Symon, Andrew, Jackie, Lynn, Susan, Tony, Bruce,
Paul and Neil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
