<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSINGS ON PERSON NO. 6 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 6 billionth person was born last month and I can definitely
tell the difference.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, traffic is much worse in South Florida now than it
was this same time last year. It is true that Floridians always say
traffic is worse this year than it was last year, and probably
would continue to do so if the cities sank into giant sinkholes and
ceased to exist. But that is just idle chitchat, a variation of
``Hot enough for you?'' and ``We sure needed this rain,'' whereas I
have proof.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I saw my first Michigan license plate on Oct. 30
this year compared to Nov. 10 a year ago. This is the kind of thing
that can happen when 6 billion people start jockeying for elbow
room: A butterfly beats its wings in Japan; a retired autoworker
from Lansing gets in his Lincoln Continental and drives to
Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. That's how hurricanes begin. Still, I think the same
theory could apply.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, I read in the paper that we are experiencing a severe
stone-crab-claw shortage and what few stone crab claws are
available are priced at what one would expect to pay for a tank of
gas for a Lincoln Continental. The paper blames this on hurricanes
that struck North Carolina, causing widespread flooding, which
destroyed a lot of pigs, not to mention pigs' feet, which are used
by Florida fishermen as bait for stone crabs.
</P>
<P>
   With the 6 billionth person having been born only a month ago,
the obvious question here is: Why on earth do stone crabs eat pigs'
feet? I've seen pickled pigs' feet in those big glass jars,
swimming around in some sort of unidentified red liquid _ I'm
guessing cherry Kool-Aid and vinegar _ and it's not the sort of
thing that strikes me as a gourmet delight, especially among your
high-end crustaceans.
</P>
<P>
   If pigs' feet aren't available, why can't we substitute
something else? Like a Big Mac or maybe a wad of Spam. If I were a
stone crab and I had been fed a steady diet of pink, waterlogged,
Kool-Aid-scented pigs' feet, I think I would virtually leap into
the boat if someone waved a Quarter Pounder with Cheese in front of
my nose, or whatever passes for a nose on a stone crab.
</P>
<P>
   (The fact that stone crabs are selling for $14.95 a pound is
further evidence that they are holding out for a better class of
bait. It is entirely possible that by the time the 7 billionth
human is born, stone-crab traps will have to be baited with filet
mignon.)
</P>
<P>
   Since the 6 billionth person was born, I have also noted an
upswing in TV commercials by Linda McCartney, which is doubly
strange given the fact that Linda McCartney is dead. Linda is a
(deceased) spokeswoman for People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, an organization whose members, one must presume, are also
not big pigs'-feet eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Linda's message was that people should stop fishing because
fishing is a form of torture and/or murder, depending on whether or
not you let the fish go. She gave as evidence the fact that fish,
when removed from the water, flop around and gasp for air, a sign
that they feel pain.
</P>
<P>
   As hard as it is for me to discount the opinion of someone who
feels so strongly about her cause that she is willing to defend it
from beyond the grave, I intend to continue eating fish, preferably
grilled or sauteed in lemon butter. However, if she can prove that
broccoli emits a silent scream of agony when you throw it into the
steamer, I promise to stop eating it immediately.
</P>
<P>
   I am not saying that human being No. 6 billion is personally
responsible for early tourists from Michigan, the pigs'-feet
shortage, fussy stone crabs or Linda McCartney's reincarnation.
</P>
<P>
   But if Sarasota were suddenly swallowed up by a giant sinkhole,
I'd definitely start getting suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
