(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-WALL _ PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ With a badge and a gun and
a loyal following, Maj. Jan Zeman is back on duty 10 years after
the end of communist rule, in pursuit of lawbreakers and
subversives who threaten the social order. The fictional Maj. Zeman
was the former Czechoslovakia's favorite television police
detective during communist times. A decision by Czech Television to
re-broadcast the 1970s serial has raised a fierce debate in the
Czech Republic over whether the show is propaganda or entertainment
or history. It comes at a sensitive time when the present-day
Communist Party is enjoying a surge in support amid the country's
economic malaise. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: The anniversary of the Czech ``Velvet Revolution'' is
Wed., Nov. 17. Re-sending this story for those papers who haven't
used it previously.) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-POLL _ WASHINGTON _ Would you send your child to a good
school near your home or to a better school that is pretty
difficult to get to? In a national poll released by Public Agenda,
the nonpartisan, nonprofit research group, 40 percent chose the
closest school and 54 percent chose the better school. The
pollsters also discovered that most parents aren't interested in
and admit knowing ``little'' or ``nothing'' about two often-touted
reforms _ school vouchers and public charter schools. (Mollison,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-REACTION _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Alcee Hastings of
Florida and other black Democratic House members join
representatives of the NACCP and the National Urban League at a
news conference Friday to discuss ``Florida Gov. Jeb Bush's
proposal to end affirmative action in Florida.'' (Schultz, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-MOVIE _ WASHINGTON _ ``Y2K: The Movie'' is an
``irresponsible'' spark that could
</P>
<P>
   light a panic among many Americans. But it also could do some
good if it leads
</P>
<P>
   people to take sensible precautions for Jan. 1 computer
glitches. That was the
</P>
<P>
   split verdict among a dozen government and industry officials
who gathered with
</P>
<P>
   a reporter this week to watch a preview copy of the NBC
suspense-thriller, which
</P>
<P>
   airs at 9 p.m. EST Sunday. (Geewax, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Most presidential candidates have been
burning up the talk show circuit for months. Front-running George
W. Bush finally makes his debut this week, with an appearance on
20/20 Wednesday, and on Sunday's Week in Review. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-FUND _ ATLANTA _ Democratic presidential candidate Bill
Bradley will be
</P>
<P>
   in Atlanta today for a fund-raiser at the home of Anne Cox
Chambers, a media magnate and former Gore supporter who parted ways
with the VP over cable regulation. He will also meet with students
and faculty at Morehouse Medical School. Later Bradley will meet
with members of the Jewish community, many of whom are in town for
the United Jewish Communities' General Assembly. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-ADS _ WASHINGTON _ Democrat Bill Bradley debuts his
first television advertisements of the campaign Tuesday. The ads,
produced by a Madison Avenue ad team, will run in Iowa and New
Hampshire beginning Wednesday. As merits. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   UGA-CLASSACTION _ ATLANTA _ U.S. District Judge B. Avant
Edenfield in Savannah rules that reverse discrimination case
against UGA, in terms of race and gender, can become a class-action
case. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ATLANTA _ There's been a lot of speculation in the
media about Lockheed Martin closing its Marietta plant. But the AJC
has obtained a draft of a plan that would give the nation's largest
defense contractor $150 million a year for the next three years to
keep the Marietta plant's C-130J line open. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JEWELL-LAWSUIT _ ATLANTA _ ABC has settled with onetime Olympic
bombing suspect Richard Jewell for $5,000, the network's New York
lawyer confirms. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-INTERNET _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander is expected to unveil an ambitious plan to make state and
local government more Internet accessible. She envisions, for
example, the ability to go on the web to renew your driver's
license and other government chores. (Rodriguez, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IN AMERICA 1118
</P>
<P>
   Eds: This is another story in a series of reports on life in
small-town America _ the values, the stories and the characters _
at the end of the millennium. Photos and a sig/locator map are
available.
</P>
<P>
   ALTO, Ga. _ I never knew a giant tree could rock a baby to
sleep, much less me. But it did. Yep. I slept in a tree. A
125-foot-tall tulip poplar. Her name is Rachel. Sleeping in a tree
isn't something to do when you need your rest, but it's something
unforgettable. I wasn't alone. We were a tree ``village'' of five,
each with different reasons for being there, just as each would
have different responses to the night in Rachel's arms. (Ezzard,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GA-BAPTISTS _ ATLANTA _ Report on vote of Ga. Baptist
Convention, expected to remove two churches from its rolls for
being too accepting of gays and lesbians. Convention will also be
electing a new president in a race expected to be uncontested,
adopting an annual budget, etc. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-FIRES _ ATLANTA _ Wildfires have forced the closing of an the
Appalachian Trail section in North Georgia, U.S. Forest Service
officials said today. Some trails had been closed Monday, but
officials added the Appalachian Trail segment in White County as of
9 a.m. today. The fires have burned more than 2,100 acres in the
Blood Mountain Wilderness Area. No homes or highways are threatened
at this time. (Badie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   FLU-BODIES _ Semi-frozen bodies unearthed a year ago in the
Arctic and dismissed by scientists as worthless have unexpectedly
yielded a scientific prize: fragments of the virus that caused the
1918 Spanish influenza pandemic, which killed 40 million poeple in
11 months and was one of the worst epidemics in recorded history.
At a virology conference held Tuesday in London, a member of the
Arctic research team revealed that the the brains and organs taken
from the bodies, six coal miners who died on a remote Norwegian
island in October 1918, are ``riddled'' with the virus. (McKenna,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
