<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COMDEX17-COX     11-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET IMAGES SHINE AT COMDEX
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Judging by the buzz Tuesday at the Comdex computer
trade show, sharing your favorite snapshots online with family and
friends or, if you like, with the whole world, will be the next big
thing to hit the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   With prices for digital cameras, scanners and ink-jet color
printers falling fast, as quality continues to improve, the
consumer market for Internet images appears ready to forge ahead.
Spurring growth, experts here say, will be faster Internet
pipelines into homes, improved compression formats and
user-friendly Web sites. The sites offer easy remote editing of
pictures while hosting free storage and retrieval services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for huge growth is certainly there,'' said
Kristy Holch. As head of the Infotrends Research Group, a
Boston-based market consulting firm, Holch invited Bill Gates and
other industry leaders to review the latest online imaging trends
with reporters and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Gates spoke not as Microsoft's chairman but in his lesser-known
role as the 1989 founder and sole owner of Corbis, home to some 65
million digital images, with more than 2.1 million of them
available online. The company licenses its huge library to
professionals as well as offering consumers both fee-based and free
services on its web site, www.corbis.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to browsing (online) for the photos that you're
most interested in, it's still too slow,'' Gates said, ``You'd be
better off to have somebody FedEx you a bunch of photos and then
look through those,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But such frustrations should ease soon, Gates predicted, as U.S.
households increasingly become equipped with speedy links to
cyberspace, through new technologies that are currently entering
the broad marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Gates predicted, flat-panel screens, speakers and
wireless networks will become commonplace items in American homes.
``They are already installed in the house that I live in,'' Gates
noted, ``but of course not at a reasonable price.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll be able to go through your database and pick out
life-like images,'' he said. ``And you can put them on whatever
screen you prefer, whether it's in your living room or on the
refrigerator.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how quickly other people catch up with the
richest man in the world in the image-capture department. ``Bill
has access at his home to stuff that even we can't look at,'' said
Peter Howe, Corbis' vice president for photography and creative
services, after Gates had left the room.
</P>
<P>
   According to Infotrends' Holch, by the end of the year, 8
percent of U.S. households will own either a digital camera, a
camcorder or a ``roving eye'' tethered to a personal computer now.
Fewer than 15 percent own a scanner, Holch said.
</P>
<P>
   But even consumers with access to only $5 toss-away cameras can
smoothly move into the digital realm if they have an Internet
account.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Kodak and America Online created a ``You've
Got Pictures'' facility that is proving increasingly popular with
AOL's 18 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Users take their film in to be developed and pick up their
prints and negatives in normal fashion. But if they check a box and
fill in their screen name, their pictures will also be delivered
electronically to a PC via the Internet. From there, AOL makes it a
simple task for users to e-mail the pictures or to store them on a
computer's hard drive
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, both dedicated and portal-based ``photo
communities'' are sprouting on the Internet. ``Its the Poloraid
effect,'' said David Rowley, president of PhotoPoint, one such
image hosting site. ``People love to see the picture at once and to
share it quickly with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowley's service, at www.photopoint.com, allows its members
unlimited free storage of their photos online. They can be
captioned, cropped and linked to online auction sites, such as
eBay. Users can determine who else, if anyone, can view their
virtual albums.
</P>
<P>
   But even if sites such as PhotoPoint should blossom, they'll
still be a place for old-fashioned prints, to be largely digitally
produced in the future, said Bruce Chizen, executive vice president
of Adobe Systems, a leading supplier of image editing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will still want to have a piece of paper to work
with,'' Chizen predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
