<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AFFIRMATIVE-REACTION1     11-16 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-REACTION17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGISLATORS, CIVIL RIGHTS GROUPS OPPOSE JEB BUSH FOR ELIMINATING
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION PROGRAMS
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Federal lawmakers joined civil rights groups
Tuesday to speak out against ending affirmative action in Florida
as proposed by Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The affirmative action law was all we had for a chance at
equality of opportunity,'' said Rep. Carrie Meek, a Democrat from
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   An executive order issued by Bush last week reaffirmed the
state's commitment to pursuing diversity, it but eliminated
affirmative actionprograms for university admissions, state
contracts and government employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush says he wants to promote diversity, but he
doesn't want laws to enforce it,'' Rep. Corrine Brown, a Democrat
from Jacksonville, said. ``But without these laws, diversity and
opportunity won't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said affirmative action gave her the opportunity to run
for elected office in Florida as a black woman. She held up a pie
with a sliver cut out illustrating the small number_ 2 percent _ of
state contracts that women and minorities receive from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pie is sliced up,'' Brown said, ``we need to all get
a piece. As it stands now, we barely get a sliver.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown sent letters alerting the Justice Department and other
federal agencies of Florida's plans to drop statewide affirmative
action last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's decision to eliminate equal opportunity
programs in the state of Florida is a mistake, and the
repercussions will be felt for generations to come,'' said Hilary
Shelton, Washington director of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alcee Hastings, a Democrat from Miramar, criticized Bush
for not consulting with black and minority lawmakers before issuing
the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it was a mistake for Governor Bush to fail to reach
out to the five black and Hispanic members of Congress, for it is
our communities who are to be impacted,'' Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, a D-Mich, and ranking member of the House
Judiciary Committee, called for hearings on Bush's order before the
committee, which has rejected proposals to end affirmative action
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
