<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OIL-ROYALTIES17-COX     11-16 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ROYALTIES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CRUSADE ENDS FOR OIL'S TOP SENATE DEFENDER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the past year and a half, Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, resolutely defended oil companies from paying
higher royalties for drilling on public lands.
</P>
<P>
   Almost single-handedly, she shut down action in the Senate on
the annual Interior appropriation bill until her colleagues agreed
to postpone new royalty regulations for at least one more year.
</P>
<P>
   But as Congress rushed to complete annual spending bills for the
federal government this week, the Republican leadership quietly
pulled the plug on Hutchison's crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., the key Interior appropriations
subcommittee chairman who had backed her before, told White House
negotiators Monday that the leadership would seek no more delays
for the royalty system, set to go into effect next March 15.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton will formalize his promise by letter or by a floor
statement, his spokeswoman, Cynthia Bergman, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's response was resigned. ``I'm disappointed with the
agreement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to attack the proposed new royalty system as
``complicated and unworkable,'' she predicted, as she has for more
than a year, that it will threaten jobs created by independent oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain hopeful that the new (Minerals Management Service)
director will work with Congress and the producers during this
shortened moratorium period to develop a fair and effective rule,''
she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, the industry is expected to pay $66
million more a year for drilling on federal property.
</P>
<P>
   The royalty payments are designated for education, conservation,
parks, state governments and Indian reservations. Critics have long
charged that the current system is so lax that it permits companies
to short-change the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win shows that ordinary citizens can still prevail in
Washington,'' said Danielle Brian, executive director of Project on
Government Oversight. The Washington-based watchdog group has led
the effort to make oil companies pay the full bill owed for
drilling on the public's land.
</P>
<P>
   States, including Alaska, California and Texas, have collected
nearly $5 billion in lawsuit settlements in royalty disputes.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Hutchison has been the energy industry's top
defender as well as its top campaign money recipient. During the
last election cycle, the oil and gas industry donated $1.2 million
to her re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute Tuesday restated its opposition
to the royalty rules drafted by the Clinton administration as too
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have consistently said that the industry wants a rule that
is fair, simple, workable and that conforms to existing statutory
and lease provisions,'' the group said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The institute called on the Minerals Management Service to start
from scratch on the royalty rules.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
