<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1621 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CONTEMPORARY18-COX     11-16 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPORARY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New generation of buyers discovers something different in
contemporary lines
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 16.
 &HT;    By Danny Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Soon after moving into his condo in Midtown Atlanta
two years ago, Daylon Lutzenberger faced a dilemma shared by other
first-time home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   His furnishings, a mix of hand-me-downs and inexpensive pieces
acquired since college, were comfortable, but their traditional
look didn't reflect the fresh modern environment of a high-rise
unit with its skyline view. ``I'd gotten very tired of all the dark
woods and formal prints,'' said the 34-year-old telecommunications
manager for Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   Lutzenberger wanted a more contemporary feel, but it wasn't the
radical leap to sleek surfaces and harsh lines he sought. By
working on a limited budget with an interior designer, he
discovered a warm transitional look that comes from furnishings
with clean lines, light woods, satin metal finishes and textured
fabrics _ one that fits his busy lifestyle to a T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contemporary is something that speaks of today's time and
place,'' said Herbert Brito, Lutzenberger's designer.
</P>
<P>
   And, as young successful professionals move in on baby boomers
in the home decorating market, manufacturers are responding with
soft contemporary furnishings that create comfortable, inviting
rooms while giving buyers something a little different.
</P>
<P>
   Those furnishings became a common thread among lines shown this
month at the Chicago Design Show, the nation's top trade preview of
high-end contemporary pieces from around the world, destined for
showrooms by early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Driving them, designers said, are a number of factors _ fashion
trends, mass media design exposure, a nostalgic recall of classic
lines as a new century looms, a strong economy ripe for risk
taking, the home invasion of technology.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, a market dominated by traditional tastes,
contemporary continues to make noteworthy inroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think old Atlanta is still in a traditional mind-set for the
most part,'' said Atlanta interior designer Charles Gandy. ``But we
have so many people moving in here from all over the world that the
concepts of the traditional South are slowly changing and becoming
more contemporary.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning for technology
</P>
<P>
   Many contemporary consumers are transient professionals eager to
express themselves differently from their baby boomer parents. ``A
lot of the wealth in the past few years has been among young people
with Internet start-ups,'' said Mayer Rus, editor of Interior
Design magazine.
</P>
<P>
   They're not in gray suits sitting behind desks but in blue jeans
juggling laptops. ``It's a new generation trying to define itself
with a different way of showing its success,'' Rus said.
</P>
<P>
   They're opting for furnishings with clean, simple lines yet ones
that make a statement among the mass-produced ``suites'' their
parents bought. They're often turning to classic modern pieces
considered cutting edge in their day and now dubbed a collective
``retro'' by young buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's sort of the right time for them. They're young
enough to care about it,'' Julia-Carr Baylor said of the vintage
modern furnishings she sells in her Atlanta showroom, Belvedere.
``It's all about good lines and shapes. And I think, at the end of
the day, if something's designed really well it always comes back
in style.''
</P>
<P>
   While looking back, young consumers also must look forward,
because the impact that technology will have on homes can't be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is going to explode, and as it does it will change
how we design homes,'' said interior designer Gandy. ``No longer
will we need an armoire. We'll just hang the TV on the wall like a
picture. We used to never do home offices. Now, everybody has
one.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge will be to maintain the cozy atmosphere of home
while avoiding the harsh look of the office. To do that, more
emphasis than ever may be placed on furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Though plenty of manufacturers at the Chicago show offered
sleek, high-tech designs, the emphasis was on soft, clean lines and
warm materials.
</P>
<P>
   In his American Revisionist collection for FreWil, Los Angeles
designer Bil Wilson created a classic yet contemporary line of
'40s-inspired furnishings that borrows elements from both a
traditionalist, Duncan Phyfe, and a modernist, Paul Frankyl.
``Until now, most of my collections have been high modern,'' he
said. ``With this, I'm going for a broader traditional market that
wants clean lines but not the same old thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The transitional pieces easily could blend with both traditional
and contemporary decors.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Brand Furniture was targeting the lure of nostalgia with a
collection that recalls the Hollywood glamour of the same era.
Chairs with gentle curves and contoured lines feature maple with
textured fabrics that make you want to snuggle, while a glasstop
coffee table offers a more contemporary feel with its mix of steel,
leather and Douglas fir.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going after the first-time home buyer who wants comfort
and style but with an almost heirloom quality,'' Brand said. ``The
pieces have contemporary refinement but are almost traditional in
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the transition designers say a growing number of new
homeowners like Lutzenberger are after.
</P>
<P>
   Making the shift
</P>
<P>
   Because his job requires him to travel so much, the Atlantan
wanted his first home to be an inviting retreat that offers
everything a hotel, office and airplane don't. He wanted a calm and
relaxing interior away from the buzz of computers and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   His designer, Brito, helped him create such a setting that
emphasizes warm, natural materials but with simple lines that play
off the urban locale of Atlanta's Hanover House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all slowly evolved,'' Lutzenberger recalled. ``Generally,
Americans think of contemporary as black and white and chrome, very
sterile and cold. But we used warm tones, such as textured sisal
and wool rugs and a mix of leather and fabrics along with granite,
limestone and lots of maple.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was able to take advantage of Brito's access to
products available only to the trade, most of the furnishings came
from mainstream contemporary retailers, such as Innovations and
Domus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something done on a shoestring,'' Brito said, ``but we
kept it very simple, shopped around and then customized a few
things we couldn't find so that his money went into some special
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room, he designed a round glasstop table with
sapple wood base, then paired it with simple chrome and birch
Philippe Starck chairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the master bedroom, Lutzenberger needed an attractive
headboard, so Brito created a large concave square substitute and
upholstered it to pick up the lines and upholstery of a bedside
chair and ottoman. ``For someone who doesn't have an interesting
bed or can't afford the art to hang over one, you can let a
headboard like this become the focal point of the room,'' the
designer said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled throughout the two-story condo are remnants of
Lutzenberger's past love for traditional _ an old black trunk here,
a mahogany armoire there _ which don't seem that out of place with
his new passion for soft contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been quite a journey to get to this point,'' he said,
``but now when I come home after traveling all week, this is where
I want to be. It's so fresh and clean and comfortable, it's almost
therapeutic.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
