<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greens take the spotlight in Meriwether woman's garden this time
of year
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 18.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRANTVILLE, Ga. _ Ellen Frances Rosser, like so many food
gardeners, never stops growing for the table. Assorted victuals
thrive even as food crops for us hot-weather growers fade into
faraway memory.
</P>
<P>
   For dabblers like me, the list of edibles is pitifully short to
begin with, as is harvest time; my tomatoes and cayenne peppers, my
1999 food output, are long gone. But, when I visited Rosser
recently at her Meriwether County home near the Coweta line, the
growing patch was so lush, it might as well have been summer.
</P>
<P>
   Collards, cabbage, several types of mustards and turnips were
fully leafed out, beckoning us _ Rosser, her south Fulton County
daughter Marsha Ramsey, and me _ to admire.
</P>
<P>
   How tender the lovely green leaves look and feel this time of
year, when so much else in the garden has shriveled and died. What
culinary memories they evoke. And what promises they make as
Thanksgiving, that greatest of all eating holidays, draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Across the yard, rose and other blooms added their own fresh,
fragrant contrast to the season of supposed decline _ most notably,
the camellia that was planted in a 1-gallon nursery container 20
years ago. It remains in that container, its roots grown through
the bottom to support its 10-foot height.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was engaged in something else,'' explained Rosser, who is 83
years old. ``I never got around to planting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Food crops always were planted, though. Ever since Rosser and
her husband, parents of 11 children, moved into this home in
November 1941. Recent crops include corn, peas and okra, one of
whose 6-foot skeletons still stood on this day, a single pod
perched atop the plant, drying.
</P>
<P>
   But greens star these days. I could just taste them on a
Thanksgiving plate, seasoned with fatback or ham hock, accented
with okra and joined by corn bread and mashed potatoes, pork chops,
duck, peas, beans _ and whatever else talented cooks make for us
eager eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey, a star chef and caterer, whose sumptuous dishes of
barbecue, chicken and all manner of vegetables and pies warm the
hearts of many, was eager to get picking. So, she waded into the
greens patch and filled a bag with leaves while her mother
kibitzed, warning her daughter not to damage the tender treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Appetites whetted but still a few hours away from mealtime, the
three of us went inside to do what food lovers do when we're not
eating: We talked about eating. Dominating the kitchen and our
conversation was a luxury model Maytag gas range, now almost 50
years old, white enamel, trimmed in real chrome.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Rosser said, her children have urged, ``Mama,
get yourself a new stove.'' But she always replies: ``This stove
knows me, and I know it. I don't want to learn any new
appliances.''
</P>
<P>
   As we stood around this incredible cooking machine, mother and
daughter recalled the meals it has known, while my mouth watered at
the memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all learned how to cook on this stove,'' said Ramsey of her
brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   And they all learned how to grow in the garden. As their mother
still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be fall without my greens,'' Rosser said.
``They'll be here for Christmas,'' getting tender in the chills and
freezes. By then, Rosser will be thinking of spring crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planting is never over with me,'' she said. ``I just love my
garden year-round.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee May is a regular columnist on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
