A1623 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MTV-BIORHYTHM17-COX     11-16 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-BIORHYTHM17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MTV on Holocaust: A horrific history lesson'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Living skeletons wander through concentration camps. Naked
corpses are thrown into a pit. Synagogues burn.
</P>
<P>
   The images of the Holocaust are profoundly disturbing, but when
they're given the MTV treatment _ whip-edited into a brain-jarring,
jangling frenzy, speeding by so fast as to be almost subliminal _
they become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Bear it. MTV's Holocaust special tonight is deeply righteous
television, a blend of hip style and timeless content that
shouldn't work but does. Older folks will probably hate it, but
MTV's target audience _ roughly 12- to 24-year-olds _ will get the
history lesson of their young lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``BIOrhythm'' is MTV's version of A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' series,
half-hour assemblages of snippets on pop culturati such as Britney
Spears and Jim Carrey. Producer Jeff Olde, who did a ``BIO'' last
year on the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., says he wanted to continue
to stretch the show. So he went to Steven Spielberg's SHOAH
Foundation, which tapes interviews with Holocaust survivors, and
they pointed him to Bert Strauss, 74, who was a teenage Jew in
Germany when Hitler came to power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation will not last long,'' Strauss recalls his
family saying as the Nazis enacted anti-Jewish laws. ``It's a
temporary solution.'' Within a few years he was in a railroad car
headed to a death camp called Stutthof, where he recalls ``the
smoke, the odor of burning flesh.'' He was 15.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss, who speaks at high schools about the Holocaust, is the
story here, but he's also a symbolic stand-in for the 6 million
Jews killed in the Holocaust, and the millions of others who died.
</P>
<P>
   The special jumps maniacally between Strauss' interview and the
archival horrors, which play like a fever dream. But Strauss'
detailed narrative, and Olde's onscreen fact-flashing, leave no
doubt that this was no dream, that this happened. And is still
happening, in its own twisted way _ one of the last images in the
show is of an American rally of neo-Nazi youth earlier this year,
giving the raised-arm salute to a giant burning swastika.
</P>
<P>
   In a half hour (22 minutes without commercials) there can be no
real depth or context given. That is for other endeavors, and
``BIO'' should not be faulted for being what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``BIOrhythm: Holocaust''
</P>
<P>
   10:30 tonight on MTV
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
