A1624 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WORKSHOP-GARDENSCALE1     11-16 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-GARDENSCALE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to construct garden scales
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Nov. 18.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you've ever read the instructions for applying
fertilizers, insecticides or weed preventers to your lawn and
scratched your head, you're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   They typically call for spreading X amount over X area.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't have a spreader for putting out .5 pounds of
crabgrass preventer per 1,000 square feet, for example, how do you
measure?'' said Walter Reeves, the Georgia Extension Service's
horticulture educator.
</P>
<P>
   His fifth-grade science teacher taught him well.
</P>
<P>
   In his metro Atlanta yard, Reeves creates a makeshift set of
garden scales using a carpenter's level, heavy-gauge wire and a
pair of plastic buckets, then suspends the contraption from a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Using the baseline of 1 pint equaling 1 pound, Reeves begins
filling one bucket with water and the other with the desired amount
of material until the level indicates the scales are balanced. He
remembers the parts by reciting the old saw ``A pint is a pound the
world around.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple apparatus takes only minutes to assemble and costs
less than $10, he said.
</P>
<P>
   STEP 1: Using heavy cord and wire, Walter Reeves hangs a
carpenter's level from a tree and drills a hole in each end of the
level. He then hangs a bucket from each side, attaching it with
wire threaded through one of the holes.
</P>
<P>
   STEP 2: Pour a pint of water (16 ounces) into one of the
buckets. This will be the equivalent of 1 pound.
</P>
<P>
   STEP 3 and 4: Pour fertilizer (in this case, the granular kind)
into the other bucket, stopping when the bubble is in the center of
the level. The scales will have measured a pound of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   S U P P L I E S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A level
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2 plastic buckets
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Heavy-gauge wire
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cord
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A drill
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
