u p BC-BRADLEY-ADS-COX     11-16 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley's new TV spots makes formal introduction to voters
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying Bill Bradley is still largely unknown
despite 11 months of campaigning, his campaign previewed two
television ads Tuesday designed to introduce Bradley to voters.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second biographical spot set to begin in Iowa today and New
Hampshire Thursday portrays Bradley as a ``basketball hero'' and a
straight-talking senator who tackled tax reform, race and health
care while in office.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign on Tuesday also launched a new feature on Bradley's
Web site that allows Internet users to access streaming video of
Bradley and other senators talking about his life and record.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign appearances, Bradley has sought to portray himself
as a Washington outsider who led a life outside of politics before
winning a New Jersey Senate seat in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But the biographical ad focuses heavily on Bradley's Washington
experience, flashing views of the Capitol and including brief
interviews with Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.) and Bob
Kerrey (D-Neb.).
</P>
<P>
   The script includes some hyperbole. Moynihan describes the 1986
Tax Reform Act, which Bradley sponsored, as the ``first major
reform of the 20th century. . . Bill made it happen,'' Moynihan
says to the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley played a central role in the bill, but he was one of
many members of Congress, including Rep. Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.), now
the House minority leader, and former Republican Sen. Bob Packwood
of Oregon, who had a hand in the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also features a New Jersey woman named Maureen Drumm, who
went to Bradley when he was in the Senate and urged him to support
legislation requiring insurers to cover two days of hospital care
for childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to Senator Bradley, my daughter is alive today,'' Drumm
says in the spot. Bradley's bill ending so-called ``drive-through
deliveries'' became law in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley spokeswoman Anita Dunn also said the spots were
presented to focus groups for feedback. But she said the
focus-group input did not change the overall message of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has repeatedly said that his campaign would not rely on
polls or focus groups, but instead communicate what he believes is
right for the country.
</P>
<P>
   A second ad, set to air in both Iowa and New Hampshire next
week, features Bradley pledging to run a substantive campaign based
on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be better if we had more than sound bites and
photo ops when we were choosing a candidate?'' Bradley says.
``Sometimes you'll agree with me; sometimes you won't. But at least
you'll know exactly where I stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Both ads were produced by a consortium of advertising experts
from Washington to Madison Avenue. Vice President Al Gore already
has run four different ads in the two battleground states, and Dunn
said Bradley was to some extent playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Bradley is still not as well known to people,'' Dunn
said. ``They know the vice president very well. . . . We need to
have voters get to know Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
