<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TURKEY-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      11-16 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKS GIVE AMERICAN PRESIDENT A WARM WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IZMIT, Turkey _ The red carpets were rolled out. The press
gushed with praise. And even in this devastated city, traumatized
earthquake victims lined their tent floors with colorful rugs and
poured coffee to welcome President Clinton, his wife and his
daughter on this cold, rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Clintion. I love you,'' declared a sign
hand-painted by a Turkish boy, one of about 20 kindergartners being
taught in the makeshift tent school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children of America are thinking of you,'' Clinton told
the youngsters. Hearing the translation, the excited children
shouted ``thank you!'' in English. While one child held a US flag,
the group sang the Clinton family a Turkish children's song about a
very small bird.
</P>
<P>
   For the oft-beleaguered Clinton, his visit to Turkey has been a
welcome series of greetings, compliments and gratitude for his
promises of disaster aid and closer economic ties with the United
States. His popularity here has not been hurt by a series of
anti-Clinton protests in neighboring, archrival Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Turks have been just as effusive with the first family. At a
state dinner in Clinton's honor Monday, President Suleyman Demirel
repeatedly commented on Hillary Rodham Clinton's ``elegance'' and
lauded her ``intellectual personality.''
</P>
<P>
   At the tent city in Izmit, Turkish greeters presented Mrs.
Clinton with pink roses. While the president _ who has been on a
nonstop schedule for several days _ struggled against obvious
exhaustion, and Mrs. Clinton queried mothers about the
psychological state of their children, Chelsea exhibited perhaps
the strongest emotional connection with the sufferers of the August
quake.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest Clinton held a smitten 2-year-old in her lap.
Later, children who had been in a gym class under a large tent
broke away when they saw Chelsea, swarming around her before posing
for pictures with the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Yoldas, a paper factory worker injured in the earthquake,
expressed his ``honor and happiness to meet the president,'' as the
Clinton and Yoldas families shared cookies and tea under the
Yoldas's tent.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's headlines in the Turkish press couldn't have been more
positive if they had been written by the White House press office.
``Like a Turk,'' two newspapers described the US leader in banner
headlines, a description meant as high praise.
</P>
<P>
   Other papers headlined Clinton's Turkey-friendly message.
``Clinton: We Are On Your Side,'' said Zaman, a religious
newspaper. ``The Future Is Turkey,'' said Ortadogu, a nationalist
publication. Most papers quoted extensively from Clinton's speech
and included photos of the smiling president.
</P>
<P>
   The reception is in contrast to the welcome Clinton is expected
to get Friday, when he travels to Greece, a military ally of both
the United States and Turkey, but long at odds with Turkey over the
fate of Cyprus and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls in Greece show that 83 percent are opposed
to a visit by the US president, a State Department official said.
Clinton already has cut his visit to Greece from three days to one
day.
</P>
<P>
   But in Turkey, the feeling is almost universally friendly toward
Clinton, whose five days in the West-leaning, Islamic nation will
be the longest stay here by any US president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's rhetoric has been encouraging to the controversial
nation, often a target of criticism for its human rights record.
While even Demirel admitted that ``clearly, there is torture'' in
Turkey, Clinton was understanding, almost apologetic, saying that
even the United States had had slavery and denied voting rights to
women and non-landowners when the nation was young.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Clinton arrive empty-handed. He promised loan guarantees
to help rebuild after the most recent quake, which hit the eastern
town of Duzce on Friday. The United States is also sending 500
tents to shelter the quake victims, who are facing a cold winter.
US disaster aid teams have already been dispatched to the area to
help.
</P>
<P>
   On trade, Clinton told Turkish and American business leaders
Tuesday that the Overseas Private Investment Corp. will ``double
its activity in Turkey'' to more than $1 billion. Further, the
Export-Import Bank will provide $1 billion in lending authority to
12 Turkish banks.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is still reeling from the effects of the Russian fiscal
crisis of 1998, as well as two quakes in three months. Annual
wholesale inflation was 65 percent in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
