<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1639 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-HOSPITALS-INTERNS-IV-     11-16 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-INTERNS-IV-5TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH WARINESS AND JOY, INTERNS STEP UP
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Last in a series.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carol Lampkin was a chatty woman with a sweeping
smile who needed a lot of medical attention. And she did not want
it from anyone but Dr. Jennifer James.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lampkin's principal complaint was reflex sympathetic
dystrophy _ pain without underlying cause, the sort of phantom limb
pain amputees sometimes suffer. She had broken her neck in a
motorcycle accident when she was 23, but it did not affect her
until she was 47, and since then she had had several surgeries.
Now, at 53, she felt numbness along her right cheek down to her
first two toes. ``I feel a burning sensation and a tingling,'' she
said. ``I feel like I've been electrocuted.''
</P>
<P>
   She used a walker or a cane. Among other ailments, she suffered
from hypertension. She had had a civilian desk job with the New
York City Police Department, but work was now out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James saw her in the outpatient clinic during her first
month of internship, and she had been back repeatedly. She always
kept her appointments and Dr. James appreciated that. Inside her
clinic exam room at St. Luke's Hospital, Ms. Lampkin glowed.
Sometimes, her pain got so bad that she had to be admitted to the
hospital. She would call to inform Dr. James, and Dr. James would
make a point of dropping in to see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted me to her was she was nice and courteous,'' Ms.
Lampkin said. ``She takes the time to listen. It's not easy to get
that, because when you're in the clinic they take your blood
pressure, talk to you for a minute and you're gone. She wanted to
know about me. And if she doesn't know something, she doesn't make
it up. She goes and reads up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   In her fidelity, Ms. Lampkin represented what the teachers meant
when they talked about ``continuity of care'' _ doctor and patient
bonding like atoms in a molecule. Caring for Ms. Lampkin was what
Dr. James had in mind way back in July, when she had said, ``What a
doctor is is being compassionate and just being there for people.''
Most of the time, especially with all the pressures brought on by
managed care, the hospital moved too erratically, too fast. Here in
the spring of her internship, though, it was that kind of bond that
made Dr. James feel happiest about medicine.
</P>
<P>
   She thought fondly of another clinic patient: The first time she
saw him, she threw him out. He told her he had once worked for the
CIA and now sold books on the street and fought unknown demons. He
drank 24 to 36 beers a day and smoked heavily. He was drunk. He got
abusive. But he returned another week, behaved properly, and Dr.
James accepted him as a challenge. He had suffered a stroke but
refused necessary surgery. She coaxed him into it. Afterward, he
told her, ``You saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've almost gotten him to stop smoking,'' she said, ``and we
talk about stopping drinking. I think I'm getting closer. With him,
I feel I really did something. I was a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   She brought in her next patient. He was new, a little
turned-inward, a little bellicose. He believed he had sprained his
ankle on a crack in the sidewalk. He said the emergency room had
told him he needed new shoes, not medical care. He walked a lot. He
was homeless. He wanted an X-ray. She said that was unnecessary.
His ankles were swollen. She told him that meant something might be
going on with his heart; she wanted other tests done.
</P>
<P>
   He said no and no and no. He was loud and brassy. ``You must
think I'm stupid,'' he said. ``You don't want to spend the money on
an X-ray. If you don't want to treat me right, I'll go somewhere
else.'' She persevered. He said no. Exasperated, she brought in her
supervisor. She watched as he knelt down and listened patiently to
the man, gave credence to his opinion but nudged him toward Dr.
James' view. The man capitulated. She wondered if it was because
the supervisor was older and a man.
</P>
<P>
   She did not let that bother her. Her next two patients failed to
show up. She had time. The man's shoes were too small and tattered.
She asked him if he wanted to go to the volunteer department to
look at the donated clothes. She and her husband both gave clothing
there. She thought his feet looked the same size as her husband's.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they sifted through bins of used shoes. She dug out a
pair of 11{ sneakers. He slipped them on. ``These feel real good,''
he said. A smile blossomed. ``Thank you, doctor,'' he told her. Out
in the real world, when would she ever have time to find a man a
pair of shoes? She did not think of it that way, just that a
connection had been made. ``That was cool,'' she said. ``It felt
really cool to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Step Off the Treadmill
</P>
<P>
   Time sped by in the final months, more of a blur. The fatigue,
though, persisted. Even during vacation, Dr. Bryan Holland slept
poorly. His body was used to no sleep. He had deliberately stopped
watching ``E.R.,'' the staple of doctors in training. It felt like
a continuation of work. His parents had given him a keyboard for
Christmas, and he unwound by playing it, mostly Mozart and some
Beethoven. He had been reading Robert Frost.
</P>
<P>
   He worked relentlessly. He found that he was really obsessive,
always wanting everything done just so, and he knew he was probably
going to drive the interns he supervised next year crazy. He had no
patience for interns who complained endlessly about how taxing the
work was. ``I think they should suck it up and go on,'' he said at
dinner one night. ``They should feel blessed that they're in the
position.''
</P>
<P>
   One day he had a treat _ a glimpse of life beyond residency. He
spent the afternoon at the private office of Dr. Steven Wolf,
director of the pediatric neurology clinic.
</P>
<P>
   He saw a succession of cases of attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   A young boy with a wild tassel of hair came in, compulsively
talkative. He could not sit still for a moment. Holland asked him
what he watched on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch every cartoon that has green, brown or red or gray or
blue. The cartoons in black and white, I don't think they're so
funny. Did you know the `I Love Lucy Show' used to be called the `I
Can't Stand Ethel Show?'''
</P>
<P>
   His mother said he had a lot of anger inside him. He fought
constantly with his brother. The boy then interrupted to say that
his teacher liked to punch kids and kick them and pull their hair.
``He even likes electrocuting the kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf came in. He asked Holland to describe the movements he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't seem like tics,'' Holland said. ``They seem
voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said, ``Right. Just a fidgety kid with ants in his pants.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he said, ``So Dr. Holland, would you classify him as
attention deficit disorder? Dangerous word.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland: ``He's borderline, but I wouldn't classify him as that
as yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf: ``So he has symptoms of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Wolf told the mother: ``What I'd like to do is gather more
information. I'm going to give you a teacher evaluation form for
the school so we can get more information.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy said, ``To gather more information about my family,
please contact Dumb brother.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said, ``This is a clever kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland liked being in a real office. It was far less chaotic
than the clinic, with more involved parents with better insurance
than the Medicaid patients he usually saw. To a young doctor
learning the subtle arts of diagnosis, it was a welcome step off
the clinic treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   He admired Wolf's style. But he also saw the unmistakable
pressures. With night pressing in, Wolf's staff had gone home. He
continued seeing patients, never failing to ask for every $10 and
$15 co-payment. Insurance cutbacks were killing him, he said. His
revenues dropped year by year. Having interns do some office shifts
was one way to prop up the economics. He did other things now, like
expert testimony in court cases and patient studies for drug
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Holland came to understand that he was treating
not just a child, but also the often incoherent effects of an
environment full of perils and mysteries. ``I've learned that you
really have two patients _ the child and the mother,'' he said. ``I
notice now when mothers are calm when they bring in a sick child.
Why isn't that mother agitated? What comes to mind is, the mother
is not attentive.''
</P>
<P>
   He very much appreciated that it was strange times. Working the
ward on his final rotation, he was stupefied by a 14-year-old girl
who said she had already had 68 sexual partners. When a week later,
a 17-year-old said she had had 13 partners, no one blinked.
</P>
<P>
   And then Holland was taking a history from a mother of a
4-year-old boy. He got to the section about relatives. The mother
said the boy's sister had been shot to death two days ago. Holland
went numb. He looked at his sheet. The next part dealt with form of
payment. He could not bring himself to ask. He left it blank. The
hospital would have to figure that out.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
