<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CHRISTMAS-1700(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING A LONE STAR CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In San Antonio, they celebrate with luminarias on the River Walk
and re-enactments of Joseph and Mary's search for shelter. In
Galveston, it's a parade of lights _ at sea. And in San Angelo,
it's an Old West party, with campfire concerts and a military
parade.
</P>
<P>
   All over Texas, the holiday season is greeted with festivities,
from jolly to sacred, traditional to bohemian. So put off the
shopping, pack an overnight bag and bring home some holiday cheer
from one of our favorite celebrations:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO: With luminarias glowing throughout downtown, San
Antonio rivals even Santa Fe for the Southwest's warmest, most
romantic feel in its deeply cultural celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking off the nearly 100 events spread out over roughly a
month is the lighting of some 750,000 lights Nov. 20 on the
University of the Incarnate Word campus, followed Nov. 25 by the
illumination of legions of snowflake lights at the Witte Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The River Walk's profusion of lights twinkle to life Nov. 26,
when the annual river parade and lighting ceremony commences at 7
p.m. The same day, the Fort Worth Dallas Ballet and the San Antonio
Symphony begin a weekend run of ``The Nutcracker'' at the Lila
Cockrell Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The city's rich Hispanic heritage inspires a wealth of
celebrations, starting with the Fiestas Navidenas, which will kick
off Nov. 27 with a mariachi celebration and the lighting of Market
Square. The same day, Pancho Claus arrives at Alamo Plaza and the
Guadalupe Players offer a mini-performance of Los Pastores, the
Christmas story in Spanish, at the Witte Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta de las Luminarias, Dec. 3-5, 10-12 and 17-19, is the
candlelighting of the River Walk to symbolize the lighting of the
way for the Holy Family. That's not to be confused with Las Posadas
on Dec. 12; that's the candelighted re-enactment of Joseph and
Mary's search for shelter by the local conservation society at
historic La Villita. All of which is different from La Gran Posada
on Dec. 17, when parishioners of the extraordinary San Fernando
Cathedral downtown do another re-enactment, culminating with a
musical presentation and Mexican fiesta at the cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   For details on these events, as well as holiday home tours in
the King William district and stage productions, contact the San
Antonio Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at (800) 447-3372 or visit
www.sanantoniocvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GALVESTON: This Gulf Coast town gets right into the holiday swim
with its annual Harbor Parade of Lights on Nov. 27, when lighted
and decorated sail and power boats cruise through Galveston Harbor
after sunset. Celebrators can participate by riding on the Colonel,
a 19th-century-style paddle-wheeler that will dock at Pier 23, or
by watching along the Pier 21 dock. Details, Galveston Island
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau, (888) 425-4753.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Galveston's famous Strand historic district is
transformed into Victorian England for Dickens on the Strand, Dec.
4-5. Very merry revelers deck out in period clothing and jam the
streets to enjoy the old London-style markets by day and the
rollicking street-party scene at night. Expect everything from
handbell choirs and bagpipe bands to the queen's guard of
beefeaters to wizards and sword-swallowers. Info from the
historical foundation, (409) 765-7834.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES: For a holiday celebration honoring those from
Texas' Republic days, join in the Nine Flags Festival, Dec. 3-5 and
10-11, in this East Texas town. In addition to a lighted parade,
downtown marketplace, hayrides, candlelighted tour of Victorian
homes and afternoon tea, there will be a Texian Christmas at
Millard's Crossing, a village filled with authentic period
buildings, and Dickens storytelling in Oak Grove Cemetery, the
resting place of four signers of the Texas Declaration of
Independence. For details, call (888) 564-7351 or visit
www.visitnacogdoches.org.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LA GRANGE: Texas' early German heritage is gift-wrapped for the
season at this Central Texas burg, where the Monument Hill and
Kreische Brewery State Historical Park is aglow, Dec. 4, 11, and
17-18. Costumed living-history actors take small tour groups along
lighted pathways in the evening through the decorated 3-story home,
built in the 1850s by master stonemason H.L. Kreische.
Wassail-sipping and pastry snacking are included. For reservations,
call (409) 968-5658.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANGELO: Probably the most rugged of holiday settings is
found in this West Texas town, where the Concho Christmas
Celebration lasts from Dec. 3 till Dec. 31. Some 2 million lights
shine along the Concho River and throughout the vintage downtown
that first weekend, outlining pathways for walking and driving
tours.
</P>
<P>
   The month's activities include a cowboy campfire concert on Dec.
3, a Dec. 4 Asleep at the Wheel concert, a campfire breakfast Dec.
5 and period military parade ceremonies at the beautifully restored
Fort Concho National Historic Landmark, Dec. 3-5. All details can
be had from the convention and visitors bureau, (800) 375-1206.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   A baker's dozen of holiday happenings we can't resist:
</P>
<P>
   MARSHALL: Wonderland of Lights, Nov. 24-Dec. 30. How many
twinkling lights does it take to create a fairyland in the Harrison
County seat in East Texas? Would you believe 7 million? The county
historical museum and dozens of other buildings in this vintage
downtown are strung with more lights than the eye can comprehend.
Live entertainment adds to the merriment. (903) 935-7868.
</P>
<P>
   AMARILLO: Nite of Lights, Nov. 24-Jan. 1. Every evening through
New Year's, the Panhandle city's John Stiff Park will glow with 100
lighted scenes, including ice skaters, skiers, carolers and toys.
(800) 692-1338.
</P>
<P>
   CANYON: The esteemed Panhandle Plains Historical Museum holds
its annual Christmas Open House Dec. 3-5. Interpreters in costume
will re-enact Christmases past, including the Panhandle's pioneer
period, the roaring '20s, the Depression and Dust Bowl days, the
World War II years and the poodle-skirted '50s. There's music, food
and visits from Santa in his sleigh. (806) 651-2244.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Thanksgiving Day Parade, Nov. 25. Don't like baking
turkey or watching TV? Head to downtown Houston and see Toys on
Parade at 9 a.m. with 450,000 other spectators. (713) 654-8808.
</P>
<P>
   HILL COUNTRY: Christmas Lighting Trail, Nov. 26-Dec. 31. Eleven
pastoral towns west of Austin are draped in hundreds of thousands
of lights, and each of the hamlets offers individual festivities,
including historic homes tours, street markets, caroling, concerts
and dances. Check your map for the roads to Blanco, Bulverde,
Burnet, Dripping Springs, Fredericksburg, Goldthwaite, Johnson
City, Llano, Marble Falls, Mason and Round Mountain. (830)
997-8515.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON: Christmas Candelight Tour of Homes, Dec. 2-4, 9-11.
The Historic Jefferson Foundation opens four of the best
gingerbread homes in this East Texas riverboat town to the public.
Carolers add to the spirit. (903) 665-2672.
</P>
<P>
   LUBBOCK: Candlelight at the Ranch, Dec. 11-12. Take a trip back
to the turn of the century for a Panhandle Plains Christmas
interlude at the Ranching Heritage Center. (806) 742-2482.
</P>
<P>
   GRANBURY: Christmas celebrations south of Fort Worth begin with
a lighted parade on Nov. 26 and continue with the Enchanted Forest,
Nov. 27-28, Dec. 4-5 and Dec. 11-12, as well as the candlelight
homes tour, Dec. 4-5. (800) 950-2212.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINE: Victorian Christmas Steam Train rides, Dec. 4 and 11.
Travel a 15-mile route in the comforting Piney Woods while nibbling
on famous Eilenberger's Bakery fruitcake and sipping wassail.
Costumed hosts and carolers add to the setting. (800) 659-3484.
</P>
<P>
   SALADO: Christmas Stroll and Homes Tour, Dec. 3-5 and 10-12.
This charming Central Texas town near Austin keeps the decorated
Main Street shops open late, while opening 10 cabins, homes and
buildings for evening and afternoon tours. (254) 947-5718.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON COUNTY: All dolled up for the season, Brenham, a
hospitable town between Austin and Houston, has its downtown
Christmas stroll Dec. 3-4, with tea tastings and lighted angels. A
few miles away at Washington-on-the-Brazos State Park, stagecoach
rides, dulcimer music and tales of Christmases in the days of the
Republic are told, Dec. 4. And the tiny burg of Chappell Hill
lights up for its Teddy Bear Parade and Santa's firetruck arrival
on Dec. 11. (800) 225-3695.
</P>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG: Weinachten, Dec. 3-12. A downtown German
Christmas festival in this Hill Country favorite offers a parade,
tree lighting, arts and crafts market, Santa visits, musical
programs and food stands. (830) 997-6523.
</P>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS: Candlelight Tour and Wine Nachfest, Dec. 4.
Glowing lights illuminate the handmade Furniture Museum,
Conservation Plaza and the Sophienberg Museum downtown, where
German snacks are served. Meanwhile, the Hummel Museum and Art
Gallery also offers seasonal music and decorations. (830) 625-5636.
</P>
