<HEADLINE>
IN TEXAS, FIND A PLACE AT AN INN OR B&AMP;B
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-TEXAS-CHRISTMAS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In your holiday road-trip frenzy, don't forget to find a place
to stay. The chambers of commerce in each location will have ideas,
but here are some of our picks:
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO: The Riverwalk Inn is a marked departure from the
mansion and cottage variations found near downtown. Here, an
assemblage of five 2-story log homes dating from 1842 and relocated
from Tennessee offer a total of 11 rooms _ named for Alamo heroes,
of course, with fireplaces and private baths. There's an expanded
continental breakfast in the morning, lemonade and cookies in the
afternoon, and dessert in the evening. Rooms start around $100. 329
Old Guilbeau St., (210) 212-8300 or (800) 254-4440.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful spot for gastronomic restoration is El Mirador, 722
S. St. Mary's St., (210) 225-9444. Excellent soups and Tex-Mex
lunch plates are complemented by an evening selection of roasted
cabrito and grilled specialties.
</P>
<P>
   GALVESTON: Inn at 1816 Postoffice is a grand Victorian home that
was fastidiously renovated in 1995 for operation as a B&AMP;B. Elegant
furnishings, formal gardens and gourmet breakfasts make this an
island star. There are four rooms with private baths, and rates
begin at $125. 1816 Postoffice St., (409) 765-9444 or (888)
558-9444.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks down, find gratifying eats in the form of
shrimp or beef empanadas, grilled shrimp and other Central American
delights at Rudy and Paco, 2028 Postoffice St., (409) 762-3696.
</P>
<P>
   LA GRANGE: You'll be glad you drove the 15 miles northwest from
La Grange via Texas 159 to The Settlement at Round Top. Among the
spread of 10 restored historic buildings are an 1830s log cabin
with a stone fireplace and a Civil War-period cottage with a parlor
stove and clawfoot tub. A full breakfast is included, and rates
start at $95. 2218 Hartfield Road in Round Top, (409) 249-5015 and
(888) ROUNDTOP.
</P>
<P>
   In La Grange, order fresh, crispy fried chicken and homemade pie
at the Bon Ton, 2359 Texas 71, (409) 968-8875. On the Round Top
square, dig into burgers, plate lunches, steaks and catfish at
Klump's, (409) 249-5696.
</P>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES: A retreat deep into the countryside and near Lake
Nacogdoches is Pine Creek Lodge, about 15 minutes west of town via
Farm Road 2782. A scattering of modern cabins filled with
hand-crafted wood furniture offer a lot of privacy and escapism.
Luxurious it's not, which appeals to those wary of lace and
antiques. A full breakfast is included; rates average about $100.
(409) 560-6282 and (888) 714-1414.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexican plates, steaks and chicken, head to La Hacienda, a
renovated 1913 home at 1411 North St., (409) 564-6450.
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANGELO: Hinkle Haus Bed &AMP; Breakfast at 19 S. Park St. offers
three bedrooms with private baths near the Concho River; (915)
653-1931. If that's full, try the Best Western, La Quinta or
Holiday Inn. Slake those hunger pangs with chicken-fried steaks and
rib-eyes at Zentner's Daughter Steak House, 1901 Knickerbocker
Ave., (915) 949-2821, or home-style enchiladas and tacos at Fuentes
Cafe, 9 E. Avenue K, (915) 658-4081.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
