<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO REJECTS REFERENDUM ON TARGET RANGE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello on Tuesday abruptly
abandoned an agreement with President Clinton to allow residents of
the island of Vieques to vote on a White House plan to reopen part
of the island to Navy target practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello acted after his advisers warned him that the proposed
White House formulation for the ballot failed to give voters a
chance to support Rossello's position that the Navy must
permanently cease using the island's target range.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Aguilar, Rossello's spokesman in San Juan, said the
Democratic governor accepted the recommendation of his working
group after initially agreeing to the referendum plan in weekend
telephone discussions with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor and his working group believe there is enough
consensus on Vieques for the Navy to cease bombing and leave the
island so that no further civic consultation is needed,'' Aguilar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello relayed his decision to Clinton in a telephone call
late Monday. Clinton is in Turkey, three days into a 10-day foreign
trip.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials had no immediate comment on Rossello's
change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Flavio Cumpiano, a lawyer in Washington, D.C., representing
Puerto Rican groups opposed to the Navy's use of Vieques, said
Rossello's turnabout has triggered plans by opponents of Navy
operations to step up demonstrations on Vieques and across the
country on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The date, Nov. 19, marks the seven-month anniversary of the
accidental bombing that killed a Puerto Rican guard employed by the
Navy. The Navy suspended bombing after that tragedy and is urging
Clinton to allow the resumption of live-fire training there.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is also the anniversary of the day that Christopher
Columbus landed on Puerto Rico in 1493 on his second voyage to the
new world.
</P>
<P>
   Cumpiano criticized the proposed referendum because the options
didn't include asking voters whether the Navy should leave Vieques.
Instead, the only two options were whether to resume bombing or to
approve Clinton's plan to cut bombing to 90 days a year, shift to
non-explosive inert weapons and receive sizable increases in
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That formulation is completely unacceptable,'' Cumpiano said.
</P>
<P>
   Cumpiano added: ``The governor's misstep at this crucial stage
certainly doesn't help the cause. But we are united: if Rossello
sells the cause down the river, we still have popular support for a
permanent end to bombing and Navy withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Navy operations announced plans in San Juan on
Tuesday to move hundreds of demonstrators to the target range on
Vieques on Friday to join dozens of protesters encamped there since
April to thwart any resumption of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Rallies also are planned on Friday in major cities across the
United States, including Washington, D.C., Baltimore, Md.; Los
Angeles; San Francisco; Hartford, Conn.; Boston, Cambridge, Mass.;
Amherst, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Navy Rear Adm. Craig Quigley, a defense
department spokesman, declined to discuss ongoing discussions
between the president and the governor of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is seeking an immediate White House go-ahead to enable
a Navy-Marine Corps battle group led by the aircraft carrier Dwight
D. Eisenhower to conduct live-fire training on Vieques in early
December before scheduled deployment for the Persian Gulf on Feb.
18.
</P>
<P>
   The 899-acre live fire impact area and an adjacent 11,000-acre
buffer zone and maneuver area have been closed since the April
accidental death of the security guard.
</P>
<P>
   The hilltop observation post is located at 10 miles from the
nearest of the island's 9,300 civilian residents.
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said while the Pentagon awaits the outcome of the
Clinton administration's discussions with Rossello, the Navy is
preparing to formally notify Puerto Rico of plans to conduct
live-fire training before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a 1983 agreement, the Navy provides 15-days
notice to Puerto Rico when live-fire training is planned on
Vieques, located about eight miles off the eastern end of Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
