<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-FUND-COX     11-16 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-FUND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's wealthiest woman backs Bradley after break with Gore
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrat Bill Bradley will visit Atlanta today to
talk about health care and attend his first Georgia fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will speak to students and faculty at the Morehouse
School of Medicine this afternoon and to members of Atlanta's
Jewish community at the Atlanta Civic Center.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, Bradley's rival for the Democratic nomination, is
making a vice presidential visit to the city this afternoon to
speak to the United Jewish Communities General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's fund-raiser will be held at the mansion of Anne Cox
Chambers, the state's richest resident, according to Forbes
magazine. In 1998, the magazine estimated her personal wealth at
$9.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers is chairman of Atlanta Newspapers, which owns The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, and part owner of the companies that
comprise Cox Enterprises, one of the nation's largest, privately
held media conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who backed Gore's failed 1988 presidential bid, was
unavailable to talk about her reasons for supporting the former New
Jersey senator. Bradley met Chambers about a year ago through
mutual friends, according to his spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, an influential player inJimmy Carter's presidential
win in 1976, supported the Clinton-Gore ticket in early 1992. But
Chambers fell out with Gore in late 1992 over government regulation
of the cable television industry, a core component of the Cox
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was the Senate co-sponsor of legislation in 1992 that
mandated reductions in cable rates and forced cable companies to
share their programming with competitors. The cable industry
opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue had to do just in general with the vice president's
attitude toward the cable industry and his attitude for regulatory
burdens in a climate in which Mrs. Chambers and others believed was
unwarranted,'' said Alexander Netchvolodoff, Cox's vice president
of public policy. ``I think she just got turned off.''
</P>
<P>
   The first public hint of the rupture occurred in May 1995 when
the Georgia Democratic Party invited Chambers to attend a
fund-raising event at what was then the Hotel Nikko. Gore flew in
from Washington to headline the dinner, which raised $75,000 for
the state party and Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers declined to attend the event in a pointed note to then
Gov. Zell Miller, said Steve Wrigley, Miller's chief of staff.
Chambers wrote that she could not support Gore given his views on
the cable television industry, he said. The May 1995 fund-raiser
also came in the midst of the second congressional battle over
cable television. All through 1995, congressional leaders and the
Clinton-Gore administration fought over what was to become the 1996
Telecommunications Act.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans argued that the bill, which dealt
extensively with the telephone industry, should also deregulate
cable companies. Gore and the administration fought that position,
arguing that the industry shouldn't be deregulated before cable had
more competition.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and her sister, Barbara Cox Anthony, Cox's other major
stockholder, wrote several letters to the administration arguing
for deregulation, said Greg Simon, who was then Gore's senior
domestic policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cox sisters were one of a lot of people in the cable
industry who complained about our stand for consumers,'' Simon
said. Ultimately, the administration agreed to deregulate the
industry three years after the bill went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers' break with Gore has given Bradley a small opening in a
region of the country where he is less well-known than Gore and at
a decided political disadvantage. Georgia is also one of the 12
primary states that are packed together in a group to hold
primaries five weeks after the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers has done most of her political work at the national
party level. She contributed more than $200,000 to the DNC and
Democratic candidates since 1990 and has hosted several Democratic
fund-raisers at her home. She has been less active at the state
party level.
</P>
<P>
   The host for tonight's event is Chambers' daughter, Katharine
Rayner. Chambers, who gave $1,000 to Bradley in March, is in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of the other Georgians who are on the host committee
have a record of giving to federal political candidates. Perhaps
the biggest names on the list are Holcombe Green, CEO of WestPoint
Stevens, and Bertis Downs, the Athens, Ga., attorney for Georgia
rock artists R.E.M.
</P>
<P>
   Green was a big backer of President Clinton in 1996 and he has
contributed more than $63,000 to Democratic parties and candidates
since 1992, including a $1,000 contribution to Bradley this year.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Rep. Terry Coleman, who is also a member of the
host committee, said sponsors hoped to raise $150,000 to $200,000
for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
