<HEADER>
A1653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-RECONCILE-BOS     11-16 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-RECONCILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LEADERS' WORDS AIMED AT RECONCILIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ After centuries of hatred, division, and polarizing
bloodshed, Irish nationalists and unionists who want Northern
Ireland to remain British engaged in an unprecedented exercise of
mutual reassurance Tuesday as they prepared to break the impasse
that has stalled the peace process for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of statements that are part of a carefully
orchestrated piece of confidence building, Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble and Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams went out of their
way to give each other the political cover they need to sell a
compromise to their skeptical grass roots.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said his party, which represents most Protestants in
Northern Ireland, is willing to drop its demand that the Irish
Republican Army turn in its weapons before unionists form a
power-sharing government with Catholic nationalists that will
include two Sinn Fein cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said that republicans, who for two centuries have
considered it their duty to use force to seek an independent and
united Ireland, accept that the turning in, or ``decommissioning,''
of IRA weapons ``is an essential part of the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams gave his most explicit repudiation of violence yet,
including a condemnation of vigilante beatings and shootings that
the IRA and its loyalist counterparts routinely use to police the
neighborhoods they control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally opposed to punishment attacks,'' Adams said.
``We are totally opposed to any use of force or threat of force by
others for any political purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a public repudiation of politically-motivated violence, and
of the ongoing IRA practice of punishment attacks, was considered
crucial as Sinn Fein seeks to convince unionists that it is
committed exclusively to democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA is expected to issue its own statement, perhaps as early
as Wednesday endorsing the Sinn Fein statement and designating a
representative to meet retired Canadian General John de Chastelain,
who heads a commission overseeing the disarming of paramilitary
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events that is supposed to lead to a break in
the impasse was choreographed by George Mitchell, the former US
senator from Maine who brokered the 1998 Good Friday Agreement and
has spent the last 10 weeks trying to save it from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement called for the creation of political institutions
to transform the conflict, over whether Northern Ireland should
remain part of the United Kingdom or merge with the Republic of
Ireland, from a violent to a political debate. But the process
effectively stalled 17 months ago when the unionists said they
would not sit in government with Sinn Fein until the IRA began
disarming, and the republicans countered that nothing in the
agreement linked creation of the government to decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two months of patient coaxing by Mitchell,
however, Trimble on Monday indicated that he is willing to risk his
leadership by seeking his party's backing for the compromise that
drops the party's ``no guns, no government'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   If Trimble gets approval from a meeting of the 800-member party
council tentatively set for Nov. 27, the local government could be
formed within two weeks. It remains unclear when, or if, the first
IRA weapons would be turned in, though unionists want to see some
``product'' by January.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble Tuesday made what political observers here described as
the most conciliatory statement ever by a unionist leader aimed at
a Catholic nationalist audience. Unionists have historically
regarded nationalism as treason, and one of Trimble's predecessors
had once famously described Northern Ireland as ``a Protestant
state for a Protestant people.''
</P>
<P>
   But, standing in a cold drizzle on the steps of Castle Buildings
at Stormont, Trimble held out an olive branch, saying: ``The UUP
(Ulster Unionist Party) recognizes and accepts that it is
legitimate for nationalists to pursue their political objective of
a united Ireland by consent through exclusively peaceful and
democratic methods. The UUP is committed to the principles of
inclusivity, equality, and mutual respect on which the institutions
are to be based. It is our intention that these principles will
extend in practice to all areas of public life and be endorsed by
society as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Many republicans remain skeptical that unionists are prepared to
share power with them. Adams has argued that the only way to get
the IRA to turn in weapons is to implement the Good Friday
Agreement and show that politics offers an alternative to violence.
He reiterated that theme Tuesday, using what observers said was the
strongest language ever by a Sinn Fein leader to renounce violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an unprecedented opportunity to start afresh. An
opportunity to put behind us the failures, the tragedy and the
suffering of the past,'' Adams said. ``By providing an effective
political alternative we can remove the potential for conflict.
That conflict must be for all of us now a thing of the past, over,
done with, and gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The similar and conciliatory language used by Adams and Trimble
gave credence to suggestions that Mitchell's attempts to get the
two leaders to know each other better had produced empathy for each
other's position as they battle hardliners in their constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinn Fein wishes to work with, not against, the unionists and
recognizes this as yet another imperative. For Sinn Fein,
cooperation and accommodation is the objective of this process,''
said Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said, ``We now have a chance to create a genuine
partnership between unionists and nationalists in a novel form of
government. It offers us the opportunity to put past failures
behind us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
