<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-BERKELEY-THANKSGIVING     11-16 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKELEY-THANKSGIVING-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BERKELEY, Calif.: in November. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRINE-CURED ROAST TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Alice Waters
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4 hours and 15 minutes, plus 72 hours for brining  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   } cup plus 2 tablespoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   1 leek, white and light green parts only, cleaned and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 12- to 14-pound naturally fed, free-range turkey
</P>
<P>
   Wild Mushroom Stuffing (see recipe) or other stuffing
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil or butter
</P>
<P>
   Fresh rosemary branches, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. In 16-quart or larger stockpot, bring 2 gallons water to a
boil. Add salt and sugar, and stir until completely dissolved. Turn
off heat, and add carrot, onion, celery and leek. Add bay leaves,
peppercorns, coriander, red pepper, fennel seeds, star anise and
thyme. Refrigerate until cold.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove giblets from turkey. Cover and refrigerate liver if
using in stuffing. Discard remaining giblets or reserve for another
use. Add turkey to stockpot. If necessary, weight it with a plate
so that it stays below the brine's surface. Refrigerate for 72
hours, then remove from brine and allow to come to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Loosely fill the turkey at both
ends with stuffing, and truss as you would a chicken.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place turkey in a large roasting pan, and roast until it
starts to brown, about 25 minutes. Reduce oven setting to 350
degrees, and roast for 12 minutes more per pound, until internal
temperature at deepest part of the leg reaches 130 degrees. (Total
roasting time will be about 3 hours.) Baste frequently with olive
oil or butter and pan juices, using rosemary branches as a brush if
desired. If the bird begins to darken too much, cover it loosely
with a piece of foil. Before serving, remove turkey from oven and
leave covered with foil. Allow it to rest for 20 minutes before
carving and spooning the stuffing into a serving dish. Yield: 15
servings.
</P>
<P>
   WILD MUSHROOM STUFFING
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chanterelles
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, peeled and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   \ pound smoked bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 turkey or chicken liver, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 day-old baguette, crust removed, to make 4 cups cubed
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 lightly beaten egg, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   1. Clean mushrooms and cut them in half crosswise. In a large
skillet over medium heat, melt 2 tablespoons butter, and add
shallots and \ of the garlic. Saute until softened, about 2
minutes. Add mushrooms, and season with salt and pepper to taste.
Saute until mushrooms are softened, about 8 minutes. Chop coarsely,
and transfer to a large mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. In the same skillet, melt remaining butter. Add the onions
and the remaining garlic. Saute until softened, about 3 minutes.
Season with salt and pepper to taste, and add to the bowl of
mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   3. Return skillet to medium heat, and add bacon. Cook until
crisp, then remove bacon (discard or save for another purpose),
saving fat. Add diced liver to pan, and saute over medium heat
until browned, about 2 minutes. Drain well, season with salt and
pepper to taste, and add to mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a large mixing bowl, combine bread cubes and enough milk
to saturate them. Drain bread, squeezing gently. Add to mushrooms,
and mix gently. Add herbs and mix again. If desired, add egg to
bind stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Enough for a 12 to 14 pound turkey.
</P>
<P>
   PARSNIP AND POTATO PUREE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   10 all-purpose potatoes, peeled and quartered
</P>
<P>
   8 medium parsnips, peeled and cut into equal-size chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 quart milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter, or as desired
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place potatoes in large saucepan and cover with cold water.
Bring to a boil over high heat, then reduce to a simmer and cook
until very tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, place parsnips in a medium saucepan and cover with
a mixture of half water and half milk. Bring to a boil, reduce
heat, and simmer until tender, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drain potatoes and parsnips well, and immediately combine in
the large saucepan. In a small saucepan, heat about 1 cup milk
until warm. Mash potatoes and parsnips together until smooth,
thinning to taste with warm milk. Season with butter, salt, and
pepper to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   STEWED FENNEL
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 large fennel bulbs including feathery fronds on top (or
substitute \ cup chervil leaves for the fronds)
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fennel seed, finely ground in a spice grinder or
with a mortar and pestle
</P>
<P>
   2 pinches red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. Clean and trim fennel bulbs, cutting off fronds. Wash and
finely chop fronds, and set aside. Cut bulbs into eighths, and
place in a medium saucepan. Add olive oil and 1{ cups water.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cover pan and bring to a boil over high heat, then
immediately reduce heat to medium. Stir fennel, cover, and stew for
5 minutes. Add chopped fennel fronds, ground fennel seed, red
pepper flakes, and salt to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir mixture, and raise heat to medium-high. Cook, covered,
until liquid has nearly evaporated and fennel is thoroughly cooked
and soft, about 10 more minutes. (If necessary, simmer uncovered
for a few minutes to reduce liquid.) Remove pan from heat and add
lemon juice. Toss to mix well. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
