<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS-CO     11-16 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot's profit tops estimates
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot's third-quarter profit rose 46 percent,
helped in part by higher-priced goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded to Tuesday's news by nudging the stock up
$1 to $79.75.
</P>
<P>
   Several other companies, including Dayton Hudson, Limited and
Staples, also reported better-than-expected quarterly profits as a
strong economy fueled sales across the retail sector.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly sales for Cobb County-based Home Depot rose to $573
million, or 37 cents a share, from $392 million, or 26 cents a
share, in the year-ago period. The retailer beat analysts'
expectations by 2 cents a share, according to a survey by First
Call.
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter sales totaled $9.88 billion, an increase of 28
percent from $7.7 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at stores open at least one year rose 10 percent from the
same period last year, topping the retailer's forecast for a gain
in the high single digits. Same-store sales are a key retail
indicator because they exclude sales from new and closed stores.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth quarter, Home Depot expects same-store sales to
rise by a high single-digit rate, Chief Administrative Officer Ron
Brill said during a conference call. He was not more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of the core business is providing us with the
opportunity to invest in future growth, inside and outside the Home
Depot stores,'' Brill said. Growth vehicles outside the core
warehouse realm include Expo Design Center, Villager's Hardware and
installation services.
</P>
<P>
   Sales growth in the third quarter was driven by pricier decor
items, flooring, tool rentals and installations, Brill said. Home
Depot also continued to review its merchandise mix and weed out
unprofitable products.
</P>
<P>
   The average sale was $48.75, up from $45.62 in the year-ago
period. Average weekly sales per store rose to $879,000 from
$847,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gross margin, which measures the amount of profit from each
sale, widened to 29.3 percent from 28.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the third quarter, Home Depot opened 32 stores, including
its first in Hawaii and its third site in Santiago, Chile. The
company ended the period with 878 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot plans to open 51 stores in the fourth quarter,
including a second Villager's Hardware store in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   A replay of Home Depot's conference call with analysts is
available for five days at the company's Web site at
www.homedepot.com.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
