<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-CLINTON-675&AMP;AD     11-16 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-CLINTON-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS CONSOLE EARTHQUAKE VICTIMS IN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Spelling of `Clintion' in 7th graf cq.) 
(nk) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ It was a familiar scene: President Clinton
consoling disaster victims, promising a swift rebuilding effort and
pledging federal assistance. The difference Tuesday was that the
disaster in question struck halfway around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Using the same approach he employs after hurricanes, tornadoes
and other disasters close to home, Clinton visited a tent city
about 50 miles east of Istanbul, the Turkish capital, that was set
up for survivors of the earthquake that struck in August, killing
more than 17,000. Another earthquake on Friday struck Duzce, 115
miles east of Istanbul, killing 547 people and injuring 3,300, the
Turkish government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a camp inhabited by 9,000 victims on the outskirts of the
town of Izmit, Clinton bounced a baby in his arms, sipped Turkish
coffee in one family's tent and listened attentively as survivors
described their struggles in the aftermath of the quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the most difficult thing about living in this tent?''
Clinton asked a woman holding an infant inside her living quarters.
She complained of the cold weather outside and humidity inside. The
green military-style tent, normally used to shelter 10 soldiers,
had become the temporary home for 17 members of the Gencenler
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're grateful for you letting us into your home,'' Clinton
said as he exited. As a steady rain fell, he strolled through the
encampment with his wife, Hillary, and the Clintons' daughter,
Chelsea. At one point Chelsea held a 2-year-old boy named Betul in
her lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a beam fall and the next thing I knew I awoke in the
hospital,'' Ismail Yoldas, the father of three children, told the
Clintons of the moment the August earthquake struck. Yoldas
expressed his ``honor and happiness to meet the president.'' His
twin daughters smiled and answered yes when Mrs. Clinton asked if
they liked the makeshift school set up in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Clintion,'' said a hand-painted sign written by a
young boy in the kindergarten tent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children of America are thinking of you,'' Clinton told
the 20 youngsters packed inside for lessons. After a brief
translation from the teacher, the children thanked Clinton in
unison and then sang a Turkish children's song about a little bird.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reassured the earthquake survivors who excitedly
surrounded him that the American government would pitch in to help
them rebuild their lives. Already, the United States has donated
$14.5 million as well as thousands of tents, blankets, rolls of
plastic sheeting and portable latrines. In a grim reminder of the
earthquake's wrath, the U.S. government has also shipped 10,000
body bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could imagine what our lives would be like if such a thing
were to happen to us, as we have seen it happen to families in the
United States,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of last week's second earthquake further east
in Duzce, Clinton said, an additional 500 military tents were sent
along to provide thousands of victims with shelter through the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   To promote rebuilding efforts in both quake sites, Clinton said
that the Federal Emergency Management Agency would help train local
officials in disaster response and that the Export-Import Bank
would extend $1 billion in loan guarantees to companies that invest
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the earthquake, one aide said, to engage in
``seismic diplomacy'' to try to ease regional tensions. Large
earthquakes in both Turkey and Greece have prompted unprecedented
cooperation between the long-antagonistic states, a process that
Clinton said had created ``a genuine opportunity for fundamental
and enduring reconciliation between your two lands.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the third day of a 10-day swing through southeastern Europe,
Clinton used every chance he could to encourage Turks to put past
animosities aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so impressed that a total of 87 other countries came
forward to help the people of Turkey who were hurt in the
earthquake,'' Clinton told a gathering of quake survivors and
relief workers after his tour of Izmit. ``And we were very grateful
that one of the countries that came forward to help was your
neighbor, Greece. And then, when the Greeks had their earthquake,
the Turkish people came forward to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's main message to the victims was similar to the one he
delivers at every disaster scene, whether it is a North Carolina
town ravaged by a hurricane, a string of communities in Arkansas
leveled by a tornado or a distant nation ravaged by a killer quake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay with you and work with you,'' Clinton said. ``I
just want to urge you to keep your spirits up, keep the smiles on
your children's faces, keep helping the people who lost their loved
ones in the earthquake and know that together we will get through
this to better days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
