<SLUG> BC-BBN-JONES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National League MVP award likely to go to Atlanta's JonesBy
Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves' MVP fraternity is tiny but expanding. Its
newest pledge should be inducted today, when Chipper Jones is
expected to become only the sixth Brave named National League MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stands a chance to win by the largest margin this decade.
24 voters in the Baseball Writers' Association surveyed informally,
twenty-one said they had voted Jones first on their ballots.
Thirty-two writers vote for the award, two from each National
League city.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Jeff Bagwell might have been the favorite in July, but
Jones probably won the award when the Mets played in Atlanta in
September. They surrendered four hits to him, all outcome-dictating
home runs, in a three-game sweep that all but secured the Braves'
eighth division title in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But that series was just the exclamation point on a season in
which Jones hit the most Braves home runs since Hank Aaron. After
an offseason that was scarred by his dissolved marriage and that
preceded the final year on his contract, Jones had the kind of
season that made his boyhood baseball idol, Dale Murphy, proud.
Facing added pressure with each injury the Braves endured, Jones
gave them an offensive hero they had not seen this side of Terry
Pendleton, who helped start this decade long run in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all four of those Braves will have something more in
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how special it was until later on,'' said
Aaron, who won his only MVP award in 1957 at age 23.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, when he got the call that he had won the award, was in a
hotel room in Chicago doing his offseason work of public relations
for Miller Brewing Co. Jones will sacrifice an afternoon of golf,
fishing or hunting today to address the media.
</P>
<P>
   But despite 42 years of the changes in major-league baseball,
the award means the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means you're the best in the league,'' Aaron said. ``You've
had the greatest year of any player that year. . . . I don't think
anyone was close to Chipper, as far as I was concerned, putting
together a complete year in all categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones became the first player in major-league history to hit
.300, score 100 runs, hit 40 home runs and 40 doubles, draw 100
walks and steal 20 bases. Jones had career-bests with a .319
batting, 45 home runs, 126 walks and 25 steals. He finished in the
top 10 in the National League in 10 major offensive categories and
set a new National League record for home runs in a season by a
switch-hitter, surpassing Todd Hundley's 41 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Both Aaron and Murphy agreed that the most impressive statistic
of the switch-hitter's season came in his power numbers from the
right side. In his first four major-league seasons, Jones had 12
homers from the right side. This year, under the tutelage of Don
Baylor, who was hitting coach, Jones had 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've watched enough to know Don Baylor helped him
tremendously,'' Murphy said. ``His right-handed production _ what
an incredible jump. It's a sign he's teachable, he wants to
learn.''
</P>
<P>
   After a relatively quiet June, an All-Star snub and a second
significant blow to the Braves lineup with the loss of Javy Lopez,
Jones heated up. He hit .413 with 11 homers in July and .336 with
10 homers and 23 RBIs in August.
</P>
<P>
   He had 69 RBIs in his last 94 games to raise his one lagging
statistic and become the first Brave to post four-consecutive
100-RBI seasons since Murphy, 1982-85.
</P>
<P>
   Jones reached base in an Atlanta-record 39 consecutive games,
spanning the entire month of July and half of August. He matched an
NL record by drawing walks in 16 consecutive games, in late August
and early September. Five times this season, he won extra-inning
games with a home run. He led the National League by hitting .367
from the seventh inning on.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Jones played 157 games at the demanding position
of third base.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron predicted that Jones' future will be as an outfielder.
``That's when you'll see a real offensive explosion,'' he said. But
wherever Jones is on the field, both Murphy and Aaron have a
feeling that he will be in this MVP position again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember meeting him when he first signed,'' Murphy said.
``Everybody said the same thing about me _ man, he's skinny. He's
just a skinny, high school kid. But he's worked hard,'' Murphy
said. ``He's certainly earned this. He has a lot of talent, but he
wants to improve and he loves to play the game. That kind of
combination will be exciting to watch. He's already fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is the first time he'll have this
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
