<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TOY-STORY-REVIEW-LADN     11-16 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-STORY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY STORY' SEQUELS BUILDS ON AND EXCEEDS ORIGINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  3.5 stars  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 19) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a slightly darker turn into, um, doll psychology proves
something of an inspiration for ``Toy Story 2.'' In this follow-up
to the first all-computer-animated feature, the talking toys are
more neurotic, more desperate for children's affection and
irreparably damaged inside by surface injuries, even when the
latter can be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sublimely silly strategy for a kids' movie that, coupled
with the ever-expanding graphic capabilities of industry leader
Pixar Animation, makes for supremely clever comedy. And even adults
might be touched as deeply as their tots by the film's moments of
true anthropomorphic poignance.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic has never been so affecting.
</P>
<P>
   A toy's joy, not to mention its purpose, is to be played with,
and the idea of that being curtailed is the source of much anxiety
here. It begins with our old pardner, Woody the stuffed cowboy
(voiced by Tom Hanks), frantically searching his owner Andy's room
for his missing hat. Andy is about to take off for summer camp, and
his favorite plaything can't wait to go along _ until a last-minute
arm tear gets Woody shelved.
</P>
<P>
   As if this isn't devastating enough, Woody is soon kidnapped by
Al McWhiggin (Wayne Knight), proprietor of Al's Toy Barn and an
over-age collector. He takes Woody to his penthouse lair _ in an
art deco tower conspicuously marked No Children Allowed _ where the
terrified toy soon discovers that ... he's a star! Yes, the
long-gone 1950s puppet show ``Woody's Roundup'' generated scads of
merchandise and, as part of a complete set, Woody is now an
invaluable collectors item.
</P>
<P>
   Woody meets his onetime stablemates Jessie (Joan Cusack), a
high-spirited, storage-fearing cowgirl; Bullseye the happy horse;
and Stinky Pete the prospector (Kelsey Grammer), still in his
original packaging and, though affable, warped by never having
known a child's love. These new friends convince Woody to be
perfectly sanguine about Al's plans to sell them to a toy museum in
Japan, where they'll be admired, if not played with, by generations
of kids, not outgrown by a single, ungrateful one.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, meanwhile ... space ace Buzz Lightyear (Tim Allen)
leads an expedition of Potato Heads and Slinkys to save his friend.
Among other adventures, Andy's toys cross busy city streets and
make their way through elevator shafts. Most uproariously, they get
lost in Al's Barn, where they must deal with a pack of partying
Barbies and Buzz encounters dozens of doppelgangers _ including one
deluded soul who, like Buzz in the last movie, thinks he really is
an astronaut hero.
</P>
<P>
   As hyperkinetic madness ensues, director John Lasseter and his
high-tech team take every opportunity to show us how far the
medium's come in the five years since their first trip to the
playpen. The toys are more emotionally and physically expressive,
the settings and set-pieces more elaborate, and the camerawork
infinitely more mobile than in the original ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Humor has kept pace with technology. No less than seven credited
writers have cooked up a feast of visual and conceptual gags. A
running ``Star Wars'' satire pays off brilliantly when you least
expect it, our heroes' miniature perspectives are constantly
challenged by the big real world, and the style differences between
'50s and '90s toys are, well, playfully exploited.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few elements faster computers and quick wits
have failed to master. For one, the human characters still look
more synthetic than the toys. For another, the filmmakers struggle
to squeeze every beloved character from the first movie into this
one, whether there's really anything for it to do or not.
</P>
<P>
   And sentimentality is a bigger issue than it was the last time
out. Yet the feelings here are so heartfelt _ to say nothing of
fundamentally weird _ that that's hardly the problem it could have
been. Indeed, the wistful new Randy Newman song ``When She Loved
Me,'' sung with touching tenderness by Sarah McLachlan, supports a
beautifully visualized memorial to the exhilaration of a little
girl's affection and the sorrow of her older self's rejection. It's
every toy's tragedy _ and, with its metaphoric wallop, something
most parents will understand all too perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you never owned a doll that cried, scenes like this are
sure to moisten your eyes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The film: &LR;  ``Toy Story 2.'' (G) &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Voices of Tom Hanks, Tim Allen, Joan Cusack, Kelsey
Grammer, Don Rickles, Wayne Knight. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by John Lasseter. Written by Lasseter,
Andrew Stanton, Pete Docter, Ash Brannon, Rita Hsiao, Doug
Chamberlin and Chris Webb. Produced by Helene Plotkin and Karen
Robert Jackson. Released by Walt Disney Pictures.  &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 34 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Playing: &LR;  El Capitan, Hollywood. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  3.5 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
