<HEADER>
A1679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH17-COX     11-16 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush taking on a higher profile
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two weeks before his long-awaited first debate
appearance, and two weeks after his disastrous attempt to field an
on-camera question about world leaders, Gov. George W. Bush is
undergoing a small-screen test.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who spent part of Tuesday behind closed doors with several
hundred of his top fund-raisers, is doing an unprecedented round of
high-profile network TV interviews this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time,'' said Bush adviser Karl Rove.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP presidential frontrunner began Tuesday with a live
interview on NBC's ``Today.'' Tonight, a recorded interview with
Bush will air on ABC's ``20/20 Wednesday.'' On Thursday, he goes
live on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday, Bush will make his first foray into the world of
the weekend morning talk shows with an appearance on NBC's ``Meet
the Press.'' For months, other presidential contenders have
gleefully accepted invitations to get free TV time by showing up on
the Sunday morning shows. Bush, however, has declined.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said it's all been part of a strategy timed to coincide
with when Americans, rather than just the politically hyperactive,
are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a process of building. We needed to lay out a number
of significant policy speeches and so forth as a good backdrop,''
said Rove.
</P>
<P>
   The TV appearances coincide with today's release of Bush's
autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep.'' The interviews also give Bush
a chance to deal, on camera, with reporters questions in the weeks
leading up to the Dec. 2 debate in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In his Tuesday appearance on ``Today,'' Bush touched on a
variety of subjects, generally offering familiar answers to
familiar questions, including one about the now-infamous pop quiz
in which he could not name the leaders of Pakistan, India and
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is I should have done what Senator
(Bill) Bradley did, and not answer the questions by saying, 'I'm
not going to play pop-quizzes,' and talked about how I intend to
keep the peace, which is what I'm going to do Friday in
California,'' said Bush, referring to an upcoming foreign policy
speech at the Reagan Presidential Library.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's foreign-policy credentials also are questioned in
tonight's taped interview on ABC's ``20/20 Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully concede people can trip me up with questions,'' he
said. ``But the American people, those are the people who are going
to have the ultimate decision in this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had been among the more accessible governors in recent
Texas history until the presidential campaign began, now operates
inside a tightly controlled shell in which interviews are granted
selectively. Bush also has ended his tradition of always stopping
to answer reporters' questions after his public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he opted not to talk with reporters after he spoke
at an orientation session for gubernatorial appointees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, I'm spending a fair amount of time out of state
these days,'' Bush told the appointees, drawing laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm focused on Texas, though,'' he added. ``And I mean, I am
still the governor, and I've got a lot of work to do as the
governor, which I do.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the speech, Bush went back to work on the campaign,
heading to the Hyatt Regency for a private session to thank his
campaign ``pioneers,'' supporters who have each raised more than
$100,000 for the White House race.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
