A1683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEWELL-LAWSUIT-COX     11-16 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWELL-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Richard Jewell settles ABC lawsuit
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Jewell has settled, for $5,000, his libel suit against
the American Broadcasting Co. stemming from comments made by a
radio talk show host after the 1996 Centennial Olympic Park bombing
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hobermann, head of litigation for ABC, confirmed the
settlement, but would not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The suit concerned comments made during the Lionel Show on WABC,
a New York radio station owned by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ABC filed a motion to dismiss the suit on the ground that the
comments were a matter of opinion and thus not subject to a libel
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell, working as a security guard, was initially hailed as a
hero for spotting the backpack that held a bomb that exploded early
on July 27, 1996, killing one woman and injuring 111 people. Within
a few days, Jewell was identified as a focus of the FBI
investigation of the bombing. He was cleared of suspicion three
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell's libel suit against The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
newspapers is pending. He has obtained settlements for unspecified
amounts from CNN, NBC-TV and Piedmont College, Jewell's former
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
