featuring famous football Joes after several of its subjects
complained about the rap song that accompanied it. Writing a column
about humor in TV commercials,  &UR; Michael Miller  &LR; of the Pittsburgh
Business Times had watched the spot, ``My Name Is Joe,'' in which
players including  &UR; Joe Namath &LR; ,  &UR; Joe Montana &LR; ,  &UR; Joe &LR;  Theisman
 &UR; Theismann &LR;  and Mean  &UR; Joe Greene  &LR; were seen over the chorus of the
 &UR; Eminem  &LR; rap song, ``Hi! My Name Is ...'' and contacted some of
those featured.
</P>
<P>
   Miller informed them that the lyrics included mention of
suicide, rape, sexual mutilation and drunken driving. &UR; Cindy &LR; 
 &UR; Mangum &LR; , assistant to former Washington Redskins coach  &UR; Joe &LR; 
 &UR; Gibbs &LR; , said, ``I told the NFL, surely they didn't know what that
song was about, or they would not have risked their relationship
with Joe Gibbs. That song is not what Joe Gibbs is about.''
</P>
