<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SAYS PLAN WOULD CUT MEDICARE AID TO SOME TEACHING HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A plan before Congress aimed at bailing out ailing
teaching hospitals would actually cause 121 institutions _ many of
them in the Northeast _ to lose money, the Greater New York
Hospital Association said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under a proposal that would more evenly distribute the money
Medicare gives to train medical residents, most of the teaching
hospitals would start losing money in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   According to the health care trade association, New York would
suffer a net loss of $45 million, Pennsylvania $7 million, Maryland
$5 million, the District of Columbia $3 million, Massachusetts $2.9
million and Texas $2.6 million, the association reported.
</P>
<P>
   California would gain $21.9 million, Florida $13 million,
Minnesota $7.5 million, West Virginia $6.6 million and Tennessee
$6.5 million, according to the association.
</P>
<P>
   The association based its conclusions on an analysis of data
provided by the Health Care Financing Administration, the federal
agency that oversees Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest hit would be two hospitals in New York City _
Montefiore Medical Center, slated to lose $10 million over five
years, and Beth Israel Medical Center, which stands to lose $8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, 600 hospitals, such as Albany Medical Center in
Albany, N.Y., would see no impact, and 271 hospitals would gain.
</P>
<P>
   This reshuffling of Medicare money to teaching hospitals was
part of an agreement to restore $12 billion in Medicare payments to
health care providers. The money was cut in 1997 when Congress
balanced the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House Ways and Means
health subcommittee, has argued that disparities in what Medicare
pays to teaching hospitals for each resident are unfair. It amount
ranges from $20,000 to $223,000 per resident.
</P>
<P>
   The disparities arose in 1984 when Congress decided to pay
teaching hospitals money for training resident physicians based on
what the institutions calculated were their uncovered costs.
</P>
<P>
   If a teaching hospital had the support of a state legislature or
had a wealthy population of patients, Medicare paid less for each
resident.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the older East Coast institutions got four times as much
money per resident as some of the newer hospitals in the West and
Sunbelt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan now before Congress, teaching hospitals would be
limited to getting between $48,000 and $96,000 in Medicare money
for each resident physician, according to the New York hospital
association. The plan is expected to be approved this week.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the 121 hospitals facing cuts are vowing to
fight the decreases in Medicare money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill was not supposed to redistribute money from one
hospital to another _ it was supposed to provide relief from
Medicare cuts enacted in 1997,'' said David Rich, senior vice
president of government affairs for the hospital association. Rich
said he is hopeful that ``we can come back in the future and try to
turn this around.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Rich predicted many of the hospitals facing Medicare
cuts would have to tighten their belts by cutting staff,
eliminating community services or reducing the number of residents
they train.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Coast Hospital, a small facility in San Francisco, will
lose $234,044 in funding from 2000 through 2005, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland and Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
at the e-mail address judy &LR; hearstdc.com or dan &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
