<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKPLACE-DISCOUNTS-A     11-16 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-DISCOUNTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESKTOP DISCOUNT SHOPPING: THE NEWEST PREREQUISITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First came corporate day-care centers. Then it was concierge
services that pick up employees' dry cleaning or deliver their
groceries for a fee. Now comes the virtual discount mall, offering
workers everything from books to car insurance at up to 10 percent
off, right on their office computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest attempt to please without giving big raises, some
of the nation's largest companies are trying to make shopping of
all kinds both cheaper and easier for their employees. It is part
of an explosion of ``soft benefits'' that, unlike the hard
perquisites of health insurance and retirement plans, cost
employers almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment at a 29-year low and people working longer
hours, executives see the programs as a way to lift workers'
morale. They also assume that employees who do their shopping in
cyberspace will spend less time ducking out of the office to run
errands. At the least, Susan R. Froid, a senior human-resource
manager at Microsoft, said, employees ``don't have to spend all
their free time figuring out what they're going to do _ it's an
easy decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the pull for Lisa Rose, who works on hiring and
training for Sylvan Learning Systems, an education company in
Baltimore. When she heard about the offers, she logged onto
Sylvan's Web site and bought medical insurance for her 6-month-old
Labrador, Ewing, who is named after the New York Knicks center whom
her husband idolizes. The cost, $16 a month, is deducted from her
paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   She also bought roadside insurance that covers towing, locksmith
service and travel planning for $4.16 a month, not even bothering
to compare the insurer's prices with AAA's. ``It was so easy for me
to sign up, and I don't have to pay another bill every month,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has picked up in recent weeks, with such corporate
giants as AlliedSignal, Hallmark Cards, Nordstrom and Northwest
Airlines connecting to their internal Web sites virtual malls where
merchants sell everything from Hickory Farms sausage to MCI
Worldcom long-distance service. The pioneers for such plans
include, Blue Cross/Blue Shield, Boeing and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult to attract employees, and the retention side
is getting more difficult,'' said Joe Demarte, the vice president
for human resources at Nordstrom, the department store chain, which
employs 40,000 people. The discounts are the latest addition to a
benefit package that includes adoption advice and discounts on
legal services.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual malls are an Internet-age remake of the old
corporate discount card that gave employees free tickets to a
nearby amusement park or a few dollars off at the local florist.
The World Wide Web, however, allows workers in far-off satellite
offices to take advantage of the discounts. It also enables
employers to negotiate deals for a much wider array of products,
including more expensive ones like insurance or even home-mortgage
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet discounts are part of a wider move toward offering
more soft benefits to placate time-burdened workers. In 1994, for
example, only 8 percent of companies made car insurance available
to workers through company-sponsored plans. Next year, the portion
should rise to 35 percent, according to Hewitt Associates, a
human-resources consulting firm in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The virtual malls are typically operated by Internet start-ups,
which charge employers nothing for the service and build
password-protected links from the corporate intranet sites to, say,
toysrus.com. In exchange for what amounts to advertising on the Web
site and in company brochures describing the program, merchants
then offer the 5 percent to 10 percent discounts and pay a few
percentage points of each sale to the Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is even creating a new niche of e-commerce.
Employeesavings.com received a $5-million investment earlier this
fall from Benchmark Partners, which previously financed eBay and
Webvan. By early 2000, Employeesavings says its plans will cover
two million workers. And Rewards Plus, which sells only financial
products, expects its annual sales to more than double to $9
million this year, as it increases its work force by 25 percent
each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are not without their downsides. Not all employees
have Internet access, and those who do not _ some Nordstrom sales
clerks or Northwest flight attendants, for example _ are often the
ones who need the discounts the most because they make less money.
(Companies say, however, that some of the discounts are available
over the phone or at local stores.)
</P>
<P>
   Web shopping is also a potential threat to productivity, giving
workers a company-approved reason to procrastinate. Already, the
peak time for Web traffic and many consumer e-commerce sites is the
middle of the workday, when people have access to high-speed
corporate Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   But human resource managers said they were not worried. ``This
isn't something where you're going to go out and play for hours,''
Demarte said. ``It probably isn't any different from what they
already do'' by making personal phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be cheaper. Robert A. Arrison, 41, a computer systems
administrator at Aramark Inc., the Philadelphia food service
company, was shopping for homeowners' and auto insurance a year
ago. He checked the rates of Allstate Insurance, which had sold him
a previous policy, and Allmerica Financial, which participated in
his company's discount plan. By going with Allmerica, he said, he
saved almost $200 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
