<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINT0N-OSCE-1117-COX     11-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINT0N-OSCE-1117-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO PRESS RUSSIA TO CEASE CHECHNYA BOMBING, BEGIN TALKS
WITH REBELS
 &HT;    (625&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Clinton hopes to use a meeting here
Thursday among his European and Central Asian counterparts to press
Russia to end its bloody two-month-old campaign against Chechen
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   He faces an uphill battle, though, trying to convince Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to enter into peace talks with Chechnya's
rebel leaders and abandon massive air strikes that have left
hundreds of civilians dead and some 200,000 others homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be clear with Russia that its fight against terrorism
is right, but that the use of indiscriminate force against
civilians is wrong,'' Clinton said Monday in a speech to Turkey's
general assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has stressed the need for a political solution to the
Chechnya dispute, and he insisted that continuing Russia's military
campaign was ``likely to exacerbate the very tensions Russia wants
to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue appears certain to dominate a two-day summit opening
here Thursday among heads of state from the 54 countries that
belong to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old OSCE groups the United States and the countries
of Europe and the former Soviet Union. The Vienna-based
organization is meant to knit together former Cold War foes around
such civilian themes as respect for human rights, and improving
cultural and scientific contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has long favored strengthening the OSCE as a sort of
civilian analog to NATO, the Western military alliance built to
stand sentry against the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to trade on Russia's affinity for the organization,
Clinton and a number of U.S. allies are expected to press Yeltsin
to invite the OSCE to play a mediating role between Moscow and
separatists in the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think OSCE is a very logical party for that,'' said White
House National Security Advisor Samuel Berger. ``It's the
institution that (the Russians) really see as embrasive of all of
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   A few OSCE civilian observers are in parts of Chechnya,
monitoring what they can of the situation there and offering some
humanitarian aid for refugees. Activities in both areas could be
stepped up on short notice as an inducement to bring Yeltsin to the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly at least, he's resisted such overtures up to now.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Yeltsin has sharply hardened his public views in
apparent anticipation of being ganged up on at Thursday's summit.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin contends that Russian troops and warplanes are waging a
just fight against Chechen
</P>
<P>
   terrorists Moscow accuses of blowing up buildings and killings
civilians in Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader, expected to attend the OSCE summit, said
Monday that Western powers ``have no right to blame Russia for
destroying bandits and terrorists on its territory.'' He vowed to
press the fight, widely supported among Russians, ``as long as
there is even one terrorist there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chechen separatists regard their province as illegally occupied
by Russia. Generations of Chechens have been taught from an early
age to loath their Russian overlords and to adopt independence as a
bone marrow ambition.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is an explosive one for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops suffered a humiliating setback at the hands of
Chechen rebels during fighting three years ago. Despite two years
of all-out combat, the Russian army was unable to subdue fiercely
anti-Russian Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The situation struck hard at the national pride of Russians,
already reeling from the abrupt loss of empire that came with the
Soviet Union's collapse. With Russia facing parliamentary elections
in December and a presidential vote next June, Chechnya has become
fraught with political overtones, making compromise difficult for
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya won't be the only topic on the OSCE agenda. Leaders are
also expected to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  update the organization's charter _ for the first time since
the Soviet Union collapsed at the end of 1991 _ to reflect growing
ties among former Cold War rivals;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  agree to reductions in the number of troops and tanks allowed
to be deployed in ways that could be seen as a threat by other
countries. Those revisions would be contained in changes proposed
to the so-called Conventional Forces in Europe agreement;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and approve the establishment of crisis prevention teams, made
up of human rights monitors, election observers and others, that
could be dispatched on short notice to try to head off the outbreak
of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
