<HEADER>
A1705 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-ALLEN-ALLEY-R     11-16 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-ALLEN-ALLEY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITEFIRE RESURRECTS `ALLEN'S ALLEY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Our rating:  1 star  
(Eds: Not for use before Friday, Nov. 19) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
By JULIO MARTINEZ 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _  &UR;  &LR; Legendary radio personality and social
commentator Fred Allen (1894-1956) deserves better treatment than
this woefully misconceived dramatic survey of his life and career.
Playwright Arnold Peyser and director Pamela Hall fail to establish
a viable structure for this look at Allen's 18-year radio tenure
(1932-1950) as writer and star of ``Allen's Alley,'' but the main
culprit is television actor Jack Riley, who literally stumbles and
mumbles his way through the role of Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser has set the piece at an NBC broadcast studio in 1956, six
years after ``Allen's Alley'' had been canceled by the network. The
occasion is a reunion of Allen, his wife Portland Hoffa (Denise
Moses), and the ensemble of actors who had created all the
memorable characters who inhabited Allen's fictional ``alley.''
</P>
<P>
   The stated purpose of the gathering is to prepare a
retrospective memorial edition of the show, but that is just
Peyser's device to reprise memorable vignettes from the show and
rehash the events of Allen's life, including his early vaudeville
years, his lifelong romance with Portland, his made-up feud with
radio-rival Jack Benny, and his struggles with network executives,
censors and the encroaching Communist witch hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Peyser's creaky expositional efforts to highlight
40-plus years of Fred Allen's life, this journey down memory lane
of the ``golden age of radio'' would be entertaining except for the
monumental miscasting of Allen, whose wry wit and nasal delivery
ruled the airwaves during the '30s and '40s. Riley, who is perhaps
best-known for his recurring role as the misanthropic Mr. Carlin on
``The Bob Newhart Show,'' appears totally uncomfortable performing
on a live stage despite the supportive efforts of a talented
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   None of the classic ``Allen's Alley'' routines come to life.
What does work, however, are the characterizations of Allen's
repertory ensemble, including Peter Donald (Ted Schwartz), Kenny
Delmar (Glenn Taranto), Parker Fennelly (William Knight) and
Minerva Pious (Diane Botnick), bringing to life, respectively, such
legendary fictional personalities as the always inebriated Ajax
Cassidy, blowhard politician Sen. Claghorn, ultimate New England
curmudgeon Titus Moody and the hilarious Yiddish housewife Mrs.
Nussbaum. Moses is quite believable as the always perky and adoring
Portland, and Whitney Rydbeck provides a brief but effective turn
as Jack Benny.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What: &LR;  ``Mr. Allen, Mr. Allen.'' &UR;  &QL; 
Where: &LR;  The Whitefire Theatre, 13500 Ventura Blvd., Sherman Oaks. &UR;  &QL; 
When: &LR;  Through Dec. 5. Performances at 8 p.m. Thursdays through
Saturdays; 2:30 and 7 p.m. Sundays. &UR;  &QL; 
Tickets: &LR;  $25. Call (323) 655-8587. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  1 star &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
