<SLUG> BC-GAY-ENDORSE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM AMMIANO WINS KEY ENDORSEMENT FOR S.F. MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: CORRECTS 5th graf first name of Moscone)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund, a major financial
supporter of homosexual candidates for state and local offices,
endorsed Tom Ammiano Tuesday for mayor of San Francisco in the Dec.
14 runoff against incumbent Willie Brown, a longtime supporter of
gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   If Ammiano, 58, wins, he will be the first openly gay chief
executive of a major U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bond, the Victory Fund's executive director, said that
while Brown, 65, has been ``a tremendously fair-minded leader''
with a strong gay rights track record, ``our mission to elect great
openly gay and lesbian public servants is clear, even when they are
not running against anti-gay extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond added, ``We must open up the political process wherever we
can until sexual orientation is no longer a barrier to public
service.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the selection between two pro-gay candidates, Bond
invoked the name of Harvey Milk, the gay San Francisco supervisor
gunned down in 1978 along with George Moscone, the city's mayor at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Milk, Bond said, ``It is not enough to have friends
represent us, no matter how good those friends may be. We must give
people the chance to judge us by our own leaders and our own
legislators.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said both mayoral candidates have such strong gay rights
records that he doesn't anticipate gay and lesbian public policy
issues becoming a major factor in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, formerly the Democratic speaker of the state assembly in
Sacramento, is the city's first black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, president of San Francisco's board of supervisors,
waged a successful write-in candidacy on a shoestring budget of
$25,000, placing second after Brown in the Nov. 2 mayoral election
and ahead of former San Francisco Mayor Frank Jordan and a dozen
other candidates. Ammiano won 25 percent of the vote to Brown's 39
percent. By holding Brown to less than 50 percent of the vote,
Ammiano forced the run-off.
</P>
<P>
   The victory fund, which endorsed Ammiano in two previous
campaigns for city supervisor, cited his work as a ``driving
force'' behind the city's domestic partnership legislation that
requires city contractors to offer domestic partners of employees
the same benefits offered to the spouses of married workers. The
fund also cited his campaign promises to bring more affordable
housing and jobs to downtrodden neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano has also been endorsed by the San Francisco Probation
Officers Association and the San Francisco Tenants Union.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has won endorsements from the city's Republican Party and
the San Francisco Apartment Association, the city's largest
landlord group.
</P>
<P>
   The Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund has generated more than $2
million for gay and lesbian candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
