A1716 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BOND-LLEWELYN-IN     11-16 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOND-LLEWELYN-INTERVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q DISHES THE SKINY ON BOND 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Repeating for Long Beach Press Telegram) 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; We wanted to know what distinguishes the five actors who have
played James Bond over the years, stamping the character with
unique interpretations of the suave and deadly superspy. So we
asked the man who knows everything (and the only guy who's worked
with them all): Desmond Llewelyn, the wry, 85-year-old Welshman who
has played Q, British Intelligence's irritable master gadget-maker,
in 17 of the 19 official Bond films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean (Connery), being the first, was, of course, the
prototype,'' Llewelyn says. ``People who saw Roger Moore first
prefer him. He made Bond much lighter because he couldn't copy
Sean's visceral charisma, naturally. So he made him more jokey.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then poor old (George) Lazenby,'' he says, referring to
the underequipped, one-shot star of the sixth Bond film, ``On Her
Majesty's Secret Service.'' ``I mean, he just wasn't an actor. But
he wasn't that bad; if he'd behaved properly, he might have been a
very good Bond. But he acted like an idiot on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we had Timothy Dalton (1987's ``The Living Daylights''
and 1989's ``Licence to Kill''), who to the Bond aficionados, of
course, is the nearest to Ian Fleming's Bond. Fleming said that
Bond was what every man wants to be but knows damn well that he
can't be, and he was a very unpleasant character. Timothy made no
concessions whatsoever to the movies, he just made him a really
hard man. So a lot of people, even if they thought they were
wonderful films, didn't think his really felt like Bond films.
There wasn't enough fantasy in them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Pierce (Brosnan), I think, has gone back to Sean in a way,
except Sean very seldom looked really beaten up. But Pierce does
for that second after a fight _ but then he straightens his tie and
is back to normal, which of course you have to be, you've got to
remain romantic whatever happens to you. But he does show pain. And
he has the best connections of any Bond with the opposite sex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
