<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CAUCASUS-ART-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGIA TRIES ANXIOUSLY TO STAY OUT OF CHECHEN CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ Capped in snow, the Shatili Mountains are
fabled for their rugged beauty. These days they are also one of the
Caucasus' more anxious borders.
</P>
<P>
   To the north is Chechnya, a brutal battleground for the Russian
military. On the southern side of the mountain divide is Georgia, a
former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgians would like nothing better than to stay out of the
fighting in the rebellious Russian province to the north. But they
have had to contend with a hard-nosed Russian military, which
recently sought permission to open a new front against Chechnya
from Georgian territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important for us to have good-neighborly relations
with Russia, but good relations do not mean saying no to our
principles,'' said Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze in an
interview. ``I am categorically opposed to having Russian and
Georgian border troops jointly defend the border with Chechnya. And
I am even more opposed to the idea of the Russian side using
Russian bases in Georgia against Chechnya in a military campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   When world leaders meet this week in Istanbul to discuss
security issues, the increasingly tense situation in the Caucasus
will be among their top concerns. Diplomats have been working
behind the scenes on conventional arms limits, energy pipelines and
the burning conflict in Chechnya to make the summit meeting a
success _ or, at least, not a disappointing embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Baltic nations during Soviet times, the Caucasus is
shaping up as an arena for East-West competition, and possibly even
a bit of Russian intrigue. The tone may have been set last week
when Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev declared that Russia
and the United States were locked in a bitter struggle for
dominance of the Caucasus, Caspian and Central Asian regions.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Georgia's leaders are worried that Russia is
determined not only to subdue Chechnya but also to try to reverse
Russia's waning influence in the neighboring region.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Georgia would be particularly
sensitive to the political winds blowing from Moscow. Shevardnadze,
a former Soviet foreign minister, has repeatedly insisted that the
future of his country lies with the West. He has even said Georgia
intends to apply for NATO membership in 2005, which would be the
last year of Shevardnadze's next term as president, assuming he is
re-elected next spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia is also a poor nation, burdened with secessionist
movements of its own and a long legacy of economic and military
dependence on its Russian neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Russia still maintains four military bases here, including the
Vaziani air base just 30 minutes from Tbilisi, Georgia's capital.
Shevardnadze's policy has been to develop Georgia's links with the
West while gradually easing the Russian troops out.
</P>
<P>
   Russia recently removed the last of its 15,000 border troops.
Georgian officials have sought to use the coming Istanbul meeting
to negotiate the closing of key Russian bases as well as to bring
about a sharp reduction in the number of Russian forces here. The
understandings are part of an updated accord limiting conventional
arms, which diplomats hope to sign in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Georgia's relations with Russia have worsened
as a result of the Chechen war. And Georgia's officials have become
concerned that the Russians are in no hurry to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In October, for instance, Russia sought to send several hundred
border troops back to Georgia to help the Georgians patrol their
50-mile-long border with Chechnya, the only stretch of the Chechen
border that is not under Russia's jurisdiction. It is currently
guarded by 160 lightly armed Georgian border troops.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 4,000 refugees, mostly women and children, have
crossed into Georgia in the last two months to flee the fighting in
Chechnya. That is a trickle compared with the 200,000 refugees who
have fled to Ingushetia, another Russian republic bordering on
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia believes that the mountain passes to Georgia may
become an exit route for Shamil Basayev, the Chechen warlord sought
by the Russians, or some of his fighters if Russian troops continue
their march into Chechnya and seize Grozny, the capital. Russian
officials have also charged that arms have been smuggled across the
border, an allegation Georgians deny.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has also broached the idea of using some of its bases in
Georgia in the military campaign against Chechnya, the Georgians
say. Sergeyev planned to come to Tbilisi to discuss the plan, but
his trip was canceled after Georgia rejected the idea, Georgian
officials here said.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgian government fears that the Russian aim was to use
its border troops and bases to encircle Chechnya and open up a new
front in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we gone along with those options, we could have been drawn
into a big conflict in the Caucasus,'' Shevardnadze said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Georgia's rebuff, however, did not go down well in Moscow. Soon
afterward, Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin declared that
citizens from Georgia and the neighboring former Soviet republic of
Azerbaijan would have to obtain visas to travel to Russia,
ostensibly to guard against arms trafficking and infiltration by
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Then Russian military officials unleashed a barrage of
allegations suggesting that the Georgians were in league with the
Chechen fighters. In fact, there is no love lost between the
Christian Orthodox Georgian authorities and the militantly Islamic
Basayev, who fought on the side of Muslim secessionists in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite the angry words, experts here doubt that Russia has a
grand strategy to reassert itself in the Caucasus. But as Russian
President Boris Yeltsin's physical and political health has
declined, rival agendas have emerged in Moscow, with the Russian
militang a particularly hard line.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate test of Russian intentions will come this week at
the Istanbul meeting, held by the Organization for Economic and
Security Cooperation in Europe, where world leaders hope to sign an
updated version of the 1990 agreement limiting conventional forces
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that accord, the Georgians want the Russians to
accept the principle that their forces in Georgia should not exceed
those of the modest Georgian military. That would force the
Russians to cut their armored combat vehicles in Georgia, for
instance, by more than half.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials want the Russians to agree to quit the
Vaziani air base, near their capital, and the Gudauta base, in the
Georgian Abkhazian region.
</P>
<P>
   The Vaziani base is a visible reminder of Moscow's once-dominant
role here. Gudauta is situated in the breakaway Abkhazian sector,
where Georgia has long suspected the Russians of aiding the
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   At least some Georgian officials, however, are dubious that
Russia is prepared to meet their demands and to reduce, quickly,
its military presence in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's broad strategy is to keep their numbers in the
Caucasus and even increase these numbers,'' said Archil Gegeshidze,
the national security adviser to Shevardnadze. ``Agreeing with our
proposals and starting a process of reduction is something that is
against their long-term strategy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
