<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1719 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-BOND-STORY-LADN &LR;      11-16 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOND-STORY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MORE UNTO THE BREACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Repeating for Long Beach Press Telegram) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Once more unto the breach ...
</P>
<P>
   The 19th official James Bond movie, ``The World Is Not Enough,''
opens Friday, begging the not-so-burning question, so what's new?
</P>
<P>
   After all, over 37 years and 20 previous movies (``Casino
Royale'' and ``Never Say Never Again'' were the two made outside of
Broccoli family control), the British spy films have settled into a
formula as rigid as it is successful. Monomaniacal villains,
decorative babes, exotic locations, ridiculously extended stunt
sequences, bad puns and gadgets galore, shaken martinis _ it all
spells big box office. The last two outings, ``GoldenEye'' and
``Tomorrow Never Dies,'' each grossed around $350 million
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mess with that kind of success much. But for his third
outing as supersuave Agent 007, Pierce Brosnan wanted to at least,
well, feel something.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this one, we've hit a new chord, or at least one I
haven't hit in the last two movies,'' the 46-year-old Irish actor
reckons. ``I think we've gone back to what the original premise of
the character was in some respects. And at the beginning of this
one, I said that I couldn't do another `Tomorrow Never Dies.' I
wanted to do what's important to the character, what his
relationships mean to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``World's'' plotline sends Bond out to the Caspian Sea republic
of Azerbaijan, where Elektra King (French actress Sophie Marceau),
the beautiful heiress to an oil- company fortune, is trying to
build a pipeline to the West through Asia Minor. It's presumed
Russian interests might be behind attempts to sabotage the project
and the successful assassination of Elektra's father.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is really pulling the strings has hired the most
implacable of cat's-paws, Valentin Zukovsky (``The Full Monty's''
Robert Carlyle). The ruthless Russian has a bullet lodged in his
skull that is slowly killing him. But it also makes him impervious
to pain, which renders him a particularly hard guy to frighten or
fight. Eventually, everyone from Bond's boss M (Judi Dench) to
halter-topped American nuclear scientist Christmas Jones (``Wild
Things'' vixen Denise Richards) gets in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   But, wait! Didn't Brosnan say he wanted this film to be more
than just action? That, one reckons, is why somebody called Michael
Apted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose the reason I was brought in was to try to beef up
the drama a little bit, maybe concentrate on story a bit more,''
says the English documentarian and director of such fact-based
feature films as ``Coal Miner's Daughter'' and ``Gorillas in the
Mist.'' ``I think that's why they wanted a drama director rather
than an action director, although I still wondered why they wanted
to see me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bond franchise already had a longstanding team of
craftspeople in place, and Apted was happy to leave much of the
wide-scope action footage _ a powerboat chase down the Thames
River, the series' umpteenth ski sequence in the French Alps _ to
Terry Madden's capable second-unit crew (which shot 104 days to the
Apted unit's 109).
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you have to deliver what people want; you can't
start changing it to Chekhov,'' Apted notes. ``After doing the
kinds of films that I've done, it was thrilling to be given these
new challenges. I was very dependent on other people _ the stunt
coordinator, the special effects coordinatior _ but once you kind
of got the hang of it, it was really exciting to add that string to
your bow, as it were.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary-maker in Apted also influenced ``World's''
somewhat unorthodox definition of exotic locales. Instead of the
standard Mediterranean or tropical settings, he took the film to
the polluted oilfields of the former Soviet Caucasus and to Bilbao,
Spain, where the acclaimed new Guggenheim Museum could dominate the
opening scene's background.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, exotic was being on a beach, but that's not
exotic anymore,'' Apted figures. ``When I saw these huge oil cities
built on the Caspian, and the Guggenheim, that redefined exotic for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The operating question was, however, how much redefinition can
such a formula-dependent enterprise take?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never sure what all the elements are to a Bond movie's
success,'' admits Michael G. Wilson, who with step-sister Barbara
Broccoli has been producing Bond films since before the death of
series originator Albert ``Cubby'' Broccoli. ``It's always
difficult, especially because we look at a variety of different
territories. The United States is only 25 to 30 percent of our
income, and you never know from one territory to another what will
or won't play for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you learn from your mistakes, but it's a little
harder to learn from your successes,'' Wilson continues. ``The
temptation, when you do research, is to hear what people like about
the film and to give them more, and that's usually where film
series fall apart. People will tell you what they remember about
our films, and it's action and gadgets and stuff like that. But
that's all they remember; they won't verbalize the fact that you
have a good story. But I've found that if you don't have a good
story, people will say that the picture doesn't work for them,
though they won't be able to say why.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds right. Still, Apted felt obliged to shovel on all the
elements people keep going back to James Bond movies for.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you do the best you can with it, and if my casting
Denise Richards as a nuclear scientist makes some sleazebags laugh,
then fine,'' the director says a bit testily. ``But I have to
deliver that, I have to deliver the jiggle-vision, if you will,
like I have to deliver action and gadgets and all that. The
challenge is, can I push it and make it more interesting and more
entertaining? Nonetheless, there are certain definite features I
have to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, the not-known-for-her-rocket-science-skills
Richards is fielding the inevitable snickers good-naturedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk a lot about defusing bombs in the movie, and people
have been kidding me about it,'' the glamorous actress
acknowledges. ``But I was kind of expecting that. Traditionally,
though, the women in Bond films haven't just been armpieces.
They've all been smart and most of them have had great jobs _
they're either spies or doctors or scientists. That's what's fun
about it, to be able to play a smart woman who also gets to do all
of these things. It's great to be a part of the whole history of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice for the statuesque physicist. But there are limits,
apparently, to how fully a fantasy figure such as 007 can be
humanized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate balance,'' Brosnan admits. ``You shouldn't
find out too much about Bond personally, because the great joy of
the character is the mystique of the character. If you read Ian
Fleming's books, you glean an awful lot about him in some respects.
But he is very solitary and, above all else, a survivalist. He's
always been a ruthless killer; maybe now he's a little more
vulnerable with women.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think he's a gentler Bond,'' Brosnan is quick to
add, lest diehard fans become alarmed. ``He's been doing his job a
long time now and he's seen a lot of killing; his life is always
under threat. Maybe he's just a bit more philosophical now than he
was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, Brosnan's interest in the character has been
sufficiently renewed for him to scotch the rumors that ``World''
will be his last Bond outing. Apted, too, had enough fun to
consider directing another franchise entry, even with the attendant
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   As for the further future of the most profitable movie series of
all time, it remains to be seen if the formula's welcome will ever
wear out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It endures and keeps itself fresh because of two phenomena,''
producer Wilson reckons. ``One is that we are contemporary films,
so as we go through time the world changes and Bond changes with
it. The other thing is that we recast the series from time to time,
and that rejuvenates it because the actors are all leading men who
bring their strong personalities to it _ which, in a way, creates
new variations on the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's indefinitely open-ended, though,'' Wilson concludes.
``I think we're just as good as our last movie and that's about the
way it is. We'll come to an end some time, but I think the
character will always be around because, like Sherlock Holmes or
Superman, he's just one of those fictitious characters that
captures the public's imagination.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0265 </DOCNO>
