<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1721 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WINE-APPOINT-ART-NYT &LR;      11-16 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-APPOINT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIR OF HEWLETT-PACKARD TO BECOME CHIEF EXECUTIVE OF WINERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For months the speculation on Lewis E. Platt,
who retires as chairman of Hewlett-Packard Co. at the end of the
year, has been that he would join a venture capital firm, a medical
instrument company, or perhaps an Internet start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Platt will join Kendall-Jackson Wine Estates Ltd. as
chief executive on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Platt, who is 58, is the latest and most dramatic step
Kendall-Jackson has taken to bolster its executive ranks, though
Jess Jackson, the company's founder and principal owner, is himself
regarded as one of the most savvy and aggressive managers in the
wine industry. A San Francisco lawyer, Jackson started his family
wine business in 1982. Jackson, who is 69, will continue as
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jackson said he was creating Kendall-Jackson Wine
Estates by merging the Kendall-Jackson Winery with the Artisans &AMP;
Estates collection of ultra-premium wineries, also owned by the
Jackson family, which includes Hartford Court, Lokoya, Cardinale,
Legacy, Cambria and Stonestreet. The new company also owns a
barrel-making concern in France and a California-based distribution
company.
</P>
<P>
   Since the initial public offerings of Robert Mondavi Corp. in
1993 and Beringer Wine Estates in 1997, industry analysts have
suggested that Kendall-Jackson, based in Santa Rosa, Calif., would
be next. Though the company keeps saying that no deal is imminent,
Tuesday's announcement was broadly interpreted to mean just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is obviously part of a plan to dress up the company for
Wall Street,'' said Marvin R. Shanken, editor and publisher of The
Wine Spectator, a wine magazine. ``Whatever the reason, it's a
big-time show of strength and commitment. The level of expertise
and experience of Platt is unprecedented for a California winery.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, wineries have tended to recruit from a fairly narrow
range of beverage and hospitality industry executives; up until
now, Kendall-Jackson has been no different. In September, Alfred W.
Rossow, 66, joined the company as chief financial officer from
Boston Beer Co., makers of Samuel Adams. And in September 1998,
Leonard Cairney, 53, joined the winery from Beaulieu Vineyards as
president. He continues as chief operating officer of the new
company.
</P>
<P>
   For Platt, joining Kendall-Jackson turns an avocation into a
second career. ``Ever since coming to California in 1980, I
developed an interest in wine, which has grown over time and
actually become a big part of my nonwork life,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to help Kendall-Jackson build its sales outside the
United States, and, not surprisingly, to use information technology
to improve the company's internal operations.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding an initial public offering, Platt said, ``no decision
has been made. But obviously, that will be something that we will
be looking at as a way to continue to let the company grow. They
have been acquiring properties and expanding, and we would like to
continue the growth while maintaining the quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson hiring Platt ``is a sure indication that this is
now a very important industry,'' said Tom Pirko, president of
Bevmark, a beverage industry consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson, including the Artisans brands, sold 3.7 million
cases of wine in 1998, for estimated revenue of about $360 million.
For 1999, the company estimates that case volume will be slightly
down, because of a short grape harvest, but revenue will remain
flat because the company was able to raise prices on some wines.
</P>
<P>
   At Hewlett-Packard, Platt will be succeeded as chairman by
Richard Hackborn, a former Hewlett executive and board member. He
was replaced as president and chief executive by Carleton Fiorina,
who joined Hewlett in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
