<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-BAPTISTS-COX     11-16 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-BAPTISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Baptists oust 2 churches
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. _ In an unprecedented move, Georgia Baptists meeting
at the Coliseum in Macon, Ga., expelled two Atlanta churches
Tuesday for ordaining homosexuals and condoning same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   In separate actions, messengers to the annual meeting of the
Georgia Baptist Convention voted 2,086 to 262 to exclude Decatur's
Oakhurst Baptist Church and 2,111 to 228 to remove Atlanta's
Virginia-Highland Baptist Church from convention rolls. The
convention represents 1.3 million Baptists in more than 3,415
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Georgia Baptist Convention encourages, indeed urges, our
churches to minister to everyone including homosexuals,'' the Rev.
Robert White, the convention's executive director, said in
explaining a recommendation by the convention's executive committee
to cut ties to Oakhurst and Virginia-Highland. ``The problem is
what is the church's disposition toward the sin of homosexuality?
Does your church minister to homosexuals . . . or does your church
go beyond that to honor the sin of homosexuality?''
</P>
<P>
   At Oakhurst, gays and lesbians serve as Sunday school teachers,
choir members, deacons and ministers. Virginia-Highland was once
the site of a same-sex blessing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that honoring homosexuality in this way is an
error,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Oakhurst and Virginia-Highland pride themselves on their
openness, which their pastors say is a response to the urban
communities in which they are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community of faith owes an apology to no one for its
ministries and for its witness as a church on mission,'' the Rev.
Timothy Shirley, pastor of Virginia-Highland, told the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ministry that lesbian and gay Christians offer so joyfully
to our church is a blessing and a crucial part of the life of this
congregation,'' said the Rev. Lanny Peters, pastor of Oakhurst.
</P>
<P>
   The votes for expulsion came after messengers refused a request
by Peters for a period of reconciliation and conversation among the
state's Baptist churches about the issue of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our church has been in dialogue for 20 years about
homosexuality,'' he said. ``We do not believe such an important
matter should be dealt with in 10 minutes at this convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Urging the convention to ``draw a line in the sand, written in
blood,'' the Rev. James Merritt, pastor of First Baptist Church in
Snellville, said, ``The issue before us is not homosexuality. . . .
The issue before us is fidelity to the truth of the word of God.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Chris Graham, pastor of the Church of the Savior in
Roswell, cautioned, ``There are people here today who have gay
children, gay grandchildren and who work with people who are gay.
They will go home with the question where, in this great body of
Christ that we uphold, where will those children, those
grandchildren, those friends find a home?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakhurst and Virginia-Highland need the Georgia Baptist
Convention,'' he said, ``but you are mistaken today if you don't
think this convention needs Virginia-Highland Baptist Church in
Atlanta and Oakhurst Baptist Church in Decatur.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Harris told a news conference, ``What we have
done today has been a grevious thing for all of us to go through.''
But, he said, ``we need to love people enough to correct them and
encourage them and discipline them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he knows of no other churches facing action by the
convention. ``We don't have anyone who is monitoring churches or
looking for churches to exclude,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both ministers and lay members of Virginia-Highland and Oakhurst
said the convention's decision will make little practical
difference in their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our church will go on. Our ministries will continue,'' said
Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
