<HEADER>
A1731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISERS-ART-     11-16 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUNDRAISERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CONTRIBUTORS THANKED, THEN URGED TO RAISE EVEN MORE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Breakfast cost $1,000 inside the Texas Ballroom
at the Austin Hyatt, but the 300 or so well-tailored men and women
wearing ``Bush for President'' name tags Tuesday didn't seem to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   They are the top national fund-raisers for Republican
presidential candidate Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, and, not
surprisingly, many of them happily brought their checkbooks. ``Next
to my church,'' said John Mahaffey, the wealthy owner of a string
of radio stations, ``the most important thing I'm doing this year
is working for George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Political fund raising is sometimes compared to squeezing water
out of rocks, but Bush's campaign has made it seem like the easiest
job in the world. With nearly $60 million raised so far, the Bush
team is already the most successful in political history. And
Tuesday, the campaign brought its financial supporters together for
the first time to say thank you in a day of private meetings that
seemed equal parts pep rally and strategy session.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to recharge us to get out there and raise more
money,'' said Donna Tuttle, a former deputy secretary of commerce
under President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   These might be considered rough times for the Bush campaign,
which to date has known few of them. The governor's commanding lead
in different polls has eroded in recent weeks, particularly in New
Hampshire, where Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has gained on him. And
he remains the butt of late-night TV jokes about his knowledge of
world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But if they were not swaggering down the hallways of the Hyatt,
the people whose fund-raising efforts have been critical in helping
Bush establish his front-runner aura didn't appear very worried.
The word coming from the lips of men in the dark suits was
``energized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message is, `You've done a good job, keep it
up,''' said Matt Fong, a former U.S. Senate candidate in California
who is co-chairman of Bush's campaign there.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For a campaign rolling in money, a gathering of its biggest
rainmakers might be reason for extravagance. And though some of the
bell-hops pocketed nice tips, excess was hard to find. Each guest
got a signed copy of Bush's recently released autobiography, ``A
Charge To Keep,'' a video copy of upcoming campaign commercials and
a list of recommended local restaurants. For those who arrived on
Monday night, there was a reception at which Bush worked the room.
</P>
<P>
   Ray M. Goodman, a New York state senator who is also Manhattan
Republican Party chairman, said the thriftiness theme was
appreciated, even by an audience accustomed to corporate jets. In a
briefing Tuesday morning, officials said they had kept down costs
on salaries so that none of Bush's campaign employees were among
the 40 highest paid people working for any of the presidential
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advertising people were saying they don't even have
carpeting in the agency that has been set up,'' Goodman chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, campaign officials told the audience of plans to spend
the money on a sweeping media campaign that will initially target
12 states, including New Hampshire. In the briefing, the officials
said that even if McCain runs a close second in New Hampshire, or
possibly wins, they doubted he had enough money and resources to
significantly carry the fight into other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy looks like he's running on empty right now,'' Goodman
said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In conversations with several fund-raisers from different
states, nearly all of them said their jobs had been surprisingly
easy this year. Many had raised money in the past for the
governor's father, former President George Bush, or even Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a lot,'' Ms. Tuttle said, ``let's face it, someone
says, `Omigosh, here comes another letter.''' But in the case of
Bush, she said her biggest problem was finding donors who hadn't
already given.
</P>
<P>
   The government limits contributions to an individual candidate
to $1,000 per person. But Tuesday's breakfast offered people who
have given the maximum to do it again, and do it legally, by
contributing to the campaign's general election legal and
accounting fund.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edenfield, who worked as state campaign finance chairman in
Georgia for President Bush, said fund-raisers in Georgia had
already raised $1.7 million for the governor, more than double the
goal. He said 150 members of a state committee for Bush were asked
to ``exert best effort'' in raising $10,000 each, while the
governor has also appeared at three fund-raisers in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield dismissed the suggestion that Bush's coffers have
mostly been filled by wealthy donors and people tied to corporate
interests. He said the average donation in Georgia is $450, and he
said the fund-raising represents ``a pocketbook poll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ahead in fund raising because some people want him to be
president,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
