<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1734 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      11-16 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN`T TRUST A ROBOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have come to accept the fact that not all mice eat cheese.
Some of them crawl across computer screens and nibble at my icons.
</P>
<P>
   I have accepted the concept of glassless Windows, sneezeless
viruses, juiceless Apples, meatless spam and a fishless Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   But I cannot accept the proposition that a computer-driven robot
is capable of squeezing an avocado without leaving a bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is the apparent mission of corporations with names like
</P>
<P>
   Cabbages-for-Kings.com. These computer-driven companies are
supposed to do the shopping for homemakers who are otherwise
occupied walking their poodles, rearranging their Beanie Baby
collections or inventing a cure for the common cold.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they may do Bill Gates' grocery shopping, but they won't
do ours.
</P>
<P>
   Can you guess how long it takes Alice the Artist to complete her
shopping just in the produce section of her favorite supermarket?
It's a minimum of 30 minutes and she's not spending the time
watching the spray turn on and off over the lettuce bin.
</P>
<P>
   Say she is shopping for bananas. She wants one or two ripe
enough to eat that day but she'll add four or five unripe ones, for
future consumption. No, she doesn't buy green-green bananas. As an
artist she is looking for a banana that is phthalo yellow-green on
the outside, cadmium lemon-yellow in the center. Set your shopping
bag down. This may take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   I don't buy ``a pound of fresh mushrooms.'' I'm looking for 20
or 30 beauties with clear complexions and short stems, each
whispering ``take me'' as I browse through the bin.
</P>
<P>
   I may juggle 10 or 15 yellow onions, before I select two of
them.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the easy part of shopping. Alice sometimes thinks she
will have to put my picture on a milk carton after I have wandered
off into the cheese section. When I am looking for inexpensive
pinot noirs, merlots or cabernets with decent Wine Spectator
ratings, it may take longer than a liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   I can't buy a jar of olives without comparing the size,
price-per-ounce and the hue of the pimentos with every other jar of
olives on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a 30-foot freezer chest will defrost while I have the
door open trying to decide whether to buy ice cream or frozen
yogurt, low fat or Healthy Choice, Butter Brickle Bahama or
Chocolate Espresso With Cherries.
</P>
<P>
   If you think this sounds like work, then you should do your
shopping on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping can be pure entertainment. You've heard of ``The Joy of
Cooking.'' It has been said that ``joy'' is 90 percent
anticipation, 10 percent realization. Every step down a shopping
aisle, I'm anticipating. Some days I may anticipate some:
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Mac
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 green pepper, chopped
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon Italian herbs
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce jar pizza sauce
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces uncooked macaroni
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pepperoni, sliced
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   Every supermarket has a special on ``our leanest ground beef.''
OK, how lean is it? You have to closely inspect the label for fat
content. Is the meat red, gray or some obscene shade in between?
You have to ``be there,'' man! You can't leave a decision like this
to computer clerks.
</P>
<P>
   After you have made the big decision go home, get out a large
skillet, then moosh together the ground beef, onion and green
pepper in the pan. Cook over high heat until meat is no longer red.
Pour off any pan fats.
</P>
<P>
   OK, add to the pan the garlic salt, Italian herbs (oregano and
basil), the black pepper and the pizza sauce. Simmer everything,
covered, 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the macaroni in boiling water, according to package
instructions. Drain the pasta and add it to the contents of the
skillet. Stir everything around and then pour into a lightly
greased 8-by-12 oven dish. Scatter the pepperoni over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the casserole into a 350-degree oven for 25 minutes.
Remove, scatter the cheese over the top, and return casserole to
oven for 5 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Serves four to six.
</P>
<P>
   Banana-Chocolate Chip Cookies
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups flour
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   { cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 firmly packed cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe bananas, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup uncooked oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   { cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   { cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   The bananas in this recipe have to be ``mashable.'' If this
stumps you, call Alice. She'll run down to the market and pick out
a couple for you.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the first five ingredients into a mixing bowl. Well, don't
just stand there. Mix!
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and canola oil in a beater bowl. Well, don't
just sit there. Beat, until creamed. Dump in the eggs and mashed
bananas and beat again, until ingredients are thoroughly combined.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the flour mixture, plus the oatmeal, raisins, chocolate
chips and walnuts.
</P>
<P>
   When everything is combined, drop tablespoons full of batter 1{
inches apart on a greased cookie sheet. Or you can make the cookies
larger, if you want.
</P>
<P>
   Bake at 350 degrees for about 15 minutes, or until browned
around the edges, then enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   What you have here is science with a smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
