<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1737 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MICH-YOUTH-VERDICT-71     11-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-YOUTH-VERDICT-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY CONVICTED OF SECOND-DEGREE MURDER IN KILLING COMMITTED WHEN HE
WAS 11 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ A state jury on Tuesday found a boy guilty of
second-degree murder for a killing he committed when he was 11. He
is believed to be the youngest American ever tried and convicted of
murder as an adult, in a case that has highlighted a national trend
toward putting children on trial as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, all but six states have adopted new juvenile justice
laws that allow more children to be tried as adults, with Michigan
adopting one of the toughest statutes of all in 1996. Civil
liberties and human rights groups have opposed these laws,
contending that treating children as adults will turn them into
hardened criminals.
</P>
<P>
   But many state-level Republican politicians have led campaigns
for adult trials and long prison sentences for juvenile offenders,
using the slogan, ``adult crime, adult time.'' Michigan Gov. John
Engler, a Republican, welcomed Tuesday's verdict, saying that
11-year-olds were mature enough to understand the seriousness of
firing a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The convicted boy, Nathaniel Abraham, was 11 years and 9 months
old when he went out on a hillside here in this northern suburb of
Detroit on the evening of Oct. 29, 1997. He used a borrowed,
.22-caliber rifle to shoot a stranger who was walking out of a
convenience store, killing him with a single bullet in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel could receive a sentence of up to life in prison. But
prosecutors said they would ask that he be incarcerated initially
in a juvenile detention center and reassessed at ages 19 and 21 to
determine whether he had been rehabilitated enough for release or
should be sent to a prison for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The jury acquitted Nathaniel of first-degree murder, which would
have required the prosecution to prove him guilty of planning the
killing. But while the judge in the case, Judge Eugene Moore, gave
the jury the option of finding Nathaniel guilty of involuntary
manslaughter, the jury ended up choosing instead the charge of
second-degree murder, which requires proof that the killing was
intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that he knew the firearm was dangerous,'' said jury
foreman Daniel Stolz. The jury deliberated for four days before
reaching a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel, who was impassive during the trial, appeared shaken
but did not cry when the verdict was read. ``He doesn't understand
it, he literally never has,'' said Geoffrey Fieger, a prominent
lawyer who defended Nathaniel for free. Fieger contended during the
trial that Nathaniel lacked the mental capacity to be held
responsible for his actions. Court-appointed psychologists found
that Nathaniel had below-average intelligence for his age and
limited ability to control anger.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger said his law firm had checked with officials in all 50
states and found that Nathaniel was the first American ever tried
for murder as an adult and convicted for a killing at such a young
age. But Melissa Sickmund, a senior research associate at the
National Center for Juvenile Justice, a non-profit group in
Pittsburgh, was more cautious about declaring Nathaniel the
youngest, citing a paucity of state and federal statistics on very
young offenders. A federal report earlier this autumn on juvenile
justice noted that children as young as seven were tried as adults
during the eighteenth century.
</P>
<P>
   The jury here in Oakland County Circuit Court acquitted
Nathaniel, who now 13 years old, three other charges, including
felony possession of a firearm during the murder. Fieger said he
would file a motion within a week asking Moore to overturn the
guilty verdict on the second-degree murder charge, on the grounds
that Nathaniel should not be found guilty of fatally shooting
someone while acquitted of possessing a gun to fire the shot.
</P>
<P>
   But Patricia Mell, a professor of criminal law at Michigan State
University, questioned whether the motion would be successful.
``Just because verdicts are inconsistent doesn't necessarily mean
that they're overturned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing on the sentencing was scheduled for Dec.
14. But Lisa Halushka, the assistant Oakland County prosecutor who
handled the case, said that it was likely to be postponed because
various trial records needed to be prepared and Nathaniel might
need to be interviewed again by a court-appointed psychologist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fieger said he believed that race had played a role in the
prosecution and conviction of Nathaniel, who is black. Oakland
County is only 8 percent black, and was mainly settled in the 1960s
and 1970s by whites fleeing Detroit, which is now three-quarters
black. There was only one black, an elderly man, on Nathaniel's
jury; the jury had seven women and five men.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halushka strongly denied that race had played any role.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger indirectly acknowledged during the trial that Nathaniel
had fired the shot that killed the stranger, Ronnie Greene Jr., who
was 18 at the time of his death, and who was black. Fieger said
Nathaniel had been shooting at trees, and that Greene's death had
been a tragic accident.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Fieger contended that Nathaniel was 288 feet
from Greene at the time of the shooting, and could not have hit him
deliberately at such a distance with the rifle, which was 30 years
old and missing its stock. Defense witnesses also suggested that
the bullet entered Greene's head so far above the hairline that the
bullet must have ricocheted off a tree branch overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halushka offered a very different account during the trial.
She said that Nathaniel was only 200 feet from Greene, and that
Nathaniel had used balloons for target practice during the days
before Greene's death. Prosecution witnesses also contended that
Greene's bullet wound was consistent with his having tilted his
head at the moment of impact, and did not indicate that the bullet
had struck him from above. Nathaniel was firing from a steep
hillside overlooking the convenience store.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Michigan is one of the leaders in a move by Republicans to allow
ever younger children to be tried as adults with a judge's
permission and for an ever lengthening list of crimes. A
three-year-old state law allows prosecutors to ask judges for
permission to try any youth as an adult, no matter how young. Until
the law was passed, children had to be at least 14 to be tried as
an adult with a judge's permission. Other states have also been
lowering this age to as young as 10.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has long mandated that anyone 17 or older be tried
automatically as an adult, unlike many other states and the federal
government, which require that a defendant be at least 18 to be
automatically considered an adult. While Michigan once had a
reputation for liberalism, the state's increasingly conservative
Republican Party now controls the state's House and Senate, as well
as the governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halushka said that Tuesday's verdict would make sure that
Nathaniel would receive treatment and not pose a risk to society.
But Fieger predicted that Oakland County would be ridiculed for
Tuesday's decision, adding, ``The rest of the world will rightfully
scorn this and hold us in contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International U.S.A., the American arm of the global
human rights group, condemned Tuesday's verdict. ``As America
exhorts other nations to uphold basic human rights principles, we
should begin with the ABC's of human rights and treat our own young
offenders as children _ not as adults,'' said Curt Goering, the
American group's senior deputy executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
