<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1117-COX     11-16 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-CRASH-1117-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EGYPTAIR PILOT'S FAMILY OUTRAGED AT SUGGESTION OF SUICIDE
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ Still in disbelief that her pilot husband is
dead, Omyama Mahmoud Fahmy says it is unimaginable the he would
bring down an airplane on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shocked. I don't believe he would do anything like that. I
don't doubt. I know it. Not him. Not any pilot,'' Fahmy said.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy's husband, Gamil Hamid El-Batouty, is among the pilots
suspected by authorities considering whether a murder-suicide
solves the riddle of the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990, which killed
217 people.
</P>
<P>
   Television news reports late Tuesday showed Batouty as the focal
point of the probe by National Transportation Safety Board
investigators. The mere suggestion, however, outrages members of
his family, who call it everything from an anti-Islam insult to a
cover-up by the airplane's manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators Tuesday were keying on a recording from the
cockpit that reportedly indicates the pilot left the cockpit and
someone else uttered a Muslim prayer before the airplane began a
fatal dive.
</P>
<P>
   Without an apparent mechanical or weather-related cause of the
crash, the NTSB Tuesday considered handing the case over to the FBI
as a possible criminal matter but delayed its decision so Egyptian
experts can have more time to review the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty had been in a first-class seat as part of the crew that
would take over midway through the New York-Cairo flight.
</P>
<P>
   Cairo newspapers Wednesday morning slammed those making
accusations against the pilots. It was quickly turning into a point
of national pride.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Egyptians, members of the Batouty family are outraged
at what they say is a rushed conclusion that a Muslim saying must
be a prelude to an act of terror.
</P>
<P>
   To them and others, the supposition smacked of an anti-Islam
bias and a national insult. Perhaps, they say, the Muslim
invocation came after pilots learned of a mechanical problem.
Muslims commonly repeat a prayer when faced with even small perils
or uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these men. I know them very well. They are good pilots
and good men. None of them would be capable of this,'' said
EgyptAir pilot Roshdy Zakaria, who trained all five pilots on board
the flight. ``How do we know the prayer was not the prayer of a man
who was about to die.''
</P>
<P>
   NTSB chairman Jim Hall told a press conference Tuesday that his
investigators were building backgrounds of all five pilots on board
Flight 990.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy, however, said she has not been contacted by any
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Though her husband was approaching his 60th birthday in
February, at which point he would have to retire, family members
said he had too many plans to take his own life.
</P>
<P>
   They say he had asked a son to meet him at the Cairo airport to
help carry two Michelin tires he had bought before leaving New
York. He had promised his 10-year-old daughter Aya a special gift.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the long-range plans. Batouty had invited friends
to a New Year's Eve party, marking also his 35th wedding
anniversary. He wanted to spend his retirement in a villa he had
bought in a Cairo suburb.
</P>
<P>
   In their apartment in the upscale Heliopolis neighborhood
Tuesday, the women of the family were dressed in black as they had
been since the crash. A picture of Batouty was on the wall and
another in a frame above the television. The living room was
decorated with a Asian vases and framed photos of the Batouty's
five children.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Fahmy, sat in a black dress and a gold necklace with a
turquoise scarab, the mythical Egyptian beetle meant to keep away
evil. Batouty gave it to her for their last anniversary. She wept
and said she will wear black the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have hope that he will come knock on my door,'' she
said through tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved flying,'' she said. ``He didn't take any days off
except when he went on the Haj.''
</P>
<P>
   The Haj is the Muslim pilgrimage to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, and
Batouty made it twice. As do most religions, Islam considers
suicide a shameful death.
</P>
<P>
   Fahmy said her husband was ``always happy,'' and never had so
much as a tooth pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Family members scoffed at the notion that Batouty ever had
psychological problems. He was, they said, a healthy, six-footer
with a barrel chest. He was also the son of a wealthy Nile Delta
family whose family name was now being smeared by what they called
a cover-up by airplane manufacturer Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Family members urged reporters to call his friends. They showed
two other tires he had brought from New York on a previous trip,
noting that he had stripped the label off one so he could match
them on his next trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a family man. He would never do this to his family,''
said Walid El-Batouty, a close cousin of the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of another suspect, co-pilot Adel Anwar, 37, were
not available Tuesday. But, he was headed home Oct. 31 for his
wedding, scheduled just a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmad al-Habashi, the pilot who may have left the cockpit
shortly before the flight went awry, was also hailed as a skilled
captain.
</P>
<P>
   Even the night after the crash, al-Habashi's brother Mohammed
sought out television cameras to offer apologies to family members
of the victims. He assured them that his brother was the ``most
disciplined pilot in this company.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
