<HEADER>
A1742 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-16 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUAL ROLES IN CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It wasn't supposed to work this way.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's national visibility as first lady was expected
to provide her pending New York Senate campaign with invaluable
publicity that could not be matched by her Republican rival, a mere
mayor of New York City. Her initial forays into the state were
greeted with the adulation found most often these days only among
youthful readers of Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   But Rudolph Giuliani is making more political points in his own
day job thus far than Clinton has managed to do in hers.
</P>
<P>
   He is cleverly manipulating the task of running a big city by
taking policy positions that appeal to identifiable groups of
voters across the state. She, by contrast, has not yet mastered the
correct balance between fulfilling her public responsibilities as
the wife of a president and defending the interests of New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's dilemma was painfully evident during her
meeting on the West Bank last week with Suha Arafat, wife of the
Palestinian Authority leader. Clinton remained silent during
Arafat's inflammatory diatribe against Israel and only denounced
the remarks a day later, after clearing her reaction with the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani , with an eye on the Jewish 10 percent of New York's
population, sharply criticized her temporary timidity.
Traditionally, Democratic candidates need about two thirds of the
Jewish vote to win statewide in New York. (Jews were 12 percent of
the statewide vote in last year's U.S. Senate race and 23 percent
of the vote in the 1997 New York City mayoral race.) Recent polls
show Clinton getting about half of their vote despite the fact she
is in tune with more Jews on domestic issues than the mayor,
</P>
<P>
   Her West Bank gaffe promptly produced a round of stories about
sagging morale in her campaign, lethargic support among her allies
and such a lack of political savvy that she might not run after
all. The latter speculation comes mostly from people who didn't
want her to run anyway and can be dismissed as such.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that Giuliani has been running an
aggressive, productive pre-campaign and she has not. He has the
advantage of not having to clear anything with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   He's on his own, which gives him the freedom to make decisions
based more on his campaign needs than on the interests of New York
City. Clinton, by contrast, is still linked to the Clinton
administration and caught between the conflicting pulls of loyalty
and independence.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is in its early days. Neither candidate has
officially declared, and although most polls give him an edge, it
is within the margin of error so that the two are in a statistical
dead heat. Surveys indicate so many people have already made up
their minds that the struggle could be over the hearts and minds of
fewer than 10 percent of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has not lived up to her early promise. Perhaps a sag
in her standing was inevitable as reality set in. In March, when
her dominant image was that of noble, wronged wife, her statewide
approval rating stood at 52 percent. Now that she is seen as a
self-promoting candidate it has fallen to 37 percent in the latest
New York Times/CBS poll.
</P>
<P>
   She has had to fend off complaints about her lack of residence
in the state; the financing of her new house in New York, her
television commercials and campaign trips, and her waffling about
the president's clemency offer for convicted Puerto Rican
terrorists. Good news has been rare.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani has been busy. He has alienated some groups
but strengthened his image as a tough leader with others.
</P>
<P>
   His demand that the city withhold funds from the Brooklyn Museum
of Art for its display of a dung-splattered Virgin Mary was popular
with Catholics although a court ruled it unconstitutional
censorship. His crusade to force taxi drivers to pick up blacks and
travel to high-risk neighborhoods has been cheered by civil rights
groups.
</P>
<P>
   His insistence that the City Hall steps be closed to most
rallies has been challenged in court as violating the First
Amendment right to free speech, but many voters like the idea of
sustained order and calm at the doors of government.
</P>
<P>
   These actions affect only the city that he runs. But the
symbolism of a guy in charge who gets things done reaches the rural
counties and small towns of upstate New York, where both he and
Clinton are still essentially strangers.
</P>
<P>
   And although Giuliani has been sharply critical of her at every
opportunity, she has not responded with equal ferocity. If this is
a slugfest, she has yet to learn the right moves.
</P>
<P>
   The role of first lady normally calls for a demure manner and a
ladylike approach. But she must now be a candidate first and White
House spouse second.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, she has been sharp-tongued in defense of her
husband and his policies. But this is a different battlefield. To
win, she must carry her own banner and never let it fall, as she
did in the unfortunate West Bank episode.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
