<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-STATES-NYT &LR;      11-16 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-STATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATELY, STATE AND FEDERAL OFFICALS WEIGH OPTIONS ON MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sometime in the next two or three months, a diverse
alliance of state and federal officials _ some elected, some
appointed, some Democrats, some Republicans _ must reach agreement
on one of the thorniest public policy issues of the day: What to do
with Microsoft Corp. if, as expected, a federal judge finds the
company guilty of violating the nation's antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most optimistic among them, Iowa Attorney General Tom
Miller, places the odds that all of them will agree at only
``something better than 50-50.'' After taking a back seat to the
Justice Department for most of the trial, some attorneys general
for the 19 states that are co-plaintiffs in the case may no longer
be content to let the federal lawyers drive the case solo through
the remedies stage.
</P>
<P>
   With the publication of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's
exhaustive findings of fact on Nov. 5, a guilty verdict on at least
some of the counts seems inevitable. And the judge published a
schedule making it clear that he would hold a separate proceeding
of some sort to establish a remedy, which could range from forcing
Microsoft to rewrite some of its contracts to breaking up the
company.
</P>
<P>
   To get ready for that, the Justice Department and the attorneys
general are deliberating and investigating their options. While the
partner-plaintiffs have said they agree that the remedy must deal
in some way with the Windows operating system monopoly, there are
many paths that might achieve that goal. And while they are talking
to one another, they are operating on two wholly separate but
parallel tracks.
</P>
<P>
   If in the end, the Justice Department and the attorneys general
do not agree, most likely they will give the judge different,
possibly conflicting recommendations for a remedy _ hardly the most
effective way to present their case.
</P>
<P>
   For the states, the effort to reach consensus is complex.
Nineteen attorneys general are equal partners in the states' suit,
which was filed at the same time as the federal suit and combined
with it for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys general are elected officials with the same pressures
and ambitions as any other pubic-office holder. And among the 19
are representatives of both major political parties and most every
possible political viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's a diverse group,'' said Miller, who is
directing the effort at devising a recommendation. ``But consensus
is important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller holds a conference call every Monday with some of the
other attorneys general or their assistants to discuss developments
in the Microsoft case. Most of the discussion in the last few weeks
has involved remedy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the states have hired their own academic
consultants, ``and we talk to a fairly wide range of people
representing the best thinking we can find,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, he added, is for the states that participate in the
calls to try to reach a consensus on a remedy sometime early next
year. The judge's verdict is expected in February, with a remedy
proceeding shortly after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can reach a consensus,'' Miller said, ``we will take it
to the other attorney generals'' for a group discussion and vote.
That is the first hurdle, the one Miller said holds just better
than 50-50 odds for success.
</P>
<P>
   The next goal will be to take the states' recommendation to the
Justice Department to see if it can be made to work with the
federal government's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said, ``it's important that we not get in an adversarial
position with the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be easy. Some of the attorneys general and their
aides, while grateful for the effective prosecution of the case,
say they no longer want to take a subordinate role to the Justice
Department and David Boies, the department's lead trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more tension between the states and Justice on
remedies than there was during the trial,'' said a senior aide to
one of the attorneys general. ``During the trial, we were mostly
just passengers, but now there are two different trains running on
parallel tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Hovenkamp, a professor at the University of Iowa College
of Law who is advising the states, said be believed that the
attorneys generals generally face political pressures ``to propose
something different from what the federal government does.
Otherwise they will seem superfluos.'' He said those pressures may
surface in this case, too.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some of the states have the power to request
monetary damages on behalf of their citizens, something the Justice
Department cannot do. Some attorneys general have said they intend
to use that power.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he often speaks informally with Joel Klein, head of
the antitrust division, and other department officials. But he
insisted that in those calls he cannot speak for the other
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   For the Justice Department, reaching a conclusion on a remedy
recommendation is made difficult principally because the issue is
complex. Every proposed remedy has its own significant attributes
and liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The department has been soliciting opinions from academics and
other anti-trust experts for more than a year. Timothy F.
Bresnahan, an economics professor at Stanford University, took a
leave from his job this summer to join the Justice Department staff
and help devise a remedy proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While still at Stanford, he solicited opinions and analyses on
remedy proposals from other economists and antitrust experts. The
inquiry had to remain informal because any organized effort would
run afoul of federal rules governing the establishment of advisory
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Now a small group of senior Justice Department officials is
studying these opinions and others, weighing their options. Before
making a decision, officials said, the White House will probably
want to be involved, since the recommendation is a major policy
decision, not a law enforcement matter. Until now, administration
officials said, White House officials have had no involvement in
the Microsoft case.
</P>
<P>
   If, in the end, the states and the federal government cannot
agree, the two plaintiffs will probably submit separate
recommendations to the judge. Trying to put the best face on that
possibility, Miller said: ``That wouldn't necessarily be bad. Maybe
our side will get two shots at it while Microsoft gets only one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
