<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-VIDEO-DISC-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO KNOW THE SIGHTS AND SOUNDS OF DVD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's odd about DVD. With three million players in use, the
digital video disc has emerged as the fastest growing format ever,
and that includes the audio CD and the videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, according to one industry study, 40 percent of the American
public doesn't know what DVD is. ``My mother doesn't,'' said Karen
Stetler, a producer at the Criterion Collection, a New York company
that turns out DVD special editions at the high end of a market
that is filling with thousands of titles.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of an acquaintance gap, perhaps a primer is in
order, and for that there is no better authority than Criterion.
Years ago, operating in a former ballroom on the beach in Santa
Monica, Calif., the company made laser discs, those grand 12-inch
silver platters that brought films, often classic ones, to video
with superior clarity and sound and accompanied by supplemental
information _ interviews, documentaries, essays and the like _ that
helped explain the movie and how it was made. Now Criterion makes
five-inch DVDs, laser's advanced successor.
</P>
<P>
   Obscured in the '80s and '90s by the rise of the videocasette,
laser never became more than a niche for film buffs. By contrast,
DVD is regarded as the eventual replacement for the cassette. As
such it has the full attention of the studios, which are sprucing
up their films, new and old, for a digital format that not only
makes most tapes look like mud but, with vastly more space for
added features than laser disc, radically expands video for the
average viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is a broader audience being introduced to this kind
of work,'' said Peter Becker, Criterion's president. Digital
compression has opened the possibilities. ``We're now able to do a
level of restoration and supplemental work that exceeds anything we
were able to do on laser,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously some films are better candidates for special treatment
than others. Criterion chooses classics and older movies from the
library of Janus Films, which includes the likes of Fellini,
Kurosawa, Renoir, Godard and Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   From its laser days the company has cultivated ties with
prominent directors like Martin Scorsese and, before his death in
1990, Michael Powell, and young ones like Kevin Smith (``Chasing
Amy'') and Paul Thomas Anderson (``Boogie Nights''), who studied
laser disc as a virtual adjunct to film school.
</P>
<P>
   Criterion divvies up its work among 30 producers and technical
experts in video, sound, design, compression and other areas.
``We're interested in good contemporary films that deserve special
treatments,'' Ms. Stetler said. For her, one example is David
Cronenberg's ``Dead Ringers,'' about a pair of identical twin
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The film moved to DVD with all its special laser features
reformatted for the digital disc, down to drawings and photographs
of the medical instruments and sculptures designed for the film.
Cronenberg, a notably private man, contributed an audio commentary.
``I thought his audience would be really interested in hearing from
him,'' Ms. Stetler said.
</P>
<P>
   At any one time, Criterion projects swing from, to name some
current examples, Alfred Hitchcock's ``The 39 Steps,'' Carol Reed's
``The Third Man'' and Michael Powell and Emeric Pressburger's ``The
Red Shoes'' to Scorsese's ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' and Wes
Anderson's ``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   The first task is to locate the best film elements _ various
negatives and positives _ to work with on the transfer to a digital
master. ``Most of the films we do are old,'' said Maria Palazzola,
Criterion's ranking expert on the move from film to disc. ``I get
an itemized list from all over the world as to what elements
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   If some are missing, she jumps on a plane and goes looking. ``We
try to find as much as we can because if something is mislabeled or
has been in a vault a long time and is assumed to be good but
isn't, we're stuck,'' she said. Now and then even good material can
be improved upon. Renoir's ``Grand Illusion'' is an example. ``We
thought we had the best elements when we did the transfer for laser
disc,'' she said. ``Then for the DVD we found some better elements,
so we went to Paris and did a new transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Directors and cinematographers often work at her shoulder during
the transfer. The cinematographer Jack Cardiff was on hand for the
transfer of ``The Red Shoes'' in London. ``That was a case where he
came in and made the film look like what he wanted on the theater
screen,'' Ms. Palazzola said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick, who didn't travel, received ``rushes'' of each
day's transfer work on the laser discs of ``Lolita'' and ``Dr.
Strangelove.'' Scorsese sent his film editor, Thelma Schoonmaker,
to work on the DVD of ``The Last Temptation of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schoonmaker also happens to be Michael Powell's widow, and
she and Scorsese supplied a trove of supplemental items for ``The
Red Shoes'' DVD, along with advice on where to find other
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Supplements, Ms. Stetler said, are primarily derived from four
sources: the filmmaker, the studio, libraries, archives from
museums and organizations like the British Film Institute. ``We
look for things that will enhance understanding of the movie,'' she
said. Directors often contribute the most. ``Scorsese saves
everything, so on `Last Temptation' he gave me huge amounts of
stuff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Shoes'' comes with commentary by Cardiff and two stars
of the film, the dancer Moira Shearer and Marius Goring; many
stills from the set; a reading of the Hans Christian Andersen fairy
tale by Jeremy Irons, and an animated film of Hein Heckroth's
painted storyboards, which can be played split screen with the
film.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best aspects of DVD is sound. Up to nine soundtracks
are available on a disc. Becker stressed that each be used
appropriately or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Man'' includes a reading of Graham Greene's
treatment that became the film. For ``The 39 Steps,'' the Criterion
producer Susan Arosteguy went to Marian Keane, a Hitchcock expert
and former film professor of hers, for a commentary. ``Sometimes we
do a more scholarly reading of a film, rather than anecdotal,'' Ms.
Arosteguy said. ``It's a nice way to get you into Hitchcock's work
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the disc is the 1937 broadcast of the Lux Radio Theater
adaptation of the film, starring Robert Montgomery and Ida Lupino;
it is introduced with wonderful panache by Cecil B. DeMille.
</P>
<P>
   Sound work is a separate specialty. For newer films it generally
concentrates on making the film sound its best on the latest home
theater equipment. For older films, a forensic machine (the same
one that takes distortions out of wiretaps) is used to remove hiss,
crackle and clicks. ``The first principle is to do no harm,''
Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   All that is left, then, is to make sure that the viewer can
maneuver around the disc efficiently. For that there is the disc
designer's true pride and joy: the menu, or index of features.
Materials can be organized in many ways. ``What to do should be
clear, easy, geared to the film,'' Becker said. ``We don't want our
discs to be difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1747 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUFFLER-MEN-ART-$ADV2     11-16 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUFFLER-MEN-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE CAN BE ART IN CAR PARTS, TOO: TAKE MUFFLER MEN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Muffler men are the cigar-store Indians of the
late 20th century, trade figures made to stand in front of shops to
advertise what is sold inside.
</P>
<P>
   Both are considered forms of folk art, but the skinny metal
figures with shimmering muffler heads and torsos and pipe-thin legs
found outside auto repair shops are wittier, more imaginative and
flamboyantly painted than the stolid carved Indians of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Today's metal icons depict cartoon characters, space creatures,
robots, cowboys, bikers, boxers, guitarists, devils and pop culture
images like John Lennon and Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Produced by mechanics in the shops where they work, the muffler
men are being made as advertising art, proliferating as roadside
attractions outside the shops throughout the Los Angeles
metropolitan area. Most are not for sale, and to deter theft, most
are either welded to a post or chained down.
</P>
<P>
   Their makers _ most are Hispanic _ repaint them frequently to
keep them looking shiny new. But they weather fast, lasting for no
more than a couple of years. So far, very few figures appear to
have survived long enough to show up in flea markets and art shows,
and that may explain why most people have no idea what muffler men
are.
</P>
<P>
   Now muffler men are moving into the world of art, in two
exhibitions at the Fowler Museum of Cultural History at the
University of California at Los Angeles. One of them, ``Muffler
Men, Munecos and Other Welded Wonders,'' which was organized by the
Fowler, is the first museum exhibition devoted entirely to these
figures.
</P>
<P>
   On display through April 28 are 34 metal images of people, space
creatures and animals. There are also two muffler figures at the
Fowler in ``Recycled, Re-Seen: Folk Art From the Global Scrap
Heap,'' a traveling exhibition organized in 1996 by the Museum of
International Folk Art in Santa Fe that closes on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect art in an auto repair shop,'' said Patrick A.
Polk, a curator of the ``Muffler Men'' show. ``But these figures
have been seen all over this country and beyond its borders. I have
personal reports of them in Brazil, Mexico, El Salvador, Senegal
and South Africa. It's an international phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk, a graduate student who is the archivist for the
university's folklore and mythology program, organized the show
with another graduate student, Timothy C. Correll.
</P>
<P>
   The two became interested in muffler men two years ago while
researching storefront decoration in the Los Angeles area. Polk
said: ``I had been aware of these figures but never paid very much
attention to them until the day we came on a spectacular scene
where a dozen figures were lined up out front of a shop by the
owner, Frank Afra, who had made them. We stopped and took a closer
look, and after talking with Afra, we decided that muffler men were
worth further study _ possibly even a show or a book.''
</P>
<P>
   The curators produced both. (The museum catalog costs $59 in
cloth, $29 in paper.). But the history of muffler men they
uncovered is, at best, spotty. The earliest, and tallest, muffler
man they found is an eight-foot giant with bright green legs that
stands at the entrance to the ``Muffler Men'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Made in 1970 by Joe Luria, the owner of a shop in Carson,
Calif., it is called the ``Carson Muffler Robot'' and is based on
one that he had devised in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Polk and Correll have never found any evidence of muffler men
made before 1970, even photographs. But they have been told that
many existed in the 1950s and '60s, and they are certain that
muffler men have been around for most of this century.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was being planned while a smaller one _ of 14
figures _ was taking place late last year at Gallery 414 in Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as there were auto mechanics, there were auto
mechanics making things with reused parts of cars,'' Polk said.
``When they were first produced at the turn of the century,
automobiles were loud, raucous things. The mufflers we have today
were not developed until the 1920s or '30s.''
</P>
<P>
   The form has evolved little since then. But makers represented
in the show vary their figures by the features they paint on the
faces and the things they add: simulated musical instruments,
ersatz vacuum cleaners, robot jetpacks, goggles, clothing and bar
stools.
</P>
<P>
   Space creatures come with silvery wings made from heat shields,
claws of spark plugs and alternator wiring connecting packs on
their backs. A minimalist fantasy figure combines two kinds of
mufflers: a canlike type for the bright yellow torso and a
rod-shaped glass pack muffler for the red sausagelike head, the
work of Manuel Rodriguez and Efran Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   A different approach is seen in ``Recycle, Re-seen.'' A muffler
man, made in 1992 by Jack King of Des Moines, sports a bright red
ribbon for a tie with light-bulb eyes in a hubcap face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muffler men are a grass roots form of folk art expressing our
car culture,'' said Aarne Anton, a New York dealer in 20th-century
folk art. ``If one person makes muffler men in a garage in a
prominent place, it inspires so many others to come up with their
own special version.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
