<SLUG> BC-BBA-CY-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ GARNERS SECOND CY YOUNG, UNANIMOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was unanimous, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring Pedro Martinez against his peers was only incidentally
about comparing him with the other pitchers in the American League
last season. That's what made Tuesday's announcement that Martinez
was the choice on all 28 ballots for the AL Cy Young Award so
anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone understood that the Red Sox righthander was in a league
of his own last season. The barometer for gauging his performance
was provided not by such contemporaries as Mike Mussina of the
Baltimore Orioles or Aaron Sele of the Texas Rangers, but by a roll
call of the all-time greats, Hall of Famers such as Sandy Koufax
and Steve Carlton, Bob Feller and Bob Gibson, Juan Marichal and
Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much expected this,'' Martinez conceded Tuesday in a
conference call from the Dominican Republic, where he received
confirmation that he had become just the third pitcher to win the
Cy Young Award in both leagues, joining Gaylord Perry and Randy
Johnson, the Arizona Diamondbacks lefthander who Monday was named
the National League winner.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez won the NL award for the Montreal Expos in 1997,
he gave the trophy to Marichal, who after his glory years in San
Francisco briefly pitched for the Red Sox and is now sports
minister in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   This one, Martinez said, he intends to place in his own trophy
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take it home to my people,'' he said. ``Enjoy it
with my family and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   He may need additional space in that trophy room come Thursday,
when the AL Most Valuable Player will be announced. Martinez would
appear to be a leading candidate, along with countryman Manny
Ramirez, the Cleveland Indians outfielder who knocked in 165 runs.
But as many as eight players have a legitimate shot at the award,
including Texas DH Rafael Palmeiro; Cleveland second baseman Robbie
Alomar; Texas catcher Ivan Rodriguez; New York Yankees shortstop
Derek Jeter and closer Mariano Rivera; and Red Sox shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra, the AL batting champion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for whom he'd cast his vote, Martinez showed some hometown
favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick, I'd probably pick Nomar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez also made it clear how much it would mean to him to
win the MVP, something no AL starting pitcher has done since Roger
Clemens was a dual winner (Cy Young, MVP) for the Red Sox in 1986.
Some are biased against voting for a pitcher as MVP, though
Martinez was dismissive of that argument.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to exclude pitchers from consideration, he said,
then why not exclude other part-timers like designated hitters,
too?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 25 of us on a roster,'' he said. ``We're all
qualified. There shouldn't be any discrimination against anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win it, fine. If I don't, that's fine, too. There's no
crying in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to the hitters rendered helpless on a regular
basis by Martinez last season. His 23 wins were five more than the
three AL pitchers with the next-most: Mussina, Sele, and Bartolo
Colon. Mussina and Colon were second and third in the Cy Young
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   His ERA of 2.07 was 1.37 points lower than the 3.44 of league
runner-up David Cone of the Yankees, and 2.80 lower than the league
average.
</P>
<P>
   There have been just two other occasions _ Dazzy Vance in 1930
and Greg Maddux in 1994 _ when the pitcher with the league's best
ERA was more than a run better than the runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out 313 batters, 113 more than runner-up Chuck
Finley of the Angels. Opponents batted a league-low .205 against
him, 70 points below the league average. He averaged 13.2
strikeouts per nine innings, more than five more a game than
runner-up Finley, and his 1.6 walks per nine innings were just
behind Gil Heredia of Oakland, 1.5.
</P>
<P>
   He did for pitchers what Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa have done
for sluggers, but given the homer-happy times in which the game is
now played, what he did may have been even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes just the fourth AL pitcher to be a unanimous
selection, joining Detroit's Denny McLain (1968), the Yankees' Ron
Guidry (1978), and Clemens (1986 for the Red Sox, 1998 for the Blue
Jays).
</P>
<P>
   How do you improve on a season for the ages?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm able to do it again,'' he said. ``I hope to improve
on it. I don't see why not. I'm still young, I'm still healthy, I
expect to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox go into next season with a great deal of uncertainty
in their rotation beyond Martinez. Bret Saberhagen's rotator cuff
surgery may sideline him until at least midseason, lefthander Kent
Mercker elected to become a free agent rather than exercise his
contract option to return, and the Red Sox made Pat Rapp a free
agent rather than exercising the option they held on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be good enough,'' he said. ``We did it last year. We
finished in first place in pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Saberhagen is down, we'll have to pick him up. Hopefully
one of the young people will do the job, Brian Rose or Juan Pena.
Ramon (Martinez, his older brother) is coming back healthy,
hopefully. Wakie (Tim Wakefield) we can use any time as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kids. We need to be healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   His own health, which became an isuue when he strained a back
muscle in the postseason, is fine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a lot of swimming,'' he said. ``It feels completely
normal right now.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be no better news for the Sox than that: All is well
in the universe of Cy Martinez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
