u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-585&AMP;ADD-N     11-16 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CHINA TRADE ACCORD IS NOT A DONE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-TRADE-DEAL, CHINA-ASSESS and related stories) 
(bl) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took three U.S. presidents, two Chinese leaders and dozens of
negotiators 13 years of sometimes dramatic brinkmanship to clear a
path for China to join the World Trade Organization. Now, to listen
to proponents and critics of the measure, the hard work begins.
</P>
<P>
   The trade accord announced Monday is perhaps the most sweeping
agreement of any kind between the United States and China since the
two nations resumed normal diplomatic relations a generation ago.
But unless Congress agrees to forgo the right to review China's
trade status each year, a debate that has become an annual ritual
in Washington, U.S. companies will not enjoy any new trade
advantages, and this week's agreement could become a milestone of
another kind: How politics trumps diplomacy when it comes to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this has been going on long enough that Congress
can separate trade and all the other concerns about China, which we
all have,'' said Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., who has been a
proponent of international agreements on free trade. ``But if
experience is any guide, the Chinese are likely to do something
provocative _ like lobbing missiles off Taiwan _ and that's going
to be a factor in the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential congressional opposition is one reason that China's
accession to the trade body is not a done deal. The European Union,
Canada and several major nations still face negotiating their own
bilateral trade agreements with China. European Union officials had
allowed the United States to take the lead in negotiations, but
Clinton administration officials have been careful to speak only
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Few expect the European Union or Canada to derail China's bid to
join the global trade body, given that other countries are eager to
take advantage of the broad concessions China has made to reduce
tariffs and allow foreign banks, farmers and telecommunication
companies more access to its huge market. China is expected to try
to complete side agreements with other nations before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that process goes smoothly and China does become a WTO
member, some U.S. businesses say many of the headline benefits of
the accord will take years, and considerable sweat and tears, to
realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that its easier to negotiate and agreement like
this than to make it work in practice,'' said Brad Smith, general
counsel for international affairs at Microsoft, who has long pushed
China to protect copyrights on foreign computer software. ``The
agreement is an important milestone in the sense that it gives us a
solid foundation, but now we have to get busy doing the hard
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   And all this assumes that China's leadership, which has faced
domestic pressure to protect Chinese industry and jobs, will remain
firmly behind the agreement. The accord Monday was seen as giving a
boost to Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, a plain-spoken reformer, but
Chinese politics are notoriously hard to read, and few dismiss the
possibility of a political backlash against trade concessions
there.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the trade agreement still give it good odds of
winning congressional backing and, longer term, being fully carried
out. Bolstering their case is an outpouring of support from
American businesses, which have promised the strongest lobbying
campaign on a trade issue since Congress approved the North
American Free Trade Agreement in 1994. Administration officials
also promised an intensive effort to push the agreement through the
remaining hurdles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers set the tone Tuesday by
promising to mount a vigorous defense of the benefit of trade and
globalization for average Americans. ``This means more jobs for
Americans,'' he said. ``It means larger export markets for American
producers to provide high-wage jobs. It means a more stable,
competitive, global economy. It means better opportunities for
American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor union leaders were equally vigorous Tuesday in their
vows to block approval in Congress, with some predicting that they
could stop this deal the way they have blocked other administration
trade initiatives. Teamsters president James P. Hoffa denounced the
pact as a ``slap in the face not only to workers in America, but to
their counterparts in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders predicted that they could block approval of the
deal by mustering an unusual coalition Democrats, labor-friendly
Republican moderates and some conservative Republicans angry about
human rights violations in China.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will likely take up the issue in February, shortly
after the beginning of the new session. Though proponents of the
measure would prefer to keep the debate focused on the merits of
increasingly trade with China and broadening access to its market,
a battle they think they can win, China's critics will surely seek
to make the debate as wide-ranging as possible. Critics say China
spies on the United States, ships sensitive weapons to troubled
regions, often breaks its word after sealing international treaties
and suppresses all kinds of political and religious opposition at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., who has opposed granting China
low-tariff treatment in the United States in the past, said the
broad aspects of the China relationship weighed on President
Clinton's decision to seal a trade deal now, and will weigh on
Congress when it considers whether to give up its right to review
China's trade status each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable that we will consider the full range of
issues about China because it goes to China's credibility _ whether
they can honor a deal,'' said Ms. Pelosi.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the uncertainty in Washington is that past turning
points in the bilateral relations, like state visits and the annual
trade review, have prompted an outpouring of damaging revelations
about China's international behavior, including allegations about
its theft of U.S. nuclear secrets and infiltration into the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the pattern,'' said Huang Yasheng, a China expert at
the Harvard Business School. ``As soon Congress starts
deliberating, you can bet that some kind of bad news will leak
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Huang said he suspects that China's willingness to
grant broad concessions on trade was motivated, in part, by its
desire to deny critics in the United States a annual forum to
attack China and keep relations in a deep freeze. But to achieve
that goal, China will have to endure at least one more round of
intense attacks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui said supporters of the China agreement will likely
prevail, though previous votes on extending China's trade status
suggest the tally could be close. ``Probably the most likely reason
this will go through is that if we don't give China permanent trade
status, all other countries will get tariff reductions and we
won't,'' Matsui said, drawing a scenario in which China enters the
WTO but Congress doesn't approve the terms that the United States
negotiated to make accession possible.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the trade deal clears the congressional hurdle, U.S.
business could face years of hard bargaining, court fights and
diplomatic lobbying before that get the advantages it promises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
