<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LOCKHEED-COX     11-16 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rumors of plant's closure have politicians trying to work dealBy
Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rumors that Lockheed Martin Corp. is considering
shutting down its Marietta, Ga., plant are fueling political
support for a plan that would give the defense contractor $150
million to keep its cargo plane line open.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Georgia's congressional delegation strongly support
the plan, saying it would stabilize the C-130J cargo plane until
2002 when the Air Force plans to start buying at least 150 of the
$50 million planes.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's lawmakers say the plan defies the speculation that
Lockheed Martin has placed its Marietta plant on the chopping
block. If Lockheed were seriously considering selling or closing
the plant, they ask, would the company have worked out such a
long-term plan with the Air Force?
</P>
<P>
   The plan essentially gives Lockheed Martin a down payment on
future orders in an effort to keep the company from eliminating the
assembly line because of a lack of orders, Sen. Paul Coverdell
(R-Ga.) said.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has estimated it would cost some $680 million to
reopen the Marietta facility if Lockheed shuts down its cargo plane
line. In addition, the price of the plane would increase to as much
as $70 million, according to congressional documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is putting a downpayment down to make sure that this
center of intelligence and capacity is there to build the plane
that the Air Force wants,'' Coverdell said. ``If you jeopardize the
line, you jeopardize the aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, called an Economic Order Quantity, is similar to the
way the federal government pays farmers not to harvest certain
crops. The difference is that this proposal would allow Lockheed to
begin work on at least two of the aircraft that the Air Force
intends to purchase starting in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to give Lockheed money to keep the line ``warm'' came
after a meeting between Coverdell and Air Force Secretary Whitten
Peters in July.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that meeting, Peters sent a team to Marietta to
assess how many planes the company needed in its production cycle
to keep the C-130 line open.
</P>
<P>
   Peters presented Coverdell and other members of the Georgia
delegation with the proposal in August. Coverdell said he told
Peters that he wasn't interested in the Air Force buying planes
that it didn't want. ``I also told him I'm not interested in having
the Air Force shoot itself in the foot by not buying the planes
now,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is now under consideration at the Air Force, which is
drafting its spending plan for 2001. Coverdell and other members of
the delegation have met with Defense Secretary William Cohen in an
effort to make sure the plan is in the Defense Department's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly not a handout,'' said Jim Grant, Lockheed's
director of government acquirement. ``The $150 million in fact puts
us to work. It gives us the opportunity to build planes a little
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) strongly supports the plan, but he is
taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland and Sen. Tim Hutchinson (R-Ark. ), a fellow member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, are creating a bipartisan
commission of lawmakers in the Senate and the House who want to
ensure the future of the C-130J program.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has assigned a liaison to the commission, as have
the Air Guard and Air Force Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The fleet of some 600 C-130Js is aging; some aircraft are 40
years old. The demand for the aircraft is high, Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you chopped Marietta, you'd have to recreate it and that
would be next to impossible,'' said Cleland, noting that the plane
is almost entirely produced at the Marietta plant where some
families have two generations working.
</P>
<P>
   ``This aircraft cuts across the depth and breadth of our
nation's armed forces,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan is not included in the Defense Department's proposed
budget, Cleland said he would continue to try to sell the aircraft
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators are working on a deal to sell as many as six
aircraft to the Kuwait government, but it is not signed. The
Italian government has also expressed an interest in four planes.
</P>
<P>
   Not to move forward with the plan would be a major mistake, said
Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), whose district includes the Marietta plant
with its 8,000 workers. Barr said it made no sense to allow the
cargo plane line to be ``mothballed'' when there will be a high
demand for the plane in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a phenomenal waste of money to allow the line to
be shut down only to be restarted in a few years,'' Barr said. He
has sent Cohen a series of letters urging approval of the plan in
next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that the rumors of the demise of the C-130J line
and Lockheed Martin's plant in Marietta are greatly exaggerated,''
Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the House Armed Services have also given the plan a
nod. Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.), a committee member, said the
plan is not the same as giving a farmer a subsidy to let a field go
fallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lockheed will not be paid to delay production of aircraft,''
he said. Rather, the plan would allow Lockheed's contractors and
subcontractors to continue operations and deliver airplanes to the
military sooner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
