<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE REACHES OUT TO ENVIRONMENTALISTS WITH NEW TRADE REQUIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seeking to win the active support of environmental
groups that have so far failed to muster much enthusiasm for his
presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore announced Tuesday
that President Clinton was signing an executive order requiring
that environmental reviews be part of all new trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``America can and should use its trade policy to strengthen
environmental protection both at home and abroad,'' Gore said in
front of cameras at the airport here before returning to
Washington, D.C. ``This is really a significant, watershed event
for the relationship between trade and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The order will require the U.S. trade representative to conduct
full scale environmental reviews early in all major trade
negotiations, Gore said, ``so that we can use that information to
shape emerging trade agreements and to better protect our own
environment and the global environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the executive order does not apply to the environment in the
countries with which the United States enters into trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the order begins to put environmental concerns on a par
with business concerns in international agreements, a step that
environmental groups hailed Tuesday as significant, if only a start
in the long-time struggle between businesses and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a crucial time, as the world's trade ministers
prepare to meet in Seattle at the end of the month to discuss
international trade rules, and it sends a signal that the United
States considers environmental standards important.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes at a crucial time for Gore in his campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination. He has failed so far to stir
the passions of the environmental community on his behalf. The
administration's decision to let Gore make Tuesday's announcement
was a reflection both of his need to make some headway with this
important constituency and also of his push to make the
administration more sensitive to environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the vice president's hand behind this,'' said Daniel
Seligman, director of the Sierra Club's trade program. ``It
distinguishes him from the rest of the pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Seligman described former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for
the nomination and someone who has received strong marks from
environmentalists on other matters, as ``missing in action'' on
this subject.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Petsonk, international counsel for the Environmental
Defense Fund, welcomed the action as a good first step in bringing
the environmental impact of trade agreements before the public. She
said the executive order essentially codified the routine practice
during the Bush administration of making such assessments and that
the order now puts the burden on any future president to undo it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement Tuesday followed an hour-long closed-door
session with about a dozen environmental leaders here Monday night.
They have expressed concerns about the administration's commitment
to an array of environmental issues, from protection of salmon in
the Pacific Northwest to the permanent placement of a tug boat in
waters here to try to steer oil barges clear of hazards that could
result in spills.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the meeting described Gore's posture as
unusually pleading. He told his listeners that he and Clinton could
not have won in 1992 without their support and that while they may
have been disappointed with some administration actions, he needed
their active involvement now.
</P>
<P>
   Participants also said Gore distanced himself from some of
Clinton's environmental actions. For example, when asked about a
strip-mining provision that is being sought by Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., but is opposed by environmentalists, Gore said he had been
``on the road'' and was not up on the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   He also told them that environmental reviews would be a central
topic at the World Trade Organization talks here later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Seligman of the Sierra Club said the spirit of Gore's remarks
was encouraging. ``The core concern of environmentalists on trade
agreements has been the way trade rules restrict countries like us
from enforcing environmental standards,'' he said. ``We're not
trying to inject environmental standards into WTO; we want to
prevent WTO from weakening the standards we already have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
