u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX     11-16 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waddell patient despite losses
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even scouting prospects in Slovakia and Finland, Don
Waddell never was far from his hockey team last week.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone provided direct updates from his wife, his coach
or team counsel. It also provided a hookup to the Internet for
long-distance broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to two games on Real Audio,'' the Thrashers'
general manager said. ``I was up until 4:30 in the morning both
nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell is home now, but not quite on a rescue mission. Although
the Thrashers return home for tonight's game against Tampa Bay
after getting swept on a four-game road trip, Waddell is not
preparing to drop the roster in the office shredder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where your patience is tried,'' he said. ``You have to
be careful and not let your emotions get carried away with this.
The last few nights, don't you think I've been tossing and turning,
wondering, `OK, how can we get better? Is calling up (Andreas)
Karlsson going to make us better?' But if we won in Montreal, we'd
be sitting here thinking, `We're going in the right direction.' You
can't let a few losses dictate what you're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said he has no plans now either to swing a trade or call
up a prospect from Orlando (IHL) in an attempt to help a team that
scored six goals during the road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' last victory came against the Lightning two weeks
ago. But they followed that with losses to Boston 4-2, Florida 4-1,
New Jersey 5-1 and Montreal 4-2. However, the game against the
Devils was the only one the Thrashers never were in, which helped
persuade Waddell to hold off on any moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were losing every game 5-1, 6-1, I'd just say, `We're
not good enough,' '' Waddell said. ``But there's been games we
could've won, so you're hoping the players are using this as a
learning experience. You're hoping you don't go through games 60
through 70 like you did these last four.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlsson, a 6-foot-3 center with five goals and four assists
with Orlando, probably will be the next call-up from Orlando. Dean
Sylvester, a 6-2 winger with four goals, and defenseman Brett Clark
also could be summoned.
</P>
<P>
   The league has no shortage of trade speculation, particularly
with high-profile forwards Alexei Yashin and Keith Primeau still
out of camp and New Jersey's Brendan Morrison reportedly having
asked to be traded. But the Thrashers don't have the veteran
resources to make a deal and probably aren't going to part with any
of their younger players, prospects or draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day my phone rings, and every day I'm on the phone,''
Waddell said. ``That's my job. If something makes sense, I have to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything out there right now that makes sense? Not a
thing. . . . You don't make change for the sake of making change.
You make a change if it's going to help your hockey club. You don't
make a change to shake things up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers will play four of their next five games at home,
which Waddell hopes will be positive. The team has recorded six
points (2-2-1 with one regulation tie) in its past five home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm banking on,'' he said. ``We have a homestand,
and we need to win some games. You stay focused, you stay positive,
and you tell yourself you're still moving forward. It's not a
situation like, `We have to win tonight to make the playoffs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
