<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-ASSESS-825&AMP;ADD-     11-16 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ASSESS-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CHINA'S CONTRADICTORY IMPULSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-TRADE and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On Monday, President Jiang Zemin warmly played host to
American officials at his residence to celebrate a major trade
agreement that commits China to far-reaching economic reforms and
broad international ties.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, on the other side of Chang An Avenue, Jiang's
security police forcibly detained more than a dozen members of the
banned Falun Gong spiritual movement who had dared to unfurl a
yellow banner and meditate in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   The two events, only 24 hours apart, illustrated the
contradictory impulses now driving China, a country that one moment
seems to be hurtling toward a more open future and the next seems
mired in narrow communist orthodoxy and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, one day after the announcement of a trade deal that
is likely to lead to membership in the World Trade Organization,
China's state-controlled news media uniformly gushed over the
deal's benefits for business as well as foreign relations. The pact
will ``improve relations with other major powers, particularly the
U.S.,'' said the Beijing Youth Daily, a newspaper that just four
months ago was castigating the United States as an imperialist
invader for its bombing campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of paradoxes in China now that are difficult
to resolve,'' said Minxin Pei, a senior associate at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts in and outside China, as well as President Clinton,
have predicted that the opening of the economy required for entry
into the WTO would ultimately push China to liberalize in
non-economic spheres as well _ promoting, for example, more freedom
of the press and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the contradictory facets of China remain mostly
uncoupled, creating the odd juxtapositions of the past 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic dimension of China has been transformed to allow
for market forces and private property,'' said He Qinglian, a noted
author and economist from Shenzhen. ``But the other dimensions _
politics and ideology _ have changed very little. The political
system has changed only as much as demanded by economic change. And
in ideology, there's been very little change at all.''
</P>
<P>
   This is partly because China's leaders are much more unified on
the need for economic reform than for political reform, said Pei of
the Carnegie Endowment. And Chinese citizens are, for the moment,
far more concerned with improving their living standards than with
voting, he added.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts point out that there is a unifying impulse
behind the leaders' seemingly contradictory actions: to maintain
the power of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furthering of reform and opening characterized by the WTO
deal and the intensified crackdown on the sect and dissidents are
both fully in line with Deng Xiaoping theory, which calls for `both
hands being aggressive,''' said a researcher at the Institute of
Marxism, Leninism and Mao Tse-tung Theory of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   He said the leaders hoped that the trade deal would bring
foreign investment to maintain high economic growth, which would in
turn promote stability. ``If they can achieve these goals, it can
help consolidate the rule of the Communist Party, which _ remember
_ is the most important of Deng's four cardinal principles.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the Chinese government has grown increasingly
at home living in this divided world, making little effort to link
liberalizing economic and social policies with politics at home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 and '98, in the months preceding the exchange of state
visits by Jiang and Clinton, the Chinese routinely released
dissidents as a goodwill gesture, held only a few political trials
and even tolerated the development of an embryonic democratic
party.
</P>
<P>
   But this fall, even as Jiang toured Europe and chatted on the
phone with Clinton in pursuit of a trade agreement, Chinese courts
were sentencing pro-democracy activists to long prison terms after
brief trials without lawyers. And the Chinese police were detaining
thousands of Falun Gong members for practicing the form of exercise
and meditation that the government had banned.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong is an idiosyncratic blend of traditional Chinese
exercises and Buddhist and Taoist religious beliefs that was widely
popular _ before it was banned in July _ among middle-aged Chinese
for its supposed health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the government has been conducting an old-style
Maoist propaganda campaign to wipe out what it has labeled an
``evil sect,'' complete with re-education for members and detention
or labor camps for those who have publicly continued its practices.
</P>
<P>
   But in a China now filled with Internet cafes and Hong Kong
cable television, campaigns do not work as they used to, and this
one has fallen flat both among more devoted practitioners and among
the many Chinese who see the group as mostly harmless.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Tuesday, on a crisp fall morning in Tiananmen Square, a dozen
or so practitioners unfurled a banner reading ``The Great Law of
Falun'' and held out their hands to begin their exercises, a small
protest to attract the attention of the U.N. secretary-general,
Kofi Annan, who is visiting Beijing this week.
</P>
<P>
   Police in uniforms and plain clothes _ on bicycles, in vans and
on foot _ were out in large numbers and the protesters were kicked
and then shoved into vans, which sped out of the square, witnesses
said, apparently lightly injuring a bystander.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is unclear how long China's leaders can
aggressively open their economy to the outside world while pursuing
a totally closed political system at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole process of economic pluralism inevitably
leads to pluralism in ideology and other spheres, because it leads
to diversity of economic interests which in turn produces
distinctive needs and values,'' said Ms. He, the author and
economist.
</P>
<P>
   She said that at a time when China is changing so rapidly, the
country's sustaining value systems, Confucianism and communism, are
both collapsing _ leading to the rise of groups like Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   ``China still adheres to a monolithic ideology,'' she said.
``But a specialized professional society like China is becoming
requires a more innovative, pluralistic ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, as China's stock prices, after an initial surge in
response to the trade agreement, tapered off Tuesday, investors and
economists in China seemed uncertain that opening the economy
would, by itself, lead to the economic growth that the Communist
Party wants and needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of paradoxes we see today can last for some time,''
said Pei of the Carnegie Endowment. ``But no society can tolerate
that kind of dissonance forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
