u f BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT     11-16 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TEXAS REPS. APPLAUD OPENING CHINA MARKET TO FARMERS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Nov. 16 -- Texas congressmen gave a collective nod
to a U.S.-China trade deal that chops in half duties placed on farm
products that Texas has had trouble exporting.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which all but ensures China's membership in the
World Trade Organization, cuts tariffs on cotton, rice, wheat and
corn products, and permits trade between private companies for the
first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas representatives who oversee agriculture policy in the
House, Agriculture Committee Chairman Larry Combest, R-Amarillo,
and Ranking Member Charles Stenholm, D-Stamford, cautiously
supported the deal, saying it appears at first glance to be
favorable to U.S. farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is an important step towards an improved
trading relationship with China,'' Stenholm said in a press release
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, signed Monday by U.S. and Chinese trade
officials, China will reduce tariffs from an overall average of
22.1 percent down to 17 percent, and slash even more from
agricultural duties -- from 31.5 to 14.5 percent on average by
2004. U.S. exporters of wheat, corn, rice and cotton would enjoy
greater access to China. China promised to eliminate export
subsidies, opening the market for U.S. cotton and rice producers.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the agreement all but secures China's entry into the
World Trade Organization, the international trade policing body,
opening up international markets to China's textile and electronics
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pringle, a lobbyist for the Texas Farm Bureau, said
</P>
<P>
   the China deal is good news for Texas rice farmers. Texas makes
a long-grain rice that the Chinese would buy, he said, even though
that country already produces large amounts of rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``[With] the reduction in tariffs for corn and wheat and feed
grains such as rice, it's going to be a big plus for Texas,''
Pringle said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. sold $1.3 billion in agricultural goods to
China, including cow hides, grains and feeds, according to the
Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. exported $118 million of cotton to China last year, out
of $2.5 billion in total world cotton exports.
</P>
<P>
   Texas exports much less in food goods to China than to Mexico
and Latin America, both due to the high tariffs, as well as the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Texas exported $42.7 million in crop and livestock commodities
to China last year, and $32.1 million for processed foods. By
contrast, Texas sold $1.1 billion in crop and livestock to Mexico,
the state's largest trading partner, and $1 billion in processed
foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some room for growth there,'' said Beverly Boyd,
spokeswoman for the Texas Department of Agriculture. ``As the
leading cattle and cotton state in the nation, anything that
provides markets is definitely going to help Texas agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress will vote on whether to grant China permanent ``normal
trade relations'' status next year. Without permanent NTR status,
China's application to join the WTO next year would not open up
Chinese markets to U.S. businesses.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington's relations with China consistently have remained
tense over human rights and campaign finance issues, Farm Bureau
Lobbyist Steve Pringle foresees a battle among the Texas delegation
over the NTR vote.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran free-trader Rep. Bill Archer, R-Houston, who chairs the
Ways and Means committee that will vote on China's ``normal trade
relations'' status, said the administration did a ``good job'' of
securing the trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   Archer will vote to give China NTR status, which would benefit
South Texas, said Archer's spokesman Sean Rushton. ``Houston is, in
terms of tonnage per year, the biggest U.S. port; from that
perspective trade can help,'' Rushton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
