<HEADER>
A1769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FLA-FSU-COX     11-16 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLA-FSU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowden hopes history won't be repeated
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ The sequence of events from two years ago is
sharp in the 70-year-old mind of Bobby Bowden. The thrill of
success fades with time, the Florida State football coach said.
Heartache, however, remains clear forever.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has had a lot of success. On Oct. 23, he became the fifth
Division I-A coach in history to win 300 games. In his 33 years as
a head coach, he has lost 85 games. None of them, Bowden said
Tuesday, caused him more pain than the 32-29 loss to Florida in
Gainesville in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took Daddy a long time to get over that one,'' said son
Terry, the former Auburn coach who now is an analyst for ABC. ``In
some ways, I still don't think he's gotten over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State was 10-0 and ranked No. 1 that day. The loss
knocked the Seminoles out of a date with Nebraska in the Orange
Bowl, where they would have played for at least a share of the
national championship. Losing such an opportunity was bad enough.
Losing it to the Gators was unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 game was on the minds of Bowden and his Florida State
players as the No. 1 Seminoles prepared to play at No. 3 Florida on
Saturday. As was the case in 1997, a win puts Florida State into a
game _ the Sugar Bowl _ that will decide the national championship.
But also as in 1997, a loss would be a bitter failure and render
the season a failure by Florida State standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I cried after the 1997 game,'' defensive
tackle Jerry Johnson said. ``I don't want to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Florida State appeared to be in pretty good shape
late in the game. It had the ball and the lead, 26-25, with 4:58 to
play. Grind it out, Bowden told offensive coordinator Mark Richt.
We don't want to give the ball back to these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the plan,'' Richt said. ``We did not want their
offense to touch the ball again.''
</P>
<P>
   When Travis Minor burst off left tackle for 36 yards to the
Florida 6-yard line, the Seminoles were poised to put the game
away.
</P>
<P>
   But three plays later, Florida State was on the Florida 3-yard
line. Bowden decided to kick the field goal to give his team a
four-point lead, 29-25, with 2:38 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to score a touchdown and put the thing away,''
Bowden said. ``But we had to kick the field goal to get a
four-point lead. Now they have to move the ball 80 yards in just a
little time.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida took over on its 20. On the first play from scrimmage,
Gator quarterback Doug Johnson and wide receiver Jacquez Green
pulled a trick they had worked out on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson went to the line of scrimmage and gave a hand signal to
Green, indicating a short curl route about 10 yards over the
middle. Knowing that the Florida State secondary probably knew
their signals by then, the two had agreed that when Green saw the
sign, he would change his route and go long.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Cornerback Samari Rolle rushed up to cover the short
route, and Green blew past him and hauled in a pass that covered 63
yards, to the Florida State 17-yard line. Two plays later Fred
Taylor scored to put Florida ahead 32-29 with 1:46 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of plays that caused us to lose that game,
but that's the one people remember,'' defensive coordinator Mickey
Andrews said. ``I sure know I remembered it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, FSU quarterback Thad Busby was intercepted
and the game was over.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Florida State enters Florida's Swamp on Saturday, the
Seminoles are determined that such painful history will not be
repeated. Nobody should have to go through that twice in a
lifetime, Bowden said. Not even a 70-year-old coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time after that game before I was right with the
world,'' Bowden said. ``I do not want to go through that again.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE AT FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   _ When, where: 3:30 p.m. Saturday, Florida Field, Gainesville,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: CBS.
</P>
<P>
   _ Series: Florida leads 26-15-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last season: Florida State won 23-12.
</P>
<P>
   _ Records, rankings: Florida State 10-0, No. 1; Florida 9-1, No.
3.
</P>
<P>
   _ At stake: If Florida State wins, it will play in the national
championship game in the Sugar Bowl. If Florida wins, and also wins
the SEC championship game on Dec. 4, it has a good chance to reach
the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
