<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOPS URGED TO DELAY VOTE ON CATHOLIC COLLEGE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- As the nation's Catholic bishops sequestered
themselves to debate a proposal that would tighten church control
over Catholic colleges, educators and theologians urged Tuesday
them to put off a vote on the issue, saying there are still too
many unresolved concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop's vote, expected Wednesday, caps a year of debate on
a document drafted by a relatively conservative group of bishops
that attempts to strengthen the Catholic identity of colleges.
Known as Ex Corde Ecclesiae, the document would require colleges to
make sure a majority of their faculty and trustees be ``faithful''
Catholics, ask the presidents of institutions to take an oath of
fidelity, and require theology professors to have a mandate from
the local bishop saying they were teaching an approved version of
Catholic doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The bishops are facing pressure from the Vatican, which first
asked for the document nearly 10 years ago, and rejected as too
weak the version the bishops overwhelmingly approved in 1996. But
many Catholic colleges insist that the current version of Ex Corde,
written more along Vatican lines, will end up hurting the church
and the colleges by launching them into divisive debates on how to
define ``faithful,'' what to do with professors who refuse to seek
a mandate, and how much sway bishops would have over day to day
decisions like what speakers or student groups to allow on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the academy are afraid the bishops will vote hastily
when there are still a number of unresolved issues,'' said Father
Thomas Rausch, head of the theology department at Loyola Marymount
University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was to come this morning, and approval requires
two-thirds of the bishops here, which Tuesday totaled 283. The
bishops can vote to approve the document, or they can simply vote
to table it, sending it back for more consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents took as a sign of hope that the bishops had requested
a secret ballot, as opposed the more usual voice vote or show of
hands. This way, they said, the bishops could vote their true
feelings without fear of recrimination from the 10 cardinals, most
of whom have been vigorous supporters of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the conference of bishops went into private session for
the afternoon, in which they were expected to spend much of their
time debating Ex Corde. Outside the vote, observers predicted that
the 10 cardinals would try to assess the document's chances of
success based on the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the leadership thinks it won't get two-thirds, rather than
embarrass themselves and the Vatican, they'll just send it back for
more study,'' said Father Thomas J. Reese, editor of America, the
Jesuit magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ex Corde Ecclesiae came out of the concern that Catholic
universities would go the way of their Protestant cousins: as
places like Boston College, Notre Dame, and Georgetown became more
national universities, they would also become more secular. The
Vatican first approved it in 1990, and it was to be adapted, or
``normed'' to each region of the world within a few years. But no
other region has approved it, and the US region, as the largest, is
expected to set the standard. The US conference of bishops approved
a set of norms in 1996 by a vote of 226-4. But the Vatican sent
back that version, asking for a legal interpretation. A revised
version that came out of the bishops meeting here a year ago
prompted wide complaint from colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents support defending their institutions against
creeping secularism. But what's at stake, they say, are principles
key to the tradition of higher education in this country: academic
freedom and institutional autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the concerns were addressed in yet another revision that
came out in the early summer. But that version, Rausch said, simply
put the worrisome passages into the footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty of the vote, though, is that no one among
the bishops or colleges seems to know exactly how the document
would play out. Much, supporters and opponents agree, depends on
particular relationships between college presidents and bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Still, supporters say, Ex Corde is a necessary step to
protecting the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't preserve, as Catholics, the gift the church has
given to the world through our universities, then who will,
Harvard?'' said Manuel Miranda, head of the Cardinal Newman
society, which has been one of the strongest supporters of the
version of Ex Corde approved last year. ``The universities, left to
themselves, are not doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
