<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, FOR THE GOOD OLD DAYS OF 1998
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when the USC-UCLA game would inspire the
passions of the local citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the USC-UCLA game would decide the Pac-10
representative for the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the USC-UCLA game was shown on national
television and actually was awaited with breathless anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, for the good old days when the schools believe it or not
actually fielded winning football teams that routinely were in the
Top10 rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Why, I can remember way back to 1998 when the Bruins came into
the game undefeated and needing a victory to preserve a shot at the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   They got it, of course my memory isn't quite good enough any
longer to recall the last time the Bruins actually suffered the
indignity of losing to USC but, alas, that would be the last
important victory in the UCLA program.
</P>
<P>
   Well, anyway, for better or for worse, they're going to stage
this country's most renowned college football city rivalry again
this Saturday when the Trojans and Bruins stumble into each other
at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   As you might have heard, USC and UCLA are the latest to become
ensnared in the Great L.A. Sports Curse of the 1990s that has
featured such ugly phenomena as the Raiders and Rams bolting the
area, the Dodgers deteriorating into a low-rated Fox comedy show,
the Lakers making it a sacred spring custom of getting swept in the
NBA playoffs, the Clippers being, well, the Clippers, the Angels
getting everyone fired, etc., etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are all sorts of riveting questions surrounding
Saturday's pillow match between the Bruins and Trojans even though
both teams enter it with 4-6 records and both have inspired
dizzying levels of indifference among their loyalists this bitterly
disappointing season:
</P>
<P>
   Will R. Jay Soward, the Trojans' notoriously brash receiver,
make a Joe Namath-like victory guarantee for his team, which,
considering that the Trojans have lost eight straight times to the
Bruins, might not be such a brash proclamation?
</P>
<P>
   Will the Trojans' goofy second-year coach, Paul (Can't) Hackett,
finally put the finger of blame on himself rather than on his
players and coaches as he's done in the past if the six-point
favorite Trojans are upset?
</P>
<P>
   How will the Bruins' coach, Bob Toledo, explain to disgruntled
alums his reasons for keeping quarterback Ryan McCann hidden all
season if McCann is able to continue the magic against USC that he
displayed against Washington?
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans are playing horribly and losing at halftime not
exactly out of the realm of possibility will their voluble
athletics director, Mike Garrett, storm into the dressing room and
give his best Rockne impersonation, as he's been known to do in the
past?
</P>
<P>
   Will Paul (Can't) Hackett wear his sunglasses even if it's an
overcast day, as he did in South Bend during the Trojans' glorious
loss to Notre Dame?
</P>
<P>
   Will the retired broadcaster, Keith Jackson, who actually came
out of retirement this fall to work again for ABC until he decided
to re-retire this week in lieu of working the USC-UCLA game, watch
the proceedings on television, or will he participate in a lawn
bowling tournament?
</P>
<P>
   Will Soward and Kareem Kelly storm off the field in protest if
Paul (Can't) Hackett decides to replace his quarterback, John Fox,
with Mike Van Raaphorst, as he's been known to do in the past?
</P>
<P>
   Will John Papadakis, the 300-pound beloved father of injured
Trojans' running back Petros Papadakis, invite the team over to his
San Pedro restaurant for the traditional pregame Greek repast, or
will he skip the annual ritual and, instead, Fed-Ex a crate of feta
cheese to the Trojans in protest of their lousy record?
</P>
<P>
   Will the Trojans win one for dear old Travis Claridge, their
senior right tackle who has started every game at USC since his
freshman season, meaning he has suffered unspeakable agony?
</P>
<P>
   Will Chad Morton score more touchdowns than DeShaun Foster?
</P>
<P>
   Will and this is on the lips of every fan in L.A. John Fox throw
more touchdown passes than Ryan McCann?
</P>
<P>
   What UCLA defense will show up, the one that yielded 55 points
to Oregon State or the one that shut down the Washington Huskies so
effectively last Saturday?
</P>
<P>
   What kind of trick plays does the tricky Bob Toledo have in
store for the Trojans?
</P>
<P>
   What kind of trick plays that the not so tricky Paul (Can't)
Hackett have in store for the Bruins?
</P>
<P>
   Where will the bus bringing the Bruins' players to the Coliseum
park?
</P>
<P>
   Is it true that Terry Donahue would savor a Bruins loss even
more than Trojan fans will?
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans blow another one to the Bruins, will some wealthy
Trojan alum from Orange County step gallantly forward and offer to
buy out the remaining three years on Hackett's contract to save the
USC football program from imminent ruin?
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone other than the coaches, players, cheerleaders, band
members, alums and ADs oh, I'm sure UCLA's Peter (Principle) Dalis
is quaking in his bureaucratic Guccis even care about a about a
game whose unimportance this season is exceeded only by its
insignificance?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
