<SLUG> BC-GA-FIRES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More firefighting help arriving to battle Georgia blazes
 &HT;    By Rick Badie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Another 100 firefighters are expected to join a
massive national effort today to stop wildfires raging in three
rain-deprived northeast Georgia counties.
</P>
<P>
   The specially-trained ``Hot Shot'' crews arriving today bring to
375 the number of firefighters from across the country who since
Monday have joined local firefighting efforts. The initial fires
started Saturday in the Blood Mountain Wilderness area, but since
then others have ignited in the volatile region. Forest Services
officials say the fire were deliberately set.
</P>
<P>
   Now six fires are burning about 2,500 acres, the most worrisome
being Rich Mountain in Gilmer County. One of three fires on that
mountain continued to burn late Tuesday, threatening about 700
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Uncontrolled fires continue to burn at Stanley Gap in Fannin
County and on Blood Mountain, southwest of Neels Gap. Another three
fires in Lumpkin County and one in Gilmer County were contained
Tuesday, but still burned.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service officials worry that upslope winds, forest
foliage and dry conditions may spark fresh fires or rekindle
smothering ones. Firefighters will work through the night to
prevent the fires from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a pretty tough situation,'' said Mike
Melton, a commander overseeing the effort. ``This is rugged,
remote, tough terrain. We're dealing with the wilderness, some
private land and some federal land. And we've had a dry summer. We
need rain.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, forest officials closed a 13-mile stretch of
the Appalachian Trail as well as access routes between Woody Gap
and Neels Gap. Two of the contained fires are located near Blood
Mountain, southwest of Neels Gap in Lumpkin County.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, smoke from the Rich Mountain fire was visible at
Woody Gap, about 10 miles north of Dahlonega. Firefighters spent
Tuesday battling blazes ranging from 6 to 10 feet high in rugged,
breath-taking terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``That fire is going pretty good,'' said Dennis Daniel, a
district ranger with the U.S. Forest Service in Blairsville. ``And
it has the potential to get bigger. It's going to take significant
resources to get it under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters arriving today from the West will join their
colleagues in working 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. daily. That will allow
more crew members to be on hand in the middle of the day, ``when
everything is hottest,'' Melton said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 firefighters battled the initial blaze on Blood
Mountain over the weekend.Three fires started about the same time
Saturday afternoon in the 7,800-acre wilderness area, which sprawls
across the Lumpkin-Union county line. Blood Mountain is Georgia's
highest point on the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   No firefighters have been injured since crews from the
Chattahoochee National Forest, National Park Service, Georgia
Forestry Commission first began battling the blaze over the
weekend. Out-of-state firefighters hail from California, Puerto
Rico and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Badie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
