<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX-CRUSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORVALDS BUILDS EXPECTATIONS ABOUT NEW `SMART' CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ For years now one of the most closely guarded
secrets in California's Silicon Valley has concerned what goes on
inside a one-story building in Mountain View known for its
dark-tinted windows.
</P>
<P>
   The company inside is Transmeta Corp., but few could say what it
did. Speculation about its motivations heated up when Transmeta
hired Linus Torvalds, developer of the Linux computer operating
system and a folk hero among many programmers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, speaking here Monday night before a crowd of 7,000 at
Comdex, the world's largest computer trade show, Torvalds began to
spill the beans. But not all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Transmeta, Torvalds said in the course of his talk, makes a
``smart'' microprocessor, the first built with software. But then,
when an audience member dared to ask Torvalds to elaborate, he
clammed up. He said he couldn't comment further. The company, he
said, would disclose full details on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike the ambiguous, adrenalin-charged teasers that
Hollywood produces for its untested blockbusters, the computer and
software industry is well known for building marketing buzz as it
labors to iron out kinks in new products.
</P>
<P>
   In Transmeta's case, this strategy is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's created hype by not creating hype,'' said Kevin Krewell,
senior analyst with MicroDesign Resources in Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The computer elite at Linux Business Expo, a sideshow at Comdex,
say Torvald's comments, along with clues provided in four patents
Transmeta has filed with the US Patent Office since Nov. 3, 1998,
suggest the announcement may be worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, microprocessors are providing the brainpower to
drive portable devices such as palm-size organizers and cellular
phones. Until now, they haven't been made to hold software, which
must sit separately on a computer's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Transmeta, it seems, is out to change that, but exactly how
remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's controllable through software, you can download
upgrades directly onto the chip'' without having to physically
remove the chip from the computer and replace it with a new one,
said John Sherman, chief executive at Sherman &AMP; Associates, a
software developer in San Diego. ``Imagine having a Pentium II and
being able to just download software to change that chip to a
Pentium III.''
</P>
<P>
   Programmable microprocessors potentially mean the chip would
also morph from one type, say a chip made by Intel to run Microsoft
applications, to a Motorola chip that runs Apple Macintosh
software, said Christopher Bohan, an analyst with Headwaters
Capital, a securities trading firm in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already have software emulators that let you run an Intel
program on a Mac and vice versa, but that's very inefficient,''
said Bohan. ``This would make the transition a lot faster, and
that's one of the things that makes this a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the computer world where speed is a premium, anything that
makes software run faster is seen as a valuable commodity, making
the Transmeta microprocessor concept a potential milestone, said
Phil Hughes, publisher of Linux Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they're doing, and they know they've got a
serious product,'' said Hughes, who believes the secrecy
surrounding Transmeta had to do with its desire not to tip its hand
to competitors. ``They see this as revolutionary, and they don't
want someone else to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With its product now close to launch, Transmeta apparently
believes it is safe to release a few crumbs through Torvalds.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the company's one-page Web site, which previously was
blank, added another scrap for the hungry. Displaying the product's
name, ``Crusoe,'' the page proclaims: ``We rethought the
microprocessor to create a whole new world of mobility,''
suggesting that its new chip would be used in small, mobile
computing devices such as cellular phones or pocket-size ``Internet
appliances.''
</P>
<P>
   The site also has a ``secret message'' that can be accessed by
looking at the site's source code. The brief message said: ``Crusoe
will be cool hardware and software for mobile applications. Crusoe
will be unconventional, which is why we wanted to let you know in
advance to come look at the Web site in January, so that you can
get the full story and have access to all of the details as soon as
they are available.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Transmeta may be unconventional, its investors are
anything but. Among those who have banked on the company's future
are Vulcan Ventures, owned by Paul Allen, a founder of Microsoft
Corp. Others who have reportedly poured hundreds of millions into
Transmeta include Soros Funds, BankBoston Robertson Stephens, and
Institutional Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Will Crusoe live up to this level of
anticipation?'' said Krewell of MicroDesign Resources. ``The
Transmeta folks will say they haven't created expectations, because
they haven't said anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But here in Las Vegas, where the dice roll all night, they
certainly have created anticipation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
