<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-TURKEYSIDES-SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEYSIDES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1997).
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Simple Side Dishes Complement Turkey  &HT;       
 These recipes all come from ``The San Francisco Chronicle 
 Cookbook,'' by Michael Bauer and Fran Irwin (Chronicle Books,  &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; No Thanksgiving is complete without a tableful of
side dishes to accompany the traditional holiday turkey. The trick
is picking dishes that complement the bird without competing but
that are also wonderful in their own right. Picking and choosing
cooking method is important, too, since oven space is often at a
premium.
<P>
   Oven-Fried Sweet Potatoes are a great twist to grandma's sugary
sweet potato casserole. The addictive sweet potatoes caramelize in
the oven, giving off a natural sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bauer's Drunken Beans are a great alternative to plain
steamed green beans. Beans are added to a vodka reduction, which
glazes them beautifully. (All the alcohol is cooked off.)
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant bitter flavor of Braised Bitter Greens tempers the
richness of the rest of the holiday meal. And the combination of
fennel, orange and red onion make for a refreshing salad.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MICHAEL BAUER'S DRUNKEN BEANS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup vodka
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound green beans
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large saucepan over medium-high heat.
Add the onion, 1/2 teaspoon or so of the pepper, and a little salt.
Saute about 3 minutes. Turn heat to high and add 1/4 cup vodka and
the vinegar. Reduce to a glaze and add more vodka, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with the final 1/4 cup of vodka. When the liquid has
evaporated, add the green beans and cover with water. Add more salt
and pepper and let boil over high heat until all the cooking liquid
has evaporated and forms a glaze on the vegetables. This should
take about 35 to 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 11 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 540 mg sodium, 3 g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FENNEL, ORANGE &AMP; RED ONION SALAD
</P>
<P>
   This simple salad, from Georgeanne Brennan, is pretty, has great
flavor and is quick to make. It goes well with turkey and other
rich meats, such as sausage, roast pork or pot roast.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 medium fennel bulbs
</P>
<P>
   2 oranges
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped chervil, arugula or parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Trim the fennel bulbs, removing the stalks and any discolored
pieces. Cut into 1/4-inch slices and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the oranges, divide them into sections and remove the white
pith. Set aside 6 sections and cut the remainder in half and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the onion into thin slices and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the juice of the 6 orange sections, the olive oil,
balsamic vinegar and chopped herbs to make a dressing. Combine all
the salad ingredients in a glass or ceramic bowl; add the dressing
and let stand at room temperature for about 30 minutes. Stir
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Serve as is or on a bed of butter lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 140 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 13 g carbohydrate,
9 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 41 mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OVEN-FRIED SWEET POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   The slices of sweet potatoes become crispy and slightly
caramelized in the hot oven, bringing out their natural sweetness.
Pile them on a heated serving platter and let guests help
themselves. Some people, you will find, may enjoy eating them with
their fingers. This recipe, from Georgeanne Brennan, makes a nice
change from the traditional candied yam dish.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 pounds sweet potatoes (12 to 15 potatoes)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 3 or 4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh marjoram or thyme
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 475 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut them in half across the middle, then
cut the halves lengthwise into 1/4-inch-thick slices. Put the
slices into a bowl and add 1/2 cup oil, the marjoram or thyme, salt
and pepper. Toss several times to coat the slices with oil and
seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the slices evenly in a single layer on baking sheets.
Bake for 8 to 10 minutes, then turn the slices and bake until
slightly crisped and tender, 5 to 7 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Scoop the hot slices back into the bowl. Add the remaining 3 or
4 tablespoons oil and turn the slices until they glisten.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 305 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 41 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 15 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 342 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ONE MARKET'S CREAMED SPINACH WITH BACON &AMP; ONIONS
</P>
<P>
   This recipe, from chef Bradley Ogden, goes well with turkey,
whether it's barbecued, smoked, brined or the traditional roasted
bird.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced bacon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds spinach, washed, dried
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups cream
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Render the bacon in a Dutch oven over moderately low heat until
crisp. Add the onion and saute until softened. Add the spinach and
cook, turning and stirring, until just wilted. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the excess liquid into a skillet. Add the cream to the
skillet, bring to a boil and reduce by half. Season with nutmeg.
Pour over the spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 325 calories, &LR;   &LR; 11 g protein, 11 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 29 g fat (16 g saturated), 90 mg cholesterol, 321
mg sodium, 8 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BRAISED BITTER GREENS
</P>
<P>
   These greens, from Joyce Goldstein, are delicious, and go
particularly well with the Thanksgiving feast. The bitter flavor
tempers the richness of dark-meat turkey and gravy, of butter-laced
mashed potatoes, creamed onions, sweet potato casserole and all the
other lush dishes of the holiday table.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 to 21/2 pounds assorted bitter greens (escarole, chicory, beet
greens, mustard greens, collards, mizuna, broccoli rabe, endive,
etc.)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, as needed
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 garlic cloves, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh very hot pepper, finely minced, or 1 tablespoon hot red
pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons minced anchovies (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Wash the greens well and trim off any tough stems or unsightly
leaves. Cut or chop very large leaves into large bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil. Add the greens and
cook, uncovered, for about 10 minutes, until quite soft. Drain
well.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little olive oil in large saute pan. Add the garlic, hot
pepper and anchovies, if using. Warm over moderate heat for a few
minutes. Add the drained greens, tossing them in the hot oil.
Simmer gently for 5 minutes. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 21 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fat, 0 mg cholesterol, 25 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
