<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED RATE INCREASE REASSURES INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board raised the federal funds and discount
rates Tuesday by a quarter of a percentage point to cool down the
economy, saying the nation is expanding in ``excess of its growth
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market index leaped to a record after the news, while
the Dow Jones industrial average staged a surprise rally, gaining
more than 170 points after the Fed's Open Market Committee
announced its decision at about 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed reassured by the Fed's statement that it does
not intend to raise rates again in the near future, a promise it
had made in June after the first of the current round of increases
in the federal funds rate. Markets seemed to trust that this would
be the last rate increase for a while, given that the vote came on
the heels of recent government reports that inflation is low and
productivity is accelerating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is saying, `We don't care if the Fed raised rates.
We just don't want it to do it again,' '' said William Rhodes, a
vice president in Boston for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that if the government's report on the consumer
price index, to be released Wednesday, is ``really ugly, people
will begin to second guess what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed, seeking to slow an economy that grew at a 4.8 percent
annual rate in this year's third quarter, said it would raise the
federal funds rate a quarter point, to 5.5 percent. That reinstated
the interest rate banks charge each other for overnight loans to
its level in 1998, before a money-loosening policy was instituted
to avert financial crises abroad and on Wall Street. The full
reversal was cited as another reason investors were confident
another rate hike is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed Tuesday also raised the discount rate that it charges
member banks by a quarter point, to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focus on inflation _ the traditional reason for
raising rates _ the Fed tilted its reasoning subtly to focus on the
risks of a fast-growing economy. The gross domestic product, which
grew 4.3 percent in 1998, gained speed during the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although cost pressures appear generally contained,'' the Fed
statement said, ``risks to sustainable growth persist.'' Despite
strong productivity gains, ``the expansion of activity continues in
excess of the economy's growth potential.'' The excess growth has
drained the economy of workers, a trend that must be ``contained if
inflationary imbalances are to remain in check.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase, economists said, was inevitable, if not now
then early next year. Economists for months have predicted that the
Fed members would be compelled to take back all of the rate
reductions instituted during last year's global crisis, from which
the world economy has rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was optimistic it had seen the last of the rate
hikes. The Dow rose 171.58 points, up 1.6 percent to a 10,932.33
close. The Nasdaq index gained 25.64 points; the 1.84 percent rise
in the technology-heavy index pushed it to a new record, 3293.05.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the time being there's a closure here,'' said Dick Rippe,
economist for Prudential Securities Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the tea leaves in the Fed's statement, economists noted
that it contained some ambivalence _ even confusion _ about what to
do in this unusual period of rapid growth and low, low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In this booming economy, extremely high productivity, due to
investment in computer technology by corporate America, has been a
key force in keeping inflation in check. Productivity rose at an
astonishing 4.2 percent rate in the July-September quarter,
continuing a trend started more than a year ago that is credited
with keeping wage costs, a component of inflation, in check. The
Labor Department also reported recently that producer prices in
October fell by 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the argument the United States is experiencing a
technology-driven boom _ the ``New Economy'' _ criticized the Fed
for its latest rate hike. Wayne Angell, a former Fed governor and
now senior managing director at Bear Stearns &AMP; Co., said, ``We have
a huge rate of return on capital in the United States, which is
giving us a wonderful world that is benefitting everyone.'' Yet, he
said, ``the Fed seems dissatisfied with this near-utopy condition
that has developed.''
</P>
<P>
   With inflation relatively low, Nicholas Perna, an economist with
Perna Associates, said the Fed gave other arguments for its rate
increase. In order to increase rates, he said, the Fed ``said if we
continue to grow as fast as we are we'll have a problem,'' Perna
said.
</P>
<P>
   This does not, he warned, preclude the Fed from raising rates
again next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
