A1786 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CHINA-IMPACT-COX     11-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business entities like sound of U.S.-China trade pact
 &HT;    By Ben Sutherly
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Ohio _ The trade accord reached Monday between China and
the United States is drawing measured but hopeful reactions from
commodity groups and brokers hungry for more details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it positive? Yes. To what extent? I think it's too early to
tell,'' said Bob Linkhorn, president of Limaco Inc., an Urbana cash
grain broker and agrimarketing consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Linkhorn said the deal will be no ``short-term fix'' for low
soybean prices. But he said hopes for long-term Sino-U.S. trade
relations underpin the agreement, which would reduce beef and pork
tariffs from 45 and 20 percent, respectively, to 12 percent for
both products by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   News of the accord pleased American Soybean Association
officials, who said China and Hong Kong took in about $890 million,
or 12 percent, of U.S. soy exports last year _ just four years
after China exported some of its soybean products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major leap forward. We think China will continue to be
our largest growth opportunity for U.S. soybeans,'' said Bob
Callanan, ASA communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Callanan said China's booming economy and increased per capita
spending are fueling unprecedented demand for soybeans and other
soy products. He said China already consumes more U.S.-processed
soybean oil than any other country.
</P>
<P>
   Callanan said ASA will urge Congress to grant China permanent
``normal trade relations'' status if the country becomes part of
the 135-nation World Trade Organization. Currently, uninterrupted
trade with China requires annual congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The pact with China also is raising hopes within Delphi
Automotive Systems Inc.,
</P>
<P>
   Delphi spokesman Peter Rowe said, ``Delphi is eager to review
the details of the agreement to assure it will open up
opportunities for our company.''
</P>
<P>
   He said company officials are ``delighted'' that negotiators for
the two countries reached an agreement and hope the other World
Trade Organization members will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Membership in the WTO will help China continue economic
reforms, accelerate their progress into the market economy and
improve the living standards for all Chinese citizens,'' Rowe said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-China trade agreement will likely help NCR Corp.'s
efforts to sell automatic teller machines, cash register and store
systems and data warehousing systems, said Sajid Malhotra, NCR's
investor relations vice president.
</P>
<P>
   NCR opened an ATM manufacturing plant in Beijing last month and
has plans to sell ATMs and other products in emerging markets such
as China and India, Malhotra said. ``We have no doubt ATMs will
present huge opportunities in India and China because these are
both cash-based economies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While there is one ATM for every 15,000 people in the U.S.,
there is only one ATM for every 1 million people in China and one
for every 10 million in India. China and India make up one-third of
the world's 6 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   NCR has been doing business in China for 10 years and holds 40
percent of the ATM market.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra said ATM deployment in China depends more on acceptance
by local banks than the new trade agreement. But as foreign banks
move in and offer ATMs, it may prompt Chinese banks to use them
too, Malhotra said.
</P>
<P>
   NCR has some customers in China that have NCR data warehouses _
large computer systems to track vast amounts of information, he
said. However, China lacks national or regional retailers similar
to Wal-Mart or Home Depot so it is more difficult for NCR to sell
cash register and retail computer systems to smaller stores and
operations, he said. _ Staff Writers Lynn Hulsey and Laura A.
Bischoff contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Sutherly writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: ben_sutherlycoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
