<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics.  WINE POTPOURRI: Light and Fruity Goes Great With Thanksgiving 
 &HT;       
 Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Thanksgiving ranks high on the list of popular
American holidays. Why? My guess is that people like Thanksgiving
because it has no political or religious connection. Instead,
Thanksgiving is a day for families and friends to come together and
celebrate the American way of life.
<P>
   Of course, that American way of life often means eating, eating
and more eating. Thanksgiving meals are personal, with favorite
dishes showing up on the table year after year. Although the meal
usually revolves around the traditional bird, the range of side
dishes bring on a variety of flavors and seasonings that challenge
even the most creative wine drinker.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you could wimp out and go for the safe-three: a
simple semi-dry white, a fruity ros &LR; e &LR;  and a user-friendly red.
You'd have all the bases covered but the easy way out doesn't say
much for your wine choices.
</P>
<P>
   The meat _ turkey, ham _ whatever, is not as important as the
side dishes. Turkey breast meat on its own is fairly bland and
lightly flavored, usually calling for a light white or red wine.
Dress up the meat with gravy, a scoop of seasoned dressing and some
cranberry sauce and a light white disappears under flavor overkill.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed is a wine with more guts and maybe a little
sweetness, like Riesling, Chenin Blanc or a light red such as
Beaujolais or a California Gamay. Another ideal choice with this
menu is a dry to semi-dry fruity rose, especially if the meat of
choice is ham. As for the candied yams; lose the wine and buy a
bottle of sweet apple cider instead.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you can't get through the day without Cabernet Sauvignon
or Chardonnay, leave those wines for another meal. Most popular
Chardonnays are too oaky and most Cabernets are too young and
tannic, setting up serious confrontations with traditional
Thanksgiving side dishes. Keep the wine simple and fruity,
including Merlot and Zinfandel, unless you can find a light and
fruity example of either wine where oak is not the dominant
component, as it is in many of the young reds now on retail
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The main thing is to relax, enjoy the day and the meal and don't
worry about the wine. A traditional Thanksgiving meal is not the
time to bring out your best bottles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Wine Choices &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Two wines that pop up this time of year is Beaujolais and
sparkling wines. Both are good choices with Thanksgiving dinner.
</P>
<P>
   French Beaujolais Nouveau, the first red wine of the new vintage
is released the third Thursday of November and on store shelves
soon after. Nouveau is the ultimate quaffing wine, fruity, grapey
and very drinkable, just the kind of red wine to complement a range
of Thanksgiving flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Sparkling wines are more problematic, since some people find the
bubbles get in the way of a good meal. And a good match is needed
so the delicate fruit of most sparklers isn't overwhelmed. If
bubbly is your choice for Thanksgiving meal, stay with California
Blanc de Noirs or Extra Dry, Italian Asti Spumante or French
sparkling Vouvray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peter Mondavi Rare Wines &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Peter Mondavi Family, owner of Charles Krug Winery in the
Napa Valley, has released a selection of 4000 bottles of Charles
Krug Vintage Selection Cabernet Sauvignons dating back to 1974.
Bottle sizes range from 750 ml to 18 liter, with an emphasis on
larger bottles. All wines have been stored in the winery's cellar.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact Andy Fromm at (707) 967-2214.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Q &AMP; A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In September, a reader asked about a wine reviewed in the
Chronicle Wine Selections, called Buffalo Ridge Syrah. We had the
wine but not the producer. Then, thanks to alert readers, the
mystery was solved. The Buffalo Ridge brand is owned by winemaker
Tom Eddy, with the Syrah grapes coming from the French Camp
Vineyard in the Central Coast. You can reach Eddy in Napa at (707)
462-7196.
</P>
<P>
   Sasikala Devi of McKinleyville wrote to say she thinks wine is
``bloody sour grape juice,'' and it's ``too trendy and too pc.''
Devi enjoyed a recent Potpourri on Sherry and asked if I would ever
consider writing about other fortified wines like Port and Madeira?
You bet. In fact, I've written about both Port and Madeira and plan
to write more about these two excellent, but often ignored, wines
in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Plan for the Future &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you like Australian wines, especially reds from the Barossa
Valley, McLaren Vale and Coonawarra, set your sights on the red
wines of the excellent 1998 vintage. A vintage chart, based on a
scale where 10 is perfection, published by the Australian Wine
Export Council gives a 10 to Coonawarra reds and a 9 to red wines
from the Barossa Valley and McLaren Vale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Mixable Cognac &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to crack the growing market of generation x-ers,
Cognac producers are also spending a lot of time, effort and money
on promoting the ``mixability'' of Cognac. Not since the first
Cognacs were sipped in the 15th century has there been much
interest in serving Cognac any other way but straight, as an
after-dinner drink.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a refreshing drink is a blend of Cognac and tonic. The
Cognac producers enjoy Cognac with crushed ice, ginger ale and
tonic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Refreshing News &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen often, but a California winery is dropping
Chardonnay from its line in favor of a lesser-known white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley's Swanson Vineyards has decided to stop making
Chardonnay and concentrate on Pinot Grigio. The 1997 vintage of
Swanson Carneros Chardonnay is the winery's last. Swanson also
produces Syrah, Merlot, Sangiovese and Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
