<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-PIE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.  SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Dreamy Pie: Park Chow chef balances flavor, 
 texture in perfect ending for Thanksgiving feast 
 &HT;       
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Tony Gulisano may have his heart in Italy, but he
has a way with American desserts.
<P>
   At his new Park Chow, a sister restaurant to his moderately
priced Chow in the Castro, the chef serves a spectacular version of
pecan pie.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with most pecan pie recipes is that they are so rich
and sweet that the nuts seem like an afterthought. Gulisano doesn't
skimp on the ingredients; the filling is cooked giving it a silken
texture. During baking the pecans rise to the top.
</P>
<P>
   This is only one of the homey pies he serves at his
Italian-style restaurant; it could be butterscotch banana or
coconut cream.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Guliasano makes a great roast chicken and an
old-fashioned spaghetti and meatballs. Few dishes are more than
$10.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Park Chow, 1240 Ninth Ave. (near Irving Street), San
Francisco; &LR;   &LR; (415) 665-9912. Open from lunch through dinner daily.
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Boiling the filling. &LR;  Pecan pie filling is rarely cooked before
being poured into the shell and baked. It's a technique usually
reserved for chess pies.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Freezing the pie shell. &LR;  The unbaked pie shell is placed in
the freezer briefly so when the filling is poured in, the crust
will stay firm.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; The brown sugar. &LR;  Pure cane sugar, such as C &AMP; H, has a
reliable flavor and texture.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BUTTER PECAN PIE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Crust
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups unbleached all-purpose flour + additional flour for
rolling pastry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sea salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (6 ounces) chilled unsalted butter, cut into cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ice water
</P>
<P>
   The Filling
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups pecans (halves and pieces)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup C &AMP; H golden brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 scant cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon sea salt
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream or lightly whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the crust:  &LR; Combine the 11/2 cups flour and the salt in
a food processor and mix briefly. Gradually add the butter to the
flour mixture while pulsing the processor on and off, until the
butter is cut into pieces the size of small peas. With the
processor running, gradually add the ice water and process until
large clumps form. Remove the dough from the processor, shape into
a ball, and flatten into a disk. Wrap in plastic and refrigerate 1
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Let the dough soften slightly at room temperature. Roll the
dough on a lightly floured surface into a 13-inch round. Carefully
transfer the dough to a 9-inch pie pan. Trim any dough hanging over
the edge. Crimp the edges decoratively. Freeze for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the filling:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Combine
the pecans, brown sugar, corn syrup, butter, flour and salt in a
heavy saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, stirring
constantly. Remove from heat. Cool 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the eggs and vanilla. Stir about 1/2 cup of the
hot sugar mixture into the eggs to temper them, then stir this
mixture into the hot sugar mixture. Pour the filling into the pie
shell.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10 minutes. Reduce the oven temperature to 325. Bake until
the custard has set and the nuts rise to the top, about 30 to 40
minutes. Transfer to a rack and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with ice cream or whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 715 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 78 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 45 g fat (20 g saturated), 157 mg cholesterol, 393 mg sodium, 2 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
