<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKBOULUD-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS: Restaurant Recipes Inspire Boulud's Cookbook  &HT;     By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Some famous-chef cookbooks dazzle with extravagant
victuals and preparations. Celebrated chef Daniel Boulud's
just-published book shines with a simple love of food and respect
for ingredients.
<P>
   The book is modeled after the menus of his New York restaurant
Caf &LR; e &LR;  Boulud, where dishes are listed in four categories _ La
Tradition (classic French), La Saison (pick of the seasonal
provender), Le Voyage (garnered from cuisines around the world),
and Le Potager (from the garden). Diners at Caf &LR; e &LR;  Boulud are
encouraged to skip from category to category with their taste buds
as the only guide. The chef invites readers of ``Caf &LR; e &LR;  Boulud
Cookbook'' to do the same, and it's splendid advice.
</P>
<P>
   Boulud admits he takes a few liberties with traditional recipes.
He embellishes &LR;  garbure &LR;  (thick French peasant soup, usually based
on potatoes and cabbage) with lobster and duck confit _
unquestionably more  &LR; haute &LR;  than the hearty dish served at Caf &LR; e &LR; 
Boulud near Lyon, which was started by his great-grandparents. But
he says the spirit and soul of the original farmhouse dish are
intact.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, many of the book's recipes seem complicated,
but the reason is not that many orchestrate a kitchen tour de force
(some do), but rather Boulud gives us the whole dish, including
side dishes and garnishes. This is a fine idea: If you wish, you
can recreate the whole experience of a meal; if you are not that
ambitious, you can simply cull the main part from the description.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Veal Gremolata with Kale Polenta is an inspired
combination, but either the veal tournedos with their savory
gremolata topping or the fried polenta cakes could be paired with
other, simpler foods. The three chocolate mousses layered in a
martini glass at the cafe could be served without the additional
chocolate sauce and garnish. For that matter, any one of them would
be delicious by itself.
</P>
<P>
   The chef/author's practical bent will endear him to home cooks.
He has you prepare a simple scallop and tomato gratin in individual
gratin dishes _ unless you just want to put the whole dish for six
into one pie plate. He details many classic techniques, but also
makes frequent use of labor-saving devices like the blender and
food processor. And he writes that Clams Casino are a great party
starter, because who could be standoffish when everybody is sitting
there licking their fingers?
</P>
<P>
   Boulud comes across as a man who harmoniously blends his French
past and his American present. Take Sea Scallops on Crushed
Potatoes, Sauce Charcuti &LR; e &LR; re: The scallops are an American
standby, as are the potatoes, baked, their flesh coarsely crushed
with lots of butter, shallots and parsley. But he finishes the dish
with sauce  &LR; charcutiere &LR; , a traditional French sauce of wine,
vinegar, ham and cornichons usually accompanying pork. The
juxtaposition of the sweetness of the seafood and the savory
acidity of the sauce is superb. We can barely wait for spring to
try the Chilled Spring Pea Soup made with English sweet, sugar snap
and snow peas, fava beans and leeks and onions, highlighted with
bacon and cream. But we celebrated autumn with a marvelous chicken
dish with pearl onions, apples and quince that's virtually a
one-dish meal.
</P>
<P>
   For a thoroughly practical finale, Boulud and co-author Dorie
Greenspan include a glossary of terms, ingredients and techniques,
a source list, a guide to kitchen tools and a handful of base
recipes _ stocks, vinaigrette, a tomato confit of many uses and the
recipes for several pastry crusts, including an aptly named P &LR; a &LR; te
Sublime that yields three crusts. No freezer should be without one.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Caf &LR; e &LR;  Boulud Cookbook; French-American Recipes for the &LR; 
 &LR; Home Cook,'' by Daniel Boulud and Dorie Greenspan, with color &LR; 
 &LR; photographs by Gentl &AMP; Hyers (Scribner; 400 pages; hardcover, &LR; 
 &LR; $35). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HONEY-GLAZED CHICKEN WITH QUINCES &AMP; APPLES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 1 tablespoon cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 large quince, peeled, halved, cored, cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 (31/2-pound) chicken, cut into 8 pieces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces pearl onions, peeled and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 Granny Smith apple, peeled, cored and cut into 1-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsalted chicken stock, store-bought low-sodium broth,
or water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring 2 quarts of salted water to a boil in a medium pot. Add 1
tablespoon of the vinegar and the quince and boil gently for 10
minutes. Drain the quince well and set aside to cool; pat dry
between paper towels if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Center a rack in the oven and preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large oven-proof saute pan or skillet over
high heat. Season the chicken with salt and pepper and add the
pieces to the pan, skin side down. Brown the chicken for 5 to 7
minutes, then turn the pieces over and brown the other side for 5
minutes. Transfer the chicken to a plate and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   You need about 2 tablespoons oil for the next step, so pour off
any excess from the pan. Lower the heat to medium and add the
onions, sugar, cinnamon and rosemary to the pan. Season with salt
and pepper and, turning often, brown the onions evenly, 8 to 10
minutes. Return the chicken to the pan along with the quince, apple
and honey. Turn to coat the ingredients with the honey, then cook
for another 8 to 10 minutes to lightly caramelize everything. Add
the remaining 1/2 cup vinegar, stirring and scraping up any bits
that may have stuck to the bottom of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Slide the pan into the oven and roast the chicken for 10
minutes. Transfer the pan to the stove-top again, turn the heat to
medium and add the chicken stock or water, bringing it just to the
boil. Stir to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Discard the cinnamon and rosemary and spoon the chicken, fruit
and sauce directly from the pan at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 465 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 18 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 28 g fat (7 g saturated), 134 mg cholesterol, 132
mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
