<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1792 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-TASTE-BIRD-SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-BIRD-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.   TASTER'S CHOICE: Upbringing Makes Diestel Winning Bird  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Now that you know the best way to cook a turkey
(see related story), which brand of turkey should you start out
with to get the best result? Or does the brand make no difference
at all?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people swear by fresh turkeys; others insist that frozen
turkeys preserve the bird's flavor at its peak. Then there's the
question of free-range.
</P>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted nine brands of turkey, including frozen,
fresh and free-range, ranging in price from 79 cents per pound to
$2.79 per pound.
</P>
<P>
   All weighed between 11 and 15 pounds. They were cooked
simultaneously at the California Culinary Academy in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   When the turkeys came out of the oven, they all looked the same.
Each sported crispy looking, nicely browned skin. But flavor was
another story.
</P>
<P>
   The turkeys were allowed to rest for 15 to 20 minutes before
being carved. Then each panelist was given dark meat and center
cuts of breast meat _ the breast was removed from the bone after
roasting and cut crosswise into slices so each panelist received
meat close to the skin as well as close to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the fresh turkeys fared much better than the frozen
birds. Only one of the frozen turkeys scored above 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe that more exercise for turkeys means more
flavor may be right: three of the top four spots went to free-range
turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture allows turkeys to be labeled
and marketed as free-range if they are allowed to roam outside
(still within a confined area). That doesn't mean that the birds
actually  &LR; do &LR;  walk around, but they must be given the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it may be something other than just the
free-range label that makes a great turkey. What the free-range
distinction does  &LR; not &LR;  define is how much space the birds have in
which to roam, what they eat, whether they have been given
antibiotics or how they have been slaughtered and processed.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Diestel of Diestel Turkey Ranch in Sonora says two other
components make a big difference in the flavor of turkeys: the feed
and how old turkeys are when they're slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give the turkey time to grow up naturally,'' she says. They
refer to it as ``real flavor from real time.''
</P>
<P>
   Diestel turkeys are raised on vegetarian feed, made up primarily
of corn, and soybeans, with no added fat. The birds are 20 to 24
weeks when they're slaughtered, as opposed to most commercially
raised turkeys which are 10 to 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the panel, what Diestel is doing makes a big
difference. &UR; Diestel Turkey Ranch &LR;  ($1.59-$2.79 per pound at many
supermarkets) outscored its closest competitors by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   All of the panelists commented on Diestel's exceptional
moistness _ two pointed out that it was even juicy when cold. Two
panelists also commented that the flavor was exceptional. Another
described it as ``everything a turkey should be.'' All would buy
it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Willie Bird  &LR; ($1.89-$2.09 per pound at many supermarkets) _
another fresh, free-range turkey _ took second place. Three
panelists enjoyed the turkey flavor; one described it as a ``clean
turkey flavor.'' Two others liked it less, finding it lower in
flavor than Diestel and not as moist. Three would buy it, one might
buy it, one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Foster Farms &LR;  ($1.39 per pound at Cala) came in third, ranked
just below Willie Bird (which is as much as 70 cents more per
pound). Three tasters found this fresh turkey particularly moist
and liked the flavor. However, one dissenter described it as
virtually flavorless. Three would buy it, one might buy it, and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Norbest &LR;  (89 cents-$1.89 per pound at some
supermarkets), which is free-range but frozen. One panelist thought
the meat was moist and dense although somewhat tough. Another said
gravy might moisten it nicely. Three liked the flavor, but all
noted it was not as flavorful as Diestel and Willie Bird. Two would
buy it, one might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zacky Farms &LR;  ($1.29-$1.59 per pound at many supermarkets) came
in fifth. Panelists found this fresh turkey (not free-range) to be
dry. One panelist also described the texture as ``powdery.'' But
two tasters found it just as full-flavored as the top-scoring
brands. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Butterball &LR;  ($1.29 per pound at some supermarkets) came in
sixth. Three panelists described this frozen (not free-range)
self-basting turkey stringy. One liked the flavor and juiciness,
but another described the meat as ``firm and tough.'' One would buy
it, two might buy it and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Empire, Safeway Select and The
Californian, but these turkeys were not ranked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner of La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur
and Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
