u f BC-IUE-COX     11-16 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IUE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delphi employees will not get negotiated raise
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Workers at one of three unprofitable Delphi
Automotive Systems plants will not receive proposed salary
increases negotiated by their national labor union, but employees
represented by a different union are getting pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   A Delphi spokesman and officials of the United Auto Workers of
America and the International Union of Electronic Workers sought to
minimize the difference, saying the plants face different
competitive issues and so have different ``fix-it'' agreements with
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi spokesman Jim Hagedon and Gary Hill, president of the UAW
Local 696, confirmed that the 2,600 Delphi employees at brake
plants on Wisconsin and Needmore roads will receive the 3 percent
annual salary increases the UAW negotiated for members in
September's four-year contract agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2,200 workers at Delphi's Kettering, Ohio, suspension
plant will not receive the 3 percent annual increases negotiated as
part of the tentative four-year contract agreement announced Monday
by the IUE.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to do what they had to do to keep the plants open,''
said Denny Thomas, secretary/treasurer of the IUE District Council
7.
</P>
<P>
   Delphi spokesman Peter Rowe said the company does not make
public the average worker's salary, nor does it break out wages by
union representation. But the average Delphi employee earns $43.71
an hour in wages and benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   IUE negotiators were successful in getting Delphi to add one
year to the existing three-year ``no close'' pledge for the
Kettering plant and to give those employees the $1,350 signing
bonus negotiated for other IUE members.
</P>
<P>
   The Kettering plant and those on Wisconsin and Needmore roads
are working under local contracts with ``fix-it'' plans designed to
save them from sale or closure. The company has said the three are
on target for becoming profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Union and company officials have refused to divulge details
those agreements, but Hagedon said the ``fix-it'' plans recognize
the plants produce two different products and need different
agreements to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The IUE tentative four-year contract announced Monday also
covers General Motors workers. Ratification is expected to be
completed by Nov. 23. It covers 20,000 workers nationwide and 9,600
locally. In addition to the pay raise and bonus, the pact offers
better job security provisions and improves pensions and the
cost-of-living formula.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The 450 workers at the GM Moraine engine plant scheduled to be
replaced by the new Isuzu-GM engine plant will be covered under the
new pact until their union negotiates a new deal, said Stephen
Trent, IUE Local 801 shop chairman at the engine plant.
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu is the majority owner in the new engine plant, known as
DMAX, but a bargaining agreement reached in 1998 will continue to
protect workers' GM pensions and retain retirement rules and some
other benefits. He said workers won't move off the GM payroll until
the second quarter of 2000, so an agreement needs to be in place by
then.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would rather remain a GM employee, but the union
needed to work with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ultimately better than no jobs,'' said Trent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike area Delphi and GM plants that are covered by both
national and local contracts with the companies, Local 801 is
likely to negotiate a single master agreement for the DMAX plant,
Trent said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: lynn_hulseycoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
