<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-LOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DEADLINE PASSES, FEW OVERDUE BANK LOANS IN PAKISTAN REPAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ A deadline for some of the most wealthy
deadbeats here expired on Tuesday, with only a pittance in overdue
bank loans repaid and leaving the nation to wonder whether its new
military government will _ as promised _ begin putting a who's who
of the high and mighty behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   By early Wednesday morning, just after the midnight time limit,
no announcements of arrests had been made. ``Details are still
being worked out,'' said a top official who insisted on anonymity.
``Dozens of willful defaulters will go to jail. But remember, our
object is not to fill the prisons or close down businesses, but to
recover money.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, the effort has so far been a failure. According to
bankers, 1 percent of the $4.2 billion in bad loans has been
collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the defaulters do their defaulting with finesse,'' the
area manager here in Islamabad for Emirates Bank International,
Akbar Alam, said. ``They don't keep the money in their own name,
and many don't even keep it in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after seizing control in a bloodless coup on Oct. 12, Gen.
Pervez Musharraf declared war on high-level corruption. Leading his
list of evildoers were the well-connected wealthy who are accused
of having borrowed money that they had no intention of repaying.
The general, trying fist-pounding populism, gave them a month to
make good on their debts.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, lists of prominent debtors have been appearing
in newspapers. At the top was a family that owed $66.8 million.
Close behind was the family of the ousted prime minister, Nawaz
Sharif, whose arrears were placed at $42.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have been taking out advertisements that announce, ``The
last day for settlement'' is drawing near. Working hours were
extended to have loan officers available for borrowers who were
gripped with fear or stricken with conscience.
</P>
<P>
   But as the deadline approached, the pressure seemed to diminish
rather than grow. The new government itself began to hedge.
</P>
<P>
   Shaukat Aziz, who gave up a job as a Citibank vice president to
be finance minister, declared on Nov. 5, ``The cancer of corruption
has reached a point where it is now eating away at the vitals of
our societal body.''
</P>
<P>
   But by last weekend he was saying that ``only a small group''
had willfully deceived the banks and that the law had to proceed
with ``equity, justice and reasonableness.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, the new government realized that
although there was abundant financial skulduggery, the greater
amount of the debt stemmed from genuinely honest-to-goodness
failures. What is more, there was a worry that the net effects of
the crackdown would make businessmen heed the wisdom of
Shakespeare, neither a borrower nor lender be, a conservative
financial strategy that does not make for a very dynamic economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this hue and cry is not good for Pakistan,'' said M.
Masood Ahmed, who is in charge of loan recovery for the United Bank
in Islamabad. ``The government is destroying the culture of
banking, with every Tom, Dick and Harry getting their names
published as defaulters. Foreign investors are not going to be
interested in Pakistan now.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation itself is at the cliff's edge of bankruptcy, owing
$32 billion to international creditors. About 57 percent of all
revenues, Aziz said, goes toward servicing the debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
