<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-BESTTURKEY-SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 2697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTTURKEY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods.  The Turkey Bunch: Here's the story, of a flock of turkeys  
 That were cooked up almost 30 different ways...  
   
 By Lynne Bennett  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Thanksgiving means tempting turkeys with brown
crispy skin, luscious rich dark meat and succulent white meat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But talk to a dozen people and you'll get a dozen opinions of
how to roast the perfect bird _ low, high or variable heat; basted,
brined or stuffed; draped with butter-soaked cheesecloth, breast
down then up or up then down; roasted in a bag; deep-fried, grilled
or smoked. And we won't even go into how the Pilgrims might have
cooked their turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle Food staff set out to determine the best way to
oven-roast a holiday turkey. We also delved into deep-frying,
smoking and grilling methods.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight turkeys and a dozen tryptophan-laced days later, we
have a winner that takes less time to cook than most standard
recipes and will make a perfect centerpiece to your Thanksgiving
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In testing the methods, we looked for the best overall result,
best appearance, best skin, best taste and best texture. To keep
the test as reliable as possible, we used the same brand and size
of turkeys throughout _ Safeway Manor House frozen turkeys,
weighing an average of 12 pounds _ and roasted them straight from
the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Our first step was determining what internal temperature was
best for ``doneness.'' We roasted several turkeys at 325 degrees
since most recipes call for that oven temperature. After tasting
birds cooked to an internal thigh temperature of 180 degrees
(turkey-jerky), 170 degrees (acceptable but better with gravy), 160
degrees (juicy white meat but softer, dark meat that was pinkish
near the thigh bone), we decided 165 degrees produced the best
overall white and dark meat. The juices ran clear and there were no
traces of pink near the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Most sources recommend cooking poultry to an internal thigh
temperature of 180-185 degrees, but U.S. Department of Agriculture
standards say 160-165 degrees will kill contaminants, including
salmonella. The temperature also continues to rise several degrees
when the turkey is allowed to rest the recommended 20-30 minutes
before carving. (A good way to double-check is that the meat should
not be pink and the juices should run clear.)
</P>
<P>
   The thigh usually takes longer to cook than the breast, as our
tests confirmed, so temperatures of the breast are generally higher
than the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Once we found 165 degrees as the best internal temperature, we
looked at which roasting temperature would be the best way to get
there. We roasted turkeys at 350, 375 and 400 degrees, and took
each bird out of the oven when their thighs reached 165 degrees.
Although all were acceptable, one staffer summed up comments on the
400 degree bird: ``By far the best turkey (so far)! Loved the dark,
white and skin.'' A 12-pound bird will take 13/4 to 2 hours to
cook.
</P>
<P>
   The 400-degree oven temperature is fine on a turkey up to 16
pounds (which will take about 21/2 hours to cook). Larger turkeys
should be roasted at a lower temperature (see Big Bird section
below).
</P>
<P>
   The next breakthrough was discovering that varying the oven
temperatures from high to low or low to high or starting the bird
breast-side down didn't make the difference, and moister, juicier
white meat came at the expense of an evenly brown, crisp skin.
</P>
<P>
   Our next step was to maintain the 400 degrees oven temperature,
leave the turkey breast-side up the entire time, and try various
basting solutions to improve the bird.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Basting is Better &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Basting strictly with butter resulted in a wonderful, buttery,
evenly browned and crispy skin. Basting another turkey (No. 15)
with 1/2 cup stock to start and pan drippings after the foil was
removed was even better _ it helped deglaze the roasting pan and
gave this turkey great skin and a richer, complex flavor. This
became our new Best Way (and was repeated as No. 17).
</P>
<P>
   Then we tried stuffing the turkey and cooking it the same way.
But roasting it at 400 degrees until the thigh reached 165 degrees
turned the turkey into toast before the stuffing got to the
recommended safe temperature. For a stuffed turkey, it's best to go
with the standard lower roasting temperatures recommended in the
chart elsewhere in this section.
</P>
<P>
   Our last step to try improve our Best Way unstuffed bird was to
brine it before roasting. We eliminated salt from the basic
seasoning since the salty brine had already penetrated the meat.
This was a turbo-charged turkey that had Food department staffers
and visitors from other departments waxing poetic poultry prose and
planning their Thanksgiving turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Best Way to prepare a smaller turkey is to brine it before
cooking _ turkey No. 21. Brine it according to the accompanying
recipe for 12 to 24 hours, then rinse and dry it well. Spread 2
tablespoons of softened butter over the skin and sprinkle with 11/2
teaspoons of ground black pepper over the skin and in the cavity.
Tuck the wing tips under, tie the legs together, and place the
turkey breast up on a V-shaped roasting rack in a shallow roasting
pan. Cover the breast tightly with aluminum foil and place in an
oven preheated to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the turkey 50-60 minutes, then remove the foil and
immediately baste with 1/2 cup of turkey stock. The stock should
help deglaze the roasting pan and provide additional pan drippings.
Leave the foil off and baste with pan drippings every 20-30 minutes
until the internal thigh temperature reaches 165 degrees; a 12- to
16-pound turkey will cook in about 2-23/4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Start checking the internal temperature after about 11/2 hours
of roasting time. If the legs begin to get too brown, cover loosely
with foil. Let the turkey rest at least 20 minutes before carving.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AN APPEALING ALTERNATIVE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you do not want to brine, roasting the turkey according to
the No. 17 method is the way to go. Sprinkle it with a mixture of
41/2 teaspoons of kosher salt and 11/2 teaspoons of ground black
pepper over the skin and in the cavity before roasting. Roasting
time for a 12- to 16-pound turkey is about 13/4-21/4 hours; a
16-pound turkey will take about 2-23/4 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE BIG BIRD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Not every large family wants to cook two 12-pound turkeys so we
wanted to translate this Best Way method to a bigger bird. A
22-pound turkey that was cooked at 350 degrees with the breast
tightly covered with foil for the first half of cooking and then
basted with stock and pan drippings was wonderful. Remember to
cover the legs loosely with foil if they begin to get too brown.
Total roasting time is about 31/2 hours. Brining would have made it
even better.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; OTHER ALTERNATIVES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   We also tried deep-frying, grilling and smoking turkeys. Any of
these would free up the oven for cooking the rest of the holiday
meal, but they do require additional equipment and probably an
extra set of hands or two to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Many people swear by the deep-frying method,  &LR; the &LR;  way to cook
turkey in Louisiana and other parts of the South (for more details
on deep-frying, see the story elsewhere in this section). A
deep-fried turkey with dry rub on the skin, under the breast skin
and in the cavity was quickly dubbed ``Chernobyl Bird'' for its
overly dark, inedible skin. However, the firm-textured meat was
surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   The deep-fried turkey that was first injected with a
butter-garlic-herb marinade and allowed to marinate for 12 hours
was better. The meat remained moist and juicy even though several
tasters described at as ``too rich'' and the marinade flavor too
predominant. The skin of this deep-fried turkey (No. 25) was
wonderfully brown and crisp without any greasy reminders of
deep-fried food.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Food staff said they preferred the traditional
turkey and would not go to the extra trouble and (equipment)
expense for a deep-fried fowl _ not to mention having to deal with
several gallons of very hot oil.
</P>
<P>
   Turkeys No. 26 and 27 were both brined before being grilled and
smoked. While the grilled turkey was fine, the one smoked over
indirect heat with soaked applewood chips added to the briquettes
was the hands-down winner. The skin was not as nice as the grilled
bird, but the flavorful, moist meat and mild smokiness more than
compensated. It took about 21/4-3 hours to cook.
</P>
<P>
   And even after tasting 28 turkeys most testers confided that
they were  &LR; not &LR;  tired of turkey, and were even looking forward to
preparing their own Thanksgiving turkey _ according to our Best Way
for cooking it to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Begin optional trim. &QL; 
 &QL; 
For those who are not yet on turkey-information overload, here are
some additional insights learned during our turkey adventures:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Basting &LR; . Use the top portion of the pan drippings to baste.
It contains a larger proportion of fat and oil, which helps brown,
moisten and flavor the skin. Avoid the solid specks at the bottom
of the pan. These can darken more than the skin and even burn.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Brining &LR; . Variations on brine may be made by varying the
spices and herbs. If you don't want to brine the bird in your
refrigerator, use an ice chest. Place the turkey and brine into a
double-layer of garbage bags. Smoosh out all the air pockets, close
the bags up and pack in the chest with ice. The bird will happily _
and safely _ brine away. All that extra space freed up in the
refrigerator will make the cook happy, too.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Deep-Frying &LR; . Because of the mess and the danger of a grease
fire, deep-frying should be done outdoors. Another caveat: This
method requires an investment in special equipment.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need a high-BTU (over 100,000) propane burner with jet
flame, which will keep 4 to 5 gallons of cooking oil at 360
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Other items include: an aluminum pot (about 28 quarts) large
enough to hold the turkey and oil, a long-stem (12-inch)
deep-frying thermometer, a fire extinguisher and metal wire (we
used 16-gauge galvanized) to raise and lower the bird in the oil.
We also purchased an injector for the marinade and a vertical
poultry roaster to help with handling and draining the bird.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller birds are easiest to deep-fry. We fried our 11-pound
turkeys 3 minutes per pound.
</P>
<P>
   Check these resources to find equipment, ingredients,
instructions and advice on deep-fried turkeys:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cajun Shoppe, P.O. Box 168, Lake Charles, LA 70602; (800)
434-2809. Web site:  &LR; www.cajunshoppe.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Cresco Restaurant Equipment and Supply, 1750 Alameda St., San
Francisco; (415) 255-9955 or (800) 265-9955. Web site:
 &LR; www.restaurantequipment.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Doc Miller's Original Deep Fried Turkey Hook, c/o Iowa
Wholesale Supply Co., 14 South Second Ave., Marshalltown, IA 50158;
(800) 383-4555; Web site:  &LR; www.barbecuen.com/docmiller/ &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Tavolo. Web site: &LR;  www.tavolo.com/wares &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Defrosting.  &LR; Don't wait until the last minute to defrost a
fully frozen turkey. Our hard-as-rock, 12-pound birds took longer
than package instructions indicated, both when defrosting in the
refrigerator and in cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Turkeys cook more evenly when fully defrosted, so take the extra
time and don't try the oven-defrosting method. On two earlier
attempts, we tried putting a turkey that was extra cold into the
oven. The first bird had to cook too long to reach 165 degrees,
which resulted in drier meat. The other bird, when carved, revealed
some residual pinkness at the thigh bone.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Equipment.  &LR; We used a V-shaped nonstick rack in a standard
18-inch oval enameled roasting pan. Our 12-pound turkey just fit
without hanging over the sides.
</P>
<P>
   A rectangular roasting pan would work well, too, but whatever
size pan you use, most of the turkey should be above the sides of
the pan to assure even cooking and browning.
</P>
<P>
   A big help in all the testing were the digital thermometers (see
What's New) with probes and the magnetic oven thermometers that
stuck to the inside wall of the oven, helping ensure the oven heat
matched the temperature selected on the control.
</P>
<P>
   Another must was the standard plastic bulb-baster for the
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The Seasoning.  &LR; We kept the basic seasonsing simple: Two
tablespoons of softened unsalted butter rubbed on the skin,
followed by 41/2 teaspoons salt mixed with 11/2 teaspoons ground
black pepper (a 3 to 1 ratio).
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is more salt than is called for in many
recipes, we wanted to have a flavorful skin and great pan
drippings. The gravies made with the pan drippings did not require
any additional seasoning. The amount of salt may be reduced, if
desired. Adding celery, onions, fresh herbs, etc. to the cavity,
would provide moisture and flavor, especially to the pan drippings.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Taking the Temperature &LR; . It does take practice to hit the
spot in the thigh just right the first time. Aim for the fleshiest
part, just below the leg-thigh joint, and deep enough to probe the
middle of the thigh. Or, insert the thermometer into the thigh from
the breast. Whichever way you use, stay away from the bone, which
carries and holds the heat faster than the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, test both thighs to make sure the turkey has cooked
evenly. Allow several seconds for the thermometer to fully
register. Rotating the pan while cooking the turkey will help it
cook evenly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, you may want to calibrate your thermometer so you
are sure it is reading the temperature accurately. Place it in an
ice slush that is half ice, half cold water and deep enough to
cover about 2 inches of the thermometer. Temperature measurement
occurs where the ``dimple'' is on the stem. Since water freezes at
32 degrees, any difference in the actual thermometer reading should
be taken into account when taking the temperature of your turkey.
Alternately, an instant-read thermometer can be adjusted by turning
the small calibration nut at the back of the dial.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GRAVY FROM BRINED PAN DRIPPINGS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Making gravy from the pan-drippings of brined and roasted turkey
takes extra care because the salty brine carries over into the
drippings. The heat from oven roasting also reduces the pan
drippings, increasing the saltiness even more.
</P>
<P>
   To successfully make gravy from a brined bird, strain the pan
drippings and defat them by putting the drippings in the freezer
after they have cooled. The fat will rise to the top and can be
lifted off.
</P>
<P>
   To thicken the gravy, make a roux with equal amounts of unsalted
butter and flour. Cook it over medium heat, stirring occasionally,
until the roux begins to look ``grainy,'' about 3-4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Put turkey stock in a separate pan, and heat. Add a bit of roux
to the warm stock while whisking. Allow to come to a simmer to
thicken. Add more roux, whisking, until the gravy comes to desired
thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Taste the defatted pan drippings to determine the saltiness.
Then add a tablespoon at a time to the gravy to balance the
seasonings. Add herbs, wine or pepper to taste, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHEZ PANISSE'S BRINE FOR TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 gallons cold water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves, torn into pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh thyme, or 4 tablespoons dried
</P>
<P>
   1 whole head of garlic, cloves separated and peeled
</P>
<P>
   5 whole allspice berries, crushed
</P>
<P>
   4 juniper berries, smashed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the water in a large pot that can easily hold the liquid
and the turkey you intend to brine. Add all ingredients and stir
for a minute or two until the sugar and salt dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   Put your turkey into the brine and refrigerate for 24 hours. If
the turkey floats to the top, use a plate or other weight to keep
it completely submerged in the brine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  The recipe may be halved or doubled; the important thing
is to have enough brine to completely cover the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Before roasting, remove the bird from the brine and drain well.
Pat dry. Follow The Best Way instructions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
