<SLUG> BC-TOGETHER-THEATER-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXING A COCKTAIL OF DISCONNECTED PARTYGOERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Bob Morris' most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
playwright Christopher Durang.  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was late last month, a week before the first
preview of the Broadway revue ``Putting It Together,'' a collection
of Stephen Sondheim songs, and Carol Burnett was still figuring out
how to tug Ruthie Henshall's earrings off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to pull your hair,'' said Ms. Burnett, who opens
in the show Sunday night with Ms. Henshall at the Ethel Barrymore
Theater. ``But if I pull your earlobes off, that's OK, I guess,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henshall, the young musical-comedy star who came over from
London last summer to play Velma Kelly in the musical ``Chicago,''
laughed. Ms. Burnett winked. Then the two actresses went back to
working out Bob Avian's on-the-verge-of-violence blocking for
``There's Always a Woman,'' a dueling-dames tour de force from the
musical ``Anyone Can Whistle.''
</P>
<P>
   On the attack in three-quarter time, they danced around while
flashing fake smiles at each other and enunciating invective
complex enough (especially when combined with the composer's
elaborate syncopation) to keep stopping them in their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a woman, the counterfeit check,'' they sang in
counterpoint, ``the snake in the woodpile, the pain in the neck.''
Suddenly they came to a halt. ``This is so tricky,'' Ms. Burnett
confided to Eric D. Schaeffer, the director who worked with her on
the original production produced by Cameron Mackintosh at the Mark
Taper Forum in Los Angeles last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you have to learn each line phonetically,'' added
Ms. Henshall. The number is just one of many tongue-twisting songs
in an evening set at an uptown dinner party filled with tension,
passion, separation and, ultimately, redemption.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of two hours, the host couple, played by Ms.
Burnett and George Hearn, watch their faltering marriage unravel
and realign itself, as the older man goes after the younger woman
(Ms. Henshall), who arrives on the arm of John Barrowman, while
Bronson Pinchot portrays the narrator.
</P>
<P>
   Putting across the psychological tinderbox-tone of this scenario
and the convoluted Sondheim lyrics (Ms. Burnett also tackles the
acid-tinged ``Ladies Who Lunch'' and the famously frenetic ``Not
Getting Married Today'' from ``Company'') requires precision,
perspicacity and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   After their rehearsal, Ms. Henshall and Ms. Burnett (whose role
will be played by Kathie Lee Gifford on Tuesdays) took a break to
breathe, drink bottled water and talk in prose.
</P>
<P>
   BOB MORRIS. Art isn't easy, is it?
</P>
<P>
   CAROL BURNETT. It's not a walk in the park. But Sondheim never
is. The music is hard to learn and attention must be paid to his
lyrics. He's always surprising you.
</P>
<P>
   RUTHIE HENSHALL. Carol, I'm just amazed. How do you deal with
``Not Getting Married Today''?
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. I sing it slower than most. I want audiences to
understand the words. If you sing too fast, they can't.
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. It sounds pretty fast to me.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. When Julie Andrews did this show in 1993, she told me
she rehearsed the number with a pencil in her mouth. I told her I'd
try it. I never did. Maybe I should call her and ask what she
meant. I mean, where would you put the pencil? Under your nose?
Between your teeth?
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS. Sondheim tends to depict parties as arenas for social
warfare. And there is a good deal of forced civility in this show.
Can you relate to that off the stage?
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. I'm not a party person, if that's what you mean. And
as I get older I get worse at surface talk. It's a problem because
so much networking in New York is done at parties, at least that's
what I'm told. If that's really so, I'm going to be out of work
soon.
</P>
<P>
   MORRIS. Clive Barnes once described Sondheim's characters as
people you'd go out of your way to avoid at a cocktail party. Is it
hard playing such unhappy archetypes?
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. After you strip away the layers to these characters,
you realize they're as decent as the rest of us, and they're all
looking for the same things we are _ love and happiness.
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. John and I play this couple at the beginning stages of
a relationship, when it's romantic and passionate, and you don't
have to work hard at it at all.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. That never lasts, does it?
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. No, it doesn't. When you really love somebody, you
have to work at the bumps you come up against.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. You mean mountains.
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. My character finds it hard watching an older couple
and seeing what a marriage can become. George sings this
heartbreaking ``Follies'' song, ``The Road You Didn't Take,'' which
is about the regret you have later in life. It's very touching. In
a show like this, you really connect to your emotions.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. This is what Sondheim's about _ relationships and
getting through life. But it's not all darkness, either. There are
laughs, too. And opportunities to be bitchy in a very funny kind of
way. You can really get your feelings out in this show.
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. It's marvelous to be an actress and get paid to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   BURNETT. In ``Could I Leave You?'' I get to do a lot of
screaming. It feels like doing the Tarzan yell on my old television
show. I feel totally purged when I walk off the stage, so when I
get home I don't feel like kicking the cat. Not that I'd ever
actually kick my cat.
</P>
<P>
   HENSHALL. Of course not, Carol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
