<HEADLINE>
GROWTH OF WORLD ECONOMY TO EXCEED EXPECTATIONS, REPORT PREDICTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to delete photo note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The world economy is growing at an unexpectedly fast
pace because of surprisingly strong expansion in Japan and South
Korea, a more modest upturn in Europe and economic resilience in
the United States, an organization of the world's richest nations
said Tuesday in a semiannual appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development, which helps coordinate policy among the affluent
nations, said it expected the global growth rate to reach 3.5
percent next year. Its assessment in May had forecast growth in
2000 of 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook for world and OECD-wide output growth has improved
substantially over the past few months,'' the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   Its report suggested that Japan's economic recovery in
particular had been more vigorous than anticipated. The
organization's earlier assessment projected that Japan would
continue to struggle next year against recession, its worst since
the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``These changes reflect mainly unexpected near-term momentum in
the United States economy, a stronger and more rapid resumption of
growth in Japan and, particularly, South Korea, as well as a
slightly better outlook for the European Union,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, it said, is showing signs of expansion and in 2000 and
2001 is expected to grow 2.8 percent in the 11-nation euro currency
zone. In its last report, the OECD predicted euro zone growth next
year of 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggested that European countries would make
progress against high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   It forecast 3.1 percent growth for the United States next year,
after predicting last spring that the American economy faced a
natural slowdown and 2 percent growth after eight years of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   And it said that Japan, the world's second-largest economy, had
emerged from recession faster than expected, but that in the long
term it faced risks from the continued appreciation of the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese currency's strength this year has already hurt
profit at many big-name corporations that derive much of their
business from exports, like Sony, Toyota and Hitachi. The yen's
rise partly reflects the increased prospect of higher interest
rates in Japan because of the heavy borrowing that the government
must undertake to stimulate growth through spending.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Japanese government announced a new package of
economic stimulants worth about $171 billion, almost twice the
amount that had been expected a few weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-member OECD, founded in 1960, was originally made up of
nations in Europe and North America. It expanded to include Japan,
Australia, New Zealand and Finland. More recently, Mexico, the
Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland and South Korea have joined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
