<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-Texas to study state services
 &HT;    By Erik Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The chore of waiting in line to renew a driver's
license or motor vehicle registration could be a thing of the past
in Texas, courtesy of a plan introduced by Comptroller Carole
Keeton Rylander Tuesday that would integrate government commerce
with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's ultimate goal is to offer recommendations that would
eliminate obstacles and lower costs for services the state
provides. For Texans, it would mean being able to perform many
government-related transactions, including license renewal, sales
tax payments and permit applications, over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander, who is serving her first year as comptroller, said the
project evolved out of work performed in her office. ``It really
hit home with my staff when they showed me how much paper we were
using for some taxpayers to report that they owed no taxes,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander unveiled e-Texas, a commission that will oversee 14
separate task forces that will explore ways to streamline state
government.
</P>
<P>
   Project officials said the initiative is overdue and would allow
the state to keep up with advancing technology. ``Government by its
very nature doesn't have competitive pressures (like) other
businesses competing to tell you when to change,'' said Wendy
Gramm, co-chairman of the e-Texas commission and wife of U.S. Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Officials could not put a specific price tag on the venture or
identify how much money could be saved, but Rylander said the
funding would come from a mixture of public and private funds. The
comptroller's office has a $9 million research budget.
</P>
<P>
   The new project will be considered a joint effort with the Texas
Performance Review, one of the hallmarks of the tenure of former
Comptrollers John Sharp and Bob Bullock. Although most functions of
the new commission will be relegated to offering suggestions in the
next legislative session, Rylander said other proposals, such as
the license-renewal plan, could be implemented much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task force will get busy on that immediately,'' she said.
``That's something that we have the authority to do; we just need
to use the technology to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is similar to one Rylander had proposed in the
Citizen's Waste Fighting Commission while on the campaign trail
last year. E-Texas' 14 committees will review specific functions of
Texas government and offer suggestions for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Rylander created a task force to investigate
public schools _ a move that, as the state's chief tax officer,
went beyond the scope of any comptroller before her.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander disagreed with speculation that e-Texas' oversight
committees would overstep her boundaries as comptroller, asserting
that the project is one built out of necessity and not a
re-creation of the Texas Performance Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as overlap or duplication,'' Rylander said. ``I
see it clearly as my responsibility and my authority to make sure
dollars are being used effectively and efficiently in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Rodriguez writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: erodriguez(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
