<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-MARKETPLACE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: EXPLAINING THE INVESTOR EUPHORIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FED-RATES) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Interest rates may rise, the Federal Reserve Board
may fret, but there's just no keeping a good bull market down.
</P>
<P>
   Voicing concerns that the economy is too darn hot and employment
is way too tight, the Federal Reserve Board on Tuesday raised
short-term interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point. Stock
investors generally dislike interest rate increases because, in the
broadest sense, they raise the cost of operating a business. Rising
rates also make bonds more attractive than stocks as investments.
</P>
<P>
   So it was not too surprising that the Fed's rate increase
spooked stocks after it was announced. A quick blip upward could
not be sustained, and the Dow Jones industrials fell about 140
points on the news.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, stock traders got their bearings and roared with
approval over the move. The white-hot NASDAQ composite index gained
73.51 points on the day, a 2.28 percent increase. The Dow Jones
industrial average raced ahead 171.58 points, or 1.59 percent. At
the end of the trading day, the Dow stood at 10,932.33, just 3.8
percent below its high reached last August.
</P>
<P>
   The investor euphoria following the Fed's action seemed to be
based on two assumptions. Most compelling was the view that the
Fed's action was the last rate increase for the foreseeable future.
The next meeting of the Fed's Open Market Committee takes place on
Dec. 21, an unlikely occasion for anyone except Ebenezer Scrooge to
raise rates. The meeting after that, in early February, is expected
to feature economic statistics distorted by year 2000 anomalies. As
a result, many economists have concluded that the Fed will not move
again on rates until next spring regardless of what the economic
data say.
</P>
<P>
   Stock investors also liked Tuesday's decision by the Fed to
shift into neutral on any future moves. Before the meeting, the Fed
had assumed a stance that favored tightening.
</P>
<P>
   The increase Tuesday in the federal funds rate, the Fed's third
increase since June, raises the overnight rate charged by banks
lending excess funds to one another. The Fed also raised the rate
at which banks can borrow from the central bank, called the
discount rate, to 5 percent, a quarter-point move. Some banks
responded by raising the prime rate, a benchmark for what they
charge some of their best customers, with others likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But even as stock investors celebrated, bond investors took up
their worry beads. Bond prices fell, pushing up the yield on the
30-year U.S. Treasury bond to 6.06 percent on Tuesday, from 6.024
percent on Monday. Bond investors chose to read the Fed's statement
that accompanied the rate rises as a warning that further rate
increases will follow if the economy does not start to cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see growth slow down to insure that this is in fact
going to be the last tightening move,'' said Stephen Slifer, chief
U.S. economist at Lehman Brothers. Slifer pointed out that recent
hints of a slowdown, flattening retail sales and a decline in the
housing sector had to be echoed in other data for the Fed to relax
on rates. ``If this turns out to be another fakeout and growth
continues to be 4 to 5 percent,'' Slifer said, ``the Fed will be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   In its comments, the Fed gave clues to what economic data it
will be watching most closely in coming weeks to help it decide
where to go on interest rates. A prime cause for alarm is the low
unemployment rate, the central bank said. With unemployment falling
to a 29-year low of 4.1 percent last month, many fear that the
United States is running out of employable workers. Such low
unemployment cannot continue indefinitely without leading to higher
labor costs and rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, overall economic growth is running well ahead of
the rate the Fed would prefer to see. The initial estimate on gross
domestic product growth in the third quarter is an increase of 4.8
percent; economists say this figure may be revised up to 5.5
percent. Either number is far above the Fed's target growth rate of
3 percent or even 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fed's statement made no mention of elevated stock
prices and the ensuing ``wealth effect'' from investors who feel
freer to spend, Greenspan has telegraphed to investors that rising
stock prices have become a factor in his decisions on rates. In a
speech before the Business Council on Oct. 28, Greenspan alluded to
the wealth effect when he remarked upon the ``expanding net worth
of households relative to income.'' If the nation's households are
seeing their net worths rising faster than their incomes, much of
this is driven by stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the strong rally seen in stocks on Tuesday may have
the unintended consequence of increasing the likelihood of future
rate boosts. This is also a risk because a rising stock market
translates very closely to increased retail sales and other
measures of economic strength.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to International Strategy and Investment, an
investment advisory firm, the stock market and Christmas sales are
inextricably linked. Last year, for example, the market was up 17
percent in the fourth quarter from the third quarter, and retail
sales grew at a strong 11 percent rate from the previous quarter.
Conversely, in 1997, the stock market rose 3 percent in the fourth
quarter, and retail sales moved up at exactly the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   Slifer agreed that the stock market acts as a great force on the
economy. ``If the stock boys keep revving it up here and stock
prices go up again,'' he said, ``then budding signs of a slowdown
will disappear and GDP growth will continue.'' Another rate
increase would probably follow.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's focus on the domestic economy in its statement, and
the absence of any mention of the international economic situation,
is also revealing. The message, said William Dudley, chief U.S.
economist at Goldman, Sachs, is that the Fed is far from finished
with raising rates. ``I think it's telling you that they're going
to keep tightening as long as the economy is too strong,'' Dudley
said. ``If the economy keeps going along at this pace, the Fed is
going to have to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley added that the Fed said that its action Tuesday ``should
markedly diminish the risk of inflation going forward.'' But
investors who see a sign of no further rate increases should recall
that the same statement was made the last time the Fed raised
rates, in August.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the stock market seemed to welcome Tuesday's action
by the Fed as its final move for a while, additional economic data
could quickly change the picture. Wednesday's announcement of the
Consumer Price Index for October is expected to show an increase of
.2 percent from October 1998. If the number checks in much higher
than that, all bets are off, traders say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-DEAL-ART-     11-16 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-DEAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-CHINA TRADE TALKS: DRAMA DOWN TO THE LAST HOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CHINA-TRADE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late last Friday evening in Beijing, an angry and
frustrated Charlene Barshefsky declared to the Chinese on other
side of the negotiating table, ``You are wasting my time.'' Then
she pulled out the oldest pressure tactic in a negotiator's bag of
tricks: She demanded to see the country's prime minister, Zhu
Rongji, and declared that the next morning she would head for
airport.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. At 3:10 a.m. Saturday, Barshefsky's team was awakened
by a call inviting her to Zhongnanhai, the walled, lakeside complex
next to the Forbidden City where China's top leaders live and work.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later they were escorted in to see the 71-year old
Zhu, the champion of Chinese economic reform who U.S. intelligence
agencies had concluded was quickly losing power after a failed
meeting on trade in April with President Clinton in Washington. He
volunteered that China's leaders had met until 2 a.m. to decide how
high a price they were willing to pay for entry into the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' said Zhu, according to Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, and other American participants in the week of
high-tension negotiations, ``I am going to tell you what we can do,
and what we can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight hours later _ after two more threats by Barshefsky
to leave town and another critical intervention by Zhu _ the
world's most populous nation and its most powerful nation closed a
deal that leaders of both countries needed, for very different
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   What was at stake for Zhu and for President Jiang Zemin was the
future of their own effort to complete one of the most astounding
economic reform programs in history while preserving the Communist
Party's absolute political control. Only by allowing in foreign
competition, Zhu has long argued, will China's giant, inefficient
industries be whipped into shape and prepared to compete around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, a deal would mean he could leave office claiming to
have taken the biggest single step toward integrating China with
the West _ admitting it to the club of capitalist economies, and
winning its agreement to live under the rule of international law.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky knew what she had to deliver. ``It's the legacy
thing,'' she told friends at a birthday party for her husband in
Washington a few days before she left for Beijing. For the
president, she said, ``there's nothing bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The winding road the two countries took to Monday's
groundbreaking agreement was strewn with obstacles. There were
cultural miscues, furious arguments within the White House, a
divided leadership in Beijing, a bombed Chinese embassy in
Belgrade, and constant political calculations about how the AFL-CIO
and dispirited Chinese steel workers might react.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Clinton paid a price: China backed away from its
April offer to allow American telecommunications companies and
insurance firms to take a 51 percent stake in Chinese companies,
allowing only a noncontrolling stake of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The give and take had all the ingredients of any modern trade
negotiations between great powers: secret phone calls between
presidents, the constant tension between geo-strategy and domestic
politics and an endgame that turned into a weeklong game of
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing it worked,'' said Gene Sperling, Clinton's
national economic adviser, who was against a deal in April, and for
it once his boss made it clear that the April rejection was a huge
mistake. But the hard work may be just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Once China makes it into the World Trade Organization _ months
of work are still ahead _ Sperling and others expect a long, hard
slog as China's domestic interests try to undo on the ground what
negotiators just signed on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strangest aspect of these talks is that China was a
founding member of the very organization it just spent 13 years
negotiating to re-enter.
</P>
<P>
   Though a civil war was under way in China, the Nationalist
government was among the first to ratify the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade in 1948. After the Nationalists fled the mainland
for Taiwan the next year, and Mao Tse-tung created the People's
Republic of China, it was unclear which China inherited the seat.
Taiwan held it for a year, then withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, as Deng Xiaoping began China's rapid march to
a market economy, China's leadership realized that it needed to
re-enter the club. It was a matter of national prestige. But it was
also a hard-headed issue of economic advantage. As long as China
remained outside the treaty, countries were free to place high
tariffs on Chinese-made goods _ or to to block their entry
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   The talks began in July 1986, and a deal seemed within reach
three years later _ until the the student protests in Tiananmen
Square were crushed. Everything froze.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few signs of progress after Clinton's election in
1992, but he was focused on the passage of the North American Free
Trade Agreement, then the Senate battle to ratify a new accord that
created the World Trade Organization, the earlier agreement's
successor, as a truly powerful enforcer of world trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, China's enthusiasm for opening its economy waxed and
waned.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until Clinton and Jiang began exchanging state visits
two years ago that the talks became serious. And then the magnitude
of what China would have to do _ open its telecommunications
market, allow the distribution of American movies, dramatically
lower protections for its car industry, let American insurance
companies sell policies around the country _ seemed more than the
Chinese leadership could bear.
</P>
<P>
   By April, though, Zhu was ready to deal. He came to Washington
determined to seize the moment and cut a deal. He carried with him
some breathtaking proposals: American firms could take up to 51
percent of Chinese telecommunications companies and insurance firms
_ two strategic industries for China. Detroit's automakers could
have full access to China within 5 years, with low tariffs. U.S.
negotiators were astounded.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Bill Clinton was not ready.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was awash in charges that China had stolen nuclear
secrets. Clinton was still recovering from the allegations _ never
proven _ that the Chinese government secretly contributed to
Democratic campaigns. Moreover, Zhu's offer was missing an
agreement that the United States could continue to act unilaterally
if China ``dumped'' steel or other products selling them below cost
to gain a U.S. market share. It was a huge issue for the American
labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   The day Zhu was arriving, Clinton gave a speech warning that
America should fear an economically weak China, not a militarily
strong one. Many took that as a sign that he was ready for a trade
deal. But his advisers were deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky, National Security Adviser Sandy Berger and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright all favored the deal. Sperling, White
House Chief of Staff John Podesta and political aides who focus on
domestic issues were against it. And so was the biggest heavyweight
in the administration, the Treasury secretary at that time, Robert
Rubin. ``We judged it couldn't pass in Congress,'' he said. ``And
that would be a bigger embarrassment for the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   When Zhu arrived, Clinton invited him for a nighttime talk in
the White House family quarters. It was a meeting full of miscues.
Clinton said he could make a deal _ but it would be politically
hard for him, and could be politically difficult for Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better, he said, to announce ``major progress.'' The
prime minister was confused, but did not insist. And so the visit
stumbled on, with Clinton ``only half focusing on it,'' said one
participant.
</P>
<P>
   Then the White House published a 14-page list of Zhu's
``concessions'' _ which many of China's industrial and political
leaders had not seen. They were outraged at what was being given
away. So were American executives, but for different reasons. At a
meeting at the White House the next week, they cheered Barshefsky _
and screamed at Sperling. Clinton had an explosion of his own over
the breakdown. ``I've rarely seen him as angry as he was after Zhu
left town,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Zhu, who by that time was in New York, and asked
him to restart talks. But Zhu said he could not do so until he got
back to Beijing. And as soon as he returned, he was under attack
there.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, the CIA delivered an analysis to the White House
declaring that Zhu had been politically undercut by the failed
trip, and that his political enemies were using the list of trade
concessions to bury his economic reform program. Berger later told
a colleague that the April meeting was ``one of the biggest foreign
policy mistakes of the second term.''
</P>
<P>
   It might have been fixable, but the bomb that blew up the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade in early May also blew up the talks.
The wave of nationalism that followed left China's leaders in no
position to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In late August, Clinton wrote Jiang a letter, hand-delivered by
Sen. Diane Feinstein, D-Calif. He asked to get the talks started
again at an Asian summit meeting in New Zealand. But the meeting
was a dud. ``The president kept saying, `All our negotiators are
here, let's get going,''' recalled one White House official. ``And
Jiang would nod, say something noncommittal, and nothing would
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton kept pushing. On Oct. 16, he called Jiang and said he
would soon send a ``bottom line'' offer and would follow it up _ if
Jiang wanted _ with a visit by Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jiang's response was not very revealing,'' said one silent
participant allowed to listen in to the call. ``But we thought that
there was a serious division in the Chinese leadership, and the
only way to resolve it was to force the issue.'' The hope was that
China would decide it wanted to be a a major player at the opening
of global trade talks in Seattle in late November.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a downside. In April, China was the supplicant,
looking for the deal. Now Clinton looked like he wanted it more
than Beijing did. ``It's never good to look too eager,'' warned
Barshefsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 8, Clinton called again, wondering if Jiang had read the
U.S. offer. He had, Jiang responded, sounding interested but
noncommittal. Barshefsky, he said, should come to Beijing. But
Clinton ended with a caution: ``I don't want to send Charlene to
fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Barshefsky brought political protection with her: Sperling, who
came to assure the Chinese that the once-divided White House now
wanted the deal _ but that there were some political concessions
Clinton could not live without.
</P>
<P>
   Once the talks began, Barshefsky and Sperling realized the
Chinese side was treading water. ``They clearly didn't have
instructions from the top,'' Sperling said. The deal they offered
was far less than what Clinton turned down in April. After three
days, Sperling, taking a prearranged cue from Barshefsky, blew his
top. Soon after that, Barshefsky did her take-me-to-your-leader
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu offered the Americans the right to buy up to 49 percent of
telecommunications firms, and extend protections against Chinese
import surges for 10 years after the agreement takes effect. But he
said there were political limits to what he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Control of information was clearly their sensitive point,''
Sperling said. ``The whole idea of letting foreigners take 51
percent control of the telecommunications network _ Zhu made it
clear he couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He sent the negotiators back to the table. But by Sunday night,
lower-level Chinese officials were clearly fighting a rear-guard
action, raising anew issues that the Americans thought were long
settled. On Sunday night, Barshefsky called Clinton to report that
the talks were ``in a downward cycle'' and that she planned to
leave Monday morning unless there was a sudden break.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, she recalls, said, ``If you can't break the cycle, come
home.'' But clearly he was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, back in the negotiating rooms in the Ministry
of Foreign Trade, things looked worse. Then, Sperling and
Barshefsky were told that Zhu _ who does not make a habit of
visiting drab Chinese ministry buildings _ wanted to see them
upstairs. There, he talked about the political pressures on China.
Barshefsky leaned over and wrote on Sperling's legal pad, ``This is
like a Seinfeld episode.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a few minutes, Zhu made the concessions necessary for
the Americans to claim they got a respectable deal: foreigners
could take up to 50 percent of telecommunications firms, and the
United States could continue invoking its anti-dumping laws against
Chinese imports for up to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved, the two Americans decided to take the deal. But first,
they needed a private place where they could place a call to
Clinton. There was only one: the women's bathroom. ``It wouldn't
have been so bad,'' said Barshefsky. ``Except that Gene wanders
around a lot when he's talking on a cell phone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
