<HEADLINE>
45,000 NAZI-ERA SWISS BANK ACCOUNTS FOUND, COMMISSION REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (mcd)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A commission that is seeking Holocaust-era accounts in
Swiss banks has found nearly 45,000 accounts in addition to the
5,570 already published, said a person who has read a draft of the
group's report.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to be released in a few weeks, the report is being
prepared by the panel, headed by the former Federal Reserve
chairman, Paul A. Volcker. The group met on Monday in Zurich to
review the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which has been three years in the making, is not
widely expected to recommend payments in addition to the $1.25
billion for Holocaust victims and their heirs that two major Swiss
banks agreed to in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Whether some or all the additional 45,000 accounts will be made
public and what language will be used to describe the bankers'
handling of the accounts have been sticking points in trying to
arrive at the final report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Underlying those questions has been the bankers' fear that in
the face of the considerable number of accounts, the commission
might recommend additional sums to settle claims that Swiss banks
hoarded money belonging to Jews who died in the Holocaust and
profited from dealings with Nazi Germany. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In August, two high-level Swiss bankers and the president of the
Association of Swiss Banks sent a letter to Volcker and his aide,
Michael Bradfield, expressing that concern. The settlement,
separate from the Volcker panel, is generally viewed here as bowing
to threats to boycott Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   When news of the banks' role in World War II began emerging, the
banks said they had just 755 accounts that could be linked to World
War II-era victims. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some 500 auditors scoured hundreds of Swiss banks looking for
accounts established from 1933 to 1945. The four auditing groups of
the commission have checked millions of names for possible links to
accounts and turned up 44,747 accounts with such links and an
additional 1,934 that appear to belong to senior Nazi officials or
Nazi collaborators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The information in each account's records varies from just the
name of the account holder to complete written transactions over a
period of years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The World Jewish Congress, which has been pushing for full
disclosure of Switzerland's wartime activities, wants information
on all accounts to be public to help survivors and heirs to reclaim
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to have all accounts published,'' the secretary
general of the congress, Israel Singer, said. ``But we are, of
course, concerned that if we unleash a wave of interest that we
also do justice. This has to be weighed.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the bankers' association, James Nason, said:
``Our position is that banks have seen the individual audits and
basically accept them. We hope the final report accurately reflects
the findings of the individual audits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
