<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASES OF PILOT SUICIDE ARE RARE, BUT NOT UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With AIRCRASH) 
(sw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is extremely rare for an airline pilot to crash a plane
deliberately. But it has happened.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, a SilkAir Boeing 737 was cruising at 35,000
feet in clear weather over Indonesia when it suddenly went into a
steep dive and crashed into a river, killing all 104 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Though a definitive finding has yet to be released by Indonesian
authorities, investigators believe that Tsu Way Ming, the jet's
captain, disconnected the cockpit voice recorder and flight data
recorder to mask his actions and then forced the plane into a dive.
Tsu had recently been demoted and disciplined by the airline and
had large gambling debts.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also believe that the crash of an Air Morocco
commuter airplane in 1994 that killed 51 people was a deliberate
act by the pilot. And the co-pilot of a Japan Airlines DC-8 that
crashed in Tokyo Bay in 1982, killing 24, was subsequently
institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives and representatives of pilots unions said on
Tuesday that the current battery of medical and flying requirements
that airline pilots must meet are good enough to weed out those who
might be mentally unstable. But some critics countered that
relatively little is being done by airlines and aviation
authorities to screen pilots for psychological distress.
</P>
<P>
   About half the major airlines give pilots a psychological test
as part of the hiring process, but few if any ever follow up, said
Dr. Robert Pressman, a clinical psychologist with Strategic
Outcomes, a company in Providence, R.I., that specializes in
selecting personnel for sensitive professions like flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is doing ongoing screening right now to my knowledge,''
he said. ``It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   To fly a commercial jet in the United States, a pilot must get a
medical checkup every six months from a doctor approved by the
Federal Aviation Administration. Though the examination is designed
mostly to ensure that the pilot is physically fit, the aviation
agency said that the doctors are also trained to discern whether a
pilot might be under psychological stress or depressed.
</P>
<P>
   The complementary standard set by the International Civil
Aviation Organization for its 185 member countries requires a
medical checkup every 12 months. The authorities have yet to prove
that suicide was the cause of the EgyptAir crash on Oct. 31, but
Egypt, as a member of the international organization, has agreed to
meet that minimum standard, although its civil aviation authority,
like the FAA, could require more frequent checkups.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots in the United States are also required to have their
flying skills evaluated by a pilot instructor on a simulator at
least once a year. And they are subject to surprise checks by FAA
inspectors and random drug tests by their employers. In addition,
the aviation agency says that it keeps a record of all pilots'
driver's licenses, which the agency compares to a national registry
of people arrested for drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Some airlines go further than the agency rules. United Airlines,
for example, the world's largest airline, requires pilots to
undergo an annual company physical that includes questions about
their personal lives. Both American Airlines and Delta Air Lines,
the nation's second and third-largest carriers, declined to comment
on their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots' unions oppose the expansion of psychological testing
because they say the current tests are unreliable and the problem
is extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the various requirements, individual pilots are able
to hide problems like drug abuse and alcoholism that would bar them
from flying. One pilot at a major airline continued to fly, even
though he had had his driver's license revoked for drunken driving
and had been arrested for beating his girlfriend while he was
drunk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
