u s BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     11-16 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOMETIMES CHARACTER PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's nice to see a team get one right. Bill Parcells' faith in
Ray Lucas was a joy to behold Monday night. The spectacle had
nothing to do with rooting for the Jets, but rather seeing a
blatant case of respect and admiration pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells saw something in Lucas beyond the gleaming intelligence
and ambition that made Lucas a willing member of the special teams.
More important, Lucas saw something in himself throughout a
teasingly inconsistent season.
</P>
<P>
   What a change from the foolish team officials who keep recycling
obvious bad actors like Lawrence Phillips and Isaiah Rider and
Derrick Coleman and, to some degree, a certain Rent-a-Met left
fielder we could name.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody around the Jets knows Parcells wants Lucas to succeed
at quarterback. Parcells is so pragmatic and driven that he rarely
seems to have loyalty or kindness toward anybody, except maybe a
small cadre of coaches and players who live with his blustering
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is not such a raging egomaniac that he would casually
stick a personal favorite at his game's most important position.
Lucas has been different. The coach saw beyond the hard-working
Jersey guy _ no small consideration, probably _ who played
quarterback for Rutgers but was not projected as more than a
special-teams prospect as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him when I got him that I didn't know what do with
him,'' Parcells said Tuesday. ``Now I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was looking for a quarterback who could produce on a
cold Monday night in New England. The prospect of this likable and
versatile young player getting a chance brought me to the tube at 9
p.m., probably the first time in 5 or 10 years that I consciously
sat down for a Monday night football game.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a compelling mix of emotion and skill from Lucas,
artfully angled passes and impromptu dashes. The Jets hung on for a
24-17 victory that can fill their entire season highlight film,
which has been looking for content since Vinny T. went down.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the defense and the blockers made it possible for Lucas to
have his wonderful night. Yes, Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet
saved drives with their acrobatic catches. But quarterback is the
key position, and Parcells saw something in Lucas that everybody
could savor, oh, for at least a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to work on his fundamentals,'' Parcells was insisting
Tuesday afternoon. ``The only thing he doesn't have to work on is
his desire to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The player had made the plays that won the game, but the coach
had the right to be proud of his faith. General managers and
coaches are often stunned that the man-with-a-history they just
brought in to energize a franchise winds up loafing in practice,
dogging it in games, even playing cards in the clubhouse during a
big game the way Rickey Henderson did this fall with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't character count for something? You want to scream when
the Atlanta Hawks trade a solid citizen like Steve Smith for a
problem like Isaiah Rider. The Atlanta management must now put up
with Rider's antisocial acts the same way the Charlotte Hornets
must put up with Derrick Coleman's, and insidiously the Knicks are
putting up with Latrell Sprewell's so-far-benign solipsism.
</P>
<P>
   All too often, the club misses the signals for disaster or
confusion. The Yankees, for example, may indeed be trying to obtain
Ken Griffey Jr., which would not only intrude on a team that has
won two straight World Series but also ignores Junior's own history
of loathing the very ground on which the Yankees play.
</P>
<P>
   As everybody knows by now, Junior was frightened at an early age
by every child's idea of the bogeyman, an angry Billy Martin, when
he was playing in the clubhouse. Junior has always implicated
George Steinbrenner in his grudge against the Yankees. Why would
George even think of offering a nine-digit contract to Junior?
</P>
<P>
   Are the Yankees missing Griffey's suspicion of the Big City? His
nervousness with questions from the press? What about the
inevitable conflicts with the owner himself?
</P>
<P>
   Junior does not poison a clubhouse like Albert Belle, does not
antagonize people like Barry Bonds, but he has given clear signals
that he prefers an adoring framework. If smug Seattle couldn't hold
him, he might do well in Cincinnati or Atlanta, where seldom is
heard a discouraging word.
</P>
<P>
   Teams need to observe the clues from players. Sometimes the
attention to character pays off in addition by subtraction.
Sometimes it pays off with a compelling victory on a cold night on
the road, the way a hopeful young quarterback Ray Lucas lived up to
his dreams Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
