<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADERS TO OPPOSE CONGRESSIONAL APPROVAL OF CHINA DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Union leaders on Tuesday vowed to try to block congressional
approval of the Clinton administration deal for China to join the
World Trade Organization, predicting that they could stop the
accord the way they had blocked other administration trade
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor leaders said they felt betrayed that President
Clinton, after having promised to ``put a human face on the global
economy,'' would reach a trade-liberalization pact with a country
that has suppressed unions and imprisoned labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO president John Sweeney cited a case in which several
Chinese labor leaders were jailed after having led a demonstration
by workers who were demanding back wages.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the AFL-CIO's international department, Barbara
Shailor, said: ``In China, the labor-rights situation is
particularly egregious. It's not only that they can't have unions,
but attempts to form unions will put them in prison and, sometimes,
put them before an execution squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders predicted that they could block approval by
mustering a majority in the House that would include most
Democrats, labor-friendly Republican moderates and conservative
Republicans angry about what they called China's human rights
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a very serious fight for us,'' the chief lobbyist
of the AFL-CIO, Peggy Taylor, said. ``This will certainly be as
serious as any trade fight we've been in. The consequences of this
deal are huge.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest concerns is that by letting China join the
WTO, the United States would give up its ability to punish China
unilaterally over trade violations, because the 135-nation group
would adjudicate trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders said the accord made it all the more important
that ministers at the trade group's meeting in Seattle in two weeks
agreed to allow trade penalities against countries that violated
fundamental labor rights by, for example, not allowing unions or by
tolerating child labor.
</P>
<P>
   Several union officials said they feared that the trade group
would never approve such penalties after a giant country like China
with extensive labor-rights violations joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to fight this big time,'' Mark Levinson, director
of policy at the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile
Employees, said. ``It's an outrage that a country with China's
record on labor rights is allowed into the WTO without any attempt
to improve its record. Once a country as big as China is in the
WTO, that may forever doom the WTO as a forum where progress can be
made on labor rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In condemning the agreement, Sweeney used unusually harsh
language toward an administration that he usually treats as an
ally. Calling the accord ``a grave mistake,'' he said, ``It is
disgustingly hypocritical of the Clinton White House to invoke the
need to `put a human face on the global economy' while prostrating
itself in pursuit of a trade deal with a rogue nation that
decorates itself with human rights abuses as if they were medals of
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Several union officials said the deal would probably soften
support for Vice President Al Gore, whom the AFL-CIO endorsed for
presidency in October.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, the labor movement dealt Clinton one of his
worst legislative blows when it persuaded the House not to approve
a ``fast track'' bill to extend his authority to negotiate trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a much bigger fight than fast track,'' Levinson
said. ``The consequences for the U.S. economy are much greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Several labor leaders said they thought that Sweeney would fight
the agreement especially hard, because other labor leaders have
criticized him for not being tough enough on trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to stop this, it's going to be in the House,''
said Teamsters political director Michael Mathis. ``It's going to
be very close.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's economics adviser, Gene Sperling, said that
Washington had won concessions on several labor demands, among them
protections against a surge in imports. Sperling said that China
would not agree to some labor demands and that if the
administration had insisted on them, the agreement would have been
scuttled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pulling China into a rule-based global trading system,''
Sperling said, ``and getting much more involvement by the United
States and other democracies in their economy will in the long run
do more for labor and human rights than making demands that China
wouldn't go along with and would have blown up the agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
