u f BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-B     11-16 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE CLAIMS COULD COST HANCOCK $32 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. expects to pay
out an extra $32 million this year to cover surprise claims by
newly found heirs of burial policies whose owners the insurer never
knew had died.
</P>
<P>
   In a rush to find scores of missing customers as it converts to
a publicly traded company, the Boston insurer said Tuesday it
expected to find 10 percent of some 400,000 missing policyholders
deceased. That means Hancock must immediately give policy heirs
benefits, typically $1,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's 13th-largest life insurer is under fire for losing
track of one-quarter of its customers as it reorganizes from a
mutual company owned by policyholders into a stock company owned by
shareholders. Most missing policyholders who turn out to be alive
are owed stock in the new company, cash, or beefier policies as
part of the transformation. Heirs of policies whose original owners
died get regular death benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that it probably won't succeed in tracking everyone
down before it issues first-time stock Jan. 28, Hancock said
Tuesday it would give missing policyholders up to seven years after
its $2 billion initial public offering to come forward and claim
compensation due under the change. Most policyholders are owed at
least 17 shares, estimated to be worth at least $340. Some
policyholders are owed far more.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.4 million policyholders that Hancock has kept tabs on have
until Nov. 30 to choose stock or cash. Some 2.8 million out of
Hancock's total 3.3 million policyholders are eligible for
compensation under the ``demutualization'' process.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said beneficiaries, or heirs, typically come forward to
claim money when policyholders pass away. But the insurer admitted
it had lost track of more customers than usual.
</P>
<P>
   To solve its missing persons dilemma, Hancock has enlisted
credit-reporting agencies, address search firms, and state
officials to track customers. The task is tough because many
policies in question were sold earlier this century, before easily
traceable Social Security numbers became commonly used on
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, which will spend at least $250 million on
demutualization, says it is also hamstrung by privacy laws that
prevent it from seeking policyholders by publishing personal
details, including names, in newspapers and Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of the Commonwealth William Galvin, whose office
is using voter registration lists to look for customers, said
Hancock is obligated under state law to regularly publish lists of
unpaid dividends _ a procedure that could have helped Hancock track
missing customers had it been followed, Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual for the insurance industry, Hancock is making cash, not
stock, the automatic compensation unless policyholders elect to
receive shares. Hancock had hoped to cash out most of its smaller
policyholders, who are an expensive administrative hassle.
</P>
<P>
   But in a big surprise, the insurer is finding that twice as many
people as expected have opted for shares. About 60 percent of
policyholders so far have elected stock, with more than one third
of customers reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials now estimate that nearly one in three
policyholders, or around 900,000, will initially wind up with stock
in the new firm. Previous estimates had projected one in five. The
revised ratio may widen, since some small shareholders will likely
sell their stock. The change means Hancock could have extra cash
from its IPO, since a lesser chunk will used to cash out
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Hancock is debating whether to set aside up to 5
percent of shares in the new company for stock option programs,
including 401(k) pension plans, for its 7,500 employees. Top
executives and directors will get hefty stock awards under other
plans in 2001, whose details Hancock has not announced.
</P>
<P>
   The insurer's top brass will not be awarded any form of stock
for one year following the IPO. Hancock executives also can't buy
shares at the IPO price, and thus can't benefit from the bounce
that new shares typically make. Senior executives wanting an
immediate piece of the action can buy stock on the open market 21
days after the IPO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
