<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FELDMAN-MUSIC-ART-$AD     11-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELDMAN-MUSIC-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FASCINATION WITH THE SOUND OF SILENCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Lawrence A. Johnson writes about music for The Chicago Tribune, The
New Criterion and Opera News.  
 By LAWRENCE A. JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the Flux Quartet's recent premiere performance of Morton
Feldman's String Quartet No. 2 in its complete six-hour version,
the three orchestral works on a new Feldman disc seem like
Webernian essays in atomistic compression.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman was a Brooklyn-born original for whom traditional forms
and unfolding musical development held little interest. Rather, he
was fascinated by the sounds of individual notes, the long
silences, expansive structures, isolated chords and spare timbral
combinations, a sonic counterpart to the visual works of artist
friends like Mark Rothko and Jackson Pollock.
</P>
<P>
   For some, Feldman's distinctive brand of musical stasis can be
the equivalent of aural water torture; others find a hypnotic
concentration and enigmatic mystery to his music, which become more
compelling with repeated listening.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman wrote few works for orchestra, yet in the three works
here _ ``Coptic Light,'' ``Piano and Orchestra'' and ``Cello and
Orchestra'' (Argo 448 513-2; CD) _ the more varied palette provides
an ideal entry point into his unique sound world, less daunting and
ascetic than the composer's chamber music.
</P>
<P>
   Written for the New York Philharmonic in 1986, a year before
Feldman died, ``Coptic Light'' takes its title from the composer's
interest in oriental carpets, the intricate patterning of which
provided the impetus for this 30-minute work. Feldman's largest
composition for orchestra, ``Coptic Light'' is characteristic in
its nonlinear progression, proceeding in quiet undulating waves,
though here the textures are more resplendent, the patterns more
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle billows of string chords and rippling piano notes crest
and recede, the interweaving musical textures coalesce and
fragment. Over the long span, the repeated notes in ``Coptic
Light'' become more angular and insistent, later relaxing into a
cascade of harp figures. Like the Eastern textiles from which
Feldman draws his inspiration, there is no beginning or discernible
destination, and it is the concentrated musical tones and
instrumental coloring that sustain the listener's interest.
</P>
<P>
   The two concertante works are more anti-concertos than
traditional solo and orchestra showpieces, and both again show
Feldman's interest in sonic painting with individual notes and
subtle hued timbres. ``Piano and Orchestra'' begins with a single
note from the soloist, to which the strings respond, and for the
next 22 minutes, the cryptic beauty of Feldman's music casts its
spell.
</P>
<P>
   Rare triple fortissimo chords are like seismic upheavals, yet
most of this music derives from its quiet hypnotic power. A change
in piano chording or isolated events like a single swish of a
maraca or a shimmering cymbal assume great significance in this
elliptical, infinitesimally subtle music.
</P>
<P>
   A later motif for double-basses has an undeniable jazz flavor,
and grinding woodwinds present unsettling conflict before the
reprise of the introductory piano chords provide a slight yet
palpable sense of returning to a safe harbor.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Cello and Orchestra,'' the soloist's phrases are longer and
more lyrical in profile, set against an orchestral backdrop of
ominous pedal-points pizzicato passages for the solo cello elicit a
sense of dark drama, as does a rocking two-note repeated passage in
the cello's highest register, which becomes an important part of
the musical flow.
</P>
<P>
   Again, those looking for a linear sonata-form development will
search in vain, but there is a sense of subtle progression and
unfolding progress to these works that reveals itself with close
and repeated listening.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tilson Thomas, a friend of the composer, shows himself a
superb advocate of Feldman's music in incisive, fully committed
performances with the New World Symphony Orchestra. Throughout, the
conductor brings out the luminosity of this music, allowing
Feldman's iridescent textures to be revealed naturally without any
special pleading.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Feinberg, the pianist, and Robert Cohen, the cellist, prove
equally skillful solo partners in these interpretively difficult
works, and the orchestra's alert and sensitive playing is all one
could wish for.
</P>
<P>
   The excellent recording allows every note of Feldman's music its
full value and color, in an acoustic that ideally blends clarity
and refinement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
