<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BOSNIA-MEIGS-ART-850&AMP;     11-16 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MEIGS-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA IS PEACEFUL NOW, BUT WILL IT STAY THAT WAY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Peace has come to Bosnia, but is
it here to stay?
</P>
<P>
   The American officer who led the 32,000 NATO peacekeepers here
for the last year, Gen. Montgomery Meigs, thinks that it is too
early to say. ``There has been progress,'' he said in a recent
interview here. ``Three years ago they wouldn't even talk to each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian barricades on the road between Sarajevo, where
Muslims are a majority, and the Bosnian Serb Republic, where almost
all the Serbs live, disappeared after the peacekeepers arrived.
Today, driving between the two places is no more eventful than
crossing the border between New York and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Even in hardline Bosnian Serb villages where graffiti express
support for Arkan, a paramilitary leader charged with crimes
against humanity, some people give a friendly wave to NATO patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the sandbags and concrete brick walls that protected
people in Sarajevo from snipers in the Serb-controlled
neighborhoods across the river during the war, between 1992 and
1995. Brightly painted trolley cars packed with passengers now run
past the gutted, almost totally collapsed concrete headquarters of
the newspaper Oslobodenje, whose basement presses never stopped
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins of the newspaper's tower, a prime target for the Serbs
during the war, are being preserved as a monument to past
suffering, like the blasted steeple of the Kaiser Wilhelm Memorial
Church in West Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   But Oslobodenje is more a symbol of successful Bosnian defiance
than a witness of repentance and reconciliation, as the Berlin
tower is. Those feelings do not yet seem to have taken root among
the Bosnian Serb, Muslim and Croat populations here, driven apart
by the war and still wary of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Radovan Karadzic and Gen. Ratko Mladic, two of the most
notorious Bosnian Serb leaders, both later indicted by an
international tribunal in the Hague on war crimes charges, are
still exercising power behind the scenes, and the peacekeepers have
not arrested them.
</P>
<P>
   Mladic is believed to have fled to Serbia, but Karadzic is said
to be in hiding in a sector of Bosnia that is under the supervision
of French peacekeepers. French and American officials have publicly
batted responsibility for the failure to arrest him back and forth
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here explain that NATO's prime mission in Bosnia is
not to arrest indicted war criminals but to maintain a safe and
secure environment.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers from 37 countries, their numbers to be reduced to
20,000 after elections next spring, can arrest war crimes suspects
they run across during the normal course of their duties, but only
when they believe that it is prudent and when no bystanders would
get hurt. They have arrested 13 so far.
</P>
<P>
   Meigs, choosing his words carefully, said, ``I wish we had
encountered more persons indicted for war crimes during the course
of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrested war crimes suspects include Gen. Radislav Kristic,
a Bosnian Serb army commander seized last December, and Radislav
Brdanin, a member of the Bosnian Serb parliament, taken in July.
But NATO troops have sometimes treated others differently when they
thought it necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Momir Talic, chief of staff of the Bosnian Serb army, was
secretly indicted in March but not arrested until Aug. 26, while he
was attending a military conference in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Talic, according to international officials here, was helpful in
keeping Bosnian Serb resentment over the NATO bombing of Kosovo
last spring from soaring out of control. He also supported the
current Bosnian Serb prime minister, Milorad Dodik, a man both the
United States and Russia still believe they can do business with in
Bosnia. Meigs and other NATO officials met with him more than once
to discuss security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some NATO officials concede that nothing will change
fundamentally in the Serbian part of Bosnia until Karadzic and
Mladic, with their ties to the Yugoslav security apparatus of
President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade, are taken off the
chessboard.
</P>
<P>
   Meigs, who after a year here turned over command of the force on
Oct. 18 to Lt. Gen. Ronald E. Adams, another American officer, went
back to his overall assignment as commander of the U.S. Army in
Europe, but Adams will also have his work cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next couple of years have to see a lot of developments
here,'' Meigs said. ``The umbilical cords of the various ethnic
communities to Belgrade, Zagreb and the Middle East have to be
cut.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The top Bosnian Muslim leader, President Alija Izetbegovic,
toured Iran, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia last month, and Saudi Arabia
has a big aid mission in Sarajevo, but allied officials are more
worried about Islamic fundamentalist fighters from other countries
who came here to back Bosnian Muslims during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Some apparently can still float in and out. Mehrez Amdouni, a
suspected associate of Osama bin Laden, who is believed to have
been the architect of the attacks on American Embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania last year, turned out to have a Bosnia-Herzegovina
passport when he was arrested last month in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers here have since been asking the government whether
bin Laden might have one, too, but have so far received no answers.
</P>
<P>
   With municipal elections here expected next spring, Meigs said
there was a chance for democratic institutions to develop, and
perhaps for the return of more than a few tens of thousands of
refugees from other ethnic groups into the homogeneous areas
controlled by Bosnian Muslims, Croats and Serbs that emerged from
the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to help these people define what is an ethical,
controllable state intelligence apparatus,'' Meigs said. ``All of
the mechanism that was built up during the communist years here to
control the population needs to be rooted out, and it hasn't
been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the amount of money that's spent on defense in this
country is a scandal,'' he added, with 40 percent of the federal
budget still spent on the military even though fighting among the
Bosnian Serb, Muslim and Croat armies stopped four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is now trying to get the three factions to reduce their
armed forces from 30,000 in the Serbian part of the country, and
30,000 in the Muslim-Croat federation by 15 percent, as they agreed
to do after an international summit meeting in Sarajevo July 29.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent meeting with Ante Jelavic, the Bosnian Croat member
of the tripartite presidency of this tortured country, Meigs urged
faster progress. ``The extent to which you can attract
international institutions and investments here will depend on the
momentum of improvement,'' the general told him. ``One of the
things I am extremely worried about as I leave is how you build a
court system that all of you can trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Meigs said, true peace might come to the Balkans
only after there is democratic change in Belgrade. ``Until the
people of the former Republic of Yugoslavia change their
government,'' he said, ``things are going to remain pretty
precarious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
