<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-DUMPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE SHIP OFFICER FACES CHARGES IN DUMPING CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Alaska, N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Royal Caribbean's newest and biggest ship, Voyager of the
Seas, arrived in Miami last week on its maiden voyage, the
welcoming ceremony included a surprise. Agents of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service boarded the ship and arrested one of its
chief engineers, accusing him of ordering crew members on another
vessel to dump untreated oily waste water into the Pacific Ocean
and the Inside Passage of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer, Oystein Larsen, 52, was indicted by a federal
grand jury in Los Angeles on charges of conspiracy and causing
false statements to the U.S. Coast Guard about illegal discharges
from the Royal Caribbean ship Nordic Prince in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   If he is convicted, Larsen will face a maximum of 15 years in
prison and a $750,000 fine. He is free on $250,000 bond pending
arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   For Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd., the second-largest cruise line
after Carnival Corp., the arrest was the latest chapter in a long
government investigation into the company's dumping practices.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the company pleaded guilty to discharging
contaminated water from its fleet in the mid-1990s and agreed to
pay $9 million in fines. This year, the company pleaded guilty in
July to six more illegal dumping accusations, including discharging
hazardous waste, and agreed to pay $18 million more in fines.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrest of Larsen was a clear signal that the
government's 5-year-old investigation is continuing. The focus has
shifted from the company to individual Royal Caribbean officers and
employees suspected of participating in the scheme, which involved
using concealed pipes to bypass waste treatment systems and pump
contaminated water overboard in seas from New York to Alaska to
save money.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed in U.S. District Court in New York and Miami
this month and other records unsealed by a federal judge in Miami
shed new light on the ongoing inquiry and raised accusations that
Royal Caribbean's outside lawyers wrongfully concealed
incriminating information from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Martenstein, a Royal Caribbean spokeswoman, said the
company was cooperating with the authorities in the investigation
of crew members and has instituted strict new environmental
policies.
</P>
<P>
   At sentencing in Miami this month on the line's July guilty
plea, prosecutors praised Royal Caribbean for adopting new
practices, including placing an environmental officer on each of
its ships, installing new waste treatment systems and increasing
training for employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaudits contrasted with the picture painted by
government documents of how the company and its lawyers behaved
before the final plea agreement was reached in July.
</P>
<P>
   In a sentencing memorandum for the judge in Miami, prosecutors
said Royal Caribbean, instead of trying to get to the bottom of the
conduct, carried out a shadow investigation of the government's
initial criminal inquiry in an attempt to learn what investigators
were discovering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the government sought to interview an RCCL employee
or began to focus the investigation upon certain individuals, RCCL
helped to retain, and paid for, a separate attorney to represent
the employee,'' the memo stated. Corporations routinely provide
lawyers for employees, but prosecutors contended that Royal
Caribbean's tactics were defensive and have made it more difficult
to obtain information for the ongoing inquiry into the actions of
unnamed individuals.
</P>
<P>
   What is more unusual, Royal Caribbean agreed to pay an
additional $1 million fine in July because the government said it
had improperly withheld documents. In court papers, the government
accused lawyers from a prominent Washington firm, Venable, Baetjer,
Howard &AMP; Civiletti, of improperly withholding incriminating
documents sought by subpoena in the criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers represented the company in the initial
investigations of dumping in Puerto Rico and Miami, which resulted
in the 1998 pleas.
</P>
<P>
   In an addendum to the sentencing memo, prosecutors Thomas
Watts-FitzGerald and Richard Udell said the outside lawyers learned
that a former Royal Caribbean employee had filed a suit in Norway
that included photographs of a pipe used to bypass the treatment
systems on the line's Sun Viking. Royal Caribbean also provided its
lawyers with a 1996 e-mail that contained specific accusations by a
former employee of illegal dumping by the Sun Viking.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, prosecutors were focusing on two ships and were
unaware of the extent of Royal Caribbean's dumping. The
incriminating material was not turned over because the lawyers said
it was protected by attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But last summer the information was provided to prosecutors
after the Washington lawyers were replaced by Robert Fiske.
FitzGerald praised Fiske in court for recognizing that the
documents were not privileged and turning them over. As a result of
the delay, however, Royal Caribbean paid an additional $1 million
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Donald Middlebrooks of U.S. District Court in Miami
unsealed the addendum over the objections of Benjamin Civiletti,
chairman of the Venable firm and a former U.S. attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the judge, Civiletti said the decision to
withhold the information was part of a legitimate legal strategy
and argued that it was unfair to impugn the firm and its lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Civiletti made only one appearance in the case; two other
lawyers from the firm, Judson Starr and Jerry Block, were the main
representatives of Royal Caribbean. James Shea, the firm's managing
partner, said the government was exaggerating the episode and could
have challenged the privilege claim during its investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Grand juries in at least two cities, Miami and Los Angeles, are
continuing to examine the role played by individual Royal Caribbean
employees in the illegal dumping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
