<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CRASH-FBI-BOS &LR;      11-16 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT SPECIALISTS TO REVIEW FLIGHT 990 COCKPIT TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS AND CHARLES SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The FBI was poised Tuesday to take over the investigation into
the downing of EgyptAir Flight 990 because officials believe the
crash was a deliberate act _ and perhaps the largest mass murder in
American history.
</P>
<P>
   While top officials in US Government agreed to the formal
transfer from the National Transportation Safety Board to the FBI,
it was delayed repeatedly Tuesday by concerns of the Egyptian
government, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing late Tuesday, NTSB Chairman James E. Hall praised
the Egyptian government as a ``partner'' in the ongoing
investigation, and said it will send ``experts and officials'' to
help analyze the information from the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   While there was ``no sign of a mechanical or weather-related
event that could have caused this accident,'' Hall said, there are
``differences in cultural interpretation'' of some crucial remarks
on the recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said they still expected the FBI to assume control of
the investigation in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expected shift, officials still don't know why a
member of the EgyptAir flight crew _ believed to be a co-pilot _
might have deliberately pushed the jet into a terrifying,
near-supersonic dive from its cruising altitude of 33,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir officials said Captain Ahmed El Habashi and First
Officer Adel Anwar were scheduled to fly the first leg of the
11-hour flight from New York's John F. Kennedy International Aiport
to Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Los Angeles Times reported that co-pilot Gamil El
Batouty asked to fly the first leg and was at the controls when the
jet went down. Batouty, 59, was nearing retirement; sources said;
his daughter was critically ill, and the Los Angeles Times said he
was worried about paying for her lupus treatments.
</P>
<P>
   A relative of Batouty called the allegation outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   The expected criminal investigation will now focus on the
members of the flight crew and what they did in the hours, days and
weeks before the flight. The investigation will also explore their
beliefs, relationships, political ties, finances and any criminal
histories.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope to discover if the death dive of the Boeing
767-300ER was a suicidal act or a politically-motivated mission
targeting the more than 100 Americans on board, or Egyptian
military personnel, including three generals.
</P>
<P>
   One high-ranking official familiar with the investigation, said
evidence points to ``someone who had personal problems'' rather
than an act of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said investigators believe the crash was deliberate
because, a half-hour after takeoff early on Oct. 31, one pilot left
the cockpit and the remaining pilot talked of ``going into death,''
according to some reports.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe he made the remark just before the plane's
auto-pilot was disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   But if the utterance, which has been described as a prayer, was
made after the plane began to dive, the words may instead represent
``the pious act of a Muslim recognizing he is in great danger,''
said Vince Cannistraro, former CIA head of counter-terrorism
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The brother of co-pilot Batouty reacted vehemently Tuesday to
the direction the investigation was taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes us very angry to hear the media saying that a man was
praying and therefore he must be either committing suicide or be a
terrorist,'' said Walid Batouty,.
</P>
<P>
   Walid Batouty said his brother, 59, and the father of five, was
scheduled to fly the second leg of the trip once the jetliner
reached the coast of Europe. He expressed disgust at suggestions
that his brother would kill himself and 216 others so his family
could claim insurance money.
</P>
<P>
   ``EgyptAir insurance covered (his daughter's) medical bills and
would do so when he retired,'' Walid Batouty said. ``Why aren't you
focusing on three Boeing airplanes, TWA, Swissair, and EgyptAir
taking off from JFK and crashing?''
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that a battle to control the airplane was
being waged inside the cockpit, when the other member of the flight
crew returned.
</P>
<P>
   Because the elevators on the horizontal stabilizer were in
opposite directions _ one was pointed up, the other down _ aviation
specialists said that indicates a struggle for control of the
airplane in the twin-yoke cockpit, with one pilot pulling on the
yoke to get the plane to climb as the other pushed the other yoke
forward, to make the plane dive.
</P>
<P>
   The voice recorder captures the pilot, who returned to the
cockpit, saying ``pull with me, pull with me,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's expected investigation faces daunting obstacles: there
are no eye-witnesses, the pilots are all dead, those who knew them
best live in the Middle East and speak another language, and much
of the evidence lies deep beneath the Atlantic Ocean, some 60 miles
south of Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he has asked the Navy to contract for a large ship
with heavy lift capabilities to assist in recovery. Investigators
want to examine the jet's cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Though investigators are focusing on the men inside the cockpit
that night, those who knew them say none had an obvious reason to
commit such a horrific act.
</P>
<P>
   There were five pilots on board the airplane, but only two were
assigned to be flying the first leg of the 11-hour flight.
</P>
<P>
   According to EgyptAir Captain Roshdy Zakaria, deputy chief pilot
of the Boeing 767-300 for the airline, Capt. Habashi and First
Officer Anwar were at the controls on the first leg of the flight.
Two other pilots, Captain Raouf Noradin and First Officer Batouty,
were the relief crew and sat in an area outside the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Relief crews are common on long intercontinental flights. Also
on the flight as a passenger was Hatem Rushdie, EgyptAir's chief
pilot for the Boeing 767.
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria doubted that any of the pilots could have intentionally
crashed the plane as a form of suicide, or that one of them could
have been an extremist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these men well,'' he said. ``They are good pilots, and
they are good men. None of them could be capable of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, a co-pilot, was a deeply religious man, Zakaria said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would describe him as a devout Muslim, a traditional and
very religious man,'' he said. If it was his voice captured on the
recorder, ``How do we know that this prayer was not the prayer of a
faithful man who knew he was about to die?''
</P>
<P>
   Habashi, 57, was the father of four children and had flown for
38 years. His brother, an air-traffic controller in Cairo, said
Habashi was also a traditional and a devout Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good father and a good husband and the most
disciplined pilot in the company,'' said Mohammed Habashi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no problems in his life,'' said Zakaria. ``He was a
nice guy. . . . I cannot predict what happened, but I don't believe
this talk about a suicide. I know these people too well.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar was engaged and had asked Zakaria if he could fly the next
New York trip on Friday, Nov. 5, so he and his bride could
honeymoon in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that sound like someone preparing to kill themselves, and
all of the passengers on a plane?'' Zakaria asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writers Ann Scales, John Donnelly, Judy Rakowsky,
Susan Mulligan contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
