<HEADER>
A1830 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AND GOP LEADERS SEEK TO PUT FINISHING TOUCHES ON
BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House and the Republican Congress
struggled on Tuesday night to pay for nearly $7 billion in new
spending with using money from excess Social Security contributions
to cover the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Once an agreement is reached, Republicans will try to pas the
remaining five budget bills in one $390 billion package.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very close,'' said the House majority whip, Tom
DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But they are still demanding that the White House agree to an
across-the-board cut of .42 percent in all the spending bills, and
so far, the White House has not budged. President Clinton vetoed a
.97 percent across-the-board cut passed by Congress two weeks ago,
calling it a ``blind'' and ``mindless'' way to make a budget.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on its size, that cut could recoup some or most of the
$7 billion the Republicans have added in recent weeks, some of it
on their own, some at the president's behest.
</P>
<P>
   The rest could be made up with accounting maneuvers, like
delaying the last paycheck for Pentagon personnel in September 2000
until after Oct.1, the beginning of the next fiscal year, which
would shift more than $2 billion from this year's budget into next.
</P>
<P>
   There was one encouraging sign as night fell on the Capitol:
Jack Lew, the White House budget director, was carrying a small
notebook instead of a bulging briefcase when he entered the
chambers of the Senate Appropriations Committee to talk with the
Republican negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those Republicans, like the chairmen of the Senate and
House Appropriations committees, Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska and
Rep. C.W. Bill Young of Florida, say they hate the idea of an
across-the-board cut, because it trims spending indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, they have to support it. Their leaders have
demanded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some across-the-board cut,'' promised the House
majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey of Texas. Stevens said on Tuesday
night that the idea was ``on the table,'' but ``on the edge of the
table,'' where it has been pushed by Democrats' opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans say that either the White House must make the
cut or come up with nearly $7 billion in savings by some
combination of specific cuts and accounting mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   The $7 billion in savings is necessary for the Republicans to be
able to claim the final budget will not dip into Social Security
surpluses. That vow has been their rallying cry in Congress this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But to keep that promise, they have used a budgetary device
making close to $20 billion in spending disappear from the federal
ledger _ a device calculated by the Republicans to make their
numbers come out the way they want.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office puts the total cost of the
year's 13 spending bills at roughly $610 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is $30 billion more than the spending limits, or caps, that
Congress swore to uphold in this year's budget when it passed the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997. It is at least $15 billion more than
the surplus of general government funds, which would mean that the
rest would have to come from the Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the
Republican-controlled Congress ``spent money from the Social
Security trust fund, and we busted the caps that were agreed to in
1997. It's all very, very regrettable,'' he said in an interview
with CNN. ``And we may pay a heavy price in not being able to make
Social Security whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the other Republicans in Congress fervently deny
this. ``Republicans have balanced _ will have balanced the budget
without raiding Social Security,'' DeLay said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The different tenses he used show that Republicans may have to
rely on higher-than-expected tax revenues in the coming months to
ensure that their fiscal 2000 budget will not use the retirement
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   If that does not happen, they may have to find a way to cut the
budget in midyear, said DeLay, who has been the chief Republican
spending strategist in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is,'' DeLay explained, ``we will have a mid-course
correction come January or February, and if it looks like we're
going to spend the Social Security surplus, we'll cut spending to
make sure we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the spending bills tap into surplus Social
Security revenues has absolutely no effect on the long-term fiscal
health of the retirement funds, according to almost every
independent budget analyst and fiscal expert.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the political contest over which party is the truer
guardian of the Social Security system has become one of the big
symbolic struggles in this session of Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
