<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TURKEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLEDGES MORE AID 
TO TURKISH QUAKE VICTIMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c. 1999, Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ President Clinton toured a tent city filled
with earthquake survivors Tuesday, promising more U.S. aid to a
nation devastated by back-to-back temblors.
</P>
<P>
   The president, accompanied by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and daughter Chelsea, strolled from tent to tent in nearby Izmit
during a steady cold rain to comfort families who lived through the
Aug. 17 earthquake that claimed 17,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that we in the United States will do
everything we can to help you until your lives return to normal,''
Clinton told a crowd. ``We will stay with you and work with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States would send another 10,000 tents
in response to a second earthquake last week in nearby Duzce. The
United States initially provided 6,000 tents after the Aug. 17
quake left 300,000 people homeless. Turkey also will be eligible
for $1 billion in Export-Import Bank loan guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton urged the Turks to take the opportunity presented by
warmer relations with Greece to move toward a permanent
reconciliation. Both countries momentarily suspended their rivalry
to help the other with earthquake aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the ordinary people in Greece and Turkey who have
suffered from these terrible natural disasters can send a clear
message to the leaders that the people of this region can get
along, and they should get along, and when they do get along, our
children's lives and futures are better,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president touring a disaster area has become a common scene
in the United States where he often surveys the damage caused by
floods or hurricanes, and meets with those who lived through it.
</P>
<P>
   For the Turks, it was all rather new.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the devastation, families greeted the Clintons with a
``welcome'' sign and pink roses for the first lady. The Clintons
ambled down a double row of cotton-lined, olive-green tents,
entering the new home of the Gencenler family. Seventeen people,
down from 21, live amid seven mattresses, two small sofas, two
electric space heaters, a refrigerator and a television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the most difficult thing about living in this tent?''
the president asked a woman holding a small baby. ``The hard days
of winter,'' she responded. ``And the humidity in the tent. The
heat makes a lot of humidity.''
</P>
<P>
   They were among 9,000 people living in 1,200 tents in this
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-year-old named Betul crawled into Chelsea Clinton's lap.
``We're grateful for you letting us into your home. We wanted to
listen and think about what the next steps are, how we can restore
you to a normal life,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are grateful to God and our government,'' the woman
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spoke to Ismail Yoldas, a paper-factory worker
injured by a falling beam. His family rushed cookies and tea to the
Clintons. The Clintons also toured a makeshift school, where one
boy held up a misspelled but well-intentioned sign: ``Welcome to
Clintion. I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another boy called out, ``We want to thank the American children
for their support.'' The students sang a Turkish children's song.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rubble in the city has been cleared away, and
hundreds lined the street to see the president.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Guarnieri, a member of the National Security Council
humanitarian staff, said the people in Izmit felt the tremors from
the earthquake last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really shook people up emotionally,'' she said. Duzce is
about 70 miles from Izmit. ``Shelter is really critical,'' she
said, noting the temperature falls below freezing at night.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated the residents would live in the tent city through
the winter. ``Clearly, a lot needs to be done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two rescue teams from the United States helped locate survivors
and the dead after the Aug. 17 incident. The United States
government also provided three ships, 2,200 Marines and 22
helicopters to assist people. U.S. officials helped restore the
water system in Izmit. They also provided 10,000 body bags.
</P>
<P>
   The twin earthquakes have many of this city's residents on edge.
Wire services reported many citizens near panic this week amid
fears of a third disaster. Some people spent the night in parks or
in their cars, afraid to stay in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, earthquake concerns have had little effect on the
president's schedule. He will attend a two-day summit here of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe beginning
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on day three of a 10-day tour of southeastern Europe,
also went sightseeing in this historic city, once a major hub of
the Roman, Byzantine and Ottoman empires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
