<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: CHIEF JUDGE PICKED
</P>
<P>
   Judge Claude Jorda of France was picked as the new president of
the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia in
The Hague. Chosen from among the panel's 14 judges, he succeeds the
American Gabrielle Kirk McDonald, who chose not to extend her
expiring term. Jorda, 61, has criticized the panel's backlog of
cases and has said he plans reforms.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: SUED OVER BEEF
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's executive decided to bring legal action
against France because it continues to ban British beef in defiance
of a ruling ordering the ban lifted. France has said mad cow
disease still poses a threat to consumers of British beef. Paris
officials said they were close to lifting the ban. Other countries
also still bar British beef, including Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: SKI VICTIM PAYOUTS
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary committee approved a government proposal to
award $2 million to the families of each of the 20 ski tourists
killed when a U.S. military jet cut the cables of a ski lift in
northern Italy in February 1998. The bill now goes to the Senate
for approval.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: CANCER RULING
</P>
<P>
   In a landmark decision, Britain's Court of Appeal ruled that a
hospital was negligent when it failed to diagnose cancer in three
women. Each will receive damages ranging from $32,500 to $48,700,
their lawyer said, paving the way for other cases in Britain, which
has one of the worst cancer-related death rates in western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: SLAVE TALKS STALL
</P>
<P>
   Two-day talks in Bonn on compensating Nazi-era slave workers
have stalled over how much money survivors should get. Wolfgang
Gibowski, spokesman for a group of German companies, described as
``absolute nonsense'' a statement by the victims' lawyer that
companies and the government had increased their joint offer to
$5.3 billion from $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: U.S. NEWSMAN RULING
</P>
<P>
   A court told an American journalist charged with slandering the
Turkish army that the charge would be dropped if he committed no
other offense in the next three years. The journalist, Andrew
Finkel, who wrote the article for an Istanbul newspaper, said he
had hoped for a full acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: PROTEST ON NEO-NAZIS
</P>
<P>
   The Simon Wiesenthal Center urged the government to halt
neo-Nazi activities in the formerly deserted village of Los
Pedriches in southeast Spain. The center said neo-Nazis are
organizing paramilitary camps in the village. News reports said two
Italians linked to a British-based group called International Third
Position had bought most of the vacant homes there since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: ATTACKS HALTED
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the ruling Taliban told Afghans to stop attacks on
United Nations offices and said Kabul would pay for damage caused,
the official Afghan press agency said. But hours later the Security
Council condemned the violence that accompanied the imposition of
sanctions on Afghanistan for its failure to turn over the militant
Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: TRUCE DASHED
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia has dashed hopes for
a monthlong holiday truce suggested by the government, saying even
a temporary cease-fire hinges upon Bogota's willingness to meet 10
demands, most of them considered impossible to meet.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA: REBEL CHIEF LOCATED
</P>
<P>
   Military officials say they have located the rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi and that they are attacking his location directly.
Savimbi's rebel army, Unita, has suffered several defeats in recent
months, but the military's report could not be verified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
