<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-PIPELINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH AGREEMENTS IN SIGHT, 
CLINTON CHEERS CASPIAN PIPELINES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c. 1999, Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Ignoring continued agitation by Russia,
President Clinton embraced proposed Caspian Sea oil and gas
pipelines Tuesday as critical to the region's future and security.
</P>
<P>
   ``These will help to diversify our sources of energy and help
the newly independent countries of the Caucasus and Central Asia
stand on their own feet. They will put Turkey, our trusted ally,
front and center in the effort to create a secure energy future,''
Clinton told executives at the Turkish Business Council.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey will sign an agreement this week
offering promises of financial support plus a legal framework for
the project when 54 nations gather here for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   They hope the accord will prod an 11-member oil company
consortium to construct a $2.4 billion, 1,240-mile oil pipeline
from the Azerbaijani capital of Baku, through Georgia, to the
Turkish port city of Ceyhan on the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   A second agreement for a $2.5 billion gas pipeline will be
signed by the same three countries and Turkmenistan to bring gas
from Turkmenistan to Turkey. Clinton will witness the signings on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that accord, Turkey agrees to cover cost overruns
associated with construction inside its borders. But the oil
company partners have not yet committed to the deal. U.S. officials
are hoping the gas pipeline will be in place by 2002 and the oil
pipeline by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   For six years the Clinton administration has pushed the idea of
the Caspian Sea pipelines to counter efforts to construct a system
through Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. plan has upset Russia, which accuses the United States
of attempting to take advantage of its weakened status and control
the reserves. The U.S.-backed plan would loosen the hold Russia has
over former Soviet states, but the United States contends it will
foster democracy in those emerging nations.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike Hammer said the political goal of the
United States is to avoid placing a pipeline across Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin envoys traveled to Baku last weekend to urge Azari
officials to back away from any deal that bypasses Russia and Iran.
Russia contends its proposed alternative across the Black Sea is
more feasible. But a U.S. official said Azerbaijan remains
committed to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made great strides toward the proposed Baku-Ceyhan oil
pipeline and the trans-Caspian gas pipeline,'' Clinton told the
Turkish business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet if you polled the citizens of the United States and
Turkey, over 90 percent of them would never have heard of the
Baku-Ceyhan oil pipeline or the trans-Caspian gas pipeline. But if
we do this right, 20 years from now, 90 percent of them will look
back and say, thank you, for making a good decision at a critical
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish President Suleyman Demirel called the pipelines
``pivotal projects'' for the region. ``These projects offer the
most economic, shortest and safest alternative for energy
transportation,'' Demirel told the Turkish executives.
</P>
<P>
   Oil reserves also are a key factor in Russia's efforts to quash
any Islamic rebellion in Chechnya. Its bombing of civilians also
will be a major topic of discussion at the OSCE sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The oil pipeline project is spearheaded by the Azerbaijan
International Operating Co., led by London-based BP Amoco. The
consortium plans to spend upwards of $10 billion to produce an
estimated 4 billion barrels of oil from Caspian Sea fields off the
coast of Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium currently is exporting about 100,000 barrels of
Caspian crude, primarily through a relatively small pipeline that
runs from the Azeri capital of Baku to Supsa, a Georgian port on
the Black Sea, a consortium spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium has a second pipeline that extends to the Russian
Black Sea port of Novorossiysk. But that pipeline traverses
Chechnya. And the Russians, who must take possession of the oil
once it crosses the border, have been unable to do so in recent
weeks as the fighting in Chechnya has raged.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have assured officials in Baku they could
build a bypass around Chechnya within six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they've been saying that for quite a while, there's not
really any evidence of that happening,'' said Michael Townshend, BP
Amoco's director of international affairs in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, BP Amoco threw its support behind the Baku-Ceyhan
route, but the other partners must still be persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies long have been reluctant to commit such a
substantial amount of money to construct a pipeline, in large part,
because the reserves discovered in the Caspian have fallen short of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium partners have been looking for companies
exploring other fields in the region to help cover the cost of the
pipeline. The agreement to be signed this week will give potential
participants the legal and commercial framework they will need to
evaluate the project, Townshend said.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium partners have long argued that if government
leaders believe a Baku-Ceyhan line is so vital to the stability of
the region, then the governments should provide subsidies to help
defray the cost of construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration already has promised to provide
support for the project through the Export-Import Bank, the
Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the Trade and Development
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
