u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN POLLSTERS CHALLENGE SIZE OF TURNOUT IN PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Several independent pollsters have challenged
official results of the governing party's Nov. 7 presidential
primary that showed a huge turnout of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Two pollsters suggested that party may have exaggerated the
turnout, perhaps greatly, to enhance the image of the party's
invincibility going in the presidential race next year. But they
did not question the outcome of the primary, won by Francisco
Labastida Ochoa, the candidate of the power structure.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters' findings have added to an uneasy sense in the
country over figures published by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party showing that 9.72 million people voted in its first
competitive primary, which was open both to party members and
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders, including President Ernesto Zedillo, pointed to
the robust turnout to say that the primary drew an enthusiastic
response and demonstrated that the party is going strong despite
years of economic crises and corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
   For the party, known as the PRI, proving that the primary was
clean and fair is crucial to rebuilding its credibility. The party
has dominated Mexican politics for seven decades, but has been
famous in the past for winning elections by buying votes.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials vigorously defended the accuracy of the primary
vote count. ``We did not invent these figures,'' Felipe Solis
Acero, a top official of the party commission which ran the
primary, said Tuesday. ``Behind every vote, there is a ballot that
has been marked.''
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters say they do not doubt that Labastida won a
crushing victory over his closest opponent, Roberto Madrazo
Pintado. According to the final results Labastida won the most
votes in 272 of 300 electoral districts while Madrazo came out
ahead in only 21.
</P>
<P>
   The district results were based on a reported total of 5.33
million votes cast for Labastida and 2.76 million for Madrazo. The
remaining 1.63 million were divided among two other contenders and
invalid votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was inflated,'' said Daniel Lund, who conducts
polls for Mori de Mexico, an affiliate of a British public opinion
firm. ``The total is just not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lund said the candidates' percentages appeared to be correct,
but he estimated that no more than 5 million votes were cast in
all. Lund did not conduct a complete exit poll, but had observers
posted at polling stations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw in the polling places was that roughly half of the
people reported as having voted actually appeared so we could count
them,'' Lund said.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Moreno, who conducted a nationwide exit poll Nov. 7
for the newspaper Reforma, said, ``It appears that there were a lot
more votes than voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreno said many of his poll-takers called in during the day to
report that they could not get his required minimum of 15 voter
interviews at a polling station. He said he was astonished to see
that the final results for the same polling places showed 150 or
more voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers don't check out,'' Moreno said. Both pollsters
acknowledged that their information is incomplete and both said
they intended to conduct new studies.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, and a third pollster from a separate firm who
expressed similar doubts but asked not to be identified, presented
their views Monday to a group of American portfolio investors at a
closed-door conference organized by Warburg Dillon Read, the
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Another pollster, Warren Mitofsky, who conducted a exit poll at
5,000 voting stations for the Televisa television network, disputed
his colleagues' contentions. Based on what he called ``an enormous
national sample,'' he estimated on the night of the primary that
just over 10 million people had voted.
</P>
<P>
   After casting his ballot in a desolate polling station in
northern Mexico, one of the losing candidates, Humberto Roque
Villanueva, lamented that the turnout had been ``less than
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, in the hours after the results were announced, frustrated
followers of Madrazo complained of vote-buying and ballot-box
stuffing by Labastida across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Madrazo, faced with a decisive defeat, surprised his
followers by deciding not to challenge the honesty of the primary.
Instead he closed ranks with the party to help it win the election
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI will face the most competitive presidential contest in
its history next July, when Labastida will stand against two other
strong candidates, the more conservative Vicente Fox Quesada and
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, who is left-of-center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
