<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FED RAISES INTEREST RATES ON CONCERN ABOUT INFLATION
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve raised the federal funds rate by a quarter
of a percentage point, to 5.5 percent, saying that the combination
of strong growth and low unemployment had left the economy
vulnerable to inflation. It was the third time this year that the
central bank has raised rates to slow the economy, and the move
clearly signaled that the Fed's growing faith in technology's
ability to improve efficiency and temper inflationary pressures has
its limits.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks jumped as investors bet that the Fed is done with raising
interest rates in the near future. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 171.58 points, or 1.6 percent, to 10,932.33. The Nasdaq
composite index climbed 73.51 points, or 2.3 percent, to 3,293.05,
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased 25.64 points,
or 1.8 percent, to 1,420.03, a record.
</P>
<P>
   COMCAST TO BUY LENFEST FROM AT&AMP;T
</P>
<P>
   Comcast agreed to buy the cable television company Lenfest
Communications from AT&AMP;T and the Lenfest family for $5.21 billion
in stock, adding 1.25 million subscribers in the Philadelphia area.
AT&AMP;T agreed in May to sell cable systems and provided an option on
others to Comcast in exchange for withdrawing from the bidding for
MediaOne. Class A shares of Comcast rose $2.6875, to $44.
</P>
<P>
   PFIZER STEPS UP HOSTILE CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer stepped up its effort to acquire Warner-Lambert,
beginning its attempt to oust Warner's board and outlining the
advantages of the hostile takeover to Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   KENDALL-JACKSON NAMES PLATT CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   For months the speculation was that Lewis Platt, who retires as
chairman of Hewlett-Packard at the end of the year, would join a
venture capital firm, a medical instrument company, or an Internet
start-up. Wrong. Platt will join Kendall-Jackson Wine Estates as
chief executive on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   GENENTECH SEEN IN PATENT ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   Genentech, the pioneering biotechnology company, has agreed to
settle its long-running patent battle with the University of
California over genetically engineered human growth hormones. The
university's board of regents is scheduled to consider the
agreement this week.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPLEY TO LEAVE CHASE ON JAN. 1
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Chase Manhattan, Walter Shipley, will retire on
Jan. 1. He will be succeeded by William B. Harrison Jr., the chief
executive of Chase, the nation's third largest bank. Shipley is
leaving 11 months before he reaches the mandatory retirement age of
65. Shipley, who has worked in the banking industry for 43 years,
became chairman in March 1996 after the merger between Chase
Manhattan and Chemical Bank. Under Shipley, Chase's stock has risen
135 percent.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION RISES 0.7 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production climbed a bigger-than-expected
seven-tenths of 1 percent in October, its fastest rate in seven
months, as utilities and factories rebounded from a dip in
September, the Federal Reserve said.
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS' PROFITS BEAT FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, Dayton Hudson and Limited reported
better-than-expected third-quarter profits as a strong economy
fueled sales of everything from tools to housewares to clothing.
J.C. Penney said its profit fell 24 percent as it lost shoppers to
low-price stores, but its results still beat revised forecasts by a
penny.
</P>
</TEXT>
