<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-SCHOOL-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON ARRESTED IN PROTEST OVER EXPULSIONS IN DECATUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson was arrested Tuesday in a
protest over the expulsion of seven students in the Illinois city
of Decatur for a melee at a football game.
</P>
<P>
   Although the protests have been imbued with the language of the
civil rights movement, the conflict centers less on race than on
the strict zero-tolerance disciplinary policies. Such codes suspend
or expel students for any act of violence and became widely used in
the wake of school shootings in Colorado and Arkansas, among other
places.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has said the issue is not racism, but unfairness in the
school board's expulsion of seven students, all of them black, for
a melee that involved no weapons.
</P>
<P>
   While defenders of such policies say strict rules are needed to
ensure a safe environment for learning, critics say the policies
are often unduly harsh, affect minorities disproportionately and
have led to a soaring expulsion rate that sets many troubled
students adrift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have this illusion that once a child has been
dropped from school, they simply disappear,'' said Donald Moore,
the executive director of Designs for Change, an education research
organization in Chicago. ``Well, they don't disappear. They're on
the streets, they're shoplifting.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the perception that schools have become violent, Moore
said, the crime rate in classrooms has been falling in recent
years. Between 1993 and 1997, school-related offenses fell to 102
crimes for every 1,000 students, from 155 crimes for every 1,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders of strict discipline, including many school
administrators, say it is needed for students to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical to have rules and structure so kids know where
they stand,'' said Charles Chieppo, a spokesman for the Pioneer
Institute, a conservative research group in Boston that promotes
charter schools. ``It's especially important to have structure in
schools where many of the students come from homes without much
structure.''
</P>
<P>
   The involvement of Jackson has clearly annoyed many residents of
Decatur, a city of 83,000, with schools that are nearly 40 percent
black. A group of students Tuesday stood with a banner that read,
``Honk if you support the school board.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and school officials met Tuesday morning, but neither
side budged. A few hours later, Jackson slowly pushed his way
though a mob of reporters and cameras to get to the edge of school
property, where he was handcuffed and led away.
</P>
<P>
   School officials have made plain they resent Jackson's presence.
Kenneth Arndt, the school superintendent, told protesters, ``Go
home _ you're definitely not going to get through our doors.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson last week vowed to march on the school, officials
canceled classes, fearful of a confrontation. They also met with
Jackson and offered to reduce the initial two-year expulsion for
the students to one year, with an option for the students to begin
attending an alternative school for troubled students immediately.
</P>
<P>
   That offer was rejected by Jackson, who called for the students
to be allowed to return to their own school in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
