<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1859 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-AIRCRASH-ART-2NDTAKE-     11-16 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: Arabic,'' he said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hall said that the authorities would soon bring a large vessel
to the scene that could continue the search, even in rough winter
weather, for human remains and wreckage of the plane. Aviation
experts said that no matter who was in charge, authorities must
still recover more sections of the aircraft from the sea floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that retrieval of the cockpit area would be a
priority. In some previous crashes, information stored in on-board
computer chips yielded valuable data about the condition of the
aircraft in the seconds before impact. Unlike older planes, most
cockpit instruments in the 767 are displayed on video screens that
preserve no information after a crash.
</P>
<P>
   As federal authorities reconstructed the final horrifying
seconds of the flight, safety and law enforcement officials said
that everything was normal on Oct. 31 as the flight reached its
33,000-foot cruising altitude. Then just after 1:49 a.m., things
went terribly wrong in less than 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual events began seconds after the pilot, el-Habashy,
briefly left the cockpit, the officials said. The other pilot
repeated quietly and calmly, ``Tawakilt ala Allah,'' according to
the officials. Intelligence officials said that the phrase has no
known connection to any political or terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
   At about this time someone shut off the autopilot. The officials
said that the voice recorder's cockpit microphones picked up
el-Habashy saying in Arabic, ``What's going on?'' or ``Let's fix
this.'' Seconds later the plane began its steep descent to less
than 17,000 feet. It is unclear at exactly what point in the flight
that the two men spoke, but the flight data recorder showed that 8
seconds after the autopilot was disconnected, the plane began its
plunge.
</P>
<P>
   During the steep dive, the two parts of the tail that control
whether the plane dives or climbs moved in an unusual fashion.
Although in normal flight operations the two parts move in tandem,
investigators said they were initially baffled by the movement of
the left and right parts of the tail in opposite directions. The
officials now hypothesize that one pilot may have been desperately
trying to pull out of the dive while the other pilot was pushing
the plane's controls down. Such an action would overcome the link
that usually moves the two surfaces in tandem and would position
them in opposite ways.
</P>
<P>
   Near the bottom of the dive, someone turned the engine control
levers to the cut off position _ a possible, but not definitive
clue that a struggle was underway in the cockpit that ended when
someone shut down the engines.
</P>
<P>
   After reaching the bottom of its dive, the plane regained
altitude, climbing several thousand feet until it stalled _
reaching a speed too slow to remain airborne. The aircraft then
apparently broke and fell into the Atlantic, killing all 217 people
on board.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging evidence indicates that while recovery operations
will continue at the site of the crash, 60 miles south of
Nantucket, American and Egyptian investigators will compile highly
detailed biographical accounts of the EgyptAir crew members, all of
whom had recently undergone medical and psychological evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it was unclear whether investigators had gleaned most
of what they expect to extract from the voice and data recorders.
They initially said there was nothing on the tape to indicate a
criminal act. But in more thorough analysis and evaluations by
Arabic speakers, their conclusions have changed dramatically. And
some officials cautioned that further analysis might lead them to
still different theories about the cause of the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
