<HEADLINE>
DR. KING'S WIDOW TESTIFIES IN A CIVIL TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., in 2nd graf, spelling of Loyd is CQ) 
(mcd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ Coretta Scott King testified before a jury for the
first time Tuesday about the assassination of her husband, the Rev.
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., here 31 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King was the first witness in the wrongful death civil
trial of Loyd Jowers, a Memphis cafe owner, who once claimed on
television that he had been part of a conspiracy to kill the civil
rights leader. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King testified that her family believes the trial might
solve mysteries she believes still surround her husband's death.
``We're concerned with having the truth come out in a court of law
so that it can be documented for all,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages from Jowers and ``unknown
parties.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Earl Ray was convicted in the 1968 killing after pleading
guilty in 1969. He later recanted his confession, and spent the
rest of his life trying to get a new trial. Ray died in prison in
1998. His lawyer for the last 10 years of his life, William Pepper,
is representing Mrs. King and her four children in the trial.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the Kings have embraced Pepper's
theories, which point toward an intricate alleged conspiracy
involving a Memphis produce dealer, the Mafia, the Memphis police
and the Army. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jowers' lawyer, Lewis Garrison, in his opening statement, did
not refute the conspiracy claims, just the extent of his client's
involvement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some who have studied the King assassination say this trial is
not a sincere effort at finding the truth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
