<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-FORBES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE REPUBLICAN GROUP ADMONISHES FORBES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Iowa, N.H.) 
(sw) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a dispute that pits Steve Forbes against the Republican
Leadership Council, a moderate group that includes many supporters
of George W. Bush, the Forbes campaign said on Tuesday it would
file a complaint with the Federal Election Commission over
television advertisements by the council that are critical of
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The council is airing the advertisements, a spokesman said
Tuesday, because it fears that Forbes will attack other Republican
candidates, as he did Bob Dole in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Forbes has a track record of running negative ads which
proved, four years ago, to hurt the entire Republican Party,'' said
Mark Miller, executive director of the council, which raises money
for moderate Republicans. ``We do not want to see that happen to
Republicans this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements feature a woman who says that when Forbes ran
in 1996, she ``kind of liked him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But then he spent all his money tearing down his opponents,''
the woman says. ``He hurt the Republican Party.'' After warning
that Forbes ``might start it again,'' the woman says, ``Someone
needs to tell Steve Forbes that if he doesn't have anything nice to
say, don't say anything at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While the council does not endorse candidates, many on its board
are Bush supporters and Miller estimated that 60 to 70 percent of
its members back Bush. Forbes is aligned with the conservative wing
of the party.
</P>
<P>
   A council official, who asked not to be named, said: ``We had
reports that Forbes was going to go with ads critical of Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes has no attack advertisements on the air. He is
currently running three commercials _ one promoting his views on
taxes, another on Social Security and the third is biographical.
They do not mention any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign said it would file a complaint saying that
the council's $100,000 advertising campaign represents an ``excess
contribution'' to the Bush campaign. The council said the ads are
not campaign contributions, but ``issue advocacy'' advertising,
which are permitted by federal law as long as they do not directly
advocate the election or defeat of a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising is airing in Iowa, New Hampshire and Washington
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the advertisements Tuesday on the Today show,
Bush said he had not seen them, nor read about them.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican candidate, John McCain, sent a letter to the
council criticizing the advertising as a violation of campaign
finance law and urged that it be halted. ``I do not believe that
either Steve Forbes or his campaign have conducted themselves in
such a matter as to require your admonishment,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
