<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-ARTS-COLLEGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN COLLEGE FOR THE ARTS FACES LOSS OF U.S. MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ As a White Earth Chippewa, now 59 years old,
Catherine Ryker grew tired of minimum wage jobs and wanted to
become an art teacher. So she enrolled here in the Institute for
American Indian Arts, the only college of its kind in the country,
where Indians teach art and culture to Indians as a way to preserve
their ethnic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Jessie Ryker-Crawford, a former waitress who is 37,
has the same ambitions. On any given day, she sits beside her
mother in painting and drawing classes.
</P>
<P>
   But years from now, it remains a lingering question to Ms.
Ryker-Crawford, as well as to faculty members and other students at
the institute, whether Ms. Ryker-Crawford's children, Jason, who is
10, and Tonya, 7, will have the same opportunity as their mother
and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the budget now being finalized in Congress will
be the last to include support for the institute, $2.12 million for
2000. As a federally chartered two-year college now under the aegis
of the Interior Department, it has received taxpayer dollars since
opening as a high school in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the college has produced scores of artists,
curators and tribal leaders _ graduates who have earned higher
degrees, some of whom have helped Indian art become a $500 million
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ralph Regula of Ohio, chairman of the Interior
appropriation subcommittee, has vowed to end all federal support
for the institute. He insisted he has ``no personal animus'' for
the college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent a lot of money on Indian culture, in many
different ways,'' he said by telephone from Washington. ``It comes
to a point, do you assume it's in perpetuity or do you develop a
program that's self-sufficient?''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee decision has stung students, staff and faculty,
fueling bitterness and, as some see it, reinforcing an image of
American Indians as a throw-away culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hate them for their beliefs of who native people
are,'' Ms. Ryker-Crawford said. ``But there are a lot of
misconceptions. It angers me, but it saddens me more. I've never
seen students and staff work so hard in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Others took sharper aim at lawmakers. ``What they're saying is
that this school isn't valid; our culture isn't valid,'' said Mary
Young Bear, a Meskwaki from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's loss of federal support comes as administrators
are fighting to fulfill Regula's vision of a college that has a
broader appeal, offering a greater variety of courses in a more
spacious setting. A local business group has donated 140 acres for
a new campus.
</P>
<P>
   But growth has been a struggle. Annual enrollment remained
around 220 for a decade through the early 1990s. Then, the budget
cuts and management problems forced administrators to lay off more
than half the faculty and staff, which affected recruiting. This
year, about 135 students, who pay annual tuition of $10,000, take
classes from 11 full-time teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Construction has begun on buildings that will allow the college
to double its enrollment at the new location. Private donations,
like a recent $3 million gift from the American Indian College
Fund, are helping.
</P>
<P>
   But Della Warrior, president of the college, says she worries
that further belt-tightening could affect the quality of education
the college provides and discourage enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he really recognizes how integral art and
culture are to native American people to make a living and give
them future potential,'' Ms. Warrior said of Regula. ``Unless we
get major endowments and gifts, I don't see how we can continue to
operate.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lomahaftewa, a Hopi-Choctaw and a well-known American
Indian artist, was one of the institute's first students. After
receiving a master of fine arts degree from the San Francisco Art
Institute, she returned in 1976 to teach and remains on the
faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' she said of the federal budget cuts and the lawmakers
who enact them, ``this is like another broken treaty. Native
peoples have always been guaranteed education and health, but then
the programs are all cut back. They don't recognize native people
for who we are, America's first people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look how we're treated,'' she added. `'We take 10 steps
forward, then 20 steps back. To me, nothing has changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2141EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1886 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMERICAN-DANCE-$ADV21     11-16 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-DANCE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY OF PARTNERING BY AN ART AND A MEDIUM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There could be little argument that ``A Celebration
of 100 Years of American Dance on Film'' was one of the most wildly
improbable dance events of 1999. But the program also suggested
profound changes in the nature of dance in America, and in the
relationship between dance and the electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour event, presented in mid-October at the Juilliard
Theater, scampered from late 19th-century films by Thomas Edison of
antic and elegant black dancing to the cool hyper-acrobatics of
Elizabeth Streb in the 1990s. Blurring the distinction between art
and archive, the program featured mainstream film dance and
recorded dance, from early film experimentation with movement to
dance filmed for television.
</P>
<P>
   The film and video clips represented an adroit balancing of
social and theatrical dance, and of anecdote and history, by the
dance writer Marian Horosko and the Broadway choreographer and
director Donald Saddler, who put the program together with Theodore
S. Bartwink, the executive director of the sponsoring Harkness
Foundation for Dance.
</P>
<P>
   The event was also sponsored by the Dance Collection of the New
York Public Library for the Performing Arts. But what, as some in
the audience asked at the end, was it all in aid of?
</P>
<P>
   One of the great pleasures of ``A Celebration of 100 Years of
American Dance on Film'' was its rag-bag nature. The scraps got
decidedly less vivid and consequential toward the end, when Ms.
Horosko and Saddler seemed suddenly to feel that there was a
balance sheet to be filled with the names of all the worthy dance
enterprises of the 1980s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But there were gorgeous scraps of bright silk and nubbly wool to
be plucked from that bag in the first half of the evening, which
brought the program into the 1950s. The sheer volume and range of
dance represented in more than 70 film and video clips and
photographs was stunning. ``We've done so much,'' one dance
aficionado said simply as he left the theater.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, ballet was the only show in town. But it was a
foreign show, a matter mostly of exotic imports. There were few
American-born ballet stars and until the 1930s no ballet companies
founded by Americans. Modern dance was born, in America and Europe,
a decade or so into the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pioneers and major artists who made all this
possible were represented in ``A Celebration.'' There were also
rich revelatory glimpses of less familiar artists like the
modern-dance choreographer Helen Tamiris and the German
Expressionist Harald Kreutzberg. A purported Isadora Duncan wafted
among columns at an apparent garden party.
</P>
<P>
   And footage of solemn young women in 1930s classes at the
Bennington School of Dance, the forerunner of the American Dance
Festival, affirmed the do-or-die seriousness of the enterprise of
American modern dance a few decades later.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Celebration'' gave equal time to popular dance, from
ballroom and dancing parties to artists that ranged the hilarious
vaudeville artist Joe Frisco to James Cagney, a dancer of
exhilaratingly casual grace. Only in recent years, however, with
the elevation of indigenous and popular dance to high art, would a
performer like Frisco be considered an artist.
</P>
<P>
   There were hoedowns as choreographed by Michael Kidd in the 1954
film musical ``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers'' and as danced,
with charming sedateness, by Eleanor Roosevelt with young soldiers.
Frisco's gyrating legs and ground-hugging moves could be seen in
Bob Fosse's ``Steam Heat'' and in a Michael Jackson music video.
</P>
<P>
   A beautifully photographed film view of Bill ``Bojangles''
Robinson, that stage and film star of the 1920s and '30s, attested
to the technique and artistry of tap, reiterated in video of a
1990s performance by the Brooklyn-based Young Hoofers.
</P>
<P>
   The glories of film dance as conceived by Busby Berkeley and
Fred Astaire, whose ideas about dance and film were in themselves
so suggestively different, are a world apart from the cool,
deceptively dispassionate evocations of dance that survive from the
heyday of the Public Broadcasting System series ``Dance in
America'' in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Dance was once considered a comfortable part of popular culture,
at least in film. Anna Pavlova played a major role in a 1915
Hollywood-produced silent feature film. The dancing of the Nicholas
Brothers helped sell film musicals, and dance was the whole point
of film musicals by Berkeley, Astaire and Gene Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Every major American city may have its own ballet troupe today,
and often a few modern-dance groups as well, but as Kidd has
pointed out, choreography in today's mass-market films is mostly a
matter of the staging of shoot-'em-ups in action movies.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet was once filled with glamorous international stars, many
of whom were shown in ``A Celebration.'' That era has ended for
dance, paradoxically in a time when American culture has become
increasingly driven by larger-than-life personalities. The program
offered other reasons to mourn, among them the loss of the Joffrey
Ballet as the major and frequent rescuer of lost glories like
``Parade'' and ``The Green Table.''
</P>
<P>
   Public television is no longer able to afford the kind of
comprehensive recording of modern American dance history
exemplified by ``Dance in America.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also an increasing closeness between the dance and the
electronic media of film, video and, now, computer-generated
imagery. The use of film as a decorative component of live dance is
certainly not new. And the haunting ``Poem for the Theater No. 6,''
revived in September by Beverly Blossom, suggests that the
integration of dance and film was being imaginatively explored in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But seldom has electronic imagery been used with such
sophistication and profundity as in Merce Cunningham's ``Biped,''
presented this summer at the Lincoln Center Festival, and in the
central solo of Pina Bausch's ``Danzon,'' performed earlier this
month at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Electronically produced imagery were one with the movement,
intimately extending and reinforcing the central themes of the
choreography and of the essential, defining physicality of dance.
The appropriation of dance by film, as an equal partner in the
production of art and entertainment, was a glorious part of ``A
Celebration of 100 Years of American Dance.'' Today, perhaps, it is
dance that is appropriating film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
