<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 17
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MRSCLINTON-PALESTINE-NYT (moved on Thursday, Nov. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, Nov. 11,
about a visit by Hillary Rodham Clinton to the West Bank
misidentified the Palestinian health minister, who said to Mrs.
Clinton at a gathering of public health officials: ``I would like
to remind you of the words that you said to Israeli and Palestinian
children. Words that are inscribed in the hearts of all
Palestinians, when you told them that the path to a just and real
peace is the establishment of a Palestinian state.'' The minister
is Dr. Riad Zanoun. (Jihad Mashal, who also spoke, is an official
of a nongovernmental Palestinian health care organization.)
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-INTERNET-ACCESS-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Nov. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Nov.
10, about services that offer fast Internet connections misstated
the translation of A.D.S.L. It is an abbreviation for asymmetric
digital subscriber line, not asynchronous.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incompletely to the ownership of the
(AT)Home cable Internet service. AT&AMP;T is the largest shareholder,
not the only one.
</P>
</TEXT>
