<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     11-16 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT TAKES STAND IN EAST TEXAS DRAGGING DEATH CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A pale but clear-speaking Shawn Allen Berry
testified Tuesday that he initially lied to investigators about
running away when a black man was chained to his pickup because he
wrongly believed that merely being at the scene made him guilty of
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that he was now telling the truth, Berry admitted
driving James Byrd Jr., 49, out to a remote logging road with two
avowed white supremacists to drink beer. But Berry said he tried to
intervene when the other two attacked Byrd, then backed off and
offered no more help to Byrd because of ``paralyzing fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the battered victim was pushed toward Berry at one
point, he was able to jump out of the way by ``human nature,'' the
24-year-old cinema manager said during cross examination.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's is the third capital murder trial to stem from a 1998
torture slaying that has rocked this East Texas community of 7,100.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Ku Klux Klansmen John William King Jr., 25,
and Lawrence Russell Brewer, 32, were convicted and sentenced to
death for chaining Byrd behind a pickup and dragging him three
miles along a bumpy rural road.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in Berry's trial are expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Berry testified that while guzzling beer and cruising at 2:30
a.m. on June 7, 1998, he didn't think King posed a danger to Byrd
because his friend's threats and big talk over the years were never
followed up with action.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said that at one point he rushed between Byrd, who was
sitting in the passenger seat, and King, who was reaching in from
outside the truck. At that point, King warned Berry that he could
face the same fate if he tried to intervene, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry backed off, taking his friend's threat seriously because
King was now following through and actually assaulting someone, he
said. Fear paralyzed him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do anything more to stop it,'' Berry said, pausing
a moment with his head down before adding: ``I couldn't move. I've
never been in a position where I couldn't move before.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most emotional turn of his 41/2 hours of testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Berry spoke evenly, not losing composure when District Attorney
Guy James Gray expressed disbelief in his account and noted
inconsistencies. Berry was polite in his responses and referred
unerringly to the victim as ``Mr. Byrd.''
</P>
<P>
   In the high-ceiling courtroom, the defendant wore a white shirt
and muted pinstripe shirt. He had neat, close-cropped hair and a
pale baby face. Gone were the scruffy goatee and unruly hair shown
in his jail-house mug shot. His clothing covered several tattoos
but, unlike those of King and Brewer, they carried no racist
symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful-looking defendant testified about his star-crossed
life. His biological parents never married and he hadn't met his
Ohioan father until two weeks ago. Whereabouts of his mother,
described as wild, are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   His stepfather committed suicide when Berry was 17. He ran away
from an overbearing step-grandmother and dropped out of school
before completing 9th grade. At 17, he was arrested with King while
burglarizing a vending machine company and spent 90 days in jail
boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in the Byrd slaying two months before he was to
wed a former beauty queen and the mother of his 2-year-old son, who
had twice filed, then disavowed, domestic violence charges against
him.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney noted that Berry used the pronoun ``we''
45 times in his statements to investigators about the killing, but
in a ``60 Minutes II'' interview and on the stand, he used the word
``they.'' Berry said he always used ``they'' but contended that
interrogators who wrote out his accounts employed the word ``we.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry insisted that no one smoked at the scene where Byrd was
beaten and chained behind the pickup, and that cigarette butts
found with the DNA of the three whites apparently fell out of the
truck's ashtray at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Gray later said to reporters that butts found close to a circle
of Byrd's blood suggested that all three participated. Berry, while
not an avowed racist like the other two whites, might have been
drawn in by the sheer emotional force of a ``pack'' attacking its
prey, a variation of a thrill-seeking murder, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor also questioned whether Berry was so scared that
he ``wet his pants,'' as the defendant testified. Under
cross-examination, Berry said he nonetheless continued to wear the
same sodden Polo jeans and underwear until the next afternoon. An
FBI forensic expert testified earlier for the prosecution that he
detected only a ``dribble'' of urine on the jeans.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
