<P>
   (NYT6) PAMPANGA, Philippines -- Nov. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR NOV.
17 -- POLLUTION-II-3-BOS, 11-16 -- Epifania de Leon carries her
8-year-old daughter, Michelle, who looks like a child half her age.
She is unable to eat solid food and her legs are gaunt and
malformed. Her eyes and mouth widen, and her fists clench as she
repeatedly fends off spasms. She spends her days lying on a floor
or cradled in her mother's arms. Her family blames the contaminated
wells that continue to be used for drinking water. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MADAPDAP, Philippines -- Nov. 16, -- ADV. FOR NOV. 17 --
POLLUTION-II-2-BOS, 11-16 -- At the temporary evacuation center
adjacent to the former Clark Air Base, Digna Esuza, 8, washes
herself with water from a pump that is supposed to be shut off
because of high levels of toxins. Contaminated water at Clark is
just one trouble spot. Military records highlight scores of toxic
threats at Clark - once the largest Air Force base outside the
United States - as well as at the former Navy base at Subic Bay, 65
miles to the west. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MADAPDAP, Philippines -- Nov. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR NOV.
17 -- POLLUTION-II-1-BOS, 11-16 -- Elvira Taruc holds her
5-year-old son, Abraham, in a two-room cinder-block hospital where
he goes to get his medicine. Abraham and hundreds of other children
who were born or raised at nearby Clark Air Base tapped wells and
ate food grown in land that was contaminated with the residue of
chemicals, insecticides, and hazardous waste generated by the Air
Force, which abandoned the base in 1991. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROCKLAND, Mass. -- Nov. 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR NOV. 17 --
POLLUTION-I-3-BOS, 11-16 -- Bob Stanton, who has a rare form of
cancer, near the end of the runway at the former South Weymouth
Naval Air Station, about 600 yards from his house. The EPA says the
station is contaminated with volatile organic compounds and heavy
metals. Stanton, who has a very rare form of Ewing's Sarcoma cancer
called Primative Neuroectodermal Tumor and in remission after two
years of treatment, suspects a link to increased cancer rates in
the area. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MARION, Ohio -- Nov. 16, 1999 -- POLLUTION-I-2-BOS, 11-16
-- These three women, all former students at River Valley High
School, have been treated for leukemia. They are, from left, Kim
Tolnar, class of '82, Jami Cummings, class of '93, and Amanda
Lovett, a senior. After health officials began investigating the
cancer cases two years ago, the residents of Marion learned for the
first time that they unknowingly built their school on top of a
former US Army dumpsite filled with toxic waste. (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FALMOUTH, Mass. -- Nov. 16, 1999 -- POLLUTION-I-1-BOS,
11-16 -- Range Officer Glen Morin walks past UXOs (Unexploded
Ordinance) of mortar and anti-tank rounds on the firing range at
the Massachusetts Military Reservation. The EPA closed the range to
artillery and mortar fire in 1997. An estimated 50 million acres of
land in the United States have been used as bombing and target
ranges by the military. Cleaning up just five percent of the land
would cost $15 billion, according to the Defense Science Board, a
Pentagon advisory group. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
