<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MIDNITE-VULTURES-ALBU     11-16 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDNITE-VULTURES-ALBUM-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MIDNITE VULTURES': ROCK COMEDY WITHOUT PUNCH LINES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laughter is the immediate response to most of the songs on
Beck's sixth album, ``Midnite Vultures'' _ so much so that it could
be called a comedy record.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a comedy record in the sense that intelligent directors
make comedy films: it's one big aesthetic disposition, rather than
the series of bulletlike jokes on what are commonly called comedy
records by the likes of Adam Sandler and Chris Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnite Vultures'' is funny without making actual jokes. (It's
last track, ``Debra,'' is the only song with something resembling a
narrative.) Beck has a pitch-perfect ear for pop-music convention,
but ``Midnite Vultures'' presents a kaleidoscope of folly; it
doesn't stand still long enough to make single punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   If it had to be compared to a particular film comedy, it might
be Quentin Tarantino's ``Pulp Fiction,'' with its vivid language,
cartoonish exaggerations, sendups of eroticism and self-importance
and sequences of script and action that leave your jaw hanging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midnite Vultures'' (Geffen DGC 0694904852) is inscribed with
all of the above. And as with that movie, there are bound to be
critics soon accusing Beck of racialist caricature; he has never
gone so far before in the direction of mockery.
</P>
<P>
   But here, at last, is a rock star who is using irony the right
way. His appropriations from pop history are so precise that he
forces you to admire, rather than snicker at, the materials he is
working with.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to satirize something, one can assume that
there's something good in it, and through Beck's junk-shop overlay
of nonsense rhymes and funny sounds, you can feel the grooves; you
know he's paying respect. Above all this hovers a thesis that you
don't feel Beck is pushing on you, but it's there: most American
pop musicians these days, whatever their skin tone, are all in
pursuit of the same archetypes of sound and character. Race, as a
definer of what sort of song a person should sing, is more
meaningless than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, to be too hung up on this issue _ which really leaps out
at you by the album's fifth track, ``Hollywood Freaks'' _ is to
ignore what the album accomplishes. ``Midnite Vultures'' is a
ricochet ride through American pop from around 1975 to around 1995
(he seems to hesitate at lampooning the present), and somehow it
all arrives with one man's stamp.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Beck Hansen got to ``Odelay,'' his commercial and
critical breakthrough of 1996 in his mid 20s, he had created his
own style _ blithe, capricious folk songs joined to hip-hop
backbeats, with his messily-played acoustic guitar roughing up the
edges and shrewd samples offering the listener a thousand paths to
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mutations,'' from last year, took a left turn _ a mellower
mood, no samples and a few songs straightforward enough to be
covered by other, less pointedly ironic singers. But ``Midnite
Vultures'' makes all that came before sound primitive.
</P>
<P>
   You put on ``Midnite Vultures'' and you laugh, but what are you
laughing about? Is it karaoke-show laughter? Beck keeps a running
list of pop styles you haven't thought about for years, creating
loving quasi-parodies that enhance your memory of the styles and
thereby makes any casual radio listener over 25 feel like a
connoisseur. (You recognize them as styles, not as particular
songs: there's the slow-rolling mid-'90s West Coast funk in
``Hollywood Freaks,'' the robotic electro of Kraftwerk and Zapp in
``Get Real Paid,'' the voluptuous, passe beats of Tone Loc in
``Pressure Zone,'' the Mick Jaggerish falsetto in ``Debra''.)
</P>
<P>
   Is it a nervous laughter? Beck seems self-aware enough to
realize the danger in playing with stereotype yet still goes ahead
and appropriates some of Prince's most flamboyant musical gestures.
Or are you laughing because Beck is a Roberto Benigni-type _ a guy
with such strong charisma that he can't move a muscle without
seeming funny?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To get a better reading on Beck, we have to look at what's
around him. This has been a year of style-swapping in what we used
to refer to as the categories of black and white music. Many of the
new R-and-B songs by black artists are held together by
acoustic-guitar lines that sound lifted from James Taylor albums.
</P>
<P>
   Garth Brooks made a record (``Chris Gaines: Greatest Hits'')
that is more in keeping with black radio than any of Kid Rock's
kitschy pimp posturing. The white rap-metal bands Limp Bizkit and
Korn have gone multiplatinum by refashioning hip-hop as
stressed-out cries for help; they're using psychosis to try to top
their favorite music's boasts and beats.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's own mission of appropriation is broad, knowing, a little
bit sly. He doesn't have to worry about whether a certain phrase or
style fits his persona, because his is a persona of accretion, a
thousand voices bottled inside one guy's throat.
</P>
<P>
   There's a (italics)huge(end italics) amount of information
passing before your ears on ``Midnite Vultures.'' Produced by Beck
(with contributions from the Dust Brothers, Mickey Petralia and
Tony Hoffer), the album has sonic depth; with its samples and
background vocals and overlaid rhythms, it approximates the
experience of gazing at a stained-glass window.
</P>
<P>
   Beck has taken cheesiness-spotting to previously unscaled
heights: he revels in outdated rhythm-machine sounds, ``Sanford and
Son'' keyboards, an electronically altered chipmunk-voice asking
``do you want to feel this?'' But where all that ought to sound
shallow, he sees a greater purpose for it. He turns the details
into great pop: it makes you move, makes you sing.
</P>
<P>
   (This record will be a favorite at parties for a long time; some
of its choruses are as strong as any in pop.) He seems to want to
keep showing you how some cultural appropriation is natural and how
some is artificial, and puts both examples next to each other as
often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Beck is a slippery character. He seems to have a congenital
horror of appearing pretentious. (Last year, when he was still
making the album, he said that he was avoiding end-of-millennium
bombast by making a ``big, dumb pop record with dumb lyrics.'') He
never seems altogether serious about anything, but he knows a great
deal about what he doesn't want to be.
</P>
<P>
   So he doesn't invest his persona in any particular style; he's a
master at undercutting the grandeur of his own grand gestures.
Throughout ``Midnite Vultures,'' he'll be at work on a fairly
straightforward lyrical image or an acceptably soulful musical
gesture and then something steps in the way _ a word he thinks
hilarious, like ``garbageman'' or ``hot dog,'' a silly effect like
a psychedelic guitar squiggle. He'll throw a phrase at you that
seems to signify, then you realize it's just an exercise in trying
on someone else's voice.
</P>
<P>
   But as the best film comedies deal with something of substance
on a lower level _ middle-age unhappiness in ``Groundhog Day,''
delusions of grandeur in ``Rushmore,'' the tangle of American
interracial antagonism and jealousy in ``Pulp Fiction'' _ so does
``Midnite Vultures.''
</P>
<P>
   The substance is the funk, which is real; whatever Beck sings,
he sounds persuasive. He's working on a new paradigm in popular
entertainment: an ironist who serves the public instead of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know if I'm worth your time,'' he pleads in ``Get
Real Paid,'' and wouldn't you know, he seems to mean it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
