<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DOCUMENTARY-BURNS-     11-16 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOCUMENTARY-BURNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIC BURNS: FOR SIMILAR FILMMAKERS, A BROTHERLY INDIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mcd) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We would have to get to this eventually, so we might
as well get it out of the way now. The sibling rivalry thing.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Burns is the filmmaker who directed ``New York: A
Documentary Film,'' a 12-hour series on the history of New York,
which is being shown on the public broadcasting system this week.
He is the younger brother of Ken Burns, the better known
documentary filmmaker who gave us ``Baseball'' and ``The Civil
War.'' How do they get along?
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother lives in New Hampshire,'' Burns says.
</P>
<P>
   OK. But are they close?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a funny way. We're both so involved in our work. He
has an office in New York across from mine. We can go four months
without seeing each other. You can't not be close if you grow up in
the same room and are 18 months apart, but we're each reasonably
willful people and have in some ways gone our own way.''
</P>
<P>
   He seizes on something that sums it up, and which, in happy
addition, has to do with the subject he is trying to promote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philip Lopate had a great expression we used in the film. He
said New Yorkers cultivate a benign indifference for each other.
That's the way Ken and I are right now. It's kind of good to be
left alone and do what you each do. Like New Yorkers say: `Don't be
my friend. Leave me alone. Do whatever it is you want to do. Other
than that, get out of my face.'''
</P>
<P>
   Is it a surprise that a filmmaker who spends 12 hours on a
subject cannot give you a short, snappy, answer? Ric Burns, 44, who
spent many years pursuing a Ph.D., cannot respond to anything in a
cursory manner. His, you might say, is the graduate student style:
The way he dresses (blue work shirt and chinos) the way he comes at
a subject (more than you need to know, orally foot-noted, but
fascinating). Even his apartment, where his wife, Bonnie, a former
Canadian Broadcasting Corp. journalist, is amusing their young son,
Simon, is in student country, near Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Burns _ actually a Burns brothers _ documentary
style: sepia photo stills; period film clips, evocatively spotted
or faded; boldface names for narrators. Ken Burns went into the
business first, bringing Ric in later. (The younger Burns was the
co-producer of ``The Civil War.'') Since 1990, Ric Burns has worked
with other partners on several critically acclaimed documentaries,
including ``Coney Island'' and ``The Way West.'' ``New York,''
which Burns directed, co-produced (with Lisa Ades) and wrote (with
James Sanders), is his most ambitious project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It emerged out of a conversation James and I had 10 years ago,
when we got drunk in the Algonquin,'' Burns says. ``I had been
struck, ever since reading Robert Caro, with the idea that a city
could be a story. What was so remarkable was to discover there
 &UR; was &LR;  a story, the story of capitalism and democracy rising in
America. The Dutch came here not to practice religious freedom, but
to get rich, and because of that they didn't have any rules for
excluding people.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a Ric Burns documentary and a Ken Burns
documentary?
</P>
<P>
   Younger siblings, he said, probably ``tend to market themselves
as gloomier and more brooding.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``Ken is more attracted to stories that are
eventually triumphant: the Brooklyn Bridge. I was more interested
in the Donner Party: darker, more catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   The spelling of Burns' first name isn't an adorable affectation.
His given name is Eric, but his family called him Ric. Burns'
father was an anthropologist and professor at the University of
Delaware, as well as ``an obsessive photographer''; his mother was
a biologist. Ric Burns brings out a visual, a carefully preserved
issue of the National Geographic from 1959. It contains the one
story his father ever published, about an Alpine village in France.
There is also a picture of Burns' mother, holding Ken, who was then
2. She was given a diagnosis of metastatic breast cancer when Ric
Burns was 3, and she died when he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, Ken and I were constructed twins,'' Burns says. ``I
think because my mother knew she was dying, my parents were very
eager to bring me along as rapidly as they could. My mother taught
me to read at 4, I skipped second grade and went into the same
grade as Ken.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I found myself literally behind Ken. The most
ludicrous thing is a series of photographs of us in little gray
short pants and red bow ties. I think what we now know about child
rearing, they should have dressed Ken in purple corduroy and me in
orange plaid. It would have been better for individuation.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns had planned an academic life. He received a B.A. in
English literature from Columbia, a master's degree in philosophy
from Cambridge. Eventually, however, he found the academic world
claustrophobic. His brother invited him to work with him on ``The
Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked together five years,'' Burns says. ``If you wanted
to go to the best university and learn how to make a film, go and
make a film with my brother. It was the greatest experience in the
world, but having gone through it, you would not want to not
control the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken is not going to work for me and I'm not going to work for
him. Unfortunately, that rules out, for the near term,
collaboration. Though maybe each of us will change. It would be
interesting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
