<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRCRASH-PILOTS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-PILOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN IN COCKPIT OF EGYPTAIR 990 HAD SOLID EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With AIRCRASH, moved in `w' news file) 
 (nk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ As EgyptAir Flight 990 left New York's Kennedy
Airport shortly after midnight on Oct. 31, the three men in the
cockpit of the Boeing 767 covered a wide spectrum, and each
appeared to have solid credentials.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Ahmed el-Habashy, 57, was a family man who had two
wives, three children and a 26-year career spent entirely with
EgyptAir. The co-pilot, Adel Anwar, 36, was single, and had flown
for the airline for just five years. He was hurrying home to Cairo
to prepare for a marriage planned for the coming Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The third man, Gamil al-Batouti, 59, was not at the controls but
sitting in an observer's seat. He was nearing the customary
retirement age of 60, and was to end his career in March.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour into the flight, however, something went
wrong, and investigators are now concentrating their efforts on
determining whether it was Batouti, the veteran pilot who had
trained many of his country's pilots, who set into motion the
events that ultimately brought the plane crashing into the ocean,
killing all 217 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said that they have identified
Batouti's voice as that of the person in the co-pilot's seat, the
person who is heard on the cockpit voice recorder making a
reference to God. Investigators now strongly suspect that Batouti,
shortly after the plane's pilot briefly left the cockpit, then
initiated a set of actions that sent the plane into a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have cautioned that they are far from reaching
conclusions, and they have acceded to the wishes of the Egyptian
government that the voice recorder be analyzed further and that the
significance of the reference to God be interpreted more fully.
Certainly no one has offered any reason why Batouti or any other
member of the crew would have wanted to crash the plane.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week, Mohammed Fahim Rayan, the
chairman of EgyptAir, said that both the pilot and co-pilot,
habashy and Anwar, had been pronounced fit within the past five
months after undergoing what Rayan called rigorous psychological
checkups within the past five months. The airline executive was not
asked directly about Batouti, whose name surfaced as the focus of
the investigations only early Tuesday in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   But Rayan said that all pilots and other crew members are
required to submit to the test as part of an annual procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively little is at the moment known about the crew members
aboard, including Batouti. Batouti was married with E five
children, the eldest of whom was 21. He was scheduled to retire on
March 4, when he would have turned 60, and had been ``a little
depressed'' at the fact that he had never been promoted to captain,
according to Mark Abdelazim, a concierge at a Manhattan apartment
building who had befriended Batouti, as well as other EgyptAir
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to have made it, but he was a happy person,''
Abdelazim said.
</P>
<P>
   Batouti, a former Air Force aviation instructor who joined
EgyptAir only in 1987, had told friends that Flight 990 would be
his last before retirement, according a report Tuesday in the
Egyptian newspaper Al Akhbar.
</P>
<P>
   Batouti was seated in the cockpit along with habashy and Anwar
at the time of takeoff, according to Abdelazim Sedki, who is
director of media and marketing for EgyptAir. But habashy and Anwar
were acting as pilot and co-pilot, while Batouti was sitting in one
of two observer's seats, Sedki said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two men are required to pilot a 767, under standard
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to habashy, Anwar and Battouti, the Egyptair crew
members traveling on the plane included five other qualified
pilots, three of whom were simply hitching a ride back to the
airline's home base.
</P>
<P>
   In all public statements so far, EgyptAir officials have said
they saw no reason to suspect wrongdoing by any of the assigned
pilots. At the news conference last week, Rayan, the chairman of
the state-run airline, said that Habashy had been declared to fit
to fly on Oct. 10 and that Anwar had passed his most recent exam,
sometime last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In requiring that the pilots and other crew members undergo
annual tests, Rayan insisted, the airline treats employees in
sensitive positions with the same kind of prudence that it does
bomb threats. ``They have to be checked,'' Rayan said.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming days, investigators will be seeking to learn
everything they can about Batouti, as well as the other crew
members. Family members will be interviewed. Flying records will be
checked. For the moment, though, investigators have no solid notion
of why Batouti might have taken the action they think the voice and
data recorders indicate he did.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Wasef, a cook at a restaurant near the Manhattan hotel
where many EgyptAir pilots stayed when in New York, said he had
known Batouti casually. He said Batouti had brought his wife and
young daughter to the United States early last summer in an efort
to get medical care for the young girl.
</P>
<P>
   Wasef said he was aware of Batouti's pending retirement, but
that he had seen him briefly the day of the flight and noticed
nothing remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was willing to live another life of doing nothing but
taking care of other business,'' Wasef said. ``He had plans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
