<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAPHONE-MANNESMANN-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEEKING MANNESMANN, VODAFONE CONTEMPLATES 2-TIER STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Brushing aside a legal challenge to its advisers and
the rejection of a $106.4-billion offer over the weekend, the
mobile phone giant Vodafone Airtouch PLC said Tuesday that it would
present a sweetened bid for Mannesmann AG later this week, and was
prepared to make a hostile move on the German company if that
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, sensing that a hostile bid was looming, drove down
Vodafone's stock price in heavy trading more than 7 percent, to
2.7175 pounds, or $4.40. But Mannesmann's shares soared intraday to
2.175 euros _ 14.5 euros above Vodafone's previous offering price _
before falling back to end the day's trading in Frankfurt at 207.65
euros, or $214.46.
</P>
<P>
   The market behavior of the two stocks presented Vodafone chief
executive Christopher Gent with what analysts regarded as a tricky
choice. A takeover of Mannesmann would make Vodafone _ already the
global wireless leader _ one of the world's biggest
telecommunications companies with dominance in Europe's
fast-growing wireless market and powerful positions in the United
States and the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost could make that sort of move perilous, since a
slide in Vodafone's stock price would render a hostile bid more
expensive and would risk alienating its own investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weaker Vodafone Airtouch shares are, the deeper it will
have to dig and the less attractive the deal will look to its
existing shareholders,'' said Nigel Hawkins, an analyst with the
brokerage firm Williams de Broe. ``It's a desperately difficult
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wight, an analyst with Commerzbank in London, said a
hostile bid was ``not going to be very pretty in the near term, but
the strategic rationale for doing it is so strong that it's the
price they may feel they have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fear that Vodafone will have to pay a heavy
premium,'' said John Jensen of Salomon Smith Barney. ``If their bid
doesn't succeed, it'll be negative, and if it does and it's too
expensive, that will be negative, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone and Mannesmann have been partners for years in Germany,
Italy and France. But when the German company reached an agreement
to acquire Orange PLC, Britain No. 3 wireless operator, last month,
it became a competitor on Vodafone's home territory. Gent
complained at a news conference Tuesday that Mannesmann had not
consulted him about that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Mannesmann's $33 billion purchase of Orange led to speculation
that a hostile bid by Vodafone was imminent, particularly after
Mannesmann rejected the $106.4 billion proposal made Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle intensified, Mannesmann sought a High Court
injunction preventing Vodafone's main advisers, the Wall Street
powerhouse Goldman, Sachs, the leading investment banker in Europe,
from advising it. Goldman's objections to an injunction are to be
heard Thursday and it has voluntarily suspended its service until
then.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, Gent argued that a combination of
Vodafone and Mannesmann had ``compelling logic'' because it would
mean control of Europe's biggest wireless markets with 30 million
customers and would create savings of $800 million in 2003 and $970
million in 2004.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Vodafone's initial bid was made directly to Mannesmann
chief executive Klaus Esser, Gent said a new bid would be presented
to Mannesmann's supervisory board Friday.
</P>
<P>
   German supervisory boards include labor representatives,
managers and outside directors, and they set the broad outlines of
company policy. Vodafone executives indicated that they believed an
approach to Mannesmann's supervisory board might elicit a more
sympathetic response than Esser's outright rejection of the earlier
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope that the supervisory board sees the logic of
putting the businesses together,'' Peter Bamford, chief executive
of Vodafone's British division, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Arun Sarin, chief executive of Vodafone's U.S., Asia and Pacific
division, said in an interview that ``we would very much like for
this to be a friendly transaction,'' adding, ``There is no need for
this to be hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   If the approach to the supervisory board failed, Gent told
reporters, ``We're prepared, if necessary, to proceed with an
unsolicited bid.''
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a successful hostile takeover in Germany,
and Mannesmann is protected by a company regulation that no
shareholder can control more than 5 percent of voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gent said he would canvass his company's shareholders over the
next two days before deciding at a Vodafone board meeting on
Thursday how much to bid.
</P>
<P>
   The offer made Sunday valued Mannesmann at 203 euros a share, or
$209.65 at current rates, and offered 43.7 Vodafone shares for each
Mannesmann share. Analysts now forecast that Vodafone's revised
offer will have to be in the region of 240 euros, or $247.87, a
share to interest Mannesmann stockholders. That would value
Mannesmann in the region of $130 billion, making an offer the
largest hostile bid ever.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in Mannesmann's share price has partly reflected
speculation that other companies might join with Vodafone to make a
bid, possibly Bell Atlantic Corp., a Vodafone partner in the United
States. But Bell Atlantic chief executive Ivan Seidenberg said
Tuesday that his company was not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Gent disclosed his intentions Tuesday as Vodafone announced a
113 percent gain in first-half earnings, to $1.42 billion. The
results exclude the costs of Vodafone's merger in January with
Airtouch of San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
