<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-MYERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYERS HAS FOUND NICHE WITH GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When the Los Angeles Galaxy's Roy Myers' name
came up in trade talks earlier this season, the last place the
former New York/New Jersey striker wanted to play was in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to mention his name, but someone on the team in
New York told me, `Don't go to L.A. because there are too many
cliques on the team,' '' Myers said. ``They said it would be
difficult to break in.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers didn't get his wish and struggled early with his new
teammates. But in L.A., he's back playing his familiar midfield
position and producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a striker,'' Myers said. ``My physical build doesn't
permit me to be a forward; you have to be a little stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the midfield, I can see everyone in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade certainly has paid off. The Galaxy is 14-5 since
acquiring Myers, who finished the season with four goals and seven
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I have a lot of confidence from the players and the
coaches,'' Myers said. ``I'm feeling better and better each week.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's even formed his own clique, albeit one that only
operates on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos struggled after
fellow playmaker and defensive specialist Martin Machon left to
play in Mexico. Cienfuegos already was a marked man, but without
any help, he also was an easy man to mark.
</P>
<P>
   That changed when Myers arrived in July.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start in Los Angeles, Myers has adjusted and become
a perfect complement to Cienfuegos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has definitely given me a helping hand,'' Cienfuegos said.
``I was one of the happier people when he arrived because he helped
me with the attack, and we complement each other well.''
</P>
<P>
   With two playmakers in the middle, United's Richie Williams, who
is responsible for shutting down the opposing team's top player,
could be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Roy is very skillful one-on-one,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi
Schmid. ``He can beat people on the dribble and make something out
of nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's on defense where the 30-year-old Myers' work is often
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying all along that the one guy who really doesn't
get a lot of mention and is a very, very key player and maybe the
key in this game is Roy Myers,'' said Galaxy assistant coach Ralph
Perez. ``We know what he can do offensively, but it's the little
things he does on the other end that make him complete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
