<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CY-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S UNANIMOUS: MARTINEZ WINS AL CY YOUNG AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez became only the third pitcher to win Cy Young
awards in both leagues when he was given the American League honor
unanimously Tuesday. Martinez figured that would happen, after he
went 23-4 with a 2.07 earned run average for the Boston Red Sox and
established himself as the game's most dominant pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The real mystery is whether he will win the most valuable player
award, something that pitchers have done only 18 times before. The
results of that voting will be announced Thursday; Martinez is
considered a front-runner, along with Cleveland's Roberto Alomar
and Manny Ramirez, Ivan Rodriguez of the Texas Rangers, Boston's
Nomar Garciaparra and the Yankees' Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley was the last pitcher to win both the Cy Young
and the MVP in the same season, in 1992; only nine pitchers have
done so since 1956, the first season of the Cy Young award.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who seemed headed for a 30-victory season before he
was sidelined by shoulder soreness in July, received all 28
first-place votes for the Cy Young award this year, for 140 points.
Mike Mussina of the Baltimore Orioles finished second with 53
points, and Mariano Rivera, the Yankees' closer who did not allow a
run for the final two and a half months of the regular season, had
27 points for third place. Two writers in each of the 14 American
League cities vote on the award, picking first, second and third
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much expected it, but it's always nice to receive an
award like this,'' said Martinez, who won the National League Cy
Young award in 1997 with the Montreal Expos. Randy Johnson _ who
was named the NL Cy Young award winner for 1999 on Monday _ and the
Hall of Famer Gaylord Perry are the only other pitchers to win the
award in both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's earned run average was nearly one and a half runs
lower than Mussina's 3.44, which was second in that category, and
nearly three runs lower than the league ERA of 4.86. He averaged
13.2 strikeouts per nine innings; Anaheim's Chuck Finley was
second, with 8.44. When Martinez struck out 17 batters in a game
against the Yankees in September, allowing one hit and no walks _
the most strikeouts ever in a game pitched against the Yankees _
David Cone and others remarked that it was the best pitching
performance they had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope I'm able to do it again, and improve on it,'' said
Martinez, who turned 28 in October. ``I don't see why not. I'm
still young.''
</P>
<P>
   After Martinez was introduced as the Cy Young award winner
Tuesday, in a conference call with reporters, many of the questions
he answered were about Thursday's MVP announcement. Martinez
himself said the MVP award ``would mean a lot, probably more than
the Cy Young award.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players _ particularly position players _ believe that
pitchers should not be considered for the MVP award, because the
best pitcher can be honored with a Cy Young award, and because
pitchers do not play every day.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez disagrees with the premise that pitchers cannot be the
most valuable player. ``I don't see why not,'' he said.
``Otherwise, we should be erased from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win it, fine. If I don't, fine. There's no crying in
baseball. But they shouldn't discriminate against anyone for their
position.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox went 24-5 (.828) in games started by Martinez; their
record in the games he did not start was 70-63 (.526). Only three
NL pitchers have won both the Cy Young and MVP awards _ Don
Newcombe in 1956, Sandy Koufax in 1966 and Bob Gibson in 1968 _
while Denny McLain (1968), Vida Blue (1971), Rollie Fingers (1981),
Willie Hernandez (1984), Roger Clemens (1986) and Eckersley have
done so in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that if he were voting, he would pick Garciaparra
for MVP. The Boston shortstop was the anchor of the Red Sox lineup,
winning the batting title with a .357 average, driving in 104 runs
and collecting 190 hits even though he played in just 135 games.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar appeared to play with joy for the first time since his
spitting incident with Umpire John Hirschbeck in 1996. He batted
.323, with a league-high 138 runs, as well as 120 RBI., and played
defense worthy of another Gold Glove award.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, the Indians' cleanup hitter, drove in 165 runs, best in
the league, and hit .333. Rodriguez won another Gold Glove for his
defense and hit .332. The Yankees had the best record in the league
and Jeter was the team's best everyday player, topping the league
with 219 hits and finishing second to Garciaparra with a .349
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez strained his back pitching in the playoffs, dominating
the Yankees in Boston's only victory in the AL Championship Series
in spite of his ailment. He said he has been getting regular
treatment for his injury in the off-season, indicating that he will
be ready for the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
