<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PRICELINE-AIRTICKETS-     11-16 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICELINE-AIRTICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE BIG AIRLINES JOIN OTHERS ON PRICELINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Priceline.com, the online company that lets consumers bid for
everything from airline tickets to cars and groceries, has signed
up three of the nation's top six airlines, in effect doubling the
number of airline seats it can sell.
</P>
<P>
   By signing up the carriers _ No. 1 United Airlines, No. 2
American Airlines and No. 6 US Airways _ Priceline is now working
with eight of the nine largest U.S. carriers. Other U.S. carriers
working with Priceline are America West, Delta, Continental,
Northwest and TWA; 20 foreign lines also participate.
</P>
<P>
   Airline tickets were the first merchandise Priceline sold when
it began operations in April 1998. Prospective buyers submit an
offer for a ticket online; if their price is accepted, they must
purchase the ticket. Buyers also must be flexible about their
departure time, and be willing to make a connection en route. Those
conditions have made Priceline's service far more practical for
leisure travelers than for those flying on business.
</P>
<P>
   Although Priceline has insisted from the start that its ticket
program would help airlines get rid of unsold seats, most major
airlines resisted cooperating with the company, supposedly because
they were unwilling to turn over control of their inventory to a
third party. Initially, only TWA and America West, among the
smallest of the nation's major airlines, worked with Priceline.
Then last summer, Delta joined up, and was followed by Northwest
and Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Braddock, chairman and chief executive of Priceline,
said the decision by American, United and US Airways to join forces
with the online company represented an endorsement of Priceline's
success. According to Braddock, Priceline's weekly sales of airline
tickets have increased tenfold since January; the company sold
5,000 tickets a week at the beginning of the year and now sells
more than 50,000 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Braddock, who said Priceline's airline program generated 80
percent of the company's total revenues, also predicted the
addition of the new airlines would create ``dramatically better
results'' for the airline program. And he said the expanded airline
program would lure more customers and create more opportunities to
sell them Priceline's other services.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Harris, airline analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, said the
decision by American, United and US Airways to participate proved
that the company was ``an important distribution channel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past airlines felt they could ignore it,'' he said,
``but that hurt them, and now they want in on it.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its agreements with the three airlines, Priceline has
restructured warrant agreements with all its U. S. airline
participants to give them equity positions close to the size of
their share of the domestic market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
