<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1932 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-YOUNG-HUNTERS-1STLD-W     11-16 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-HUNTERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-745(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRA AND STATE WILDLIFE AGENCIES PROMOTE HUNTING BY CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ore., Texas, N.Y., Conn., Mass.)  (subs 14th graf for additional info on NRA grants) 
(ART ADV: Photos (NYT8, NYT9) were sent on Nov. 15 to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTER, N.J. _ Thirty-one hunters in camouflage pants and
orange vests gathered just after dawn on a recent Saturday morning
at a state preserve here, sipping from steaming cups, munching
doughnuts and talking about barrel gauges and bird dogs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a quintessential fall scene, except that the cups
contained cocoa, not coffee, and these hunters were boys and girls,
many just 10 years old and some shorter than their shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   They were waiting to follow grown-up guides into the Black River
Wildlife Management Area to shoot pheasant _ five dozen farm-raised
birds that volunteers had deposited in fields there an hour
earlier. On a patchwork of other state preserves across New Jersey,
nearly 500 other children were doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   It was Take a Kid Pheasant Hunting Day, an event run since 1996
by the New Jersey Division of Fish, Game and Wildlife, and partly
paid for by the National Rifle Association Foundation, an arm of
the gun lobby. (The state supplied the wardens and the land; the
gun foundation paid for the birds and the shotgun shells.
Volunteers from New Jersey hunting clubs supplied the dogs and the
doughnuts.)
</P>
<P>
   Shooting programs for children are nothing new; the NRA and
private gun clubs have had them for generations. In recent years,
state wildlife agencies around the country have run special youth
hunts for an assortment of game, including wild pigs, rabbits,
ducks and deer. But the New Jersey pheasant shoot was an example of
a newer and growing phenomenon _ of public state wildlife agencies
and the gun lobby working hand in hand to promote hunting among
children.
</P>
<P>
   The public agencies and private group say they are motivated by
the same goal: to shore up hunting's popularity, which has been
slowly declining in the 1990s, according to recent federal and
state hunter surveys. The trend has left gun groups anxious to find
new members and state wildlife agencies _ whose budgets are almost
entirely dependent on license fees and income from an 11 percent
federal tax on guns and ammunition distributed to the states _
scrambling for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shooting sports are like any other endeavor _ youth is our
future,'' said William Poole, director of education and training
for the NRA. ``The state agencies understand that same
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoting hunting among young people, he added, ``is mutually
beneficial to all of us, and to meeting all of our missions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun makers are chipping in, donating hundreds of ``youth-size''
shotguns over the last few years to state agencies for children's
shooting clinics and hunter training.
</P>
<P>
   But animal rights and gun control groups have sharply criticized
the state-run youth hunting programs, saying they are designed to
create new interest in guns just as the country is grappling with a
spate of shootings by children and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we head into a new century,''said Stuart Chaifetz, the
founder of Honor and Non-Violence for Animals, a New Jersey animal
rights group, ``do we really want to have the state teaching kids
that shooting is fun?''
</P>
<P>
   National gun control groups like the Violence Policy Center have
criticized the flow of public money to private hunting initiatives
for children. For example, in 1993, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service was widely criticized for giving a $230,000 grant to the
National Shooting Sports Foundation, a private group representing
gun makers, to create and distribute to schools a videotape
promoting the role of hunting in wildlife management.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been little public debate about the flow of money
in the other direction _ from the private NRA Foundation to public
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the flow is still a trickle. Most youth
shooting programs sponsored by the NRA are run by private groups,
like the Boy Scouts, Jaycees or shooting clubs. Since 1993, the NRA
Foundation has awarded more than 3,000 grants totaling $21 million
to such groups. But since 1996, NRA grants ranging from $1,000 to
$10,000 have gone to state-run youth hunting programs in Oregon,
Texas, New Jersey and a few other states, NRA officials say, and
this kind of partnership is growing.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey game officials say they are happy to accept the
money. ``The NRA promotes safe and responsible gun handling,'' said
Patrick Carr, the state's hunter education administrator, ``and
members raise money so the foundation can support programs like
ours. We're showing these youths the proper way to use a firearm in
a legal activity _ hunting. If you don't show them the right way,
that's the wrong move.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Texas Parks and Wildlife Commission recently used a $10,000
NRA grant to help buy and develop software for a big-screen hunting
simulator that is trucked to schools and county fairs, where
children and adults can fire virtual guns at virtual game.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife has received money
from the NRA and Pheasants Forever, a private pheasant-hunting and
conservation group, for its annual pheasant hunts for children.
</P>
<P>
   The pheasant group has bought farm-raised birds for the
children's hunts, while the NRA grants have been used to buy
ammunition for shotgun clinics that are offered on the same day,
said Tony Burtt, the outdoor skills coordinator for the Oregon
wildlife agency.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, New Jersey, New York, Connecticut and Texas are among
more than three dozen states that have received donated batches of
50 small shotguns for use in clinics and hunter education programs
from H &AMP; R 1871, a gun maker in Gardner, Mass., which specializes
in small firearms for children and women.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Sharpless, a senior vice president at the eight-year-old
company, said the donation program was focused on improving gun
safety, not on promoting gun use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not courting kids into the shooting sports,'' he said.
``These are kids whose families are already hunting. The goal is to
facilitate safety. You wouldn't put a 6-year-old child on a 26-inch
mountain bike.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In late October, Connecticut held its annual youth pheasant hunt
on state property in East Windsor, north of Hartford. The
Connecticut program is much smaller than New Jersey's and is not
underwritten by the NRA. Even so, it generated its share of
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 20 or so people who picketed at the entrance to the
Dr. John E. Flaherty Field Trial area outnumbered the seven hunters
between the ages of 12 and 16 who spent several hours stalking
pheasants with volunteer adult guides. As the children arrived, the
protesters chanted, ``Shame, shame.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this does is provide living targets for these kids and
increase their comfort level with firearms,'' said William Manetti,
52, of New Haven, Conn., a founder of the Animal Rights Front, a
small New Haven group.
</P>
<P>
   David Leff, Connecticut's deputy commissioner of environmental
protection, defended the program. He said the program provided a
substitute for the kind of guidance that used to come from older
relatives but is fading.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The annual youth pheasant hunt in New Jersey, held Nov. 6, one
week before the regular pheasant-hunting season, which began Nov.
13, has been more popular every year, said Carr, the state hunter
education administrator, growing from 143 participants in 1996 to
around 500 this year.
</P>
<P>
   On this Saturday morning at the 3,000-acre preserve in Chester,
Carr and several other state officials and volunteers checked in a
steady flow of children.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone had learned of the hunts in the annual state
booklet announcing hunting regulations and season dates. Many of
the children, including several girls, said they had grown up
planning to follow their fathers into the field. Michael Meola,
from Denville, said he enjoyed taking his son, also named Michael,
on the children's hunts because they were safe and uncrowded.
``It's controlled,'' Meola said. ``Not like when you take them out
on opening day with a million guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   All of them had junior hunting licenses pinned to the back of
their orange vests and had taken the mandatory 10-hour state
hunting education course. Several boys restlessly hefted their
shotgun cases while others were told by their fathers to not touch
their guns until cleared to pick them up.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, out in the fields, volunteers were opening
crates, pulling out the pheasants, then _ holding the birds by the
legs _ spinning them to make them dizzy, so they would stay put in
the grass until flushed out.
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot, the pointers and setters owned by volunteer
dog handlers eagerly paced to and fro.
</P>
<P>
   Standing atop a picnic table, Carr gave a briefing on safety
rules. ``Keep your muzzle up,'' he said. ``Don't shoot a bird on
the ground; don't shoot cripples. The dogs will get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have a fun day, but be safe and responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the children lined up to receive six shells apiece.
</P>
<P>
   As the last morning mist evaporated, the group headed off to the
far corner of the state tract, which winds along the Black River.
Groups of four children followed the dog handlers to separate
fields, each of which had been stocked with two pheasants for each
young hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Carr explained that the stocking helped ensure that at least a
few children would kill a bird. ``We can't pull the trigger for
them, but we can certainly put the bird out in front of them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Konboz, 11, of Hawthorne lugged her father's full-size
12-gauge shotgun as she and her father, Anthony, and two boys
followed Scott Wardrop, of Wayne, his dog, Limestone Annie, and his
daughter Kristen, 13.
</P>
<P>
   The dog, scurrying through the weedy field, flushed out the
first bird after about 20 minutes, but it alighted in a tree before
Mary, who was given the first shot, could pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't we shoot it in the tree?'' asked Ray Jensen, 11, of
Brodheadsville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Ray Sr., hesitated, then said: ``We can't. It's not
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The group hiked on, with Annie weaving ahead, nose to the
ground. Sporadic gunfire came from adjacent fields. Another
pheasant burst from the bushes. But Mary hesitated _ appropriately
_ as the bird curled around behind her over the heads of the
hunting party, eliciting a wave of quick dives for cover.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning progressed with no kills by Wardrop's group of
hunters, Konboz said their low success rate proved that this was a
sport, not a slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   During a break, the children rested on the grass, their guns
around them, drinking from cartons of fruit punch and talking about
Harry Potter.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, nobody in Wardrop's group had killed a bird, and
only one had pulled a trigger.
</P>
<P>
   When all the groups returned to check out with officials after
the two-hour hunt, the hunters learned that other groups had had
better luck. Carr noted that 11 of the 64 stocked birds had been
shot, with one more killed by a diving red-tailed hawk.
</P>
<P>
   The successful young hunters pulled their pheasants from pouches
to pose for pictures. One bird exploded to life and burst into the
bushes. It was retrieved by a dog and killed by one of the dog
handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dara, chairman of the New Jersey Federation of Sportsmen's
Clubs, a private group that provided most of the volunteers, said
anti-hunting sentiment just stiffened the resolve of hunters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at 30 years ago versus today,'' he said. ``Then, you
still had kids out in the field with their fathers and you had very
little violence in society, even though there were more guns per
person. Just look at things now.''
</P>
<P>
   He said animal rights demonstrators even showed up at a recent
fishing tournament sponsored by the sportsmen's federation. ``Can
you believe it _ fish rights?'' Dara said. ``But that's all right.
They just help unite us.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 11 a.m., the first round of young hunters and their
fathers headed home, some to cook their birds, others to talk about
the ones that got away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
