<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1936 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-KAROYLI-HNS &LR;      11-16 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KAROYLI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Coming in second in the Pan Am Games was a warning sign. A
last-place finish at the gymnastics world championships confirmed
suspicions that something was amiss.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What to do, then, with the 2000 Summer Olympics coming up fast?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we needed was to draw on the most experienced, most
successful coach in the world,'' Bob Colarossi, president of USA
Gymnastics, said Tuesday. ``We're lucky we had that available to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Bela Karolyi is back, and the next 10 months figure
to be lively as the road to Sydney comes through Houston after all.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi, 57, returns in a different capacity, not as coach but
as national team coordinator. That new role was announced Tuesday
by USA Gymnastics, which has turned to the Romanian-born,
Houston-based legend to resurrect a program that has fallen on hard
times since winning team gold at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi will design the overall training program and oversee
preparations for the U.S. effort in Australia. He also will serve
as adviser to the individual coaches, direct the team's final
preparations and have a key role in determining the composition of
the team.
</P>
<P>
   So much for that retirement he announced after Atlanta. Now,
with less than a year to get ready, Karolyi will attempt to whip a
young, inexperienced team into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting 2000 to be the greatest year of my coaching
career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi has been a member of the U.S. coaching staff at the last
four Olympics. Since Atlanta _ where he directed a group that
included Dominique Moceanu and Kerri Strug to the team title _ he
has managed grass-roots gymnastics camps and clinics at his
500-acre ranch near Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the individual coach system the United States
employed so successfully in '96 has produced fractious philosophies
and subpar results. After finishing last among six teams at worlds,
USA Gymnastics acknowledged a different approach was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi might not have the title of coach, but it is clear who
is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, the athletes will be directed toward the same
goal,'' Karolyi said. ``We'll coordinate their effort, not
chaotically go that way or that way. We want to guide based on a
common understanding: Our focus is not exclusively national or
Olympic trials, but the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Karolyi will conduct periodic camps in the months
leading to the Olympics. He'll hold an introductory session in
Tulsa, Okla., next month for the 14 to 16 top prospects and their
coaches, with subsequent gatherings at his ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Given his bombastic nature, Karolyi's presence makes him the
dominant personality in just about any undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   But Colarossi and Karolyi insisted Sydney is not bound to become
Karolyi's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the concerns of the individual coaches would be
exactly that question,'' Karolyi said. ``They deserve credit for
their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not even a question that I'm going to step on the floor
and take anything away from them. What I'm ready to do at this time
_ what I consider very important _ is to coordinate the coaches'
efforts, to bring them together, to make them understand certain
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm called `coordinator,' not `national team
coach.'''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi said he had been approached a year ago about assuming
some role with the struggling national team but had rejected the
idea because, ``At that time, I didn't feel there was so much
need.'' The continued demise of the program changed his mind, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi rose to international prominence as coach of 1976
Olympic gold-medal winner Nadia Comaneci, who scored the sport's
first perfect 10. Over the years, he has produced 28 Olympians,
nine Olympic champions, 15 world champions and six U.S. national
champions.
</P>
<P>
   His golden touch will be put to the test again as he tries to
restore the U.S. program to the heights of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '96, we had a very experienced, seasoned group of
athletes,'' Colarossi said. ``This group of athletes has a lot
lower level of experience, although they have great talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system Bela is going to put into place is going to do two
things: It's going to shore up whatever deficiencies they have, and
it's going to allow them to draw from the confidence and experience
that Bela just possesses naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi said he will not take on any full-time students in
preparation for Sydney, citing ``an immense conflict of interest. I
would not be able to do that, and I would not be willing to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Trials are in August in Boston. After a few days
off, the team will come to Houston for a final training camp before
leaving for Australia. In the interim, Karolyi clearly has his work
cut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy thing was to sit back and wait for better results in
Sydney,'' Colarossi said. ``But our feeling was that we owed it to
everyone who invests in our sport to try and step in and make a
change and make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Karolyi, as the summer of 2000 suddenly gets a good deal
more interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
