<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXAS-EXECUTION-TEX     11-16 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDEMNED MAN RESISTS GUARDS BEFORE EXECUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Desmond Jennings, condemned for a double
killing at a drug haven in Fort Worth, Texas, just after Christmas
1993, was executed Tuesday night after defiantly struggling with a
five-man team of guards who subdued him in his holding cell and
carried him to the death chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, 27, remained unruly right up until he was strapped to
the gurney where the lethal injection was administered. He declined
to make a final statement, and was pronounced dead at 6:22 p.m.,
seven minutes after drugs were administered.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance, which began just after noon when officials
attempted to remove Jennings from his cell at the Ellis Unit to
take him to a holding cell outside the death chamber, was the first
time since at least 1982 that a condemned inmate in Texas refused
to comply with orders requiring him to prepare for execution,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Prison system spokesman Larry Todd said Jennings had warned the
Walls Unit warden that he had no intention of going quietly to his
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not do this,'' Jennings was quoted as saying before the
five-man extraction team subdued him. The team was outfitted with
helmets, face guards, chest protectors and shin guards, officials
said. Jennings threw no punches, and no one was hurt in the
struggle, Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, who once worked as a nurse's aide and had a
ninth-grade education, was convicted of fatally shooting Sylvester
Walton, 44, and Wonda Matthews, 27. According to court documents,
Jennings and an accomplice entered a house in southeast Fort Worth
seeking drugs on Dec. 27, 1993. Shortly after entering the house,
Jennings opened fire with a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Walton was killed by a bullet that hit him in the nose and
traveled through his brain. Matthews was shot twice in the face and
once in the back of the head. Jennings took a pouch containing a
small amount of drugs and money from Walton's pocket before he and
his companion left the house, records show.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1995 trial, prosecutors called Jennings a drug abuser
who lusted for ``the taste of blood.'' Authorities said he also
killed at least three others in 1993 in what were described as
drug-related attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings spent his last day reading and lying on a prison bunk.
After first refusing to take a call from his son, Jennings spoke by
telephone with the youngster. He declined to eat breakfast and did
not order a final meal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the condemned man had no history of discipline problems
during his four-year prison stay, he did not leave Death Row
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   When officials came to take him from his cell at the Ellis Unit
at 12:30 p.m., he refused to budge, officials said. An extraction
team was assembled and Jennings was subdued with a pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
   He was placed in a prison van for the half-hour trip to the
Walls Unit in downtown Huntsville, and he walked from the vehicle
to a holding cell outside the death chamber without incident. He
was shackled at the ankles and wrists, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was not in restraints after he was placed in his
holding cell. But when the team arrived shortly before 6 p.m. to
escort him to his execution, Jennings was quoted as saying he was
``ready for round two.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the team subdued Jennings without using the chemical
spray, Todd said. The corrections officers had to carry the
5-foot-6, 185-pound Jennings to the chamber and place him on the
gurney.
</P>
<P>
   As he was carried to the chamber, he told guards, ``Thank you
for not using gas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since 1982 (when the state resumed
capital punishment) that an incident like this occurred,'' said
Larry Fitzgerald, another prison system spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Hamza, Wonda Matthews' sister, viewed the execution and
said ``justice had been served.'' She said she felt pain for
Jennings' family.
</P>
<P>
   ``God says you have to forgive, but I don't have to forget,''
said Hamza, who declined to talk about her sister other than to say
she left three children, who are now 15, 14 and 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The execution, the 29th in Texas this year and the 193rd since
the state resumed capital punishment, was witnessed by 15 prison
officials, three relatives of victims, a chaplain and five news
media representatives, including one from the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings was also accused of gunning down Dino Beasley, 29, and
Charlotte Dickerson, 31, who was found fatally shot on Christmas
Eve 1993 inside a drug house; and Larry Eugene Wilson, 43, who was
killed by a shotgun blast Oct. 23, 1993, at a marijuana house.
</P>
<P>
   The execution was the first of three scheduled for this week. On
Wednesday, John Lamb of Hunt County is scheduled to die, and on
Thursday, Jose Gutierrez of Brazos County is scheduled to be
executed.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
