<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MILLENNIAL-ART-2TAKES     11-16 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIAL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DREAMSCAPE OF MILLENNIAL FEARS AND HOPES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The public impact of the millennium has so far been pretty tame:
anxiety over New Year's party plans and mild speculation about
whether global computers will, indeed, hit a bump when midnight
strikes is about as far as it goes.
</P>
<P>
   But for most Americans not so long ago (and for many Americans
still), the idea of the turn of the millennium carried profound
weight. It wasn't just a date to scratch off the calendar. In
Judeo-Christian religious terms, it signified the end of time, the
culmination of history, when good and evil faced off once and for
all, and God's kingdom arrived on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of final days comes from biblical texts, the Book of
Daniel in the Old Testament and the Book of Revelation in the New
Testament. But millennialism isn't confined to dogmatic beliefs or
an event. It is also a mood, a state of expectation, a sense that
one has a leading role to play in the cosmic drama. And America has
always envisioned itself as the millennial nation, with a destiny
to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Puritans called themselves ``a city on a hill,''
a moral beacon for a depraved Europe. The young American republic
of the 19th century was described as the New Eden, uncorrupted,
fecund, redeemed. In the 20th century, the country's wealth and
technological power seemed to confirm that the Space Age future lay
here.
</P>
<P>
   Millennial thinking resonates through American politics, from
Manifest Destiny to the ``vision thing'' any presidential hopeful
is still required to spin out. It has always been there in high
art: in the nationalist allegories of Hudson River School landscape
painting, in Social Realism, with its demand for a new order, in
Abstract Expressionism, with its commitment to the sublime.
</P>
<P>
   And nowhere is millennialism more consistently explored than in
vernacular culture. This fact makes ``Millennial Dreams: Vision and
Prophecy in American Folk Art,'' organized by Gerald C. Wertkin at
the Museum of American Folk Art through May 14, one of the few
genuinely timely museum offerings of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Like the millennium, the show is very much about popular
religious ideas of time, and the earliest images are of the
mercurial Father Time himself, seen in photographs of New England
gravestones. On one, carved in 1681 for the Boston astronomer John
Foster, he is a protective presence, preventing death from making
full claim on the deceased. But on another, dated 1743, he turns
predatory, wielding the scythe that cuts life down.
</P>
<P>
   Just as visions of time expressed both fear and hope, concepts
of the millennium have invited two very different approaches. One,
described as premillennialist, envisions a sin-riddled world
hurtling toward destruction from which a few repentant souls might
be saved. The other, a &UR;  &LR; postmillennialist view, proposes a more
agreeable picture of paradise attained on earth, a Godly universe
gradually transformed and perfected through the strenuous efforts
of human beings.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the mid-19th century, premillennialism has found avid
champions. Prominent among them was William Miller (1782-1849), a
farmer-turned-prophet in upstate New York, who calculated that the
world would self-destruct in 1843 or 1844, and who printed up
instructional charts to get his followers over the end-of-time
hump.
</P>
<P>
   His alarmist sensibility lives on in art today. One finds it in
the manic, visionary work of the prolific Rev. Howard Finster of
Alabama. And it is there in the vivid paintings of the Pentecostal
preacher William A. Blayney (1917-1985), each of them a
diagrammatic breakdown of the Book of Daniel, filled with
apocalyptic monsters and real-life despots.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is postmillennialism, whose upbeat, messianic message
has been an important force in progressive America culture. In the
view of the late historian Alan Heimert, postmillennial optimism
helped ignite and fuel the American Revolution. It was a prime
ingredient in the religious awakenings that swept the country from
the 18th to the 20th centuries. And it has consistently been the
impetus behind the nation's great reform movements, from abolition
to temperance to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Both attitudes are evident in the Museum of American Folk Art
show, which is, like the biblical millennium, introduced by angels.
Gabriel sounds his horn on a Connecticut weather vane. The
archangel Michael strikes a militant pose in a devotional painting
from New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A limestone angel with wide-awake eyes by William Edmondson
(circa 1870-1951) is backed up by an 1848 quilt stitched with
angelic words by Maria Cadman Hubbard: ``Little acts of kindness,
little words of love make our earthly Eden like our heaven above.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For American utopians, of which there have always been many,
human and divine realms were contiguous; the promised land was here
and now. This was true of Shakers, who believed that their leader,
the English-born prophet Mother Ann Lee (1736-1784), had ushered in
the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Shaker life _ communal, celibate and industrious _ was conceived
as a version of heaven on earth. Every material aspect of it, from
buildings to bonnets to furniture, was shaped to sustain the ideal
of utilitarian perfection. And certain items were thought to have
been directly conveyed, in essence and sometimes in fact, by
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   These included so-called gift drawings. Some were pictures of
symbolic trees and fruits; others were heart-shaped valentines
dense with written texts. Most were produced by women like Hannah
Cohoon and Polly Ann Reed, who experienced visions during the
dynamic, revivalist period in Shaker history known as ``Mother's
Work.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, women have played a crucial role in pre- and
postmillennialist art. Such is the case with quilters like Maria
Hubbard and Harriet Powers (1837-1911), an ex-slave from Georgia,
whose stitched scenes of the Apocalypse incorporated textile
traditions from West Africa. And then there were painters, none
more engaging than Sister Gertrude Morgan (1900-1980), a street
preacher, singer, and founder of the Everlasting Gospel Mission in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who began and ended her artistic career at the command
of a divine voice, painted narrative scenes from the Book of
Revelation on window shades, funeral parlor fans and pieces of
shirt cardboard. She also created exultant depictions of a paradise
populated with interracial angels, an apt symbol of the perpetual
harmony that defines the millennial era.
</P>
<P>
   No image of that harmony is more familiar than ``The Peaceable
Kingdom'' of the Pennsylvania artist Edward Hicks. If Morgan set
her sights on heaven, Hicks kept his trained on earth, but an earth
made new, where lions and lambs lay down together and where the
Quaker leader William Penn sealed a pact of friendship with
American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, a substantial selection of Hicks' work is on
display at the Philadelphia Museum of Art (through Jan. 2), in one
of several millennialist shows that don't bill themselves as such.
Others include ``The Shaker Legacy'' at the New York State Museum
in Albany (through Jan. 2.) and an exhibition devoted to the Virgin
of Guadalupe, a millenarian political icon for Mexican-Americans,
at El Museo del Barrio in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Is millennium-inspired thinking still active in modern America?
One can certainly locate it in the 1960s counterculture, with its
evangelical hunger for social transformation and cosmic
consciousness. It is there in New Age culture, which brings the
extraordinary into the everyday and has roots going back into the
19th century, when Spiritualism and the nascent women's rights
movement were closely linked.
</P>
<P>
   One might even look for it in contemporary art. A version of
premillennialist pessimism is detectable in the scathing moral
indictments of a polemical artist like Sue Coe. And postmillennial
perfectionism lives on in the paintings of Agnes Martin and the
luminous, perception-altering environments of Robert Irwin, such as
the one on view at DIA Center in Manhattan (through December).
</P>
<P>
   Their work, and the ardent, insistent visions of the artists at
the Museum of American Folk Art, are reminders of the many ways the
millennium might be considered. Not just in terms of Y2K
get-togethers and glitches, but in terms of what has been and might
be. Millennialism is, for better and worse, an American legacy, and
part of the wound-down but still ticking mechanism known as the
American Dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
