<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1941 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BALLET-HISPANICO-2TAK     11-16 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-HISPANICO-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSELYTIZERS FOR A CULTURE THAT SELLS ITSELF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the choreographer Garth Fagan.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent warm afternoon, a crowd of lively boys
and girls make their way along West 89th Street in Manhattan to the
homey headquarters of Ballet Hispanico. With their book bags heavy
with dance gear, they jokingly try out ballet moves to the loud
salsa pouring from an open window.
</P>
<P>
   In a neighborhood that Dominicans, Puerto Ricans, Cubans and
many other Hispanic nationalities call home, it seems only natural
that there would be a dance school here dedicated to their
cultures.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1970, when Tina Ramirez established the Ballet Hispanico
school and company, it was a revolutionary act. Hispanics not only
had few dance schools, they also had trouble getting into dance
companies, an almost unimaginable situation now with the dazzling
Hispanic dancers in mainstream ballet and modern companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This fall Ms. Ramirez and her groundbreaking enterprise won two
major honors. In September, she received the Hispanic Heritage
Award for Education at the Kennedy Center in Washington. Since its
founding, almost 10,000 children have studied at the Ballet
Hispanico School, which now enrolls 600 students yearly for classes
in Spanish, modern and jazz dance and ballet.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't even include the thousands who have studied in its
outreach programs around the country. In addition, the Ford
Foundation gave Ballet Hispanico a $1 million grant, an impressive
amount in these days of cutbacks to cultural institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew that finally we would be widely recognized,''
she says, walking though the building's lobby as students stream
through on their way to class. ``Our music and dance are so
powerful, so earthy, so rhythmic; in the end, few can resist.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ms. Ramirez has invited a few guests to see the three new
works receiving their New York premieres at the Joyce Theater
during the company's two-week season, beginning on Nov. 30. In a
spacious second-floor studio, a distance from the happy clamor
below, her 12 dancers warm up, preparing for the very different
choreographic styles of the American David Rousseve, the Cuban
Pedro Ruiz and the Brazilian Regina Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 22 nations that speak Spanish,'' says Ms. Ramirez.
``They have many similarities and many differences, although all
share Arab, Jewish, African and American-Indian influences. I
represent as many as I can, but I also commission non-Hispanics who
understand our culture.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the repertory includes works by choreographers as
diverse as the postmodernist Susan Marshall and Talley Beatty and
George Faison, both of them influenced by jazz and African dance.
This season's programs pair the American Ann Reinking's jazzy
``Ritmo y Ruido'' with the Spaniard Ramon Oller's highly theatrical
works ``Good Night, Paradise'' and ``Bury Me Standing.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a Mexican matador and a Puerto Rican
schoolteacher, Ms. Ramirez, who spent her early years in Venezuela
before coming to New York, is a good example of the Hispanic mix.
``From my father I learned to appreciate grace, since the bullfight
is a dance,'' she says, ``and from my mother I learned respect for
education.''
</P>
<P>
   She takes her place at the far end of the studio. Small and trim
in black slacks and a white silk blouse, her dark gray hair pulled
back from her delicate face, in her mid-60s she still carries
herself like a dancer. Studies with the legendary Spanish dancer
Lola Bravo, the Russian ballerina Alexandra Danilova and the
Polish-American choreographer Anna Sokolow and years performing
with the Hispanic troupe of Federico Rey left their mark.
</P>
<P>
   She clicks a button on the boom box, and on comes the jazz
pianist Eddie Palmieri's rambunctious score for Rousseve's
``Somethin' From Nothin'.'' Feet start tapping. In couples and
alone, the dancers strut and slink to the center of the room,
projecting despair in spite of their robust sensuality. ``Why is
everybody so down?'' asks a dancer. Slowly, impelled by the music,
their spirits seem to soar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rousseve's inspiration came from Palmieri's music and from
hearing parts of ``Remembering Slavery,'' a series of early
20th-century recorded interviews collected by Ira Berlin, read on
National Public Radio. ``I show how people who supposedly have
nothing find joy in very simple things, such as dancing,'' Rousseve
explains. This is his second piece for Ballet Hispanico; he
choreographed ``When Dreams Explode'' for the company in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like exploring the intersection of Hispanic and African
cultures,'' he says, ``and these dancers understand. Most
importantly, they're passionate about dancing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the piece ends, Ms. Ramirez makes her way from one dancer
to another, offering suggestions; sometimes simply asking for a
tilt of the head or a higher extension. She takes Alessandra
Corona's hand and places it on her hip. Then, assuming the same
position herself, she thrusts her shoulder forward and immediately
adds more bravado. All this coaching is accomplished with the
utmost seriousness. But as she leaves the troupe to talk to her
guests, she's smiling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so wonderful in the last section,'' Ms. Ramirez says,
``is that you're seeing every dancer's own version of salsa.
There's Pedro's Cuban style.'' She brings her arms in close to her
chest, rises on her toes, swivels her hips and demonstrates Cuban
salsa.
</P>
<P>
   In quick succession, she follows with the Puerto Rican salsa of
Eric Rivera, the Venezuelan salsa of Hector Montero and, laughing,
the Korean salsa of Jae-Man Joo, capturing the nuances of each one.
``You don't have to be Hispanic to feel Hispanic,'' she says.
``It's an organic culture, a welcoming culture.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She picks up a notebook filled with sketches for the costumes
for Rousseve's piece, sexy wraparound dresses and hip-hugging
pants, all in vibrant colors. ``This is what kids are wearing,''
she says. ``They spend nothing and yet look great. So we're using
the same styles. We're in touch with real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jody Arnhold, chairman of the Ballet Hispanico board, nods in
agreement. ``Tina's a part of the neighborhood, a part of the
public schools and a part of the world,'' says Ms. Arnhold. ``She's
deeply connected to society.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ramirez returns to her post at the end of the room and
starts the music for Ruiz's work, played by the Cuban groups Los
Activos and Conjunto Cespedes Vitier. A company member since 1985,
Ruiz makes his choreographic debut with ``Guajira,'' a celebration
of the hard-working women who live in rural Cuba. ``When I was a
child growing up in Havana, I'd go to the country on Sundays with
my grandfather,'' he says. ``The people there spent all their lives
on the land. Many of their traditions came from Africa. My ballet
recalls that way of life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He paints a picture of people whose pleasures are simple but
intense; whose bodies easily combine with nature. In one scene the
men and women prepare the ground for planting, and in another the
women bend over, scrubbing clothes in a stream. Skillfully, Ruiz
conveys how work and flirtation bind the people together.
</P>
<P>
   It's a piece close to his heart. For the backdrop, he
commissioned a mural of rolling green countryside under a sea-blue
sky, ``just as I remember it,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Ruiz's sunny piece, Ms. Miranda's takes a
clear-eyed look at the decadence of contemporary Rio de Janeiro,
using a dissonant score by Damaso Cerruti and Vinicius Brazil.
Named after one of the city's main arteries, ``Avenida Brasil,''
the work presents a series of explosively violent scenes, many
using movements from the Brazilian martial art capoeira.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to give an aerial view of the street, a glimpse of
many personal stories,'' says Ms. Miranda. ``People have a tourist
idea of Brazil; I want to show something truer.''
</P>
<P>
   Trained in dance theater, she first brought her own ensemble,
Regina Miranda Actors and Dancers Company, to the United States in
1997. It was then that Ms. Ramirez saw the company perform at St.
Mark's Church in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After the guests leave, the hard work of refining the pieces
begins. Ms. Ramirez shows no sign of flagging as she prepares to
put in a few more hours. She spent her morning handling
administration, and all week she has attended dance concerts in the
evening, on the lookout for interesting choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a connection with what's going on right now is very
important to me,'' she says. ``I think that's why audiences
everywhere are so drawn to us. We reflect what they know of life _
the difficulties and the joys.''
</P>
<P>
   A few students pause at the door to watch. As they leave, she
says, ``Dance offers them so much _ pride, discipline, focus.''
Someone in the studio turns on the Palmieri music and, subtly
moving her shoulders and hips, she walks in rhythm back to her
dancers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
