 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Wednesday, November 17, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ABALONE  &LR; _ Abalone farming isn't the quickest way to make a
buck. Although the rock-clinging mollusk is in short supply and its
meat fetches $60 or more per pound, the seaweed-munching mollusks
grow at a snail's pace. It takes at least three years of care and
feeding to grow a modest 3-incher in captivity. To fetch a greater
return, US Abalone of Santa Cruz County, also known as US Abs, is
muscling into a new market with its abalone pearls. The Davenport
aquaculture company, which grows abalone in beachside tanks, has
just printed a catalog for its cultured abalone pearls fashioned by
Carmel's Crossroads Jewelers and plans to sell them from its Web
site (www.usabalone.com). By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GROW A BUSINESS _  &LR; Export market is big for small businesses. By
Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; COMDEX  &LR; _ ``Internet appliances'' are the talk of the town in Las
Vegas this week. The term _ and its virtual synonym, ``information
appliance'' _ refer to Internet-access devices that are simpler and
cheaper than PCs. The idea has been talked about for several years,
but at this week's Comdex computer trade show, it has moved front
and center. That's mainly because the biggest players in the PC
industry, starting with Microsoft, Compaq and soon Dell, are
getting into the game. Starting next year, they are hoping to
market such contraptions to the 50 percent or so of U.S. households
that have so far resisted the charms of the PC _ and to put them in
the kitchens and bedrooms of families who already have a computer
in the den or the study. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CAMPBELL &LR;  _ Tom Campbell is a House Republican who represents
Silicon Valley and also happens to teach antitrust law at Stanford
University. If his views on the Microsoft case carry any
credibility, the Seattle software giant should settle now before
it's too late. Campbell said in an interview that media coverage
has widely overlooked the most damning conclusions of Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's 207-page findings of fact: Microsoft met with
its competitors for the clear purpose of restraining trade. By
Carolyn Lochhead
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLATT  &LR; _ The appointment of former Hewlett-Packard chief
executive Lewis Platt to the helm of Kendall-Jackson at the
beginning of next year is designed to help the biggest North Coast
wine producer become more of a global competitor. It also positions
K-J for a possible public stock offering as early as the end of
next year. Platt, 58, who was replaced as CEO at HP in July by
Carly Fiorina, retains his chairman title at the nation's
second-largest computer company until December. After that, he said
in an interview, he will move from Los Altos to Sonoma County and
begin his ``second career.'' By Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENENTECH  &LR; _ Genentech has offered to pay the University of
California $200 million to settle allegations that 20 years ago,
scientists working for the biotech giant spirited a patented DNA
sample out of a UC lab and used the specimen to develop a
top-selling growth hormone drug. UC and Genentech declined to
comment on the proposed settlement, which is scheduled for a vote
before the UC Board of Regents tomorrow. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HAMBRECHT  &LR; _ WR Hambrecht, a San Francisco Internet-based
investment bank, said yesterday that it is letting investors take
part in the firm's venture capital and private stock deals directly
through its Web site. The move makes it easier for affluent
individuals to make investments not normally available to the
public by buying an ownership stake in young companies before they
sell stock in a public offering. By Sam Zuckerman
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; GAS _  &LR; Gas prices in the Bay Area have come down nearly a dime in
the past month, but are still well above last year at this time,
the California State Automobile Association said yesterday. Higher
crude oil prices, meanwhile, may mean that pump prices have gone as
low as they'll go for the time being. The average price for a
gallon of unleaded regular gas in the Bay Area dropped 8 cents
since October, to $1.45, the automobile association reported. The
Northern California average fell 6 cents, to $1.43, while the
nationwide average slid only a penny, to $1.28. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LEVI'S &LR;  _ Philip Marineau, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s new chief
executive, has initiated a sweeping shakeup at the San Francisco
jeansmaker. In an internal memo obtained by The Chronicle, Marineau
outlined plans to replace top managers and to fuse some U.S. and
global functions, a process that will result in an undetermined
number of layoffs. Most of the changes are effective immediately.
By Carol Emert
</P>
