r f BC-LEVIS-LEVI'S_SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-LEVI'S </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Levi's CEO Resizing Staff For a Better Fit  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Philip Marineau, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s new chief executive, has
initiated a sweeping shakeup at the San Francisco jeansmaker.jeans
maker. &LR;
<P>
   &LR;  In an internal memo obtained by The the  &LR; Chronicle, Marineau
Marinea  &LR; outlined plans to replace top managers and to fuse some
U.S. and global functions, a process that will result in an
undetermined number of layoffs. Most of the changes are effective
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In his six weeks on the job, Marineau said he learned that ``we
have leadership and operational issues, especially within the
Americas, that must be fixed as soon as possible to deliver next
year's business plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, ``we need to staff the organization at the
appropriate size to match our level of sales,'' said the memo,
which Levi's staff received late Monday. Levi's sales have been
falling precipitously for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Without mincing words, Marineau announced that John Ermatinger,
president of the Americas division, and Rob Holloway, vice
president of marketing for the United States, will be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``While John and Rob are both highly skilled professionals, it
is my assessment that they do not have the level of experience and
track record in their current roles to accomplish what we need to
be successful,'' Marineau stated in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   Ermatinger and Holloway did not return telephone calls
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In a move to cut costs, Levi's will combine the U.S. and global
divisions of three departments: marketing, finance and information
systems. Other departments, such as human resources, have already
merged.
</P>
<P>
   Layoff decisions will be made within each department, so it is
not clear how many jobs will be lost, said Levi's spokesman Jeff
Beckman.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic changes initiated by Marineau demonstrate that he
``is setting a direction for this company, which has been
fundamentally directionless for quite a while,'' one former Levi's
executive said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Both the personnel changes and restructuring should strengthen
the company, said the executive, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau was in meetings and unavailable for comment, Beckman
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Marineau joined the company, he told The the  &LR; Chronicle
that he planned to work as much as possible with the existing
management team. But the top ranks at Levi's are starting to look
radically different.
</P>
<P>
   Marineau will run the Americas division until a replacement
search  &LR; for Ermatinger is found.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, James Capon, a marketing vice president, has been
promoted to president of the Levi's brand in the United States U.S.
 &LR; and Bobbi Silten, marketing director for Slates, will become
president of the Dockers and Slates brands for the United
States.U.S. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Larry Ruff, the vice president of global marketing, will head
the new marketing team, while Janie Ligon, vice president of
direct-to-consumer marketing, will retire. Ruff's duties will be
expanded to include consumer relations, Web marketing, licensing
and publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Glick, the company's chief information officer, will run
the information systems effort while Tom Kasten, a vice president,
will retire.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Moreno, a senior vice president and general counsel, will
manage both the corporate and Americas legal departments. He will
also run Levi's Latin America operations until a new Americas
America's  &LR; president is found.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Goya, senior vice president of human resources, is
retiring after 30 years but will stay until her replacement is
found.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's is also searching for a head of global sourcing, a new
position that will centrally coordinate materials purchasing and
clothing manufacturing. Currently Levi's U.S., European and Asian
arms source products separately, competing against each other
instead of working together to get the best deals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Marineau announced the impending departure of chief
marketing officer Gordon Shank, a 25-year company veteran whose job
became redundant when Marineau joined.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the personnel changes, Marineau said Levi's needs to
fix its ``go to market process,'' which includes ``everything from
product design right through to the presentation of our brands at
retail.''
</P>
<P>
   Capon and Karen Hanna, vice president of human resources in the
Americas, will develop recommendations for improving this process.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for fiscal year 2000, which Marineau helped develop, ``are
realistic and deliverable, and they will enable us to stabilize the
business, honor our financial commitments and reward employees for
their performance,'' Marineau said in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
