<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-GAS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Bay Area Prices Fall 8 Cents In Auto Association Survey  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Gas prices in the Bay Area have come down nearly a dime in the past
month, but are still well above last year at this time, the
California State Automobile Association said yesterday.
<P>
   Higher crude oil prices, meanwhile, may mean that pump prices
have gone as low as they'll go for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for a gallon of unleaded regular gas in the
Bay Area dropped 8 cents since October, to $1.45, the automobile
association reported. The Northern California average fell 6 cents,
to $1.43, while the nationwide average slid only a penny, to $1.28.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California motorists still pay the highest prices in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition here just isn't as intense as other places,'' said
Paul Moreno, a spokesman for the association. ``On the horizon, we
have higher oil prices, which will have an impact at the pump.''
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil hit its highest price in almost three years yesterday,
trading for $25.70 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil prices have more than doubled this year and are up 18
percent this month alone amid cutbacks in output by oil-producing
nations.
</P>
<P>
   While the automobile association's statistics won't reflect this
trend until next month, the U.S. Department of Energy said Monday
that its weekly survey showed the nationwide average gas price
rising to a six-week high of $1.25 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The California Energy Commission, meanwhile, said the statewide
average for regular unleaded rose slightly in the last week to
$1.34.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glaviano, the commission's petroleum analyst, said it looks
like California gas prices may settle near current levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably reaching a level where we shouldn't expect
prices to drop much lower,'' he said. ``They may be bottoming
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Since October, San Francisco has seen one of the steepest drops
in gas prices, with the average cost down 11 cents, to $1.51,
according to the automobile association. A year ago, the city's
drivers were paying just $1.27 at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's average gas price slid 7 cents since October to
$1.44, compared with $1.14 a year ago, and Oakland's average also
declined 7 cents, to $1.47, compared with $1.20 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Northern California's most expensive gas is Gas is most &LR; 
expensive  &LR; in the Lake Tahoe area, where the average gallon runs
$1.56, down just 3 cents from October but still considerably higher
than last year's $1.19.
</P>
<P>
   The north state's cheapest gas is in Chico, with the average
gallon costing $1.32, down 9 cents from October but up from last
year's $1.12.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the cheapest gas is in the Southeast, where the
average gallon sells for a mere $1.19.
</P>
<P>
   California gas prices outpace the national average in part due
to the state's stringent environmental regulations, which require
cleaner-burning fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Pump prices soared to record high levels this summer due to high
demand and a series of snafus at state refineries, which reduced
production levels.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
