r f BC-HAMBRECHT-HAMBRECHT_S     11-16 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBRECHT-HAMBRECHT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 WR Hambrecht Seeks Investors Via the Web  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WR Hambrecht, a San Francisco Internet-based investment bank, said
yesterday that it is letting investors take part in the firm's
venture capital and private stock deals directly through its Web
site.
<P>
   The move makes it easier for affluent individuals to make
investments not normally available to the public by buying an
ownership stake in young companies before they sell stock in a
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Several other firms have set up Internet sites to link investors
with private companies looking for capital. Hambrecht said it is
the only online company to give individuals a chance to participate
as partners in venture capital and private equity investments the
firm itself makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just an agent for these companies. We're principal
investors ourselves,'' said J.D. Delafield, Hambrecht's director of
private equity.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, founded two years ago by Bill Hambrecht, who
previously headed the San Francisco investment bank Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist, has already raised nearly $27 million in 16 private equity
deals. Until Hambrecht started promoting its private equity program
on it Web site recently, participation was limited to a select list
of core clients.
</P>
<P>
   Private stock deals, especially in the cases of young companies
with scant track records, are highly risky. And, because there are
no public markets for a company's stock, investors have practically
no way of converting their shares into cash if they need money in
an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Securities and Exchange Commission only
lets accredited investors take part in private equity transactions.
To be approved, investors must have $1million in net worth or
annual income of $200,000 for individuals and $300,000 for couples.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
