<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1949 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NY-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-$     11-16 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RADIO-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVING IMPORTANT (AND GENEROUS) FRIENDS HELPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Valerie Gladstone, a New York writer, is the daughter of Henry
Gladstone, the longtime WOR radio broadcaster.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At WNYC's office, on the 25th floor of the handsome
old Municipal Building in Lower Manhattan, volunteers are hunched
over the telephones in the rotunda, a drab space that belies its
grand moniker, frantically responding to listeners pledging money.
</P>
<P>
   Even fortified with coffee and bagels, they look tired.
Reporters in the news department, usually out chasing down stories,
alternate with staff members like Mark Hilan, local host of
``Morning Edition,'' and Fred Child, musical and cultural director,
to plead unashamedly for desperately needed support. These are the
final hours of the station's recent fund-raising drive.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to make sure WNYC (93.9 FM and 820 AM) remains a
bastion of creative public broadcasting, and chances look good.
This was the first regular drive that broke the $1 million barrier
in contributions.
</P>
<P>
   As the station celebrates its 75th anniversary, it faces not
only continued high payments for its broadcasting license but a
backbreaking 200 percent hike in charges from National Public Radio
for syndication of several programs, including the acclaimed news
and feature series ``Morning Edition'' and ``All Things
Considered.'' The miracle is that they seem to be pulling it off.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, the last day turned out nicely, with the actor Paul
Newman phoning in on his drive into Manhattan to offer a $25,000
grant from Newman's Own, his foundation. Another listener called to
say that a musical broadcast she heard on WNYC in 1933 had inspired
her to become a concert violinist.
</P>
<P>
   Since WNYC has a history that includes coverage of a ticker tape
parade in 1927 for the Arctic explorer Richard E. Byrd, Mayor
Fiorello La Guardia reading the Sunday comics to children in the
1940s and Bob Dylan's radio debut (in 1961 on Oscar Brand's ``Folk
Song Festival,'' a show that continues to this day), it's not
surprising that fund drives inspire calls from people with
sentimental connections to the station.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone here is used to them. The drives come three times a
year, and employees seem to get a charge out of interacting with
the audience and watching the donations mount on the computer
screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the price of doing exciting programs,'' says Mark
McDonald, managing editor of news and information, ``it's well
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been concern about the station since 1995 when Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani made good on his threat to sell WNYC Radio and TV
to help relieve the city's expected $2.3 billion budget gap. Dow
Jones/ITT quickly bought the television station for $203 million
but didn't take the radio station.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in an overwhelming show of support, nearly 28,000
listeners pledged a remarkable $1.4 million during a four-day drive
to keep the station independent and commercial-free.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe no one had realized just how important WNYC had become to
its audience. A board member who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, a donor of millions of dollars to WNYC since its
independence, says he wasn't willing to see ``a station so plugged
into the city and the world converted into another commercial
station with generic programming.''
</P>
<P>
   A board, including Wilma S. Tisch, Jerry Della Femina, Peter H.
Darrow and Lally Weymouth, negotiated a $20 million license
purchase to be paid over six years. In January, the fourth of six
payments comes due; so far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   The split with the New York City government carried with it
another significant change. No longer would the mayor appoint
WNYC's president. In 1995, the board elected Laura Walker, a former
Children's Television Workshop producer, to the job.
</P>
<P>
   At home in Brooklyn Heights on maternity leave until January,
she maintains regular contact with the station between feedings of
her 2-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walker, who is 41, has quickly made her mark, proving that
the station can be innovative, even while burdened with heavy
costs. Under her leadership, WNYC, which was already the most
popular of all local public stations has increased its listenership
from 800,000 to more than one million.
</P>
<P>
   Membership has grown by 60 percent, with contributions rising
almost 100 percent, from $5.5 million to more than $10 million last
year. She has also managed to attract a huge increase in corporate
support from institutions as diverse as Chase Bank, MBG Classics
and Talkcity.com (one of a variety of contributing Silicon Valley
firms).
</P>
<P>
   Already the development of a Web site, WNYC.org, has become an
important new way to give programming a lengthy shelf life and
attract another audience. In 1998, $19,000 was pledged via the Web;
in 1999, $51,000.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ms. Walker initiated the station's first gala
fund-raising dinner, which brought in $750,000. Earlier this month,
three devoted WNYC listeners _ the network television news anchors
Tom Brokaw, Peter Jennings and Dan Rather _ were hosts of the
second gala, bringing in more than $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   All these gains have helped offset the loss of the city's annual
$1.5 million support and the station has balanced its $16.9 million
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Now, along with the hefty payments still due on the purchase
price, the station has to find the revenue to pay NPR's alarming
increases. In 2000, those fees jump to $1.9 million (up from
$640,000 in 1996). Once based on total station revenues, these
charges are now determined by the number of listeners. So the more
successful the station is, the more it has to pay.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To deal with NPR's new policy, Ms. Walker spearheaded the
formation of the Major Market Partnership, a group of executives
from the 10 major public stations. ``Specifically,'' she says,
``we're working with NPR to phase in the new dues structure and to
make certain the value of the local stations' audience is
understood as a part of NPR's national underwriting efforts.''
Which means making sure they recognize the local stations'
contribution to their success.
</P>
<P>
   NPR's president, Kevin Klose, says the current fee arrangement
was not meant to be permanent. ``This is not the end of the
story,'' he says. ``However, the reason we changed our policy is
that the current one more directly reflects the value NPR programs
have brought to the station in terms of listener numbers. It is
still fairer than the previous system, which was based on station
revenues. In fact, as many stations complained about the old system
as complain about this one. We're hoping to put something into
effect more satisfactory to all the stations within a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation with NPR may be unsettled, but the direction of
WNYC's programming is not. Proudly, Ms. Walker mentions
already-proven shows like Brian Lehrer's news programs ``On the
Media'' and ``On the Line''; Leonard Lopate's 14-year-old ``New
York and Company,'' on which a week's guest list might include
Henry Kissinger, the artist Chuck Close, the opera star Christa
Ludwig, the singer Barry White and the author John Updike; and John
Schaefer's ``New Sounds,'' created in 1982, which introduces new
music, underwrites live concerts and commissions pieces.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the changes. Jonathan Schwartz, the radio
personality who began proselytizing for Frank Sinatra and American
standards on New York radio in 1967, just joined WNYC with shows on
Saturday and Sunday nights. In the news and information division,
documentaries are becoming integral.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the reporter-producer team of Beth Fertig and
Jane Bryant Johnson are in Zimbabwe gathering material for a
documentary on how HIV-positive African immigrants to the United
States seek treatments for their relatives and friends in Africa. A
news reporter, Amy Eddings, is working on a three-part series,
``The Juggling Act,'' to be broadcast in January, about how
families cope in a world of multiple demands.
</P>
<P>
   WNYC plans three new shows in the next six months. Starting in
late January, ``Satellite Sisters'' takes to the air in four test
markets, including New York. The one-hour show, scheduled for
Saturdays, is a five-way conversation among five sisters who live
around the country and abroad, dealing with what one sister calls
``real life as the soap opera it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the spring are ``The Next Big Thing,'' with the former
NPR cultural reporter Dean Olsher as host and producer, and a
series with Kurt Andersen, the New Yorker writer and former editor
in chief of New York magazine, as host.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows will examine culture in its broadest sense.
Andersen's show, still untitled, is being developed by Susan
Morris, who produced arts programming for the BBC and Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show how the arts are embedded in our lives,'' says
Ms. Morris. ``I learned that there's a music programmer on Air
Force One,'' she says. ``Well, I became interested in who he was
and whether Bill and Hillary had different tastes and if certain
music was played after and before certain events.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused. ``I'm also trying to find out why so many opera
singers like golf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
