<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TV-MARY-AND-RHODA-ART     11-16 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARY-AND-RHODA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OLD PALS, STILL TRYING TO MAKE IT AFTER ALL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The night view stretches forever from the terrace of
the 16th-floor duplex on Central Park West. Inside, it's the
proverbial telephone booth. In the center of a room about 20 feet
square, Mary Tyler Moore practices throwing her left hook while
she, Valerie Harper and a film crew patiently work around one
another, setting up for the next scene.
</P>
<P>
   Space is tight, but this is ridiculous. Is there room for the
camera? Furniture is removed. Lose the couch.
</P>
<P>
   From 1970 to 1977, as Mary Richards and Rhoda Morgenstern, Ms.
Moore and Ms. Harper made ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' one of the
most successful series in television history. Now they are back
together making ``Mary and Rhoda,'' a television movie that began
as an idea for a series and may yet lead to one.
</P>
<P>
   References to the possibility of a new show often enter their
talk, but for now the focus is clear. ``We want to feel we've made
the best movie we can,'' Ms. Moore said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, which ABC expects to show early next year, Mary and
Rhoda reconnect in New York, where they both have daughters in
college. Mary has lived in the city for years and is the widow of a
congressman who died five months ago. Rhoda, a native New Yorker,
has returned from Paris. Having divorced her philandering French
husband, she wants to pursue her interest in photography and be
near her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Moore came up with the major plot elements herself. In fact,
she put the project together herself, which is not the kind of
thing she used to do in the old days with ``The Mary Tyler Moore
Show'' or with her company MTM Productions, which was run by her
former husband Grant Tinker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did zip,'' she said. ``I was chairman of the board.'' On the
set she was on a kind of automatic pilot. ``I never had to get
involved in the acting because the show was so brilliantly written.
It was like a perfect cake put before me every week. I never had to
reach for moments. I instinctively knew how to act them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago she proposed a new series. ``It didn't fly,'' she
said. Even seasoned writers couldn't get by the aura and mystique
of the old show to create characters who were familiar yet totally
different people in a completely changed world facing entirely new
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the same character,'' said Ms. Moore, who will turn 63
next month. But writers kept sinking back into the old
characterizations.
</P>
<P>
   ABC turned down the series but backed the movie. ``The series
died because they never got scripts they thought were sharp enough
to bring those characters back,'' said Susan Lyne, the network's
executive vice president for movies and mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Ford, who wrote the film, said the two-hour format gave
Mary and Rhoda breathing room to re-establish themselves as new
people in fresh lives. ``To give credit to anyone who attempted it
as a series, I don't think I could have done that in a half-hour,''
she said. In a movie, the memory of ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show''
needn't hang quite so heavily. ``We're trying to move on from that,
not be reminiscent, because it's important to see who they'd be
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is directed by Barnet Kellman, the director of ``Murphy
Brown'' among other shows and films. ```The Mary Tyler Moore
Show,''' he said, ``gave us a character who was starting over,
taking chances. That's what energized the series. What I like about
this story is that it puts Mary in that position again later in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellman and Ms. Moore credit much of the character development
to Ms. Ford, 34, who began her career as a stand-up comic at 14 and
has written for ``Family Ties'' and other series and been a writer
and producer in Canadian television. ``There was one initial phone
call from Mary,'' she said. ``We came from the same place about
where we wanted to approach it. Her instincts are unbelievable. She
gave me a lot of confidence and made me want to do it well for her
because she had such a great eye.''
</P>
<P>
   In the duplex scene Mary Richards punches the air in
satisfaction over having stood up for herself in a messy situation.
``I don't want to play familiar roles,'' Ms. Moore said. ``I want
to play people who make my palms sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old days Mary Richards was an independent young woman,
but in the movie she faces a new reality in which independence
imposes an updated set of demands. The congressman, a good fellow
all around, made some bad financial decisions and now Mary needs a
job. Or as Ms. Moore put it, ``I'm 60; I haven't worked in eight
years; is there hope for me?''
</P>
<P>
   She and Ms. Ford developed the story together. ``One of the
first things I said to Mary was that I really wanted this to be a
drama, because to me that's the only way to explain the 20 years we
haven't seen and the only way the comedy will work for me,'' Ms.
Ford said. ``As a drama it's just easier to do.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In its potential for intimidation, New York is as much a part of
the story of two women, now of a certain age, starting their lives
over as Minneapolis was for Mary and Rhoda when they first became
friends in their early 30s. The entire film has been shot in the
city, a rarity for a television movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pay a price for the beauty and texture of New York,''
Kellman said. ``You're in practical locations. In a New York
apartment you can't move the wall. If the camera is jammed in the
corner five feet away, you have to use a wide-angle lens, which
catches everything it sees. You're dealing with reality all the
time, which is great when it gets on screen but it's hard to get it
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Mary Richards lands a position with a television news
station run by Jonah Seimeir, played by Elon Gold, a man in his
early 30s who bears absolutely no resemblance to Lou Grant (Ed
Asner), the gruff, traditional newsman whom Mary worked for on the
old show in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart, glib and attractive in a way that makes him both
distrustful and substantial,'' Kellman said. At one point Mary
accuses him of hiring her to defuse claims of age discrimination
arising from a situation with Cecile Andrews, played by Christine
Ebersole, an anchorwoman in her late 40s. Jonah freely admits that
that is indeed the main reason he hired Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way Mary and Lou have switched roles,'' Kellman said.
``Mary is representative of those old values she learned at that
station in Minneapolis. This kid is the product of contemporary
media savvy, cynicism and business reality. At the same time, which
is really challenging, the guy's not a fool or a cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   And what has become of Rhoda? ``The old Rhoda was waiting for a
man to stamp her valid,'' said Ms. Harper, 59. No more. ``She has
grown much more confident over the years in that she's unwilling to
stay in a marriage that is not a good one. She's still the same
spirit, still has the New York accent. She's had her baby in her
late 30s so she's pretty well formed up. Rhoda is suffering a bit
of empty nest. She's coming home, she wants to be near her
daughter, who's seeking her own life, so that's delicate. She likes
to be needed, wants to be loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Central to the film, of course, are the two daughters, who help
their mothers bridge the more than 20 years they have been gone
from ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show'' and bring them into the present.
Both are loyal but strive for independence. Mary's daughter, Rose,
played by Joie Lenz, wants to leave college to be a stand-up comic.
The mothers are given formidable young women to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The daughters help them be different people,'' said Marisa
Ryan, who plays Rhoda's daughter, Meredith, a pre-med student at
Columbia. ``She's trying to be on her own, get out of Rhoda's
grasp, deal with the divorce. She's very close to her dad, and
Rhoda's constantly vocalizing how she loathes him. Actually she's
more like Mary, more studious, focused, more of a go-getter. She
has the humor, but she's more strait-laced than Rhoda.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, these sound like solid characters for a new series.
ABC won't comment on the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to do a two-hour movie is just right,'' Ms. Lyne
said. ``It gives you a chance to see who they've become and how
they act in a world that has changed dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Later there will be time to consider other possibilities, as
Kellman pointed out. ``The movie has to be a stand-alone,'' he
said, ``but I was also careful in the writing and casting to make
sure it worked as a setup for a series. You want to give the other
characters their due. In a movie they can be straw men or props,
but in a series they have to be interesting enough to see them in
the round, in that you'll want to see their foibles and the
difficulties they present to the central characters.''
</P>
<P>
   A bonding between the daughters might be an appropriate
development. Ms. Ford, like others around the film, is closemouthed
about details in the script. ``Part of the fun,'' she said, ``will
be the surprise of what that's like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
