</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Genentech Offers to Settle UC Patent Row
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Abate and Tanya Schevitz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chronicle Staff Writers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Genentech has offered to pay the University of California $200
million to settle allegations that 20 years ago, scientists working
for the biotech giant spirited a patented DNA sample out of a UC
lab and used the specimen to develop a top-selling growth hormone
drug.
</P>
<P>
   UC and Genentech declined to comment on the proposed settlement,
which is scheduled for a vote before the UC Board of Regents
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the deal would settle a case that UC filed in 1990
and nearly won at a trial this summer. A settlement would let both
sides avoid the risk and expense of a retrial, which was slated to
begin in January.
</P>
<P>
   Although terms of the settlement have not been released, an
informed source said UC general counsel James Holst sent out a memo
on Monday outlining Genentech's offer to pay UC $150 million in
cash and to spend an additional $50 million to erect a building on
the university's new research campus at San Francisco's Mission
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The memo calls the $50 million a gift that would let Genentech
propose a name for the building.
</P>
<P>
   Legal observers called the offer a huge victory for UC and one
of the largest patent infringement settlements in history.
</P>
<P>
   John Storella, a San Francisco patent attorney, said that for UC
to get a settlement that large ``without the risk of a trial
represents a great deal'' for the university.
</P>
<P>
   Although the agreement would cost Genentech more than its 1998
profit of $182 million, Genentech's shares rose 6 percent yesterday
as news of the settlement leaked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant amount of money, but Genentech can afford
it,'' said Carol Werther, a biotechnology stock analyst in New
York. ``It's better for shareholders to have Genentech put this
lawsuit behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the regents approve the current arrangement, it would mark
the second time this year that Genentech has made a large payment
to settle alleged improprieties involving Protropin, a drug
developed for children who are abnormally small because of hormone
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Genentech agreed to pay $50 million to end a Food and
Drug Administration probe into allegations that during the late
1980s and early 1990s, it had encouraged Protropin prescriptions
for children who were short but otherwise healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Although UC did not file suit against Genentech until 1990, the
patent dispute traces its roots to 1978, when several scientists at
UC San Francisco discovered and patented part of the gene in the
body that is used to make human growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that discovery, Genentech, then a fledgling
biotech firm, hired one of those UC scientists, Peter Seeburg, to
join the company in its attempt to develop a growth hormone drug.
Seeburg testified in court earlier this year that he returned to UC
San Francisco on the New Year's Eve after his hiring and took a
sample of the DNA back to Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg, now a biochemist at the University of Heidelberg in
Germany, further testified that he and another former Genentech
scientist, David Goeddel, later used UC's sample to help make the
growth hormone gene that became the basis for Genentech's Protropin
drug.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial that ended in June, Genentech acknowledged that
Seeburg had taken the DNA sample from UC, but it said it never used
that sample to develop Protropin.
</P>
<P>
   Goeddel, a respected scientist who left Genentech to found
another South San Francisco biotech firm called Tularik Inc.,
testified that he had independently created a human growth hormone
gene that was different and larger than UC's DNA sample _ so much
different, in fact, that Genentech was granted its own patent for
Goeddel's discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that ended in June never directly addressed the two
scientists' conflicting testimony, but rather zeroed in on the
narrower legal issues of whether Genentech's DNA was substantially
the same as UC's earlier invention and, thus, was a patent
infringement.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial ended in a hung jury when eight jurors voted in
favor of UC and one held out for Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as one of the ironies of the proposed deal, Seeburg and
four other current or former UC scientists whose names appear on
the patent will earn a share of any settlement under university
rules that split the profits from patented inventions with the
inventors.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg and the others could collect $20 million each, according
to a Los Angeles Times report that could not be independently
verified. Such a payment to the scientists would leave UC with $50
million in cash and the $50 million building pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is likely to get a hard look by the regents,
which is one reason UC officials have been tight-lipped about its
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nice to get the money,'' said one regent. ``But in one
sense, we came damn close to winning the whole ballgame, so I don't
know how good a settlement this is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MONDAY-NIGHT-ART-     11-16 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MONDAY-NIGHT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: relaxed tones.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Upstairs, there is an exhibition of seamless coordination. On
nearly every play, Michaels adjusts his glance from the field to
the monitors and to Kelly Hayes, the spotter, whose right index
finger guides Michaels to his color-coordinated spotter's board
with players' names and statistics. The names emerge from Michaels'
mouth without pause.
</P>
<P>
   Using data from his play-by-play score card, the statistician,
George Hill, writes out yardage gained, time of possession or
timeouts remaining on white index cards that he passes to his
right, usually to Michaels, who frequently leans over during breaks
to ask for information.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels and Esiason stand throughout nearly all the game,
wearing headsets. Sometimes, Esiason turns left to Michaels, bends
his knees and spreads his arms to stress a point. Michaels rarely
turns to his partner. Their gesturing describes an ongoing chat, if
not with themselves, then with viewers. Michaels likens his
gesturing to a band leader's exertions to advance the music.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the crew whose role is a wild card is Lesley
Visser. Cautioned twice by National Football League officials last
month for encroaching beyond the dotted yellow line on the
sideline, Visser is mostly at the mercy of breaking news, injuries,
coaches' revelations _ and the elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duchess, how are you doing?'' Michaels asks her during a
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like frozen custard,'' says Visser, who is wearing work
boots over two pairs of socks that are separated by a plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   This night, the coldest of the season, she never leaves the
field for a break and is barely on camera. ``Better to be seen too
little than too much,'' she says, ``so people are glad to see
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels is clearly the star of the first two-man ``Monday
Night'' booth since 1986. Esiason, with his career as a quarterback
with the Jets, Bengals and Cardinals, his platinum-blond hair and
hulking physique, is more recognizable. But Michaels is more
accomplished: a play-by-play announcer who is part analyst,
offering more than a terse recitation of play and yardage.
</P>
<P>
   To gain an analytic foothold, Esiason is focusing more on what
quarterbacks do, as he works on a broader vision of the field. He's
got a quick, judgmental wit. In comparing Johnson to Minnesota's
Cris Carter, Esiason says: ``Keyshawn Johnson's an arrogant Cris
Carter. He'll tell you how good he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason's smartest call is his rapid detection of a pass
interference call _ in essence, an illegal pick by the Jets Richie
Anderson _ that negates a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason enjoys chiding Michaels, mostly about his partner's love
of The Four Seasons hotel chain, and recently feigned offense when
the stage manager handed Michaels a hot dog before him. ``I know
he's the star and all,'' Esiason said.
</P>
<P>
   One senses that Esiason wants to be known for being
unpredictable. At halftime of last month's Giants-Cowboys game,
Michaels conducted a somber interview with Michael Irvin, the
Dallas receiver who had suffered a spinal injury a week earlier.
Just as the conversation ended, Esiason strode into the booth and
asked loudly, ``Hey, did anybody cry yet?''
</P>
<P>
   During a commercial break on Monday, Esiason says he will be
attending an event this week at the ESPN Zone restaurant. ``I'm
representing `Monday Night Football,' '' he says, with a
characteristic tone of exasperation. ``That's all I do, represent
`Monday Night Football,' without you.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaels responds, ``I'll be representing `Monday Night
Football' at the Canyon Ranch in Tucson.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of Dierdorf is turning Michaels and Esiason into an
increasingly viable team. They appear to like each other. At one
point, Michaels asks Esiason how long his throat needed to heal
from last week's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wednesday,'' Esiason says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad. What did you take for it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not,'' Esiason says, ``I just shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets race to a 24-3 lead, but New England closes to 24-17,
behind Bledsoe's touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``True to form, Drew Bledsoe is sticking it to his old coach,''
Esiason says.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier in the quarter, during a break, he sounded
frustrated by Bledsoe: ``Every week, we get one lousy quarterback
performance.'' Despite the surprise of a Jet victory, it is not an
edge-of-the-seat thriller. The scoring ends midway through the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels and Esiason leave quickly, escorted out of Foxboro by
motorcycle police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't had a compelling game in a long time,''
Michaels says in the limo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants-Buffalo Super Bowl,'' Wolfe says. ``Maybe we should
play the second halves first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People only remember the end,'' says Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, they don't remember the end,'' says Wolfe.
``They're asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of coming games fails to excite Michaels. The
season ends with San Francisco against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to think about it,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
