<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PLATT-PLATT_SFCHRON &LR;      11-16 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATT-PLATT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Kendall-Jackson Set to Take on the World  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The appointment of former Hewlett-Packard chief executive Lewis
Platt to the helm of Kendall-Jackson at the beginning of next year
is designed to help the biggest North Coast wine producer become
more of a global competitor.
<P>
   It also positions K-J for a possible public stock offering as
early as the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Platt, 58, who was replaced as CEO at HP in July by Carly
Fiorina, retains his chairman title at the nation's second-largest
computer company until December. After that, he said in an
interview, he will move from Los Altos to Sonoma County and begin
his ``second career.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kendall-Jackson and Hewlett-Packard would not seem to
have much in common aside from their hyphenated names, Platt said
both face similar challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation is taking place in both industries, and both
industries are increasingly global,'' said Platt, who has spent the
past 33 years with HP and the last seven as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Jess Jackson, the 69-year-old founder and chairman of K-J, said
he was attracted to Platt because of his maturity and worldwide
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In September, K-J also made another key move. It hired Boston
Beer Co. Chief Financial Officer Alfred Rossow to fill the CFO slot
at K-J, which had been vacant for three years. (K-J's previous CFO,
Peter Scott, took a similar position at Beringer, which changed its
name to Beringer Wine Estates and went public.)
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, K-J changed its name last week from
Kendall-Jackson Winery to Kendall Jackson Wine Estates.
</P>
<P>
   ``K-J now has a killer lineup with more public company
experience than either Beringer or Robert Mondavi,'' said David
Freed, a partner of Silverado partners winery and vineyard
investment firm in Napa. ``I would expect an IPO next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt declined to say if or when K-J might go public but
acknowledged that a stock offering would ``definitely be one way to
gain more capital to expand.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``Going public is always a consideration, but I'm
not sure the distraction of going public is something we need right
now.'' To go public, he observed, a company must perform
consistently, but in the wine business it is sometimes necessary to
make long-term investments at the expense of short-term profits.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be too negative on the notion of going public, Jackson
quickly added, ``Lew Platt and Al Rossow could take us there in a
blink.'' If K-J decides to do an initial public offering, Jackson
suggested ``it wouldn't be before the end of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, K-J sold nearly 3.8 million cases of wine for $362
million. The company has more than a dozen brands and owns wineries
in California as well as Argentina, Chile and Italy. But compared
to HP, which gets more than half its $5 billion revenues from
overseas sales, K-J is provincial. More than 90 percent of its
sales are domestic.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jackson and Platt want to make K-J more of a global wine
power.
</P>
<P>
   Although Platt has not toiled previously in the wine field, he
has been a wine fan and collector since moving to California in
1980. For his wife's 50th birthday in 1995, he shelled out $3,000
for a 1945 bottle of Chateau Petrus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
