<SLUG> BC-WACO-SHELLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special counsel seeks custody of shell casings found at Mount
Carmel
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Special Counsel John Danforth asked U.S. District
Judge Walter S. Smith Jr. of Waco Tuesday to grant him temporary
custody of shell casings found in 1993 at a government sniper
position at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   The request comes after Danforth asked the FBI to turn over all
weapons carried during the Branch Davidian siege.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Office of the Special Counsel wants to determine
whether the shell casings came from bullets fired by the ATF or the
FBI. The FBI has insisted that its agents did not fire any shots
during the siege.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers' report to Congress in September stated that
the agency recovered a dozen .308-caliber sniper rifle casings and
24 Israeli-made .223-caliber casings from a house across from Mount
Carmel. ATF agents originally used it as an undercover house. FBI
agents later used the house as an observation post and sniper
position.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the FBI's weapons have been retooled, testing the shell
casings could prove productive, according to the lead attorney for
the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not change the hammer on the firing mechanism,'' said
Houston lawyer Mike Caddell. ``It's the strike mark on the shell
casings that can be analyzed microscopically and determined if
there's a match between any of those shell casings and the weapons
used by the FBI at Mount Carmel on April 19.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agent in charge of the sniper position was Lon Horiuchi,
who is a defendant in the wrongful death lawsuit filed by surviving
Branch Davidians against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Horiuchi has denied firing any shots at Mount Carmel, although
he admittedly fired the shot that killed Randy Weaver's wife,
Vicki, at Ruby Ridge. An FBI agent, who later recanted his
statement, reported hearing a shot come from the direction of the
sniper position held by Horiuchi on the day of the fire that led to
the deaths of David Koresh and 75 followers.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth _ in a motion filed by Edward L. Dowd Jr., deputy
special counsel _ told Smith that he wanted the shell casings so
that he could have them reviewed by experts and tested.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the deadline set by Smith for any government agency
to turn over evidence pertaining to the Davidian lawsuit. The case
is set for trial this May.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the shell casings, Danforth asked Smith for a May 1993
report by the Texas Rangers related to the test firing of ATF
weapons; negatives and crime scene photographs taken by the Rangers
or the FBI; the Rangers' plan for recovering evidence at Mount
Carmel; and any Rangers' diary, journal, notes or memorandum
discussing the collection of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Mark England writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
E-mail: mengland(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
