u f BC-MILLENNIUM-AD-COLUMN-     11-16 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MANY CONSUMERS BRISTLE AT MILLENNIUM HYPE, AGENCY
CONCLUDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the countdown to the millennium begins in the advertising
world, one huge global agency has some surprising advice: don't
hype it.
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising, with worldwide clients
like Coca-Cola, General Motors and Nestle, says surveys of consumer
attitudes show that many are already tired of the hoopla
surrounding the New Year and that promoting it will just create
more background noise.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, some consumers _ mainly outside the United States _
automatically associate the millennium with the Year 2000 computer
problem and serious havoc, not exactly the kind of association an
advertiser wants to make.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by McCann Pulse, a research service
division of McCann-Erickson, part of the McCann-Erickson World
Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos. McCann Pulse tries to
determine behavior and attitudes, the better to create advertising
to which consumers will respond.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that for most consumers the millennium has
symbolic and emotional meaning about the future and the past, said
Joseph Plummer, executive vice president and director for global
brands strategy at McCann-Erickson Worldwide in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to a big promotional event like the Super Bowl, the
coming millennium is less about a big party than it is about
feelings that run surprisingly deep. Thus, for all but the most
light-hearted products, to play up the millennium with a big
short-term promotion would miss the point and perhaps even annoy
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, young adults surveyed in the United States, Germany and
the United Kingdom expressed irritation about Year 2000 media hype.
In Britain, in particular, young adults expressed fear that high
prices would prevent them from celebrating the way they would like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are expecting the hype _ that will only put you in
the pack with everyone else,'' Plummer said. ``Most of the
associations and feelings around the world have to do with
longer-term hopes and dreams, things like peace on earth and better
education. If that's how consumers are feeling, to run a promotion
for December with a big giveaway belittles it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, true party-oriented products like candy bars can
rightly cash in on the millennium, especially if the promotion is
intended for children, Plummer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a fun product, and you want to just have fun, then
it's fine,'' he said. ``But on a deeper level, we're saying to try
to associate with it in a bigger, more long-term way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, McCann Worldwide urged some clients to sponsor the
Millennium Wheel and the Millennium Dome, both in England, as a way
to associate with the New Year in a positive and meaningful way.
The Millennium Wheel in London is a 1,500-ton Ferris wheel,
offering 25-mile views, that was constructed for the millennium and
will remain a permanent tourist attraction. The Millennium Dome is
a huge exhibition space being constructed in Greenwich, England.
Both are taking corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of thing people really appreciate,'' Plummer
said. ``Both will be there long beyond January, they have
permanence, and are symbols of reviewing the past and looking to
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann began conducting surveys last March in response to client
inquiries about whether to capitalize on the millennium. The survey
included talking to 1,500 people in 19 countries, and was followed
up in August and September with additional questions to another
1,500 people in 21 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't thinking of asking about it, but in country after
country Y2K came up, so we decided to explore it deeper,'' Plummer
said, referring to the popular designation for Year 2000 computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that in countries like the United States there
was a feeling that the issue was being addressed. (This consumer
feeling may account for some advertising here that pokes fun at the
subject.) But respondents in places like Russia and Indonesia
expressed great concern and the advice is to steer clear of any
millennium promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also revealed another simmering consumer view in the
United States: that technology is growing too powerful. In
interviews, consumers even made associations between possible Year
2000 problems and biotechnology, which Plummer said ``really scares
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology showed up as an Achilles' heel,'' he said.
``There's this sense that we'll get through Y2K but that technology
is pervasive, that its getting too powerful and that it's
worrisome.''
</P>
<P>
   To offset this feeling, Plummer said marketers of technology
brands from equipment manufacturers to high-technology
communications services need to reinforce consumer trust over the
long term. The agency also has recommended that advertisers, even
those not usually associated with possible technical problems,
reassure consumers that they have checked their systems. This
advice seems to be conventional wisdom in the advertising world
given the vast amount of advertising and direct mail addressing the
computer-readiness issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a delicate balance, and it needs to be quite factual,''
said Plummer, adding that companies can only check their systems,
but don't really know what will happen. ``It's extremely important
not to overpromise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2212EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
