r f BC-ABALONE-ABALONE_SFCHR     11-16 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABALONE-ABALONE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 
 Pearls Add Luster to Risky Abalone Venture 
 &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Abalone farming isn't the quickest way to make a buck. Although the
rock-clinging mollusk is in short supply and its meat fetches $60
or more per pound, the seaweed-munching mollusks grow at a snail's
pace.
<P>
   It takes at least three years of care and feeding to grow a
modest 3-incher in captivity. To fetch a greater return, US Abalone
of Santa Cruz County, also known as US Abs, is muscling into a new
market with its abalone pearls.
</P>
<P>
   The Davenport aquaculture company, which grows abalone in
beachside tanks, has just printed a catalog for its cultured
abalone pearls fashioned by Carmel's Crossroads Jewelers and plans
to sell them from its Web site (www.usabalone.com).
</P>
<P>
   Pearls produced by abalone are not the traditional spherical
variety produced by oysters. Unlike the docile bivalve, abalone
have a powerful foot that is adept at kicking out foreign objects.
</P>
<P>
   That would ordinarily make it hard to culture abalone pearls.
However, US Abs says it has a proprietary way to permanently attach
an inserted bead to the inside of the abalone's shell. The bead is
then covered with layers of lustrous nacre. After 12 to 18 months,
the critter can be harvested both for meat and a ``blister'' or
half-dome ``mabe'' pearl, which might sell for $200 or $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could make a living doing meat, but pearls make us
interesting to Wall Street,'' said US Abalone CEO James Webb, who
has started talking to investment bankers about a possible IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Abalone traditionally has been a pricey item on the menu, with
restaurants charging $40 to $80 for a single entree. Webb said it
is popular from sushi bars in Japan to San Francisco restaurants
such as Rubicon, Big Four and Charles-Nob Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Duarte's Tavern in Pescadero charges $22.50 for a sandwich and
$45 for an abalone dinner. ``It's a good seller,'' said owner Ron
Duarte. ``But it's really tedious work to prepare and we'd love to
get bigger ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-inch abalone that sell for $4 or $5 each yield only about
an ounce of meat, and the texture and mild flavor are similar to
the much cheaper scallop or calamari steak.
</P>
<P>
   US Abs hopes to turn a profit this quarter, but it has been a
long time coming. Webb, whose background includes stints as a
private investigator, a fishing boat captain and a venture
capitalist for Alan Shugart's Pebble Beach Ventures, got interested
in aquaculture while writing a thesis on the subject for an MBA
degree in Monterey in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrimp, salmon, catfish and trout are commodities,'' he said.
``I wanted something in short supply and high demand.'' He teamed
up with marine biologist Tom Ebert, whose father, Earl, pioneered
growing abalone in captivity while working for the California
Department of Fish and Game in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   US Abalone raised $5 million from private investors, including
$2 million in a direct Internet stock offering three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   US Abalone started at Pillar Point by Half Moon Bay, growing
abalone in cages suspended from floating rafts. But Webb said the
labor cost to raise and lower the cages to feed and harvest the
abalone was too high. The site also lacked the controlled growing
conditions US Abs now has on 4 acres of beachfront land about 10
miles north of Santa Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The company bought the facility from SilverKing Oceanic Farms,
another aquaculture company that had a bright idea but hit
financial shoals in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   SilverKing raised smolt, released them to the ocean and then
waited for them to return up the fish ladder to their original home
years later, fat and ready for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that commercial fishermen quickly learned
of the annual homecoming and perched offshore to intercept the
incoming salmon. SilverKing mounted a legal challenge but came up
empty again and went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   US Abs leased the site in 1993 and took two years to get permits
to grow Haliotis rufescens, also known as Pacific red abalone,
which can grow to 10 inches or more in the sea.
</P>
<P>
   But coastal abalone is increasingly rare as a result of
overharvesting and a commercial moratorium on abalone hunting.
Voracious sea otters and disease also have taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Farm-raised abalone is a pricey and puny alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The process starts with trying to make abalone more amorous. In
the wild, abalone release their eggs and sperm at about the same
time once a year.
</P>
<P>
   For a commercial abalone grower, who wants a continuous supply
of product, that is not a good trait. To prod the gastropods to
procreate on a more-regular basis, their handlers resort to various
tricks like increasing the water temperature, turning on
ultraviolet lights or throwing a splash of hydrogen peroxide into
their water.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the nearly microscopic ``seed'' abalone are put in
separate tanks where they are fed single algae called diatoms.
After consuming this baby food diet for about six months and
growing about half an inch, the young abalone are treated to
seaweed for the first time and consume a whopping 5 percent of
their body weight a day.
</P>
<P>
   US Abs has about 2 million abalone at various stages of
development and hopes to increase sales from 100,000 this year to
500,000 in 2000. Within a few years it hopes to have at least half
its crop producing pearls.
</P>
<P>
   Although this will add a year or more to the growing cycle, it
should be far more profitable than selling only the meat.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 20 licensed abalone farms in California but
only about a half-dozen are producing. The biggest is Abalone Farm
near Morro Bay in Luis Obispo County, which sells about 600,000
live and vacuum-packed abalone a year. But it has been profitable
only for 2 two  &LR; of the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely labor-intensive and difficult business,''
said Abalone Farm President Ray Fields. ``But farmers are eternal
optimists.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are abalone slow growing, they can succumb to various
problems. The abalone-eating sabellid worm accidentally imported
from South Africa in the early 1980s has wreaked havoc in some
unprotected farms. Warming seas caused by El Ni &LR; n &LR; o in 1997 and
1998 also killed many abalone. So has fresh water runoff during
winter and spring storms.
</P>
<P>
   At Tomales Bay in Marin County, Abalone Acres and Liquid Earth
Abalone were both washed out of business by storms that reduced the
salinity of the water to the point where most of their abalone
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Mariculture of Santa Cruz is another abalone farm that
also no longer answers the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, entrepreneurs are clamoring to get into the
abalone business. In July, four abalone farms received permission
from the California Coastal Commission to grow more than 2 million
abalone in floating cages off Pillar Point in San Mateo County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
