<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Export Market Is Big for Small Businesses 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I have a small business that sells to a number of states but am
interested in exploring exporting overseas. Where do I to start
looking for information?
<P>
   A: You are not alone. More and more small businesses are rushing
into the export market.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Small Business Administration reported last week that
the number of small businesses that sell abroad tripled in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses now account for nearly 31 percent of total &LR; 
 &LR; U.S. exports and 97 percent of all firms that export are small
businesses. Emerging markets are especially important to small
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   For example, small exporters are responsible for about 38
percent of all U.S. goods going to China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   So, where to start? You might try the Small Business
Administration's Office of International Trade Web site
(www.sba.gov/oit). It discusses a range of resources including
trade links for first-time exporters.
</P>
<P>
   There are 19 U.S. Export Assistance Centers, which market the
SBA's loan guarantee programs to small business exporters and
lenders. The closest center is in San Jose, and they will guarantee
as much as 90 percent of a purchase order up to $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Sachs, director of the export assistance center in Long
Beach, says these centers help ``export-ready clients'' who either
have exported before or have received inquiries from potential
overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
   For small businesses like yours which are just starting to
explore opportunities, Sachs suggests checking out SBA-sponsored
training conferences or getting counseling through the Service
Corps of Retired Executives and the nationwide network of Small
Business Development Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Also check out the U.S. Department of Commerce's Trade Promotion
Association. Its comprehensive trade database allows you to check
which countries might be most interested in your product and who
your main competitors would be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Software Deductions
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: What are the rules on deducting the cost of software bought by a
business?
</P>
<P>
   A: As a general rule, software bought for business use must be
depreciated over a 36-month period, according to tax attorney Fred
Daily. But there are three important exceptions:
</P>
<P>
   _Software with a useful life of less than a year _ and given the
rapid change in technology, this could apply to a lot of programs _
can be deducted as a business expense in the year you buy it.
</P>
<P>
   _When software comes with a computer, and its cost is not
separately stated, it is treated as part of the hardware and
depreciated over five years.
</P>
<P>
   _You can write off an entire computer system, including bundled
software, in the first year (under a special provision, IRC Sec.
179) if the total cost is less than $19,000.
</P>
<P>
   Daily, author of ``Tax Savvy for Small Business'' (Nolo Press,
$29.95, &LR; ) &LR;   &LR; ( &LR; www.nolo.com), also offers these six year-end tax
planning tips for small businesses:
</P>
<P>
   1. Establish and contribute to a tax-advantaged retirement plan
such as an IRA, Keogh or 401(k). By contributing before the end of
1999, you not only will get a tax deduction, but see your earnings
in the plan compound tax-deferred. Hint: if you don't have the
money, you might want to borrow it for the tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   2. Buy that new computer or other business equipment before the
end of the year and deduct up to $19,000 without having to take the
usual long-term depreciation deduction. Tip: You can still get this
deduction if you only charge the expense and don't pay for it until
next year!
</P>
<P>
   3. Get your records in order. Accurate records are the key to
getting your tax return done in time and can ward off an IRS audit.
Hint: Use a simple software program like Quicken.
</P>
<P>
   4. Sell or donate obsolete business equipment and out of date
inventory by the end of 1999. This will offset your business income
and reduce your taxes. Tip: If you donate goods, make sure you can
back up the donation with documents showing the value and to whom
the items were given.
</P>
<P>
   5. Prepay state income taxes for 1999. If you pay all of your
state income taxes before the end of December (instead of waiting
until April 15, 2000), you get the full federal tax deduction for
1999. Otherwise, you'll have to wait another year.
</P>
<P>
   6. Buy supplies and other business items you would normally
purchase in the first part of next year, to accelerate the
deduction to 1999. Typically, the earlier you can claim a
tax-deduction, the longer you will have use of the money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
