u f BC-DRUG-MERGER-NYT &LR;      11-16 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER INCREASES EFFORT TO WIN WARNER-LAMBERT BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pfizer stepped up its effort Tuesday to acquire Warner-Lambert,
beginning its attempt to oust the New Jersey company's board of
directors and outlining the advantages of the hostile takeover to
Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   William Steere, Pfizer's chairman, also made it clear that he
was not going to be overly patient in his dealings with
Warner-Lambert. Two weeks ago, Warner-Lambert had announced a $72
billion merger with American Home Products, which included a $2
billion breakup fee and a clause that would hinder the use of stock
in a future deal.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer filed an amended complaint in Delaware Chancery court
Tuesday that could hasten the removal of both roadblocks. In the
company's annual meeting with analysts Tuesday, Pfizer executives
said that they expected the court to rule in the company's favor in
four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Steere expressed even more confidence. Speaking to analysts and
reporters about Pfizer's bid to acquire Warner-Lambert, he noted
that Pfizer ``would persist and prevail,'' and that his company
``was determined to seize this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer had planned to use the meeting with analysts Tuesday to
ward off concerns that its bounty of drugs under development
trailed that of many of its competitors. Pfizer's executives spent
more than two hours detailing the progress of their existing drugs
_ seven of which have projected annual worldwide sales this year of
$1 billion or more _ before highlighting several compounds under
development.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Pfizer clearly had other motives. The company wasted little
time reminding executives of Pfizer's sizzling historic financial
performance in comparison with many of its competitors. In several
key categories _ including 1999 year-to-date revenue growth _
Pfizer and Warner-Lambert were industry leaders, while American
Home Products was 12th.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Home Products said that the company's
pipeline was the strongest in its 73-year history and that as far
as the company was concerned, it was the strongest pipeline in the
entire pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer executives also noted that Warner-Lambert would actually
hurt its own financial performance if it were to merge with
American Home Products. Pfizer said that Warner-Lambert's pro forma
return on equity would drop to 34 percent from 40 percent if that
merger took place.
</P>
<P>
   While Steere and his executives were enthusiastic about their
proposed takeover of Warner-Lambert, the day's presentations
clearly irritated Lodewijk de Vink, Warner-Lambert's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers Pfizer presented today created no long-term stock
value,'' he said. ``Their deal is about now. Our merger with
American Home Products will help us achieve our strategic objective
to create a company based on new product introductions.'' Despite
de Vink's reservations, several analysts said they were favorably
impressed by Pfizer's presentation. The company provided details on
three new drugs, including one for asthma, that some analysts
believed could be strong sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am always impressed with Pfizer's presentations,'' said
Viren Mehta, a partner at Mehta Partners. ``Pfizer is clearly
committed to acquiring Warner-Lambert at any cost. They are trying
to establish a position of strength so they will not feel rushed to
change their offer for Warner-Lambert in haste.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer has also applied more pressure to its court case. Pfizer
made a point of noting that Warner-Lambert's tactics to avoid a
takeover could harm the combined company if Pfizer's takeover bid
is successful.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues in the court case is the type of bookkeeping
that Pfizer would use to account for its proposed merger. As part
of its amended court complaint, Pfizer said that if it had to use
purchase accounting to buy Warner-Lambert, the good will from the
transaction could be in excess of $80 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
