<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CAMPBELL-CAMPBELL_SFC     11-16 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-CAMPBELL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft `Big Time' Guilty, Silicon Valley Congressman Says  &HT;     By Carolyn Lochhead 
 &HT;     Chronicle Washington Bureau 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Washington _ Tom Campbell is a House Republican who represents
Silicon Valley and also happens to teach antitrust law at Stanford
University.
<P>
   If his views on the Microsoft case carry any credibility, the
Seattle software giant should settle now before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said in an interview that media coverage has widely
overlooked the most damning conclusions of Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson's 207-page findings of fact: Microsoft met with its
competitors for the clear purpose of restraining trade.
</P>
<P>
   Such a violation of Section 1 of the Sherman Act is so basic and
so clear cut that Microsoft is ``big time'' guilty, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gotten no attention to speak of,'' he said, since
even the Justice Department has been riveted on the judge's finding
that Microsoft is a monopolist that abused its power to harm
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   That finding deals with the much grayer Section 2 of the Sherman
Act, Campbell said, and could be questioned and even reversed on
appeal, despite the deference courts give to a trial judge's fact
findings.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge's finding that Microsoft executives met with
competitors _ Netscape, Intel, Apple Computer, IBM and RealNetworks
_ for the purpose of dividing markets and restricting competition
is what lawyers call a ``per se violation'' of Section 1 that
leaves no room for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge finds that Microsoft did that,'' Campbell said.
Whether the actions harmed consumers or had any effect whatsoever
is irrelevant. Such meetings are simply illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is garden variety,'' Campbell said. ``You must not sit down
with your competitor and agree not to compete. If the antitrust
attorney at Microsoft didn't tell that to the boss, then she or he
ought to have been fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a prohibition ``is so basic in law that a company that goes
ahead and does it anyway brings out the most strenuous
enforcement,'' Campbell said. ``I think the Justice Department is
going to go for a very, very tough remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he added, ``Since this is what Judge Jackson believes
_ he believes that Bill Gates sat down with his competitors and
proposed an agreement not to compete _ I think the judge is going
to be disposed to grant the toughest kind of relief that Justice
asks for.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, the California Democrat whom Campbell is
challenging next November, has not commented extensively on the
case. In a television interview last week, Feinstein said she hoped
for a settlement and questioned whether the 1890 Sherman Act should
apply to the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is opening up a kind of commerce and a way of
doing business that has been atypical and unknown in the United
States,'' Feinstein said. ``So the law has to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell agreed that Section 2 of the Sherman Act may be
inappropriate to the high-tech industry, which is characterized by
so-called network effects, in which standardization around core
technologies leads to a winner-take-all pattern of industrial
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Microsoft is the classic example of such a pattern; its
ubiquitous Windows operating system both enables the writing of
software applications that everyone can use, and creates what
Jackson found to be a ``barrier to entry'' by competing operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Section 1 is ``as good today as it was in 1890,'' Campbell
argued. ``There is nothing entrepreneurial about agreeing with a
competitor not to compete. ... If the judge's finding is correct
that the CEO of a very, very important company sat with a
competitor and agreed not to compete, then it was essential that
Justice bring this case, or else we don't have a rule of law in
this line of our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Letting such actions go unpunished, he argued, would do far more
economic damage than pursuing them. ``If price fixing, market
division, agreements not to compete were permitted, it would be
devasting to the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Campbell's conservatives colleagues sharply disagree,
attacking the government suit as an unwarranted intrusion that will
lead to government regulation of the world's most dynamic market.
</P>
<P>
   As Sen. Slade Gorton, the Washington Republican who is
Microsoft's most vigorous political defender, put it, ``Should the
government take a major step toward destroying America's greatest
success story and regulating the high-tech industry, our global
leadership in the area of high tech will be put at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell agreed that any continuing government regulation of
Microsoft's actions should be avoided, but he said he does not view
a breakup with the loathing that some conservatives do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a clean solution that does not involve the
government monitoring business practices _ and on these things I am
conservative, I'm very much against the federal government
regulating how business is done _ a clean way to solve this is a
separation of the operating system from applications,'' Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also dismissed conservative critics who have begun
arguing that the precedent for Microsoft is not the famously
successful breakup of the AT&AMP;T telephone monopoly, but rather the
government's pursuit of United Shoe Machinery Corp. in 1953 and the
Schwinn bicycle company in 1967, both now widely viewed as
misguided and destructive.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he teaches both cases as ``pathologies'' of
antitrust case law, because neither company had the market power
that the government alleged. But both cases are ``terribly false
examples'' to apply to Microsoft, he argued. ``AT&AMP;T was a
monopolist, Microsoft is a monopolist, United Shoe was not a
monopolist and Schwinn was not a monopolist,'' he said. ``Both of
those were eventually roundly criticized and are no longer followed
in antitrust.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
