<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT TESTIFIES, BLAMES OTHERS FOR DRAGGING DEATH 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999, Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Shawn Berry never took Bill King's threats to
harm a black man seriously because the white supremacist had a
reputation for talking big and then walking away, Berry told jurors
Tuesday in his capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just Bill,'' he said. ``Ask anyone who knows Bill if
he'd ever back up anything he said, and they'll tell you no.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berry also testified that when King threatened him, he was
so petrified that he gave up his attempts to intervene, stepped
aside and watched as his two co-defendants beat James Byrd Jr.,
chained his ankles to a pickup and dragged him more than three
miles through the East Texas woods last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do anything more to stop them. I couldn't move,''
Berry said. ``I didn't say anything. I didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 24, spent more than four hours on the witness stand,
blaming his co-defendants for the gruesome killing on June 7, 1998.
King, 25, and Russell Brewer Jr., 32, were tried separately earlier
this year and were sent to death row.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's case is expected to go to an all-white jury today after
closing arguments. If convicted, Berry will return to the courtroom
for the trial's punishment phase, which could result in a life
prison sentence or death by injection.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, prosecutors showed the jury seven statements, some of
them conflicting, that Berry gave police shortly after his arrest,
and they played excerpts from a jailhouse interview by CBS anchor
Dan Rather that was broadcast on 60 Minutes II in September.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Berry tried to explain his changing stories to the
jury as his lawyer, Joseph C. ``Lum'' Hawthorn, read each sentence
of his statements and asked Berry whether they were true or false.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had nothing to do with it whatsoever,'' Berry said in his
first statement, which he contends is still true.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said he lied when he told investigators that King was
driving as the three men headed into the woods east of Jasper with
Byrd in the bed of Berry's pickup. He lied again, he said, when he
told police he had run away once he realized King and Brewer
intended to attack Byrd, 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to say that I drove out to that road,'' Berry
said. ``I didn't want to say that I was anywhere near Mr. Byrd.''
</P>
<P>
   After the men left Byrd's mangled, decapitated corpse outside
the gates of a black cemetery and headed back to their apartment,
Berry said King and Brewer convinced him that he was just as guilty
as they were for being present at the crime scene, and he said he
feared retaliation from the two racists if he turned them in to
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill said if I were to turn them in, no matter what prison
unit I ended up in, they'd find me,'' he said. ``I believe anybody
in their right mind would be worried about them.''
</P>
<P>
   But on cross-examination, Jasper County District Attorney Guy
James Gray suggested that Berry was lying for a more obvious reason
_ to save his own skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't want to admit the degree of your involvement,''
said Gray, who contends Berry was a full participant in the killing
and that he drove the truck not just to the crime scene but also as
Byrd was being dragged.
</P>
<P>
   And Gray reminded Berry of his previous testimony that King had
a habit of making threats he never carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time Bill King ever said anything, he was never near the
person,'' Berry explained. ``This time, he was acting on what he
said. And he had Russell Brewer with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray also pointed out that instead of calling his uncle, a
highway patrolman, for help, Berry spent the day after the killing
getting rid of the evidence. He and King went to a local carwash to
clean Berry's truck and to wash off a 24-foot logging chain used to
drag Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Berry later led police to the chain, which he said had been
stashed by King and Brewer in the woods outside a friend's trailer
house.
</P>
<P>
   Gray pointed out that Berry had used the word ``we'' 45 times in
his written statements to police, but by the time he appeared on
national television, he had rehearsed his story and had begun to
use the word ``they.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he gave a performance equal to the 60 Minutes
performance,'' Gray said outside the courthouse later. ``He is a
pretty good witness. He's a nice looking boy. (But) I don't believe
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premise that he didn't know what his companions were like
and he was going out there just merely to drink beer and nothing
else, that's not true,'' Gray continued, ``and I don't think anyone
can believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said Berry's testimony was very believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did great,'' he said. ``I'm very, very happy with
the way he did and I've heard a lot of people say the same thing. I
think he was very credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn rested the defense case Tuesday by showing jurors a
color photo of Berry and his young son, Montana, on an overhead
projector.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden is expected to decide this
morning whether to allow prosecutors to show the jury photos of
King's and Brewer's racist tattoos, which they got while members of
the Confederate Knights of America, a small racist prison gang.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the tattoos would help jurors decide whether it
would have been obvious to Berry that he was placing Byrd in danger
by offering him a ride in the middle of the night while he was with
two Klansmen.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Berry's brother, Louis, read a statement on KJAS, a
local radio station, expressing sympathy for the Byrd family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply sorry about what has happened,'' Louis Berry said.
``I wish there was something I could do to stop the hurt and pain
for all the families involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Berry said his family wanted to reach out to the Byrd
family but didn't know what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish I could have been with my brother on that night,''
he said. ``I sincerely believe I could have helped him prevent what
happened. I believe he was simply by himself and outnumbered by
people who had already made up their mind.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
