<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO CLEAR THE WAY FOR KOBE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kobe Bryant is nearly ready to play again, and his
imminent return from the injured list will force changes to both
the starting lineup and the 12-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant will be reevaluated this morning by team orthopedist Dr.
Stephen Lombardo. He already has resumed shooting, dribbling and
light-contact drills and has proclaimed himself recovered from the
broken right hand he suffered Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns, the Los Angeles Lakers will once again be
overloaded with guards and small forwards.
</P>
<P>
   They waived Sam Jacobson last week to make room for forward
Robert Horry but are still carrying just five big men to go with
seven guards and small forwards.
</P>
<P>
   That means a guard will be removed to make room for Bryant, and
the likely choice is to send rookie John Celestand back to injured
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get big guys,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``We
need big bodies on this team. We've got a lot of small forwards and
guards _ I don't like to have over seven on the roster, players who
can bring the ball, handle the ball. And then you've got to have
your five big guys who can take the abuse and the pounding and
cover the lane, rebounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Celestand was activated Monday when Tyronn Lue went to the
injured list because of a sore right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's eventual return to the starting lineup will force
either Ron Harper or Derek Fisher to the bench. Jackson likes to
play big-guard tandems, which would seem to favor Harper, but
Jackson said he hasn't made that decision yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be Harper that goes to the bench. (Bryant) may be
teamed with Derek. We'll see how that goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Fisher remains a starter, Jackson looks forward to
playing long stretches when the 6-foot-7 Bryant is teamed in the
backcourt with either the 6-6 Harper, 6-6 Brian Shaw or 6-7 Rick
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have anticipated playing big guards together,'' he said.
``When (Bryant) comes back, that's going to be part of the
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballot time: Fan voting for the NBA All-Star teams opened
Tuesday, with four Lakers on the Western Conference ballot: Bryant,
Shaquille O'Neal, Glen Rice and Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots are available at NBA arenas, movie theaters and online
at www.NBA.com.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game will be played Feb. 13 at the Oakland Coliseum
Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
