<SLUG> BC-TV-SANFRANCISCO-465&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG SURPRISE IN KRON-TV SALE WAS THE BUYER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Young Broadcasting Inc. will be heavily in debt,
bereft of any history in San Francisco and probably not on the best
of terms with NBC after stunning the TV industry this week by
buying NBC affiliate KRON.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, things look peachy for the station and its
future owner.
</P>
<P>
   Young Broadcasting emerged as the winner in the sweepstakes to
buy KRON as part of Chronicle Publishing Co.'s fabulous
going-out-of-business sale, which has included the pending purchase
of the San Francisco Chronicle by Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Young's purchase includes a 51 percent stake in BayTV, the local
cable news and information channel.
</P>
<P>
   That the sale figure is $823 million, the most ever for a TV
station, is the lighter part of the general astonishment. The
bigger surprise was Young _ a station group in which, only three
years ago, WBAY-TV in Green Bay, Wis., looked like an awesomely
muscled giant.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom was that NBC would buy its biggest
affiliate. And if not NBC, then maybe Rupert Murdoch and his Fox
station group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are kind of scratching their heads,'' Don Fitzpatrick,
a San Francisco TV consultant, said of the news that Young will buy
KRON.
</P>
<P>
   With stations in Rockford, Ill., Lansing, Mich., Sioux Falls,
S.D., and similar centers of American urbanity, Young had the
industry visibility of a burrowed mole until it purchased KCAL-TV
in Los Angeles in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It bought the unaffiliated KCAL from the Walt Disney Co. and
immediately embarked on an ambitious program of station
improvements. To wit, it pink-slipped employees in droves. The KCAL
massacre, reasonably enough, is now raising anxieties at KRON.
</P>
<P>
   Deb McDermott, executive vice president of Young Broadcasting,
said by telephone Tuesday that it's too soon to assess the
situation at KRON. But comparisons with KCAL would be erroneous,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said Disney had fattened KCAL to the extent that it
was grossly overstaffed. She said that isn't the case at KRON.
</P>
<P>
   ``KCAL and KRON are two very different television stations,''
McDermott said. ``KRON is absolutely a jewel. ... It's a very
well-run, efficient television station.''
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said it's ``premature'' to say whether existing KRON
managers will be asked to stay. She added that the call letters
will remain KRON, a holdover from the soon-to-end Chronicle era.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said all the right things about her company's
commitment to local TV news. But a quick survey of journalists in
cities where Young owns stations indicated a spectrum of good and
bad news operations.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick, who is particularly knowledgeable about TV news,
described the Young Broadcasting shops as ``kind of nondescript.''
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper reporter in one of Young's bigger cities said the
company runs tight news operations and invests relatively little in
physical plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scheduled to visit KRON Wednesday, besides McDermott, were
Vincent Young, chairman and chief executive officer of Young
Broadcasting; Jim Morgan, the company's chief financial officer;
and Ron Kwasnick, president of the Young station group.
</P>
<P>
   San Franciscans may wince to know that among these future
Channel 4 overlords, Young and Morgan are based in New York,
Kwasnick in Lansing, Mich., and McDermott in Nashville, Tenn.
Besides KRON and KCAL, the group's biggest station is WKRN-TV in
Nashville. KRN for corn, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   One local TV veteran, who asked not to be identified, noted
Young's debt load and said he anticipates layoffs and other
cutbacks at KRON.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just not the type of people who are going to fund some
of the things a family-operated station would do,'' the source
said. ``That's just not the way life is.''
</P>
<P>
   The same source also said Young is buying a ripe plum _ the NBC
affiliate in the nation's fifth-largest, and highly lucrative, TV
market. ``There's an expression that you can't get out of the way
of the money in San Francisco,'' the source said. ``I mean business
is very, very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the source said, California television stations will
rake in a pile of revenue from political advertising. And, as an
NBC affiliate, KRON will benefit from the network's carrying the
Summer Olympics from Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The KRON-NBC affiliation contract extends through 2001, and KRON
executives have said that it's virtually unbreakable, even with the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had shocked many industry observers, and perhaps alienated
KRON's owners, by its use of bully-boy tactics to carve out the
station for itself. The tactics included threats to end network
compensation to KRON and to clamp down _ apparently illegally _ on
allowing the station to pre-empt network programming.
</P>
<P>
   NBC reportedly also made a pre-emptive $700 million offer for
KRON and demanded a 30-day exclusive negotiating period.
</P>
<P>
   That offer was rejected and, according to one well-connected
source, NBC wasn't among the final bidders for the station.
</P>
<P>
   But it might be too early to rule out NBC as a future owner of
KRON.
</P>
<P>
   Several sources characterized Young Broadcasting as a
medium-size station group, precisely the type of media company
that's prey for a buyout by a larger company.
</P>
<P>
   The most exotic scuttlebutt Tuesday involved NBC's buying Young
Broadcasting at some future time. That would give the network not
only KRON but also a second outlet in Los Angeles, now permitted
under Federal Communications Commission rules.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, San Francisco is about to enter a new
media environment in which none of its major TV stations, except
public station KQED, is locally owned.
</P>
<P>
   Funny that with all the fuss about newspaper consolidation, no
one in the Bay Area has paid serious attention to the loss of a
locally operated television station. From banks to department
stores to TV stations, and even to newspapers, San Francisco is
becoming a branch office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
