<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH PROBLEMS SLOW UCLA'S RUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA sophomore forward JaRon Rush did not have an
enjoyable freshman year. He was hurt. He was homesick. He was
disciplined for missing practice. His shooting touch never arrived,
and the Bruins lost in the first round of the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Rush spent the summer at home in Kansas City, then returned to
campus hoping for a healthy and happy sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it's been more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   He got sick the first day of practice, lost 10 pounds and missed
a week. Chronic back pain ruined a few more days. He strained his
right elbow during a dunk contest at Preview Day, and last week, he
missed a team meal.
</P>
<P>
   Rush is finally healthy enough to practice, but he can't. He's
in Kansas City on personal business and is questionable for
Thursday's exhibition game. (His absence was approved by coach
Steve Lavin, and Rush is in good standing with the team.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's cool with coach Lavin, we're talking and
communicating,'' Rush said last week. ``I just need to get healthy
and practice. When I'm out there, it clicks. I worked on my
shooting and ballhandling, and with the experience of last year,
I'm more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush, 6-foot-7, has not regained all the weight and strength he
lost while sick, his back is a constant problem, and his elbow has
not healed. But because of his energy level, he needs just two or
three practices to regain rhythm and timing _ meaning he should be
ready for next week's season opener against Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``JaRon has picked up the new offense better than I would have
expected considering he's been out,'' Lavin said. ``He's been
banged up, and he's missed practice time, but considering what he's
missed, he's performed well.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up: The Bruins play their final exhibition Thursday at 7:30
p.m. in Pauley Pavilion against the California Midwest All-Stars,
who feature former Cal State Northridge guard Brooklyn McLinn. The
All-Stars are 2-10 on their tour, defeating Washington 94-87 but
losing to USC 102-90.
</P>
<P>
   The team's fluctuating roster could include former UCLA players
Charles O'Bannon, Pooh Richardson and Mitchell Butler, who have
been cut by NBA teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a tight game,'' Bruins guard Earl Watson said. ``I'd
rather play against Charles, Mitchell and Pooh.''
</P>
<P>
   Young update: Sophomore guard Ray Young won't play Thursday or
next week because of an injured ligament in his right (shooting)
thumb suffered 10 days ago. The Bruins initially feared the
ligament was completely torn, but it now appears to be partially
torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surgery's still a possibility, but we're very encouraged,''
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Who's in, who's out: The Bruins should be in better shape
Thursday than they were last week, when six players were available
to play a Lithuanian club team.
</P>
<P>
   Center Dan Gadzuric might play despite tendinitis in his right
knee and a hyperextended left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jerome Moiso also has tendinitis but is expected to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Rush will play if he's back from Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Ryan Bailey probably won't play because of tendinitis in
his right foot. He has missed several weeks and is questionable for
Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Barnes is academically ineligible during the fall
quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
