A1975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-     11-16 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE REACHES OUT TO ENVIRONMENTALISTS WITH NEW TRADE INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 2 new grafs bgng, In fact ..., to clarify
how order would apply to other countries, add examples from Gore;
pickup 5th graf pvs, Even so ...; also drops Seligman's remark to
last graf only.) 
 (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seeking to win the active support of environmental
groups that have so far failed to muster much enthusiasm for his
presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore announced Tuesday
that President Clinton would sign an executive order requiring that
environmental reviews be part of all new trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``America can and should use its trade policy to strengthen
environmental protection both at home and abroad,'' Gore said in
front of cameras at the airport here before returning to
Washington, D.C. ``This is really a significant, watershed event
for the relationship between trade and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The order will require the U.S. trade representative to conduct
full environmental reviews early in all major negotiations, Gore
said, ``so that we can use that information to shape emerging trade
agreements and to better protect our own environment and the global
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the executive order is not binding on America's trading
partners, but it encourages other nations to take the environment
into account as they develop their economies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he wanted to end subsidies that promote over-fishing
and eliminate trade barriers that prevent the United States from
exporting cutting-edge technologies that could help other countries
clean up their air and water.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the order begins to put environmental concerns on a par
with business concerns in international agreements, a step that
environmental groups hailed Tuesday as significant, if only a start
in the enduring struggle between businesses and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a crucial time, as the world's trade ministers
prepare to meet in Seattle at the end of the month to discuss
international trade rules, and it sends a signal that the United
States considers environmental standards important.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes at a crucial time for Gore in his bid for the
Democratic nomination. He has failed to stir the passions of the
environmental community on his behalf. The administration's
decision to let Gore make Tuesday's announcement was a reflection
both of his need to make some headway with this important
constituency and also of his push to make the administration more
sensitive to environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Petsonk, international counsel for the Environmental
Defense Fund, welcomed the action as a good first step in bringing
the environmental impact of trade agreements before the public.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement Tuesday followed an hour-long closed-door
session with about a dozen environmental leaders here Monday night.
They have expressed concerns about the administration's commitment
to an array of environmental issues, from protection of salmon in
the Pacific Northwest to the permanent placement of a tug boat in
waters here to try to steer oil barges clear of hazards that could
result in spills.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the meeting described Gore's posture as
unusually pleading. He told his listeners that he and Clinton could
not have won in 1992 without their support and that while they may
have been disappointed with some administration actions, he needed
their active involvement now.
</P>
<P>
   He also told them that environmental reviews would be a central
topic at the World Trade Organization talks here later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Seligman, director of the Sierra Club's trade program,
said the spirit of Gore's remarks was encouraging. ``We're not
trying to inject environmental standards into WTO; we want to
prevent WTO from weakening the standards we already have,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
