<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: DELTA TERMINAL AT LAGUARDIA; EVER BIGGER SHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of the improvements have been in place almost a week, but
Thursday the Delta Shuttle will formally open its newly renovated
Marine Air Terminal at New York's La Guardia Airport _ a terminal
used almost exclusively by business travelers flying between New
York and Boston and Washington. The U S Airways Shuttle departs
from that airline's main terminal at La Guardia.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the improvements resulting from Delta's year-long, $7.5
million overhaul are an upgraded business center with free fax and
photocopy services, and several computer stations. A new Bloomberg
News station in the waiting area has two computers and a larger
screen with a continuous display of financial results and stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the gate area, automated ticketing kiosks with touch-screen
technology allow passengers to receive their boarding pass in less
than a minute. The re-designed passenger waiting area now has more
electrical outlets and telephones with data ports for computers.
Baggage carts with cover flaps _ and weather screens on the outside
baggage conveyor belt _ will provide better protection for checked
luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Promising ``many enhancements'' in the near future, William
Crumbley, the managing director of the Delta Shuttle, said that the
overwhelming majority of its passengers traveled to or from New
York. Since its acquisition from Pan Am in 1991, the Delta Shuttle
has carried more than 15 million passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Ever-Bigger Ships
</P>
<P>
   Bigness may not be everything, as the economist E.F. Schumacher
argued in his 1973 book, ``Small Is Beautiful,'' but you couldn't
prove that from the cruise industry's ever-bigger ships. On Nov. 8,
Carnival's Cunard Lines announced that it had completed plans for
what will be the longest passenger ship ever built (1,100 feet), to
be introduced in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, on Nov. 10, the Port of Miami-Dade officially
opened what it described as the world's biggest cruise passenger
terminal (250,000 square feet). And a day after that, this season's
biggest cruise ship, Royal Caribbean's 142,000 ton Voyager of the
Seas, capable of carrying 3,100 passengers, arrived in Miami in
preparation for its year-round seven-night cruises to the western
Caribbean beginning Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, a number of cruise lines with small ships
sailing interesting itineraries. But the reason for the huge ships
is that they are intended not just to take passengers on a cruise
but on a floating vacation, the better to compete with land-based
resorts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pan Am Expands Service
</P>
<P>
   Pan American Airways current incarnation is only a shadow of its
former self, but today it is scheduled to begin round-trip service
six days a week between its headquarters in Portsmouth, N.H. and
Gary/Chicago Airport in northern Indiana, and similar service
between Gary/Chicago and Sanford/Orlando Airport in central
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired following bankruptcy proceedings in June 1998 by four
New England investors, Pan Am operated as a charter airline until
October, when it began Portsmouth-Orlando flights six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   More Leg Room on Delta
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Dec. 2, Delta Air Lines will begin flying the Boeing
767-300ER aircraft between New York's Kennedy International Airport
and Phoenix's Sky Harbor Airport. Delta said its business-class
seats had more than double the space of first-class seats of other
carriers flying nonstop between New York and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   LanChile-Alaska Air Accord
</P>
<P>
   LanChile said Tuesday that it had entered into a code-sharing
agreement with Alaska Airlines. Passengers on both airlines are
eligible to participate in each other's frequent-flier programs.
Also, through Jan. 31, 2000, LanChile frequent-flier members can
earn 1,865 miles when they stay at participating Hyatt Hotels and
Resorts in Chicago, Dallas, Los Angeles, Miami, New York, San
Francisco, Buenos Aires and Santiago, Chile. After January, each
stay at a Hyatt will earn 385 miles. And when LanChile joins the
One World alliance, tentatively scheduled for next March, its
frequent-flier miles can be redeemed toward flights on other
alliance airlines, including American Airlines, British Airways,
Qantas Airways and Air Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
