<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-OPERA-465&AMP;ADD-SCHOOLS     11-16 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-465&AMP;ADD-SCHOOLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OPENING YOUNG EARS TO OPERA: Guild brings the romance and
temper  tantrums of `La Boheme' to schools  
 By SYLVIA RUBIN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what must be a first, Puccini's ``La Boheme''
was compared to NBC's hit sitcom ``Friends''  &LR; the other day &LR; . &LR; 
 &LR; Well, there (set ital)are(end ital) roommates and romance. Also
sex, jealousy, flirtation and temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   It made sense to the 500 grade-schoolers who came to watch an
abbreviated version of the opera Monday morning at the Treasure
Island School. The cafeteria was overflowing with little bodies as
the curtain rose on Rodolfo, the poet, and Marcello, the painter,
in their cold attic apartment in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Even whittled to 45 minutes, this production by the San
Francisco Opera Guild _ featuring free-lance opera singers and nine
eighth-graders from the school in small speaking parts _ managed to
capture the essence of Puccini's tale of bohemian life in the
1830s.
</P>
<P>
   The Guild's school outreach education program, called Opera a la
Carte, will put on 130 performances of ``La Boheme'' this fall in
schools from Napa to San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Students who help put on the shows, from those with speaking
parts to the ones who paint the backdrops and stage-manage, will
attend a final dress rehearsal of San Francisco Opera's ``La
Boheme'' in early December. The opera opens December 4.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth-grader Annette Tran, who played the philosopher Colline,
said she wasn't sure what a philosopher is but thought she knew
what a bohemian is. She squinted her eyes and thought. ``Wait, I
remember my homework ... someone who is poor? A painter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People from France. Writers and painters,'' said Shera Chhoth,
who plays a street kid.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the students in Manuel Tchakalian's music class have
been listening nonstop to a ``La Boheme'' recording with Luciano
Pavarotti and Mirella Freni.
</P>
<P>
   Tchakalian also happens to be a physical education teacher,
which strikes the kids as comical. He thinks this makes perfect
sense. ``Sports and music are both very emotional,'' he said.
``They are not passive activities. They are active.''
</P>
<P>
   In music class, his students said, Mr. T. is as active as an
umpire. He waves his arms around. He speaks in exclamation points.
``He gets so excited,'' said Tran. ``Sometimes, he cries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He drops his glasses. He gets carried away,'' said My Linh Le,
who plays the guard.
</P>
<P>
   All true, the teacher admitted. ``I want them to really hear
Pavarotti. I was saying, `Listen! Listen!' My arm flew up _ that's
when my glasses came off.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, he added, he is Armenian. ``We are very emotional; we
are kind of crazy people,'' he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Any opera, even a 45-minute one, is better than any commercial
music on the radio today, Tchakalian said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Kerrigan, a former opera singer who is a Guild member and
Opera a la Carte producer, has been condensing great operas for 15
years and has learned to do it seamlessly. All the characters are
there: the landlord, Parpignol, the street kids, the cafe waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the arias are there,'' she said. ``They are just
shortened.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Erina Newkirk, who plays Musetta, Marcello's on-again, off-again
girlfriend, got the audience's attention in Act 2 when she threw a
tantrum in the cafe and made Marcello jealous as she lifted her
skirts to flirt with her lover Alcindoro, played by eighth-grader
Don Huynh.
</P>
<P>
   The audience cracked up when Rodolfo (Jimmy Kansau) and Marcello
(Todd Donaran) clowned around in Act 4, just before Mimi (Hope
Riggs) arrived, too weak to walk.
</P>
<P>
   And there was respectful silence a few minutes later when Mimi
could no longer hang on to life.
</P>
<P>
   So what if this production had no lights and no supertitles? So
what if it was done on a tiny bare stage with no costume changes?
Puccini's characters were poor, after all. As Mimi lay dying on a
folding chair with a footstool under her feet, the emotions were
there. One teacher was caught weeping.
</P>
<P>
   As the curtain closed, the student actors were glad it was over.
Performing is so nerve-racking. Tell it to the cast and pianist Ron
Valentino, who flew to their cars after the show, taking off to
another school, another performance.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, the cast briefly took questions from the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you get so mad?'' someone asked Newkirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you be mad if someone stepped on your foot, just for
the fun of it?'' Newkirk replied. ``You have to put yourself in
your character's place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you do your voice?'' another asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of practice,'' Donaran answered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
