<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pioneer track owner Earles dies
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Flags will be raised at half-staff today and Thursday
at Atlanta Motor Speedway in memory of Martinsville Speedway
founder H. Clay Earles, who died Tuesday morning after a yearlong
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Earles, 86, was one of the original builders of the track in
Martinsville, Va., and remained actively involved as co-owner and
CEO until his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I remember the most about Mr. Earles was that he
always took care of the competitors,'' said driver Sterling Marlin.
``But he'd take care of the big boys and take care of the little
guys too.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the smaller teams would always go run his races
because they knew he'd take care of them and that he cared about
them.''
</P>
<P>
   AMS general manager and president Ed Clark was 8 years old when
he first met Earles.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR racing has lost a great pioneer who dedicated every day
of his life to making our sport better,'' Clark said. ``Men like
Clay Earles laid the groundwork to make NASCAR racing one of the
most popular sports in America today.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricklin takes seat
</P>
<P>
   Due to a strange turn of events, Hut Stricklin signed a one-race
deal with Butch Mock Motorsports to drive the No. 75 Ford this
weekend at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Musgrave, the team's former driver, provided one of the most
shocking scenes of the Winston Cup season when he parked his car
and quit during the middle of last Sunday's Pennzoil 400. Musgrave,
who was going to be replaced by Wally Dallenbach next season
anyway, said that he was tired of driving a ``non-competitive''
car.
</P>
<P>
   New deal for Elliott
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Elliott, brother of driver Bill Elliott, agreed Tuesday to
provide engines for the No. 9 Ford of Melling Racing for Sunday's
NAPA 500 and the entire 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a reunion for owner Mark Melling and Elliott, who
worked together for seven years before parting ways in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was somewhat of an emotional decision as my dad wanted
this partnership to materialize at some point,'' Melling said.
</P>
<P>
   Late for a reason
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek won't be arriving in Atlanta until just before
qualifying on Friday so he can spend more time with his pregnant
wife. Andrea Nemechek will remain hospitalized until at least
Friday after suffering a broken shoulder, a fractured neck
vertebrae, several broken ribs and a small lung puncture when her
husband wrecked the family vehicle Sunday night in Concord, N.C.
Doctors said the injury will not effect the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Extra laps
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, the record-setting rookie driver, will make an
appearance from 3-5 p.m. today at the Home Depot in Dunwoody.
Stewart will also participate in a chat session on
www.homedepot.com from 8:30-9:15 p.m. Todd Bodine will sign
autographs at the Varsity downtown from 12-3:30 p.m. today. ...
Cicci-Welliver Racing announced that Tim Fedewa will return to the
No. 36 Busch team for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
