A1994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEWS-ASSEMBLY-COX     11-16 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-ASSEMBLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jewish General Assembly opens
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At Hartsfield International Airport Tuesday, Alon
Baker got off a plane from Israel and found this greeting written
on a poster held by a volunteer from the Atlanta Jewish community:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shalom Y'all. Welcome to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   And with that _ and a free bag of boiled peanuts _ he became one
of more than 4,000 Jews from around the world arriving here for a
three-day conference, the 68th annual General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The conference _ at least the first registration day _ was
almost as much about the condition of Southern hospitality as it
was about the global state of the Jewish faith and international
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's a particularly Jewish Southern food,''
said Linda Selig, co-chair of the conference, which is being hosted
by the Jewish Federation of Greater Atlanta. ``Maybe it's lox and
grits?''
</P>
<P>
   Selig was talking on the convention hall floor of the Marriott
Marquis downtown, where a steady stream of conventioneers and
delegates from around the world were registering for the meetings,
which will feature Vice President Al Gore as the kickoff speaker
this afternoon and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Friday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   She was clutching a cell phone, and in her eye was the edgy look
of a host expecting roughly 4,000 people for dinner, at her place _
tonight. She wasn't far wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, with the help of Selig and other organizers, 24
prominent members of Atlanta's Jewish community _ including Chuck
Wolf and Charles Ackerman _ opened their homes and liquor cabinets
and set out Kosher snacks for the visiting multitude.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dimant, 53, of Toronto, is a member of B'nai B'rith, a
Jewish service organization, and has attended four General
Assemblies in other cities around the country. He said he isn't
surprised at the city's down-home hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected the people to be warm and gracious,'' he said.
``This is Atlanta, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   At the home of Peter and Margo Savitz, about 50 delegates
arrived by bus in the early evening and mingled in the dining room
over Kosher finger food _ vegetables and dips; chips; nuts,
California roll sushi _ and in the kitchen, nursing beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a very distinct difference between Jews in the
South, and Jews from other parts of the country,'' said Anne
Firestone, visiting from Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Jews are nicer, more friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Savitz said she would liked to have put on a bigger spread
of food _ fried chicken wouldn't have been a bad idea _ but ``we
had to be careful to be considerate of dietary laws.'' Otherwise,
there were few convivialities not exchanged through the day,
between this community and the world's, and old friends who make
the annual assembly a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a running conversation, and it's just that (there's
a) 365-day gap between sentences,'' said Ivan Michael Schaeffer,
national chairman of United Jewish Communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not be able to escape the fact that there will be
hundreds of people hugging and kissing around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
