<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-HORMONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENENTECH TO SETTLE PATENT DISPUTE OVER GROWTH HORMONES  
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genentech Inc., the nation's pioneering biotechnology company,
has agreed to settle its long-running patent battle with the
University of California over genetically engineered human growth
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is scheduled to come before the UC Board of
Regents' finance committee at a closed meeting Wednesday night and
to be approved by the full board in an open session Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement will cost Genentech $200 million, according to a
report in The Los Angeles Times. That would be the largest payment
ever for patent infringement in the burgeoning biotechnology
sector, where it sometimes seems as if every breakthrough is
accompanied by a trip to court to settle who owns it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to comment until it is completely final,''
said Laura Leber, a spokeswoman for Genentech, which is based in
South San Francisco, Calif. Several spokesmen at the university
said they could not comment until Friday. Lawyers involved in the
negotiations declined to comment or did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Patent lawyers said a $200 million settlement might be among the
five largest in any patent case, although such figures are often
kept private and the actual value of an agreement can be
complicated by cross-licensing when both parties are businesses.
But analysts said the settlement would not be a major burden for
Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Growth hormones, which are used to encourage growth in short
children and to treat a number of adult diseases, accounted for
just over a fifth of Genentech's $1.15 billion in revenue last
year. The company has more than $1 billion in cash as well as the
deep pockets of Roche Holdings, its majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's shares jumped $4.25, to $76 yesterday. Analysts said
the climb reflected both general buying of biotechnology stocks and
optimism about Genentech's drug pipeline. The analysts said
positive buzz about a Genentech drug being developed for asthma and
hay fever and an abstract posted yesterday on the Web site of the
American Society of Hematology about results with Rituxan,
Genentech's drug for non-Hodgkins lymphoma cancer, both lifted the
stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the settlement would have had much of an impact
one way or another in a neutral market,'' said David Molowa, who
follows the company for Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the settlement may have been a relief for some
investors. The university sued Genentech in 1990, five years after
the company began selling its Protropin hormone. When the case
finally reached trial in federal court in San Francisco earlier
this year, Genentech fared badly. A jury unanimously rejected
Genentech's argument that the university's patents were invalid and
came within one vote of deciding Protropin had infringed it.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were scheduled to retry the infringement issue in
January in a trial that would have covered both Protropin and a
second hormone product, Nutropin. The hormones are produced in
bacteria that have the gene that codes for the human hormones
spliced into their own DNA. Had the new jury decided the company
was guilty of willful infringement, the university could have been
awarded $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The patent dispute grew out of research at the university's San
Francisco campus led by Howard Goodman, Peter Seeburg and John
Shine, all of whom have since moved on. Seeburg's first stop after
leaving the school in 1978 was Genentech, which had been founded
just two years earlier. His decision to return to the campus on
Dec. 31, 1978 and take genetic material he had been working on to
Genentech led to accusations that Genentech's first growth hormones
not only infringed on the school's patent but owed their existence
to theft of its property.
</P>
<P>
   The misappropriation dispute was settled in 1980 when Genentech
agreed to pay up to $2 million in royalties. Genentech has denied
that Seeburg's materials played a role in subsequent development of
commercial products. Those products are not genetically identical
to the hormone genes isolated, cloned and patented at the
university, so the battle has been over whether they violate the
hazier portion of the law that bars products that are
``substantially equivalent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
