<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GARDEN LOSES A STAR: SERENA WILLIAMS QUITS TOURNAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All beads and bravado, she was supposed to be making
a much-ballyhooed debut Tuesday night in the Chase Championships at
Madison Square Garden. By the time the paying customers arrived
with their legitimate expectations of watching the 1999 U.S. Open
champion clobber the competition, the 18-year-old Serena Williams
was already back home in Florida sharing a couch with her Jack
Russell terrier.
</P>
<P>
   It was a triple blow to the marquee: no Serena for singles, no
more plotting for an all-Williams-sisters final, no more Williams
sisters doubles team.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Williams sister, ranked fourth and threatening to
overtake her older sister, abruptly withdrew from the tournament
Tuesday morning after straining her back while practicing forehand
volleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few forehand volleys, I suddenly felt an excruciating
pain in the upper left side of my back,'' she said. ``I didn't feel
anything pop or pull, but all of a sudden I couldn't move, run,
walk, and even the simplest task of breathing became nearly
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Steffi Graf, the living legend who collected 22 Grand
Slam championships and ruled women's tennis with her iron forehand,
spending a record 377 weeks at No. 1, was honored with a gala
retirement ceremony between matches Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, 30, officially retired in August before the U.S. Open. The
ceremony was attended by most of the 16 Chase singles participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``One moment in time, I've felt like I've had so many of
those,'' said Graf, visibly moved by the five-minute standing
ovation she received from her fans. ``I'll miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   The former New York Knicks Earl Monroe and Dave DeBusschere
raised a banner to the rafters that listed the years of her five
championship seasons here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FSU-WARRICK-COX     11-16 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-WARRICK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warrick expects Gator assault
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Speaking to reporters for the first time
since his ill-advised, ``I didn't kill the president'' remark,
Florida State receiver Peter Warrick labeled his involvement in a
department store scam ``immature'' and ``bad judgment'' before
sending a message to Florida's defensive backs. When asked how he
would cover Peter Warrick, Warrick said: ``I probably wouldn't show
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, though, isn't looking forward to facing the Gators'
fans when the top-ranked Seminoles visit No. 3 Florida on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really like playing away, not since I got in
trouble,'' he said. ``They try to dog me. I know it's going to be
the same way like Clemson and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (Florida) a great team. What scares me is the crowd.
You can't hear anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans at Clemson and Virginia taunted Warrick with chants of
``jailbird,'' dressed in prison stripes with No. 9 on their backs
and displayed signs referring to Warrick's arrest for accepting
illegally discounted merchandise at Dillard's in September. One
sign played off the popular ``John 3:16'' Bible verse sign seen at
many football games. It read, ``Pete 21.40,'' referring to the
amount Warrick and a former teammate paid for more than $420 worth
of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   At Virginia, Warrick said he had beer dumped on him after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw those signs it was funny, but it really hurt me
that probably people who used to like me were showing signs,''
Warrick said.''But deep down inside I was laughing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden is telling
Warrick to do when he steps onto Florida Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many of them will (taunt Warrick), but there
certainly will be one in the crowd ... 20, 30, 100, 1,000, maybe
10,000, depending on how many sacks Dillard's has got,'' Bowden
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete is a very sensitive guy. Pete is a good guy. He doesn't
want to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Warrick hasn't exactly been taking a low-key approach on the
field. In his first game back after serving a two-game suspension,
he ran his finger across his neck, giving the cut-throat sign to
the Clemson players as they ran onto the field. In Virginia, he ran
up to the section where the Cavaliers' school band and students sit
and taunted them before police intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's reaction may have been out of frustration over subpar
performances at Clemson and Virginia, spotty efforts for the player
once considered the front-runner for the Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   FSU offensive coordinator Mark Richt sai he had to ``call out''
Warrick in front of his teammates for his poor practices. Before
the suspension, Warrick had been one of the team's hardest-working
players. But, Richt said, ``He came back practicing about like he
did his sophomore year. I wasn't real happy about his practices
until (last Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Richt had seen enough two days before the Virginia game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lackadaisical Thursday practice,'' Richt said. ``We
wore shorts and everybody thought it was a day off and the tempo
was horrible. I got on his case a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the week of the Maryland game, Warrick appeared relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great week of practice, as good as I've seen him
practice,'' quarterback Chris Weinke said. ``There seemed to be a
determination more so than I've seen before in him. He was having
fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick warmed up for Florida with nine catches for 134 yards
and three touchdowns against Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Warrick does not believe that a repeat performance of
last season's win over Florida _ eight catches for 119 yards and a
touchdown and a touchdown pass he threw _ will help him get back
into the Heisman race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I shot myself in the foot by the mistake I made,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That mistake resulted in Warrick pleading guilty to first-degree
misdemeanor petty theft, with one year probation and 30 days in the
county work program. Warrick said he was against pleading to a
felony or serving time in jail, both of which were an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were talking about taking the felony, I wasn't going
to take that felony,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about (jail) a lot. My mom (said), `Pete, you ain't
doing no jail time. It's not like you're a criminal. I know you
made a mistake but you don't deserve to do 30 days in jail.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like she was right. It hurt me deep inside that
somebody wanted me to spend time in jail for what I did. I know I
was wrong. I know I made a bad judgment. I've just got to move on
from my mistakes. I know that's something I will never do again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom D'Angelo writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
