<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S GRAU HAS DIFFICULT DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two weeks ago, in the midst of UCLA's demoralizing
three-game losing streak, a 240-pound mass of perspective walked
onto Spaulding Field in the form of Bruins long snapper Jeff Grau.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, Grau had been a witness in a murder trial in
Santa Monica Municipal Court. The victim: his brother, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, 1998, in Westchester, Michael Grau, 27, was shot in
the heart by his ex-girlfriend's boyfriend during an argument.
</P>
<P>
   In the trial, the shooter told the jury that because of two
tumors in his back, doctors had removed the protective bone plate
from his lower spine. That made him susceptible to paralysis if
struck in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Since he and Michael Grau had been in fights before, the shooter
claimed self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   The jury agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to peace with it, but my dad (Howard) has had a
really hard time,'' Grau said. ``It's been rough, but all my
friends have helped me out as much as they could to get my mind off
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made me realize that even though we were losing, it's
great to be here. It's put everything that's happened this season
in perspective. Life is short, and football is fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the day: UCLA coach Bob Toledo is unbeaten in the city
series. He was 3-0 as a USC assistant in the 1970s, 2-0 as a UCLA
assistant (1994-95), and 3-0 as the Bruins' boss.
</P>
<P>
   Good memory: Toledo has not forgotten USC tailback Chad Morton's
preseason promise that the Trojans would defeat UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was brought up Monday, it was brought up (Tuesday), and I
think it will be brought up a few more times,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Roster update: Tight end Bryan Fletcher (sprained ankle),
defensive tackle Ken Kocher (sprained ankle) and offensive tackle
Blake Worley (sprained knee) are probable. They are not expected to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Lovell Houston (concussion) has not been cleared to play;
Julius Williams probably will start.
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Keith Brown's career is over after fracturing
his shoulder against Washington. ``It's just unexpected to end my
senior year like this,'' Brown said. ``I was really looking forward
to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Brown, Kenny Pritchett becomes the third-string
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Drew Bennett is the No. 3 quarterback, but he'll spend
the week at receiver. The Bruins barely have enough time to get
starting quarterback Ryan McCann and backup Scott McEwan ready,
much less Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Ricky Manning Jr. will return punts again this week.
</P>
<P>
   Changing it up: The Bruins switched Pasadena hotels last week
for the first time in school history to be closer to their Friday
night destination: ``The Fight Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the film received just two positive reviews _ from
center Matt Phelan and defensive tackle Pete Holland _ the change
of routine had the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty loose before the game, which is not where you'd
expect us to be,'' Holland said. ``I think it helped a little.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKLPLACE-AVIS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKLPLACE-AVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDE THE COMFORT ZONE  
</HEADLINE>
  (mcd) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being eliminated from the race for chief executive, A.
Barry Rand resigned as executive vice president at Xerox in January
and announced his goal to run a Fortune 500 company. On Nov. 9, Mr.
Rand, 55, got his wish, landing at Avis Rent A Car, a company based
on Long Island that expects to make Fortune's list in April.
</P>
<P>
   I aspired to run my own company, and that wasn't going to happen
at Xerox. Paul Allaire, Xerox's chairman, selected an external
candidate to succeed him. We didn't have a debate about his choice.
We'd known each other for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I thought I was going to look elsewhere. But he
asked me to stay on and would have appointed me vice chairman this
year. I said OK But then I asked myself why I was staying, and I
didn't like the answers: that vice chairman was a nice title, that
the job was comfortable, that I was making good money.
</P>
<P>
   I felt like a hypocrite. I'd always taught my family that you
have to take risks. You have to stay faithful to your dreams. Life
is about hurdles, and you have to be a hurdler in life.
</P>
<P>
   When I took over Xerox's distribution operations in 1986, we had
problems everywhere. I quickly realized you can't just sit in the
hallowed halls of headquarters and depend on the next tier of
executives. You have to get out and talk to customers, talk to
employees. I don't mind saying, ``I don't know.'' I have the
self-confidence to say that. I don't mind the risk of being seen as
the person who doesn't know it all.
</P>
<P>
   I started some new businesses and changed the culture. Xerox
became a world-class organization. That increased my expectation
level. It made me believe I can compete with the best in the world.
So I said, ``Why not? Why shouldn't I run my own company one day?''
The goal snuck up on me. I also asked myself what I love in life.
And I realized that running businesses and developing teams gave me
the same sort of psychic energy that I got when was I playing
football and basketball back at Archbishop Carroll High School in
Washington, when I thought I was an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   So I quit and went out looking for a company to run. The caution
I got from many executive recruiters was don't jump for the first
thing. So I kept myself busy searching and analyzing the job
market. I wasn't around the house looking for things to do. My wife
would say, ``I thought you were supposed to be relaxing. You're
traveling all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Then I had another goal. I wanted to be reacquainted with my
wife and 16-year-old son and 8-year-old daughter. So I was OK with
waiting. Over the summer, we went to Morocco, London, Florida,
California and several islands.
</P>
<P>
   When we got back, I turned to the search full time. I didn't
want this to go beyond a year. At the recommendation of Ken
Chenault of American Express, Cendant had contacted me about a
board seat. Avis wasn't looking for a C.E.O. at the time. A
triumverate was leading the company. But Stephen Holmes, a board
member at both companies, and I quickly realized I was a great
match with Avis. Now I'm here. The eagle has landed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2315EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-765&AMP;AD     11-16 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR 2 ALL-BUT-DECLARED SENATE CANDIDATES, PRESSURE TO DECLARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani had
been planning formal campaign announcements as soon as this
January, complete with all the usual trappings: balloons and
speeches, endorsements and a statewide flyaround.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton has now postponed her announcement until
February, if not later, and Giuliani's advisers are hinting he may
forgo one altogether.
</P>
<P>
   From one perspective, a simple announcement by either person, as
one Democratic member of Congress put it Tuesday, would be an
elaborate exercise in stating the obvious, since both have been
engaged in full-bore politicking since last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But obvious or not, pressure seems to be growing _ particularly
in the case of Mrs. Clinton _ to get in or out of the race finally
and formally. With each passing day and each new reported delay,
there is another quiver of concern that either of these candidates
may be suffering a case of the political butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she needs to announce very soon,'' said Judith Hope,
the chairwoman of the state Democratic Committee. ``I truly do.
That's one of the things that needs to happen. I'm urging her to do
so.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the concern and speculation, if hard to ignore in
political circles these days, is built upon a questionable
foundation. Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani have repeatedly all but said
they are in the race to stay. And aides to both said in interviews
Tuesday that the prospect that either would not run was remote,
although certainly not, by a long shot, absurd.
</P>
<P>
   But the seriousness of Mrs. Clinton's intentions has clearly
become the subject of widespread discussion, especially after the
political difficulties Mrs. Clinton experienced during her trip to
the Middle East, for which she was criticized by Jewish leaders
back home. One Democratic consultant, Hank Sheinkopf, said Tuesday
that he had taken four telephone calls from party members and
reporters trading rumors about an imminent withdrawal by Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Giske, a longtime Democratic political strategist and a
vice chairman of the state Democratic Party, said she sensed a
growing rumble surrounding the first lady, notwithstanding her own
certainty that Mrs. Clinton will run. She suggested that both
candidates might take a lesson from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in New York don't like tentativeness,'' Ms. Giske said.
``We want our coffee right away, and we don't like to wait for
subways. We're impatient people: Everybody wants her to announce,
and they want the mayor to announce. They want to know what the
field is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's political plans have been the subject of more
scrutiny than those of Giuliani in no small part because of her
tenuous ties to New York. Mrs. Clinton has yet to move into the
house that she and President Clinton bought in Chappaqua earlier
this month, and which is being renovated for security by the Secret
Service. Mrs. Clinton's advisers said it would be implausible for
her to make an announcement until she has a home in the state.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a constant undercurrent of speculation that Mrs.
Clinton, a pragmatic and cautious politician who could presumably
pick the state she wants to run from, might decide to step out of
what a series of polls suggest may turn out to be a very tough
race. Some of this conjecture has been pushed, if sotto voce, by
Giuliani's allies who have an obvious interest in trying to spook
her in these early days.
</P>
<P>
   But the suggestions have come from Democrats as well. ``There's
a lot more whispering now about, can she get out of the race,''
George Stephanopoulos, the former Clinton adviser, said on ABC's
``This Week'' news program. He added: ``It's become a joyless
campaign. There's not a lot of momentum and energy. I think all of
the people around her say there's no way she's going to get out.
But there's a lot more people in the Democratic Party now who wish
that she would.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mayor, a number of politicians have argued the real
draw for Giuliani to this contest is the chance to run against Mrs.
Clinton, as opposed to being one of 100 people in the Senate.
Should she drop out, this becomes just another race for the Senate,
and Giuliani might be tempted to stand aside and wait for a job
more suited to his interest, such as the attorney general in a
Republican administration.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, there have been reasons for both Mrs. Clinton and
Giuliani to avoid a formal announcement. It has allowed them to
avoid the expenditures of hiring staff members and avoids the risk
of overexposure of the two candidates to the public.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Once he announces, the mayor is likely to have to give up his
weekly forum of a radio show. And, one of his senior advisers noted
Tuesday, ``He does best when he is seen as mayor as opposed to
candidate. Why not remain in our strongest position as long as we
possibly can?'' Giuliani didn't bother to formally announce his
decision to run for re-election two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, as Mrs. Clinton's advisers noted, a full year before
Election Day. Charles Schumer did not announce his candidacy for
the Senate until April, or eight months before the election.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement, though, gives the candidates a chance to lay
out the underlying themes of their campaign, to one of the larger
audiences of the race. ``There seems to be a kind of rule in the
printed press and the electronic press that this is the one day you
get to say something and they will actually report what you say _
as opposed to the other 364 days of the year,'' said Kieran
Mahoney, the Republican consultant who helped run the unsuccessful
re-election campaign of Alfonse D'Amato of New York last year.
</P>
<P>
   And there are particular reasons to move forward in this race.
For both candidates, an announcement would remove any reluctance on
the part of donors. For Mrs. Clinton, it may finally allow her to
make the transition from first lady to candidate that so many
Democrats think she has had difficulty making. ``It would give her
a fresh start,'' said one senior New York Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991116.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TAXI-CAMERAS-NYT &LR;      11-16 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TAXI-CAMERAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXI SURVEILLANCE CAMERAS ARE AUDITIONED FOR BIGGER ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an experiment aimed at deterring crimes against
taxi drivers, the city's Taxi and Limousine Commission said Tuesday
that it had installed small infrared cameras in nine cabs and
livery cars and was considering the use of such cameras throughout
the taxi industry.
</P>
<P>
   Diane McGrath-McKechnie, the chairwoman of the commission, said
in an interview that the cameras, already used routinely by cabbies
in Houston and other cities, had been in experimental use in New
York City for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabdrivers think it is an excellent idea,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment, first reported Tuesday in The Daily News,
incorporates video technology somewhat similar to the bank cameras
aimed at tellers. Fastened beneath the rearview mirrors inside
cabs, the infrared cameras are programmed to capture an image of
passengers as they open the door to get in, or as the fare meter is
turned on.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras can also be activated by taxi drivers during
robberies or other emergencies to provide evidence for police, Ms.
McGrath-McKechnie said. Each cab equipped with a camera would be
required to display a notice of its presence, which she said
``might provide the biggest advantage in deterrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the experiment was applauded Tuesday by some drivers
and industry executives, others said any attempt to make the
cameras standard taxi equipment would raise difficult questions
over passengers' rights to privacy. Some also questioned who would
pay to purchase and maintain the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``The back seat of a cab is supposed to be a sanctuary,'' said
Mike Higgins, the publisher of Taxi Talk, a magazine distributed
among New York City cabbies. ``Are they going to photograph the guy
making out with his girlfriend? And who gets the film?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGrath-McKechnie said such fears over privacy, although not
unexpected, were misplaced. She said that the infrared cameras
being used in the experiment used digital recording systems, not
film, and that images were automatically erased unless a cabdriver
or owner elected to save them for police.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that the expense of expanding such surveillance
posed more difficult questions, and that the commission had not
decided whether the city or cab owners would be required to pay for
the cameras' use. The cameras being used in the experiment were
provided at no cost by manufacturers in Australia and Canada, but
normally cost $600 to $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great idea, but who is going to pay for it?'' said
Dave Pollack, chief operating officer of the League of Mutual Taxi
Owners, an organization of 3,000 drivers who own their cabs. He
said cabbies could not afford and would not accept the financial
burden.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Goldstein, a member of Pollack's group who drives one of the
nine vehicles already involved in the camera surveillance
experiment, said he felt safer with a camera above his dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best idea they ever had,'' Goldstein said Tuesday.
A survivor of many robberies and assaults in his cab, he said the
surveillance camera ``puts people on notice that I've got a
picture, and they won't cause any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would continue to use a camera in his cab only if
the city paid for it. ``If the city wants good cabdrivers, it can
afford to make them safe,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-16-99 2320EST &QL; 
