r s BC-SOC-SOCCER-COLUMN-LAD     11-16 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED IS IN CLASS ALL ITS OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a league designed for parity, Washington D.C. United has been
the exception.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth Major League Soccer championship _ and United
will make its fourth appearance in the finals when it meets the
Galaxy Sunday in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   United won back-to-back titles in 1996 and '97 before losing to
Chicago at the Rose Bowl last year.
</P>
<P>
   United had enough depth to cruise through the Eastern Conference
again, despite injuries and almost six weeks of excused absences
for Marco Etcheverry and Jaime Moreno because of national team
commitments with Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   There is no parity when it comes to United and the rest of the
league. Fourteen of United's players have made international
appearances with their respective national teams in the past four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And when they lose a John Harkes, there is a Ben Olsen to
replace him. When they lose a Raul Diaz Arce, Roy Lassiter to the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at their team from the first year until now; they haven't
made many changes,'' said the Galaxy's Cobi Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Eight players remain from United's '96 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also helps when most of their players are guys that have
been to the finals and have that experience,'' Jones said. ``They
know what to expect, while most people on our team are here for the
first time.''
</P>
<P>
   United's back line consists of U.S. national team players Jeff
Agoos, Carlos Llamosa, Eddie Pope and Richie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to say about their midfield is Etcheverry, the
league's premier playmaker the past four seasons. Lassiter and
Moreno anchor things up front.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another scary fact: The heart of United's lineup could
remain intact for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at their nucleus _ their central midfielders,
two strikers and two center-backs _ their average age is 27,''
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``We only have one guy under the age
of 30 in our nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (United) were the ones who got the youngest, best
foreigners at the outset of the league and they've been able to
keep them with the team, as well as bring along some good, young
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of that was Bruce (Arena, former coach) having a good eye
for talent. And part of that, the league had a lot to do with.''
</P>
<P>
   When Arena left for the U.S. national team, Thomas Rongen took
over. He didn't change much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' Rongen said. ``This
organization always sets their goals high and lofty. After you win
the championship in the first year, they're (championships)
realistic goals. We always talk about trying to go as far as we
can. And we've done a good job identifying young talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, United has its critics.
</P>
<P>
   New MLS commissioner Don Garber suggested that every league has
a dominant team and ones that struggle. He said, ``success breeds
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid had a tough time interpreting that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Garber can say that,'' Schmid said. ``Success
breeds success in a normal environment, but I thought this was a
league where players didn't have a say as to where they go.''
</P>
<P>
   But in MLS, top players have their share of leverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, success breeds success and, if you're a successful
team, players are going to have an interest in going there because
they want to play for that organization, with those players, with
that city, under that coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a normal environment, you can use that to continue to get
good players. But in our environment, that isn't supposed to
happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
