<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CUBA-SUMMIT-1STLD-WRI     11-16 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-SUMMIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS IN CUBA PROVIDE OUTLET FOR DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to insert new 9th thru 12th grafs, bgng At the same. In 2nd
graf, more precisely defines the summit and corrects spelling to
Vaclav.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA _ The business card of Elizardo Sanchez, a leading
dissident here, has a curious caveat next to his phone number: ``if
it works.''
</P>
<P>
   It currently does, and then some. At his home, where the living
room is arrayed with pictures of him with the likes of Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., and the Czech president, Vaclav Havel, Sanchez
has been contacted by at least nine of the delegations that came to
Havana to attend a summit meeting of Latin American countries and
Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. At least 14 other Cuban human rights advocates
and relatives of political prisoners have held meetings with
visiting heads of state and other dignitaries, including the
Spanish prime minister, Jose Maria Aznar, and the Mexican foreign
minister, Rosario Green.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban participants in these meetings said discussions included
issues like multiparty democracy, open markets, freedom of
expression and _ they pointedly added _ an end to the U.S. embargo
against Cuba. They said the meetings were held at the request of
the various delegations, and passed without incident or impediment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before have we seen so many dignitaries coming to our
country to meet with dissidents and opponents of the government,''
Sanchez said, moments before he was whisked off in a van to meet
with a delegation from Brazil. ``This is a great acknowledgement of
a sector of our country, whose government said for many years we
did not exist or were nonpersons.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings come one week after Cuban officials not only
criticized the dissidents for wanting to hold a parallel meeting,
but detained several dozen of them for hours, and kept another 15
under arrest on suspicion of planning acts of sabotage to disrupt
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to allow Sanchez and others to meet with the
foreign dignitaries appeared to be a calculated move by the
government to allow some openness and to avoid public conflicts
that would mar the country's moment in the spotlight as host to a
meeting of presidents, prime ministers and other officials from 21
Latin American nations, Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials do not view the dissidents as a monolithic
group, which may also explain whey they have not interfered with
the meetings. They distinguish between those like Sanchez _ who is
seen as a thoughtful, if ideologically opposed, figure _ and others
who are viewed as puppets of the exile community, dedicated to
destabilizing the regime. They insist the groups do not present a
real challenge or an alternative to the government.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, President Fidel Castro said he would have
preferred that the dignitaries spend more time talking to ordinary
Cubans, who he said were not in agreement with the dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summit has been full of virtual realities,'' he said
after the summit ended Tuesday night. ``Nobody is talking about the
real objective of the summit.''
</P>
<P>
   But in closing remarks earlier in the evening, several heads of
state reiterated the need for greater openness in Cuba.
``Sovereignty also needs democracy,'' said President Ernesto
Zedillo of Mexico. ``There can be no sovereign nation without free
men and women, men and women who can exercise their essential
freedoms. Freedom to think and give their opinions, freedom to
dissent, freedom to chose.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's remarks came days after his foreign minister, Ms.
Green, met with Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Green said in a prepared statement that her meeting with
Sanchez did not constitute a change in Mexico's policy against
intervening in the affairs of other nations. Sanchez said that the
Mexican government can nevertheless play a helpful role in Cuba, as
it has in helping to resolve the regional conflicts in Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there is no civil war in Cuba, there is still a
strong confrontation between Washington and Havana,'' he said.
``Due to the good relations Mexico has with both countries, it
could make a bigger contribution to normalizing relations between
Havana and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   While not explicitly condemning the Cuban government, several of
the dignitaries who met with the dissidents expressed carefully
worded support for their concerns. Aznar, the Spanish prime
minister, said he met with the dissidents because he was not a
``part-time democrat'' and that he always wanted to make as many
contacts as possible wherever he traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Even before this week's meetings, four jailed dissidents
received a letter of solidarity signed by 43 human rights advocates
and political leaders from Eastern Europe, including Havel; former
President Lech Walesa of Poland, and Yelena Bonner, the widow of
the Russian dissident Andrei Sakharov. The letter invoked the
memory of Jose Marti, the nationalist leader who is still revered
in Cuba for his fight against Spanish rule.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening remarks Tuesday morning, Castro ignored the
dissidents, and declared that he remains committed to the path he
chose decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of the first such meeting in Guadalajara, Mexico, eight
years ago, when Cuba was widely urged to shed its communist system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advice rained down from everywhere,'' he said. ``But we
thought of another way and decided to struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban officials now say that after several harsh years of a
subsistence economy following the end of support from the former
Soviet Union, the economy is growing. Tourism has contributed
greatly, and the country is getting better credit terms, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting has given the government a chance to project an
image of its society different from the one offered by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Modest crowds turned out to greet King Juan Carlos of Spain as
he toured the restoration of elegant buildings in Old Havana. The
visitors also went to inaugural ceremonies at the new Latin
American School of Medical Science, where 1,929 students from
Central and South America are studying medicine. Enrollment is
expected to reach 8,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight of the week has already come for Hector
Palacios, a dissident who founded the Democratic Solidarity Party,
an act that led to a prison term. Like Sanchez, he said his morale
was improved by the visits with the foreign dignitaries. Yet he was
also realistic about the lasting effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we won a lot in expectations and hope,'' he said.
``Hope that we will become stronger. Hope that we will have other
doors to knock on. Hope that other eyes will look out for us. But I
do not have hope that the government will change or make a gesture
of flexibility soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
