<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAS TROJAN TRADITION GONE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who believes that change is good is obviously not a
Trojan football fan.
</P>
<P>
   USC supporters have gone through enough change the last two
decades to last several millenniums, and it's been a slow,
anguished descent, too, turning ``Fight On'' into more of a
question than a proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Two periods of probation. Four head coaches, three fired. Five
Rose Bowl berths in 20 seasons after 10 the previous 14. Bowl-less
three of the last four seasons. Five losses or more in seven of the
last nine seasons. A 13-game winless streak against Notre Dame, and
the current eight-game losing streak against UCLA that is on the
line Saturday at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But as miserable as that accounting may be, something else
around the corner may be even worse: The Trojan faithful seems to
have lost its faith.
</P>
<P>
   After so many years of immense pride, pride that occasionally
drifted toward arrogance, USC fans now appear indifferent or
defeatists. Only 57,493 came out for the Stanford game, and just
53,382 for homecoming versus Arizona State, the smallest homecoming
crowd since 1993, when the opponent was Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   At the Stanford and Arizona State games at the Coliseum this
season, the crowd vibe was as interesting as anything on the field.
The body language of the fans was all trepidation and gloom --
hands in pocket, arms across chest, eyes more wary than hopeful.
Emotional sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Trojan fans now even lack the energy to jeer anymore, like they
did in 1986 and 1994, when they booed Ted Tollner and Rob Johnson
off the Coliseum field. USC fans will muster the courage to show up
Saturday, but many will leave their optimism at home. Or at least
in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hackett only has nice things to say about the fans,
thanking them Tuesday for hanging in with a team that can't go the
distance. ``I'd like to find a way to win and let people who
suffered through this year have a chance to enjoy it.'' he said.
``Our fans have been great.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean there aren't people out there yelling (at
me). The day I was hired, half the people probably thought I was
the wrong choice. There will always be some people who, when you
don't have (a good year), will say you're headed down the wrong
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the same road. That may be the tombstone for USC football.
The malaise outlasted the fans.
</P>
<P>
   What fans tend to overlook at times like this is that the losses
can't possibly affect them more than the players. To know the
difference, one only has to look at the face of senior safety David
Gibson 48 games played, 230 tackles, three positions in his USC
career to date when he says he won't consider his USC career a
success if the Trojans don't win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The extra spoonful of fan indignation just makes the players
feel worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (fans) expect us to win. They expect Pac-10
championships, and they're disappointed when they come up and talk
to me,'' said senior safety David Gibson. ``But I'm living this
season. It's my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Our fans are) lukewarm. Like a lot of fans in L.A., they're
front-runners. When USC is doing well, they'll be there. When we're
not, they're not, and they become even more derogatory.''
</P>
<P>
   If the players take the field knowing the fans expect the worse
(ital) and (end) will talk smack afterward, then who are they
playing for, besides themselves?
</P>
<P>
   This has always been what separates college football from pro
football. College football has alums who cut through generations,
that once-a-Trojan-always-a-Trojan stuff. Sure, coaches are hired
and fired, but most players can remember their college days fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team would play a lot better if we had more
support,'' said Gibson. ``If they expect this to be a great team,
it's got to go both ways. It (gives) so much energy to a team to
have a packed house and feel the vibe of a home game.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that a large part of USC's heritage is already musty Long
Beach Poly's Kareem Kelly was nine the last time USC beat UCLA it
will be doubly dangerous if fans take a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Smith got fired for saying ``traditions'' aren't relevant.
John Robinson was rehired because he said they are. Either way,
nothing changed. Paul Hackett may leave some cold with his
coaching, but at least he's a realist.
</P>
<P>
   When USC goes calling on recruits these days, they're shown the
four Heisman trophies in Heritage Hall, but the reminiscing ends
there. The pitch isn't ``be the next Marcus Allen.'' It's ``be next
year's starting tailback.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two classes where our top recruit has played and had
a dramatic effect (Carson Palmer last year, Kareem Kelly this
year),'' said Hackett. ``That tells recruits that if you come, you
have a chance to play right away. We continue to make that promise,
because our program is at the point where we're building and we
need people who are not afraid of playing right away.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what led Banning running back Chris Howard to already
commit to USC. ``I know about the tradition,'' he said, ``but what
really attracted me was the chance to come in and start right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   But how many more Howards will commit if the fans stay home or,
worse, keep talking trash?
</P>
<P>
   USC will host a large handful of recruits Saturday as part of
their official visit. But Hackett knows UCLA is recruiting the same
kids, and the past and future for both programs will be on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some kids who say they want to go to a school that
goes to a Rose Bowl or Cotton Bowl or BCS Bowl every year,'' said
Hackett. ``And some kids will look at both teams and say `hey,
these teams have not had (a great year).'
</P>
<P>
   ``(The UCLA) game is important for a lot of reasons, but let's
face it. For eight years, we've come up on the short end, and I
don't know if there's anything more important right now than just
breaking the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight's enough. We don't need anymore. It's time to turn it
around.'' For themselves, if not the fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
