<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL ON 1996 VALUJET CRASH OPENS IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 1st and 3rd grafs to delete word `explosive`) 
 (nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One thing became clear Tuesday, as federal prosecutors
and defense lawyers made opening statements in a criminal trial
that accuses a maintenance company and two employees of shoddy work
and an ensuing cover-up in the handling of oxygen generators
implicated in the crash of Valujet Flight 592.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whom the jury ultimately believes, the 110 people who
departed Miami International Airport on that flight of May 11,
1996, were doomed as they took their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Either they died from criminal negligence, in the handling and
packaging of the oxygen generators, as prosecutors claimed, or they
died from problems with the plane itself, a 27-year-old aircraft
with faulty mechanics and wiring that should never have been in the
sky in the first place, as defense lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 592 crashed into the Florida Everglades just after
takeoff, killing all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say Sabretech, a now-bankrupt aircraft
maintenance company, and two employees _ a former head mechanic and
a subcontractor doing mechanic work _ disregarded safety to rush
through their work on the oxygen generators, which prosecutors said
caught fire in a cargo hold and caused the plane to crash. The
company and the two workers are charged with causing the transport
of hazardous materials, falsifying documents and conspiring to lie
to federal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Caroline Heck Miller said in her opening
statement that the generators, which provide emergency oxygen when
planes lose cabin pressure, were loaded into the plane's cargo hold
for transport to Atlanta without being fitted with safety caps.
</P>
<P>
   The missing caps were sacrificed for expediency, prosecutors
will try to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphasis was on getting the paperwork done, as opposed to
the task,'' Ms. Heck Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But defense lawyers described a much different company, one in
which no one intentionally neglected safety procedures with intent
to cause a crash. But even they conceded that the maintenance
workers did not know how to handle the generators.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one at Sabretech intended for that plane to crash,'' said
Martin Raskin, a lawyer for Sabretech, which did maintenance for
Valujet.
</P>
<P>
   But Raskin did not paint a safety-inspiring picture of the
handling of the generators. While maintenance workers had neglected
to put the safety caps on the generators, they carefully packaged
them in cardboard boxes and wrapped them with bubble wrap, he said
in his opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   The generators, when triggered, can reach temperatures of 400 to
500 degrees, according to crash investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The generators were not labeled as hazardous, Raskin said. ``A
bottle of bleach,'' he said, ``will tell you more about its
dangers.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the ensuing cover-up, federal prosecutors said, that
proves the mechanics knew they were putting people at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the caps were not installed, Eugene Florence, a
mechanic for Sabretech, signed a maintenance record saying they had
been. He is on trial here, along with his supervisor, Daniel
Gonzalez, the head mechanic and chief of hangar operations.
</P>
<P>
   A third Sabretech employee, Mauro Valenzuela, was also charged,
but is a fugitive from justice.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the defendants could be imprisoned for up to 55
years and fined more than $2 million. Sabretech, which went out of
business after the crash, could be fined up to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also been charged in state court with
third-degree murder and manslaughter, although no individuals are
named.
</P>
<P>
   Though federal investigators have pointed to the generators as
the likely cause of the crash, Raskin pointed to the plane itself,
a DC-9 with numerous mechanical and electrical problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane that crashed was an old plane, with old wiring,''
Raskin said. Neither the plane's auto pilot nor its intercom
worked. Flight attendants had to use a bullhorn to make
announcements to passengers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valujet, a discount airline based in Atlanta, eventually merged
with Airtran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
