<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE EXPECTED MORE FROM LINEBACKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was once thought to be the deepest position on
the Cal State Northridge football team: linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   But four days before the Matadors' season finale, not one
Matadors linebacker is among the team's top three defenders in
tackling. Middle linebacker Cos Abercrombie leads the unit with 44
tackles, followed by Jack Heaslet, who has 43.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie and Heaslet are fifth and sixth, respectively, on
the team in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've struggled in a sense this year,'' linebackers coach
Terrance Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson cites three reasons why linebackers like Abercrombie, a
sophomore, and Heaslet, a senior, haven't been able to dominate the
Matadors' tackling statistics.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, mobile defensive linemen like Shawnbay Jones (63
tackles), Brennen Swanson (60) and Erik Gardner (24) are able to
make stops, instead of simply holding the ballcarrier and waiting
for a linebacker to help.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Johnson was the defensive line coach in the spring. He
switched to the linebackers, the position he played in college at
Colorado, late in the summer after head coach Ron Ponciano was
fired and the staff changed.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Abercrombie simply hasn't been the dominant player
Johnson anticipated in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the capability,'' Johnson said of Abercrombie. ``He's
got to let his ability take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Blanton, a sophomore, has played well in the season's
latter half. Johnson looks forward to 2000 with Abercrombie and
Blanton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the guys I'm carrying into next season as my
starters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping down: Cliff Hysell, the dean of the Big Sky head
coaches, announced his resignation at Montana State on Sunday.
Hysell, 57, has been at MSU for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bobcats were projected as one of the top four teams in the
conference. But they enter Saturday's game at rival Montana just
3-7 overall, 1-6 in the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   Hysell cited health concerns as his primary reason for
resigning. He's scheduled to undergo two surgeries on his spine and
he'll require two months of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Rivalry weekend: Several CSUN players have mentioned Sacramento
State as the team's rival in the Big Sky. But those thoughts may be
pushed aside when Northern Arizona (7-3, 5-2) comes to North Campus
Stadium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks beat CSUN 68-7 in 1995 _ at the time it was the
worst loss in school history.
</P>
<P>
   But the Matadors have won the past two games, including 41-10
last year at Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the team that has brought out the most in us,''
CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin said. ``NAU is that benchmark
(for us). They are one of the more solid programs in I-AA
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe's back: Freshman receiver Joe Gilliam, who was suspended
from the team two weeks ago, returned to practice Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam, who suffered a concussion against Weber State on Oct.
30, two days before he was suspended, may or may not play this
week, Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a class-attendance issue,'' Kearin said. ``(Gilliam)'s
abided by the rules. I have no intention of doing anything with the
(starting) lineup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
