<HEADLINE>
SUNY RAISES ITS SALARY LIMIT FOR A CHANCELLOR TO $350,000 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The State University of New York could pay its next chancellor
as much as $350,000 under a resolution its trustees passed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY's current chancellor, John Ryan, who has announced his
intention to step down by the end of the year, earns $250,000 a
year. But chief executives at large public universities and
university systems in California, Florida, Georgia and other states
are paid more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big job. We're a huge enterprise,'' Thomas Egan, SUNY's
chairman, said Tuesday, adding that with more than 350,000
students, SUNY is the largest university system in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its search to replace Ryan, SUNY officials studied
what other universities pay. SUNY officials said the chancellor of
the California state system is paid $436,000, the chancellor of the
University of Georgia system $324,000, and the chancellor of the
University of Florida system $333,000.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees approved a new salary range of $275,000 to
$350,000. The raise must be submitted to the state Legislature and
to the state budget division. It is also subject to a 60-day
comment period.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan will not receive a raise, but the trustees voted to make
him emeritus chancellor when he retires and to keep him on as a
consultant to be paid on a per diem basis.
</P>
<P>
   The board raised Ryan's salary to $250,000 from $172,400 in
October 1997, and set the salary range for the position at $220,000
to $290,000.
</P>
<P>
   At $250,000, the salary was already among the highest paid to
any state official, and at $350,000, it would be far more than the
$179,000 paid to the governor or the $195,000 paid to New York
City's mayor.
</P>
<P>
   William Scheuerman, president of SUNY's faculty union, said he
was less troubled by the new raise than by the board's failure to
provide enough money for the campuses in the budget for the current
academic year that it approved Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new budget, about half of SUNY's state-operated
campuses will not receive large enough increases in their operating
budgets to cover the salary increases for faculty and staff that
were approved under the most recent union agreement. That agreement
called for a 12.5 percent raise spread over four years, through
July 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased that we're taking care of the chancellor,''
Scheuerman said. ``But I'd like to see us take care of the students
and make sure that they have enough faculty to teach them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said SUNY officials were denying that any staff reductions
would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUNY officials are saying no, no, no, but the campuses are
saying probably, probably, probably, '' Scheuerman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
