<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-16 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-16 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN the service was over and the funeral procession began slowly
rolling away, they stood shoulder to shoulder on the lush green
grass of St. James Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if it was 1965 _ or 1945 _ all over again.
</P>
<P>
   It was Prairie View A&AMP;M's proudest players standing tall and
straight for the man they loved, former Panthers coach Billy Nicks.
</P>
<P>
   It was images of two-a-days, bear crawls and three-man rolls
coming back like it all happened just yesterday. It was memories of
bloody knuckles, sore necks, long nights in study hall and the
watchful tap-tap-tap of Nicks personally knocking on dormitory
doors making sure lights were out by 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more than a coach,'' former assistant Hoover Wright
said. ``He turned players into men.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Tuesday was a time to remember championships, tough
practices and a molder of men who coached football and directed
lives for more than four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told coach (Woody) Hayes a long time ago that we always
believed those Prairie View teams were like the black Notre Dame,''
former Panthers player Bill Downey said. ``He told me, `Not really.
Notre Dame was the white Prairie View.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the things Nicks did with X's and O's proved to be
well ahead of their time, if not always universally acknowledged.
He scripted the first series of offensive plays decades before
former San Francisco 49ers coach Bill Walsh _ often credited with
developing the technique _ ever did.
</P>
<P>
   He developed diverse passing philosophies and attacking
defenses. He was meticulous about individualized meetings and
scouting reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for coach Nicks, I don't think I would have ever
done the things I did in the game,'' said longtime NFL scout
Charles Garcia, who worked more than 20 years for the Seahawks,
Browns, Patriots and Bears. ``You can look around he made a
difference with everyone here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of them stood there Tuesday on the lawn of St. James
Church, flecks of gray in their hair and Panthers pride burning in
their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   They stood shoulder to shoulder, smaller guys in front, linemen
in back, chests out, chins high. They smiled. And then someone took
a team picture for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes coach Nicks would break you down, because he knew
you had to be built into something greater,'' said Leon Carr, a
defensive back and quarterback on Prairie View's back-to-back NAIA
national championship teams of 1963 and 1964. ``That's exactly what
he did. He made you a man.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why they came to pay tribute to one of the greatest
football coaches and builders of character the sport has ever
known. They cried and laughed. They reminisced and lamented the
loss of a man who had retired nearly 35 years earlier but still was
known simply as ``coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's football fans might know Nicks only because his name was
etched among the immortals at the College Football Hall of Fame
this year. Time tends to make people forget some heroes, especially
when that hero quietly applied his craft at a predominantly black
college, working at a school tucked away off a farm road in
Southeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For many, he is known only for the impressive numbers on the
plaque in his honor hanging on a museum wall in South Bend, Ind. _
195 wins, 60 losses, five national championships and eight
Southwestern Athletic Conference championships.
</P>
<P>
   But as you saw Nicks' proteges gather for the impromptu team
picture Tuesday morning, you saw a living tribute to the man who
wanted more than just touchdowns and championships from his
players. You saw just how far-reaching his influence was.
</P>
<P>
   There were doctors, lawyers, business executives, politicians,
former NFL greats, high school coaches, college coaches, NFL
scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a profound mentor,'' said Downey, who in 1945 was
kicked out of school by Nicks for performing poorly in class but
after being allowed back in never failed to make the honor roll.
</P>
<P>
   When his Panthers career ended in the late 1940s, Downey became
a decorated officer in the military. His most vivid memory of the
effect Nicks had on the game and its people might have best
illustrated why generations showed up in Nicks' honor Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 while a colonel in the military, Downey was commanding a
unit in Vietnam when he got word that Hayes, who was touring
Southeast Asia after taking Ohio State to the Rose Bowl, wanted to
meet him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Why does he want to meet me here?''' Downey said.
``But he heard that I had played for (Nicks).''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes was escorted to the battlefield headquarters and met with
Downey for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `In my circles, when we mention the word coach, I
only think of two men _ Billy Nicks and John Wooden,''' Downey
said. ``He said, `Those are true coaches.' It inspired me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest reason football historians do not list Nicks
with the likes of Eddie Robinson is because predominantly black
colleges were not fully appreciated until Robinson broke Amos
Alonzo Stagg's all-time win record. And Nicks retired in 1965, long
before Robinson's name earned its place among the game's greats.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicks should not be forgotten as one of the greatest of the
great. Just ask one of those who stood there shoulder to shoulder
in a team picture for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had coach Nicks stayed around longer,'' Carr said, ``he would
have gotten all the recognition that Eddie Robinson got. Because he
would have just kept on beating Robinson like he always did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
